A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAYNARD-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      06-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYNARD-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISHING SALINGER AND FENDING OFF CRITICISM, BUT THE POINT IS, UM
... 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things have been kind of rough for Joyce Maynard in the month
since the world learned she was planning to sell (Tuesday afternoon
at Sotheby's in New York) the love letters J.D. Salinger sent her
when she was 18, and he a wannabe purist of 53.
</P>
<P>
   A story in the National Review called Ms. Maynard, now 45, an
``opportunistic onetime nymphet'' _ not something an author would
want to use as a pull quote on the book of life. Maureen Dowd, in
the pages of this newspaper, called her a ``leech'' woman.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, Ms. Maynard notes more than once _ wound tight, she
tends to say things more than once _ is that she has not devoted
her life to exploiting her relationship with the man who has come
to be called the famously reclusive author. She has written a
half-dozen books and only in her last did she discuss Salinger. She
has spent much of her life as a journalist, most recently in a
refugee camp in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway _ where were we? _ such was the wack to her psyche of the
press attacks that Ms. Maynard, who is notorious for writing about
everything in her life and maintains a Web site
(www.joycemaynard.com), felt she had to make an emergency visit to
her therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Buddhist,'' Ms. Maynard says, with the amused tone of
an easterner moved to Marin County. ``He said to me, `Where is the
lesson for you in all of this?' I think I know. I was a little
girl, then an older girl, then even a woman who desperately sought
approval. And I believed when I made the decision to write a book
about Salinger, I ceased being the person who needed approval, but
I wasn't. I wanted to be invited into the club instead of being
dismissed as a cheap kiss-and-tell writer. I know I'm not a cheap
kiss-and-tell writer, but I recognized that had I earned this
approval I wanted, I might not still be inviting people onto my Web
site _''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, Joyce, the lesson. You were talking about a lesson?
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson is that I'm a fellow struggler. An essential part
of my work is that things not get too comfortable for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Got two hours for a conversation with Joyce Maynard? That won't
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   A chat in a friend's apartment at the Essex House runs three and
a half hours, with a follow-up call the morning after. That doesn't
mean, however, speaking from the heart is without stress.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Ms. Maynard, who flew to New York with plans to attend the
auction, who designed her gray pantsuit and she'll tug at the label
to tell you, then fret: Migoschka. Hope this isn't going to suggest
that she is a rich person. She's a freelance writer, with a wildly
fluctuating income. This is her one $300 jacket.
</P>
<P>
   As for her life, here are just some of the excruciatingly
painful things Ms. Maynard reported in her memoir, ``At Home in the
World'' (Picador), published last fall:
</P>
<P>
   Her late father, a professor at the University of New Hampshire
in Durham, was an alcoholic. Her late mother was a magazine writer
who wrote frequently about her family.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother also took her into bed to ``cuddle'' as late as
junior high and commented on her daughter's body.
</P>
<P>
   How can one know anything about what the non-Buddhist therapists
call boundaries when one's mother does such a thing?
</P>
<P>
   Meditate on that.
</P>
<P>
   Salinger, anyway, comes into Ms. Maynard's life in the spring of
1972, when, as a freshman at Yale, she publishes a world-weary
article in The New York Times Magazine called ``A Teen-Ager Looks
Back at Life,'' and he writes to her.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Ms. Maynard drops out of Yale to live an isolated
life with Salinger. He belittles her ambition, is suspicious of the
outside world. After nine months, he tells her to leave. Later, Ms.
Maynard says, she learns he has written to other young women whom
he will also ``discard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard, who is divorced, has said that she is selling
Salinger's letters, which Sotheby's estimates will bring in $60,000
to $80,000, for her children's college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But this seems not really to be about money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the money has a huge amount to do with it,'' Ms.
Maynard says. ``I have maybe $10 right now in my checking account.
I give people apple pie lessons, I charge people $25 to come to my
house and make apple pies. I sold a book to the movies for $300,000
four years ago, but last year I made nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   This still seems to be about rage and payback and coming in for
the auction to have a ringside seat at the hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no _ I know you're wrong,'' Ms. Maynard says. ``I know the
day he dies will be a very sad one for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does Ms. Maynard feel she has to be so open?
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in an alcoholic family,'' she says. ``My parents
were the most dazzling, articulate people you could imagine. And
among all this love of words the one thing we could never mention
was my father's drinking. I had this idea that I had to keep this
perfect girl picture and never let anybody find out who I was. I
write my first book when I'm 19. Everybody criticizing me, I don't
want to join in, but I never liked that book. It was supposed to be
the voice of youth, but I never said what the young person was
really doing _ that I'd dropped out of college, was living with
J.D. Salinger, making myself throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People can call it narcissistic,'' Ms. Maynard says, ``but I
know absolutely my commitment to telling my story. It's also the
story of many women who don't feel free to tell their stories. I'm
the designated hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Later comes the message that she won't be attending the auction
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
