<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS22-CO     06-22 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stayin' alive in NYC: Knicks beat Spurs 89-81
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Playing with the ferocity that brought them to a
level in the playoffs that appeared utterly unattainable for an
eighth-seeded team, the New York Knicks road a three-headed scoring
monster to a 89-81victory that halved San Antonio's lead in the NBA
Finals to 2-1 Monday night in frantic Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston (34), Latrell Sprewell (24) and Larry Johnson (16)
scored all but 15 of New York's points to save a banged-up team
that appeared on the cusp of being swept. David Robinson and Tim
Duncan combined for 45 points that were not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy worried about a lot of things before his players
took the floor for the game that would either resurrect their
chance at a championship or doom them.
</P>
<P>
   He was concerned about the health of forward Larry Johnson _
``He's on a heckuva lot of pain medication'' _ and Johnson's
ability to help his cause with 3-point shooting early in the game.
``When he makes those shots he helps us win games. When he misses,
it's that much tougher for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He fretted over how many minutes he could expect from his
athletic young center-forward Marcus Camby because ``when he plays
a long stretch of time he gets fatigued, but that's true with
everyone on our team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson remained in the lineup despite his injury and his
off-day tirade and Van Gundy considered starting Camby because the
Knicks needed some energy. ``You make a lineup change, you have to
believe in it,'' the coach said, but he did not come off as a man
operating with great conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Too, he was concerned about the Knicks' ability to hold on at
the end of each half ``because of fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   When they jumped ahead early he got some of what he wanted, but
when Camby committed his second foul after only 5:25 he appeared to
have lost that gamble. Still, the Knicks led by as many as 14 in a
late-first quarter shootout. But it appeared to sap them, because
the Spurs quickly asserted themselves, drawing within four points
on Tim Duncan's three-point play midway of the second quarter and
then 42-40 on Sean Elliott's leaner at 3:51.
</P>
<P>
   For a team trying to get back in a series, a 49-46 halftime lead
was hardly comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes prompted a confrontation between Camby and Robinson
1:20 into the second half, their bumping and shoving leading to
double personal and technical fouls. Only 10 seconds later, Camby
committed his fourth personal _ against Robinson _ and had to leave
again.
</P>
<P>
   All this ignited Houston. He sank three straight shots, the last
a trey, and the Knicks led 56-47. But the Knicks did not score a
field goal from Houston's 3-pointer at 9:17 until 3:04. That
included 12 missed shots and 2-of-4 free throwing.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs crept back to tie at 58 on Duncan's hook with 3:34
left. It was Houston who broke the spell with a 3-pointer, adding
two more free throws, giving him 30 points on the game and the
Knicks a lead of five. But Duncan rallied the Spurs. He had 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
