</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TOP SPURS, 89-81 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Allan Houston took an ominous situation and turned it
into an inspirational journey around David Robinson, Tim Duncan and
the mighty San Antonio Spurs on Monday night before an awestruck
crowd at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The fans watched in wonder as Houston, undaunted by the
predicament the Knicks found themselves in during the National
Basketball Association finals, scored a career playoff-high 34
points to lead his team to an 89-81 victory in Game 3. At the same
time, he preserved faith in a Knicks team that seemed on the verge
of being swept in this series. They now trail two games to one,
with Game 4 at the Garden on Wednesday night and Game 5 there
Friday night,
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended San Antonio's record playoff run of 12
victories in a row and was their first on the road in these
playoffs. The Spurs got 20 points from Duncan, who was blanked in
the fourth quarter, and 25 from Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   But the night belonged to Houston, who saved the Knicks from
doom in the end. The Knicks had a 78-68 lead with seven minutes
left after a jumper from Houston. But after some poor execution,
which included a wild turnover by Latrell Sprewell (24 points), the
Spurs pulled within 4, 81-77, on a 3-pointer from Sean Elliott with
3 minutes 11 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Houston came back and nailed a jumper over Elliott to give the
Knicks their breathing room. Then Marcus Camby, who was having a
miserable night in his first start as a Knick, came back and hit an
11-foot fallaway jumper to put the Knicks ahead, 85-77, with 2:18
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks made more changes than just the addition of Marcus
Camby in the starting lineup to replace Chris Dudley. They altered
their thinking. Instead of going one on one against the Spurs,
Houston and Sprewell worked together to create open shots for each
other, and it worked to the tune of a 32-21 lead after the first
quarter. But after a sloppy and somewhat chaotic second quarter by
the Knicks, the Spurs were able to creep back into the game and
pull within 3, 49-46, at the break.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks calmed down and went back to Houston to start the
third quarter. After scoring 18 points in the first half, he kept
cooking and scored over Mario Elie on three straight possessions,
including a 3-pointer in transition that put the Knicks up, 56-47,
with 9:16 left in the third. At that point, Houston had 25 points,
almost half his team's total.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting flustered, Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich called
two quick timeouts to get his team on its defensive game. It
worked. After a turnover by Charlie Ward and two missed shots by
Sprewell, the Spurs were within 4, 58-54, with five minutes left in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was screaming for Houston to get the ball, but the
Spurs were double-teaming him every time he touched the ball. And
as the shot clock kept melting down, the Knicks were forcing up bad
shots that were being rebounded by the Spurs, who were within 58-56
with 4:01 left in the third. They tied it on a Duncan bank shot 30
seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston was unflappable. He picked up a loose ball as the
shot clock was running out and knocked down a 3-pointer at the
24-second buzzer. Then he drove into Jaren Jackson and found his
way to the free-throw line to put the Knicks up by 5, 63-58.
Problem was, Houston was the only thing going for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the shot blocking of Robinson and Duncan, it was the
poor shooting from the outside and at the line by Sprewell that was
keeping the Knicks from taking to a nice lead. Sprewell, who was 0
for 6 from the floor in the third, missed four of five free throws
in one stretch before hitting one with 1.2 seconds left to give the
Knicks a 65-62 lead entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Knicks' shooting percentage had dipped into the
30s, but by sheer volume of shots, they were ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Each team had blistered the other's defense in the first half.
The Knicks, led by Houston's 18 points and Sprewell's 12, shot 46
percent against the league's best defense. But the Spurs shot 51.4
percent against the league's second-best defense.
</P>
<P>
   While the Knicks tinkered with their game plan, the Spurs played
the same steady beat, pounding the ball into Robinson and Duncan,
who combined for 26 points and 11 rebounds in the first half. It
didn't matter if Camby was out there or not, they were still
dominating. An overeager Camby, who picked up his second foul four
minutes into the game, finished the first half with one rebound,
one blown dunk and no points in eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks' other big man, Larry Johnson, was having more
success this time around. After shooting 20 percent in Games 1 and
2, Johnson, who has been hindered by a sprained knee, looked more
mobile. He spun and shook as he worked in the post against Duncan,
scoring 10 first-half points on 5-for-9 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   This was more like it for the Knicks. They were playing with
balance while still attacking and getting to the free-throw line.
For once, they were ahead in the latter department. In the first
half, the Knicks went to the line 12 times _ which included 10
successful trips by Houston _ and the Spurs took 10 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Dumping selfishness for togetherness turned a Knicks season on
the verge of ruin into a stunning success story. That unselfishness
was evident from the start on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   A hot Houston helped give the Knicks an 11-point lead after the
first quarter. It was a lead built on teamwork and
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Once Houston sat down, the Knicks went to Johnson in the post,
and he delivered some fancy post moves around Duncan. They were
rolling as they took a 40-33 lead with six minutes left in the
second quarter. But the Spurs' defense started applying more
pressure, and the Knicks turned the ball over on three consecutive
possessions, allowing the Spurs to crawl back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were doing what the Knicks had done to little avail in
the first two games: they were hanging around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
