r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     06-22 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS JACKSON AN L.A. GUY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Halfway though Phil Jackson's first press
conference as coach of the Los Angeles Lakers, someone in the
audience wondered if he thought it would be a difficult transition
for him to become a L.A. Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Now I've never quite understood such an arcane connotation,
perhaps because over the past several decades I've met a wide
variety of people of the male gender from this area who haven't fit
any classic stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   What is a L.A. Guy, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who reads Daily Variety, adheres to the trends and
styles in L.A. Magazine, goes nowhere without a beeper and cell
phone, and is constantly ducking creditors because of a mindless
need to make a false public impression by buying expensive cars and
homes he can't afford?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who doesn't smoke, diligently monitors his diet,
works out feverishly, surfs, mountain climbs, dates groovy chicks,
invests in stocks, holds down a high-paying computer job and is a
dues-paying member of Great Expectations?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who has had a few bit parts in movies no one has
seen, hangs out in the Sky Bar and House of Blues, shamelessly
embellishes the truth, has no visible means of support, and acts
like a big shot at dinner gatherings until the waiter delivers a
tab that always results in his making mysterious disappearances?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who has Michael Ovitz's private number, plays gin
with the fellows at Bel Air, once dated Jennifer O'Neal, regularly
sees a manicurist, masseuse and aesthetician, thinks Bill Clinton
is a gas, and calls himself a venture capitalist even though he's a
trust-fund bum who has been rescued countless times from failed
investments from his long-suffering mother?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who has breakfast with Larry King at Nate `n' Al's
Deli in Beverly Hills, or is able to get a script read by Steven
Speilberg, or has had a legal beef with Michael Eisner, or is a
regular at Jerry Buss' pre-game Laker dinners, or knows Richard
Riordan on a first-name basis?
</P>
<P>
   Is it someone who looks like Brad Pitt, or Mike Myers?
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, I have no idea what construes the quintessential L.A.
Guy, although I will, in my never-ending quest to upgrade the
sporting scene in these parts, offer Phil Jackson a few tips on how
to survive his upcoming L.A. Odyssey:
</P>
<P>
   Don't Upset Dyan Cannon: I'm not sure either Del Harris or Kurt
Rambis paid proper homage to the Lakers' most passionate female
celebrity patron when they were bumbling oops, pardon me running
Laker matters. I don't know if she practices voodoo if she doesn't
like you, but never underestimate this venerable Hollywood survivor
who once even managed to marry Cary Grant. Keep her on your side,
Phil.
</P>
<P>
   See To It That Your Limo Driver Knows The Directions To The
Huntington Library: This pristine Pasadena sanctuary with its
gorgeous Japanese gardens and its impressive collection of art will
be a perfect spot for Jackson, the Zen master, to meditate when
he's having problems convincing Shaquille O'Neal that O'Neal should
spend all his spare moments studying film footage of Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Find Time To Have A Post-Game Cold One With Ol' Doc Buss: There
is nothing Jerry Buss likes more in life except for meeting ladies
a third his age than sitting around in the Forum press lounge after
a Laker match and gabbing it up with friends. It's always a
spirited affair with the participants also consuming plenty of
spirits. Like Buss, Jackson is well-versed on a wide range of
subjects, although I'm not sure his liver has the same iron
constitution as Buss'.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange A Sitdown With Ice Cube: The famed LA. rapper is a big
Laker fan and Kobe Bryant admirer. Jackson needs all the allies he
can muster as he gets ready to attempt a most delicate maneuver
transforming Kobe Bryant from a selfish, me-first basketball player
into one who actually is sensitive to the wants and needs of
teammates. There is no doubt that young Kobe is going to brood for
a while about this wild Jackson scheme, and Jackson doesn't need
the aggravation of being dissed in a rap song, does he?
</P>
<P>
   Refrain From Reminding Jerry West How Great A Player He Once
Was: There is nothing the top Laker executive detests more in life
than being shamelessly patronized. He doesn't see himself as anyone
special even though he was it is West's likeness on the official
NBA logo and he can spot a phony faster than he once was able to
drive past a defender. Jackson will have no problem in his dealings
with West unless he decides to bring up the 1972-73 season when
Jackson's New York Knicks beat West's Lakers across five games in
the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   Memorize Jack Nicholson's Greatest Lines ``Herrrrrrrres,
Johnny!'' Jackson can roar to the Academy Award winning actor,
mimicking Nicholson's famous refrain from ``The Shining.'' This
definitely would win Jackson a few Brownie points with Nicholson,
who would inevitably inform all his Hollywood pals what a swell guy
Phil Jackson is. I wonder if Del Harris ever tried such a tack with
Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Know Your Long Beach Getaways: When things are unfolding
miserably Shaq missing free throws, Kobe taking goofy shots, Derek
Fisher committing too many turnovers, J.R. Reid and Robert Horry
shying away from rebounds, etc. Phil Jackson should seek refuge in
our fair city. He can titillate himself with such thrilling
diversions as chasing ghosts at the Queen Mary, inspecting fish at
the Aquarium of the Pacific, discussing police procedures with John
Morris, gazing at celebrities at Trani's, exchanging bon mots with
Fightin' Bob Maxson &AMP; Bev O'Neill and engaging the pint-sized beer
baron Whitey Littlefield in a mean game of hopscotch, or a water
pistol duel.
</P>
<P>
   Know The Way To LAX: When all else fails with the Lakers, Phil
Jackson always can repair to an airport that can return him from
wherever he came and away from the harrowing trouble that
inevitably awaits him at his new calling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
