</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GUARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' POINT GUARDS CONTINUE TO HAVE PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The talk in the last few days had been about the
Knicks abandoning their embattled and ineffective point guards
completely, sitting them on the bench so a bigger lineup could try
to generate offense against the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the Knicks' offense finally came to life in the
89-81 victory but the point guard woes _ a burden that has plagued
them since former general manager Ernie Grunfeld showered millions
on two players who together had one fewer assist than David
Robinson did entering Game 3 _ got a bit worse. Coach Jeff Van
Gundy stayed with a standard backcourt, not pairing Latrell
Sprewell and Allan Houston together. But Chris Childs, the backup
who has outplayed starter Charlie Ward for much of the season,
sprained his left knee in the second quarter in a scuffle for a
loose ball with Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   How bad did things go? Childs was called for a kicked ball
violation and, fittingly for the kind of frustration these point
guards so frequently generate, Duncan got the ball. Childs
returnred midway through the fourth quarter, but finished with just
three points and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Knicks, Allan Houston's spectacular one-man
performance rendered the point guards an afterthought once again.
Houston and Sprewell had better luck going aggressively to the
basket than they had in the first two games and Houston, in
particular, was sterling from outside. Houston (34) and Sprewell
(24) combined for 58 points.
</P>
<P>
   But before Childs got hurt, he was part of one play that
captured the futility of the point guard tandem. With 5 minutes 21
seconds left in the second quarter and the Knicks leading by 42-35,
Ward reached in an stripped Duncan of the ball. But on the run,
Ward tried to heave the ball downcourt and instead, the Spurs'
Antonio Daniels intercepted it. He fed Duncan, who drove into the
lane for a dunk just as a trailing Childs reached up to grab his
arm for a senseless foul. When Duncan hit the free throw to compete
the 3-point play, the Knicks' mistakes had caused a five-point
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Childs' injury caused the Knicks to rely more on Ward, a
situation they wanted to avoid, despite Childs' struggle to score
in this series. Childs backs up Ward, but has outplayed him most of
the season, most acutely in the later playoff rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has been unable to perform in the new up-tempo offense. A
former college quarterback who seems best suited for a game where
he knows all the plays and has time to watch them develop, Ward's
minutes have dwindled as the Knicks have evolved from a halfcourt
offense to a run-and-gun group. While Ward's statistics are
slightly better than Childs' in this series _ he had scored 12
points and six assists to Childs' six points and four assists
entering Game 3 _ it is clear Van Gundy hoped Childs could not only
run the offense, but make himself the team's third scoring option.
</P>
<P>
   Until Game 3, the offense had foundered no matter who was at the
point, with the Knicks wasting precious seconds on the shot clock,
unable to get into their offensive sets until just 10 or 12 seconds
remained on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing: Chris Childs and Charlie Ward's importance
doesn't diminish,'' Van Gundy said before Game 3. ``Particularly
Chris. We need him not on the bench. We need him to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in the first-round series against Miami did Ward play more
minutes than Childs. Childs played 10 more minutes in the Atlanta
series and in the Pacers' series, Childs played 174 minutes to
Ward's 114. Not coincidentally, Childs' minutes increased
dramatically after Patrick Ewing got hurt. But with Childs
struggling to find his touch against the Spurs, he has split time
almost evenly with Ward.
</P>
<P>
   With Ewing out and Larry Johnson hobbled and hesitant, Childs
has failed to establish himself as a third scoring option with
Sprewell and Houston. He shot a combined 3 for 16 in the first two
games of the finals and took just two shots, and had no assists or
steals before leaving Game 3 after just 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not having turnovers dribbling up the floor,'' Childs
said before the game. ``What we're not doing successfully is
getting the ball up the court a lot quicker to get in our offense a
lot earlier. We're getting the ball with four or five seconds left
on the shot clock and we're not able to swing it or make a better
decision. But I just haven't shot the ball well. If I'm going to
shoot eight times, I need to make more than two shots. If I'm out
there, I still have to take the shots that are presented. I have to
knock it down. I have to get it to the basket better and get us
some easy baskets.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
