<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS LOSE COMPOSURE IN GAME 3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rowdiness of the New York fans and the breadth of
the situation were not supposed to rattle the reserved and
typically unflappable San Antonio Spurs. Their experience, their
calm, even their educations, were supposed to make the setting and
scenario a nonissue in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs, the National Basketball Association's ultimate
road warriors, melted beneath the heat of the Madison Square Garden
stage.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, when the intensity was feverish, the
seemingly frazzled Spurs committed four turnovers, earned two
technical fouls and allowed the Knicks to score 32 points against
their vaunted league-best defense.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was only the Spurs' second of the post-season and their
first on the road. It broke a 12-game winning streak that included
six road victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who had won by an average of 13.4 points on the road,
had not lost a road game since April 27 at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed more frazzled than Mario Elie, the Spurs' edgy
off-guard who grew up five minutes away from the Garden. Admittedly
excited about playing in the gym of his dreams, he committed two
quick fouls in less than two minutes and received a technical for
screaming at the officials after his second one. It was not the
gallant homecoming he had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always dreamed about playing in the Garden, about playing
five minutes from the crib,'' Elie said before the game. ``I had to
get 22 tickets, so I'm excited about family and friends watching. I
know where everybody's going to sit, so when I make a good move,
I'll make sure to point at my little section up there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no pointing, though, as Elie scored just five points
and was scorched all night long by Allan Houston. But Elie was not
alone in his futility. Avery Johnson, the usually sure-handed point
guard, committed two turnovers in the first quarter and four in the
first half. He averaged just 2.2 per game during the regular season
and only 2.5 throughout the playoffs. Johnson made up for his
errors somewhat by scoring 8 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the Spurs' coach, Gregg Popovich, was called for a
technical foul late in the first quarter for arguing an official's
call after a Knicks' foul. Then, the Spurs earned another technical
that led to a free throw by Houston for playing an illegal defense
in the final seconds of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   While the Knicks rode the emotion of the Garden crowd to a
blistering start, Tim Duncan suffered through an
uncharacteristically unproductive start. Missing three of his four
shots, he managed just two points over the first 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Knicks wanted to capitalize and to a certain
extent, they did, taking a 32-21 lead. But because of the
unexpected offense of Johnson and Antonio Daniels the advantage
seemed far from commanding. It is true that Robinson was big,
posting 9 points and 4 rebounds in the first quarter, but if
Johnson and Daniels had not picked up their games, it might not
have mattered. The two point guards kept the game from getting out
of hand until Duncan found himself and regained his dominating
form.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who averaged only 5 points through the first two games
of this series, scored 4 in the first quarter and 8 in the first
half. While his teammates seemed somewhat shocked, he scored on two
of the Spurs' first three field goals on driving layups in which he
moved right through the Knicks' defense. The baskets kept the Spurs
from starting the game in a near standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution of Daniels, the forgotten backup, was even more
significant. After Elie and Jaren Jackson picked up two fouls
apiece while trying to stick with the slithering Houston, the
Spurs' coach Gregg Popovich was forced to insert Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, who was moved deeper down San Antonio's bench in favor
of Steve Kerr during the Western Conference final series against
Portland, responded hugely, nailing two 3-pointers in the final 2
minutes, 35 seconds of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   His first triple sliced an 11-point Knicks' lead, their biggest
of the game to that point, to eight. His second came from 29 feet
out with nine-tenths of a second remaining in the quarter and
followed a 3-pointer by Chris Childs. It kept the Knicks from
entering the second quarter with absolute momentum. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
