<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-22 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMNL WITH LUGS LIKE THESE, WHO KNOWS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his ugly tirade on Sunday, Larry Johnson pumped
a dose of reality into the finals. He allowed everybody to root for
this to be over immediately, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, oddly enough, did not feel that way. The freelance
forays by Messrs. Houston, Sprewell and Camby that brought the
Knicks into the finals were revived in the friendly environment of
the Garden on Monday night, as the Knicks defeated San Antonio,
89-81. Now the series must last at least until Friday _ and with
these inconsistent lugs, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks had lost on Monday night, the best scenario would
have been to stay right on the court and play the fourth game
rather than make everybody plod back to the Garden on Wednesday for
a fourth game. A numb nation was already crying out: ``Just get it
over with.''
</P>
<P>
   As my mailman, Jimmy, said on Monday, ``Geez, the Little League
season is over, except for the playoffs. School is out. Spring
soccer is over. But the NBA is still playing?''
</P>
<P>
   Let's move on to Michelle Akers and Linda Medalen, predestined
to bump their combative old noggins in the final of the Women's
World Cup. Let's move on to Jeter and Junior. Maybe Steffi will
spank the little brat Martina at Wimbledon. Let us try to answer
the question that has been nagging me all spring: ``Who is this
Roger Cedeno, and why doesn't Bobby Valentine start him every
game?'' Let us look into the strip-mining of the Islanders' hockey
franchise by the Millstone gang. There is much to do.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Knicks made more than a few of us giddy, as
if we were on laughing gas. That noted observer of the passing
scene, Don Imus, railed against the front-running euphoria of some
New Yorkers (no names mentioned, for fear of self-incrimination).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever claimed the Knicks were all fine fellows, but for a
few crazed days my theory was that it was O.K. to appreciate their
weird and belated internal combustion. After all, they did beat
Riley, Wilkens and Bird in rapid succession. (Now that we think
about it, the Pacers really should be ashamed of themselves.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came to the Knicks with a history of crude gestures
while representing the United States in the world championships. He
had a feud with the sweet and affable Alonzo Mourning in Charlotte.
He hasn't exactly been Prince Charming in New York, but rather the
new face of the post-Buck, post-Doc, post-Michael, National
Basketball Association that makes Commissioner David Stern blanch
behind his doggedly optimistic remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Stern was playing spinmeister on Monday morning in his official
State of the Post-Jordan-Apocalypse address. He discussed setting a
minimum age for rookies and he also discussed the need for better
fundamentals in a time when players are shooting to impress the
director of the cable highlight shows rather than to impress their
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is time to make the players pass a fundamentals test
(layups off the glass, two-handed foul shots, soft bounce passes,
boxing out on defense) in order to qualify for a license to play
basketball, like the ancient craft guilds in Europe. But don't hold
your breath.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 playoffs have now lasted practically as long as the
entire ugly lockout-shortened season. Enough, already. That grating
sound you heard was millions of television remote-control clickers
all seeking something, anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks persevered as first Patrick Ewing and then Johnson
went down with injuries. Johnson earned a combat ribbon for willing
himself back without missing a game, but he has not been the same,
and that clearly frustrated him. But he gets gigged for $25,000 and
his team gets gigged the same for his profanity-laced outburst at
Sunday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   By cursing at league officials and his blatant contempt for the
world around him, Johnson brought us back to square one _ the
pushing and the shoving, the hard fouls and the no helping-hands of
the Riley regime, the intramural bickering, the backstabbing by the
suits, the parade of new owners, the general lack of soul coming
out of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tim Duncan and David Robinson set a tone of grace and
manners _ and skill. And Hersey Hawkins, who plays a continent away
in Seattle, received the sportsmanship award on Monday. Larry
Johnson did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had the right to dream on Monday night but Johnson's
outburst has reminded New Yorkers just what they have been going
gaga over. For that, we thank him. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
