r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     06-22 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WILL THE STARS REPEAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ken Hitchcock stood before a packed crowd at Reunion
Arena yesterday and announced his plans for the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we got one of these, why not make it two?'' the
Stars coach shouted to a pep rally that had gathered to honor the
Stars' first Stanley Cup championship. ``Hell, let's go for
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the champagne or the adrenalin rush from the
celebration. Maybe Hitchcock was just playing to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, seriously, can the Stars really be thinking about a
dynasty?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is an organization that wants to be competitive
every year, every game,'' Hitchcock said. ``And I believe it's an
organization that has been built by Bob \RGainey\S to win for the
long-term. I don't think our goals change just because we've won it
once.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will start their quest for a second Stanley Cup this
week with the expansion draft and entry draft. The push will
continue next week with the July 1 start of free agency, and it
will continue throughout the summer as Stars management tries to
solidify the roster for next season.
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars already have under contract a team that could
probably compete for next year's Cup, they also know that keeping
the fringes strong is one of the key reasons this team was able to
survive the grueling 60-day run to the championship.
</P>
<P>
   So how do they deal with the roster tweaks, the expectations,
the fact they already are physically exhausted and beaten up? How
do they take just two months off and return in early September for
training camp? How does a team regain the hunger needed to overcome
the hardships? How does a team survive the expectations of wearing
the No. 1 target?
</P>
<P>
   How does a team repeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to take it slowly, take a step back, always
be prepared for your decisions, build in a similar way to what we
did here,'' said Gainey, the Stars' general manager. ``I hope that
what we have built is something that has been built for the
long-term, and I think it is. From there, we have to just try to
continue to make decisions that we believe are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey has done that, and that's one reason this won't be a
controversial summer. The Stars already have secured long-term
contracts with several players: Mike Modano, Derian Hatcher, Darryl
Sydor, Brett Hull and Mike Keane. Players under contract for next
season are Jere Lehtinen, Jamie Langenbrunner, Sergei Zubov, Ed
Belfour, Joe Nieuwendyk, Shawn Chambers, Brian Skrudland and Grant
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Those players _ mixed with young prospects Juha Lind, Jason
Botterill, Brad Lukowich, Jon Sim, Blake Sloan, Jamie Wright, Manny
Fernandez and Marty Turco _ give the Stars a competitive team.
However, there are some key questions Gainey and his staff must
answer.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Stars have to decide in the next few weeks whether
Guy Carbonneau, 39, and Craig Ludwig, 38, are too old to play, or
whether they have one last run at a Stanley Cup remaining. Both
veterans have contracts in which the Stars hold the option.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau is almost a guaranteed return. While the Stars have
solid checking-line centers they would like to bring over from
Europe, including Pavel Patera and Roman Lyashenko, and have a
scrappy center in Aaron Gavey already in the system, no player has
the experience and grit of Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig, on the other hand, has tougher competition behind him.
Brad Lukowich, 22, played well in playoff situations. Petr Buzek,
22, Richard Jackman, 21, and Alan Latang, 23, also could be given a
chance to play at the NHL level. Or the Stars could go out and get
a more fleet-footed defenseman through free agency to pair with
Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   The club also has options on Benoit Hogue, Derek Plante and
Brent Severyn. Do the Stars need to keep those players or decide
they can live without the higher salaries of Hogue ($2 million) and
Plante ($1 million)?
</P>
<P>
   After they make those decisions, the Stars have to try to decide
if they want to sign any of their unrestricted free agents. Dave
Reid seems a bargain at $700,000 after he contributed 10 points in
the playoffs. Would he come back at the same price? Pat Verbeek
can't possibly be retained at $3.2 million, but maybe he'd play for
less. Tony Hrkac will almost assuredly be back with his $350,000
price tag.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Stars have to find out what the price is to keep
restricted free-agent Richard Matvichuk. As a restricted free
agent, the Stars have the right to match any offer on Matvichuk.
Because owner Tom Hicks has shown the ability to spend money, no
team is expected to make an offer to Matvichuk knowing Hicks will
likely match. That means the Stars and Matvichuk will have to come
up with a fair salary, something Matvichuk would likely want to be
more than $2 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars might also try to tie up playoff most valuable player
Nieuwendyk, goalie Belfour and defenseman Zubov to long-term deals,
but those are discussions that will take place later in the summer.
However, the thought of long-term deals brings up an interesting
issue about the future drives for future Stanley Cups. Will Belfour
come back with the same calm after winning the Cup? Will Nieuwendyk
have the same drive that pushed him through a grueling summer of
knee rehabilitation? Will Modano's wrist heal properly? What about
Hull's knee? Will the Stars continue to push themselves just as
hard for Hitchcock, whose driving, defensive style can at times be
wearing?
</P>
<P>
   The players don't have the monetary carrots hanging out there.
Is inner drive enough?
</P>
<P>
   Those are cruel questions for a team of players celebrating the
greatest moment in their respective athletic lives, but they're
questions that are asked by teams that have designs on repeating.
They are questions that are answered by teams that do repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have less time to get ready for next year and we'll have to
tackle the physical challenges next year,'' said Craig Button,
director of player personnel. ``But at the same time, once you've
done it, you know what it takes. You can always draw on that
experience next year and even in the summer. If you want to win,
you have to pay a price. And these players want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting them to want it just as badly, to be able to come
through even more hardship has to be a difficult challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In juniors, the first one was always the toughest one,''
Hitchcock said. ``Winning is good for any organization. I think you
just have to look at it like the Chicago Bulls or anyone else that
wins consistently. You make winning a part of your team, and your
team lives winning every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean expectations can be negative or expectations can be
positive,'' Hitchcock added. ``Here, I believe the expectation to
win is a positive thing. We should expect to win every year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
