<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     06-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WITH LUGS LIKE THESE, WHO KNOWS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no hint of this. None. There was nothing in
the first two games to suggest that the Knicks could minimize Tim
Duncan, and win their last chance to make something of this
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   How much could a home-court advantage _ even those loud and
demanding Garden fans _ be worth after two sluggish games in San
Antonio? How could the Knicks possibly overcome the player who has
roared past Shaq and Hill and everybody else of his generation? How
could they get over the loss of Patrick Ewing and the injury to
Larry Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Totally improbably, the freelance forays by Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell that brought the Knicks into the finals were
revived in the friendly environment of the Garden on Monday night,
as the Knicks defeated the Spurs, 89-81. Now the series must last
at least until Friday _ and with these inconsistent lugs, who
knows?
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks had lost on Monday night, the best scenario would
have been to stay right on the court and play the fourth game
rather than make everybody plod back to the Garden tomorrow for a
fourth game. A numb nation was already crying out: ``Just get it
over with.''
</P>
<P>
   As my mailman, Jimmy, said on Monday, ``Geez, the Little League
season is over, except for the playoffs. School is out. Spring
soccer is over. But the NBA is still playing?''
</P>
<P>
   And still playing. And still playing. It was time to move on to
Michelle Akers and Linda Medalen, predestined to bump their
combative old noggins in the final of the Women's World Cup. Time
to focus on to Jeter and Junior. Maybe Steffi will spank the little
brat Martina at Wimbledon. Let us try to answer the question that
has been nagging me all spring: ``Who is this Roger Cedeno, and why
doesn't Bobby Valentine start him every game?'' Let us look into
the strip-mining of the Islanders' hockey franchise by the
Millstone gang. There is much to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had even forfeited any dubious potential as lovable
comeback kids. Johnson earned a combat ribbon for willing himself
back from his sprained knee without missing a game, but then he got
himself gigged for $25,000 and his team gigged the same amount for
his profane outburst at Sunday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took us back to square one _ the pushing and the
shoving, the hard fouls and the no helping-hands of the Riley
regime, the intramural bickering, the backstabbing by the suits,
the parade of new owners, the general lack of soul coming out of
the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Duncan and David Robinson set a tone of grace and
manners _ and skill. And Hersey Hawkins, who plays a continent away
in Seattle, received the sportsmanship award on Monday. Larry
Johnson did not.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the Knicks with a history of crude gestures while
representing the United States in the world championships. He had a
feud with the sweet and affable Alonzo Mourning in Charlotte. He
hasn't exactly been Prince Charming in New York, but rather the new
face of the post-Buck, post-Doc, post-Michael, National Basketball
Association that makes Commissioner David Stern blanch behind his
doggedly optimistic remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson allowed anybody but a diehard Knicks fan to root for
this series to be over immediately, if not sooner. In recent weeks,
that noted observer of the passing scene, Don Imus, railed against
the front-running euphoria of some New Yorkers (no names mentioned,
for fear of self-incrimination).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever claimed the Knicks were all fine fellows, but my
theory was that it was okay to appreciate their weird and belated
internal combustion.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is happening again. The Spurs started slowly, but after
the first two games, there was every reason to think they could
pound the ball inside to Duncan _ ``certainly the best player in
the NBA,'' said Jeff Van Gundy of the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   There was not even an air of desperation in the Garden. There
have been more emotional nights in the place. Maybe it was the
sense of inevitability about the intelligent and patient Duncan,
gliding to his spots on the court. Going into the fourth quarter,
Duncan had 20 points and gave the aura of somebody about to take
the game over. He did not. He rushed a few shots, missed all four
he attempted, and never scored again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This showed the true character of the Knicks,'' Van Gundy
said. ``That was the first time we lost two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   That character includes Larry Johnson's ugly outburst on Sunday.
They are not a lovable bunch, but they won a game with no warning
whatsoever. They are still here. All else is still on hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
