<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMNNYT &LR;      06-22 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMNNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON GIVES THE KNICKS NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As he faced up Sean Elliott at the free throw line
with 3 minutes left _ rising for the shot as Madison Square Garden
rose with him _ it became clear even before the ball rattled around
and through the net:
</P>
<P>
   To get to San Antonio, you must first go through Houston.
</P>
<P>
   With the season essentially in the balance on Monday night, the
most reliable player for the Knicks in the postseason stepped to
forefront again in Game 3 of the finals and delivered another
pulsating performance.
</P>
<P>
   As pretty as his game was _ 34 points in 45 minutes and 4
assists _ Houston's less-noticeable contributions were the reason
why the Knicks have life against this impossibly tall and talented
Spurs team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to give it up to Allan tonight, he's the one who got
some of those guys in foul trouble early and ended up making it
easier for us down the stretch,'' said Latrell Sprewell. ``He was
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the first quarter, he was taking the ball to
Mario Elie, the physical and tenacious Spurs swingman, the only
native New Yorker in the finals, who came to town this week with
more confidence in his left pinky than the Knicks had in their
entire locker room.
</P>
<P>
   After two quick fouls, Elie became enraged enough to warrant a
technical and had to be sat down. The player who had help take
Houston out of his rhythm in Games 1 and 2 was suddenly
discombobulated himself.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Jaren Jackson, who also found the going tough
against Houston. Coach Jeff Van Gundy, remembering the success
Houston had had when isolated on the left wing in Game 6 against
Indiana, used that formula until the well went dry on Monday night.
Steve Kerr even got an opportunity to stop Houston in the third
quarter, and he too had little success.
</P>
<P>
   The player who so often had settled for jump shots was taking
the ball with aggression to the basket, making Tim Duncan and David
Robinson leave their men. Houston made-believe he was a point guard
at times, penetrating through the lane and finding his open
teammates on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   He made his free throws, all 12 of 12. And, finally, when the
defense gave it to him, he stuck that soft jump shot. Again. And
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling more comfortable taking the ball to the basket,''
Houston said after the Knicks came within a game of knotting the
series. ``I'm still not going to pass on any 3-point shots. It felt
good to make one finally. But to stay with this team, we have to
take the ball to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We tried to get the ball closer to the basket. In
the first two games, we were catching the ball way out on the
wings.''
</P>
<P>
   This was shaping up to be a desperate night for the Knicks. They
tried starting Marcus Camby, and he got into early foul trouble.
They tried isolating Sprewell, and he missed often before the
fourth quarter. So worried about making this a series for suitable
viewing, the beat-up and beleaguered Knicks tried every imaginable
defense to stop Duncan from dominating.
</P>
<P>
   And after all that desperation, after all that experimentation,
the one player New York turned to was the obvious choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you be the go-to guy in Game 4?'' he was asked, sitting
in the rotunda area of the Garden an hour after he had sent most
19,763 home in a euphoric state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what it calls on,'' he said, sheepishly. ``I'm
comfortable being in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say he also needs to look for his teammates when
he's covered tightly and everyone contributed and, well, just get
him the ball and get out of the way. He's the closest New York has
to a franchise player at the moment and, his inconsistency
notwithstanding, he's the best chance the Knicks have to make this
good theater.
</P>
<P>
   With 6 minutes, 29 seconds left, he dropped in about an
18-footer that pushed the Knicks ahead by 10 points _ a shot that
sent the Garden into another wild tizzy. After a few tense moments
down the stretch, after the Knicks had emerged with a game they
needed to save their season, they had Houston to thank once more.
</P>
<P>
   Every time this implausible run seems about to hit a wall, the
composed and clutch shooting guard backpacks his team to some other
plateau, above the calamity of the Garden, above Miami, Indiana
and, on Monday night, the best team left standing in the National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month ago, he started this wild script by taking a
pass at the free throw line, splitting the Heat defense and almost
short-arming a shot that hit the front of the rim and the backboard
before softly falling in. Miami Arena was dead quiet. He punched
the air, and the Knicks had moved on in unbelievable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   His last night at the Garden came in Game 6 against Indiana, a
night many say induced louder sound at the Garden than has been
heard in the past decade. Detonating for 32 points, he faced up
Reggie Miller at one point and laughed at him, as if the cocksure
Pacers veteran was not worth the time or effort, before knocking
down a jumper in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Neither that night nor Game 3 was Jordanesque, but it was the
closest thing New York has of that caliber, the closest thing the
Knicks have to combat the awesome talent of Duncan and David
Robinson. Van Gundy can try any adjustment he wants, and some may
eventually pay off over the next week.
</P>
<P>
   But the enduring image of this victory was of Houston rising
from the free throw line and dropping in his sweet shot. It is
clear: you want to get to San Antonio, you have to go through him.
Again. And again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
