<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-22 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ On opening day, in his first at-bat, Mark McGwire
walked, bringing Eric Davis to the plate for the first time as a
Cardinal with two men on and one out.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd booed loudly at Big Mac's free pass, then
several thousand rose in unison from their seats and headed for the
concession stands. Apparently, they had come only for the circus.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, albeit through no fault of his own, is ruining baseball
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals fans, once arguably as knowledgeable and passionate as
any, still stream to Busch Stadium in droves, but they've lost
their sophistication, their appreciation for the game's finer
points. Club management, in turn, has grown fat and complacent,
seemingly content to let the Big Mac sideshow pay the bills and
reap a handsome profit to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The turnstiles tell the story. On Monday night, another 41,506
showed up, the Astros' largest road gate of the season. Everybody
here has gone dinger dingy, Mac mad. How else do you explain what
has happened to the Cards since they won the Central Division in
1996, well before McGwire strode into town and got the locals'
priorities turned upside down?
</P>
<P>
   Once again, St. Louis is mired in mediocrity because no effort
was made over the offseason to shore up a rag-armed pitching staff.
General manager Walt Jocketty's thumbs must be exhausted from all
his twiddling. Come to think of it, he should be hung by same for
letting the situation fester as it has.
</P>
<P>
   First, he frittered away any chance the Cardinals had of keeping
staff ace Andy Benes after the '97 season by refusing to seriously
negotiate until Benes was already house-hunting in Phoenix, then
Jocketty sat around last winter expecting Kevin Brown to come to
him, which the highly coveted Brown hardly needed to do what with
Rupert Murdoch's billions tempting him in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Jocketty turned up his nose at Orel Hershiser,
Pete Harnisch and Hideo Nomo, each of whom would presently be an
improvement over anyone he can give the ball to today save for Kent
Bottenfield, St. Louis' resident 11-3 overachiever who put a
one-earned-run, four-hit clamp on the Astros in a 5-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cards' pitchers killed them last season, they're
routinely committing additional felonies at present, explaining why
St. Louis is below .500 and 7{ games to the rear of the
division-leading, hopefully three-peating Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The one truly relevant stat isn't McGwire's 22 home runs, the
22nd of which soared an estimated 473 feet off Sean Bergman this
night before landing in mid-upper deck. Rather, it's the 5.66 ERA
the Cardinals' starters lugged into the game. That's way last in
the Central and more than two runs per outing over what their
Astros counterparts are allowing, even allowing for Bergman's
thoroughly underwhelming effort.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another negative for your perusal: St. Louis has lost
eight more games than it has won since Big Mac arrived in a trade
that bestowed an instant hero's tag on Jocketty, a status he
continues, amazingly, to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Tony La Russa can't be deemed blameless, however.
Because the Cardinals' dugout genius (if you don't believe it, ask
him) hasn't demanded more of his GM, he deserves the pummeling he's
receiving on the talk shows _ and the firing that may be coming at
season's end if things don't change drastically.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see the Astros complaining, though. They've profited
hugely from the cockeyed value system engulfing a proud franchise
that won nine world championships and 15 National League pennants
between 1926 and 1987 with only one guy _ Johnny Mize in 1940 _
belting as many as 43 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Cards have won with pitching, defense and
their ability to manufacture runs with timely hitting and deft
baserunning. Rogers Hornsby and Stan Musial, Dizzy Dean and Bob
Gibson, plus Lou Brock _ those were the players who always
epitomized the St. Louis style, pre-McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows, the Mac-nificent one can cause tingles all over.
His third-inning blast was indeed awesome to behold. It actually
proved to be the winning run as well, a rare feat despite his
prodigious numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, when the Cardinals' pitching was showing a
measure of promise, before the effects of losing Matt Morris for
the year and both Alan Benes and Donovan Osborne indefinitely
(inevitably, too, given their recent medical histories) would be
fully revealed, this three-night series loomed as an early
showdown, a sneak preview of a hot summer's pennant race to come.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for now, St. Louis is only trying to tread water and
hope for a miraculous turnaround. Or, more modestly, a complete
game. The Cardinals still don't have one, and the overworked
bullpen has been staggered by the burden placed upon it.
</P>
<P>
   The starters are averaging five innings per outing. Even
Bottenfield, whose 11-3 record is more a reflection of aberrantly
high run support behind him than true pitching excellence, has a
mere 87 innings over his 15 starts. He went seven against the
Astros, but they carried him as much as he carried himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as much our lack of offensive prowess,'' Houston's
general manager, Gerry Hunsicker, complained, ``as it was what he
was doing. We wasted a lot of hittable pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   By the Cardinals' humble standards, nonetheless, it proved a
rare masterful performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
