<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-22 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Championships are never supposed to be so very smooth,
so incredibly easy.
</P>
<P>
   You climb this high up the mountain, you come this far, and the
last leg of the journey is supposed to feel more like a crowded,
rocking subway train at rush hour, not a relaxing carriage ride
through Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Spurs have been expecting to happen for the
past month in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, somebody hit back.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the Spurs had figured it was going to be all
through the past month of the NBA playoffs, when they went
nose-to-nose with the abundantly talented Lakers and their youthful
exuberance, when they lined up against the strong and deep and
confident Trail Blazers and their roster full of would-be starters.
</P>
<P>
   In both of the two previous series, the Spurs took a 2-0 lead at
home over LA and Portland and then expected that the real battle
would be engaged as they took to the road.
</P>
<P>
   But first the Lakers fractured from the sledgehammer of the
Spurs' strong inside game and then the Blazers wilted in the heat
of the San Antonio defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sweep. Sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the Spurs take the first two games of the NBA Finals at
home over the Knicks, and broom sales are outpacing the demand for
air conditioning in South Texas on the first day of summer.
</P>
<P>
   However, if it was this easy, then some other team in some other
year would already have done it. Surely, the mighty Bulls with
Michael Jordan dropping in from Mount Olympus would have done it.
</P>
<P>
   Sweep. Sweep. Sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Not ever. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks win Game 3 Monday night 89-81, and just like that Bob
Costas is pumping up the volume on the Knicks' Cinderella story
again, NBC is hoping and praying that it might finally have a
chance at getting TV ratings better than PBS and an ugly NBA season
is spared one more black eye of a wipeout in the championship
round.
</P>
<P>
   So Allan Houston gets on a roll of jump shots early and lives on
a steady diet at the foul line for 34 points and the
never-met-a-shot-he-wouldn't-take Latrell Sprewell fills it up late
for 24 points, and the Knicks make it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as such a big surprise only because so much of
these playoffs has been such a grand disappointment, which probably
shouldn't have been a shock coming on the heels of an ugly regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, after all, were returning home to play in front of
the loud and wild crowd at Madison Square Garden, where Spike Lee
wears his orange towel on the front row, where Billy Crystal and
Chris Rock swap jokes at midcourt, where Jerry Seinfeld fires off
one-liners from just above the court level and the players feed off
all of the sheer energy.
</P>
<P>
   This was a New York game from a New York team playing for a
hungry New York crowd. The Knicks fought and hustled and scrapped
like they were battling for a taxi in a rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks hit the Spurs with a wave of emotion at the start,
they built a 14-point lead in the first half, and they kept their
noses in front practically all the way.
</P>
<P>
   So a 12-game postseason win streak goes up in smoke. But by no
means is there suddenly a fire licking at the Spurs' heels and
threatening to devour them.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Knicks' night, their game to show that they have a
pulse, more of a heart than the Lakers and Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they got the lightning-bolt games from Houston and
Sprewell and yet the Spurs were still breathing down their necks
well into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game where the Spurs may have lost their composure
early or had it taken away from them by the officials. It was a
night that saw Mario Elie hit with two personal fouls and then a
technical while the national anthem was still echoing through the
building. Then Jaren Jackson came in to take his place and was
slapped with two fouls of his own.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game where David Robinson sailed around the basket
for 25 points and 10 rebounds, where Tim Duncan rolled up 20 points
and 12 rebounds and the rest of the Spurs' roster contributed
little _ 36 points and only 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that saw the previously unstoppable Duncan miss
shots and turn the ball over coming down the stretch, and yet the
Spurs were always there, always lurking close enough to keep the
Knicks worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you call this tonight,'' Robinson said. ``We
just never seemed to have our focus in this game. But we are a team
that has always responded well after a loss. We reset, we refocus,
and we come back strong. Hey, they played well, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, somebody hit back.
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed the Knicks' night. But still a long, long way from
being their series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
