<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALATER WASN'T SLEEPWALKING, 2ND EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater could not have been sleepwalking when he
stabbed his wife 44 times and returned 10 to 15 minutes later to
drag her into the family's swimming pool, a prosecution expert
testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepwalkers have no short-term memory,'' sleep specialist
Mark Pressman testified Monday at Falater's murder trial. ``They
wouldn't even know they had attacked a person, much less know where
the victim's body was lying in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning to the body is simply an impossible act for a
sleepwalker,'' said Pressman, a psychologist who directs sleep
disorder centers at two hospitals in suburban Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman is the second sleep expert for the prosecution, which
is expected to wrap up its case today. Closing arguments are likely
tomorrow in the 4-week-old trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman said several other actions _ witnessed by a neighbor or
reported by police _ contradict the sleepwalking defense of the
former Motorola engineer, whose attorneys say the bloody
sleepwalking episode lasted 45 to 50 minutes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Using a flashlight, which police found next to the pool pump
where the knife attack occurred. Pressman said sleepwalkers do not
know if it is day or night, so ``taking a flashlight would indicate
that the person is awake and aware.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Making a calming motion to a pet after allegedly not hearing
his wife screaming loud enough to be heard by a neighbor. ``I find
it hard to believe that he'd respond to the dog in this appropriate
manner and yet not respond to someone screaming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Applying a bandage to his cut hand. Pressman said use of a
bandage involves ``a series of very sophisticated'' motions, ``none
of which could be done by a sleepwalker.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressman's opinion of the Falater case, which he delivered
calmly and clinically, directly contradicted earlier testimony by
an internationally renowned sleep disorders researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Broughton, a Canadian authority on violence by
sleepwalkers, testified that sleepwalking ``is by far the most
probable'' explanation of Falater's admitted killing of the woman
who was his wife of 20 years and the mother of his two children.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman's disagreements with Broughton underlined the
imprecision and lack of uniform standards in the rapidly evolving
study of sleep disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp disagreements between the opposing sides' expert witnesses
have surfaced throughout the trial. They compound the difficulty
facing a jury in a case where a guilty verdict could lead to
Falater's execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different opinions and it's a changing field,''
prosecution expert Dr. David M. Baratz testified Monday, before
Pressman took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   One example of this conflict among experts concerns their
evaluation of the four nights of sleep studies on Falater, who was
brought to St. Luke's Behavioral Health Services in handcuffs. He
has been in the Madison Street Jail since the killing in early
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman said the psychologist who supervised the study used an
inappropriate method of evaluating Falater's sleep patterns. That
expert, who was retained by the defense, concluded that Falater's
brain waves showed the instability during deep sleep that is
characteristic of sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton endorsed that conclusion and the science used to reach
it. Pressman said the sleep study violated protocols that he
regards as sacrosanct, regardless of Broughton's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is really a prime example of why you need a
standard,'' Pressman said. ``Everyone is doing things differently,
and no one knows what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressman not only challenged the empirical evidence presented by
the defense experts, he also disputed their subjective
interpretations of Falater's conduct that night in 1997 and his
reaction in the aftermath of his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said many of Falater's actions, particularly leaving
his dead wife in the pool, struck him as illogical and irrational.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman said he found nothing illogical about Falater's actions
in attacking Yarmila Falater twice, stashing his bloody clothes in
the wheel well of his car, and changing into the pajamas he was
wearing when police arrested him shortly after 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes perfect sense if the defendant was awake and trying
to kill his wife,'' Pressman said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman also helped prosecutor Juan Martinez make the point
that Broughton and other defense experts should have interviewed
the eyewitness instead of relying on written reports.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman said he interviewed the witness, neighbor Greg Koons,
at length. His information was vital to the investigation into
whether Falater was sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Koons, alerted by his girlfriend that someone was screaming
outside, began looking into the Falater yard after the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Koons really gave one of a kind, direct evidence,''
Pressman said. That evidence is unique, he said, because ``there
has never been a case where there was a direct witness of someone
sleepwalking for an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the clinical sleep studies should not be
overstated, Pressman warned, because they cannot prove that Falater
is a sleepwalker. ``The most they could show is that he had the
potential'' to sleepwalk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman will complete his testimony today, after answering
questions that jurors are submitting in writing to Maricopa County
Superior Court Judge Ronald Reinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions today continued the pattern of skepticism about
the defense. One juror on Monday asked if Baratz thought Falater
had changed into his pajamas after stabbing Yarmila because he
anticipated using sleepwalking as a defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a possibility,'' said Baratz, an administrator of the
Sleep Disorder Center at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center in
Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
