<HEADER>
A4694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Kent Bottenfield is keeping one big secret, and the
rest of the National League can only sit back and guess.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sure didn't have the answer Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield tied for the NL lead with his 11th win, and Mark
McGwire homered for the third straight day as the St. Louis
Cardinals snapped the Astros' three-game winning streak with a 5-3
victory at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (11-3), who never had won more than five games in a
season, tied the Astros' Jose Lima for the league lead. He won for
the third time in four starts and helped his cause with a two-run
double during the Cardinals' three-run second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no explanation,'' said outfielder Carl Everett, who had
two of the Astros' five hits in the game. ``He doesn't have the
stuff that you would say can dominate a team. He was doing
something that we obviously couldn't solve. I don't know what it is
that he has that we're not hitting, because everything looks
hittable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we find out pretty soon, because he's keeping a secret.
He's just been going on all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield held the Astros hitless until the fourth inning as
the Cardinals built a 4-0 lead. The righthander allowed three runs
_ one earned _ and four hits in seven innings. Ricky Bottalico
pitched two scoreless innings of relief for his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, which moved within one game of .500, has beaten the
Astros three times in four meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, well behind the pace he set in his record 70-homer
season last year, hit his 22nd home run of the season in the third
inning off Astros starter Sean Bergman (4-4). The blast cleared Big
Mac Land in the left-field upper deck and was estimated at 473
feet, his second-longest of the season, behind only a 484-foot shot
that left Dodger Stadium in May.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman struggled from the outset, never finding a rhythm, and
was gone after four innings. It was his shortest outing since
lasting only 3 innings June 6 at Minnesota. He gave up five runs
and nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched terrible. I didn't make the big pitches when I had
to,'' said Bergman, who surrendered home run No. 39 to McGwire last
season, one of five homers the Cardinals slugger hit off Astros
pitching. ``I threw too many pitches that were hittable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman has dropped three of his last four starts, allowing 15
earned runs in 20 innings. The righthander said he felt some
stiffness in his throwing arm and that he could notice a drop in
velocity on his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he had real good stuff, real good velocity, and
that was my concern,'' said interim manager Matt Galante. ``We've
seen him have much more velocity than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams and Scott Elarton helped keep the game close,
combining to pitch four innings of one-hit relief.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis wasted little time jumping on Bergman in the second
inning. Bergman hit Fernando Tatis, and Shawon Dunston singled to
put runners at first and second. Edgar Renteria sent an RBI single
through the hole at shortstop, and two batters later Bottenfield
followed with a two-run double to left to put the Cardinals ahead
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire made the score 4-0 with his solo home run. The first
baseman went 1-for-4 and is batting only .158 (3-for-19) in his
last four games. All three hits, however, have been home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored a pair of runs in the fourth inning, one
courtesy of an error. Jeff Bagwell led off with a single and scored
on a single by Everett. Bottenfield had Everett picked off at
first, but McGwire's throw was wild and allowed Everett to advance
to third. Richard Hidalgo closed the gap to 4-2 with a sacrifice
fly to left field.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few highlights for the Astros came on defense. Right
fielder Derek Bell leaped and crashed into the wall as he caught a
drive by Dunston in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis built the lead back to three runs in the bottom of the
fourth on a run-scoring single by rookie Joe McEwing, who was
2-for-4 to extend his hitting streak to 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added their final run on another error. In the sixth,
Bill Spiers doubled and advanced to third when right fielder Thomas
Howard bobbled the ball. Bagwell drove him in with a sacrifice fly
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   That was as close as the Astros would get against Bottenfield
and Bottalico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fooling anybody,'' Bottenfield said. ``I'm nobody's
ace. I'm not the type of guy like (Kevin) Brown or (Curt) Schilling
or (Greg) Maddux or (Tom) Glavine. I'm not going to throw nine
shutout innings. I'm not going to throw no-hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, he did just enough to keep the Astros guessing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
