r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERMLIMITS-AZR &LR;      06-22 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON TO HONOR VOW TO LIMIT TIME IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 LIMITS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Rep. Matt Salmon on Monday dug up a political time
capsule called term limits, announcing that he will honor his
pledge to leave Congress after six years.
</P>
<P>
   And few, it seems, care anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that crystallized voter discontent with Washington in
1994 is barely a blip five years later, a result of a strong
economy, an uncooperative Supreme Court and perhaps even greater
voter cynicism than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead. It's totally dead,'' said Larry Sabato, a political
science professor at the University of Virginia, speaking of the
term-limits movement. ``Despite the rantings of the activists who
tell you that this movement is still sweeping America, you can't
find anyone talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there Salmon was, on the steps of the state Capitol, keeping
his word, along with six other House Republicans who took the
three-term pledge in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh, Rep. George Nethercutt of Washington, announced
recently that he will break the promise and seek re-election.
Nethercutt defeated then-House Speaker Tom Foley in 1994 largely on
the issue of Foley's 30-year career in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Two others who took the pledge in 1994, Rep. Scott McInnis,
R-Colo., and Rep. Marty Meehan, D-Mass., have also broken
term-limit promises.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other two representatives elected to the freshman
class of Congress of 1994, J.D. Hayworth and John Shadegg, did not
take the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   While Nethercutt expects a tough race and is being targeted by
term-limits supporters, Meehan and McInnis will likely be
re-elected. That is evidence, experts say, of the demise of the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason, according to Sabato, is the waning of voter
anger and resentment that began in the early 1990s, reaching its
apogee with the 1992 Ross Perot presidential campaign and the GOP's
Contract with America in 1994. Sabato attributes that mainly to a
healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good times. They're not that crazy about Congress,
but they really don't care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the Contract with America was support for term
limits, which the GOP-led Congress defeated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Black, a professor of political science at Emory
University, said Republicans who had railed against Democrats for
opposing term limits when they controlled Congress soon realized
the powers of incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have realized it's not a cure-all,'' Black
said. ``The problem is you had these new people in, and the system
wasn't changed. I think it kind of undercuts the argument.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Supreme Court decision that forbids states from enacting
term limits for federal offices also helped douse the fire.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters, including Salmon, argue that it's still the
right thing to do. Salmon said he would only endorse someone for
his seat who takes the pledge. Two prospective candidates who
attended the event, Jeff Flake, executive director of the Goldwater
Institute, and Susan Bitter Smith, executive director of the
Arizona Cable Telecommunications Association, have already agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon admitted that there were times he regretted voluntarily
limiting his term, something no other current Arizona
representative or senator has formally done. But he added that
knowing he wouldn't be around for longer than six years allowed him
to be more aggressive in pushing issues, even taking on GOP leaders
when he felt they were compromising the party's values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the idea of term limits is still one that works. I
don't know if it's as strong as it once was when I ran on the
Contract with America,'' said Salmon, who is weighing a run for
governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to send a clear message to the American people,
whether you're a politician or not. You give your word, it's done.
And so I hope this sends a message out to other politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Term-limit supporters were on hand to praise Salmon, saying he
focused on his job rather than spending time worrying about raising
money for re-election. Paul Jacob, the national director of U.S.
Term Limits, insists that the drive for term limits isn't dead.
</P>
<P>
   He points to 45 House members and 14 senators who have promised
to limit their service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls are as high as they were in 1994,'' Jacob said. ``In
the last election, we had five different states vote on term-limit
initiatives and every one passed. ''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob acknowledges that hopes for a constitutional amendment to
limit federal terms have dimmed. The focus remains on getting
candidates to take the pledge voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Goldstein, an ASU professor of political science, said a
large turnover among congressmen since the early 1990s accomplished
many of the goals of term limits through the election process.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein predicts that Salmon will get little mileage out of
keeping his promise if he runs for governor in three years. But
even with interest in term limits waning, breaking his word would
have been damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could help him. There are so many others who simply will
not and cannot give up power,'' Sabato said. ``He kept his pledge
when he could have probably been re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be the critical issue, but it'll make a damn
good TV ad.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
