u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS &LR;      06-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX MAKE A CLEAN GETAWAY
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-RANGERS-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems equally unlikely to imagine, on a cold day in hell or
on the longest day of summer, that John Wasdin would be regarded as
Old Reliable, that the Olde Towne Team would be running wild, that
Tim Wakefield would resemble another Flash in the pen, and that
rookie Brian Rose would be as tough to beat on Yawkey Way as he was
in the South Dartmouth Little League.
</P>
<P>
   But here the Red Sox sit, on the cusp of school vacation and in
a virtual tie for first place with the New York Yankees, because
all of those elements were present Monday night in a 5-4 win over
Texas, their third straight over the Rangers and sixth in eight
games on a rejuvenating homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the surprises, there was the constant of Nomar
Garciaparra, whose parting gift to the 27,627 fans in Fenway Park
Monday night was a 4-for-4 performance, including a rally-starting
double in the second and a single that preceded Troy O'Leary's
game-tying home run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra tormented Texas with 10 hits in 11 at-bats in the
last three games of this series, the finishing touches to a
homestand on which he hit .567 (17 for 30) and raised his average
31 points to .350, fourth best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits the ball anywhere you pitch it,'' said loser Rick
Helling, who saw a 4-2 lead vanish in the sixth when Garciaparra
whacked a breaking ball up and off the plate into center field for
a single, followed moments later by O'Leary's 14th home run of the
season, a 400-foot drive that landed in the visitors' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no good way to pitch him,'' Helling said. ``He's one
of the few guys that at pitchers' meetings, you don't talk about
the way to get him out, you just talk about trying to make good
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Such pitches were few and far between this spring for Wasdin,
who earned his demotion to Pawtucket while in Florida, but Monday
night ran his record to 7-0 with two scoreless innings of relief
while the Sox were mounting their comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be back and 7-0 is unbelievable, really,'' said Wasdin, who
picked up after Rose, the rookie who has now allowed just one
earned run in six of his first seven starts and has yet to lose,
even though Jose Offerman's error led to three unearned runs in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to explain it,'' Wasdin said. ``One of those
weird years, where the moon and sun are aligned the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who are 12-6 against the three division leaders in the
American League _ the Yankees, Indians, and Rangers _ had diamonds
on the soles of their shoes Monday night, becoming the first team
to steal two bases against Gold Glove catcher Ivan Rodriguez this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra bagged second after Rodriguez tried to pick him off
first base in the third inning but advanced no further.
</P>
<P>
   The game turned on the second steal, by Offerman, who broke for
second on a hit-and-run play with John Valentin at the plate in the
seventh. Rodriguez double-clutched, then threw the ball into the
outfield, allowing Offerman to take third after he dusted himself
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to swing,'' Valentin said. ``The curveball he threw was
really outside. I couldn't put the bat on it, so you know he really
had to reach for it. That put him in a tough place to throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, who said he took his eye off the grounder that eluded
him when the infield was drawn in with a runner on third and one
out in the sixth, was reluctant to take a bow for the steal,
apparently not wishing to make a tough task even tougher in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about that,'' he said when asked if Rodriguez was
his toughest challenge as a base-stealer. ``We all know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone does too well against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who had been doing dreadfully against Helling,
whiffing twice and flying weakly to right, hit a sinking liner that
fell in front of Juan Gonzalez for a single, allowing Offerman to
score the deciding run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helling pitched a great game,'' Valentin said. ``He kept the
ball away from me all night. He knows my strength is middle in. The
curveball I hit, it was a pretty good pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, meanwhile, have to like the way Wakefield looks. On
a day the Sox learned that closer Tom Gordon won't be back until
after the All-Star break at the earliest, Wakefield rang up his
third save in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's on to Baltimore, where the Orioles, once 15 games under
.500, have run off 10 wins in 11 games, and play their next six
against the Sox and Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   What to expect? If you're Wasdin, you consult the nearest
astrologer. Next full moon is Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
