<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POINT-SHAVING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL TERM FOR BURTON IN POINT SHAVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By L. ANNE NEWELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A former Arizona State University basketball player
was sentenced to two months in jail Monday as a U.S. district judge
sentenced five defendants for involvement in the 1994 ASU
basketball point-shaving scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Former ASU guard Isaac Burton Jr. received three years'
probation, which includes two months in jail and six months of home
detention. Burton, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit
sports bribery, also must pay $8,000 and perform 200 hours of
community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's finally over,'' Burton said after leaving the
courtroom. ``If any one of you all can get to Bill Frieder . . .
tell him I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, Vincent P. Basso, Joseph Gagliano, Joseph Mangiamele,
Dominic Mangiamele, admitted they were involved in a point-shaving
scheme allegedly masterminded by former ASU student Benny Silman
during the 1993-94 season.
</P>
<P>
   Silman, 28, is serving a 46-month prison sentence for getting
Stevin ``Hedake'' Smith and Burton to shave points in certain games
so the team wouldn't beat the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   Basso, of Chicago, received the stiffest sentence of the five
defendants in Monday's federal court sentencing, as Judge Robert C.
Broomfield ordered him to serve 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Basso, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit sports
bribery, will also be under supervised release for three years. He
was ordered to pay a $27,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harm occurred first to ASU, to its fans, its sports programs
and its coaches, especially the head coach, through no fault of his
own,'' Broomfield said after sentencing Basso.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation led to the resignation of Coach Bill Frieder,
who was not charged, and stunned the world of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield also sentenced Phoenix resident Joseph Gagliano Jr.,
a former investment adviser, to 15 months in prison, to be followed
by three years of supervised release.
</P>
<P>
   Gagliano, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit sports
bribery, promotional money laundering and avoidance money
laundering, must also pay a $6,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield sentenced former Chicago trucking executive Dominic
Mangiamele to three years probation, which includes four months of
home detention. Mangiamele, who pleaded guilty to sports bribery,
must pay $5,000 and perform 100 hours of community service also.
</P>
<P>
   Mangiamele's son, Joseph, was sentenced to 90 days in jail, to
be followed by eight months of home detention and 48 months
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Jospeh Mangiamele pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit sports
bribery, promotional money laundering and avoidance money
laundering. He was also ordered to pay a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences bring the scandal, which the FBI has called ``one
of the most significant sports bribery conspiracies involving
college athletics in the country,'' one step closer to closure.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Anthony Frank are now the only two figures awaiting
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is scheduled to be sentenced in September and Frank will
go to trial sometime in August, officials with the U.S. Attorney's
Office said.
</P>
<P>
   The group successfully pulled off the point-shaving scheme
during four basketball games in early 1994, winning hundreds of
thousands of dollars from bets placed on ASU opponents at Las Vegas
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Silman conspired with Smith to fix a game by
making sure ASU did not beat the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who told his story to ``Sports Illustrated'' last year,
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   After the pair reached monetary agreement, Silman brought in
Gagliano. Gagliano then brought in the Mangiameles, who raised the
money to place the bets.
</P>
<P>
   Smith asked Burton to help him fix the first two games, but then
Burton did not participate again.
</P>
<P>
   After the third successful game, Gagliano approached Basso, who
asked to be included in further bets.
</P>
<P>
   The scam was discovered during the fifth game and the gamblers
reportedly lost all their bets when ASU won by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   Basso's lawyer, David Appleton, had asked for leniency because
his client was only involved in the last of the two fixed games. He
also minimized what that involvement was.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one came in later or had a less crucial role,'' Appleton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. trial attorney Corbin A. Weiss disagreed, stating, ``It
is simply not true that no person here played a smaller role than
Mr. Bosso. In some respects, Mr. Bosso's role was even greater than
anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   A choked-up Gagliano also asked for the court's mercy as he
talked about spending Saturday, his 31st birthday, at his
3-year-old daughter's dance recital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is I'm sorry. I made a mistake and paid so
dearly for it already.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who has been playing basketball in Cyprus since being
banned by the Continental Basketball Association in 1997, also took
time in court to make public apologies to former coach Frieder, ASU
and Sun Devils fans.
</P>
<P>
   But making what Broomfield said during sentencing were the most
compelling pleas were the Mangiameles.
</P>
<P>
   A tearful Joseph Mangiamele told the court: ``I just wanted to
apologize for what I did. I didn't know this would destroy my
family and I would lose everything. I would never have gotten
involved in this if I'd have known the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mangiamele, a former Illinois sheriff, lost his job
because of the indictments, said his lawyer, Charles Lauer. Dominic
Mangiamele's lawyer said the case has all but destroyed the
family's trucking business. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
