u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GAME EFFORT TO SAVE FACE 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-RYAN COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They had more bounce, more zip, more oomph, more
pizzazz, more fire, more zeal, and more desperation. They knew what
had to be done, and they did it. They deserved to win this game,
the New York Knicks did.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 at home when you're down, 0-2, is time to reexamine who
you are. There is one thing we know no team wants after it has
battled and scraped and fought for months to get this far, and that
is to be swept. That 0-4 is not a pretty thing to have on your
resume.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to get weepy-eyed here. This is still an ugly
series. This resembles NBA basketball of the '70s and '80s as
military music resembles music, to borrow a phrase. But it's still
the NBA, these are the Finals, and this is the only (male)
basketball we've got.
</P>
<P>
   And it will go till at least Friday. If the San Antonio Spurs
are going to do what we assume they will do, it will have to wait a
few days. There will be no sweep in 1999. The Knicks made sure of
that Monday night with an 89-81 victory in Game 3 that will at
least enable them to save face.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no debating just exactly who was responsible for
this. As he did in the Indiana series, Allan Houston stepped
forward. The smooth swingman with the feathery jump shot carried
his team across the finish line in this one, scoring 34 points in a
route-going performance. He once again did it by mixing his medium-
and long-range jumpers with aggressive drives to the basket. Aided
by some friendly officiating (a few of the touch fouls he was given
had a distinctly Jordanesque aroma), he made a complete joke out of
San Antonio's big guards by getting both Mario Elie and Jaren
Jackson in quick foul trouble and then making it a trifecta by
embarrassing young Antonio Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   This was a very nice win for the Knicks, who are trying to win a
championship with no real center play. Patrick Ewing, you know
about. Chris Dudley, are you kidding? Jeff Van Gundy responded to
popular demand and the obvious urgency of his team's situation and
_ guess what? _ Camby was a nonfactor for three quarters, getting
his first field goal early in the fourth period on a flying
one-hand rebound jam.
</P>
<P>
   At one point you looked out there and got a sense of deja vu.
Check out the following lineup: Houston, Latrell Sprewell, Chris
Childs, Larry Johnson, Kurt Thomas. What's missing? A center;
that's what. And this against a team anchored by David Robinson and
Tim Duncan. If you're old enough, you recall a Knick team gamely
defeating a Laker squad featuring Wilt Chamberlain in a Game 5 with
no one on the floor taller than 6 feet 6 inches. Not to get
weepy-eyed, of course.
</P>
<P>
   This was a wire-to-wire victory, with the only tie coming at
58-all. The Knicks started out with a _ get this _ 32-point first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get off to a good start,'' said Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had done a good job defensively and on the boards
in Game 2,'' added Sprewell, ``but we just needed to get some
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter looked like an old-fashioned NBA quarter, if
only because the Knicks were actually making shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while,'' explained one astute Knick-watcher,
``the Knicks will move the ball. They will make the extra pass, and
when they do that they will also make shots. There is no pattern.
There is no explanation. They don't do it very often. There is no
way of knowing when they will do it again. But when they do it they
are a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, they were hanging on for the final three periods.
Duncan started having his way in the second period, and even though
the Knicks led by 3 (49-46) at the half, there was a feeling we had
already seen the best they had to offer, and there didn't appear to
be any way they could contend with either Duncan or Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   But they did. They double- and triple-teamed Duncan throughout
the scond half and they did not lose heart when the Spurs caught
them at 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I told them is, `It's a long game,' '' said Van Gundy.
``We were playing with a lot of emotion, and I thought we were
playing very well against a great team. You've just got to keep
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had been the aggressors from the start, and when the
fourth quarter began they let San Antonio know just how much they
wanted the game by forcing a violation on the inbounds pass. You
will watch a hundred NBA games and not see anyone even bother to
contest that opening throw-in at the beginning of second, third,
and fourth periods. Well, this was No. 101, and if it was going to
happen it stands to reason it would happen in the Finals, when the
stakes are highest.
</P>
<P>
   New York was leading by 3 at 65-62 at the time and the immediate
Knick response was for Sprewell to take the ball to the hoop and
sink a gorgeous lefty flipper. Duncan was called for an offensive
foul, and that's when Camby came up with the aforementioned
crowd-pleasing jam.
</P>
<P>
   New York was fine after that. The Knicks did what they had been
doing all night, which was to beat San Antonio to the long rebounds
and the loose balls and do all the things teams with a better sense
of purpose than their opponents do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our true character was tested tonight,'' suggested Van Gundy.
``This was the first time we've been behind in a series and this
was the first time we had lost two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio now has a new experience, something they haven't
experienced in weeks. They've now lost one in a row. If they don't
come out Wednesday with a little more enthusiasm, they will be on
an official losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
