<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-BOS &LR;      06-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS REBOUND AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At some point, when there are no cameras and
microphones around, the Knicks will examine all the numbers from
this game and wonder, ``How did we do that?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 19,000 people in Madison Square Garden know what they
did in Game 3 of the NBA Finals. They defeated the Spurs, 89-81,
assuring that they will not be the last victims of a series sweep
in the 20th century. How did they do it? Well, you could take all
of the celebrity filmmakers, singers, comedians, and newsmakers in
the audience and chances are they wouldn't be able to tell you.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks shot like a group of guys playing ball at lunch hour,
making 40 percent for the night and an awful 17 percent in the
third quarter. No one in their starting lineup had more than five
rebounds. They got 8 points off their bench . . .
</P>
<P>
   But they never trailed, winning a game and ending a couple of
San Antonio streaks: Twelve consecutive playoff games without a
loss and six straight games on the road without a loss.
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan Houston was incredible,'' said the Spurs' Tim Duncan,
who had 20 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Houston said Sunday that the Spurs were no better than the other
teams the Knicks have beaten in the playoffs. He played as if he
wanted to prove his point by himself. In his first 21 minutes on
the floor, he had 18 points and went to the free throw line an
astounding 10 times. He made them all. He finished with 34 points
and 4 assists. He also took Mario Elie out of the game in the first
two minutes, forcing him to pick up two fouls and a technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be a pain in the neck and unstoppable,'' said
Houston, after being told that Spurs coach Gregg Popovich called
him a nuisance. ``I just want to be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   But one player's points are not going to win a game for you.
Many people can tell you about the day a young player at Boston
Garden scored 63 points in a loss. So there must have been
something beyond Houston's points and Latrell Sprewell's 24 points,
5 rebounds, and 5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which team you want to win the series, there are
two answers on what it was that gave the Knicks the edge. In San
Antonio, someone will certainly revive the talk of an NBA pro-New
York conspiracy. Really, there are still people who swear David
Stern rigged the 1985 lottery so the Knicks could draft Patrick
Ewing. It wasn't that drastic Monday night. But a day after Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy complained about his team not getting calls,
it got calls (30-22 New York edge in free throw attempts).
</P>
<P>
   Popovich said he thought that was strange, considering that the
Spurs are a post-up team and the Knicks are a finesse team. But New
Yorkers can point to David Robinson's 17 free throw attempts. They
can also say the Spurs hurt themselves, turning the ball over twice
as often as the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really outhustled us,'' said Robinson, who had 25 points
and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   That hustle began from the start, when the Knicks took a quick
14-point lead, saw it reduced to 3 by halftime and even saw it
disappear with a 58-all tie in the third. But they never lost it.
You want a key play of the game? That was it: The Knicks never lost
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, the Garden crowd loved it. Many fans here
share the same opinion as Houston: They don't think the Spurs are
that much better than the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Knicks didn't guarantee themselves a return trip to
San Antonio for Games 6 and 7, but they did what they promised they
would do Monday night. They made some minor changes (Marcus Camby
starting at center) and played as though they had everything to
lose. Duncan wasn't bad, but the Knicks kept him scoreless in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you saw the true character of the Knicks tonight,''
Van Gundy said. ``We played extremely hard. We hung in there when
they were making runs. We were very resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   So now we are on to Game 4 Wednesday, the game that could
completely change the series. A Knicks win and the Finals belong to
anyone. A Spurs win and one of the ABA originals will most likely
have a title.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last things Robinson said before leaving the building
was: ``We take it personally when we lose. We always respond well
after a loss. Always.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
