<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, SIR, THAT'S MY MONIKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Respect for authority, for the law, for one's elders is the very
cornerstone of Western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the spoiled brats of today, this is something every
American boy of my generation was taught. We had respect pounded
into our heads and into our hides, and we came to believe in it,
finally, at the exact moment our plans for partying all night long
were superseded by concern over the amount of fiber in our diet.
</P>
<P>
   We're parents, now.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have children of your own, you recognize the role that
a thoroughly ingrained sense of respect can play when trying to
keep your kids from having the kind of fun you're no longer capable
of having.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the government has failed to help us.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of engendering our youth with a genuine belief in
respect, politicians propose a phony variety.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Congress approved legislation allowing states to
post the Ten Commandments in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the bill provided no penalties for those who
violate God's laws, perhaps because politicians are reluctant to
punish kids who'd be guilty only of following the example of their
elders.
</P>
<P>
   Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   What good is being a grown-up if you're not willing to make use
of the phrase, ``Because I said so''? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vision in Louisiana &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lawmakers in Louisiana see the issue more clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, they passed a law requiring students in their state to
address teachers and other school employees as ``ma'am,'' ``sir,''
Mr., Mrs. or Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women of the Louisiana Legislature appear to
understand that respect, in its purest form, must be earned.
</P>
<P>
   Or, failing that, it can be shoved down the throats of the
insolent miscreants who now look at us as we once looked at Richard
Nixon, leisure suits and ``The Lawrence Welk Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the Louisiana plan, which creates a
make-believe world in which children are legally required to feign
veneration for their elders, is that it doesn't go nearly far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Why limit such a glorious piece of legislation to school
personnel?
</P>
<P>
   Why not require a proper show of respect for ALL``'' adults?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, why limit the officially mandated appellations
to relatively mundane titles like ``ma'am,'' ``sir,'' Mr., Mrs. or
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Adults should be able to choose exactly how they'd like to be
addressed by children.
</P>
<P>
   I've always thought ``excellency'' had a nice ring to it. Along
with all other respectful forms of address used by British-sounding
actors wearing fancy costumes in movies no self-respecting American
male would watch unless they starred Errol Flynn or Basil Rathbone.
</P>
<P>
   Or both.
</P>
<P>
   (``The Adventures of Robin Hood,'' ``Captain Blood,'' ``The Dawn
Patrol.'')
</P>
<P>
   Any moniker beginning with ``Your'' is a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eminence.'' ``Your grace.'' ``Your worship.'' ``Your
lordship.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``most'' works as well. I'm thinking here of ``most
noble,'' ``most worthy'' and ``most worshipful.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Consider our options &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nor should the options be limited to English only.
</P>
<P>
   States that hope to make English their official language might
consider exceptions to have our more worldly and sophisticated
grown-ups referred to as ``monsieur,'' ``mein Herr'' or ``el
magnifico.'' A fan of the movie ``Gunga Din'' might enjoy having
youngsters call him ``sahib.''
</P>
<P>
   `` '' Then again, many in our generation may prefer a form of
address less stuffy than ``sir'' or ``ma'am,'' but equally
respectful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big dog,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   There are even those who may choose to resolve the issue
musically, in the manner of the great Steve Miller.
</P>
<P>
   That way, children familiar only with the crude etiquette of rap
music and grunge might come to understand exactly why ``Some people
call me the space cowboy. Some call me the gangster of love . .
.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
