 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, June 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN-ASSAULT (Zrze, Yugoslavia) _ In interviews over the
last two weeks, dozens of women and men in Kosovo and in refugee
camps in Albania told stories that suggest that sexual assault and
intimidation, if not rape, were widespread, common and used by
Serbian forces to strike at the heart of a society in which the
virginity and fidelity of Muslim women is central. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION-ASSESS (Jakarta) _ News analysis: Indonesians
have remained remarkably patient as they wait out the slow,
confused counting of the parliamentary votes they cast two weeks
ago. But it seems that whatever the outcome, the will of the people
may in large part be denied. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   TOGO-EYADEMA (Lome, Togo) _ A year after winning re-election in
voting that was widely considered tainted, President Gnassingbe
Eyadema has continued to tighten his three-decade hold on his
nation's politics, preserving his status as sub-Saharan Africa's
longest-ruling head of state.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EVANGELIST (Funabashi, Japan) _ Former Japanese gangster
starts a church, saying he has found Jesus, and takes his mission
to the streets to recruit Japanese outcasts. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-POLITICS (Baton Rouge) _ After a few years of relative
political quiet, Louisiana is reverting to traditional chaotic
form. A look at several events, focusing on the recently disclosed
alliance between the governor and David Duke, via the payment for
the list of supporters. The GOP split over an effort to distance
itself from the Christian Coalition. One senior official was locked
out of his office. And several unusual bills in the Legislature,
including one requiring students to address teachers with ``Sir''
or ``Miss.'' By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ATTORNEYS-GENERAL _ At a time of new activism among state
attorneys general, Republicans are creating their party's own
attorneys general association to promote an idea of more limited
government and raise money for the election of more Republicans to
positions as the states' chief law enforcement officers. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENTAL-PATIENTS (Undated) _ Chronically ill patients with
limited or no health insurance are increasingly filling a demand
for experimental drug study participants as drug companies rush
record numbers of new medications through the testing process. For
these people, experiments have become treatments. But the benefit
can be fleeting or nonexistent. By Gina Kolata and Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS-SHIPLEY (New York) _ Walter Shipley, who retired as
Chase Manhattan Corp.'s chief executive on June 1 but will remain
chairman, has some advice for dealmeisters hoping to ride America's
merger wave: Slash-and-burn takeovers will come back to haunt you.
By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT photo/graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JANUS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ In April, Janus 20 sat atop the
mutual fund world. It was the best performer of any large stock
fund, having doubled investors' money since the start of 1998. Now,
the fund has once more earned a prominent place on the performance
charts _ this time, at the bottom. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The next phase of a major multiyear
communications effort to promote the importance of advertising is
getting under way _ and not a moment too soon, judging by the
results of a national survey of top corporate executives. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Michiko Kakutani reviews
``True at First Light,'' by Ernest Hemingway: Africa was a fine
subject, and he had written about it well and truly in the past,
but the old days were gone now, and he was old and weary and
ailing, and what he wrote this time was not good and it was not
true.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MOVIE-STUDIO (New York) _ Will a movie lot work at Brooklyn
Navy Yard? By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-BADUM-SLAYING (New York) _ The slaying of John Badum, a
fashion insider's insider who built GoSilk, has Seventh Avenue
abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Jerusalem) _ Thomas L. Friedman looks at
Israeli politics and society.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Anthony Lewis on the Kosovo atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Knicks. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on
Game 3 of the NBA championship series. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOW-WE-NAVIGATE (Undated) _ Scientists have taken a keen
interest in how humans and other species navigate _ or fail to. The
study of what they call spatial cognition, or way-finding, is
attracting a growing cadre of researchers from all sectors of the
academic map, including psychology, neuroscience, computer science,
zoology, anthropology, linguistics and geography. By Natalie
Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEUTRINO-DETECTORS (Undated) _ Scientists operating huge
underground detectors in Japan and Canada are racing to obtain
independent proofs that the elusive neutrino _ a ghostly particle
whose vast family may constitute a large fraction of the mass of
the universe _ changes form as it flies through matter or space. By
Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-IN-ENGINEERING (Undated) _ Dr. Eleanor Baum,
electrical engineer, dean of engineering at Cooper Union in New
York and the first woman to head an engineering college anywhere,
is running a one-woman affirmative action campaign that is
transforming engineering.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFECTION-THE-GAME (Undated) _ Infection, sort of a cross
between Monopoly and Trivial Pursuit, is a new board game of
questionable taste, but unquestionable imagination. It pits from
two to nine people against one another on a playing field run
rampant with disease, from the fiercest (like malaria) to the
simply annoying (say, athlete's foot). By Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Americans, famous for wanting their
cake and eating it too, were delighted to learn that even though
French foods seem to be rich in fat, much of it artery-clogging
saturated animal fat, the French are not nearly as likely to be cut
down in midlife by heart attacks. This intriguing phenomenon is
called the French Paradox, and it has drawn comment, criticism and
speculation for much of this decade. What is helping protect their
hearts? By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENETIC-CODE (Undated) _ Researchers at Mount Sinai School
of Medicine in New York have developed a technique for conducting
espionage on a molecular level, by hiding a message in human DNA.
Using the technique, a sender would create a unique strand of DNA
that only an intended recipient could isolate and ``read'' from
millions of similar strands. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SICKLE-CELL (Undated) _ Two companies are conducting human
tests with several new types of agents that may result in the first
drugs to attack the basic mechanisms of sickle cell disease itself
and interrupt attacks once they have started. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLIND-MELATONIN (Undated) _ For the blind, the body's clock,
normally harnessed to the 24-hour cycle of daylight and darkness,
often goes into free run, disrupting sleep patterns. Now,
researchers may have help, using the hormone melatonin, for the
estimated 200,000 Americans who are totally blind and suffer from
sleep disorders. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEMALE-ATHLETE-TRIAD (Undated) _ Educators, coaches,
researchers, physicians and parents are expressing increasing
concern about the female athlete triad, a syndrome experts have
defined as three distinct but related problems: disordered eating,
suspended menstrual cycle and premature bone loss. By Linda
Villarosa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
