<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPORTSMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE-CONSCIOUS HAWKINS EARNS NBA SPORTSMANSHIP AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among NBA class notables, Sonics guard Hersey Hawkins
is officially considered an all-around nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins also believes he's been one of the most tradable players
throughout his 11-year career. So it would not surprise Hawkins if
the Sonics traded him this offseason in an attempt to get younger
and more athletic.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he expects to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no promises made,'' Hawkins said Monday at Madison
Square Garden, where he won the league's Sportsmanship Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Sonics brass) said they would love to have me back on
the team. But I know that they're going to look at their options. I
can imagine there are six or seven teams they have me going to at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the Sonics have a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins recently decided not to void the remaining two years of
his contract, which will pay him $4.1 million next season and $4.5
million in the 2000-01 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Sonics will not say it publicly, they are fielding
offers for the 6-foot-3 shooting guard. The most recent rumor had
the Sonics offering Hawkins and the No. 13 draft pick to the
Toronto Raptors for their No. 2 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker denied the offer was made. He did
acknowledge there was considerable outside interest in Hawkins at
the NBA's predraft camp in Chicago early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from adding a solid point guard and a strong, physical
inside presence, the Sonics have expressed a desire to acquire a
player who can create his own shot and play at shooting guard or
small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' role in four seasons with the Sonics has been primarily
to shoot spot-up jumpers and defend opponents' best scoring guard.
Though Hawkins was known as a pure shooter when he entered the NBA
in 1988, his shooting drastically diminished the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that had to do with the team not calling plays for
Hawkins. Another reason for his slide can be attributed to coach
Paul Westphal's decision to end Hawkins' 461 consecutive start
streak in favor of bringing him off the bench last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, who has said he would voluntarily come off the bench
next season, insists he can still help the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're given an opportunity to do those type of things, I
can do them,'' said Hawkins, who turns 33 in September. ``Do I
think I can create my own shot? Do I think I can penetrate? Yeah, I
can do that. I've displayed that in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If given the opportunity I can do a lot more of it. Of course,
it gets to the point now where you want to bring somebody in a
little younger and who has the reputation of doing that. I don't
have the reputation for doing that. Of course, people are going to
say you can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins also said the Sonics must ``find some kind of way to get
some better talent'' if they expect to compete in the Western
Conference. San Antonio, Portland, Utah, Phoenix, Sacramento and
Minnesota all have made strides while the Sonics seem to be
standing pat. And the Los Angeles Lakers are now expected to
flourish with the hiring a Phil Jackson as their coach.
</P>
<P>
   Where do the Sonics fit today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle of the pack,'' Hawkins said. ``We're definitely not up
to their caliber. That's where (the Sonics brass) have to get us _
with or without me. The fans (in Seattle) deserve better and are
used to a winning basketball team. I think I can still help the
Sonics get back to that level. But that's a decision they have to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins does not have a clause in his contract that says he can
refuse a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just hope they would trade me somewhere where I could
have an opportunity to win a championship or get into the
playoffs,'' he said. ``I wouldn't want them to trade me somewhere
where I was in a rebuilding process and looking at losing 50 to 60
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want that, and I would hope that they would have
enough respect that if they were going to trade me they would try
to trade me somewhere where I could possibly do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins received a bit of respect Monday by being honored as the
NBA player who best represents sportsmanship on the court. Hawkins
received 70 of 118 possible votes from members of the media who
cover the NBA. The league donated $25,000 to Westinghouse High
School, Hawkins' alma mater in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get some recognition for how you conduct
yourself,'' said Hawkins, who beat out Philadelphia's Eric Snow,
Minnesota's Kevin Garnett and Toronto's Vince Carter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
