<HEADLINE>
KINGDOME SWAN SONG STARTS TUESDAY NIGHT WITH LAST HOMESTAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a baseball facility, the Kingdome finds itself down
to its last strike, hosting the Mariners for just six more games,
starting with Tuesday night's matchup with the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   While people have been chipping away at the dome's hard-shell
veneer for some time, not everyone is prepared to dismiss the
city's big league baseball home of the past 22{ seasons. At least
not without some sort of acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners backup catcher Tom Lampkin grew up in Seattle, working
the Kingdome's early years as a clubhouse boy, hanging and picking
up laundry. His own playing career has taken him to every ballpark
in the majors. The Kingdome feels like home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first stadium I ever knew,'' Lampkin said. ``Back
then, it was `in.' It was the stadium. All of a sudden I come back
and it's, `Let's get rid of it.' I've always liked playing here.
The Kingdome for years has been a fixture in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when it's gone, it will be a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitters everywhere no doubt will offer a moment of silence when
the Kingdome has fulfilled its baseball obligations Sunday
afternoon against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   With its short fences, extra-firm AstroTurf and superior
lighting, the dome has been good for more than a few extra home
runs and batting-average points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a hitter in baseball doesn't like to play here,'' Mariners
first baseman David Segui said. ``Sure, players don't like it. But
the consensus of the hitters in the league is this place is a great
place to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Says shortstop Alex Rodriguez, ``I love it for all of those
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 11 seasons, Mariners center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. has
averaged nearly 20 points higher at the Kingdome than on the road
and collected 197 of his 376 home runs there. Griffey won't say how
much he'll miss the place, but he turned surprisingly angry after a
recent Post-Intelligencer story made the assumption that he was
eager to move to the new ballpark. Maybe he was just being
protective. After all, the Kingdome has been his only major league
home for 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone with a bat in his hand has benefited from
playing at the Kingdome. Entering Tuesday's action, the concrete
mushroom has served up 3,612 homers in 1,749 contests, or two per
game. The Mariners have hit 1,798, more than one per game. In
keeping with the Kingdome tradition of honoring each local long
ball, that's a lot of smoke and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariners outfielder Matt Mieske always looked forward to
his Kingdome visits while suiting up for the Milwaukee Brewers. He
says right-handed batters who can go to the opposite field, players
much like himself, can be rewarded over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Mieske says the stadium's tall but relatively close right-field
fence reminds him of another hitter-friendly park on the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Monster, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you flip the field, it's almost another Fenway Park,
dimension-wise,'' Mieske said. ``Through the years, that place has
had Wade Boggs and Ted Williams, guys who could flick the ball off
that (opposite-field) wall. Alex did it here the other night. At
other parks, you can't do that; you have to hit it over a guy's
head. It makes for more at-bats, more consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Mieske also has noticed that balls seem to carry farther at the
Kingdome when the place is teeming with people than during batting
practice, when the seats are empty. It's as if the stadium warms up
and creates its own jet stream.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jeff Fassero has observed this phenomenon, painfully so.
He has given up a major league-leading 25 home runs this season, 13
at the Kingdome. A former National Leaguer, Fassero has played in
the Houston Astrodome several times, and that ballpark, he says, is
far easier on a pitcher. Sure, the fences are deeper there. But the
big difference is the smothering air.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife asked me why the ball flies better here,'' Fassero
said. ``It's the humidity. In the Astrodome, it's 95 to 100 percent
humidity, and the ball doesn't fly. There's a lot of moisture in
the air. There isn't any here.''
</P>
<P>
   For his taste, Fassero says Safeco Field _ the Mariners' new
home, beginning on July 15 _ can't open soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be a lot happier over there,'' he said. ``This is not a
pitcher's ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco outfielder Ellis Burks, a Kingdome regular when he
played for the Boston Red Sox, posted some of his best offensive
numbers here, hitting .301 with 13 homers. For that reason, he
appreciated the place.
</P>
<P>
   Burks, however, is not so sure a full-time career in the
Kingdome would have been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can enhance a career with the numbers, but it can shorten a
career,'' Burks said of the Kingdome. ``You have to look at the
stress the AstroTurf puts on your body here. My question is, how
much longer before Junior has to play first base and not center
field?''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Mieske, ``For a visitor, you're going to feel it for a week
after you play in the Kingdome. It takes five to seven days to get
the soreness out of your body, out of your knees, out of your
ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Tuesday's contest, Mariners fans have been treated to a
different sort of ache _ more losses (900) than victories (849),
though the numbers have narrowed in recent seasons. Attendance has
ranged from a low of 10,044 per game in 1983 to a high of 39,410
per game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Mariners fans have witnessed comedic and near
tragic moments under the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay hitting coach Leon Roberts was a Mariners right
fielder from 1978 to 1980, during the franchise's formative years.
The Kingdome story he remembers best was a lesson in playing the
tricky right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto leadoff hitter Rick Bosetti slapped a ball to right, a
Texas Leaguer, which Roberts dove for and missed. Roberts chased
down the ball in the corner, wheeled and fired it _ into the
overhanging stands. The ball was deflected sideways back onto the
field, Roberts chased it down again and threw too late to keep
Bosetti from an inside-the-park homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things,'' Roberts said. ``I probably
got booed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Baltimore bullpen coach Elrod Hendricks witnessed
something he hopes never to see again in a big league ballpark. A
piece of the roof fell.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks, who once played minor league ball for the Seattle
Angels, was on the field chatting with an Orioles advance scout in
the stands when he was startled to see a section of the Kingdome
roof, a ceiling tile, come loose. The tile landed with a crash 30
feet from Hendricks and the scout and 10 feet from where the scout
had been seated. Luckily, the gates hadn't opened, and no fans were
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming down,'' Hendricks said. ``I thought it was a
piece for the air conditioning. I thought it was insulation,
something light. It sounded like a cannon when it landed. I said,
`Wow.' The only thing I could think about was I was glad nobody was
in here.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many hits the place has in it, the gray Kingdome
decor has excited no one. Mariners outfielder Butch Huskey calls
the ballpark fun, yet dull. Third baseman Russ Davis says the place
is plain and lacking in character.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field, with its modern architecture, will provide a
welcome change. Ballplayers notice these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm into aesthetics,'' Segui said. ``That's why I prefer
Camden Yards and Yankee Stadium. They're my favorite ballparks.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Diego Segui, tried not to look up when he threw the
first pitch for the Mariners in 1977. The Kingdome had him spooked.
He wasn't used to having concrete directly overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I get in there was a big impression,'' he said.
``I started looking around and (the) first thing you're thinking
is, something (could) go wrong, and with everything coming down,
you'll be buried in there forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners needed three seasons before they started to
complain publicly about their accommodations. On March 19, 1980,
they sued King County, claiming that the Kingdome was so small, the
home team was vulnerable to enemy home runs and would never be
successful. There also were complaints about poor lighting and
loose AstroTurf seams.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, improvements were made. Diego Segui, however, says
the mound never has been fixed, another reason why the Kingdome is
a hitters' park. The mound has been moved so many times to
accommodate football and other events, it remains soft and flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be the flattest mound in the whole league,'' the
61-year-old Segui said. ``It's real hard on a pitcher. You only get
halfway on your follow-through, and you get a lot of high pitches.
A good pitcher in that park is a sinker-ball pitcher who (doesn't)
have to get over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitcher who throws overhand, look at the trouble they
have in there. Look at (Ken) Cloude. You can pitch for two or three
innings, and it's boom, boom, boom, and you've lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Kingdome will be nothing but dust and memories. A place
where Griffey and Rodriguez started their careers, and Nolan Ryan
and Don Mattingly ended theirs. Where Gaylord Perry earned his
300th pitching victory and Willie Horton hit his 300th homer. Where
Randy Johnson and Chris Bosio threw no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Where foul balls hit speakers and the Mariners fell two games
shy of a World Series. Where the wind never blew and the
temperature never changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-two years is a long time,'' Fassero said. ``It's going
to be a change for the city. But I think baseball will become more
enjoyable for the fans, the conditions more conducive to
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Six more Kingdome baseball games. Once the Mariners get their
final swings in, the only ones left will belong to the wrecking
ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
