<HEADLINE>
WILD PITCH IN 12TH SINKS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ At least the standings should start changing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners play their next 15 games against division rivals
Anaheim, Texas and Oakland, and their task is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just try to catch the teams that are ahead of us,'' said
center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., ``and put the teams behind us
further behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Good games or bad this road trip _ and there were generous
helpings of both _ the Mariners were unable to do much with the
Texas Rangers. The last six days, Seattle and Texas have had the
same result, the Mariners stuck at four games behind the division
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like for the last two weeks, every time they lose, we
lose, and vice versa,'' said left-hander Jamie Moyer, who allowed
two runs in seven innings in Monday night's 4-3 loss to the
Cleveland Indians. ``It's not time necessarily to start
scoreboard-watching, but we can really help ourselves within the
next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   They could have started Monday night, had they held a one-run
lead. The Mariners scored three times in the eighth inning, and
were four outs away from a win. But relievers Jeff Fassero and Jose
Paniagua lost the lead, and Jose Mesa's bases-loaded wild pitch
scored Jim Thome with the winning run with one out in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Thome had led off with an infield single that second baseman
David Bell backhanded, but could not hold. Alex Ramirez advanced
Thome to second with a sacrifice bunt, and an intentional walk and
a single loaded the bases for catcher Chris Turner.
</P>
<P>
   With one strike, Mesa _ an ex-Indian who again was booed by his
former fans _ threw a fastball that sailed well inside on Turner,
eluded catcher Dan Wilson and allowed Thome to race home. It
brought an end to a road trip that began with four wins in five
games but ended in three consecutive defeats.
</P>
<P>
   The most energizing win on the trip was a 4-3 victory last
Thursday at Detroit in which the M's scored three times in the
ninth to erase a 2-1 deficit. After two blowout defeats, the
Mariners nearly duplicated their Detroit heroics at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a great ballclub,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said
of the Indians. ``But when you compete like we did tonight, more
often than not, that's a winning situation. We don't have the
victory to show for it, but we sure battled our butts off
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners advanced no runners past second when Indians
starter Bartolo Colon was in the game. But when Griffey came to bat
with two outs and runners at first and second in the eighth, the
Indians called on left-handed specialist Paul Assenmacher, who had
held Griffey to three hits in 14 career at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey ripped a single off the glove of second baseman Enrique
Wilson, scoring Dan Wilson with the Mariners' first run and moving
Brian Hunter to second.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Shuey came in to face Edgar Martinez, and Hunter and
Griffey pulled a double steal. That was significant, because it
allowed two runs to score when Martinez followed with a single,
giving Seattle a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, I definitely am looking to catch them off
guard, so a single can drive in two runs,'' said Hunter, who was
ejected in the 10th when he slammed his bat to the ground after
striking out on a bunt attempt. ``I was looking at pitch selection,
and they were throwing Edgar off-speed pitches, as if there was a
base open.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally put Moyer in position for his eighth consecutive
victory, which would have been a career high. Fassero _ who will
return to the rotation Thursday _ started the eighth with two quick
outs, but walked Thome and got together for an epic at-bat with
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero got ahead 0-and-2, but the rookie fouled off a slider,
then worked the count to 2-2 as Fassero threw two more sliders,
both in the dirt. Four fouls followed _ the first a long fly to
left, the last a tip _ before balls three and four. The 11-pitch
at-bat ended Fassero's night, and began Paniagua's.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had no play on a slow grounder by pinch-hitter Roberto
Alomar, and it went for a single that loaded the bases. On a full
count, Paniagua walked Enrique Wilson, bringing in the tying run.
Jacob Cruz then bounced a troublesome chopper to Russ Davis, but
the third baseman bare-handed it and retired Cruz for the out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
