<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' TWIN TOWNERS DON'T STAND OUT IN NEW YORK SKYLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We have seen this kind of thing before. Small-town
folks coming north to the big city just to get totally smoked.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stevie Wonder, not Billy Joel, who gave us the all-time
great New York state of mind anthem:
</P>
<P>
   (start ital)New York, just like Tim Duncan pictured it.
Skyscrapers and everything.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   It used to be, just a few days ago, that the Spurs' human
skyscrapers _ Duncan and David Robinson _ were too high to knock
down, too tall to be messed with.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, in Game 3 of the NBA Finals, the twin towers
from south Texas were messed up and helpless in the face of
overwhelming obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the Knicks who (temporarily) knocked the crown
off the Spurs' head; it was just being here. Home. At the Garden _
``Marcus Square Garden,'' as one rabid, leather-lunged Noo Yawker
proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to be crazy out there,'' Knicks center
Marcus Camby said in the face of the Knicks' 89-81 win Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go in and give it all my energy,''
</P>
<P>
   Energy ... as if New York needed any more of the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was Duncan who committed three consecutive turnovers
from the end of the third quarter and into the fourth. A
three-second violation, an offensive foul and a walk left this
gentle giant looking young and humbled in the belly of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out with a lot of emotion,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any team starts with belief and trust. Belief in
themselves as individuals, teammates and coaching staff. I think
good teams have that, and I think we played the game better
offensively. I think that was our true character. I think you saw
the true character of the Knicks tonight. We hung in there when
they made runs, and we stayed efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   The center of the universe: That's what it's like in the heart
of the city when any Big Apple home team is rolling toward
championship ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudy Guiliani gets a front-row seat. Spike Lee adorns his
dimunitive frame in neon rally towels. Even the president's wife
wants to muscle in on the action, donning New York ballcaps,
although the front-running potential senator was nowhere to be seen
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Marcus Square Garden'' was alive with the sound of
the regulars _ some of whom taunted members of the national media
for the overwhelming news coverage that said the Knicks, after
being blown away in Games 1 and 2, were all but dead in these NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   During the Knicks' percussive 32-point first quarter, one pack
of delightfully smug Knicks fans turned and offered a section of
reporters rally towels _ a mocking but understandable gesture.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who rooted for the Spurs to sweep, pay back wasn't
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first quarter, they really outhustled us,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were obviously pumped up by the crowd. That really helped
them. It was just a slow start by us, and they did what we usually
do. They held us off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had come home. They heard all the noise and the
craziness and it renewed their confidence (if it ever lagged), and
the Spurs got a feel for the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious _ like some disease the busy New York health
department might have to combat _ New York fever does have a way of
working its way into small cuts and taking a vice-like hold.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it. Once it was Mark Messier who was bigger than life,
grinning that smile wide as all of North America after he led the
long-suffering Rangers to their Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Or remember how the sobbing, stunned Wade Boggs _ who is afraid
of horses _ jumped wildly onto the back of that police stallion and
cantered around Yankee Stadium that balmy October night the Yankees
won the 1996 World Series?
</P>
<P>
   New York, New York, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you can't stomach the idea of the Big Apple's brash
arrogance, you can understand that big things are even bigger here.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to these Knicks, who aren't anywhere close to
big but who are apparently determined to prolong an NBA Finals that
has done little but inspire the NBA rules committee to consider
ways of cutting down on 67-point games and smash-mouth defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday night, that is. The Knicks have done what no one
but themselves wanted or predicted. They have kept this alive
because this is the city where ``Staying Alive'' became standard
operating procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a great game. They were aggressive. Allan Houston
and Latrell Sprewell were fantastic. Houston (who had 34 points)
played a great game. They were a little more aggressive,'' Duncan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the surroundings, the Spurs should have expected
nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
