<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4729 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-SPI &LR;      06-22 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS STRIKE BACK IN GAME 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took an abundance of bright orange rally rags. It
helped to have constricting defense and an unstoppable Allan
Houston. And perhaps the best part for the New York Knicks was the
``I told you so'' at the end.
</P>
<P>
   They finally broke down the road-raging Spurs, detouring an NBA
Finals that seemingly was headed down the path to a San Antonio
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt in our hearts we weren't going to get swept,'' said
New York's Latrell Sprewell, whose team's heart and courage
permeated the Knicks' 89-81 victory Monday night in Game 3 at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we could have won a game in San Antonio,'' Sprewell
continued.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks can find a sequel to how they performed at the
Garden, they might earn a return trip to the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   New York snapped San Antonio's mighty 12-game playoff winning
streak. The Knicks victory also assured there will be a Game 5 on
Friday after Wednesday's Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio still owns a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always respond well after a loss. Always,'' San Antonio's
David Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Spurs suffered a loss in the playoffs _ Game 2
against Minnesota in the first round _ they reeled off a dozen
consecutive wins. But the Spurs, who dominated the Knicks in the
first two games, now have something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   They had been invincible away from home in the playoffs, winning
all six games, until Monday night. Surprisingly, San Antonio's
average margin of victory on the road was 13.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Knicks never allowed the Spurs to lead in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Every time San Antonio appeared poised to snatch the game away,
the Knicks responded. Particularly Houston, who scored a game-high
34 points.
</P>
<P>
   He was clutch, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 81-77 late in the fourth quarter, Houston immediately hit
a 22-foot jump shot after a timeout. Marcus Camby sank a turnaround
jumper moments later, and the Knicks went ahead 85-77 with 2:18
left to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Spurs coach Gregg Popovich called Houston ``a pain in
the neck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be all the time,'' said Houston, who made 10 of 24
shots. ``I hope to be a pain in the neck and unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Houston was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   He also sank a critical off-balance 3-pointer in the third
quarter after the Spurs tied the game at 58. Houston's basket with
3:05 left and the shot clock running down put the Knicks back in
front. They led 65-62 heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big for them,'' Spurs center Tim Duncan said. ``We
thought we played hard throughout that whole possession and then
Allan Houston came up big for them.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Larry Johnson, whose 16 points gave the Knicks another
scoring threat to go with Houston's production and Sprewell's 24
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any lay down and quit in this team,'' Johnson
said. ``We're still in this.''
</P>
<P>
   New York had the best shooting percentage of any home team the
Spurs had faced on the road. The Knicks, who misfired in this
series with 35 percent shooting, shot 40 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of better execution, and that got (their)
guys into foul trouble,'' Houston said. ``We were able to get the
ball where we needed to get it. We did a much better job of just
playing together, driving the ball and kicking it to the open
man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks put early pressure on the Spurs for the first time in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the past two days pondering lineup changes, New
York coach Jeff Van Gundy shuffled his bench. He inserted the
6-foot-1 Camby in at center, figuring he could slow down Duncan or
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' Twin Towers combined for 45 points and 22 rebounds.
But they didn't control the game from the foul line. This time, the
Knicks did.
</P>
<P>
   Houston shot 12 free throws and the Knicks had eight more
freebies than the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foul trouble is a huge factor in every game. It's hurt us,''
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. `` ... Certainly we need to get
our way to the line because we know they're going to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening quarter, the Knicks offense was crisp. They
played together. They made shots.
</P>
<P>
   They just followed Houston's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Houston scored eight of the Knicks first 10 points on a variety
of shots from every spot on the floor. This time, San Antonio did
little to stop the Knicks in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really outhustled us to a lot of loose balls and
rebounds,'' Robinson said. ``It was a tough one, especially with
Larry Johnson hitting tough shots early.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotionally charged first quarter, which wound down
with Chris Childs' wide-open 3-pointer that gave New York a 32-18
advantage _ their biggest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Knicks made it apparent they were not going to
be easily discarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a series,'' Camby said. ``They only thing San
Antonio did down there was solidify home court. You're supposed to
win on your home court. Now they just put the emphasis on us. We
have three games in the Garden.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
