</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZEHEIMER-CANCER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER-FIGHTING PROTEIN MAY LEAD TO ALZHEIMER'S
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A protein that can help stop cancer by killing damaged cells
may turn out to be a major culprit in Alzheimer's disease.
<P>
   Researchers at the University of California at San Francisco
report Tuesday that the protein known as p53, well-known for its
pivotal role in cancer and basic cell biology, can trigger the
death of precious brain cells through interaction with another
substance, called amyloid precursor protein.
</P>
<P>
   The findings could lead to a new target for drug developers
hoping to find a way to block the mysterious process that robs
Alzheimer's disease sufferers of mental function.
</P>
<P>
   The study, led by Lennart Mucke and Xiao Xu at UCSF's Gladstone
Institute of Neurological Disease, appears Tuesday in the latest
issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what we know about p53 we learned from cancer
research,'' Mucke said Monday. ``What we have here is an
interesting link between two major fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutant forms of amyloid precursor protein, also known as APP,
have long been associated with Alzheimer's disease and the build-up
of a toxic plaque in the brain. However, scientists have never
quite understood just how the amyloid precursor protein can lead to
the demise of nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that the normal form of APP inhibits p53 from
switching on a ``cell suicide'' process in the brain. This
protective function is absent in the mutant amyloid precursors.
</P>
<P>
   This mutant APP is the same brain protein found in elevated
amounts in early-onset Alzheimer's cases known to run in families.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research by Mucke and UCSF professor Roger Nicoll showed
that mutant forms of APP lead to increased production of a
breakdown product, called amyloid-beta peptide, which in turn can
lead to the hallmark buildup of plaque deposits in the brains of
Alzheimer's patients.
</P>
<P>
   The new study suggests that plaque build-up is not the only
reason why brain cells may start to die off. If that turns out to
be correct, it means that preventing the plaque from forming may
not be an effective treatment in all cases of Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a drug that also aims at the p53 pathway could be an
important element.
</P>
<P>
   The p53 ``cell suicide'' process is thought to be a good thing
in cancer cases, essentially a natural system that halts the
proliferation of damaged cells.
</P>
<P>
   It's a much different story when the cells are mature, fully
wired neurons in the brain _ the elemental circuitry built up by a
lifetime of memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cancer, you are trying to keep this p53 pathway active. In
Alzheimer's, it may be helpful to keep it from being
overactivated,'' Mucke said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to do that effectively may take a long time,
probably several years. But Mucke said the cancer research at least
provides a head start in understanding the basic biology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
