<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4896 &Cx1f; sci-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONDERS-OF-ICE-NYTSF &LR;      06-22 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERS-OF-ICE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PHYSICS OF ICE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD WOODLEY  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Physicist William Harrison of the Geophysical Institute at the
University of Alaska in Fairbanks spends a lot of time with his ear
pressed against glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hear waves of creaking and groaning and cracking,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, the noise can be terrifying. On Dec. 3, 1936,
Alaska's Black Rapids Glacier awakened with a thunderous roar after
hundreds of years of repose. A colossal mass of ice, snow and rock
_ measuring a mile and a half across and 27 miles long _ crashed
down the valley at the breakneck speed of 10 feet an hour, setting
a new record in glacier velocity as it headed straight for the
local bar.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a century later, the Black Rapids Glacier is
quiet and slow.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and his fellow glacier experts have their ears to the
ice but don't have a clue when it might start moving again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure exactly why glaciers surge,'' Harrison
says. ``But I'm really not sure why all glaciers don't surge.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is.
</P>
<P>
   Ice covers roughly 8 percent of the globe and is one of the most
familiar substances, yet it continues to confound scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other liquids, water expands rather than contracts as it
freezes; that's why ice floats in water. And under pressure ice
melts rather than solidifying further like other substances.
</P>
<P>
   After studying frozen lakes and rivers for 25 years, George
Ashton, formerly of the Cold Regions Research and Engineering
Laboratory in Hanover, N.H., and now retired, says he's still
mystified: ``There are so many basic questions yet to be
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as that glacier in Alaska. When a glacier moves, it doesn't
scrape across the ground like a toboggan on a dry spot. No one
knows for certain what causes it to move at all, typically at a
languorous pace.
</P>
<P>
   The most plausible explanation is that the sheer force of
gravity causes the mass of ice to subtly change shape like cold
molasses as it slumps along.
</P>
<P>
   But other forces may be at work when a glacier tears off at a
gallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a typical surge, glaciers appear to suffer from a
failure of their internal plumbing,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, meltwater bubbles out from internal crevices and exits
from a natural downspout at the glacier's base. But when the
downspout is clogged, the meltwater backs up until the entire
glacier surges down the slope on a thin layer of water and
sediment.
</P>
<P>
   The more puzzling question is why a common patch of ice is
slippery.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still controversial,'' Ashton says.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that pressure builds up within the ice and creates
a thin film of water that greases the surface. Another is that ice
emits vapor, so that other solids actually float, rather than
slide, along the surface. A third possibility is that the top
atomic layer of ice is disordered so the atoms act like a box of
marbles and let other solids slide across them.
</P>
<P>
   Ice remains a source of mystery because of the unruly behavior
of H20 molecules. In gas form, they behave as individuals, single
and fancy-free. As water, they form a complicated, ever-changing
lattice with ties that continuously snap, reconnect and snap again.
</P>
<P>
   As ice, the molecules assume a crystal formation, placing
themselves farther away from each other, and even though these
bonds are relatively stationary, they are easily broken.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most solids, ice liquefies under pressure even at subzero
temperatures and refreezes as soon as the pressure is lifted. Hence
a loop of wire can be pulled through a solid block of ice and the
ice will immediately refreeze behind it.
</P>
<P>
   This process of regelation _ thawing and refreezing according to
variance in pressure rather than temperature _ takes place inside a
glacier all the time. But the exact dynamics of such shape-shifting
have eluded scientists.
</P>
<P>
   H20 molecules perform a host of other tricks when they bond
together as ice. To begin with, the molecular structure expands by
a volume of 9 percent as it freezes, creating a solid bigger and
lighter than water. Plus, in the process of bonding, the molecules
force out other substances.
</P>
<P>
   As seawater freezes, the ice crystals expel droplets of
concentrated brine that are eventually pulled down by gravity into
the water below, leaving the ice at the top 99 percent pure. In
fact, Eskimos depend on sea ice as their source of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   Pure ice is transparent, but the air bubbles in fresh snow
reflect light, a fact that is essential to life as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   Antarctica receives more sun radiation than anywhere else on
Earth, yet the temperatures are so cold and the ice cap so
reflective that minimal ice melt occurs each summer. Otherwise, the
water levels of the oceans would rise by 250 feet and engulf most
of the world's great cities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ice particles in the upper atmosphere reflect and
absorb solar radiation, acting as a global thermostat and keeping
Earth from burning to a crisp or freezing over.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have recently discovered, however, that atmospheric
ice may not be an entirely benign force. Although
chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, have been blamed for the destruction
of ozone, they actually do little harm until they come into contact
with ice particles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice clouds were previously considered chemically inert,'' says
Nobel laureate Mario Molina, an atmospheric scientist at MIT. ``But
we found that ice actually speeds up the destruction of the ozone
layer, because chemical reactions take place on and with ice
particles.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ashton views ice as a continuing source of
fascination and frustration. After spending most of his adult life
trying to figure out the details of how and why ice rots from the
bottom up, he still profoundly distrusts frozen rivers and offers
simple advice to anyone who ventures onto ice in the springtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a metal rod and stick it into the ice in front of you. If
water comes out, turn around and go _ run!
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Woodley is a contributor to Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
