<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ARIZONA-OLYMPIANS     06-22 2255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARIZONA-OLYMPIANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING FOR THE GOLD  
 OLYMPIC HOPEFULS SEEK LARGER SHARE OF RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `` '' ``News item:'' According to a balance sheet prepared by
investigators, 40 percent of the $33,569 given by the Salt Lake
City bid committee to an International Olympic Committee member
went to his daughter for a scholarship. The 40-year-old woman was
not a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day in the life:'' Valley boxer Ray Martinez runs at dawn,
works in telemarketing during the day and spars in the evening. The
19-year-old has postponed college in an attempt to make the U.S.
team for the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney.It's a tale of two
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   One is personified by Ray Martinez's daily routine. It's about
pursuing a dream against long odds and at great personal sacrifice.
There's nobility in the pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   The other is about cashing in on those dreams. It's about big
bucks and the influence peddling that was disclosed in Salt Lake
City's hustle to win the bidding for the 2002 Winter Games. There's
a scandal in the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's hopeful pursuit of an Olympic medal at a personal
cost and Salt Lake City's bid at any cost are symbols at opposite
ends of a widening controversy. It strikes at the heart of all
those things that are supposed to define the Olympics. The sweat,
sacrifice and struggle on the lower ends of the Olympic movement;
commercialism, corruption and greed at the top.
</P>
<P>
   The Games themselves have always been a work in progress. With
every Olympiad, there are more sports, more nations, more media
attention, more people. In the move from individual to
international, from competition to commercialism, there's
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Who owns these Games, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The athletes, whether Olympic medalists or simply hopefuls, will
tell you in words and mostly deeds that they do. Without their
efforts and the subsequent drama they provide, the Salt Lake City
Organizing Committee could have been dealing in widgets, for all
that it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   But widgets don't eat, sleep or train. The athletes do.
</P>
<P>
   Those at the top of their various sports can do so comfortably.
For example, swimmer Gary Hall Jr. of Phoenix receives an annual
training stipend of several thousand dollars. He had a six-figure
endorsement contract during the height of his success.
</P>
<P>
   For those who aspire to the top, it's often a different story,
even more so in sports like cycling and archery that are beyond the
mainstream. In an era of professionalism, they are chasing Olympic
dreams with amateur budgets and ideals. They train with little
fanfare and funding, many of them here in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As they struggle from day to day to maintain and improve their
chances on the field of play, they read about sorely needed funds
going to people who will watch it all from a comfortable seat.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly inherent conflict yields as many reactions as
there are sports.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at just a few from Valley athletes battling
daunting odds as they begin the final push toward national trials
that will determine who goes and doesn't go to Sydney in 2000: &QL; Ray
Martinez, boxing &QL; He's been near
the top of his sport. About a year ago, he was ranked No. 3 in the
the United States at 125 pounds. But since losing a
preliminary-round fight at nationals earlier this year, he's
slipped to No. 8 _ beyond a level called elite by USA Boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The elite get some money, a stipend, from United States Olympic
Committee funds. What's more, they get a lot of help in terms of
training from USA Boxing coaches. Above all, they're sure to travel
to tournaments that are stepping stones to the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and his family save every dime, stage fund-raisers
through trainer Willy Borchert's west-side gym and often ask for
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to ask people for money,'' said Martinez' father, Ray
Sr., who is an assistant deputy warden at the state prison in
Florence. ``Me and his mom (Jennie), we can't always afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Ray Sr. is thankful to USA Boxing. His son has
represented the nation in Europe. He fought last weekend in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The flight and room are paid by USA Boxing. But everything else
_ spending and incidentals _ either comes out of the family funds
or via help from Martinez's west-side neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad and mom have been there for me _ a lot'' said Martinez,
who fits his daily training around his work schedule. ``I'm lucky
to have them. They never had anybody like them. They grew up in the
projects. But for me, they've always been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Being there for the Martinez family won't be easy for the next
10 months. A key trip to Orlando for the Police Athletic League
championships is next on the schedule. It is a qualifier for the
Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, I'm going to get there,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, another promising amateur, 147-pound Ramon Olivas of
south Phoenix, had to leave the PAL tournament after winning bouts
during the first two days. Olivas forfeited before the championship
rounds when he was forced to return home because he didn't have a
place to stay in Orlando on the tournament's final night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to spend some of that money on the kids who are
committed to what they are doing,'' said Martinez's dad, who says
his son finds himself at a disadvantage against the elite boxers
who don't have to work. ``Yes, some of that money should be
diverted to those kids.'' &QL; Trevaia Williams-Davis,
track &QL; Between training at a couple of different tracks in the East
Valley,
Williams-Davis, an alternate for the U.S. team in the 400-meter
hurdles for the 1996 Olympics, works with underprivileged kids at
the downtown YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   She often trains early in the morning before her work shift. For
the most part, she runs either at Mountain Pointe High School or
Mesa Community College. A pair of starting blocks are always in the
trunk of her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nomads,'' said her personal coach, Leonard Braxton, of
the 30-year-old former Nevada-Las Vegas star who moved to the
Valley with her husband, former Baylor track star Terril Davis,
nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Davis, a relay bronze-medalist at the 1995 Pan American
Games, didn't want to talk about the Salt Lake City controversy.
There's not much she can do about it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like Martinez, she is always close to receiving the USOC money
that is divided and then awarded by USA Track &AMP; Field. The top four
nationally in each event get some financial help. Williams-Davis
was fifth last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than you can imagine,'' she said when asked if financing
her Olympic dream was difficult. ``It's almost a Catch-22. In order
to be your best _ be what you know you can be _ you have to treat
track and field as your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to train when you need to. You have to pay a strength
coach. There's nutrition. And, sometimes, you need a physical
therapist. Then, there's equipment and travel to the important
local meets.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Davis, 30, runs on the European circuit. There, life is
easier. Travel, room and board are paid by the promoters. But the
time away from home can be tough. And there is still the burden of
financing travel to key U.S. meets, such as next week's national
championships in Eugene, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, an engineer, un derstands the challenge. He's faced
it himself. Davis was Michael Johnson's roommate at Baylor for one
year and finished fifth in the 800 meters at the 1992 Olympic
Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it (money) gets to all the right athletes,''
said Davis, who works to support his wife's training and travel.
``There are a lot of people who get left out, especially in some of
the longer events. There's just not a lot funding out
there.'' &QL; Terry Ann Roach, cycling &QL; At 47, Roach is
balancing her life between a profession, responsibilities as a
single mom and training in an attempt to make the U.S. team in
track cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Her attempt is unique because of her age. When she was younger,
women didn't have the opportunities in sports that they do today.
Nonetheless, she began to display her talent on a bicycle in the
masters division, a level at which she holds three world and 10
national records.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend she won masters national championships in three
events at Frisco, Texas. She's good enough to be considered a
contender at the Elite National Championships in the 3000
Individual Pursuit and Points Race in August at Trexeltown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   All of that means she good enough to think about the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But training for the attempt is a different issue. She's forced
to travel at least twice a week to southern California for time on
a velodrome track. There isn't one in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly flights are costly, and the trips take her away from
her job as a kinesio-therapist _ rehabilitating clients who have
suffered muscular injuries. The loss of work amounts to another
cost. Then there's the travel to various competitions. Roach has
worked to secure some private sponsorship, but she receives no
Olympic funding, while many of her rivals at the top of the sport
are getting a stipend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, anywhere you go, everything is politics, from
getting your first job all the way to our government,'' said Roach,
who has an 18-year-old daughter and 22-year-old son in college.
``It's not so much what you know, but who you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is absolutely too bad that it is not restructured in a
way that they give a chance to the people who have potential. There
is always that diamond in the rough, that person who has never been
given a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're missing the boat. They just look at the best people
out there, when there are many others who could do something if
given the right attention.'' &QL; Judi Adams, archery &QL; Adams is a
two-time Olympian. She was
on the 1996 team. She also was on the ill-fated 1980 team, which
never got to compete because of the U.S. boycott of the Moscow
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was angry in 1980. But as she nears 40, she is more
philosophical. She is trying to make another U.S. team. After
working for American Express during the day, she practices by
shooting at a target in an alley behind her parents' home in the
West Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the athletes get enough of the money, but I
don't really know if that's just because I'm in archery, which
never gets much,'' Adams said. ``I can tell you that in my years at
the top of the sport, I have gotten very little.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that lack of funding, Adams feels lucky. The position at
American Express started through an Olympic jobs program. For
Adams, it has turned into a career, and it helps pay for her
equipment and other training expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she often is angered by some of the few high-profile
athletes, who are getting rich through commercial endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a Phil Mahre in skiing talks about how much money he
makes during the Olympics, the ignorant public is left to think
that, `Oh, all these athletes are pampered.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What's forgotten are the X-number of these sports that are
really struggling with athletes who still compete for an ideal
that's never going to make them rich. They are truly doing it out
of the amateur spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is all that money available that has been reported as
being siphoned to IOC members, Adams says it should go to the
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   As in other sports, travel is her biggest financial difficulty.
If an archer doesn't travel to various events throughout the
country, it's impossible to stay competitive. In some cases, it
drives promising archers from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely ones who have struggled and have made the
decision: `I just can't live like this anymore. I can't make $2,000
a year and live at home. I'm 35 years old,' '' Adams said. &QL; Eric
Albarracin,
wrestling &QL; Albarracin, a former Arizona State University wrestler,
joined the
Army to get into the chow line.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Albarracin loves K rations. It's just that those
rations are a lot more dependable and even more nutritious than
Swedish meat balls, chicken wings and chips at happy hour.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Albarracin made it to the Olympic Festival at 118
pounds with nothing but a dream. He had no car, no house and no
stove. He slept on friends' couches. He traveled to and from
practice on in-line skates.
</P>
<P>
   His training table was the happy-hour spread at bars up-and-down
Mill Avenue. Albarracin ran into trouble when a bartender began to
recognize him as this guy who was making a meal out of free ``hors
d'oeuvres'' without buying a drink.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of lifestyle that would drive a lot people off the
mat and into some serious drinking. But ASU wrestling Coach Lee Roy
Smith said Albarracin never gave up his Olympic hopes. Hence, he
enlisted, which allows him to train and compete while fulfilling
his service commitment. Otherwise, his wrestling career would have
been over, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Albarracin, who even qualified for one monthly stipend of $250,
is probably an extreme example. Nonetheless, he defines the gap _
the disparity and inconsistency _ between athlete and IOC
plutocrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hope that they're going to get the pyramid turned
around, because it's upside down'' Smith said of the money and
where so much of it seems to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us in the United States, people with the USOC and our
NGBs (national governing bodies for each sport) would very much
like to see changes in the way the IOC does its business.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
