<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-BULLY-ART-2TAKES-     06-22 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-BULLY-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT TOOK BEING THE VICTIM TO REALIZE IT WASN'T AS FUN AS I THOUGHT
IT HAD BEEN' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Wesley Edward Harrington IV, honor roll student
and varsity athlete, made sure his blue blazer was smooth and his
tie straight before he stood to tell his classmates, gathered in
the chapel of St. Sebastian's School, about the boy he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   I once was a bully, he said, and now I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the annual chapel speech required of every
student in this all-boys parochial school in Needham. And the story
Ted Harrington shared the other day with his fellow sophomores was
about the moment in sixth grade when he finally understood what his
parents meant when they told him to treat other people the way he'd
like to be treated.
</P>
<P>
   What started as one more instance of Ted Harrington, funny guy,
drawing a laugh by picking on another kid ended with five boys
jumping Harrington outside the cafeteria of the Day Middle School
in Newton. What hurt more than the blows to Harrington's body were
the blows to his pride, as kids who usually laughed with him
laughed at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was this proud kid and somebody had made himself better than
me in the eyes of my peers,'' he says, recounting the incident _
and the speech _ during a conversation in his Newton home. ``That
hurt. Just being on the receiving end of it and seeing that
everyone wasn't, like, `Oh, this is the funny kid.' It was `Oh,
this is funny.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It took being the victim to realize it wasn't as fun as I
thought it had been. I can never remember feeling good about
pounding on someone or making fun of them or a good joke I made
about someone, but I'll always remember the time I was on the
receiving end.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Harrington was not a classic bully who used hostility to
vent his anger and insecurity. Rather, as a player in the often
confusing, socially uneasy, sometimes cruel culture of American
boyhood, he was one of those kids who initiate taunts rather than
stand to the side or take the heat themselves. Bright, gregarious
and athletic, big and somewhat old for his grade, he slipped into a
social role that fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the ringleaders pretty much,'' he says. ``There
were other kids who started it and were definitely worse than me,
but I did my fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   That he could, in his moment of humiliation, learn empathy
rather than a renewed determination to dominate represents a
victory, years in the making, of home over culture. Boys may be
boys, but ``boys will be boys'' need not always prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Ted's father, Wesley E. ``Wes'' Harrington III, is a man who
isn't afraid to hug his three children (20-year-old Heather,
16-year-old Ted, and 13-year-old Kyle) or shed tears in their
presence. When Ted repeats what his father, whose company manages
medical trade associations, says about the life of a businessman,
the message is about relationships, not aggressive dealmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his business anyway,'' Ted says, ``you really need to be a
people person and respectful of what other people have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Judith Harrington, who brokers commercial printing
jobs from their home, won't let problems simmer. ``I might say this
will take care of itself,'' says Wes, ``where she'll make certain
it's discussed.'' She's also the one who bans R-rated movies, even
action films, sometimes to the groans of her husband and sons. ``I
just don't want, especially for my boys, to have those images in
their mind,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It was back in elementary school, around fourth grade, that Ted
and his friends joined to make life miserable for a precocious,
awkward boy in the neighborhood. The boy's parents finally
transferred him to a private school in fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like him now _ he's a good kid _ but I used to make
fun of him, like, every day,'' Ted says. ``I remember one time
crawling under the seats of the bus _ I thought this was really
crafty at the time _ with a page of stickers and I stuck them all
over his legs and shoes and stuff. Then, like, I went home and was
chucking little pebbles at him and stuff. I didn't even realize
that that was something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted's parents knew it was wrong as soon as the other boy's
parents told them about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were well aware that, for a variety of reasons, this boy
was having a hard time, not just in our neighborhood,'' says Wes,
51. ``You hoped _ and this is the Pollyanna part _ that your son
wasn't part of it or at least was on the periphery. Ideally, we'd
all like him to be the one who goes in there and says, `Stop it,'
but let's be real. Then to find out that he was part of it, it was
all those emotions we felt: Anger. Disappointment. Concern for the
person most affected by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Should they punish their son, Wes and Judy wondered, ground him,
or take away a favorite activity or toy? Or could that backfire, if
he blamed his loss on the boy he was bullying?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he broke a neighbor's window. This was something
that had implications for the rest of his life,'' says Wes. ``We
wanted to deal with it so he got the message.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harringtons talked to their son. How would you feel if
someone was doing this to your brother or your sister?
</P>
<P>
   ``He had what we thought were the age-appropriate responses:
`I'd stand up and fight for them, if I had to,' '' Wes recalls.
``We said fine. The point of what you're saying is it's
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they'd revisit the issue, ask Ted how things were going.
``I honestly think Ted was upfront in his answers because they
weren't always rosy,'' Wes says. ``We'd be in there saying, `Were
you part of it? Did you do anything to stop it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Ted ignored his parents. But in the
banter-and-bravado, tease-or-be-teased, conceal-how-you-feel world
of boys that age it was hard to shed his status as the funny guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened but it didn't soak in because it happened again and
again,'' he says. ``I'd feel bad about it for awhile. Then I'd be
back at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he left the school every single kid felt they had a part
in it and felt really terrible, even though we were young. We
weren't old enough to be able to admit it to anyone, but we all
knew we felt awful about it. And so whenever I see him I feel kind
of guilty. I do my best to be cool with him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Judy attended a lecture at Dana Hall School in
Wellesley that gave her some insight into Ted's experience.
Catherine Steiner-Adair, a psychologist, discussed child
development issues and Judy, notebook in her lap, wrote furiously
as Steiner-Adair spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Little boys, Steiner-Adair was saying, pass a ``tragic''
milestone by early elementary school. ``They master the poker
face,'' she said, ``and the developmental challenge of learning how
not to cry.'' If they haven't learned that by age 8 or 9, well,
they're in trouble. They're the ones who will be teased. She called
it ``losing boys to the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell little boys to disconnect from their vulnerability,
their sadness, and their feelings,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Harrington certainly wasn't opening up about his feelings
with his friends in late elementary and middle school. ``It's just
not something you did at all,'' he says. ``If you ever open up an
emotion or something, somebody would be right on that. There's this
unwritten rule that you can't be weak.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
