<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4912 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-COLLEGIANS-     06-22 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-COLLEGIANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COLLEGIANS MAKE WAVES IN NHL DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where are all the great hockey players coming from nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the best of the best no longer hail only from Canada. And
although a major European invasion of teenage talent continues to
migrate across the Atlantic to the NHL, it isn't just the Finns,
Swedes, Czechs and Russians who are making waves.
</P>
<P>
   A new trend has surfaced on NHL Draft Day, as more and more
players from U.S.-based college programs are now spilling into the
equation. And they are beginning to make quite a splash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a real good answer for it, but the
college game is going pretty good right now, no question,'' said
Bob Murray, a Boston-based agent for several hockey stars,
including the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk. ``We've seen some guys come
out of the college ranks like a Paul Kariya, who everyone realized
could step in and play the game right away, and NHL teams are
thinking, `Geez, maybe if we give these college kids an
opportunity, they can do this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little more mature, maybe a little more ready. I
think it's something you definitely could see continuing for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers support the theory. From 1991 to 1994, only 37
skaters from U.S. universities were drafted by NHL clubs. In the
past three years, however, that figure has risen to an astounding
78.
</P>
<P>
   After only six college players were chosen in the 1994 draft and
five went in '95, a total of 25, 26 and 27 were selected in each of
the past three draft classes, respectively. Three of the Coyotes'
10 picks a year ago played collegiate hockey this past season.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. collegians once again figure to play a significant role in
this year's NHL entry draft, which will be held Saturday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, only one U.S. college player in history has ever
been selected first overall _ Canadian-born Joe Murphy of Michigan
State in 1986 _ but he won't be alone forever, most scouts, general
managers and agents would agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a lot more college kids get drafted, and
the majority of them are probably going to be Americans,'' said
Brian Kilrea, coach and general manager of the Ontario Hockey
League's Ottawa 67s, who won the Memorial Cup last season in his
25th year behind the bench. ``The U.S. has jumped ahead of Canada
in many regards because they've kept up with the growth. They
continue to build rinks and continue to give players an opportunity
to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada, we can't keep up with the growth. We can't satisfy
the ice time for everyone who wants to play. Girls hockey is big
here now, too, but we just don't have the rinks like we used to.
Even the outdoor rinks. It used to be, you'd grab your stick and a
puck and go outside and play. But we're laying people off up here
and a lot of outdoor rinks aren't manned, and we've stopped making
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Canadian, it's disappointing. We're sort of forgetting
about our greatest export, which is hockey players. Now, there's
more attention being give to U.S. players and Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   That being said, Kilrea has four players from last season's
Ottawa club who are expected to be taken in the first three rounds
Saturday. Three are defensemen (Luke Sellars, Jeremy Van Hoff and
Jonathan Zion) and the other is a goalie (Seamus Kotyk). Moreover,
two other former Kilrea prospects have re-entered the draft:
defenseman Nick Boynton, who was selected ninth overall last June
by Washington; and center Matt Zultek, taken 15th overall by Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the top 20 North American prospects, however, are
skaters from U.S. colleges. They are Michigan defenseman Jeff
Jillson (No. 11), University of Maine left wing Barrett Heisten
(No. 14), Minnesota defenseman Jordan Leopold (No. 16), Maine
defenseman Doug Janik (No. 17) and Notre Dame center David Inman
(No. 19). All but Inman, who was reared in Toronto, were born in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey's growing by leaps and bounds in the United States.
Just look at how many rinks we've got in the Phoenix area now and
how many more are getting built,'' said Canadian-born Bill Lesuk,
the Coyotes' longtime director of scouting. ``We've almost had a
monopoly up here in Canada, but it's just a matter of time before a
kid born and raised in Arizona makes it to the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be long. But until then, dozens of college
players will take the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a couple of things,'' Coyotes assistant general
manager Taylor Burke said, explaining the recent influx of drafted
collegians. ``First, you typically see a lot of copycat trends in
the league, whether it's the style certain clubs try to emulate,
such as the defensive system of New Jersey, or getting big like
Philadelphia or trying to do what Dallas does. If somebody has
success with something, well, sometimes you try and see if it works
for you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Former college players like Anaheim's Kariya, Buffalo's Brian
Holzinger, Colorado's Chris Drury and Edmonton's Tom Poti are
changing the landscape. Burke thinks NHL clubs are better for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the other thing, you've got a longer period to look at
them when they're in college,'' he said. ``Guys can stay in college
for four years, and you know more about them after four years than
you do after two years (in junior hockey).''
</P>
<P>
   College players who went undrafted also are becoming prized free
agents, and a host of NHL teams, including the Coyotes, have been
quick to recognize them. Phoenix, for instance, wasted no time in
signing Maine defenseman David Cullen the moment the captain led
his school to the NCAA championship last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``College players have opened people's eyes a bit,'' hockey
agent Murray said, ``and the pros are going after them. Even the
kids who get bypassed in the draft and are too old for the draft.
There's still opportunities for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-EXPECTATIONS-2ND &LR;      06-22 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-EXPECTATIONS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla.: ... of apartheid.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Valentine's Day, Richard had just returned to Virginia
Wesleyan from Nashville, where he had been organizing protests
against South Africa's scheduled appearance in the Davis Cup tennis
championships. That night, he said, two masked intruders burst into
his office, used metal file drawers to bludgeon him, and carved a
racial epithet _ niger (sic) _ into his belly.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitalized for several days, Richard was reluctant to tell his
young son what had happened. But Joe had heard others talk about
it, and he twisted the accounts into a five-year-old's fantasy. ``I
know you were attacked by bank robbers and they cut your heart out
and put it in your stomach,'' Joe told his father.
</P>
<P>
   In the nightmarish aftermath, local police suggested to
reporters that Lapchick had staged the assault as a cheap publicity
stunt, which Richard later rebutted by submitting to a polygraph
test and a physical exam by the New York medical examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a telephone threat against Joe and his younger sister,
Elisa, who had just returned home from a visit with their
grandparents. ``It must be good to have the kids home,'' a man on
the telephone told Richard at his office. ``It may not be for
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard called home and discovered that Joe suddenly was
missing. As the police searched, Richard and Sandy, his wife at the
time, waited helplessly until a neighboring family brought Joe home
more than two hours later. The neighbors said they had taken Joe to
see their new home. ``It was the most terrifying experience of my
life,'' Richard says.
</P>
<P>
   The episode left him feeling so vulnerable that Richard took a
job the next day as a United Nations liaison officer and moved his
family to New York. There, Joe was in trouble from the start,
repeatedly picking fights with other children.
</P>
<P>
   When a child psychiatrist examined Joe, the doctor said the boy
felt guilty because he had not protected Richard from the attack
and was fearful that one day he would be assaulted like his father
had been. The psychiatrist said Joe, in his young child's mind, was
physically preparing himself for the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   A year of psychiatric therapy curbed the fighting, but Joe
continued to seethe beneath the surface. ``I don't think I grasped
that there was still a lot of turmoil going on inside him,''
Richard says.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was, Richard was not home much to assess Joe's
crisis. Driven both by a passion for his work and the coolness of
his strained marriage, Richard was away nearly nine months a year.
Joe played an entire youth soccer season and half the next season
before Richard showed up to watch him play. And as they walked away
from the field, Joe asked, ``Dad, why don't you ever play soccer
with me like the other fathers?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard thought he was helping Joe, as his father had helped
him, by not pressuring his son to excel in his sports. But
Richard's absence from Joe's sports life symbolized a deeper
separation between the father and two children. Though Richard
always told Joe and his sister he loved them and was proud of them,
the bond was weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, I never knew my dad,'' Joe says, ``until we moved
to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1984, when Richard opened the Northeastern center. Joe
was 12, and though he relished his father spending time at their
new home in Milton, Mass., Joe soon witnessed the dissolution of
his parents' marriage. They separated for good on Jan. 1, 1986.
``It was hard to see them fighting,'' Joe says, ``even if they
probably weren't meant to be together in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   When Richard quickly fell in love again, with his current wife,
Ann, Joe became increasingly resentful. ``I felt like Ann was
taking my dad away from me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joe, who divided his home life between each of his parents'
houses in Milton, started to funnel his frustration into alcohol
during his freshman year at Archbishop Williams High School in
Braintree, Mass. During the week, Joe all but abandoned interest in
school, and his grades slipped so severely that he needed to repeat
his freshman year when he transferred the next fall to Blue Hills
Regional Technical School in Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, Joe's drinking escalated. From a six-pack of
12-ounce beers, he went to two six-packs. Then it was 16-ounce
beers. Then 16-ounce beers and a pint of liquor. Then he was
drinking during the week as well. Soon, Joe was smoking marijuana,
too.
</P>
<P>
   While Joe sank into a haze, Richard was warning coaches,
athletes, and educators about the dangers of alcohol and drug use,
especially after Len Bias, the Boston Celtics top draft choice,
died of cocaine intoxication in 1986. But Richard missed the
warning signs at home, as he had squandered his earlier chance to
create firmer boundaries for Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back a lot and wish my dad was more strict with me when
I was younger,'' Joe says.
</P>
<P>
   Richard says he offered Joe more support than discipline because
he worried about the lingering effects of the attack in Virginia.
But he sees now that the strategy was flawed, particularly after
Joe slipped into substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, Richard also found handguns under Joe's
bed, which Joe now says he and his friend planned to use only for
target practice.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Richard says, his failure to grasp the severity of
Joe's distress reflects an experience that is sadly common among
contemporary parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be Joe's friend and not his father,'' Richard
says. ``I understand now when people ask, `How could the parents
not know?' I thought I was taking care of my son by trying to be
his friend, and I was not seeing that this little boy was involved
in this life-threatening situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard's wife, Ann, sensed Joe's troubles and urged Richard to
confront Joe. But Joe wanted no part of Ann's intervention or his
father's response to it. ``It may have helped me recognize the
problem,'' Joe says, ``but it made me much more reluctant to accept
Ann. She was bringing all the heat down on me. And it made things
worse between my dad and me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there was no magic fix. Only after Joe finished high
school, he says, did he recognize he had an addictive personality.
He realized his parents _ and Ann _ loved him and supported him.
And he gradually eased away from his self-destructive behavior.
``My life wasn't focused on drinking anymore,'' he says. ``It was
more on achieving success.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joe struggled academically for two years at Northeastern
and in a brief stint at Valencia Community College in Orlando, Fla.
Then he discovered while working part-time promoting nightclub
events _ and through his personal interest in cooking _ that he
wanted to pursue a career in the culinary arts at Johnson &AMP; Wales.
</P>
<P>
   But he faced a final hurdle. Joe's father has spent most of his
adult life steering young people, particularly athletes, toward
completing traditional college programs. And Joe feared letting him
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real eye-opener for me,'' Richard says. ``I realized
that whatever pressure I had exerted on him, I had been leading him
to do what he thought I wanted him to do as opposed to what he
wanted to do. He really thought his decision would displease me. In
fact, it really made me very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe, who lives with his girlfriend, Michelle, in Providence, is
preparing to develop and market a marinade based on his mother's
recipe. He says he plans to call the marinade ``Sandy's Sauce,''
and he hopes to strike it rich. He credits his father for helping
him ``fulfill a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   For Richard's part, he says he has seized the lessons he learned
from raising Joe to help him be a better father for his and Ann's
daughter, Emily, who is 9. Richard never misses Emily's soccer
games, and when he travels he no longer leaves a night early and
returns a day later, as he used to do when Joe was young. Now, if
Richard is not home to kiss Emily goodnight, he is there when she
wakes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to learn from my mistakes and do things
differently this time,'' he says. ``I really feel blessed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
