<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE TO TEST INJURED SHOULDER TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Todd Stottlemyre is still far from pitching in a big league
game, but he could have fooled his wife  &UR; Sheri during lunch on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Watching her husband act restless, she asked what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I kind of have that nervous energy,' '' the
Diamondbacks pitcher said. ``It feels like the day before I'm
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre wishes he could take the mound against the
Cincinnati Reds tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the right-hander will gently throw the ball for the
first time since going on the disabled list May 18 because of a
partially torn rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Today), the rehab starts to become fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll likely throw from about 60 to 70 feet today and
gradually progress the workload each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's champing at the bit,'' Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said.
``He'll be the happiest guy in Phoenix (today), hopefully after he
goes through (the throwing workout).''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he gained about eight pounds of muscle from
working out with weights since the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a pitcher, you're afraid to lift too much weight,'' he
said. ``I had no choice but to make every muscle, from the toes up,
as strong as I can. I'm probably stronger now than I have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he'll try to emphasize his legs and midsection
while pitching to take pressure off the shoulder. He's not given
himself a timetable on when he'll pitch in a game again, but
trainer  &UR; Paul Lessard said if all goes well, perhaps in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I call time frames and deadlines are restrictions,''
Stottlemyre said. ``If I say in three or four weeks I want to pitch
in a game, I might be realistically ready in two or three weeks.'' &QL; 
A batter's eye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reds first baseman  &UR; Sean Casey was just hoping to play again.
Then, he just wanted to make the most of each at-bat. Now, the
24-year-old in his first full season in the major leagues, is
leading the National League in hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to be leading the league right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into last season, Casey was struck in the face with a
thrown ball during batting practice while he was out in the field.
He suffered an orbital fracture of the right eye and lacerations
that required 20 stitches. A plate with five screws was inserted to
free up the muscles around the eye for normal motion and vision. &QL; 
Father's long day &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Vladimir Nunez said his wife,  &UR; Wendy, will be induced
Wednesday morning, which will allow him to be with her during the
delivery of their second child and still make it to Bank One
Ballpark in time for the game that night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
