<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-GUNS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-AR     06-22 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-GUNS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 RAPID CITY, S.D.: ... is doing.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My dad,'' Glenn says, ``has taught me that if you have to
fight, you have already lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent solutions,'' interrupts the father, ``are never
permanent solutions. Never long term. If you study history, you'll
see that US history has done nothing but taught us that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ronn was growing up here, a gun was a friend. Little boys
from his era were as interested in guns as they were in shooting
marbles. There was food in the hills, animals to be stalked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fall, when I was a kid,'' Ronn is saying, ``we hunted
deer before, and after, school. We never brought the guns into the
school. It never crossed our minds to do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado shootings, the Arkansas shootings, seeped into
South Dakota like they seeped into everyplace else. ``The West is a
small place,'' Ronn says. ``We're spread out, but there's not a lot
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Littleton also seeped, deep, into Ronn Jones. He sat down and
wrote a couple poems about the shootings, the dreadfulness of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who will have to die next
</P>
<P>
   Before we think
</P>
<P>
   Who can stop this
</P>
<P>
   We Must
</P>
<P>
   Or it will be us next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, Ronn Jones is no Auden, but he gets his poems written.
That's satisfaction enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers. We think we're on top of the world,'' Glenn says.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times when, to Ronn, his son looks and feels lost.
There are times when he just can't figure out what kind of thoughts
_ dark or lovely _ might be coursing through Glenn's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always want to find out how he thinks,'' Ronn says. ``Where
the potential conflicts may be coming from. I want to find the
philosophical areas we disagree on. We share common interests, so I
can see something coming if it's coming. I don't know if the
parents in Littleton could have seen that coming. But I know by
communicating with a child, you have a better chance at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Jones's voice goes up and down in octave range, like a
drama student's might on direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy it that children get transfixed by outside
influences, such as brainwashing,'' Ronn says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, I worship a Greek mythology God,'' the son interjects,
matter-of-factly, his head swiveling closer to his dad's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll grow out of that,'' the father says quickly, bringing a
cigarette to his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   When Glenn first wrapped his finger around the trigger of a
rifle, he was 11 years old. But when he fired that first shot,
there wasn't a deer or prairie dog in sight, only a TV. The echo
and shattered screen scared him fiercely. He laid the Winchester
down and picked up the phone and called his father. He was crying
that he didn't know the gun was loaded. The father rushed home. The
boy was shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Glenn, the fear you have now in you is enough
punishment.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The rod was spared, but not the rifle. Ronn Jones wouldn't let
Glenn Jones hunt. Ronn Jones enrolled his boy in a yearlong weapon
safety course.
</P>
<P>
   He says he knew the fear of not hunting would yank his son's
attention in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my son,'' Ronn says, the voice rising. ``I can tell you
what my son has in his room. What he has under his bed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay dad, what do I have under my bed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three skin magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   The son laughs, cackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a wanna-be cowboy hick,'' Glenn says. ``Now,
mostly what calms my anger is turning the music up and smoking
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' the father says, his eyes shooting upward, his voice
hardening, ``I wish you wouldn't tell me you smoke cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   What space there is between them narrows when the two set off
into the Black Hills to hunt. They stay through the day and night,
watching stars crawl across the sky, listening to nature's random
melodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like working together as a team out there,'' Glenn says.
``When we go hunting it's just me and my dad, alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Out there, in the hills, or on the wide-open prairie, Ronn can
sometimes feel tenseness and anger just lifting up out of his son.
It's as if he's been given some kind of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he stops talking to me I can tell something's bothering
him,'' Ronn says. ``I think, then, maybe we should go outside and
spar until he's got enough of the surface anger out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the violent video games _ ``Time Kills,'' ``Final
Fantasies,'' _ Ronn figures they're everywhere, at the mall, at the
homes of friends of his son. So he's tried to adopt an intellectual
attitude toward them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play with him,'' Ronn says. ``They're good for the
imagination. But I teach him _ and he knows _ that in fantasy
violence you can shut the game off and those people stop
bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In real life,'' says Glenn, ``you don't get to push the reset
button.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week Glenn is having a meal at a local restaurant.
He's with his girlfriend, Sammi. Sammi is 13 years old. She lives
with her mother over in back of the K Mart store in a trailer park.
She's being home-schooled. Glenn is bragging about how fast he can
drive, about his grades in school, about how much he knows about
American geography. Sammi's eyes are wide; she worships her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very good with a .22,'' Glenn says, regaling Sammi with
hunting tales.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about the two high schools in town. Glenn doesn't want
Sammi to go to Stevens High. ``Too preppy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And stuck up,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Glenn says, ``I can get through the next three
years of school. I'll be the only boy in my house with a high
school diploma. Right after high school, I'm going into the Army.
If they'll take me.''
</P>
<P>
   He figures he'll have to work, to grind, for his diploma. ``I'm
not the perfect angel,'' Glenn confesses.
</P>
<P>
   He's tried marijuana. Told his dad he tried the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   He once skipped school, was caught because the car he was
driving got stuck in a ditch and he had to be pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   When he feels he might be getting too angry or upset, when he
feels he's beyond even his father, there's a counselor he can go
to. There he can rant and rave; he can tell secrets to the
counselor. ``Some of the stuff I've done my parents couldn't take.
If they knew, I'd be grounded til I was 30.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't predict his future, anymore than he can predict the
number of elk in the Black Hills that will fall to the hunter's
rifle next hunting season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only get once chance at this life,'' the son says. ``You
screw that up, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from his father, Glenn also says this: ``I got a side to me
nobody's seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And, very sweetly, he says this: ``All my dad's poems are
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from his son, Ronn says this: ``We're all amateur parents.
We're all struggling in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one man; just one father.
</P>
<P>
   And he expresses a little sadness that his son might not
appreciate the discipline he has instilled in him _ not until years
down the road. ``He won't understand my reasons for punishment for
another 20 years, when he has a son. I hope I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The afternoons across the South Dakota landscape are beautiful
these days, clear as spilled wine.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Jones has recently started talking about setting aside the
swordplay for a stick this summer. A stick he can swing as hard as
he wants.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be something new.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Dust in his eyes. A glove on his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Dad hovering.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be something new for the Joneses.
</P>
</TEXT>
