<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-BULLY-ART-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-22 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-BULLY-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEWTON, Mass.: ... be weak.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wes remembers those unwritten rules. He grew up in Holyoke,
where junior high was his most difficult time. He was overweight,
not yet grown into the athlete he would become in high school.
``When somebody picked on me,'' he says, ``and really was
merciless, that was like a stake through the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he went to Williston Academy, a nearby boarding school for
boys. There, he recalls, some classmates taunted one boy by
dangling him by his feet outside a third-floor window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I was a candidate for sainthood,'' Wes says.
``By sheer luck, and that's all it was, I happened to fall into a
group of kids and we had other things that were more important to
us than taunting kids. I think the chemistry in our group could
have changed and we would all have been part and parcel of it. None
of us went out of our way to say, `Don't do that!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wes survived that taunt-and-tease culture, and so, it seems, has
Ted. Does that mean the wounds inflicted and wounds received aren't
so deep after all? Wes is ambivalent, though he can't say how he'd
feel if his son were the one harassed daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure the system doesn't work, if you know what I
mean,'' he says. ``I think boys and men have dealt with resolving
their issues ad nauseum. The way you traditionally deal with
conflict may not be the right way, but I don't think this will
change. And I'm not so sure it has to.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Harrington shakes her head. ``Mars and Venus,'' her husband
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mars and Venus,'' she agrees. ``But there are still so many
threats to healthy personalities in our culture and in society and
in ourselves. You have to constantly be grappling with those.''
</P>
<P>
   That night at Dana Hall, Steiner-Adair said something that gave
Judy hope. What boys who do well in high school have in common, she
said, ``is an affectionate, interpersonal connection to their
fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wes, an only child, was 16 _ Ted's age _ when his father died of
congestive heart failure. His dad was a doctor, a general
practitioner who took young Wes along on house calls and who was
open in his affection. Four years later, his mother died. If you
want a reason for his insistence on keeping his relationships in
order, look to those early losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad,'' says Ted, ``loves us every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, as the family was driving home from visiting Judy's
parents on Cape Cod, one of the boys said, ``You know what I really
miss, Dad? We don't know your parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean I just started to get all teary-eyed,'' Wes recalls.
``Ted said to me, `Are you crying?' I said, `I really miss my
parents. One of the things I don't have and will never have in my
life is the ability to put my arm around my dad and say these are
my kids.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy kind of understood that. He said, `Well, you better stay
alive because I expect to do that with you and my kids.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Every Christmas, Wes hangs an ornament on the tree for each of
his children, along with a personal letter. This past holiday he
wrote Ted how proud he was of the way he's adjusted to St.
Sebastian's. Both he and his wife schedule ``special days'' with
each child, one-on-one time when they do whatever the child wants.
</P>
<P>
   Wes goes to Ted's games, to lacrosse, soccer, basketball. In
April, after St. Sebastian's lacrosse team overcame a six-goal
deficit to beat Hingham 9-8 in double overtime, Ted broke away from
his teammates to leap into his dad's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never cold with me,'' Ted says. ``If I have something to
say he's always there with a hug or whatever. Like if I come off a
playing field and I feel like I've had a terrific game, he'll frown
upon it if I got in a kid's face after I scored or something. It
shows a little bit that morality is above all else. Being a good
person.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the things, more than sit-down talks about other
people's feelings, that together made a difference in this boy's
life. Yet the pull of the culture was strong and lessons about
respecting others were a long time in the learning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ted never again taunted the boy in the neighborhood after the
boy switched schools, but he didn't stop teasing other kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked to be the center of attention. I liked to get
people to laugh. At that stage in life I didn't quite have the wit
to be able to pull it off without it being at someone else's
expense,'' he says. ``I was blind to other people's emotions. It's
not that I was blocking it out. I just hadn't thought of it. All I
knew was I was making a joke and other people were laughing. That
was my reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came middle school. Since the incidents in the
neighborhood, the Harringtons had received no calls from parents or
teachers about Ted's behavior. Still, they were wary. They didn't
expect Ted to be teased, but they made a point of talking to him
again about bullying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern was new school, new territorial rules,'' Wes says.
</P>
<P>
   But the only sign the Harringtons had that something might be
amiss came when Ted complained about another kid, a bigger boy.
Mostly, he told them, the two avoided one another. Then just before
the school year ended, Ted was teasing another boy and the bigger
boy told him to cut it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd either give up my dignity and submit or call his
bluff,'' Ted says. ``So I called his bluff, which wasn't a bluff at
all, and he dropped me on my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after lunch, the bigger boy and his friends surrounded
Ted. ``I had this feeling that they weren't there to talk,'' Ted
says, ``so I picked the smallest one and went at him. Before I knew
it all of them had come down on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted required no more medical attention than a visit to the
school nurse. Still, the Harringtons were upset and angry. They met
several times with school administrators. They made sure the boys
would not share classes the next year. And they talked to their
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him at the time, and it's still vivid today, that you
want to bottle that feeling,'' Wes says. ``You want to never forget
how hideous you felt because you'll be that much more empathetic
the next time you could do it to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In seventh grade, Ted hung back when the teasing began. ``But I
never ever would have stood in the way,'' he says. ``You need to be
really sure of yourself to be able to do that. You're not sure of
yourself at all until ninth or tenth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Ted would rather forget all the teasing he once did.
``I feel like an idiot about it,'' he says. Other times, however,
he's glad he remembers. ``If you don't learn from something,'' he
says, ``you're going to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   His speech the other day in the chapel at St. Sebastian's marked
the first time he had said out loud what he learned that June day
in sixth grade. He elicited laughter, at nobody else's expense,
with the way he described being jumped. He closed with a passage
from the Bible, from the first book of Peter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, all of you, be of one mind, sympathetic, loving
toward one another, compassionate, humble,'' Ted read. ``Do not
return evil for evil, or insult for insult; but, on the contrary, a
blessing, because to this you are called, that you might inherit a
blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
