<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-MOTHERS-ART-BOS &LR;      06-22 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-MOTHERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY MOM HAS HER WAY OF HELPING ME DEAL WITH MY PROBLEMS SO I KEEP A
COOL HEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLESEX, N.J. _ The Gladwells' annual family reunion is some
shindig. Polish sausages sizzle on the grill, and a dozen kids
splash in the swimming pool. Proud grandmothers cradle new babies,
aunts and cousins catch up in animated conversations, and a
country-and-western band of dads and uncles fills the sun-baked,
suburban backyard with a strong beat and sweet harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Gladwell kin flew in from as far as California. The
Sumski brothers came from Long Island, and Karen Taylor, their
sister, drove up from Virginia with her two sons. Relatives
greeting Alex, her older boy, couldn't get over what a man he's
become and how much he looks like his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the spitting image of Jeff in his expressions, his
mannerisms, his wit,'' says Melanie Gladwell, a cousin from San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm like my dad,'' says Alex, a tall, husky,
and talkative 13-year-old who's not too shy to cut in for a slow
dance with his pretty, red-haired cousin. ``He was a great guy. He
played music, he told bad jokes, and he had a certain way of doing
things that made everybody happy. As I become a man, I'd like to be
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a successful career in Washington and scholarly
credentials, Alex's father, Jeff Taylor, is remembered at these
reunions as a regular guy, humble and nice, a model parent, and the
life of the party who loved to jump on stage singing his own silly
songs and strumming a guitar. Taylor's brain cancer and death three
years ago, when he was 41, clearly left a huge hole in the family's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   It also launched his wife, Karen Sumski Taylor, on a difficult
journey to find the stamina, means, faith, and humor to fill Jeff's
big fathering shoes and to raise their two boys, Alex and Luke, 6,
to be men as accomplished and decent as he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, I was worried. I wasn't sure Karen had the
character to carry on,'' says her brother, Richard, who admired
Jeff so much that he named his only son after him. ``But when I
look at Alex and Luke now, I know Jeff must be up in heaven,
smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Karen's devotion to the task. A quintessential
New Yorker _ fast-paced, in-your-face, and kind of feisty _ she has
determined that in spite of their loss and a culture that stacks
the cards against it, she is going to bring up her boys to become
moral, mannered men.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, I told myself there was no way I was gonna
let these boys fall through the cracks,'' Karen says. ``But I'd be
lying to say it's not frightening raising two boys, particularly
one who is headed for high school. And I always wonder if I am
doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually she is just too caught up in the everyday logistical and
financial challenges of single motherhood to dwell on the big
parenting picture. Her dining room table is piled high with
still-to-be-sewn costumes for the middle school play, in which Alex
stars as the wizard in the ``Wizard of Oz.'' The catalog and
curriculum she was hired to write on urban-school gardens is still
in the computer. Another kindergarten mother just called, irate
that angel-faced Luke smacked her son a time or two because he
doesn't attend Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call Luke the mutant alien in this family,'' Karen laughs,
marveling that she bore a blond, dimpled child so athletic that he
can hit a golf ball over the garage and so self-composed he can
spend a whole afternoon alone with a GameBoy. ``But he's no
religious fanatic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's noon _ drop everything!
</P>
<P>
   Karen, who dubs herself ``the crisis queen,'' needs to deliver
an easy-to-chew lunch to Alex at school. Over the weekend, he took
a baseball right in the braces. It broke a bone in his mouth,
knocked some of his teeth loose, mangled orthodontic wires, and
caused a bloody mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't know whether to sit down and laugh or cry,''
says Karen, rescuing a pan of overcooked rice from the stove.
``This parenthood stuff is just way too much for one person. I lean
on my neighbors, I lean on people at my church, but believe me, it
is just not the same as having a dad around.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jeff Taylor got sick, raising the boys was very much the
joint project of two well-educated and financially-secure parents
who saw no limits to the opportunities they could provide. Jeff
held a doctorate in economics and was on the fast track at the
International Monetary Fund. The Taylors of Fairfax, Va., dreamed
large dreams of exciting travel, a grander home, perhaps even
moving the family to China, where Jeff had studied on a Fulbright
fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because of his sheer competence, or his laid-back West
Coast upbringing, or the simple fact that he was a man, Karen
wanted him to build a powerful bond with the boys. Page after page
of Alex's photo album shows a totally devoted dad: Jeff on ice
skates, riding horses, walking on the beach, camping with the Boy
Scouts, coaching soccer, opening Christmas presents, balancing a
bicycle, breaking a pinata at a birthday party. In the morning,
Jeff would read Alex the newspaper. At night, he would play his
guitar and sing his sons to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a better father than I was a mother,'' Karen says,
surveying her toy-cluttered kitchen. ``He was gentle, patient,
calm, always wanting to do the right thing and not make a mistake.
I came from a much more knee-jerk, reactive family. As a parent, I
was all over the map. Jeff showed me there was another way.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in middle-class Massapequa, N.Y. _ she sat next to
comedian Jerry Seinfeld in an eighth-grade social studies class _
Karen was intimidated by her own father, who was controlling and
very strict. In college, she wanted to study botany, her first
love. He forbade it, steering her into medical technology because
it would provide her with a trade. Edward Sumski mostly expected
his daughter to marry and ``stay home and raise children,'' Karen
recalls, something she almost didn't do because of her own unhappy
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Anne Sumski, who is married to Karen's brother Peter, says
her father-in-law was ``a volatile, touch-the-belt man who was
always yelling'' at his offspring. ``Karen had to reteach herself
and make sure what didn't work for her and her brothers would not
be revisited on her children,'' Jo-Anne says.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Taylor, by contrast, came from a big, nurturing, Oregon
family, and he had a close relationship with his father, a school
superintendent. When he met Karen in Washington, D.C., in 1977,
Jeff was headed for a doctoral program at the Unversity of
Michigan. He convinced her to quit her job, marry him, move to
Michigan, and get her master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylors were married for 17 years. ``As I think about
raising my boys to be men, I look to what I was attracted to in
Jeff _ his intelligence, his integrity, his gentleness, his
generosity, the value he put on education,'' Karen says ``These are
qualities anybody could have, but I find them particularly
attractive in a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also acknowledged my needs, which is how I would want my
boys to be in a relationship,'' she adds. ``I want them to treat
women as equals and to encourage their spouses to grow, to achieve,
and to be what they want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen, who stopped working after Alex was born and Jeff's job
demanded more overseas travel, now has plans to pursue her early
ambitions _ horticulture or floral design. She calls Jeff's
pension, life insurance, and other benefits from the IMF ``a gift''
that, with careful budgeting, allows her to keep their comfortable
house in a quiet, family-friendly subdivision and stay at home, at
least until Luke is in grade school.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers Karen, who is 44, the opportunity to be a
full-time parent, a role she embraces with gusto and drive.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that she hangs around their schools a lot, keeping
tabs on the boys' activities, assignments, and friends. She also
has no qualms about phoning a teacher to report that Alex left his
homework on the kitchen table, or quizzing mothers of the girls who
keep calling and inviting Alex to ``hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also very direct. When Karen heard that one of the kids
in her car pool had a complaint (that she's ``always late''), she
invited the boy into the front seat of her minivan for a little
heart-to-heart chat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
