<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN23-CO     06-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moneytalk: Shoring up your retirement base
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study reaffirms a painful situation: Most Americans think
they will have enough money to support a comfortable retirement,
but many haven't done much to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   I talked last week about investing for retirement, in a column
you can find at www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com/business.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, a Washington think tank released an important
survey on how Americans are dealing with a much broader range of
tasks that go into building a prosperous retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Retirement Confidence Survey shows we have a high
degree of confidence things will come out right. In the telephone
survey of more than 1,000 people, 71 percent said they are
confident or very confident they will have enough money to retire.
</P>
<P>
   The study also indicates a high degree of self-reliance. Nearly
half the respondents said their personal savings will be their most
important source of retirement income. Only one in eight said they
look to Social Security or other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   It sure does sound good. But the study also points out specific
actions that many people haven't taken. Here's a look at the most
common shortcomings and some ideas for overcoming them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 49 percent of us have tried to figure out how much we
need to save for retirement, up from 32 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, making your best estimate of your future needs can be
monstrously complex. The question is how reliable a projection you
want.
</P>
<P>
   For a general idea, there are any number of worksheets
available. I like the Ballpark Estimate worksheet developed by the
American Savings Education Council. The ASEC is one of the sponsors
of the survey, along with the Employee Benefit Research Institute
and pollster Mathew Greenwald and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   You can find an interactive version of the worksheet on the
Internet at www.asec.org. For a printed version, write to ASEC
Savings Education Brochures, American Savings Education Council,
Suite 600, 2121 K St. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20037-1896. (Send
along a self-addressed envelope bearing $1.01 postage.)
</P>
<P>
   The worksheets _ including a somewhat more detailed version in
the retirement resource center at www.vanguard.com _ have some
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they won't help you decide how much risk you're
willing to take to boost your returns. They don't give much
guidance in deciding how costly a retirement you want to save for,
either.
</P>
<P>
   For more reliable estimates, you'll have to do some heavy
reading or hire a professional to help. A number of certified
financial planners will accept a one-time fee to draw up a plan.
The fee might run from $500 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 16 percent of Americans have saved more than $100,000 for
retirement. The median was $29,514.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to increase your retirement stash in the future,
you'll have save more from each paycheck now.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the study showed that 57 percent of Americans
could save $20 a week more than they are doing now. Only one in
eight say they would have to give up anything else to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you put $20 a week into a tax-deferred account, such as
an IRA, and earn an 8 percent return on your investments. After 10
years you would have $16,300, in 20 years it would be $51,400 and
in 30 years it would more than $127,200.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fear continues to be one of the primary motivators for
saving for retirement,'' the survey asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of respondents said they save because they can't
count on Social Security (53 percent), they've seen other people
struggling in retirement (48 percent) and they've realized that
time is running out (39 percent).
</P>
<P>
   But fear also can work against you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative motivations tend to freeze you, make you want put
your head in the sand and not do anything,'' said Elizabeth Jetton,
a certified financial planner with Financial Vision Advisors.
``Positive motivations make you want get in control and take
action. You've identified what you want. It's the difference
between being scared and hiding, or being drawn to make something
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, Jetton said, is to figure out your goals and what it
will take to reach them, then break the process down into baby
steps and start immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Few people know when they will be eligible for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with that is easy. To order a free estimate of how much
Social Security benefits you'll be entitled to, and when, call the
Social Security Administration at 1-800-772-1213. You can also
order your individualized report over the Internet at www.ssa.gov.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 36 percent have thought about insurance for long-term or
nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
   Because this can be expensive and hard to shop for, you may want
help from an insurance agent or financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to do it yourself, you can get a free pamphlet, ``A
Shopper's Guide to Long-Term Care Insurance,'' from the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners, 120 W. 12th St., Suite
1100, Kansas City, Mo. 64105.
</P>
<P>
   Another good place to start is the AARP Web site, www.aarp.org.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
