<HEADER>
A4931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX     06-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's put the stigmatism back in curse words
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A 25-year-old computer programmer from
Detroit has been found guilty of swearing with vigor and frequency
in front of children and faces a possible 90 days in jail. Seems he
was canoeing on the remote Rifle River when he fell overboard and
let loose with a string of obscenities fit to curl an old salt's
forelock.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's easy to understand the hapless sailor's
frustration at finding himself arse over teacup (my grandmother
used to say that) in a frigid river with a bunch of dry folks
watching, his timing was lousy because there was a family with
young children in a nearby canoe. Taking exception to the bad boy's
trash mouth, Dad instructed the older ones not to listen while Mom
clapped her hands over the baby's ears. Later, they filed a
complaint based on a 103-year-old ban on swearing in front of women
and children. The judge dropped the ``women'' part for obvious and
politically correct reasons, but the American Civil Liberties Union
is fighting the conviction saying it clearly violates the
Constitution. The executive director of the Michigan ACLU reminds
us that we hear unpleasant language every day _ ``on the streets,
on the radio and television, in sports stadiums, and many other
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah sure, but that doesn't make it any less revolting.
</P>
<P>
   There was never a ban on swearing in my house. It just wasn't
necessary. My father, as was expected of men in those days, cut
loose with a ``hell'' or a ``damn'' every once in a while when the
situation called for it, otherwise he minded his mouth _ even when
it called for a superhuman effort.
</P>
<P>
   It was early spring and my father had just made his annual
pilgrimage to the attic for screens. He hosed them off in the back
yard and leaned them against the garage to dry. That was on Sunday
afternoon. Monday morning over breakfast, he mentioned to my mother
that he intended to paint them that afternoon when he came in from
work.
</P>
<P>
   Since I'd been with him when he bought the paint and that
special little padded thing for rubbing it on, I figured I knew as
much about the job as anyone else, so that afternoon as my mother
lay reading her latest Kathleen Norris novel and popping
chocolate-covered cherries, I set to work and painted every last
screen. By the time Daddy pulled into the driveway, I'd finished
the job and could hardly wait to show him what I'd done. The way I
had it figured, I'd be up for at least a super deluxe fudge sundae
at Sally Ann's Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Parlor for my effort.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't quite work out as planned. Daddy took one look at
the screens, muttered, ``Thank you, darling,'' and marched into the
house. I followed at a distance because I knew when my father's
face was (SET ITAL)that(END ITAL) red, all was not well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen the screens?'' he asked my mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're leaning against the garage where you left them,'' was
her noncommittal reply.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy suggested they were not quite as he'd left them and asked
her if she'd like to take a look at (SET ITAL)her(END ITAL)
daughter's handiwork. All in a row, the three of us paraded down
the drive to the side of the garage where the screens were propped
drying in the late afternoon sun. Mother paled. Daddy got red again
and spluttered about all of the little holes being plugged with
black paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry,'' my mother warned, ``if you're going to swear, do not
do it in front of the neighbors or the child.'' As Daddy took one
last sorrowful look at what used to be our screens, she added,
``and do not take the Lord's name in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Profanity used to be a private thing, and while I confess to
being capable of holding my own in any waterfront bar, I am still
offended by the loose lips of a liberated generation where the only
known adjective begins with ``F'' and is used every fourth word.
Makes a body wonder why the English language has half a million
words and why so many folks use only a few four-letter ones.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431; email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
