<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-NOTIME-ART-2TAKES     06-22 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-NOTIME-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY FATHER ALWAYS SAYS A BLACK MAN MUST WORK TWICE AS HARD' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One winter's morning 11 years ago, Edward Palmer
dressed his three children, loaded them into his car and set off
across Atlanta, searching, like a lost soul, for a Baptist church
that would take him in.
</P>
<P>
   His pilgrimage ended at Hopewell Baptist, a tiny neighborhood
church. Sunday services had already begun, but Edward strode right
in, oblivious to the ushers and well-dressed church folk on either
side, and seated himself and his children in a front-row pew.
</P>
<P>
   After a heart-heavy pause, he stood. He had come to confess his
failings to that church full of strangers, to tell them how, in his
relentless pursuit of an engineering career, he had given short
shrift to his family, leading his wife to walk out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he broke down in tears. For in that moment, his focus
had shifted from his own inner turmoil to the 5-year-old boy
standing next to him, his son, Jadwin.
</P>
<P>
   Got to save that boy.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who had presided over his divorce had decided to award
him custody of the child, saying that only a father could prepare
his son for the world that awaits him.
</P>
<P>
   Got to raise that boy.
</P>
<P>
   It was a commandment he would embrace, though he would have to
figure out for himself how to do so. His own father slipped out of
his life when he was a young child and his parents divorced; an
ailing grandmother was the adult anchor of his young life.
</P>
<P>
   Jadwin, he resolved, would get something quite different: His
son would never doubt his demands of him, never wonder at his
dreams for him, never miss his stern determination that his boy
would not fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've go to remember, I came from a broken family before so I
always promised never to let my family be the same way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The love would prove harder to show. It has not been an easy
path for either father or son, though Edward is hardly the only
father to struggle to balance great expectations and tenderness,
his own high ambitions and the time a child needs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he alone among fathers in coming down, when it counts, on
the side of expectations and ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That judge gave me a responsibility and I intend to follow
through,'' Edward says, ``I can be friends, but it is my job first
to teach him. I don't call that rigid. I call that being a teacher
and father.''
</P>
<P>
   A teacher and father who still struggles to balance family time
with a frenzied career.
</P>
<P>
   Since Edward Palmer, 47, walked into Hopewell Baptist Church, he
has traded one busy lifestyle for another one. His religious
``calling'' came shortly after that Sunday morning but it wasn't
until 1995 that he left his job at an electrical engineering
company to become the assistant minister of Hopewell Baptist, which
has grown into one of the largest and most opulent churches in the
Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who is also studying for a master's degree in theology,
spends most of his waking hours counseling, teaching, and traveling
as far as India and Haiti to serve others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm busy in such a different way, not seeking my own selfish
desire, but seeking to help people,'' he says. ``That is the
difference. Back then, it was about helping me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While his father leads his parish, Jadwin, now 16, has rebelled.
He is casual about school work, preferring to play the class clown.
He has risked and earned his father's displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   The women in the family mainly blame the schism between father
and son on the sort of generation gap common in many households.
But they also wonder if Jadwin's behavior is a symptom of his
father's preoccupation with his spiritual work.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is mindful that his sternness may widen the emotional
divide between them, but he says it is a risk he will take in order
to protect his son from the low expectations that have defeated too
many young black men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a father has to make time for his children,'' he says,
then shifts the onus to his son. ``But he hesitates to talk to us.
. . . I tell him he has to open up and allow others in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap between father and son hasn't always been so wide. There
was a time when young Jadwin didn't want to be anywhere but near
his father, says Alice Palmer, Jadwin's paternal grandmother.
``When he was young they were real close. Ed was a single father. I
think as Jadwin got older he began to rebel. I think he is looking
for attention,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Jadwin lose his mother to his parents' divorce, but
his father had little time to spare after coming home from a busy
day, cooking dinner and cleaning the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jadwin never recovered from not having a relationship with his
mother,'' says his oldest sister, Sharell, 20, who along with their
grandmother is Jadwin's confidant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did miss her in the beginning, and maybe that has
contributed to things,'' Jadwin says.
</P>
<P>
   Sharell followed another emotional path. Only 8 when her mother
left, she wanted nothing more than to help out her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jadwin thinks I favor Sharell,'' says Edward, ``but I love
them the same. It's just that Sharell knew about those hard times.
We built a bond. She has proved herself.''
</P>
<P>
   In those early days, members of Hopewell Baptist, so moved by
the young black man who poured his heart out to them, rallied
around the Palmer family. The women would braid Sharell's hair and
help babysit Jadwin.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the family was mending itself. Edward married
Deborah Wallace, and together they had two girls, Chloe, 3, and
Amber, 16 months. And, just as Hopewell grew from a small
congregation to one with 14,000 members, Edward Palmer has thrived
spiritually and professionally; he now supervises 35 ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he is much busier than before. He takes his job more
seriously because it's a calling from God,'' says Sharell.
</P>
<P>
   But as the tapestry of Edward's life unfolded, Jadwin was
pressed to the sidelines, his self-image fraying. Jadwin shares his
father's church-bred good manners, but beyond that the gap between
them grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jadwin is not the type to take the initiative, so I try to
wait and watch to see what he wants to do (with me),'' says Edward.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad says I am a class clown,'' Jadwin says. ``It's just
that the other kids think I am funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jokes in class have been a problem for teachers at
Collins Hill High School who say they can't compete with Jadwin,
who playfully imitates them as they give lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said while he is smart and a joy to teach, he is very
distracting, too'' Deborah, his stepmother, says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
