<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4933 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BARRETT-EXPOS23-C     06-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BARRETT-EXPOS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Barrett is doubly valuable
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Being there Opening Day wouldn't be such a big deal.
After all, he hadn't even spent one minute in Class AAA yet.
Michael Barrett was destined for an honorable major league career
with the Montreal Expos. Every scouting report said so.
Nevertheless, his timetable insisted there was one charter flight
he absolutely had to make this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself last spring my No. 1 goal was not to make the
team out of spring training,'' he said. ``It was to make the trip
to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett comes home tonight, four years, two weeks and six days
after the Expos plucked him from Atlanta's Pace Academy, their No.
1 pick in the 1995 draft. He has never seen the inside of Turner
Field but will do so this week from several angles _ from behind
the plate and from third base _ when Montreal plays a three-game
series with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   And if his eyes look like they're spinning like pinwheels out
there, that's no act. The big leagues seem even bigger from the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day is a mental challenge,'' said Barrett, 22. ``The
energy on the field is just incredible. Each day you have to get up
like it's the World Series in order to hang in there and stay
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He's alive, all right, hitting .278 with 27 RBIs, and if he ever
learns to hit away from Olympic Stadium _ Barrett's road average is
.219 _ he is rookie of the year material. If St. Louis's Joe
McEwing, Pittsburgh's Warren Morris and Florida's Alex Gonzalez are
the front-running rookies, Barrett is just a length behind the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He plays both third and catcher well enough to routinely bump
veterans Shane Andrews and Chris Widger out of the lineup,
remarkable in that he'd never put on catching gear until 1996. He's
already had a taste of history. During a quick eight-game call-up
last September, he was behind the plate for Mark McGwire 69th and
70th home runs on the season's final day in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But the historic bows to the sentimental this week, during his
first games in his hometown. In some ways, the kid who watched the
Braves across the street at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium is still
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old place had a lot of memories,'' Barrett said. ``I had a
chance to talk with Fred McGriff the other day when we were playing
Tampa Bay. I told him I was a big fan of the Crime Dog. To be on
the same field with him was kind of special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos made an obstacle course of Barrett's rush to the
majors. Drafted as a shortstop after helping Pace to three
consecutive Class A state championships, Barrett hit .311 in rookie
ball in 1995 but was informed the final day of instructional league
that he was being shifted to catcher. He'd never caught in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett took a week-long crash course that fall, made a strong
impression the next spring but was exhausting himself. No one ever
told him he didn't have to jump up from his crouch to make his
throw back to the mound, or than catchers weren't expected to
sprint on and off the field during the changeovers.
</P>
<P>
   But the position came naturally and halfway into the 1996
season, he made the South Atlantic League All-Star team. In the
Class A Florida State League in 1997, he threw out a strong 33
percent of stolen base attempts. Last year at Class AA Harrisburg,
he made the Eastern League All-Star team, pumped his stolen base
percentage to 38 percent but was informed after the break he would
be playing third base.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of Widger in Montreal, after coming over from
Seattle in the 1997 Jeff Fassero trade, had made the organization
rethink Barrett's future. Learning an infield position wouldn't
hurt him, even if Baseball America ranked him the best catching
prospect in the minors last season. He went to camp last February
ready for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrett's learning to play in the big leagues,'' manager
Felipe Alou said after the Expos broke camp. ``And it isn't fair to
have him alternating from one position to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   But times have proven otherwise and Alou has even used Barrett
at shortstop this season in a pinch. He has become the Expos' best
contact hitter and is ranked sixth in the league for fewest
strikeouts per plate appearance. The first pitch he ever saw at
Olympic Stadium, he hit over the wall last April off New York's
Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett knows his run production will have to improve if he is
going to be a third baseman and also knows his game-calling at
catcher will improve as he feels his way through the NL the first
few times. But if this is the way he will make it _ two positions,
both suited for improvement _ that's the way he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy doing both because I don't think there's a person in
the game that's doing what I'm doing now,'' he said. ``It makes my
place in the game very unique and it's something I value. I feel
it's a special quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
