<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4934 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYSTERECTOMY-ALTERNAT     06-22 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYSTERECTOMY-ALTERNATIVE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many hysterectomies may become procedure of past, thanks to
surgery alternative
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The question was never if Lora Black would have a
hysterectomy, but when. Medication hadn't curbed the excessive
menstrual bleeding that had made her anemic and disrupted her life.
Her three older sisters had undergone hysterectomies. Now it was
her turn.
</P>
<P>
   But when? When could she take four to six weeks off to recover?
``There's never a good time to stop functioning,'' she says, but
the summer seemed less bad than others and, better still, was
months away at the time she decided.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Black's doctor told her about a new alternative
to surgery that uses a heated balloon to burn off the uterine
lining, which was her source of boundless bleeding. Most of it
sounded good, but the word she kept having trouble with was
``new.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she saw a patient talk about her intra-uterine balloon
therapy on a network news show ``I guess I had to hear it from
another woman,'' Black says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell her she believed television more than she believed
me,'' says Dr. Luis Morales, Black's gynecologist at Miami Valley
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Morales performed the procedure on a Friday last December. Black
spent the next day on her feet doing her Christmas shopping. She
went back to work that Monday as an occupational hand therapist
with her own business, subcontracting occupational therapists to
area hospitals and doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been incredible,'' she says six months later. ``I can go
on vacation whenever I want. I can wear a white dress any day I
want.'' She no longer needs to pile bath towels on her bed before
going to sleep. She never has to excuse herself every five minutes
from her job, a tennis game or whatever anymore to run to the
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really just dictated my life,'' Black says, ``It was
getting harder and harder to plan anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors expect this balloon therapy _ and some other new
treatments for different causes of heavy uterine bleeding _ will
put a serious dent in the 600,000 hysterectomies in this country
every year. After Caesarean sections, hysterectomies are the second
most common surgery for women and probably the second most commonly
criticized surgery for being unnecessary. The balloon procedure
could replace 20 percent to 30 percent of those surgeries,
generally those not involving fibroids or cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive menstrual bleeding is more than an inconvenience. It
causes anemia in about two-thirds of the women who suffer it, which
can lead to fatigue at least and deadly organ damage from iron
deficiency at worst.
</P>
<P>
   For 40 percent of the women in a clinical trial of the
intra-uterine balloon, the bleeding made it impossible to work
outside the home. But after the procedure, that figure was 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Black, now 43, was so tormented by her floods of bleeding that
she asked her doctor if there were some kind of medication that
would bring on menopause and end her menstrual periods entirely.
After two or three years of it, the blood bank turned her down for
being anemic and she braced herself for a hysterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was my turn,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But she knew it was a far riskier passage than gray hair or
reading glasses. On her job, she had talked to women whose bladder
control had been hindered by hysterectomies, even when only the
uterus is removed without the cervix or ovaries. Pelvic pain,
sexual dysfunction and depression can be other side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major surgical procedure,'' Morales says, with all the
accompanying risks of blood loss, infection and complications from
general anesthesia. It also costs four to five times as much as the
balloon procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he acknowledges, some doctors probably do more
hysterectomies than are necessary. The Dayton area in particular
has ``about double the rate of Cincinnati,'' says Rich Gunza, the
local executive director of Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield, and
a heavy lead over national rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Gunza and Morales both say it's often the patients who
demand hysterectomies. The operation stops the bleeding quickly and
completely, while medication can be a lengthy process with mixed
success. ``We spend more of our time telling people they don't need
a hysterectomy,'' Morales says.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon makes his case easier. Approved in December 1997,
it's a straightforward outpatient procedure that takes about an
hour. ``It's no more uncomfortable than an annual exam,'' says
Black, although cramping is common enough that Morales often needs
to use an additional sedative.
</P>
<P>
   Black apparently had adenomyosis, a condition where the lining
of the uterus grows into surrounding muscle, but it can't be
diagnosed positively without removing the uterus. She also had
fibroids, which are benign tumors in the uterine muscle. Those are
the most common causes of menstrual bleeding, but Black was unusual
in having tumors in locations where the device could reach them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a balloon on a stick,'' she says. ``It's
actually a straw.'' Inserted vaginally, the balloon is filled with
sterile sugar water that is heated to about 87 degrees. Once
filled, the balloon conforms to the endometrium, the uterine lining
and the primary source of menstrual bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to burn off as much of that lining as you can, so it
cannot do anything,'' Morales says. That leaves a woman essentially
unable to bear children but still able to develop a complicated
pregnancy, so the procedure is only for women whose families are
complete.
</P>
<P>
   An even newer treatment, for fibroids, does not necessarily rule
out pregnancy. Dr. Christopher Conley at Miami Valley has done four
uterine-artery embolizations, radiological procedures in which tiny
solid particles are snaked through an artery and left where they
block the main blood supply to the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fibroids die without the blood,'' Morales says, ``but
there is a lot of collateral circulation to the uterus, so it is
not damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks of her embolization, Kathleen Hanover was free
of her symptoms, which were similar to a mid-trimester pregnancy.
Her fibroids shrank by half in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tremendous,'' says Hanover, who works for the Miami
Valley American Heart Association. ``I was looking at sterility and
six weeks of recovery and after effects for the rest of my life
with a hysterectomy. I literally jumped up and down when I saw in
the Internet it was being done in Dayton. I was prepared to go
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Black still has very light periods, as do about 80 percent of
women after the balloon procedure. Surveys have shown an
extraordinary rate of 86 percent later saying they were ``very
satisfied'' and another 10 percent ``satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People think because their mothers and sisters had
hysterectomies that they have to have them, too,'' Black says.
``But even if the problem is hereditary, the hysterectomy isn't.
Technology has changed things. All my three sisters have told me,
`We wish this would have been available.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
