<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4939 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-GUNS-ART-2TAKES-B     06-22 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-GUNS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY DAD HAS TAUGHT THAT IF YOU HAVE TO FIGHT, YOU HAVE ALREADY
LOST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAPID CITY, S.D. _ Glenn Jones owns three guns. He is 15- years-
old.
</P>
<P>
   With one of the guns _ that would be the .22 Ruger rifle his
father bought him _ the boy can bring down prairie dog at 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Out here , in the West _ less wild these days but still wide
open _ that's the way it's always been and is supposed to be.
Children learn to shoot, and their fathers are proud to help.
</P>
<P>
   Out here, fathers and sons can loll over the carcass of a dying
animal and get to talking about the good hunt, and about their love
for one another.
</P>
<P>
   Out here, the guns don't get locked up. Just like the silverware
and dishes don't get locked up.
</P>
<P>
   But now, even this world is changing _ slowly, subtly,
powerfully. It is not that after the string of schoolyard shootings
_ from Jonesboro, Arkansas to Littleton, Colorado _ the love of
guns has lost its grip on the people of the Black Hills. But worry
has crept into the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Ronn Jones, Glenn's father, is a hunter, too. But he also
anguishes about the nuclear fallout of 1999: kids crouched behind
weeds, licking their lips, training their eye, shooting classmates
down in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   As if laws were so much dust.
</P>
<P>
   As if classmates were so many prairie dogs.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the clamor about a so-called loss of innocence in
society sometimes seems about as meaningful to Ronn Jones as the
dirt flying around the Black Hills here. In his eyes, the world's
been tricky and dark for a long time now.
</P>
<P>
   Ronn Jones feels he knows his son better than most fathers know
their sons. Feels he can predict his boy's movements, his boy's
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are times when he worries himself sick. He's just
one man, just one father. He trusts his son to use weapons wisely,
but he also fears the gathering power of violence _ of thought,
word and imagery _ in the world Glenn will inherit. Where will all
the anger go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' the father says about the son, ``I feel that I'm
losing him.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does a father raise a son enamored of guns and the
culture that surrounds them?
</P>
<P>
   This is how Ronn Jones does it: He plows into his son's life.
When necessary, he tries to bearhug the anger out of his boy.
(itals)Talk to me, Glenn. Talk. To. Me.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   He uses his own story to try to connect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember what it's like to be a teenager,'' Ronn Jones
is saying. ``I can feel the pressure of wanting to fit in. My dad
was one of the best dads ever. I lost him when he was 63. Much too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   You can travel through the bright mornings and dark nights of
the Dakotas _ so desolate, so legendary _ and wonder what an angry
child might do if provoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a kid says, `I'm going to kill so and so,' well, you need
to find out what the kid means,'' Ronn says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep the line of communication open,'' he says of his
relationship with Glenn. ``When a child makes a sweeping statement
_ `I'm going to kill that guy' _ that's a demand for attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The father says he gets dizzy sizing up the world in which we
live. ``I know what to expect from the real hoodlum, but nobody
knows what to expect from the Ted Kaczynskis. They have an agenda.
Some of these kids _ in Littleton, in Jonesboro _ they were quiet
ones to.''
</P>
<P>
   Let Glenn Jones come home from school mumbling, hunching his
shoulders, banging cabinets before slamming his bedroom door, and
he'll get a whoosh of his father, right in his face, eyeball to
eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell what kind of day he's having from the moment I say
hi to him,'' Ronn says. ``If it comes down to it, I'll take him in
my bathroom and stay in his face until I get something.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronn is a night security manager for an area hotel. Over the
years he'd listen to other adults ridiculing kids, shaking their
heads about their manner of dress. They'd just be kids swimming
through the Rapid City night _ in black trench coats, wearing rings
in their noses, often stamped with tattoos. The so-called rebels,
misfits. But somebody's children.
</P>
<P>
   Some would walk by Ronn Jones staring like owls. He'd strike up
conversations. So many reminded them of his own son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got kicked out of high school once,'' he says. ``I know what
it feels like to be an outcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronn Jones grew up in South Dakota. His father and uncles helped
put the finishing touches on Mount Rushmore, 35 miles outside town.
He fought in Vietnam and came home with a Purple Heart. He married
Kerry, who already had children. They had Glenn together. But two
of the stepchildren _ boys _ got out of the house without getting
their high school diplomas. He didn't like that. They'd listen to
him all right. But then they'd go their own way.
</P>
<P>
   Ronn vows it'll be different with Glenn. ``I still got input
with him,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Father and son are seated around the living room table. As they
talk, Ronn's wife, Kerry, walks through the house, cuddling the
family's Boston terrier. Kerry knows how to handle a weapon well
enough herself; she also works as a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a neat home, though small and cluttered. Out the back
door you can see the fields of the Dakotas stretching as far as the
eyes can roll. Dozens of paperbacks are squeezed onto a shelf. The
Joneses love Larry McMurtry; he's their Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The guns are out of sight, but the medieval swords lie just
beside the bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Try raising an aggressive 15-year-old. There can be a surprise
everyday _ for Ronn Jones, those swords were one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's love of swords and swordplay was born at a local coffee
shop here. The lady who owns it belongs to the Society for Creative
Anachronisms, an organization born in Berkeley, Calif., back in the
'60s, when counterculture activities were the rage. The SCA's aim
and interest is to re-create the European Middle Ages; they adore
the period. Members celebrate medieval times by studying history,
reading fantasy fiction, and by engaging in swordplay. The stories
are fantasy, but the swords are real.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Glenn, an SCA member, seems a little more interested
in the swords than the literature. Ronn Jones wouldn't let his son
belong to the group alone. So he joined, too.
</P>
<P>
   Erroll Flynn on the prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Jones has a raspy voice. He wears an earring. He talks
fast, words racing out of his mouth faster than his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says his father has taught him to deplore violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's stupid,'' he says. ``Just because people make fun
of you doesn't give you the right to turn to violence. There is no
reason you should ruin your life just because somebody is picking
on you.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he can't imagine taking weapons to school. ``Going into
schools with firearms isn't going to solve anything,'' he says.
``You're throwing your life away. That's prison time. That's a
felony.''
</P>
<P>
   He has learned, up close, about that. Two of Glenn's friends
were arrested after Littleton for phoning in bomb threats. ``Two of
my best friends,'' he says. The incidents baffled him. ``People
that do that don't have answers to their problems. They resort to
threats.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost two more friends recently from suicides. One immolated
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real world is not sweet and innocent,'' Ronn says,
stretching for an ashtray, lighting a smoke. ``The real world
sticks it to you. Innocence died in Vietnam. All of our eyes are
now open. It's a different world. We can't wish it away _ but we
can work with it. I wish I could raise my son the way I was raised,
where my biggest fear was being bored to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn may be clear about the hazards of aggression, but he is
still a boy _ and a teenager. He's balled his fists at classmates.
He's made threats under his breath. Ronn knows. ``I ask him to
think about how the other person feels,'' Ronn says. ``Use a little
empathy. See if there's any validity for what the other person is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
