<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Something is troubling America's boys. Is it confusion over
male roles? A violent culture? The Globe sent writers across
America to find some answers. The project, which reveals a common
struggle among Americans to raise healthy boys in a sometimes
confused and angry world, is reported in a six-part package,
accompanied by photos by staff photographer John Blanding. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEN-OUTCAST (Booneville, Ark.) _ As Bill Wagner stood watching
the sun set over his small, beloved farm at the southern edge of
the Ozark Mountains, he made an announcement of his own: To protect
his homosexual son the family would move away. By Mitchell Zuckoff.
(2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEN-GUNS (Rapid City, S.D.) _ In the West children learn to
shoot and their fathers are proud to help. Fathers and sons can
loll over the carcass of a dying animal and get to talking about
the good hunt, and about their love for one another. By Wil
Haygood. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEN-MOTHERS (Middlesex, N.J.) _ Jeff Taylor's brain cancer and
death three years ago, when he was 41, clearly left a huge hole in
the family's heart. It also launched his wife, Karen Sumski Taylor,
on a difficult journey to find the stamina, means, faith, and humor
to fill Jeff's big fathering shoes and to raise their two boys. By
Mary Leonard. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEN-NOTIME (Atlanta) _ It has not been an easy path for father
or son, though Edward Palmer is hardly the only father to struggle
to balance great expectations and tenderness, his own high
ambitions and the time a child needs. By Tatsha Robertson. (2
takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEN-EXPECTATIONS (Lake Buena Vista, Fla.) _ By all accounts, Joe
Lapchick was as gifted a father as he was a coach and an athlete.
He nurtured his son, spared him from the agony of unmet
expectations that living in a legend's shadow can breed, and
watched him thrive. By Bob Hohler. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEN-BULLY (Newton, Mass.) _ Ted Harrington was not a classic
bully who used hostility to vent his anger and insecurity. Rather,
as a player in the often confusing, socially uneasy, sometimes
cruel culture of American boyhood, he was one of those kids who
initiate taunts rather than stand to the side or take the heat
themselves. By Irene Sege. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the General National (a) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
