</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-NOTIME-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     06-22 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-NOTIME-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 ATLANTA: ... stepmother, says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teacher conferences and restrictions on television only
temporarily prod Jadwin onto the right track, before he flounders
again. His parents worry that he won't be ready to step into his
adult life when he turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that when you turn 18 it is time for you to be a
responsible adult,'' says Deborah Palmer. ``We are not pushing him
out the house, but either you go to college, vocational school, the
military, or get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward tries to impress on his son that, particularly for a
young black man, realizing life ambitions requires redoubled drive
and focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't showed me that he has the necessary skills to
survive. He has to be disciplined,'' Edward says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, discipline and focus are the hallmarks of Edward
Palmer's life.
</P>
<P>
   On this scorching day in affluent Gwinnett County, where the
family lives in a large split-level home, Edward begins the day
early, in his plush office at Hopewell Baptist Church checking his
messages at the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he will take time out with Jadwin to build a shed in the
family's backyard, help his son apply for a summer job, then rush
back to teach a Bible class at noon.
</P>
<P>
   And so it continues through 3 a.m. While most of his family
members are sleeping (except Jadwin, who is secretly watching ``The
Godfather'' in the basement) Palmer and Sharell are busy seeing off
eight church members headed to Haiti on a missionary assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in idle time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Or forgetfulness. Earlier that day, when Jadwin and his father
were heading off to deliver a job application, Jadwin realized he
had forgotten his state photo ID. To his father, it was perfect
segue into a lecture on why Jadwin can't be trusted yet to drive or
own a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh lord, not again,'' says Jadwin, cringing at yet another
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   But later, en route to retrieve the ID, there is a moment of
connection. Palmer, glancing in the rearview mirror, smiles at his
son, a lanky boy with flawless dark skin, dimples, and a strong
resemblance to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks I'm hard on him,'' his father confides, ``but I wish
I had someone as a young man to guide me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of four boys and one girl, Edward Palmer was raised
in the projects of Charleston, S.C., by his granny _ Leona Bennett.
His parents divorced years earlier and his mother, who next married
a military man, spent much of her time away.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Edward's youth was spent washing dishes, helping out,
and changing the bed for his sickly grandmother. When he turned 14,
he moved to Germany to be with his mother, but he still had to make
his own way during the years when a boy most needs a role model.
</P>
<P>
   His teacher was the world around him.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in Charleston, he saw many loveless marriages, boys his
own age running wild, and unemployed men just hanging the corners.
He vowed that would never be his lot, and that if he had a son he
would show him the way to a better life.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, father and son drove to Charleston to trace
Edward's early years and visit his old haunts. The Palmer men drove
across the seaport city, through the downtown projects where Palmer
grew up. They stayed overnight in a hotel, and ate crabs and
oysters until they were full.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just me and my dad chilling in Charleston, South
Carolina,'' Jadwin chuckles. ``It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time for us to discuss things, to reflect, just the
father and son,'' says Edward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the biggest highlights for my brother in a
long time,'' says Sharell. ``Jadwin really wants that relationship
with my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Alice Palmer: ``Sometime you can get so busy that you can
lose your child. . . . I think Jadwin loves his daddy more than
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is not the emotional father some might expect a preacher
to be, but he believes he can show his love by teaching his son.
And by being the clear voice of male authority in a household that
he won't let fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was imperative and I was determined not to let it
happen,'' he says
</P>
<P>
   But it did. His first marriage was a failure; he lost touch with
the one child who stayed with her mother. But he was more than ever
determined to be the main force in the lives of the two who stayed
with him, Sharell and Jadwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live up to what I say. I didn't want a broken family and
though I got a divorce, it didn't mean I had to give up my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard lessons he learned in life as a soldier during the
Vietnam War era, a student at the University of South Carolina, and
in the corporate world, he wanted to pass along to his son.
</P>
<P>
   And, he believes, Jadwin is finally hearing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always says a black man must work twice as hard,''
Jadwin says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he scours the internet for job possibilities _ Jadwin
says he can imagine himself as an archeologist, a coroner, even a
private detective _ he feels a new seriousness dawning about the
need to take responsibility for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I'm getting older and need to start thinking about
my future,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Edward is slowly evolving, too. While he continues to impress
hard life lessons on his son, he says he feels the need to slow
down, maybe even ease up on Jadwin _ a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying hard. He wants everything to be all right,''
Sharell says of her father.
</P>
<P>
   The means to that end? Time.
</P>
<P>
   Not long hours _ Palmer doesn't have those to spare _ but more
simple acts of sharing: working on the car together, playing hoop
in the driveway, watching movies at night or building an outdoor
shed. One recent day, Jadwin, wearing baggy jeans held up a board
while his father, dressed in a white worker's apron, hammered away
on the shed.
</P>
<P>
   Jadwin later left to see the new Star Wars movie , but when he
returned, his father was still hard at the task _ using a stick now
to hold up the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you replaced me with a piece of wood,'' jokes Jadwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything can be improvised,'' his father retorts. They both
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Later, while the two grab lunch at a local Chinese buffet _
father careful not to fill his plate, son munching through a small
mountain _ Jadwin announces his intention to become an electrical
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Just bringing it up is a bit of a risk for the boy, and a kind
of emotional test for the father _ a test which at first Edward
doesn't seem to master. ``I know an engineer needs to be
disciplined in his studies and I don't see that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, seeming to sense that he has hurt his son's feelings, he
softens and praises Jadwin for his uncanny memory _ a gift that
could make him a great historian, he suggests. Or an archeologist,
he might have added. Or a private detective.
</P>
<P>
   Jadwin flashes a sudden smile that seems to say: Maybe we are
finally on the same track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4950 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEN-MOTHERS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     06-22 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-MOTHERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 MIDDLESEX, N.J.: ... heart-to-heart chat.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So Steve, I understand ya got a little problem with my
drivin','' Karen says, mimicking a Brooklyn mob boss. ``Do ya wanna
discuss it with me?'' The boy, chagrined, didn't stay in the car
pool for long, and since then, none of her other passengers have
ever forgotten to say ``thank you for the ride, Mrs. Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a meddlesome mom, someone who is always in
their face, or worse, trying to rescue them,'' Karen says. ``But I
tell you, it makes me insane when Alex isn't doing the best he can.
He doesn't have to get straight A's, but he does need to learn to
play the game. We fight about it. Sometimes I think his mind is
disengaged from his body.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not naive; she knows a teenager's world can be one of
confusion and change, temptation, rebellion, and risk. Her middle
brother, Michael, dropped out of her family in a fog of drugs and
alcohol. So she does her best to enter Alex's life through frank
conversations on everything from video game violence to suicide,
from substance abuse to sex, and to shape it with such positive
distractions as soccer, music lessons, and drama.
</P>
<P>
   Church is central, not just to the family's social life, but
also to reinforcing the values that Karen hopes will help her sons
make the right choices as adults. ``I don't care if Alex is a
lawyer or a game-show host, as long as he lives mindfully of
himself and the people around him,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Renee LiaBraaten, the Taylors' pastor at Emmanuel Lutheran
Church, says Jeff's death has strengthened Karen as a mother, and
his life gave her an excellent model for the boys.. ``She is a very
intentional parent, and she takes advantage of the whole village of
men _ in the church, in her family, in the neighborhood _ to mentor
and nurture her sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex imagines the boys who shot their classmates at Columbine
High School must have come from homes where parents were not very
involved or supportive. ``My mom has her ways of talking to me and
helping me deal with my problems so I keep a cool head,'' he says.
``I choose my own friends, but if I make a bad choice, my mom lets
me know.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the high-school rampage in Littleton, Colo., Karen
and Alex had one of their talks about video games. She won't allow
him to buy ones that are too violent or demean women, though she
knows he will play them in other homes. Alex argued that the games
serve a useful purpose, allowing kids to vent their frustrations
and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Alex, what are you angry about?'' Karen probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Alex answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well then,'' says Karen, her fist planted firmly on her hip.
``I rest my case.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Huber, who teaches Alex eighth-grade civics at Franklin
Middle School, doesn't see the anger, either. Alex is mature beyond
his years, a good student, at ease with his friends, and ``a people
person, sometimes to excess,'' Huber says. She was surprised to
learn Alex had lost his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd never know that he had been under that kind of stress,''
Huber says. ``It's not manifested at all. Alex is very
well-adjusted, very well put together.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Taylor's brain tumor, diagnosed in January 1993, only
four months after Luke was born, had a devastating effect on young
Alex. The father who had helped him write a third-grade paper on
the Chinese political system suddenly couldn't remember to turn off
a water faucet. The dad who loved to wrestle or skate with him now
shunned physical activity, fearing it would cause a seizure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all sitting on a feather,'' says Karen, but it was the
worst for Alex. After his father's death, which came unexpectedly
at home and with the sons present, Alex became depressed. His
self-esteem plummeted, his grades fell, he couldn't make friends,
and he behaved badly in school.
</P>
<P>
   Karen got him into counseling, which helped, but she also gave
Alex a very unusual and, as it turned out, cathartic opportunity
for closure on his father's death. She allowed him to testify about
his dad's illness in a $6 million malpractice lawsuit she brought
against the doctors and hospital that treated Jeff Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylor suit, which was argued in a Washington civil court
over four weeks in September 1997, alleged that it was radiation
therapy, not a recurrence of Jeff's brain tumor, that caused a
succession of increasingly intense and finally fatal seizures.
Lawyers for the Georgetown University Medical Center maintained
that Jeff's glioblastoma, a particularly aggressive and malignant
form of brain tumor, almost always recurs. They said the doctors's
decision to aggressively treat what appeared to be a second,
cancerous tumor _ but which one hospital pathology report said was
benign scar tissue _ was based on good medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylors were crushed by the verdict: The jury found no
negligence, and Karen, who said she was seeking vindication more
than money, had to pay Georgetown $9,000 in legal fees. Still, she
took comfort when the jury reprimanded the doctors for their
``callous'' treatment of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Alex said no one made him testify, though he understood it might
make the jury more sympathic. ``It was something I really wanted
and needed to do,'' Alex says. ``I needed to tell them about the
side of my dad I saw after he was treated. It's hard talking about
it anyway. It was really hard talking about my dad to the people
who might have killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of the trial was a turning point for Karen. ``She put
her life on hold until it was over,'' says Martha Hellman, her
friend and neighbor. ``Good or bad, the verdict meant she could
move on, resume her spiritual journey, and find out how much
strength she had as a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Her relatives saw a change, too. ``At first, she was so
frightened and lonely,'' says Alexandria Gladwell, Karen's cousin
who hosts the family reunion in Middlesex. ``Now we hear Karen say,
`I need a life,' and she is starting to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Karen organized a support group at her church to let
single parents share their wisdom, bad days, and aspirations. For
her, one dream is coming true. This summer, she will pack the boys
off to a friend's house and take her first solo trip since Jeff's
death, joining a church group for a two-week aid mission to
Estonia.
</P>
<P>
   For Alex, the trial marked an early passage to manhood. It
seemed to reinforce his sense of duty to help his mother and fill
in as Luke's father. Still, acting grown-up puts pressure on a
teenager: whether to tattle on a pesky little brother or take his
hand when he crosses the street; whether to watch ``Austin Powers''
one more time or walk the neighbor's dog for a few extra bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility usually wins out with Alex. ``Hey, Mom, the Dow
is up!'' Alex calls from the TV room, where he is watching the news
instead of ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure don't want Alex feeling like he has to be the man
around the house. He's just a kid,'' Karen says affectionately.
``On the other hand, show me the page in the family rulebook that
says a mother has to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things, like sex education, are especially hard. Karen
believes even the best lessons at school or in books can't teach
love and commitment. But it embarrasses both mother and son to
discuss sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish dad were here,'' Alex will say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, Alex, so do I,'' Karen replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom tries very hard to be a dad, but there are certain
things only a father can do, like throw a baseball or a football,''
Alex says later. ``Don't get me wrong _ I love my mom, I worry
about her, she is the foundation of this family _ but it's just not
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen works to keep good men in the boys' lives and expose them
to what she calls ``guy stuff.'' Each summer she and her sons visit
Grandfather Taylor and Jeff's three brothers in Oregon. Her own
brothers on Long Island take the boys boating and fishing. Gregory
Hanson, the Taylors' next-door neighbor, is teaching the teenager
to hunt with a bow and arrow. Last year, Alex gave Hanson a
Father's Day card.
</P>
<P>
   Says Jaime Ramos, Alex's soccer coach and another strong role
model: ``Karen proves it is not your testosterone level that makes
a good father.'' Still, each Taylor _ including Luke, who sometimes
draws pictures of his dad with angel wings or sobs at the sound of
an old nursery lullaby _ is sadly aware of the empty spot in the
family portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Karen took the boys to the Washington mall for a
rally against cancer, and she hung Jeff's picture on a memorial
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to them, `We need to make dad's death count for
something,' '' Karen recalls. ``It was very emotional. We all
cried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
