<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4966 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-TEN-COMMANDMEN     06-22 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-TEN-COMMANDMENTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DOES CONGRESS MEASURE UP TO THE TEN COMMANDMENTS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Alabama and the Ten Commandments? First, an
Alabama judge refuses a federal order to take them down from the
walls of his courtroom. And now, Alabama Congressman Robert B.
Aderholt has persuaded his peers to pass a bill giving states the
right to display the Ten Commandments in schools and other public
places.
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments clause is part of the larger juvenile crime
bill that the House weakened in the service of the radical pro-gun
lobby. In the wake of the Littleton school massacre, the Senate
passed a much stronger version a few weeks ago -- handing the
National Rifle Association the first serious political defeat in
its history.
</P>
<P>
   Radical pro-gun partisans, however, could not abide the thought
that Congress might limit access to killing machines. They lobbied
hard to overturn the wishes of the majority of the American people
as expressed by the Senate's vote.
</P>
<P>
   So, the House defeated serious gun control. Instead, they
suggested that children read the Ten Commandments as a way to end
school violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that simply posting the Ten Commandments will not
instantly change the moral character of our nation,'' said
Aderholt. ``However, it is an important step to promote morality
and an end of children killing children.''
</P>
<P>
   How? A kid with an assault weapon sees ``Thou shalt not murder''
before he pulls the trigger? A pre-rampage conversion? Better
still, little ones could pull the commandments off the walls and
use them for shields while their classmates shoot.
</P>
<P>
   But if Congress insists that we hang the Ten Commandments in
schools, I suggest that we hang the Ten Commandments in the halls
of Congress. Any member caught violating God's law would be
immediately suspended or expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see how they do:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not murder.'' With any luck, there are no murderers
in the House of Representatives. But this one is a little tricky
for congressional Christians (Jews, Muslims, and agnostics are
excluded) because Jesus taught that anyone who hates his brother
has committed murder. A few might get caught on this technicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not steal.'' Do our taxes count?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not bear false witness against your neighbor.''
These are politicians. No comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not commit adultery.'' Well, they were running for
the exits during the President's impeachment trial. But boys will
be boys. Again, Christians have a tougher standard. Jesus said
anyone who looks at a woman with lust has committed adultery.
Sorry, fellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not covet your neighbor's wife, his house, his
field or his manservant, his ox or his donkey or anything that
belongs to your neighbor.'' Does that include his Lexus? What about
a nicer office in the Rayburn Building? What about aspiring to be a
senator or president?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt have no other gods before Me.'' Can Buddhists,
Hindus, or atheists hold office? If not, God and the Constitution
might be at odds. Are power and money gods?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not make for yourself an idol, or any likeness of
what is in heaven above, or on the earth beneath or in the water
under the earth.'' Well, those who cut the National Endowment for
the Arts might breathe a little easier here. But what of making an
idol of yourself? The polls? The gun lobby?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not take the name of the Lord your God in vain.''
Let's dock their pay $5 for every swear word. The money can be used
to save Social Security and fund universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Observe the Sabbath day and keep it holy.'' Whose Sabbath?
Friday, the Islamic one? Saturday, the Jewish one? Sunday, the
Christian one? Maybe all three -- they would only work four days a
week and we could cut their pay again. In addition, every member of
Congress must divest their holdings in companies that do business
on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor your father and your mother, as the Lord your God has
commanded you.'' We trust that they honor their own fathers and
mothers. But does that include all fathers and mothers? How about
federally mandated paid paternity and maternity leave? Excellent
day care centers? And, of course, decent gun-control laws so
parents will not have to worry about someone killing their
children.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to moral matters, perhaps Congress should follow
another biblical teaching. As Jesus put it, ``Why do you look at
the speck in your brother's eye, but do not notice the log that is
in your own ... You hypocrites, first take the log out of your own
eye, and then you will see clearly enough to take the speck from
your brother's.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, at the very least, pass sensible legislation regarding guns.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
