<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, June 22, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-FEE (San Antonio) _ Mexican officials are easing the
rules on the new $15 fee all visitors to the interior of Mexico
must pay beginning July 1. Businesses and the tourism industry on
both sides of the border have expressed concern that the fee _
affecting foreign nationals arriving by land, sea or air _ would
hurt commerce. By DAVID HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   SELMA-PRINCIPAL (San Antonio) _ As a student, John Simpson was
not allowed to enter Parish High School in Selma, Ala., because of
his skin color. Soon, though, the retired Air Force training
instructor will return to what is now Selma High School to become
its principal. By CECILIA BALLI. (Photo available on Wieck
database.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-ASSISTANTS (San Francisco) _ Leaders of the West
Coast's first union of university teaching assistants celebrated a
clean sweep by the United Auto Workers of representation elections
on all eight University of California teaching campuses. The UC
system's 8,400 TAs, plus 1,200 readers and tutors, voted for
unionization by a 68 percent majority Monday, with a voter turnout
of 55 percent, according to a final tabulation of election results
at six campuses. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-CROPS (Houston) _ Rodney Mowery likes to stand in the bed
of his pickup truck and look out across an expanse of tall corn in
one of his fields just south of Houston. It has been years since
Mowery has seen corn this good. Like so many Texas growers, this
member of a farming family from Rosharon, Texas, is enjoying one of
those rare periods of high yields. By NELSON ANTOSH.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TICKETS-PRICES-POP (Houston) _ When the Eagles broke the
$100-ticket barrier in some markets on their 1994 tour, fans
willingly forked over the dough because it was viewed as a
once-in-a-lifetime reunion. But now, triple-digit ticket prices are
becoming more the rule than the exception for aging rock icons on
the road. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET-PRICES-ARTS (Houston) _ There are a few things in life
that you can count on. Death and taxes. The rich get richer, the
poor get poorer. And, as time goes by, ticket prices for
performing-arts events go up. In the past decade, Broadway ticket
prices have jumped from the 1989-90 season's range of $35 to $55
for musicals and $25 to $42 for plays to the current range of $40
to $85 (musicals) and $25 to $60 (plays). By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-CLOSERANGE (Undated) _ The new book by Annie Proulx
is a skillfully wrought, albeit downbeat, collection of short
stories, set in Proulx's home state of Wyoming. By BARBARA LISS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PAX-NETWORK (Albany, N.Y.) _ Less than a year old, the
seventh network _ the Pax Network _ is desperate for attention, any
kind of attention, as it weaves in more original ``family
friendly'' programming to its lineup. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEW-CRIME (San Francisco) _ ``The Drowning People''
(Warner Books, $24, 340 pages), is 21-year-old Richard Mason's
amazing debut novel that deals with love, betrayal, murder and
revenge. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PETS-HUMANS (San Antonio) _ The bond between humans and pets is
growing ever stronger _ the product of empty-nest homes, lonely
older people, and the decline of the traditional family. The bond
is becoming so strong, says Dr. John August of the Texas A&AMP;M
University College of Veterinary Medicine, that some day medical
practices will be composed of both physicians and veterinarians. By
MARINA PISANO.
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL-OF-CENTURY (Schuylerville, N.Y.) _ The grisly end of Mrs.
Mary Eliza Billings' life marked the beginning of a true tale of
intrigue, mystery and wealth told in a self-published book released
on June 4 on the anniversary of the slaying, 120 years ago. By MIKE
HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPERM-BANK (Albany, N.Y.) _ Men, some as young as adolescents,
rely on an underused, somewhat unknown sperm bank to store sperm
because they risk reproductive damage from chemotherapy or
radiation during cancer treatment. By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   ETHAN-HAWKE (Williamstown, Mass.) _ Ethan Hawke is in a
contemplative mood. ``I've never been a very a good movie star, you
know?'' the actor muses. A half-hour earlier he'd certainly been
acting like a movie star. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-FLORIDA (Orlando, Fla.) _ We take a look at the
competition that Disney faces with Universal Studios' thrill-stoked
Islands of Adventure. By SYD KEARNEY. (With photos available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-FLORIDA-ISLANDS (Orlando, Fla.) _ Here's a news flash
for Disney: You may never be outdone by Universal, but you've
definitely been ``out-funned.'' Universal Islands of Adventure,
which celebrated its grand opening Memorial Day weekend, delivers
more thrills, chills and excitement than the combined efforts of
Walt Disney World's four themed parks. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   With: CENTRAL-FLORIDA-ISLANDSLIST
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-FLORIDA-DISNEY (Lake Buena Vista, Fla.) _ Never let them
see you sweat. That's hard to do on a summer day in central
Florida, but give the folks at Walt Disney World Resort credit for
effort. When asked what effect the opening of Universal's highly
awaited Islands of Adventure might have on the Magic Kingdom,
Disney officials are nonplussed. ``Is there a new park around
here?'' responds Judson Green, chairman of Walt Disney Attractions.
By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-FLORIDA-CITYWALK (Orlando, Fla.) _ As part of its plan
to create a destination resort, Universal is putting together
Universal Studios Escape, encompassing two theme parks, an
entertainment complex and three hotels. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-FLORIDA-PARKS (Orlando, Fla.) _ While Disney and
Universal battle it out, other theme parks across the country are
luring guests with new attractions. The granddaddy of themed
attractions, Gatorland in Orlando, Fla., celebrates its 50th
birthday this summer. To mark this achievement, Gatorland opens its
new Jungle Crocs of the World Theater, where visitors will be able
to observe the hunting skills of Cuban crocodiles. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   With: CENTRAL-FLORIDA-PARKLIST
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Just when I was beginning to think
travel promotions couldn't get any more outlandish or innovative
... By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PAYNE-STEWART (Pinehurst, N.C.) _ When the national anthem
plays, Payne Stewart places his right hand over his heart.
``Heck,'' he says, ``I sing the words.'' He is unabashed about his
patriotism. So it should be no surprise that Stewart considers an
automatic berth on the Ryder Cup team to be one of the biggest
perks to winning the U.S. Open golf championship. By PETE
DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-COURSE (Pinehurst, N.C.) _ The U.S. Open started its
51-week vacation on Monday with a smile on its face. The 99th U.S.
Open closed to critical acclaim _ with the exception of a John Daly
snit _ and there might be some implications here for the 100th
Open, next June at Pebble Beach, Calif. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In the ascendancy of quiet
superstars Mia Hamm and Tim Duncan, you'd think this would be a
placid time for sportswriters. But for every Hamm, we have a
Hingis. For every Duncan, a Daly. There's always a need for sage
advice, always a place for the voice of reason. This, of course,
isn't that place. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Despite what you're seeing on
network television, it's not inconceivable that the candidate
who'll eventually end up duking it out with Hillary Clinton next
year for the U.S. Senate seat in New York won't be Rudy Giuliani.
Instead, it could be Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every time you see another
supermodel or movie star with huge breasts and the hips of an
8-year-old boy, don't you wish you lived in some bygone era when
women weren't such slaves to the impossible quest for a perfect
body? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   BULLET-TRAIN (San Francisco) _ Build a bullet train? For $23.3
billion, twice the annual budget of Casey Jones' home state of
Kentucky? They've got to be kidding _ or high on cocaine. Why go
faster when the pace of life is killing us already? Why would
anybody want to get to Sacramento any sooner? By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
