<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PAYNE-STEWART-HNS     06-22 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PAYNE-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYNE STEWART HAS HIS EYES ON THE RYDER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ When the national anthem plays, Payne Stewart
places his right hand over his heart. ``Heck,'' he says, ``I sing
the words.'' He is unabashed about his patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   So it should be no surprise that Stewart considers an automatic
berth on the Ryder Cup team to be one of the biggest perks to
winning the U.S. Open golf championship.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a native of Springfield, Mo., who lives in Orlando,
Fla., earned enough points with his dramatic victory Sunday at
Pinehurst No. 2 to assure himself a spot on the U.S. team that will
try to win back the Ryder Cup from Europe in September at
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very wonderful spot in my heart for the Ryder Cup,''
Stewart said. ``It's more intense. The only person that I can let
down (in the Open) is myself. If I go out and make the Ryder Cup
team and don't perform well and we don't win, then I'm going to
feel that I let down my other 11 teammates, the captain and my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 42, has played in four Ryder Cups, compiling an 8-7-1
match record (2-2 in singles), but hasn't represented the U.S.
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped to be a captain's choice the last two times the
biennial competition was held, but Lanny Wadkins ('95) picked
Curtis Strange and Fred Couples, and Tom Kite ('97) went with
Couples and Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's motivated me this year was the fact that I couldn't
rely on the captains to pick,'' Stewart said. ``I felt like I was a
legitimate selection for the last two Ryder Cup teams. The
captain's choice were good choices. That's something that maybe
I'll have the opportunity to do later in my career is be a captain.
Then I can analyze, `Why did you pick him?'''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has the passion, the Dottie Pepper-like spunk, to help
the U.S. snap its two-match Ryder Cup losing streak. His
willingness to speak his mind and his no-nonsense attitude on the
course supposedly bother some fellow pros, but none of his peers
had anything bad to say Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game has to be respected,'' said Phil Mickelson, who
finished second. ``He seems to be always in contention at the Open.
He and his wife have been very gracious with Amy (Mickelson's wife)
and myself, and I've enjoyed spending time with the two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson can take some solace in the knowledge that he was part
of one of the most exciting Open finishes of recent memory. Stewart
needed a 15-foot par putt on the final hole to win. Mickelson,
Tiger Woods and Vijay Singh all had their opportunities in the
final round.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who had eight years between Open victories, vows to
handle things differently as champion this time around. He said
last time he was too hung up on trying to fulfill what he perceived
as the responsibility of being the U.S. Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more prepared to deal with everything that goes
along with holding on to this trophy for a year,'' he said. ``I
plan on doing the same things that I've been doing that got me in
position to win, which is working out and spending a lot of time at
home and playing when I want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to be running after the elusive dollar
because I've been invited to go and play here and here and here. I
had so much fun being at home, being a father, getting up in the
morning, making breakfast, taking my kids to school, going to high
school athletics. That's what my life is right now. I'm not going
to do what I did in '91.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
