<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN GOES TO PEBBLE BEACH NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ The 99th U.S. Open closed to critical acclaim
_ with the exception of a John Daly snit _ and there might be some
implications here for the 100th Open, next June at Pebble Beach,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess what we can now say today for the first time?'' Pebble
Beach director of golf R.J. Harper said. ``We've got the next U.S.
Open and we're thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The ending of this last one _ Payne Stewart's dramatic,
par-saving, championship-winning putt on the 18th hole _ will be
hard to duplicate. But even before the final shot, Pinehurst No. 2
gave Pebble Beach a modern lesson in how to make the fans, the
media, the USGA and the players happy.
</P>
<P>
   The fans just want decent seats and views with no transportation
hassles _ preferably with good weather. The USGA seems happy if
there are big names on the leaderboard, an on-time finish for TV
and par standing tall in the end.
</P>
<P>
   As for the players, it seems their concerns are different. And
what they expressed here in the confines of Pinehurst No. 2 made a
clear statement of what they want in an Open.
</P>
<P>
   They want the conditions to be fair. And by this, they don't all
necessarily mean that it is the same for every player and they
don't all necessarily mean that a good shot is rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they mean that one bad shot doesn't automatically produce
a second bad shot: They want the chance to redeem themselves. And
most found that to be the case at No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf course sucks you out, but it's good,'' said
Germany's Sven Struver, who was 15 over par in his first Open. ``If
somebody's not going to enjoy this, he's not going to enjoy golf.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the USGA has been presenting formatted Opens:
primary rough that was X inches high, secondary rough that was Y
inches high, fairways that were Z yards wide, greens that measured
XX.
</P>
<P>
   But at Pinehurst, the difficulty was presented by the pedestal
greens. The course didn't need six inches of rough, anywhere, and
it didn't have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a simple template, and what's exciting is that
Pinehurst changed that this year,'' Harper said. ``I think the USGA
is going to come in here with a more open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The players also think the Open course should test every club.
</P>
<P>
   They do not want the driver taken out of their hands by narrow,
fast, curved fairways that won't hold a well-struck, on-target
drive. This was the case at the Olympic Club in San Francisco. Jack
Nicklaus expressed concern that it could be the case as well at
Pebble Beach next year if the USGA conditions it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Patterson, vice chairman of the U.S. Amateur, says the
length of the course already has been prescribed for both the
Amateur and the Open. It will be 6,828 yards, with par 71.
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst was 7,175 yards with par 70.
</P>
<P>
   The second hole, which the everyday golfer plays as a par-5 at
Pebble, will be a tough but reachable 484-yard par-4. The USGA
wanted to shave another stroke somewhere, liking its nice round 70,
but none of the other par-5s at Pebble could budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, long, long ball hitter can reach No. 6 in two, and 14
will always and forever be a three-shot hole, and 18 is not
reachable in two for any but the angriest of golfers,'' Harper
said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge presented by Pebble generally is finding the small
greens. At the Open, the rough around the greens will heighten the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A challenge for the organizers at Pebble will be to present an
Open that is as comfortable for all as was Pinehurst. After
Sunday's grand finale, Stewart thanked the USGA for the way it
handled the large media corps that covers the final round. The tees
were off-limits, which reduced the welcome-to-the-circus feeling.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a challenge to accomplish that at Pebble Beach, where
the Pacific Ocean limits access to fairways on many holes.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said the course will provide enough bleachers to seat
17,000 of the 32,500 fans expected, which should help relieve the
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst, a village of 8,000 people, handled that well _ with a
bonus. The weather wasn't the hot, humid stuff that had been
feared. It was a little rainy, and mostly mild.
</P>
<P>
   That, Pebble Beach might be able to manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday's going to be sunny, Friday overcast with a little
fog, Saturday sunny again,'' Patterson said. ``And Sunday, it'll
blow 50 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   It's as good a guess as any.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
