<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-22 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK MS. DEMEANOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the ascendancy of quiet superstars Mia Hamm
and Tim Duncan, you'd think this would be a placid time for
sportswriters. But for every Hamm, we have a Hingis. For every
Duncan, a Daly.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a need for sage advice, always a place for the
voice of reason. This, of course, isn't that place.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: Is there any way to get fans interested in
the men's singles matches at Wimbledon? Everyone wants to watch the
bratty women. Andre helped us by winning the French, but he hurt us
by ditching Brooke. We could be second-class citizens pretty soon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Henman, a k a Greg Rusedksi, a k a Mark Philippousis, a k
a Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   Dear Anonymous et al.: How about getting New York Mets manager
Bobby Valentine to dress up as Pete Sampras during the interview
sessions? This is a character who could keep Fleet Street humming.
Too bad he can't do the same for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: What's up with Latrell Sprewell's hairstyle,
those zig-zagging cornrows? I'm not sure what they say about the
NBA at the turn of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vidal Saloon, Staten Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Vidal: Let me get this straight: You're following the New
York Knicks, who have played aesthetically challenged basketball
for most of this decade, and you're worried about Sprewell's hair?
I'm not sure why sports fans get so worked up over athletes'
tattoos, hairstyles and body piercings, as if youthful fashion
experiments revealed anything about character.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional assumption about cornrows is that they're
supposed to create an intimidating look. But to buy that, you have
to believe that all young, black men are inherently scary.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you look at Allen Iverson and see an athlete trying
desperately to disguise the fact that he's as baby-faced as
Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sprewell, the cornrows call attention away from his
scrawny physique. The new ones are very much like Dennis Rodman's
annual playoff dye job _ an hourglass for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the Finals, Rodman's coloring had always faded.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's cornrows have started to unravel. The crisp lines are
gone now, frazzled by Miami, Atlanta and Indiana, by injuries to
Patrick Ewing and Larry Johnson. That's the biggest statement his
hair can make.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: Why is everyone so appalled by my behavior at
the U.S. Open? The tournament is a disaster, an embarrassment to
serious golfers. Why can't we play the national championship on a
normal course, without rolling greens and shin-deep rough? If you
had to work under these conditions, you would boycott an event,
too.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Daly, Somewhere in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Dear John: As far as I know, no journalist quit working at the
Atlanta Olympics, so don't expect any sympathy here. As for the
U.S. Open, here's a thought: Let the USGA relax the course
standards for a few years, and let's see how you feel when more
club pros and 43-year-old amateurs start slipping onto the
leaderboard, ahead of members of the PGA Tour. Now, that would be
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   The wacky course dimensions reduce the chance for flukes. The
four contenders down the stretch this year were Payne Stewart, Phil
Mickelson, Tiger Woods and Vijay Singh. That's an impressive group
of golfers, exactly what you'd expect from a U.S. Open. Pinehurst
did its job. You and your 11 strokes on No. 8 Sunday? That was
fairly predictable, too. And the golf course had almost nothing to
do with it.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: Take up tennis, and start playing mixed doubles
with Martina Hingis. You two would make quite a pair.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: How can I make myself look more intimidating,
older and maybe a little over the edge?
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Iverson, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Dear A: Ah, an easy one. Disguise yourself as Bobby Valentine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
