<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-TRAVEL23-COX     06-22 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-TRAVEL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO TICKETS FOR THE SPACE STATION. MAKE THAT ROUND-TRIP, PLEASE
 &HT;    670&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So you're bored with the beach and you've toured
Europe. When it comes to traveling, you've been there, done that.
Where on earth can you go for a real adventure?
</P>
<P>
   How about a vacation in space?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot closer than a lot of people think,'' said Eric
Anderson, general manager of Space Adventures. The futuristic
travel agency already offers the experience of weightlessness
during tours of Star City, the Russian version of Cape Canaveral,
and is betting that travelers will soon be taking sub-orbital
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are past the snicker factor'' in the development of space
tourism, said Alan Ladwig, a NASA associate administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on Wednesday, scores of space and travel industry
officials will open a two-day conference in the nation's capital on
``Going Public: Moving Toward the Development of a Large Space
Tourism Business.'' Participants are coming from NASA, the
Department of Commerce, and the aerospace, travel, finance and
insurance industries.
</P>
<P>
   Many participants believe that the key question is when _ not if
_ the final frontier will be open to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a space tourism industry,'' said
Ladwig. ``I'm not going to predict how soon. Not in five or 10
years. But in 15 to 20, who knows? To fly in space has been a dream
of millions of people for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two real barriers: cost and safety,'' said
Keith Calhoun-Senghor, director of the Commerce Department's Office
of Space Commercialization. ``Both are technological. Surveys have
shown that the market is there.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two travel agencies already offer vacations at Russia's
Star City. The cost is about $5,000 for a three-day stay, not
including air fare. The space adventure includes a flight with
several parabolas on the Ilyushin-76, the cosmonaut equivalent of
NASA's ``vomit comet'' which provides a few minutes of
weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The next big step in space tourism is predicted to be suborbital
flights such as those taken by early Mercury astronauts before John
Glenn orbited the Earth. The X-Prize Foundation is offering $10
million to the first private firm to build a vehicle that carries
at least three people 100 kilometers or higher above the ground
(the international boundary between air and space) and lands safely
_ and then repeats the feat with the same ship within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal desire has been to fly into space. But I did not
want to do it as a government employee,'' explained Peter
Diamandis, president of the X-Prize Foundation. The problem is that
there are only two vehicles on the planet _ the U.S. space shuttle
and the Russian Soyuz rocket _ capable of making such flights, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 16 firms are competing for the prize, and the first
competing vehicles are expected to be launched between 2002 and
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Once tourists are taking suborbital flights, the next question
is ``whether 15 minutes in space is enough. Will they get the John
Glenn syndrome of 'when do I go up next?','' said Calhoun-Senghor.
Then, ``at some point, you need some place to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Space Island Group has an idea for building orbiting
hotels from the discarded external fuel tanks of the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy for shuttle crews to release the tanks to float
around in space, said Gene Myers, president of the group of
aerospace engineers and marketers. ``The tanks are as big as a
747'' and could be fitted together into a wheel shape.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers would initially have to lease the shuttle and
hire NASA astronauts, first to build a mixed-use station for public
and private efforts and then to build the early hotels, Myers
explained. But eventually a second-generation, privately operated
shuttle capable of carrying 75 passengers would take tourists back
and forth from the orbiting hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each station could hold 400 to 500 people on conditions
similar to those on a cruise ship,'' said Myers. The group is
seeking funding through corporate sponsorships similar to those for
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In a larger context,'' space tourism is already booming, said
Calhoun-Senghor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space travel is what gets attention,'' he said, but the
business begins on terra firma with such attractions as museums.
The Smithsonian Institution's National Air and Space Museum is the
most visited museum in the world. The space tourism industry also
includes space camps, NASA tours and theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   The conference at the Capitol Hill Club will ``address the
potential space tourism markets, the present state of space travel
and tourism business efforts, and set the agenda to resolve the
inhibitors'' to space tourism, said Bob Haltermann, executive
director of the Space Travel and Tourism Division of the Space
Transportation Association, a sponsor of the event.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Ladwig will speak at the conference on government's role
in space tourism _ basically developing new technologies that will
lower launch costs. It now costs about $8,000 a pound to get to
space, he said. ``You'd have to get it down to $100 a pound for a
realistic tourism market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question about the conference is, 'Is it too early?','' he
said. ``It's not too early to sort out issues'' concerning space
tourism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
