<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-COST-$ADV04-     06-22 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-COST-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    END-OF-CENTURY CONGRESS SPENDS $2 BILLION ON ITSELF
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-COST-DATA. For release Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As fireworks etch the skies with bright colors for
the last Independence Day of this century, the majestic dome of the
U.S. Capitol will look much as it did 99 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But almost everything else about Capitol Hill has changed in a
century that brought an explosion of staff, construction and
bureaucracy _ not to mention lobbyists _ to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the century's start, lawmakers had no suites of offices, only
their desks on the floor of the Senate and House, and only a rare
clerk to help with their part-time legislative duties.
</P>
<P>
   Today Congress operates the equivalent of a fair-sized city,
with 29,000 employees, its own police force, six major office
buildings and an underground trolley system to move lawmakers to
and from the Capitol whenever the bell rings for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the expense of running the Library of Congress,
the legislature now costs more than $2.2 billion a year, expected
to reach $2.4 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   House members, who averaged only about three aides each as
recently as 1947, now employ an average of 15 full-time aides in
the capital or in their home districts. Senators, who had fewer
than six staff members each in 1947, now have about 40 aides.
</P>
<P>
   Under Republican majority since 1995, Congress has pared its
payroll by more than 8,800 compared with 1991. But the overall
growth in the legislature's bureaucracy remains largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   What spurred the congressional expansion?
</P>
<P>
   Starting with President Franklin D. Roosevelt, lawmakers began
fearing their powers were slipping away to the more assertive
executive branch. Congress responded by bulking up its staff in the
late 1940s. That effort was redoubled in the 1970s, when Congress
added yet more staff, researchers and investigators, and set up its
own budget office as a counterpoint to the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Congress enlarged its operations to keep pace with new
benefit programs, regulations and agencies it was creating.
Lawmakers, who once concentrated their efforts in the capital,
began hiring more staff for home offices, where aides serve as
``caseworkers'' for constituent who have problems with programs
ranging from the Environmental Protection Agency to Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, an army of lobbyists began camping in
Washington. By 1997, the ranks included 11,500 registered lobbyists
whose organizations spent $1.26 billion to try to influence
law-making, according to the private, nonpartisan Center for
Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all moved together,'' said Thomas E. Mann, director of
governmental studies at the Brookings Institution. ``The agenda of
government expanded. The size of congressional staffs, the number
of organizations with representatives in Washington and the number
of registered lobbyists _ they all went up together.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
