</P>
<P>
   Sources: Congressional Research Service, White House Office of
Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Cost figures in constant 1998 dollars
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS OF CONGRESSIONAL EXPENDITURES
</P>
<P>
   Based on legislative appropriations proposed for fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE LEADERSHIP AND POLITICAL PARTY OFFICES: $14.2 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., $1.74 million for his
leadership office plus $406,000 for staff to handle House floor
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Minority leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is divided among other leaders and congressional party
organizations that set strategy and policy, chiefly for staff
salaries. Here's how some of the rest of the leadership money is
spent:
</P>
<P>
   _ More than $17,600 on travel, most of it for a Democratic
retreat at the Wintergreen resort in Virginia with President
Clinton at the end of his impeachment crisis in February. Meeting
rooms and audio-visual equipment rental cost about $6,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refreshments and meals for strategy meetings of the Republican
House Conference (ranging from $31.50 for Dunkin' Donuts to $1,229
for a December session).
</P>
<P>
   _ Balloons ($92.53), listed as ``supplies for official meeting''
of the Republicans in February.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE LEADERSHIP AND POLITICAL PARTY OFFICES: $11.6 million
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., receive $1.3 million each for their leadership
operations, and the rest is divided among the other party leaders
and party organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Among expenses reported this year:
</P>
<P>
   _ Senate Republicans totalled more than $13,000 in television
satellite feeds to beam their members' comments to the public
during the first two months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Senate Democrats reported spending $1,545 for satellite feeds
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   VICE PRESIDENT'S OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   Although Al Gore was elected vice president of the United
States, the job that provides his salary and much of his staff is
his post as president of the Senate. Under the Constitution, the
vice president presides over the upper chamber and votes to break
ties. Gore rarely goes to Capitol Hill, but the legislative branch
nevertheless pays $1.7 million a year to support about 30 members
of his staff, most of whom are based in the White House complex.
Congress also gives Gore a $10,000 annual expense account.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE OF THE PRESIDENT PRO TEMPORE
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, the senior Republican
member of the chamber, serves in the largely ceremonial post whose
chief duty is to open the Senate's daily sessions. ``Few presidents
pro tem in the 20th century have had much influence in the
Senate,'' says Congressional Quarterly's Guide to Congress. The
position includes an 11-person staff and costs $404,000. The Senate
is considering a $33,000 increase for next year. ``The biggest
thing is he is third in line for the presidency,'' said Thurmond's
spokesman John DeCrosta. Otherwise, the spokesman said that the
staff has ``various and sundry'' duties, such as scheduling
Thurmond's appearances.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS' SALARIES
</P>
<P>
   House speaker: $175,400
</P>
<P>
   House majority leader: $151,800
</P>
<P>
   House minority leader: $151,800
</P>
<P>
   Senate president (vice president of the United States): $175,400
</P>
<P>
   Senate president pro tempore: $151,800
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader: $151,800
</P>
<P>
   Senate minority leader: $151,800
</P>
<P>
   Expense accounts: $25,000 for the House speaker, $10,000 each
for others.
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERS OF CONGRESS:
</P>
<P>
   Salary: $136,700
</P>
<P>
   Office allowance for House: From $570,000 to about $1 million,
depending on size and population of district
</P>
<P>
   Office allowance for Senate: From $1.8 million (for each
Delaware senator) to $3.1 million (for California)
</P>
<P>
   COMMITTEES:
</P>
<P>
   Staff, expenses for 19 House committees: $115 million
</P>
<P>
   Staff, expenses for 19 Senate committees: $78.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Staff, expenses for 2 joint committees: $9.4 million
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL BENEFITS FOR MEMBERS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Office of attending physician: $1.9 million (House members pay
$290 a year, senators pay $520 a year for unlimited office visits,
hospital visits, lab work, and other treatment).
</P>
<P>
   _ Free treatment at Walter Reed Army Hospital or Bethesda Naval
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Government-financed health insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESSIONAL PENSIONS: $20 million
</P>
<P>
   Retirement benefits for members of Congress are calculated at a
higher rate than for other federal employees and include annual
cost of living increases, which few private plans offer. Pensions
this year average $60,000 per retired lawmaker, according to the
National Taxpayers Union. These funds are not counted in the annual
legislative appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE OF COMPLIANCE: $2 million
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1995, Congress voted to require itself to follow 11
laws already enacted for the rest of the country on workplace
health and safety and non-discrimination. However, Congress has
arranged its own system of enforcement that does not hold
lawmakers, or their office budgets, individually responsible. For
example, employees can charge a member of Congress with employment
discrimination, and any settlement paid comes from taxpayer funds,
with all records kept secret. Only a handful of appeals have gone
into the courts, where the cases become public.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL POLICE: $85 million
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 officers patrol the Capitol grounds and
surrounding neighborhoods and provide bodyguard protection to top
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   BOTANIC GARDEN: $3.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Congress operates the botanical garden to ``collect, cultivate,
and grow the various flora of the United States and other
countries'' for study and for garden clubs. Included in next year's
spending plan is $153,000 to design renovations for a fountain
designed by Frederic Auguste Bartholdi, the artist who sculpted the
Statue of Liberty. Renovating the fountain, just west of the
Rayburn House Office Building, is expected to cost $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDINGS AND GROUNDS: $197 million
</P>
<P>
   Besides upkeep for the U.S. Capitol and its 58.8 acre Capitol
Hill grounds, Congress also provides maintenance and utilities for
a complex that has expanded this century to include five House
office buildings, three Senate buildings, and three buildings for
the Library of Congress. Among the continuous renovations, workmen
are currently replacing the lead-based paint in phase one of a $30
million restoration project on the inside of the Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH AND INVESTIGATIONS
</P>
<P>
   _ GENERAL ACCOUNTING OFFICE: $372 million
</P>
<P>
   The investigating arm of Congress, which conducts extensive
research into whether executive agencies are carrying out laws and
programs effectively and efficiently. GAO produces hundreds of
reports with thousands of recommendations each year. The agency
also publishes an annual list of recommendations that have not been
followed. This year's report on ``open'' recommendations is 171
pages.
</P>
<P>
   _ LIBRARY OF CONGRESS: $294.6 million
</P>
<P>
   The world's biggest library, with 17 million books and other
historical documents for use by lawmakers and the public.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONGRESSIONAL RESEARCH SERVICE: $71 million
</P>
<P>
   Provides background reports for lawmakers on legislative issues.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONGRESSIONAL BUDGET OFFICE: $26.2 million
</P>
<P>
   Provides economic and budgetary estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
