<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABILITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT NARROWS SCOPE OF DISABILITY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday narrowed the scope of
a federal law banning discrimination against workers with
handicaps, saying that the law does not apply to such disabilities
as poor eyesight that can be corrected medically.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on three related cases, the court dismissed
discrimination lawsuits by two nearsighted pilots, a truck driver
almost blind in one eye and a mechanic with high blood pressure who
were either fired or denied employment.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the lawsuits was brought under the 1990 American with
Disabilities Act, which was designed to end discrimination on the
job, in housing and at medical facilities and other places that
serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines disability as ``a physical or mental impairment
that substantially limits one or more major life activities'' or a
condition where a person is ``being regarded as having such
impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing in the case of the two
nearsighted pilots, said, ``We hold that determination of whether
an individual is disabled should be made with reference to measures
that mitigate the individual's impairment, including, in this
instance, eyeglasses and contact lenses.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 opinion, the court ruled that the poor eyesight of the
two pilots, Karen Sutton and Kimberly Hinton, failed to
``substantially limit a major life activity'' in their lives and,
therefore, they were not covered under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   The court reached the same conclusion in the other two cases,
ruling unanimously that truck driver Haille Kirkingburg and 7-2
that mechanic Vaughn Murphy should not be considered disabled under
the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the cases, the court also ruled that the plaintiffs
failed to show that the companies they sued had banned them from an
entire class of job, such as pilot or driver. Instead, the court
said, the companies refused to consider each person for a specific
job with strict, reasonable criteria that the plaintiffs failed to
meet.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulings, the court said that the ADA allows companies to
prefer certain physical characteristics over others, as long as
those attributes do not rise to the level of being a disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``An employer is free to decide that physical characteristics or
medical conditions that are not impairments are preferable to
others, just as it is free to decide that some limiting impairments
make individuals less than ideally suited for a job,'' O'Connor
said in the pilots' case.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years employers have won 92 percent of the 700 ADA
cases resolved in court from 1992 to 1997, according to the
American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Lower courts had split over how far the law's protections extend
in today's cases, from Colorado, Oregon and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Bokat, general counsel of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
called the court's decision in rejecting the lawsuits ``extremely
important'' for American business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that those with true disabilities will continue to be
covered, but people with easily correctable conditions will not be
considered disabled,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Louis Bograd, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties
Union, a legal watchdog group, said the court's ruling were a
``serious blow'' to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has narrowed the ADA so that it covers only a small,
small group of people and not the people it was meant to cover,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate ruling that also centered on the ADA law, the high
court held 6-3 in a Georgia case that states may have to place
people with mental disabilities in homelike settings if they can
fare just as well there as in state hospitals. In the narrow
decision, the court said the ADA law requires such community
placement of the mentally disabled whenever appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confront the question whether the proscription of
discrimination may require placement of persons with mental
disabilities in community settings, rather than in institutions,''
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote for the court. ``The answer, we
hold, is a qualified yes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
