<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 23:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   The Times is planning about 1 1/2 pages of Kosovo coverage.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ The latest atrocity
uncovered in Kosovo: a site where Serbs apparently dug up and
removed 100 bodies of Albanians killed in early May. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Skopje/elsewhere) _ Clinton visits refugees in
Macedonia. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Skopje/Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ With only 17,000
NATO troops in Kosovo so far, Gen. Wesley Clark says NATO
governments need to send troops faster. He also says he could use
more than the 55,000 planned. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is also working on the following: NATO's problems
coping with Albanian-Serbian tensions since there are no civilian
authorities of any kind; the difficulty of assessing blame in
Kosovo because many Serbian paramilitaries wore masks; resentment
in Macedonia over accusations that the country tried to make money
off the refugee crisis; Monday's explosion in Pristina that killed
two British peacekeepers and two civilians was caused by NATO
cluster bomb; political developments in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-Y2K (United Nations) _ U.N. meeting on Y2K problem. By
Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLICE-SHOOTING (Lod, Israel) _ In Israeli-Arab slum in
mixed city outside Tel Aviv, Israeli-Arab member of parliament who
was a candidate for prime minister is shot by rubber-coated bullet
in clash with police. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PRESIDENT (Buenos Aires) _ Chilean president proposes
economic reforms after ditching entire Cabinet. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-ROYAL-ACADEMY (Madrid) _ The Royal Spanish Academy once
ruled with absolute authority over the vast Spanish empire, but now
the Americas have their own language academies that propose
home-grown changes. Disputes have even led to threats of linguistic
schisms. So, with nine out of 10 Spanish speakers now living
outside Spain, the Royal Spanish Academy has learned to consult and
negotiate. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-U.N.-DUES (Washington) _ Senate to take up question of
U.N. dues. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SUMMIT (Undated) _ The major gun industry trade
organization, after eliminating a more moderate rival last week,
plans to propose a summit conference with mayors of the nearly two
dozen cities and counties suing the firearms makers as a way to
head off litigation. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE-LEAGUE-TUTORS (Chicago) _ Some parents are spending $70 a
hour to get baseball tutors for their sons and daughters in Little
League. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FLA.-BUSH-CUSTOMS (Miami) _ Jeb Bush's wife and the customs dust
up. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS-GAYS (Atlanta) _ Local methodist groups split over
issue of gays, with Bob Barr's group separating from main group
that includes governor. By Tom Lasseter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ADA (Washington) _ Court upholds lower court rules that
American with Disabilities Act does oblige states, when medically
appropriate, to place people with mental disabilities in community
settings, not large institutional settings. While upholding the
principle, the Court sets a variety of conditions that lean toward
giving states some discretion on timing and costs. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABLE (Washington) _ Court rules in cases defining
disability that a condition that can be corrected, with glasses for
example, does not meet legal definition of disability. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-EMPLOY-DISCRIMINATE (Washington) _ Court rules in
employment discrimination case raising issue of punitive damages,
making it very difficult for plaintiffs. In many cases, if all you
can get is back pay, that is not enough of a motivation to bring
action. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-NUKE-LABS (Washington) _ Hearings on who should run the
nuclear labs. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ECONOMY (Washington) _ The nation's long run of
prosperity has left the Republican presidential candidates with a
critical strategic choice: embrace the strong economy as their own,
look for the dark side or change the subject. Even as they
grudgingly acknowledge the conventional wisdom that a strong
economy tends to help the incumbent party in national elections,
the Republicans are unwilling to cede the economy to Gore as an
issue. But their emerging approaches vary, reflecting both ideology
and the need to run against one another before getting a chance to
take on the Democratic nominee. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICING (Washington) _ Surrounded by advocacy groups, Rep.
Tom Allen of Maine escalates his drive for a prescription drug bill
that is anathema to the pharmaceutical industry; it would require
drug companies to provide the same discounts to Medicare
beneficiaries that they provide to big managed care networks, the
Veterans Administration and other big purchasers. Issue of ``price
discrimination'' has caught fire, attracted more than 100
co-sponsors. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-QUOTES (Washington) _ The vote on the Senate import quota
bill. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDUCATION  &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   WYO.-MED-SCHOOL (Undated) _ Dispute over an eccentric
entrepreneur's plan to start a branch of a Caribbean medical school
in Wyoming reveals the American Medical Association's grip over
medical education in the U.S. By Sharon King.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEAD-STUDIES (Undated) _ One new study suggests that high levels
of vitamin C in the blood is associated with a decreased prevalence
of elevated blood levels of lead, while a second study shows that
environmental lead exposure is associated with an increased
prevalence of tooth decay, according to two articles in the June
23/30 issue of The Journal of the American Medical Association
(JAMA). By John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY  &LR;  (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ ``Liberties`` by Maureen Dowd;
details later.
</P>
