<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, June 23. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   CENT: A recent Census Bureau report finds the nation's
centenarian population overwhelmingly female and doubling this
decade. Women living in the Midwest have the best chance of living
to 100. Kansas, Iowa and Nebraska were among the six states with
the highest percentages of centenarians. Missouri was 13th. We
interview local centenarians for their secrets of long life and
aging experts (or experts on aging) to find out what makes the
Midwest, and women, so lucky. Alan Bavley and Lee Hill Kavanaugh.
50. Photos, graphic
</P>
<P>
   FIRE: The Kansas City Fire Department, while angling to take
over ambulance service for the city, was caught refusing to answer
emergency medical calls during a four-alarm fire in May. A
department dispatcher was disciplined for asking MAST to handle all
but the most life-threatening EMS calls during the fire at 1300
Wyoming, and for declining to dispatch fire department personnel to
a total of seven EMS calls during the fire. Steve Penn.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER: Summer school isn't just for dummies anymore.
Increasingly, bright students are signing up for summer school so
they can squeeze in more electives or free up time to take advanced
placement courses that will save them tuition dollars in college.
Mara Rose Williams. 25. Photos
</P>
<P>
   SING: A Parkville guy worked as a meteorologist all his life,
but always loveed singing. He retired and decided to take the
singing gig a little more seriously. He landed a job as a
substitute Platter in Branson. Bill Graham. 18. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE: Folo on the Kansas City Police Department police chase in
which three young black men were killed. We'll paint a portrait of
who they were, talk to parents, etc. Also checking to see if the
chase did conform with the department's policy. Lynn Franey. 20.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   MUCAMP. Mike DeArmond. 25. Norm Stewart meanders around the
nearly 600 wannabe basketball players, gathered in clumps like crab
grass around a playground court, and allows his mind to wander.
This week of team camp _ one of four sessions that began on June 7
and conclude on July 22 _ will be the last of the Stormin' Norman
Basketball Camps. And after the 32 years, the recently retired head
coach of the Missouri Tigers admits to feeling the tug of
nostalgia. ``You think about that,'' admits Stewart, lending his
name to one, last post-retirement camp that has born his name since
1967. ``Somewhere between a year and two years of your life has
been spent in a basketball camp that you're running.'' Photos
</P>
<P>
   NBAGAME. Blair Kerkhoff. 18-20. Advance on Game 4 of the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Dutton. 16-18. Detroit at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHITLOCK. Jason Whitlock column on the Detroit Tigers' Dean
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   MVCOL. Mechelle Voepel column on how women's World Cup soccer
presents an interesting study in what is considered macho and what
isn't.
</P>
<P>
   AIKEN. Jaymes Powell. 15. Erik Aiken of Overland Park, Kan., won
the 119-pound weight class of the U.S. World Team freestyle
wrestling trials in Seattle on Sunday, and will be on the U.S. team
at the World Championships and Pan Am Games. Photos
</P>
<P>
   DANCY. Bob Luder. 15. A feature on young Jake Dancy, a kid who
was at the bottom after being convicted of assault when he punched
another guy during a game a couple years ago, but has since pulled
himself up and has started at left back for the Wizards
professional soccer team the past couple of games.
</P>
</TEXT>
