<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD SPOTS UP . . AT NO. 30? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No. 30?
</P>
<P>
   Come on, ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird has to be better than the 30th-best athlete of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Or so most would think.
</P>
<P>
   In ESPN's ratings, Bird is higher than fellow NBAers Oscar
Robertson (No. 36), Julius Erving (No. 43), Elgin Baylor (No. 58),
Jerry West (No. 62), and Bob Cousy (No. 94).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the rankings supposedly are based on
athletic ability. By all accounts, Bird was not exactly the most
athletic fella around.
</P>
<P>
   But he was one of the most feared players ever. Here's what a
few opponents had to say about Bird during the 30-minute profile
airing Friday at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather guard Michael Jordan than Larry Bird because
you have to play the game as a thinker when you're playing him,''
said James Worthy. ``You have to get inside his mind. Larry wasn't
quick, couldn't jump really high, but there was just some sleepless
nights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, Larry Bird was the only one I feared,'' said
Magic Johnson. ``A lot of black guys always ask me, `Did Larry Bird
really play that good?' I said, `Larry Bird is so good it's
frightening.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Woolridge also gave Bird his props: ``Larry was the
originator of getting in your face and talking trash. And then you
sit there and you go, `Look at this guy up in my face talking
noise.' He ain't that fast. He's slow, but he knew how to aggravate
you, agitate you enough to get you out of your game.''
</P>
<P>
   The keys to Bird's success, according to Indiana University
coach Bobby Knight, were two seldom-mentioned basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a mind that was like a camera,'' Knight said. ``He had
the best hand-eye coordination of maybe anybody that played
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Bird was a great basketball player. But the 30th-best
athlete of the 20th century?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Better than Bobby Orr, ESPN's 31st-best athlete?
</P>
<P>
   ESPN hasn't gone totally loopy.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams hasn't been ranked yet, nor has Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has Jack Nicklaus, nor Babe Ruth, nor Jim Brown, nor
Muhammad Ali, nor Michael Jordan, nor Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, nor Wilt
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NBA takes a dip
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the rate the Spurs-Knicks series is going, this is bound to
be the lowest-rated NBA Finals in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for the first game last Wednesday were 36 percent lower
than last year's Jazz-Bulls opener. The second game was even worse:
44 percent lower than last year's Finals, and 21 percent lower than
the second game in 1994 between the Knicks and Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol conceded that the loss of
Jordan has had considerable impact. Injuries have kept the Knicks
from making the series more competitive, and having a team from the
NBA's smallest television market doesn't help, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, after basically a decade of the greatest athlete of
this generation, we're due for a building year,'' Ebersol told the
Associated Press. ``And this may be ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol went on to say that he thought the ratings would be down
as much as 25-30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all over, if it goes six games we'll be right
there,'' Ebersol said. ``If it's a four-game sweep, we'll be
lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said regular-season and earlier playoff ratings were
higher than expected, so the network won't have to repay
advertisers for not delivering promised audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We so overperformed our guarantees for the regular season and
earlier rounds that we have no problems,'' Ebersol said. ``We just
have the problem of any series: We want more than four games.
That's up to the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hockey shows up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2 has live coverage of the NHL Awards from Toronto's Air
Canada Centre Thursday at 8 p.m. Ron MacLean of CBC's ``Hockey
Night in Canada'' hosts the two-hour show. ESPN2 also has live
coverage of the NHL entry draft Saturday at noon from the
FleetCenter in Boston. Dave Ryan hosts the three-hour telecast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
