<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-KOREA-2TAKES-B     06-22 1605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-KOREA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY WITH A SPECIAL LINK TO KOREA DISCOVERS A DIFFERENT
DESTINATIUON 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ There's a T-shirt on sale here that says ``Korea _
Asia's Best Kept Secret.'' Truer words were never stamped on a
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   From its border with North Korea, where perhaps the world's most
unusual tour is conducted, to its sunny southern island of Cheju,
where ancient history blends with thoroughly modern recreation,
Korea is filled with unexpected delights. Whether part of a wider
tour of Asia or as a destination in itself, the Korean peninsula is
a ``secret'' well worth discovering.
</P>
<P>
   For my wife, Linda, daughter, Amy, and me, this was a journey of
discovery in more than one way. Amy, whom we adopted at age 2, was
born there nearly 27 years ago. For 10 days in May, we explored the
land of her birth, and in addition to learning a little more about
her background, we found a clean, safe, friendly country filled
with scenery, history, culture, shopping (and more shopping),
reasonable prices, good (if sometimes exotic) food, and fun times.
With 38,031 square miles, South Korea is slightly smaller than the
state of Virginia, yet it is packed with attractions.
</P>
<P>
   We picked a serendipitous time to visit, too. A royal ritual was
about to take place, a major festival was scheduled, and holidays
would celebrate both children and their parents. What's more, the
country was abloom with wisteria, azalea, rhododendron, lilacs, and
forsythia. Even a few cherry blossoms lingered after their April
peak.
</P>
<P>
   As most trips to Korea do, this one began in Seoul. Riding from
Kimpo Airport to the heart of Seoul, we were introduced to what has
been called the Miracle by the Han River: a thriving, vibrant,
skyscrapered city that, through the fierce determination and hard
work of its people, sprang from the devastation of the Korean War
in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, the energy is almost palpable. It's a heavily
trafficked city, with sometimes daredevil drivers, and it's a huge
city. (How huge? Nearly 12 million of South Korea's 46 million
residents live in the metropolitan area. On a typical day, there
are 227 marriages and 45 divorces, 463 births and 108 deaths, 305
auto purchases, 1,272 new drivers' licenses, and 5,684 traffic
tickets.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shrines and shops
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But within this modern city is another Seoul: one that reflects
the 5,000-year-old culture and civilization of Korea _ a Seoul of
richly adorned palaces, temples, and shrines. Perhaps picking up on
Seoul's energy, we gave outselves no resting time after our long
flight and headed for Changgyungkung Palace, where the annual Royal
Shrine Ritual was taking place at the adjoining Chongmyo Shrine.
The ritual is replete with processions, colorful costumes, and
music. After joining in the jockeying for position, we listened to
the horns and drums, and my wife remarked: ``Just think, the
instruments alone are older than America.'' The Confucian ceremony
welcomes ancestral spirits of the Chosun Dynasty, entertains them,
and ushers them out. So I hope the spirits forgave jet-lagged me
for inadvertently stepping on a walkway that is reserved for
spirits alone.
</P>
<P>
   We visited another palace, Changdukkung, which conducts tours in
English and provides a wondrous look into another time. Included is
the Secret Garden. (What's the secret? There really is none, we
were told; the name stems from a mistranslation of a sign.) And we
stopped by Buddhist temples, with their striking red and gold decor
and ageless ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   But, to our daughter's delight, it was now shopping time, at one
of Seoul's most charming districts, Insadong. We wandered among the
shops and galleries bearing art, antiques (including lovely
cabinets and chests), crafts, and novelties. Calligraphy supplies
are a specialty, and my daughter ordered a seal with her middle
name: Joy.
</P>
<P>
   Insadong boasts a lot of restaurants, too, and we enjoyed our
first meal in Korea at a small place, wielding stainless steel
chopsticks over a variety of dishes, including bulgogi, a thinly
sliced and tasty meat, and kimchi, that powerfully pickled
cabbage-based food that, along with steamed rice, is the unofficial
national dish. Korean meals typically have a variety of dishes in
small bowls. While I enjoyed most of the meat and vegetables, my
tastes were too Westernized for the more exotic types of seafood
such as cuttlefish, whelk, and sea cucumbers. Koreans like their
food spicy, but usually red pepper paste is served on the side so
you can adjust the spiciness to your liking. (And if you must, you
can find Western style meals in Korea, even fast food at places
with names like Happy Wing and, yes, McDonald's).)
</P>
<P>
   Seoul is a city of shopping areas for everything from trendy
clothes to electronics to jewelry. But we next went to the
Namdaemum people's market, where an astonishing array of goods is
on sale at 1,500 outdoor kiosks, and bargaining _ sometimes major,
sometimes minor _ is permitted. Clothes, jewelry, foodstuffs,
flowers, designer look-alikes, and toys overflowed, and the prices
were excellent. One saleswoman, learning my daughter was born in
Korea, gave her a gift; this kind act would be repeated later at
the Itaewon market area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The DMZ
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following morning we did what we recommend every tourist do:
visited the Korean National Tourism Office in Seoul. Here you'll
find a multitude of booklets, brochures, displays, and _ to show
how seriously Korea takes tourism _ a complaint department. Many
kinds of tours can be booked here, including the most unusual one
I've ever taken: to the Demilitarized Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Located as it is between China and Japan, Korea has often been
the target of aggression and foreign rule. The war between North
and South Korea flared from 1950 to 1953, leading to a cease-fire
(but not a peace accord) and the creation of a Demilitarized Zone
and the truce village of Panmunjom, where Nerth Korea and the UN
Command have met sporadically ever since and as recently as last
week in a dispute over territorial waters. Only authorized tours
are permitted, and you soon learn this is no trip to fool around
on. Wearing jeans or open sandals is not permitted; no one wants to
give the North Koreans an opportunity to photograph sloppy
visitors. And because violence has flared occasionally, you are
required to sign a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a visit is fascinating, even though seeing a North
Korean soldier looking at you through binoculars may well give you
a chill. The tour includes a stop in the peace conference room,
with a line of demarcation running down the middle. You can step
from one side of the line to the other, thus going from South Korea
to North Korea. All the while you are guarded by South Korean
soldiers assuming a modified tae kwon do stance known as ROK Ready,
the ROK standing for the Republic of Korea, which is South Korea's
official name.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, which costs about $50 and takes about seven hours,
includes stops at Korean War memorials for Philippine participants,
fallen war correspondents, and 10 brave Korean soldiers who gave
their lives to save others. It also includes a buffet lunch of
mostly American-style dishes and an opportunity to shop at low
prices for a variety of goods, including Korea's popular and
beautiful amethyst jewelery. Myself, I brought home a framed piece
of the barbed wire that runs along the border for 151 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The DMZ gave us a lot to think about that day, but back in Seoul
we lightened our mood with a visit to the massive Lotte department
store. As we did on our Korean Air flight and in our hotel, the
Sofitel Ambassador, we observed the kind of constant, helpful,
enthusiastic service that, sadly, seems to be fading fast in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   At night, it was off to Korea House, a tourist favorite in a
traditional wood-framed, tile-roofed building, where we dined
Korean style and saw traditional music and dance. The dancers'
bright, multicolored costumes were topped only by their intricate
steps, with the women coordinating their movements perfectly to
make pretty patterns with fans, and the men leaping and bounding
and gyrating their heads so that streamers attached to their hats
created spirals in the air. All this was accompanied by
almost-hypnotic music from such instruments as a gong and hourglass
drum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Significant stops
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was time to see the Korea that exists away from Seoul _ a
Korea where rows of misty and mystical green hills are almost
ever-present, as are the rectangular, watery patches of land where
rice is grown. No wonder the country is called the Land of the
Morning Calm.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul you can almost always find someone who speaks enough
English (and delightfully accented at that) to help you. And most
people will go out of their way for you. Away from Seoul, English
isn't as widely spoken, although road signs are in English as well
as Hangul (Korean). If you're the adventurous type and carry a
phrasebook, you can rent a car or use the extensive public transit
system, or you can be part of a tour group. But you can also hire
drivers and English-speaking guides. Our guide from Global Tour
Ltd., a 27-year old dynamo named Sarah Chung, was simply the best
we have had anywhere. Her English was excellent, her knowledge of
the country extensive, her sense of humor delightful, and her
dedication remarkable. If I were ever to open a guide agency, I
would staff it with Sarah Chung clones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
