<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL EXPLORES THE COSMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Montreal has always been very international, but this summer it
is offering an otherworldly experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosmos: From Romanticism to the Avant-garde'' at the Montreal
Museum of Fine Arts explores how artists visualized relationships
between the earth and the universe. More than 380 works from 20
countries are featured. Artists include Frederic Edwin Church,
Thomas Cole, Albert Bierstadt, Van Gogh, Picasso, Calder, and David
Friedrich, whose work is seldom seen outside Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   As we enter the 21st century, Cosmos is all about immagination
and the relationship of earth and sky. It's a fascinating look at
our world as artists and others explored both the unknown and
reality. Some paintings are utopian views, others show the planet
in turbulence. There are scenes of beauty _ Bierstadt's
``Yellowstone'' is one. Besides paintings, there are photographs,
from daguerreotypes dating from 1854 to NASA photos, an old space
suit, sculpture, a meteorite, and scientific objects.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit can be seen only in Montreal through Oct. 17. Cosmos
is the new frontier as you've never experienced it. For more
information, call 514-285-2000 or visit www.mmfa.qc.ca.
</P>
<P>
   From Boston, Montreal is an easy five-or-so-hour drive, or just
an hour by plane with great service from Air Canada and other
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is particularly festive in summer. From July 1 through
11, the 20th annual International Jazz Festival fills the city with
music from noon to midnight. More than 400 concerts are planned,
300 of them free. For information on packages to the festival, call
888-515-0515 or visit www.montrealjazzfest.com. For ticket
information, call 800-361-4595. Other evnts include the Benson &AMP;
Hedges International Fireworks Competition through July 28, and the
Just for Laughs Festival July 15-25.
</P>
<P>
   Being the second largest French speaking city after Paris,
Montreal has a very European ambience, and a lively night life.
Saint-Denis is one of the liveliest streets at night, filled with
trendy new restaurants like Jongleux Cafe. For lively action 24
hours a day, the European-style Casino offers not only gaming
action but great dining and shows. Its dinner-theater is featuring
``Sinatra Remembered,'' a must for any Sinatra fan (one of the
stars bears a remarkable resemblance to Frank). And you won't go
broke seeing this show, which includes a three-course dinner along
with wine and a champagne welcome for $69 _ that's Canadian, which
means the American dollar buys the show at a 40 percent or more
discount. A Casino package including two nights' accommodation, and
air fare begins at $265. Call 800-MONTREAL.
</P>
<P>
   With the dollar buying more in Canada, it's a good time to visit
_ especially Montreal, one of the liveliest and most interesting
cities in North America. For more information, call 800-363-7777 or
visit www.tourism-montreal.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take off
</P>
<P>
   TWA is planning a major upgrade on its service to San Juan. The
airline has designated San Juan its first ``focus city,'' a
location where TWA will expand service. In this case, TWA is
offering nonstop service from five new cities to San Juan. Boston
will have two daily flights to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Air is now offering hourly air service from T. F. Green
Airport in Providence to Nantucket, and from New Bedford to both
Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard. Hourly departures are also
available from Logan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Use caution
</P>
<P>
   A ``worldwide caution'' has been issued by the US State
Department. The announcement was not made in response to any
particular threat or event, but to emphasize the State Department's
ongoing concern for the security of Americans overseas. The State
Department said it continues to receive reports that makes it
concerned about the safety and security of Americans worldwide.
Americans living and traveling abroad were urged to review their
security remain alert to the changing situation, and to exercise
caution. For more details, or future updates, visit
www.travel.state.gov or call 202-647-5225.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell's Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   Norman Rockwell is most identified with small-town New England
life, but he also had a flair for Hollywood. ``Hooray for
Rockwell's Hollywood'' at the Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass.
shows this side of the artist with movie posters and other
illustrations he created for the studios. The exhibit continues
through Oct. 31. For information, call 413-298-4100.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deal
</P>
<P>
   British Airways is offering a free round-trip ticket to London
with each round-trip economy class ticket purchased by June 30. The
offer is good on any British Airways ticket for summer travel
between June 22 and Sept. 30. The free ticket may be used anytime
between Nov. 1 and March 31, except for Dec. 15 through Jan. 15,
2000. From Boston, a round-trip ticket to London for the summer is
$638.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camp in Boston
</P>
<P>
   The New England Aquarium is offering Boston Harbor Island
camping trips July 24-26 and Aug. 7-8. The $80 non-aquarium member
price includes transportation to the islands and guided natural
history walks by naturalists. For more information, call
617-973-6562.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost travel
</P>
<P>
   Busabout is a network of private buses in Europe that allow
``hop on/ hop-off'' travel to more than 60 cities. Busabout passes
are said to be at least 30 percent less than any rail pass, and the
motorcoaches are staffed by represenatives who are ready to assist
travelers with tips and information. Through June 30 a $465
one-month pass includes a link to Morocco valued at $99, and an
Unlimited Pass, starting at $910 for students, includes both the
Moroccan link and 10 nights' free accommodations. For information,
call Council Travel at 800-2-COUNCIL or STA TRavel at 800-777-0112.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
World puzzle
</P>
<P>
   If you think the world is going to pieces, try putting it back
with Jixxa _ World Travel Edition. This new CD-Rom provides plenty
of fun with its 12 puzzles for beginner to expert. World-famous
scenes range from the Antarctic to the Taj Mahal and the Arc de
Triomphe. Adding to the enjoyment are features allowing for
competition with another player and being able to save your
work-in-progress to finish at a later time. Jixxa retails for
$29.95. For more information, call Rhode Island Soft Systems at
800-959-7477 or, on the Web, visit www.risoftsystems.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
