<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-KOREA-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTHER'S MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ This may have been my first trip to Korea, but the
memories came rushing back.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I were traveling with our 26-year-old daughter,
Amy, who had been adopted from South Korea at age 2. We had talked
about visiting the country some years before this trip but Amy
wasn't ready. Now she was, and here are the memories our trip
rekindled:
</P>
<P>
   As our jet neared Kimpo Airport, I could see women squatting in
the rice paddies, planting seedlings _ something we would see
almost everywhere. Amy, when she arrived in America, would squat,
seemingly for hours, while she played. Now I knew where that
position had come from.
</P>
<P>
   We saw women with babies and small children tied to their backs
by a garment made for carrying. When Amy got her first doll, she
she took a tiny blanket and showed me how she wanted the doll tied
to her back. That was why.
</P>
<P>
   The first few times Amy saw cats in our yard, she would yell and
throw things at them _ highly uncharacteristic for this fun-loving
child. During our visit, we saw no cats whatsoever, and that
explained Amy's behavior _ she was probably frightened of animals
she wasn't familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that hot and spicy Korean cabbage dish called
kimchi. A few months after Amy arrived, we took her to a Korean
restaurant and watched her devour kimchi, all the while making
hissing, blowing sounds because of the spiciness. Most of the meals
we ate on our trip consisted of small communal dishes, and kimchi
was always among them. It was the bowl I avoided and the one Amy
finished, just as she did a quarter-century ago
</P>
<P>
   While on our 10-day trip, I learned that thumbsucking and
pacifiers are frowned upon in Korea. And that, I realized, is why
Amy would get so upset when our younger son sucked his thumb. She
must have considered me an unfit mother!
</P>
<P>
   When we went to the Korean Folk Village outside of Seoul, we saw
houses with charcoal heaters that sit in the middle of the floor
and bedding that is stored at night. To our surprise, our guide
told us that families would have lived in such homes in the 1970s.
Then I remembered that Amy came to us with small scars on her arms
that were attributed in the adoption report to ``possible burns
from charcoal heaters.''
</P>
<P>
   After returning home, I was exhausted by the long flight and the
13-hour time difference. I thought about the tiny 2-year-old who
had made that flight and then wanted to sleep when we were awake
and wanted to play while we were sleeping. I could see her tired
face so clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Korea, it turned out, was a wonderful way of revisiting
memories.
</P>
<P>
   (Holt International Children's Services conducts a Family Tour
for adoptees and their families, and a Motherland Tour for selected
groups of adoptees 18 and older. For information, call 541-687-2202
or write to Holt, PO Box 2880, Eugene, OR 97402.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-KOREA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-22 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-KOREA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SEOUL: ... Chung clones.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this day, with a couple of significant stops, we would ride
some 175 miles, from west to east, to Kangwon Province and stay in
the Mount Sorak area at, of all things, a British-style hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Stop number one didn't have a lot to do with tourism, though. It
was in Wonju, where our daughter was found abandoned at age 2 and
brought to City Hall. The visit yielded no memories for Amy and no
new information about her past, but we felt it was worth making for
Amy to see the city.
</P>
<P>
   Stop number two was one of those surprises that helped make the
trip so delightful. We pulled into the Chamsori Gramophone &AMP; Audio
Museum in Kang Reung-City. And for a fan of old-time radios and
Victrolas, as I am, the place was nirvana. The museum contains more
than 4,000 items, all of them working. They range from music boxes
to many, many Victor Talking Machines to Bakelite radios to a 1925
TV set to today's DVDs, played on a sound system that will rock
you. Many of the machines were housed in beautiful cabinets, and
many were rare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorak National Park
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At our British-style hotel, the Kensington, with its rich cherry
wood and its ``tally-ho'' hunting portraits, we settled in, then
dined upon _ shall I confess? _ pizza and spaghetti. We had to fuel
up, because, after all, there was a mountain to explore the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   That mountain is Sorak, at 5,839 feet the third-highest peak in
Korea. At Soraksan National Park, which was not overly crowded this
May morning, we boarded a subway-style cable car for a scenic ride
near the mountaintop, envisioning how beautiful the trees must look
when they dress in the reds and golds of autumn. But the park is
stunning in any season, with its jagged peaks, lush valleys, and
deep forests.
</P>
<P>
   This was Children's Day in Korea (I explained to our guide that
every day is Children's Day in America) and youngsters were
plentiful in the park on this national holiday. And what
adorable-looking children they are, although their good looks
didn't deter some of them from concocting pranks, just like
children all over the world. Our daughter climbed proudly to the
peak of Sorak. But she found that to come down, it was necessary to
be more humble and scoot for a while.
</P>
<P>
   We could have spent many more hours at Sorak. But in the late
afternoon, another pleasant surprise awaited: the Waterpia
waterpark in Sokcho. Here, indoors and out, there are large pools,
fountains, massage pools, and even a lemon-jasmine pool filled with
neon green water. Seldom have I felt more relaxed than after my
soaking at Waterpia.
</P>
<P>
   We learned also that from Sept. 11-Oct. 30, Sokcho will be the
site of the massive International Travel Expo '99, open to the
public and featuring pavilions, shows, rides, a 240-foot-high
tower, nature attractions, and special events, with a theme of
``Man, Nature, and the Life of the Future.'' The expo is expected
to draw 3 million people. Afterward, the site will become a
permanent amusement and cultural park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheju Island
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With our Korean odyssey at the halway point, we flew south to
sunny Cheju, island, often called the Hawaii of Korea. It's a
favorite spot for honeymooners, offering a balmy blend of
recreation, scenery, and legend. It's also the home of Mount Halla,
Korea's highest peak at 6,397 feet. And wherever you go, you will
be met by statues of the village guardians _ smiling Mongols.
They're the emblem of the island, and we posed for pictures beside
large versions of them in the lobby of the KAL Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Cheju island features golf, hunting, horseback riding (and a
horse racing track), snorkeling, scuba diving, windsurfing,
fishing, and just lying on the beach. It even has Las Vegas-style
casinos _ for foreigners only (Koreans aren't permitted to lose
their cash foolishly).
</P>
<P>
   We, however, immersed ourselves in scenery, visiting such places
as Sunrise Peak, a volcano whose sides plunge dramtically into the
surf and where dolphins are sometimes seen frolicking; the cool,
wet Hypochae-Ri Lava Caves, including one of the few in the world
with stalagmites and stalactites; the Mok Suk Won Garden, where
basalt and driftwood have been ingeniously arranged to represent
local legends; the gorgeous and extensive Yeomiji Botanic Garden;
and the Chonjiyon Waterfall, which is striking, but do be careful
where you step: We saw a woman fall off the rocks and into the
water (she was quickly rescued). At night, there was shopping in an
underground mall that seemed to stretch on forever, and a meal at
the Lotteria, a takeoff on 1950s' America, with chrome and vinyl
chairs, a mural featuring a pink Cadillac, and even a star from a
mock Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back to Seoul
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We flew back to Seoul on Parents' Day, which combines our
Mothers' Day and Fathers' Day. Parents are traditionally presented
small flower corsages, so our daughter got in the spirit of things
by giving us corsages. Throughout the day there was a flower in my
lapel and a smile on my face.
</P>
<P>
   That evening was our opportunity to see . . . Lotte World! This
is an indoor-outdoor, Disney-style amusement park, complete with
castle. (The name Lotte, like the names Samsung, Hyundai, KAL, and
a few others, crops up everywhere in Korea, on a variety of
products, buildings, and attractions.) Being an amusement park
buff, I enjoyed myself immensely, taking in the half-hour electric
light parade starring Lotty and Lorry Raccoon (think Mickey and
Minnie Mouse), but for once I left rides the wilder rides such as
the Waikiki Wave and the Gyro Drop to the younger people.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, our last full day, was devoted to a couple of
attractions 90 or so minutes from Seoul. The first, the Korean Folk
Village in Suwon, is a must for visitors (and was the first place
where we saw more than two or three other Caucasian faces).
Although we had enjoyed the Cheju Folk Village, this one was even
more extensive, with displays of everything from making mulberry
paper to weaving silk from silkworms. The one-room wooden houses
looked old indeed _ until we learned that our guide had lived in
such a house until the 1970s. There were Korean dances and a
dramatic tae kwon do exhibition where the performers battled with
balletic grace. And there was a wedding. During the week such
marriages are staged, but on Sundays it's the real thing. The
couple, in traditional dress, faced each other, bowed, and knelt.
There is a legend that if the bride smiles during the ceremony, the
first child will be a girl. And although the bride had covered her
mouth with her billowing sleeves, her smile reached all the way
into her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The second attraction was another of those delightful surprises:
the Ceramic Festival in Yoju. Korea is a land of festivals, and at
this one, booth after booth had bargain-priced vases, lamps, and
other items, some with swirls, others with tigers and dragons.
There were snacks and drinks and Teletubbies (yes, those bizarre TV
creatures are popular here, too). My wife and daughter left with
ornate vases, and I walked away holding a Donald Duck cup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A poignant farewell
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our final day was also the most poignant because we visited the
Seoul headquarters of Holt International, the organization that had
brought Amy into foster care and eventually to us.
</P>
<P>
   A Holt representative found our daughter's records, and she
learned that she had been found clutching a note that told her name
and birthday. For 25 years, we had believed, either through
miscommunication or misinformation, that Amy's Korean name of Choi
Gi Sook and her birth date had arbitrarily been given to her by the
orphanage. Now we knew this wasn't so, and our daughter would leave
Korea with a name, a birthday, and, after visiting her birth land,
a new pride in being Korean. Looking at her, poised and lovely in a
peach-colored dress, I thought of the frightened 2-year-old who
came kicking and screaming into our lives and I stifled a sob.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to head home. Despite all that we had seen (and so
much that we hadn't, including the major cities of Pusan and
Inchon), I think that what will linger longest in memory are the
everyday scenes: uniformed schoolgirls strolling along holding
hands . . . mothers carrying their babies papoose-style on their
backs . . . a teenage boy going far out of his way to give us
directions . . . an elderly woman singing a lovely, lilting tune to
herself while climbing down Mount Sorak . . . people using what few
English words they knew to make us feel at home . . . kerchiefed
women bent over, working in the rice fields . . . sharp-dressed men
and stylishly dressed women striding down the streets of Seoul with
cell phones attached to their ears . . . and a young boy casually
sidling up to us to get a better view of such unusual-looking
people.
</P>
<P>
   Our suitcases were filled with great souvenirs, but our minds
were filled with even greater memories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
