<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PINK-GIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRENADA SPA EVEN OFFERS FENCING LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD AND TIMOTHY LELAND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINK GIN BEACH, Grenada _ The fragrance of jasmine was in the
air and sunlight dappled the red and white bougainvillea outside
our room when we awoke on the first morning of our trip to this
sweet, unspoiled Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   It was only 6:45, but there was no time to smell the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have 10 minutes before the Power Walk begins,'' the
husband warned, ``and right after breakfast we have a fencing
lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Fencing in the Caribbean?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta be kidding,'' the wife exclaimed, rolling over and
shutting her eyes for a little more sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But the husband wasn't kidding. He was already lacing up his
running shoes. There was much to do.
</P>
<P>
   We had come to this island, 100 miles due north of Venezuela,
for a stay at a five-year-old health spa known as La Source, where
the minutes of the day are calculated against the number of
activities one can fit into it between sunrise and sunset.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was, after a brisk two-mile walk along a narrow road
winding up a bluff, followed by a healthy breakfast of island
fruits and pastries, that we suited up in form-fitting white
jackets and protective gloves, and _ foils in hand _ headed to our
fencing class, prepared to learn the specifics of lunges, parries,
and ``en gardes'' that make up this martial tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It's a martial tradition that has more to do with England, which
once claimed Grenada as a colony, than the Caribbean. The King's
English is still spoken on this island, now an independent
protectorate. You also hear a local, lyrical patois that is a
mixture of Carib Indian and French, the latter having tried and
failed to capture the former in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, our instruction in fencing had nothing to do with
self defense _ unless the idea is to make adversaries laugh
themselves to death. This was all in quest of good health and
exercise. And that morning's fencing was just the beginning of
both.
</P>
<P>
   The range of activities being offered at La Source on that
typical day went like this:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7:00 a.m. Gymnasium opens
</P>
<P>
   7:10 a.m. Power walk and stretch
</P>
<P>
   8:10 a.m. Fencing lessons
</P>
<P>
   8:30 a.m. Tennis lessons
</P>
<P>
   9:00 a.m. Tai Chi
</P>
<P>
   10:00 a.m. Beginners archery
</P>
<P>
   11:00 a.m. Golf orientation
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m. Aqua aerobics
</P>
<P>
   12:00 noon Water voleyball
</P>
<P>
   2:00 p.m. Board games
</P>
<P>
   3:00 p.m. Circuit training
</P>
<P>
   3:10 p.m. Table tennis
</P>
<P>
   4:00 p.m. Intermediate archery
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m. Intermediate aerobics
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m. Caribbean dance and limbo lessons
</P>
<P>
   4:45 p.m. Guest vs. staff golf tournament
</P>
<P>
   5:00 p.m. Beach volleyball
</P>
<P>
   5:30 p.m. Evening jog
</P>
<P>
   8:00 p.m. Grenada National Golf Group concert
</P>
<P>
   9:00 p.m. Bonfire beach party
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't enough, there is another bulletin board just for
water activities: windsurfing, sailing, waterskiing, snorkeling,
and diving. Not to mention lazing around the two swimming pools a
few steps from the main restaurant or sunning on the adjacent
beach.
</P>
<P>
   The activities at the spa continue when the sun goes down and
the floodlights come on. Tennis is a popular nighttime sport
because of the relative coolness, and so is dancing by the pool to
the beat of Caribbean steel drums. (That beat adapts wonderfully to
swing dancing, we discovered.)
</P>
<P>
   Or, you can collapse into the piano bar after dinner and just
sit until closing time, which occurs whenever the last person feels
like leaving. Some guests didn't feel like leaving until 6 in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The night owls obviously weren't rigorously pursuing the
``health'' part of this health spa regimen. And, in truth, even the
most rigorous health fanatic might occasionally be tempted to
overindulge in the free tropical drinks that are available at this
spa, night and day. Stick one of the colored flags in the sand next
to your deck chair when you're sunning on the beach and someone
comes along a few minutes later to offer you a delicious Caribbean
concoction in a tall glass. And, like everything else at the
resort, the drinks are free.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this resort is an ``all-inclusive,'' meaning that
everything from airport transportation to golf lessons on the
par-three course are included in the price of admission, all
prepaid.
</P>
<P>
   The all-inclusive concept has been criticized in the press
lately, including the Globe, on the grounds that the local
population receives little benefit from a resort that is run by a
large company somewhere off the island. Furthermore, tourists at
all-inclusives supposedly don't help support the local economy or
come in contact with the local people in the surrounding
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is probably truth to the assertions in many
instances, La Source is owned by a native Grenadian, 61-year-old
Leon Taylor, who argues that the spa makes an important
contribution to the Grenadian economy _ and not only in taxes. ``We
have 250 employees here, and these are jobs that wouldn't exist
without this resort,'' he says. La Source also buys as much fresh
produce as possible from local farmers, according to general
manager Richard Fenn, and uses local taxi and limousine drivers in
addition to the entire resort staff, which is all local.
</P>
<P>
   With an unemployment rate of around 16 percent and the price of
its chief cash crop (nutmeg) falling, Grenadians are more than
willing to move from spices to tourists. ``You have to start
somewhere and resorts such as ours will encourage the tourist
industry to grow up all around us,'' Fenn says. There are
significantly fewer American tourists here than British, and some
people believe that's due to confusion over whether there is still
a ``war'' going on here. Sixteen years ago, American troops stormed
ashore and ousted a pro-Soviet junta that had seized power in a
bloody coup. The only evident legacy is a large modern airport that
provides easy access for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   As to getting out and about, there were plenty of opportunities
to see the rest of the island during our stay. In the orientation,
we were introduced to the owner of a local tourist excursion
company, separate and apart from the spa, who suggested a number of
trips around this beautiful 133-square-mile island. These included
hikes in the rain forest, visits to spice factories and rum
distilleries, and deep-sea fishing excursions. According to Fenn,
more than 90 percent of La Source hotel guests leave the resort
during their stay.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the staff here refer to themselves as ``bodyguards.''
Their mission is to guard the guests' bodies from sloth, not crime.
In Grenada there is more danger from the ocean currents than from
muggings. On the first day, a lovely bodyguard named Tamasha told
us that we could jog around the island ``anytime, anywhere.'' But
if you go swimming, she warned, be sure to stay inside the
roped-off area. ``There's nothing down here between us and
Venezuela, and that's where you could end up if you get caught in a
current.''
</P>
<P>
   We stayed in the roped-off area, no argument. As the days went
by, we signed up for the fencing classes and the archery classes,
the power walks and the snorkeling, the tennis instruction and the
water volleyball, the windsurfing and the Tai Chi, the stretching
exercises and the yoga classes.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the latter two were held in the same little gazebo
on the hill overlooking the ocean. We could go from one class to
the other without the stress of being late, which meant we didn't
have to go to the ``Stress Reduction Class,'' also offered at the
spa every day.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 the afternoon, we usually were trying to decide whether to
make ``tea'' time or ``tee'' time. With all the British influences
here, many people at the resort stop for tea and sweets on the
veranda at that hour, but we normally opted for a round of golf in
the afternoon, and were teeing off on the par-three course, alone
save for a couple of other American hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Another time-related decision at the resort is how to fit in all
the body treatments that are part of the spa package _ the Swedish
massages, the body wraps, the facials, and the foot massages that
melt away whatever remaining tensions one brings from Big Dig
traffic jams when jetting out of Boston to this idyllic spot.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite massage was aromatherapy, which utilizes specially
scented oils to accomplish specific results. We had a choice of
``The Energy Blend,'' featuring oils of safflower, almond, canola,
jojoba, lemon, lime, basil, and peppermint . . . or ``The
Relaxation Blend'' (rosewood, lavender and orange) . . . or ``The
Love Blend'' (safflower, almond, canola, ylang ylang, tangerine,
patchouli, nutmeg).
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the recipes for the special tropical drinks offered each
day at the bar sounded strangely similar to the ingredients in the
massage oils: ``Grenada Papa,'' for example, featured orange,
pineapple, coconut creme, rum, and nutmeg. Was this a drink or a
scented oil? Who could tell?
</P>
<P>
   In the end we decided it didn't matter. They were all delicious.
For the record, our favorite was the ``La Source Cocktail,'' which
is made from dark rum, coco cristal, Grenadine, pineapple, and
``seamoss creme,'' an algae from the sea, dried and boiled as
oatmeal before it is blended into the drink. Who said this isn't a
health spa?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Other Drink, not featured on the resort menu
but discussed with winks and smiles among the locals. Aptly named
``Under-The-Counter,'' this Grenadian specialty cocktail is made
from Barbados rum, raw peanuts, worm, deer horn, and part of a tree
bark found on the island called bois bande. The drink is said to
have the same effect on the drinker as Viagra. Local legend has it
that several years ago an elderly man with a young girlfriend
quaffed down two cups of the potion and later had to be taken to a
hospital emergency room, where minor surgery was performed to
offset the drink's powerful effects.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we never got near that drink. The only medical
problem we had at La Source came after our aromatherapy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   On those occasions _ oiled and pampered to a dreamy state of
mind _ we were given strict orders by our masseuse as we floated
out of the treatment room: ``No exercise, alcohol, or sun for the
next two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No exercise, alcohol, or sun for two hours?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   That creates a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   In this place, what's left?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
