<SLUG> BC-BULLET-TRAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED RAIL TO NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Build a bullet train? For $23.3 billion, twice
the annual budget of Casey Jones' home state of Kentucky? They've
got to be kidding _ or high on cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Why go faster when the pace of life is killing us already? Why
would anybody want to get to Sacramento any sooner? Where's the
kick in cruising through Pacheco Pass en route to Gilroy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine speeding the length of California at maximum speeds of
over 200 miles per hour, without ever leaving the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what it says on the California High Speed Rail
Authority's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I can imagine it. And it makes me want to reach for the
Dramamine.
</P>
<P>
   It would be more fun pedaling a bicycle cart along the Santa
Barbara boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Or riding a 1930s streetcar along Market Street in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   I rode a bullet train in France last fall _ the TGV, for ``train
a grande vitesse'' _ and it wasn't good even there. I sat backward,
it was raining and the baguettes were stale. I was nauseated all
the way from Paris to Arles.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the darned thing never got up over 150 kph (93 mph). The
thrill was nil.
</P>
<P>
   Next time I'm in France, I intend to take the lowliest choo-choo
I can find. I want an old-fashioned pullet train, the kind real
people ride with their farm animals and goatskins filled with red
wine.
</P>
<P>
   The kind that smells from engine oil and Gaulois cigarettes and
garlic and liver sausage and hay. A train out of a movie by Marcel
Pagnol.
</P>
<P>
   I want to gaze out the window onto the same sun-soaked fields
that impressed the Impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   There is no point in tying California together more tightly,
which is what the California High Speed Rail Authority intends to
do, with the blessing of the state Legislature and Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate we're going, all of California soon will be roadbed,
track and runway. We'll get a terminal case of terminalitis. The
one core value the state's 33 million residents will share will be
a tunnel through the Tehachapis.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag on this profligate project with a nifty name is
huge beyond belief. Put the money into schools. Or health care. Or
birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Or give it to me.
</P>
<P>
   The bureaucratic bozos behind this boondogle say 20 million
passengers will use the bullet train every year. That works out to
54,794.52 people per day. Enough to fill PacBell Park, and then
some. I don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it were built, the average person won't be able to
afford a ticket to ride an appreciable distance, if today's prices
are any indication. Fancy rail service carries a fancy tariff.
</P>
<P>
   Check it out.
</P>
<P>
   In November 2000, voters will be asked to approve a half-cent
sales tax to fund this doozy.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound like much. But neither does one drip from a
leaky faucet at midnight. Multiply it by 10,000 and you've got a
problem. That's how teensy taxes work.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too soon to begin wrapping your mind around a no vote
on the bullet train.
</P>
<P>
   But if you don't want to wait until November 2000 to register a
protest, consider firing up your computer and sending the
commission a message at its Web site, www.hsr.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   There's a public input page at the site. Punch their ticket.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Winokur writes for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box
7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
