<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD'S GIFT TO MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Every time you see another supermodel or movie
star with huge breasts and the hips of an 8-year-old boy, don't you
wish you lived in some bygone era when women weren't such slaves to
the impossible quest for a perfect body?
</P>
<P>
   I thought that too until I went microfilm diving and happened
upon a ``ladies section'' in the San Francisco Examiner from the
summer of 1909. A headline taunted: ``How to Make the Figure
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The author: Madame Lina Cavalieri, ``The Most Famous Living
Beauty.'' Her job: To ``enumerate the standards of beauty for the
female form, then discuss how these standards may be approached by
the woman who is dissatisfied, and with good reason, with her
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   You think it's hell trying to look like Naomi Campbell? Try
Madame C. on for size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly determine how far your figure falls short of
perfection ...,'' she advises. ``The critical view in the duplex or
triplex mirror may reveal that the figure is too broad or too thick
for its height. If too broad, the defect is serious, and will be
difficult, if not impossible, of remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   If the defect is merely thickness, guess what she prescribes?
``Diet, exercise and massage.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that sounds simple? It isn't. Not given the body blueprint
that Mme. Cavalieri uses for all women: ``Perfection ... according
to the canons of classic statuary. The standards of Greek sculpture
have never been improved.''
</P>
<P>
   To live up to the ``undeviating rules'' of classic statuary, a
woman's figure should be ``exactly six times as long as the foot,''
she said. Does a woman's figure include her head? Madame did not
say. If it does, then I, who have 93 1/4-inch-long tootsies, should
stand 4-feet-10-1/2-inches. But I'm 5-feet-6. If I'm allowed to
subtract nine inches of noggin, I still miss the standards of Greek
perfection by 11 1/2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   It goes downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect face _ which ``has always been pearshaped'' _ should
measure exactly one-tenth of the ``entire stature.'' The perfect
hand, from tip of middle finger to end of palm, should be the same
length as the perfect face.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, ``the body when standing with the arms extended
horizontally should form a human Maltese cross. The length of the
body should be the same as the distance ... from the middle finger
of one hand to the middle finger of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfy _ there before your mirror trying to form a human Maltese
cross? Turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the back is full and the hips bulge, the waist is large,
the figure has no elegance; is, indeed, common. If you are the
possessor of such blemishes to beauty, you should at once set to
work to remove the deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not liposuction. Diet, exercise and massage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavalieri diet? Simplicity itself. ``Reduce your diet at the
beginning by one-quarter, then one-third and after that one-half.''
</P>
<P>
   Her exercise program? ``Walk, walk, walk.''
</P>
<P>
   As for massage, which ``has always seemed to me a cure-all for
defects in beauty,'' Madame says do it deep and with an astringent
of tincture of iodine, iodide of potassium, distilled and aniseed
water.
</P>
<P>
   That is unless your ``entire outline is too meagre'' and you
need a ``curve-making and flesh-building'' cream. Then it's fresh
mutton tallow, lanolin, spermaceti and coconut oil.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1907, breast size was a big deal. But a different big
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who think their busts are too large write me often
asking how they may reduce them,'' Mme. Cavalieri confides.
</P>
<P>
   Not at all a fan of breast reduction remedies beyond diet and
exercise, she does share a ``European formula'' _ sweet almond oil,
white wax, tincture of benzoin, rose water, tannin _ but cautions
that a doctor should ``sanction'' its use.
</P>
<P>
   Last but hardly least, the most famous living beauty advises:
``After exercise and diet for improving the figure, there is
nothing so important than to be well corseted.''
</P>
<P>
   What does she mean by ``well?'' Well, the intimate sausage
casing should be ``pliable and hygenic'' and have rubber webbing in
its sides. Most important, ``every corset should have eight
garters. Yes, I mean it; four on each side.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes the Wonderbra look benign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
