<HEADLINE>
HAPPY BIRTHDAY TO ONE BIG BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's largest cruise ship, the 109,000-ton Grand Princess,
has celebrated its first birthday. And what a year it's had, plying
the Caribbean and Mediterranean waters. In its first year, the
Grand Princess:
</P>
<P>
   --Logged 101,986.6 nautical miles, using 63,000 tons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   --Carried 109,200 passengers, including 8,146 children and
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   --Hosted 47 celelbrities, including Olivia de Haviland (who
christened the ship), Buzz Aldrin, Rita Moreno, Gavin McLeod, and
Judge Wapner and Judge Judy.
</P>
<P>
   --Celebrated 157 weddings in ``Hearts and Minds,'' the first and
only seagoing wedding chapel.
</P>
<P>
   --Created 123,000 Baked Alaskas and baked 450,000 loaves of
bread.
</P>
<P>
   --Created 342,000 pizzas and served up 100,000 pounds of pasta.
</P>
<P>
   --Used 5,299,200 eggs, 93,744 pounds of sugar, and 357,304
pounds of flour.
</P>
<P>
   --Washed 59,796 towels 10,045,728 times.
</P>
<P>
   --And supplied 192,480 rolls of toilet paper, measuring 6,840
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Come late November, the Grand Princess will relinquish its title
of world's largest cruise ship to Royal Caribbean's Voyager of the
Seas, and who knows what statistics that 142,000-ton ship will
produce. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of cruises: A Card Player Cruise, with a poker room
staffed by professionals in addition to the regular gambling
opportunities, is scheduled Aug. 15-22 aboard the Carnival
Celebration. The ship will ply the western Caribbean and prices
start at less than $750. The card-playing portion of the cruise is
under the aegis of Barry Shulman, chairman of Card Player magazine.
For more information, call Pita at 702-871-1720. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: In the classic song ``Route 66'' (sung best by Nat
King Cole), 12 communities are mentioned. Give yourself 8.333
points for each one you can name. (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: In Japan, the movie ``Primary Colors'' is called
``Perfect Couple.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``I'm going to Charleston. I want to see if somewhere
there isn't something left in life of charm and grace.'' _ Rhett
Butler in Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum of the month: The 118-year-old Buckhorn Saloon &AMP; Museum has
returned to downtown San Antonio after spending several decades at
the Lone Star Brewery. The museum is filled with oddities, such as
a stuffed two-headed calf, and Western memorabilia, including a bar
that cowboys and cattlemen bellied up to for more than a century.
In all, there are more than 3,300 artifacts and 520 species. For
more information, call 210-247-4000 or visit
www.buckhornmuseum.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: There is a $500 fine for setting off a nuclear
device in Chico, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: It's not always easy to sleep well when traveling.
Here are some tips from Simmons Co., the mattress people, and Dr.
James Maas, a sleep specialist: Avoid caffeine after 2 p.m. and
alcohol within three hours of bedtime; don't eat heavy meals within
five hours of bedtime; keep your hotel room at 65 degrees; and keep
your ``power naps'' to 15-20 minutes. Or, you could read ``Travel
Tidbits'' at bedtime _ that would surely put you to sleep. &QL; 
 &QL; 
He knew: Add the name of Joseph Skatoff of West Yarmouth to those
who knew that Snowflake the albino gorilla lives in the Barcelona
zoo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wooden . . . and wild: This is a summer for roller coasters, with
new thrillers opening up in amusement parks all over the nation.
But one that sounds especially intriguing is Gwazi, which has just
opened at Busch Gardens in Tampa, Fla. This one is a wooden
coaster, just like in the old days, but it's hardly old-fashioned.
Gwazi, you see, is a double coaster. You choose the Lion or Tiger
side, and after rising to the top of each track's 90-foot lift, the
coasters fly by within feet of each other, each at top speed of 50
miles per hour, and achieve a force of up to 3.5Gs. During the 2
1/2-minute tangle, there are six close encounters. For more
information about the park, call 800-4-ADVENTURE or visit
www.buschgardens.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of roller coasters: ``The technology is there now to
build a 200-miles per hour roller coaster,'' says Paul Reuben,
editor of Park World, an amusement industry trade magazine. We
shudder. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Don't get sore: Dairl Johnson was a Navy figher pilot who injured
his back in a training accident in an F-4 Phantom fighter jet. Now
he's CEO of Relax the Back, a company that, among other items,
sells travel products such as a self-inflating lower back support,
an inflatable U-shaped travel neck rest for sleeping on planes, a
compact massage unit, a travel-size support pillow, back support
belts, and an S-shaped ``back nobbler'' for reaching sore spots.
For a catalog, call 800-290-BACK. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The communities, in order of mention, are
Chicago; Los Angeles; St. Louis; Joplin, Mo.; Oklahoma City;
Amarillio, Texas; Gallup, N.M.; Flagstaff, Ariz.; don't forget
Winona, Ariz; Kingman, Ariz.; Barstow, Calif.; and San Bernadino,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
