<HEADLINE>
EUROPE, CHRISTMAS ON SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the war in Kosovo seems over and peace may be at hand, it
has taken its toll on the European cruise season.
</P>
<P>
   Some lines have canceled cruises for lack of passengers, others
are pulling ships back to American shores.
</P>
<P>
   The good news from this is that lines are offering discounts on
remaining cruises in Europe, especially in the Mediterranean area.
The uncertainty over bookings for the remainder of the year has
even brought on a rash of holiday discounts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Orient Lines is offering Greek isles cruises on its
Marco Polo starting at $1,750 a person, and that includes hotel
stays in Athens and Istanbul. Round trip air fare is only $99.
Norwegian Cruise Line is offering 13-day cruises in Scandinavia,
the Greek isles, Black Sea, and trans-Atlantic from $1,529, if
booked by June 30. Air fare is extra.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises is offering savings of up to 61 percent on three
Mediterranean sailings in September. Cunard has 50-percent-off fare
for a second guest, and Windstar Cruises is offer two-for-one rates
through Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   While cruises booked over the Jan. 1 holiday are going for big
bucks, many lines are finding the period before and after to be
lacking customers. Carnival has noted that sailings over the New
Year's holiday have been growing _ especially this year _ while
Christmas cruises have softened. For this reason travelers thinking
of taking a Christmas cruise will find some great bargains.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Dec. 19-26 Carnival cruise on the Elation
begins at $738 a person, while the same cruise Dec. 26-Jan. 2 is
$1,938. Even Crystal Cruises is cutting its fares 25 percent on its
Crystal Harmony sailing to South America.
</P>
<P>
   Holland America is offering discounts of up to 61 percent off
published fares for holiday cruises. The two-for-one and discounted
fares are being offered on the Rotterdam, Veendam, Volendam,
Ryndam, Amsterdam, and Westerdam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Small ships
</P>
<P>
   The LeLevant, an elegant yachtlike cruise ship, will debut at
Boston's Black Falcon Cruise Port Oct. 9. The 90-passenger French
vessel will sail on an eight-day New England-Canada itinerary. The
vessel is designed for off-the-beaten-track routes and to appeal to
those who enjoy active to soft adventures. In addition to tenders,
the vessel carries a fleet of Zodiacs for otherwise inaccessible
beach landings.
</P>
<P>
   American Cruise Lines of Haddam, Conn., is building the
49-passenger American Eagle for cruises along the East Coast. The
ship, being built in Maryland, will offer large staterooms with
picture windows that open and private baths, and large observation
decks. All cruise itineraries will include daily shore excursions.
The company said ports of call will be those with ties to major
events in American history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Back in time
</P>
<P>
   While moviegoers are watching ``Star Wars,'' about a galaxy
``long ago and far away,'' EuroCruises is planning a Sept. 11
cruise to a Mediterranean world of long ago that can be traced in
monuments, cities, landscapes, and seascapes. The 22-day cruise
from Dover, England, is for ``those travelers who would rather look
back at the past millennium or two than ahead to the next one,''
said Bjarne Mikkelsen, EuroCruises president. The cruise can be
taken in 11-day segments, and large discounts are available. The
cruise is on the Black Watch, the former Royal Viking Star. For
information, call 800-661-1119.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the Web
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean's Voyager of the Seas, which will become the
world's largest cruise ship, doesn't sail until November, but
travelers can tour the ship via a new Web page. To visit the ship,
which features such innovative items as a rock climbing wall and
ice-skating rink, click on www.rccl.com/voyageroftheseas. The site
will be constantly updated _ a work in progress until Voyager is
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A promise
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line's newest ship, the Norwegian Sky, now in
the final stages of construction in Germany, is coming with a
guarantee on its maiden voyage. Since many maiden voyages have been
canceled, NCL is offering cruises a money-back guarantee on the
Aug. 9 European maiden voyage. The Sky will be sailing out of
Boston later this fall on cruises to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Sky is NCL's first inaugural in six years and will introduce
new features intended to provide passengers with flexibility to do
what they want when they want to do it, and that includes meals.
``The era of regimentation in cruises is over,'' said Geir Aune,
NCL president. Restaurants on board will offer a variety of
cuisine's, one, the Internet Cafe, will also provide direct access
to the Web by satellite from 10 computer terminals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short cruises
</P>
<P>
   Carnival says it is responding to those who want shorter
cruises. The line said by mid-1999 it will have half its fleet on
itineraries of five or fewer days. Sixteen one- to five-day
itineraries are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four- and five-day itineraries is one featuring the
line's newest ship, the 102,000-ton Carnival Triumph, out of New
York City this summer. Other short cruises sail out of Miami, Los
Angeles, Tampa, and Port Carnaveral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, consumers prefer the flexibility and convenience of
taking several shorter vacations over the course of a year and
Carnival's cruise getaways fit in perfectly with today's
lifestyles,'' said Bob Dickinson, Carnival president. He added that
short cruises also offer added value as they are less costly, serve
as a good ``first-time'' cruise experience, and can easily be
paired with a pre- or post-cruise land vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Other cruise lines offering short cruises include American
Hawaii Cruises, with three- and four-night sailings in the Hawaiian
islands; and Commodore, with two- and five-night cruises from New
Orleans on the Enchanted Capri, including a two-night cruise to
``nowhere'' and a five-night voyage to Mexico. Cunard will have
four-day cruises on its Sea Goddess I in the Virgin Islands in
December and a five-day sailing in the Mediterranean on the Sea
Goddess II in October. Disney Cruise Line, meanwhile, will offer
more of a choice when its second ship, the Disney Wonder, begins
service in August. The line will then offer sailings on Sundays,
Mondays, Thursdays, and Fridays. Norwegian offers special
``weekenders'' on the Leeward from Miami, departing Fridays, and a
four-day Mexico sailing on Mondays. Premier offers three- and
four-night itineraries from Port Canaveral to the Bahamas and two-
night voyages on the SeaBreeze departing New York City every
Friday. Princess will have Love Boat Samplers in September and
October, with Vancouver to San Francisco or Los Angeles
itineraries. Regal has one- to three-night party cruises to nowhere
from New York City through September. And Royal Caribbean
International offers three- and four-night southern Caribbean
cruises from San Juan and three- and four-night voyages from Miami
to the Bahamas, as well as three- and four-night cruises throughout
the year from Los Angels to Catalina Island and Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   For a handy free cruise planner, call Cruise Lines International
Association at 888-927-8473 or visit www.cruising.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Singles
</P>
<P>
   Some cruise lines have relaxed their single-occupancy surcharge.
River Barge Excursions (888-282-1945, www.riverbarge.com) is
entirely eliminating the singles supplement for those who book
summer cruises before June 30. A seven-day cruise from Nashville
starts at $1,480. Orient Lines (800-333-7300, www.orientlines.com)
charges only a 25 percent supplement on its Australia and Africa
cruises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
