</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PROFILE-SWIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER SWIFT'S SOFT IMAGE, A STEELY POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Lieutenant Governor Jane M. Swift is not as nice as
people think she is _ at least that's her own candid assessment.
</P>
<P>
   She was called ``Snow White'' by her colleagues when she entered
the state Senate in 1991 at age 25, the youngest woman ever elected
to the chamber. She has the haircut and the giggle to match the
nickname but the similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   Swift admits to having spontaneous and strategic ``episodes,'' a
handy euphemism for verbal, prosecutorial assaults on
administration staff who blunder. She has a long memory for
political slights and she's always prepared. Anyone who wants her
respect had better be prepared, too.
</P>
<P>
   However, both images have helped this fairy-tale rise to power,
from a working-class family in North Adams to the executive suite
at the State House, all in just over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever one may have thought of the demure-looking,
pregnant Swift during the campaign, six months into the
administration, she has made herself a formidable force.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, while Cellucci was off with Texas
Governor George W. Bush, Swift worked hard to sway legislators
about the virtues of teacher testing, one of the administration's
major policy initiatives. And this week, while Cellucci is on a
trade mission to France and Ireland, Swift will be running
Massachusetts, rolling out statewide crime statistics and filing
health privacy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   She proved her strength early on, when she was responsible for
recruiting Public Safety Secretary Jane Perlov from the New York
City Police Department, sidestepping former Senate colleague James
Jajuga, the expected choice, straining their friendship in order to
bring more women into the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark my words. Within two years, Jane Swift will be the most
powerful and influential person in state government,'' said North
Adams Mayor John Barrett III, a Democrat who created a stir by
endorsing the Republican Swift during the 1996 1st District
congressional campaign against US Representative John Olver.
</P>
<P>
   Those inside and outside the administration say Swift is a true
cogovernor, with a relationship similar to that between Governor
Paul Cellucci and former Governor William F. Weld, when the former
was lieutenant to the latter. In a building where power is asserted
as much as earned, Swift, 34, has done both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're mentally tough . . . particularly in political
situations, you're going to get rolled, day in and day out,'' Swift
says.
</P>
<P>
   Such street talk seems incongruous with a woman from the
Berkshires, whose public image is more aligned with a photograph of
her nuzzling daughter Elizabeth Ruth Hunt, born two weeks before
the last election.
</P>
<P>
   But she's more than a mom, more than second-in-command at the
State House, and her hometown of North Adams is not one of those
bucolic towns that dots western Massachusetts. It was a tough place
to grow up, particularly as part of a competitive family that Swift
says keeps her ``real,'' with a father running a plumbing business
and a mother delaying teacher work until all four children were
grown.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, her hometown mayor, says he endorsed her because, after
initial unease with the young legislator, ``she got more done than
any other senator I've ever dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes working both sides of the aisle in the early
1990s, convincing Weld and then-Senate President William M. Bulger
to squeeze $35 million out of a shrinking state budget to build the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams.
</P>
<P>
   But Swift and others say she was hardly taken seriously when she
began that congressional campaign nearly 50 points behind Olver.
She lost by about 5 points, a relatively close but crushing defeat
for the former Trinity College rugby player who does not like to
lose. And in a year when Republicans were dropping like flies, she
ran the best race in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Olver seems to get cranky just thinking about it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not interested in reliving that,'' the softspoken
congressman snapped. ``It was 2 1/2 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a quick study, her precocious political
instincts are what made at least one member of Cellucci's close
circle of advisers recommend Swift _ largely unknown east of
Springfield _ for lieutenant governor over then-Secretary of
Administration and Finance Charles D. Baker, the man characterized
at the time as being the smartest man on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I not been competitive and had something of the street
fighter instinct, I would not have been successful, nor would have
my brothers and sister,'' Swift said. ``We have all done well for
ourselves, but not because we were born to it.''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds as if she has a chip on her shoulder, or likes to
thumb her nose at the Boston establishment, or wants to make sure
western Massachusetts gets its due, few would argue the point.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her high-profile job, or perhaps because of it, Swift's
forcefulness is not always visible to the public. She is not the
governor. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the stuff to become the first female governor _ no
question about it,'' said Republican insider Ray Howell, who was
Weld's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci is the leader of the state, the one often standing
before microphones and TV cameras, banging his fist on a podium to
emphasize a point, while she stands aside, ready and able to
whisper in the governor's ear answers to technical questions
reporters throw his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy role,'' Swift said. ``I have a great deal
with Paul Cellucci. He listens to me. He allows me to take a
leadership role. If occasionally you're standing in the background
of a picture without knowing what expression to put on your face,
I'm willing to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Often that expression is one of intensity, holding behind her
back rumpled and highlighted notes, all part of her preparedness.
``The frustration,'' she added, ``is more that there are people
trying to judge what your level of influence is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gus Bickford, executive director of the state Democratic Party,
discounts her importance and does not see her as a threat in the
2002 gubernatorial election, should Cellucci end up associated with
a Bush presidency and out of the running locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been invisible,'' Bickford said. ``I'm not too worried
about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind closed doors, however, in morning and weekly meetings,
Swift does not hesitate to speak her mind. While Cellucci is laid
back, Swift is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   At one such gathering recently, Swift tore into an
administration and finance employee who was asked to make a
presentation on the state's arcane but significant School Building
Assistance Program. Feeling the report was not comprehensive
enough, and that more should be done to alter the way the state
handles the program, the lieutenant governor went on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the room who had not witnessed one of her self-described
``episodes'' before sat back aghast, eyes wide open.
</P>
<P>
   As one person who was there described the rant: ``It was
animated and long. She had very strong opinions about this issue
and wasn't shy about sharing them. It was very aggressive. It was
almost prosecutorial. It was reminiscent of Bill Weld, on the
occasion when he would delve into a subject, making very strident
points. She does her homework, she knows the issue. And she
repeatedly raised legitimate concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   When shaken attendees filed out of the room, Swift pulled aside
the administration and finance staff member and told her not to
take any of it personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes my toughness or my temper are normal emotional
reactions to situations that dovetail with my personality,'' Swift
reflected. ``There are also times when pitching a fit is a very
strategic decision. In the Senate I used to joke with my staff that
I haven't eaten a Cabinet secretary for lunch lately and perhaps
they were forgetting I could be very nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   She attributes the toughness to her mother's Italian blood, on
having two older brothers and from playing sports in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't back away from confrontation . . . and sometimes
people's feelings can be hurt by that,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   However, a softer side, one with a sense of humor, emerged last
week in an incident that also shows the comfort level Swift has
with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   When the heat forced nonessential government workers home, she
told a TV reporter that Cellucci was included in that group. The
governor says he roared with laughter at the joke when he caught
the clip on television later that night.
</P>
<P>
   Some have been waiting for Swift's ``other side'' to come to the
fore, post-pregnancy and post-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used the baby in every way possible for her benefit''
during the campaign, said one Democrat who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Swift bristles at this observation, which she has heard before.
``No one eight months pregnant wants to have TV cameras following
her around,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she does admit that being a mother, even an expectant
one, allowed her to talk about children's issues more convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also care deeply about kids. This isn't the side of me that
throws the F word around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
