<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI IS NO SURE BET 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was not quite three years ago. On a balmy,
moonlit night, I found myself gazing out at the rolling waves of
the Pacific from the promenade deck of the elegant Hotel del
Coronado in San Diego. Behind me, music blared and Republicans
boogied with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Castro, Gov. George Pataki's parks commissioner, was
in the process of earning formal recognition as Best Dancer in the
New York's delegation to the 1996 Republican National Convention.
That's when I found myself chatting with a pleasant, dark-haired
guy in a golf shirt.
</P>
<P>
   I'm Rick Lazio, he told me. I asked him what he was doing at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said, ``I'm a member of Congress from Long Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that surprised me. The framers of the U.S. Constitution
specified that you have to be 25 years old to serve in Congress.
This guy appeared to have barely made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I know now, Lazio is 41. Few people who don't live on
Long Island know who he is. But it's entirely possible that it'll
be him _ not New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ who'll face
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton next year in her race to
represent New York in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still isn't a sure thing to run, but she's a 99 percent
bet. Giuliani hasn't formally announced either, but he's
overwhelmingly likely to jump in. Most national media attention has
focused on what a cheerfully bloody contest a Clinton-Giuliani
matchup would be. And it would be, too _ King Kong meets Ms.
Godzilla.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that scenario is that Giuliani seems likely to
face a primary challenge next year from Lazio, and the outcome of a
clash between these two guys is hardly a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Giuliani's name is better known than Lazio's. But New York
City, Giuliani's base, contains only one in 12 of the Empire
State's Republican voters, and Lazio can be expected to buy name
recognition wherever he doesn't have it now through an extensive
and expensive advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lazio has the support of some serious players in the
party. It seems obvious, although not stated openly, that he would
be the choice of Pataki, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and the Lauder
family. That's Lauder as in Estee Lauder, the huge cosmetics
company. The Lauders have warehouses just for thousand dollar
bills. You can bet that Lazio would have access to a hefty share of
that cash.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lazio is the candidate of powerful Nassau County GOP chief
Joe Mondello and of Mike Long, who heads this state's Conservative
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The ties here are complicated and tight. The governor's wife has
a cushy job with the Lauder family. Long's daughter has a nice job
in the Pataki administration. Everybody here is linked to somebody
else in some intensely personal way, and Lazio would benefit
immensely from all that.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Republican Party is composed heavily of
Italian-Americans. In a primary fight, Giuliani would have no
ethnicity advantage over Lazio. As a creature of the city, Giuliani
would have no advantage in the suburbs or upstate over a
congressman from the quintessential New York City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Giuliani has been a uniquely pugnacious mayor. His
campaign slogan probably will be, ``Hey, are you looking at ME?''
Just in doing his highly visible, difficult job, the mayor has made
enemies who don't know enough about Lazio to dislike him.
</P>
<P>
   So despite what you're seeing on network television, it's not
inconceivable that the candidate who'll eventually end up duking it
out with Clinton next year won't be Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it could be the smiling, boyish-looking guy I met on
that promenade deck that night in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
