<HEADLINE>
MEXICO MODIFIES BORDER FEE THAT BEGINS JULY 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Mexican officials are easing the rules on the new
$15 fee all visitors to the interior of Mexico must pay beginning
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   All foreign nationals, including children who travel beyond the
15-mile-deep border zone, are subject to the fee.
</P>
<P>
   When the fee first came to light in February, officials said it
would apply to each visit. But under the rules announced Monday by
the Mexican consul general in San Antonio, Carlos Sada, tourists
will only have to pay the fee once every six months. Non-Mexican
business travelers will pay the fee every 30 days, Sada said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said the new rules would allay fears of financial
burdens on travelers, transportation company officials said they
were concerned about the effect of the fee on businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For airline passengers, the fee will be added to the price of
each ticket. Auto and bus passengers must pay the fee and have
their visas stamped at a Mexican bank in a border city. The visas
will be checked for a payment stamp at Mexico's interior
checkpoints, usually about 15 miles from each border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners driving into Mexico already must stop at an auto
registration station in a border city to pay a long-standing $12
fee before taking a motor vehicle into the interior. The $15 fee
will be collected in addition to that.
</P>
<P>
   Sada said the 24-hour auto registration stations, such as the
one in Nuevo Laredo, operate in conjunction with Mexican banks to
collect the auto fees. Visitors can pay the $15 fee at those banks
or at any other bank in the border cities, Sada said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are considering extending service hours to accommodate
weekend travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles already must stop twice after crossing into Mexico,
once in the border city to obtain the visa and/or auto registration
and once at the interior checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Sada said frequent visitors must keep their visas _ often called
tourist cards _ to show the $15 fee stamp when re-entering Mexico
by land or plane.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to cities along the border will not pay the fee if
their stay does not exceed 72 hours. That exemption also applies to
tourists entering Mexico from cruise ships for visits lasting fewer
than 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican citizens and Mexican-born U.S. citizens or resident
aliens who qualify for Mexican nationality will not be subject to
the fee. Mexican passports also will be accepted as proof of
nationality at the border to be exempt from the fee, Sada said.
</P>
<P>
   The government expects to collect $120 million from the fee
annually. About half of that will be used internationally to
promote tourism. Mexico is the seventh-top tourism destination in
the world, Sada said.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates are that 8 million foreign visitors entering Mexico
each year will pay the fee.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining funds will be used to upgrade immigration stations
and services at the border and at airports, and for other services
to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Sada said the fee would not create a financial hardship on
visitors because of the six-month open period for tourists and
30-day period for business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public was upset at first because no one knew then how it
would work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But businesses tied to Mexico travel remained concerned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the effect yet,'' said Juan Sanchez, the San
Antonio office manager of McAllen-based Sanborn's Mexican Insurance
Service, which sells auto insurance for Mexican travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mulet, the regional sales manager for Mexicana Airlines in
San Antonio, expressed concern over his airline's role in
collecting the fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people won't need to pay, so we will have to ask
questions beyond what airlines should do to qualify the passengers.
On the phone, that is hard to do,'' Mulet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the fee is going to hurt. We don't know for how
long, whether it is four months or six months. It is starting at
the beginning of the high-travel season,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
