<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRIMES-BYSTANDER-BOS &LR;      06-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIMES-BYSTANDER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 PROPOSED SAMARITAN LAW COMES UNDER FIRE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one denies what college student David Cash Jr.
did or did not do was deplorable. No one disputes that he probably
could have prevented 7-year-old Sherrice Iverson's death in a
Nevada casino restroom stall.
</P>
<P>
   All Cash had to do was tell casino security. But he didn't.
Instead he walked out of the bathroom as his best friend began
assaulting the girl. He kept quiet even after Jeremy Strohmeyer
confessed the murder to him.
</P>
<P>
   Cash's choice that day in May 1997 _ and his boasts afterward
that his newfound notoriety helped him meet women _ sickened
parents everywhere and spurred state and federal legislators to try
to hold adults accountable if they witnessed certain crimes against
children. Many legislators want to make inaction a crime, too, as
Nevada did recently.
</P>
<P>
   But Cash has found some unlikely allies in California, where he
still attends the state university in Berkeley and where he and
Iverson both grew up. In a rare display of unity, defense attorneys
and prosecutors find themselves on the same side of a proposed
state law. They're against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a horrible case, to have someone like David Cash come
out in public and say, `It's not my mother, it's not my sister, who
cares?' '' said David LaBahn, deputy director of the California
District Attorneys Association. ``But unless you have a very clear
law, there are going to be unintended consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Barry Broad, legislative advocate for the California
Public Defenders Association: ``There's an old statement that bad
facts make bad law. The corollary is that outrageous cases that
offend people can make for dangerous legislative activity.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBahn and Broad said they fear the California bill known as the
``Sherrice Iverson Child Protection Act'' would lead witnesses who
do not come forward promptly to demand immunity from prosecution in
exchange for their testimony. Had Strohmeyer not pleaded guilty to
kidnapping, sexual assault, and murder, Cash might well have won
his freedom under the proposed statute by agreeing to take the
witness stand, they said.
</P>
<P>
   It is even more problematic, defense attorneys and prosecutors
say, that credible testimony could be tainted in jurors' eyes if it
appears witnesses were intimidated, either by police or by their
own fear of prosecution. The California bill, which recently passed
the Senate on a bipartisan vote of 28-0 and is expected to win
approval in the state Assembly, would make failure to report
certain crimes against children 14 years old and younger a
misdemeanor punishable by six months in jail, a $5,000 fine, or
both.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada, where witnesses now have 24 hours to report their
suspicions that a child under 12 is being sexually or physically
abused, threatens similar jail time and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nevada, however, California also would exempt close
relatives from prosecution, an exemption that opponents of the bill
said would water it down to the point of uselessness. For example,
spouses would not be required to report each other, regardless of
what they witnessed. Grandparents would also be exempt. But,
opponents note, much of the abuse and sexual crimes against
children is committed by family members.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses who feared for their safety would also be released
from the reporting requirements, which mimic those already in place
for such professionals as teachers and medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you exempt family members, it seems to me you exempt a lot
of the people to whom a bill like this should be directed, if in
fact there should be a bill like this,'' said Mary Broderick,
executive director of California Attorneys for Criminal Justice.
``But you can't create a conscience in somebody by making it a
crime to do something or not to do something. I'm not sure even if
the law had been on the books when Sherrice Iverson was killed that
it would have changed David Cash's behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of more child-protection laws, however, argued that
witnesses might think twice before walking away from a crime
without contacting police, although none of the laws would require
direct intervention that might put an observer at risk.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in Nevada, Sherrice Iverson's family and friends
have lobbied heavily for the California legislation, sponsored by
state Senator Tom Hayden. The family is also suing the Primadonna
casino, about 40 miles south of Las Vegas, where Leroy Iverson was
playing the slot machines at 3 a.m. while his son and daughter
played in the building unsupervised.
</P>
<P>
   Najee Ali, executive director of the Sherrice Iverson Justice
Campaign, stressed that neither the California nor Nevada laws
would enforce morality, only accountability. Still, he conceded
such laws go counter to the tradition of not forcing citizens to
become informants against their will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been attacked from day one, because it really is
encroaching on someone's civil liberties, that you have the right
not to be involved if you don't want to be involved in something. .
. .'' said Ali. ``If you see a child being sexually assaulted or
violently attacked, you should at least alert the authorities. It's
the least you should have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the organizations representing prosecutors and defense
attorneys in California insisted the legislation would only hamper
their cases. If the bill passes and is signed into law by Governor
Gray Davis, both sides said, witnesses worried about their own
prosecution would be entitled to plead self-incrimination to avoid
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Said Broad, ``This is one of those issues where no one doubts
the sincerity of the people pushing it. It's a question of whether
it's a good idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
