<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-PRINCIPAL-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PRINCIPAL HEADS TO SCHOOL THAT ONCE BARRED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECILIA BALLI  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As a student, John Simpson was not allowed to
enter Parish High School in Selma, Ala., because of his skin color.
Soon, though, the retired Air Force training instructor will return
to what is now Selma High School to become its principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ironic that I'm going back to the high school that I
wasn't able to attend,'' said Simpson, 47, the summer school
principal at Southwest High School in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's why I decided to take that job, because I knew that
there was a force that I didn't understand just yet that was
driving me back home. Maybe I'll understand it in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Selma to give back to the community was a recurring
topic of conversation at high school class reunions. But, Simpson
said, he never thought he would be the one to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He left the city 29 years ago, after spending his youth living
the scarring reality of racial segregation and raising his
consciousness by fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, he sat through mass organizational church
meetings and marched in protests with other supporters of the 1960s
civil rights movement. He and other protesters were once forced
onto a bus with a cow prod. They spent the night ``crowded like
sardines'' in a jail with overflowing commodes until they were
bailed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That experience is the reason I know I am what I am today,
because I could never see myself in jail again. Never,'' Simpson
said. ``The experience was just horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   As Simpson finished the seventh grade, Selma was the site of
Bloody Sunday, the day in May 1965 when state troopers and the
police attacked and brutally beat 2,000 demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Racism also lingered in less historically significant moments.
For Simpson, what remains the most stark reminder of his schooling
at the all-black Hudson High School _ what he calls a
``second-rate'' education _ are the textbooks that are outdated.
</P>
<P>
   He could not fully shed his legacy in Selma even as he joined
the Air Force. While stationed at Mountain Home Air Force Base in
Idaho, a staff sergeant and mentor once took Simpson to his house
for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family sat around the table staring at me,'' Simpson said.
``And he told me, `Sorry, but this is the first black person
they've seen in their lives in color.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Simpson was assigned to Lackland Air Force Base in San
Antonio, then he spent several years at bases overseas. He returned
to Lackland in 1982, and retired from the Air Force nine years
later. At that point, he entered Southwest Texas State University
to earn a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest High School Assistant Principal Rudy Mora encouraged
Simpson, his neighbor, to try teaching, something he had practiced
throughout his time with the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Working toward his teaching certificate and a master's degree in
educational administration on week nights and weekends, Simpson
joined Southwest as a history, government, sociology and world
geography teacher. He later worked with students considered to be
in danger of dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``To become a historian or history teacher and tell these
stories (of the Civil Rights Movement) to my students, it's
incredible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson was tapped as a potential candidate for the Selma High
School position while he was home for a funeral. He was hired,
Selma City School System Superintendent James Carter said, because
of his intellect, his communication skills and his vision for the
school.
</P>
<P>
   He will be the fourth black principal of Selma High School, but
the first who attended the city's all-black public high school.
Selma desegregate its schools in 1970, the year after Simpson
graduated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took them that long,'' Simpson said, referring to the 1954
court mandate that schools be integrated. ``They did everything in
their power to keep the schools segregated, and it wasn't just
there in Selma. It was all over the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 95 percent of Selma High School's 1,200 students
are black, Carter said, due largely to white movement away from the
city.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the school's legacy, Simpson faces the challenge of
helping create a Selma High School that not only is diverse and
tolerant, but one that students want to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the main thing is to get the students to believe
in themselves,'' he said. ``My challenge would be to get those kids
that are fleeing from the school _ white flight, black flight _ to
come back to the school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
