<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY REVEALS GAINS, LOSSES OF MINORITY PROFESSIONALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In 1997, after more than a dozen years in Boston, attorney
Carleasa Coates left a position as partner at a prestigious law
firm to work in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Coates says she left for social and professional reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Software consultant Jim Collier, by contrast, was wooed away by
a California company, which offered him a position as vice
president of product development.
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of Coates and Collier are not coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of African-American professionals in Boston
has increased to 7,000 and is now growing at a rate of 3.5 percent
per year, many minorities in senior positions are leaving the area.
</P>
<P>
   A study released last week by The Partnership, a nonprofit
organization that helps companies retain minority professionals,
found that the number of entry or junior level African-American
employees at local companies grew 31 percent between 1991 and 1996.
At the same time, there was a 5 percent decline in black senior
level officials and managers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, only 18 of Greater Boston's top 100 firms had
minority officers as of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``While certain Boston industries and companies show measurable
progress in hiring African-American professionals, others struggle
to keep pace and may even show more pronounced losses than the
average levels of decline,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said the city had changed significantly over the
last 20 years, but that many minority professionals continue to
have a negative image of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Benaree Wiley, president and chief executive of The Partnership,
hopes the study will spur debate and lead to some viable solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to see growth among the number of entry-level
professionals here because the city is an academic center and there
are many, many schools,'' said Wiley. ``What concerns us is that
senior professionals are leaving, and we are not sure why.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why she left, Coates didn't mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a ceiling there, and you bump up against
it fairly quickly,'' she said. ``Even if you get into the rarified
air between the ceiling and nirvana, it is isolating because you
are probably the only one there. In 1996, I was the only black
female partner in the top five law firms in the city. That is a
problem, to look around and not see anyone like you, and then to
wonder why.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Collier, however, and a different picture emerges. A
specialist in a rapidly changing field, he credited The Partnership
and a former employer, Lotus Development Corp., with helping him
adjust to the city. And, he said, he would have remained in Boston
if he had not been offered a more lucrative job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston, there is no pretense,'' he said. ``So groups like
The Partnership are focused, steadfastly focused. They understand
that there is a need for the organization and they know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley noted the reasons for the decline could be as diverse as
the people themselves. ``Boston has many schools and could be a
great training ground for young professionals. So, the good news
may be that companies in other cities recognize the talent and are
wooing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we also know that what happens between 7
p.m. and 7 a.m. is important to being able to survive in a city,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coates, for example, noted that although The Partnership helped
her network with other African-American professionals, there were
few social clubs where minorities could meet.
</P>
<P>
   Collier, meanwhile, said the friends he met through the network
helped him develop close ties that sustained him during his first
few years in the city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While economic growth and increased competition have created an
environment ripe for mergers and acquisitions, the price has been
heavy for American workers, reports Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas
Inc., a Chicago outplacement firm. One out of nine job cuts in the
last four years occurred because of such corporate marriages, the
firm said.
</P>
<P>
   In May, 2,856 jobs were cut from US company payrolls because of
acquisitions or mergers, bringing the total to 32,606 job cuts
since 1995. ``Companies are quicker than ever to form an alliance
if it will help them maximize their potential earnings,'' says
Challenger's chief executive, John A. Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Louis Harris and Associates found that 71 percent of
people with disabilities who are of working age are unemployed, 5
percentage points more than in 1986, when the study was first
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments? Contact Diane E. Lewis at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
