<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST TRAVEL PERKS COULD SEND YOU PACKING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (note: accent over ``e'' in crudites and canapes; ylang-ylang and
eucalyptus citriodora are cq;) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when I was beginning to think travel promotions couldn't
get any more outlandish or innovative ...
</P>
<P>
   _ If guests at Ritz-Carlton hotels in Hong Kong, Singapore,
Kuala Lumpur and Sydney are singing ``Splish, splash, I was taking
a bath'' with a flair, it's because those establishments have
introduced new menus.
</P>
<P>
   Not dinner menus. Bath menus.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Kong offers a selection of eight tub
soaks created with aromatherapy bath oils and designed to _ take
your pick _ relax, cure, pamper or rejuvenate.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the best part: Each is prepared and drawn by a butler.
</P>
<P>
   Care for the ``Evening Out'' bath? According to the menu,
peppermint, rosemary and juniper invigorate and stimulate the body
and mind; guests will feel ``energized to party.'' Leaving nothing
to chance, the ``natural uplifting qualities of this bath'' are
enhanced by a glass of champagne and strawberries dipped in
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the ``Post-Workout Reliever'' is in order. This bath
of marjoram, lavender and geranium is followed by a one-hour
massage, a pot of tea and a platter of freshly prepared sushi. (No,
I'm not making this up.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ladies' Bath'' is scented with geranium and melissa
essence, with lavender to rub on the temples, and accompanied by a
glass of freshly squeezed carrot, watermelon, pineapple or
grapefruit juice and a selection of crudites.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Gentleman's Bath,'' by contrast, is ``spiced with the
woody and earthy scents of vetiver, known for its calming and
relaxing effects.'' It comes with a fine cigar, a glass of cognac
and a plate of lobster canapes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no word on whether ladies can trade their carrot juice
and crudites for cognac and lobster.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Honeymooners' Bath'' is prepared by candlelight and
features patchouli, jasmine, ylang-ylang and rose petals scattered
in the tub. The couple also receives champagne, strawberries with
brown sugar and cream, and a dozen red roses.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is the ``Flu Fighter,'' a ``medicinal blend of
eucalyptus citriodora, tea tree and ginger'' accompanied by a hot
toddy of whiskey, lemon and honey.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour's notice, a butler will arrive 15 minutes before
the desired bathing time to handle all preparations (and, I hope,
provide a second or third hot toddy if the, er, flu is serious). Or
arrangements can be made to ensure that a bath is ready upon
check-in.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $26-$38.50 (plus 10 percent service) in U.S.
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Other Ritz-Carltons in the Asia-Pacific region apply individual
touches to their bath menus. ``Ladies Bath'' participants at Kuala
Lumpur, for example, soak in exotic milk with lavender. And a
``Revitalizing Salt Bath'' is formulated with Dead Sea salt
material.
</P>
<P>
   By summer's end, all nine of the chain's Asia-Pacific properties
will offer bath menus reflecting their locations and cultures.
Baths in Bali will include essences from tropical flowers; ginseng
canapes will tempt bathers in Seoul; and Japanese tea will be
served tubside in Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent can make reservations (though I'd like to see the
expression on the agent's face when you relay your bath requests).
Or call 800-241-3333.
</P>
<P>
   _ TravelLite, an Illinois-based company, offers not a butler but
a Virtual Bellhop for travelers weary of hauling luggage through
airports or enduring long waits at baggage carousels.
</P>
<P>
   For fees that begin at $65, the ``bellhop'' will come to your
home, office or college dormitory on a specified date, pick up your
bags and make certain they are waiting at a hotel or other
destination prior to your arrival.
</P>
<P>
   To get the cheapest fares, packing early is essential: That $65
price tag is for guaranteed three-day shipping of up to two bags
that weigh a maximum 50 pounds combined. Next-day and second-day
air service are available for a higher tariff. The more bags you
ship, the more you pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtual Bellhop handles golf clubs, skis, computers and
business files, too. For information and a price list, access
www.virtualbellhop.com on the Internet or call 877-235-5467.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion for those who use the three-day service: You may
want to pack an iron to get the wrinkles out of that dress or
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'll leave you with this gem: Gatorland, an Orlando, Fla.,
attraction celebrating its 50th birthday, has launched a contest in
which 10 entrants will ``win'' the opportunity to ``wrestle hungry
alligators.'' Training with an experienced alligator wrestler is
included.
</P>
<P>
   Gator wrestling is only the second prize. First prize is a
four-day Florida vacation, including air fare, for a family of
four; 90 third prizes provide free park admission for two people.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to enter: Find your favorite photograph, postcard or
souvenir commemorating the park's exhibits over the past
half-century. Send it (or a color copy of the photo/postcard or a
snapshot of the souvenir) to Gatorland's 50 Years of Great Tales,
14501 S. Orange Blossom Trail, Orlando, Fla. 32837, Attention:
Birthday Bash. Include your name, address, phone number, a
description of the entry (no more than 50 words) and the year it
represents. All entries must be postmarked by Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, access www.gatorland.com on the Internet
or call 800-393-JAWS.
</P>
<P>
   And if you win but don't fancy grabbing gators, not to worry:
You can choose instead to spend a day with the Gatorland Zoo
curator enjoying a variety of other animals.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't request an ``Alligator Bath'' at the Ritz-Carlton,
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
