<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T SLAM THE DOOR ON YOUR WAY OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You and your friends probably get out of taxis, leave theaters,
abandon ships (when necessary), quit jobs; exit is rarely the verb
of choice for the person in the street. So why, wonders Betsy
Cazden, is it all around us? ``The suspect exited the vehicle,''
say the police; flight attendants, adding neologism to euphemism,
tell us to reference the card in the seat pocket so we'll know how
to exit in an emergency. Is this ``another example of military or
quasi-military jargon working its way into civilian life?'' asks
Cazden.
</P>
<P>
   Could be, but journalists might well be contributing to the
plethora of exits. There's a whole collection of words you wouldn't
overhear in a lifetime of eavesdropping _ amid, atop, fled, coif,
doff _ that journalists are keeping alive, often simply because
they're short. ``Serbs exit Kosovo'' trumps leave and depart and
their even longer synonyms in a spot (say, a headline) where every
letter counts.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with exit, historically
speaking; Latin had both the verb exit _ ``he/she/it leaves'' _ and
the noun exitus, long before English was born. And exit, along with
its plural, exeunt (``they leave''), was a stage direction as early
as 1538. (Perhaps its most memorable appearance comes in ``The
Winter's Tale,'' where Shakespeare forces a character to ``Exit,
pursued by a bear.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, the noun seems natural _ ``I raced for the exit'' is
colloquial English _ while the verb (``I exited as fast as I
could'') sounds pretentious. Maybe that's because doors and
directional arrows all around us are labeled ``exit,'' subliminally
persuading us that the noun is the standard word for what the Brits
sometimes label ``way out.'' (Subliminally would be the appropriate
route, too: The word comes from Latin for ``below the threshold,''
in this case the threshold of the door to consciousness.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the transitive exit that annoys Cazden is relatively
recent; the verb was used without an object, according to the
Oxford English Dictionary, from 1607 till this century. In 1844, it
was still ``She exited from the chamber,'' not ``She exited the
chamber.'' Only in 1976 do we find the plainly transitive ``he
exited the freeway,'' an Americanism that may well have been
inspired by our speedier travel on those lengthening freeways.
</P>
<P>
   This exit may be a recent arrival, but it's firmly entrenched
now, thanks to our computers. Just as access marched in unopposed
the moment we needed to talk about getting into files, exiting a
program was instantly standard usage. That doesn't mean we're
doomed to extend the usage and begin exiting our houses or cars or
buses (or accessing them, either); plenty of insider lingo stays
corralled in its own pen. The transitive exit could well remain a
verb for drivers, computer users, police officers _ and, of course,
journalists in need of a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   Worth the wait
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I have a difference of opinion on the
expression wait on,'' writes Ellen Garvey. ``I find it delightful
if he offers to wait on me in the context of bringing me a cup of
coffee or slice of toast. But my skin crawls when he announces that
he'll wait on me when I'm running a bit late. . . . Am I being
overly sensitive?''
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is yes, according to the Merriam-Webster usage
experts, who offer a thorough treatment of the debate. Wait for vs.
wait on may have begun as a regional difference _ Northerners used
for, Southerners on _ but both forms are widespread now, says M-W's
English Usage. Wait for is more common, and avoids confusion with
what waitpersons do, but it has no other claims to superiority.
</P>
<P>
   Tastes in such two-part verbs often vary from place to place; in
my native Midwest, we baby-sat for the neighbors' children;
Bostonians seem to baby-sit them. The Eastern version seems to
suggest sitting on the kids _ sometimes a useful tactic _ but
there's logic to it, too; it's the parents, after all, you are
baby-sitting for. Similarly, while we debate different from vs.
different than, Britons often say different to. (Forget that logic
I just mentioned; convention is everything in this realm.)
</P>
<P>
   In any case, if you've got a husband who thinks you're worth
waiting on and waiting for, the only reasonable conclusion is vive
la difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Word appears every other week through summer. Write Jan
Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
