<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-22 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S MISSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Who da thunk it?
</P>
<P>
   The person who has bought into the crackpot notion that next
year's Senate race here is some grand national crusade is not
Hillary Rodham Clinton. It's Mayor Rudy Giuliani, whose second-term
egomania continues to obscure his first-term problem-solving to
such an extent that he has created a small opening for a
potentially serious Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani publicly anticipates some magical Ken Starr report that
may turn out to be Godot; he screams ``carbetbagger'' to the wind;
and joins in the ``why is she doing this?'' psychobabble. Little
things _ education, health care, transportation, and housing _ he
leaves to Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In just his latest myopic goof, Giuliani went down to Washington
last week to raise serious national money, and proceeded to step
all over his message by refusing to commit himself to serving a
full, six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, meanwhile, dared to be boring and made plans for a
multiday swing through upstate New York. And for Representative
Rick Lazio, who sounds every day like a plausible challenger to
Giuliani's presumed lock on the GOP nomination, it was another
chance to say ``I told you so.''Lazio has not only taken the pledge
conspicuously, he also regularly taunts Giuliani for seeking but a
``temporary perch'' in the Senate, which just so happens to be one
of the points the mayor makes about Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There has been so much babble about this nascent campaign that
the fundamentals have been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, what's actually happened is that Mrs. Clinton has
cleared the Democratic field. Assuming she keeps running, she is
the nominee, and if she's smart (another given), she'll use her
time introducing herself and talking about the everyday concerns of
voters, shedding the podium for as much retail campaigning as
security concerns will allow, and ignoring the national press.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, however, has yet to clear the Republican field, and
his tactic of acting as if he has only adds to his imperious image
and makes that grubby task more difficult. The mayor is not George
W. Bush. And not clearing the field could mean a hard-fought
primary campaign lasting all the way into September of next year,
less than two months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Republican Party here remains a vipers' nest
of competing ambitions and ideologies. The most personal feud is
between Giuliani and defeated Senator Al D'Amato and his
considerable army of bitter henchmen.It started with Giuliani's
endorsement of Democrat Mario Cuomo for reelection five years ago.
The fact that D'Amato's protege, George Pataki, not only won but
has gone on to become as nationally ambitious as Giuliani only
complicates things.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Republicans here say Pataki gave more than casual
consideration to running for the Senate himself. And instead of
cracking heads to clear the field, several of his people are
encouraging Lazio. Still others are pushing an even darker horse,
Representative Peter King, whose conservatism includes a
right-to-life platform Lazio and Giuliani reject.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is a credible Republican. He came out of Long Island's
South Shore to whip a Democratic big shot and Al Gore buddy, Tom
Downey, as the GOP was taking over Congress. He is well-liked, and
has a genuine legislative credit from his bipartisan aproach to
last year's successful reform of public housing programs.But he is
also a combative conservative, a Newt Gingrich company commander
during the 1995 budget wars and a solid proimpeachment vote last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, he has more going for him than Giuliani's
Mario Cuomo apostasy. The best example is his suburbanite hatred
for a now-repealed tax on commuters that the mayor once
supported.From Long Island to Westchester to Rockland, taxes are
the bread and butter of Republican politics, and the issue gives
Lazio potential traction in the counties that decide GOP primaries,
often in favor of the more conservative candidate. Upstate,
traditional resentment of New York City counts even more, and in a
primary the city remains a lousy Republican base.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio still has a long way to go, but money will not be a
problem, and neither will the work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   In the national media frenzy over this race, the historical
point of reference is Robert Kennedy's uphill conquest of Kenneth
Keating here 35 years ago _ when a young collegian named Giuliani
helped defuse the carpetbagger issue by writing about the state's
first senator, Rufus King, who moved here from Massachusetts just
before his election in 1792.
</P>
<P>
   But savvy Republicans worry about 1970 and 1980, when two
liberal Republican Senators (Charles Goodell and Jacob Javits) lost
primaries to conservatives (James Buckley and D'Amato), who won in
November because their GOP foes hung around on the once-legitimate
Liberal Party line and split the left.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they see a similar problem on the right, with further
chances for ballot mischief open to the Conservative Party (which
likes Lazio) and the right-To-lifers.
</P>
<P>
   Before this race gets real, two points: The Republicans don't
have their act together; and the ``hate Hillary'' sentiment either
knocks her out of the race soon, or her issue profile will make her
look a lot like, well, a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICHEST-US-TOWNS-WORT     06-22 2558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHEST-US-TOWNS-WORTH-800&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S TOP 250 POSH REAL-ESTATE SPOTS  
  
 (NOTE: SEE SEPARATE STORY _ BC-250-RICHEST-TOWNS-WORTH _ FOR
TALLY)  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SPECIAL ATTN: Calif., Colo., Conn., Fla., Ill.)   (This ``separate buy'' financial story _ an ranking of America's
wealthiest communities _ is from the June issue of ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS FOUR EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 800 (75 WORDS),
1,025 (525), 1,700 (175) AND 2,100 (150). STORY CAN STAND IN 2,100
WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 2,250.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By LOCH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the land of the wealthy, dirt is king.
</P>
<P>
   Take a stroll through Jupiter Island, Fla., for instance. A
one-acre plot of land with 150 feet of waterfront fetches between
$2 million and $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The house sitting on that dirt might be palatial, but that
hardly matters: On this island of exclusivity, houses come and go
with alarming speed. ``There are a number of houses going up right
now, and every single one of them will eventually be knocked
down,'' says Gene Albarelle, a local broker who deals in high-end
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a speculator paid $1.65 million for an acre of ground
with a five-bedroom house on it. The house was immediately torn
down, and though its replacement has not yet been finished, the
owner is now asking $4.4 million for this small parcel of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jupiter Island is prime territory, removed by 574
feet of bridge from the strip-malled Florida mainland and situated
just 20 miles north of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Jupiter Island is also the number-one town on WORTH's
annual list of America's wealthiest enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was number two, right behind Aspen, Colo.; in
previous years it has ranked seventh and ninth. In other words,
Jupiter Island is a well-credentialed top town.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the winter residence of some of the oldest names in
American business (Field, Doubleday, Ford) as well as some of the
newest, like Chuck Curcio, founder of Tire Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   His former home, a six-bedroom, 16,000-square-foot behemoth on
five acres with waterfront, sold in April for $12.5 million; the
buyer was Stephen Garofalo, CEO of Metromedia Fiber Network
Services, who paid another $4.2 million for an adjacent piece of
property that Curcio also owned.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Island ranks number one on this year's list because its
median home sales price for 1997 and 1998 combined was $1.7
million, the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In compiling the list, we gathered data as we have for the past
three years: through public records and multiple-listing services
and with the help of Prudential Real Estate agents and brokers
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   We found (no surprise) that Americans are buying houses as never
before: 1998 was a record year for existing-home sales; some 4.78
million houses changed hands, according to the National Association
of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of newly constructed single-family homes reached levels
not seen since 1977, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, and the
nation's home-ownership rate soared to a new high of 66.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many factors driving our housing market _ it's
hard to list all of them,'' says Kory Bockman, an economist with
NAR. ``We have a tremendous job market right now, unemployment is
near historical lows, consumer confidence is high, the stock market
is strong, oil prices are low...The list just goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the appreciation in the median home price last year
outstripped inflation by 3.6 percentage points. (The median home
price for our entire list of 250 towns is $504,144, an increase of
13.3 percent over last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, according to NAR data, the West showed the greatest
existing-home-price appreciation: 7.23 percent, followed closely by
the Midwest, with 7.20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gains were especially high around hubs for the high-tech
industry. Economist Bockman says, ``I think the strength of the
high-tech industry may be the most important driving factor in the
high-end market right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The California towns of Atherton (No. 3), Woodside (No. 12), and
Palo Alto (No. 89) moved up on our list from last year, as did the
Seattle suburbs of Medina (No. 48), Yarrow Point (No. 50), and
Mercer Island (No. 157).
</P>
<P>
   Because of stock options and bonuses, a remarkable number of
home purchases at the very highest end are increasingly transacted
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Zinn, an entrepreneur who's in the process of starting a
manufactured-housing company, says she achieved peace of mind when
she and her husband, Tim, paid cash for a $1.8 million,
7,000-square-foot Mediterranean-style house in Rancho Santa Fe,
Calif. (No. 10).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in having a mortgage,'' she says. ``I like to
think that whatever happens, my home is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinn may sound a bit like Scarlett O'Hara surveying Tara _
though in the current housing market, Tara would be a teardown and
the land would be subdivided into miniature ``estates.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Zinns have 2.5 acres, which isn't bad these days. In fact,
Zinn says, ``we have total privacy, because the property is high up
and protected by trees. We could have a whole nudist colony in the
backyard, and no one would know'' _ a plot, perhaps, for ``Gone
With the Wind, Part IV.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zinns weren't the only high-end cash buyers in Rancho Santa
Fe, an expensive suburb just 25 miles north of San Diego. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to analyst John Karevoll at Acxiom/DataQuick, a
national real-estate research firm in La Jolla, Calif. (No. 83),
Rancho Santa Fe was the greenest town in the Golden State last
year: 46.1 percent of all homes sold there were bought with cash.
</P>
<P>
   In another wealthy spot _ Palm Beach, Fla. (No. 26) _ 52 percent
of the homes sold in 1998 were paid for in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, cash purchases are often made in wealthy
markets like Southern California, Colorado, and Florida, which
attract the middle-aged and successful (who are looking for a
second home) and retirees (who arrive with decades' worth of
accumulated wealth).
</P>
<P>
   The Zinns, for instance, spend part of the year in their
turn-of-the-century brownstone in Chicago's Lincoln Park area and
part of the year in their sunny California home. ``My heart is
slowly moving West,'' says Ellen Zinn, 53.
</P>
<P>
   Other such hot spots: Vail (No. 43), Telluride (No. 113), and
Mountain Village (No. 6), all in Colorado, and the Town of Paradise
Valley (No. 56) in Arizona. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 525 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,025) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The high-end ``is the segment of the market that emerged the
fastest in the mid-1990s and has done the best since then,'' says
Karevoll.
</P>
<P>
   In University Park (No. 190), near Dallas, homeowners were
practically leapfrogging one another to trade up ``from cottage or
ranch to Tudor or two-story traditional,'' says Cheryl Saldana, a
local Prudential real-estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that home prices have appreciated,'' she
adds, ``but that land value has skyrocketed. A typical
70-by-150-foot lot that sold for $300,000 in 1997 sold for $450,000
last year. It's the biggest boom year we've seen since the 1980s.
People are comparing this market to California's.''
</P>
<P>
   In some wealthy California towns, home buying has become a
high-speed, high-stakes challenge. ``Just last week, some clients
of mine made an offer on a house in Palo Alto (No. 89) that was
listed for $559,000,'' says Prudential broker Linda Hollister.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the brokers were basically standing in line, waiting
their turn to make their pitches. I was number 13 of 13, and I knew
we didn't stand a chance _ my clients couldn't afford to go more
than $22,000 above asking.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to make an acceptable offer has also resulted in a
few unusual situations: Last year, a couple of Hollister's clients
huddled in the study of a house they wanted to buy _ and didn't
leave _ as the owners huddled in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sellers' agent and I ran from den to living room and back
again with offers and counteroffers,'' Hollister says, ``until we
got the deal worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Such frantic competition has created an auction-house atmosphere
in some markets and led to a phenomenon known as ``gazumping,''
British slang for a situation in which one buyer, who thinks he has
made a acceptable offer on a house, loses out to another, who
offers more money on the sly.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the celebrity wars over houses not even on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seinfeld offered $14.5 million for a spread in East
Hampton, Long Island, N.Y., had his offer rejected, and
subsequently lost out to clothing designer Helmut Lang, who also
liked the property but came up with an acceptable $15.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, wealthy Americans continue to express themselves
through their houses in large, grandiose strokes. A few towns, like
Newton, Mass. (No. 227), have instituted house-to-plot-size ratios,
and a few have rules and regulations about architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Village, Colo. (No. 6), which sprang up in the last
four years near Telluride, is small (population: 1,000) and very,
very rich.
</P>
<P>
   As mandated by the town administration, all new homes in this
young Rockies resort have to ``contribute to a single identity''
and ``foster a sense of visual harmony and lasting value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very strict design guidelines,'' says Andy Hanley,
mayor of Mountain Village (and a real-estate broker and developer),
``so there's a little bit of a process you have to come through.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners are quick to follow the trends of those above them.
Stuart Cohen, architect and professor of architecture at the
University of Illinois at Chicago, says that ``the high-end
construction market trickles down in terms of presenting a kind of
ideal that people buying $300,000 to $400,000 houses aspire to.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly unfashionable are the ranch-style, low-slung
modernist rectangles created in the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, very few of them are of any kind of architectural
distinction, because they're coming down like crazy,'' says Cohen.
But architectural distinction _ even historical significance _ is
no protection against the bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   In Hinsdale, Ill. (No. 139) _ known as the teardown capital of
the Midwest _ more than 100 homes were leveled last year, some of
them Victorians.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenwich, Conn. (No. 23), fat green dumpsters parked in
driveways have replaced Mercedeses as neighborhood status symbols. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,700) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tearing down a house, though, is not always a swift or easy
decision. The Maloneys of Greenwich bought a waterfront house in
nearby Riverside (No. 62) for $2.3 million and struggled with the
decision of whether to renovate or level.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is Midwestern, with Quaker roots,'' says Nancy
Maloney. ``And philosophically, they're not people to tear things
down. There's something that really bothers me about just razing
the place, and I keep asking, `Can't we use anything?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although her husband and their architect finally convinced her
that building around the elements she liked would be more expensive
than replacing them, she hopes to salvage what she can: She
mentions a porthole window and a favorite faucet.
</P>
<P>
   Some architectural details, like the staircases, would not meet
current building codes even if they could be saved. ``You just
can't get away with some of these things anymore,'' she says
wistfully, ``even if you like them.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a record-breaking year of home sales, the market shows few
signs of slowing down. California has 76 towns on our list this
year, and next year looks just as strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are initially forecasting an 8 percent decrease in home
sales,'' says Leslie Appleton-Young, an economist with the
California Association of Realtors. ``And I hate to change a
forecast, but I think that sales this year are going to be
extremely strong. The biggest constraint on the market is supply.
When the market is this hot, there just isn't that much
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, says Bockman, the NAR economist, ``our numbers are
actually coming out ahead of where we were last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting the beginning part of the year to be strong
and then the second part of the year to tail off a little bit. We
expect to settle in for 1999 right around the same levels that we
had for 1998, and we may even end the year a little bit higher,
depending on how things go over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our forecasts is that mortgage rates are going to drop
shortly, and if this happens, we expect to see another glut of home
buyers hitting the market. All of those people who missed out on
the last opportunity will finally get off the fence and make that
purchase.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 2,100. FOURTH OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Higher home prices? Smaller lots? Bigger houses? It takes a
historian to put these trends into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Jackson is a former chairman of Columbia University's
history department and an expert on suburbia who lives in Rich Town
No. 163 (Chappaqua, N.Y.). He makes the point that no matter how
expensive houses may seem ``they're still cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Similar dwellings in Japan, Germany, France, or Switzerland
would almost certainly be more expensive, if they were available at
all _ and most likely they wouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have space,'' he explains. ``Both our land and our
construction costs are less expensive in the United States than
elsewhere. An acre of land in Japan would be an undreamed-of
luxury: nothing in San Marino (No. 72), Greenwich (No. 23), or even
Atherton (No. 3) could compare to it. In world terms, a million
dollars an acre is not an expensive price to pay.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: LOCH ADAMSON IS AN ASSOCIATE EDITOR AT ``EQUITY''
MAGAZINE.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (NOTE: FOR TALLY OF WEALTHIEST U.S. COMMUNITIES, PLEASE SEE
SEPARATE STORY SLUGGED BC-250-RICHEST-TOWNS-WORTH-NYTSF.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach
Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
