<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CLOSERANG     06-22 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CLOSERANGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNIE PROULX SPINS DARK YARNS OF WILD, WEARYING WYOMING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (``CLOSE RANGE: Wyoming Stories''; By Annie Proulx; Scribner,
$25.) 
 
By BARBARA LISS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to Wyoming. ``Dangerous and indifferent ground,'' writes
Annie Proulx. This is her kind of country, for she is addicted to
hard places _ Newfoundland's rugged coast in the Pulitzer
Prize-winning ``The Shipping News''; New England's rocky soil in
``Postcards.'' Landscape, she tells us, is destiny.
</P>
<P>
   And never more so than in the penetrating stories of ``Close
Range.'' Proulx's Wyoming looks nothing like the West that glows
from the pages of Cowboys and Indians magazine. Her adopted home
state is a sublimely beautiful, treacherous place where the weather
wins every time in the struggle to keep the ranch going.
</P>
<P>
   The main thing, one stoic explains, is to ``last as long as you
can, make things come out so it's still your ranch when it's time a
get buried.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone does last that long. Nowhere in the 11 stories is
there a happy ending. Not that Proulx cares about such things. But
none of the characters in ``Close Range'' escapes an abusive
childhood or a wrong choice. So read at your own peril, and be
warned that nobody gets even the absence of misery that passes for
happiness in ``The Shipping News.''
</P>
<P>
   The first story, ``The Half-Skinned Steer,'' which is included
in ``The Best American Short Stories of the Century'' anthology,
reads like the fable it is. (It comes from an Icelandic folk tale.)
A fierce old man gone from Wyoming 60 years travels back by car for
his brother's funeral. On the road, he meets up with a series of
disasters, each one worse than the one before.
</P>
<P>
   Although we know his homecoming will finish him off, Proulx
impressively builds suspense in this mournful tale. And she sets
the stage for the stories to come.
</P>
<P>
   Another pugnacious loner, Diamond Felts, makes his way on the
rodeo circuit in ``The Mud Down Below.'' Diamond has something to
prove to his father, and the first time he rides a bull, he is
consumed with ``the feeling of power as though he were the bull and
not the rider; even the fright fulfilled some greedy physical
hunger in him he hadn't known was there.'' For the reader who
thinks the rodeo might be as romantic as an old Judy Collins song,
here is the antidote.
</P>
<P>
   In a story worthy of Faulkner, the grim ``People in Hell Just
Want a Drink of Water,'' an ambitious rancher builds a dynasty on
the backs of his eight sons. Raised hard and mean, they are
contemptuous of weaker men. In their arrogance they exact a cruel
justice against the son of another rancher.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of Proulx's protagonists are male (``a reflection
of the real world, like it or not,'' she has said), Josanna Skiles,
a woman of ``plain face and thickening flesh,'' stands at the
center of ``The Lonely Coast.'' If life is an endless ridge of
disappointments for men in Wyoming, it is a valley of tears for
women. They do not go the distance in these stories.
</P>
<P>
   Josanna spends her Friday nights with her friends, reading the
newspaper personal ads aloud. The man she meets through the paper
turns out to be a handsome, quick-smiling, ``one step this side of
restless drifter.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrator, who has her own man troubles, understands what
happened to Josanna one night out on the Casper highway. And in
words too eloquent to be hers _ a young woman tending bar _ she
explains Josanna's actions.
</P>
<P>
   All of Proulx's characters suffer loneliness as punishing as a
Wyoming blizzard. In ``The Bunchgrass at the Edge of the World,''
Ottaline, a young woman ``approaching the size of a hundred-gallon
propane tank,'' works her father's ranch, pining for love.
</P>
<P>
   One day an abandoned John Deere tractor talks to her from a
gravel pit, both wooing her and ticking off its grievances. When
Ottaline is drawn to the burnt-out machine, we know that bad times
wait ahead for somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Proulx has fun with this venture into magical realism, western
style, but its downbeat weirdness will not suit everyone's taste.
</P>
<P>
   There is something for everyone _ adultery, divorce, sexual
harassment, violence _ in ``Pair a Spurs,'' a complicated tale
about a set of magical handmade spurs that pass from one person to
another. Like Proulx's accordion in ``Accordion Crimes,'' the
owners of the spurs come to a bad end.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the spurs that eat at Car Scrope, a luckless
rancher ``on his way downhill.'' Car, starved for love, or maybe
just for sex, pushes headlong into craziness. In Proulx's world, if
grasshoppers, dust storms and tractors don't get you, loneliness
will.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe a sense of despair will finish you off. The young man
whose ranch is failing in ``The Governors of Wyoming'' tells his
wife, ``I can't get a holt on it. On anything.'' Shy Hamp, whose
downfall takes entirely too long to tell, hasn't really lost the
knack of ranching because he never had it.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather's photographs of Wyoming governors reproach him
from the living-room wall. And to add insult, his wife has made a
success selling Ralph Laurenesque western clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Out of frustration and rage, Shy becomes an agitator against the
beef industry. Cows have wrecked the West, an anti-beef organizer
tells him. Well, thinks the reader, they have certainly wrecked
Shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokeback Mountain,'' the last story _ and maybe the best _
takes the most chances, surprising us with its homoerotic theme.
Proulx pours enormous sympathy into an account of two country boys
who meet one summer in their youth tending sheep and then spend
their lives running from and to their passionate relationship. One
of the men tersely sums up their situation: ``We do that in the
wrong place, we'll be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories would be wearying if it were not for Proulx's wry
observations. For example, of a teen-age girl's family history, she
writes, ``Her mother lived in Austin, Texas, with a sitar player
whose name was unpronounceable.'' About a woman who, in her
madness, throws her baby into a river, she comments, ``A murderer
she might be, but no one could say her house wasn't clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Proulx's compelling description and rich cadence bring Wyoming
fully alive. As city folks, however, we are probably not meant
always to get her characters' words. Sometimes what they say about
their ranches or their jobs is so obscure, it's as if they are
speaking a foreign language. What we do understand, though, is how
they come to grief trying to live their cowboy lives.
</P>
<P>
   But their grubby, gritty days are waning. Goodbye to the Old
West. Soon no one will be in Wyoming except movie stars and
telecommuters. ``Close Range'' shows us why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
