<SLUG> BC-UPS-DOWNTIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WEEKENDS, UPS SHIPS PASSENGERS, NOT PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is one truism in the economics of the airline industry,
it is that planes don't make money parked on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   That reality hits especially hard for the air freight business,
which does much of its business during the work week. Saturday and
Sunday deliveries are the exception rather than the rule.
</P>
<P>
   To extend the air time of some of its fleet, UPS each weekend
transforms some of its Boeing 727s from stripped down cargo planes,
to charter flights carrying human cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers don't have to sit among overnight envelopes or carry
boxes on their laps. Instead a choreographed crew takes about four
hours to put in overhead bins, seats and even galleys.
</P>
<P>
   UPS is the only cargo company to try to adapt its planes for
such weekend use, according to the Air Transport Association, the
trade group representing most major airlines and air freight
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an interesting thing because aircraft utilization is a
big thing,'' said ATA spokesman David Fuscus. ``Cargo planes may
get an average of two or three hours a day and passenger airplanes
may get as many as 13 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of shipping people on weekends instead of packages,
came out of a UPS employee group looking at asset utilization, said
Paul Martins, director of air charter service for UPS.
</P>
<P>
   But it took a year to go from from brainstorm to takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   First there was some design and engineering changes needed for
the five Boeing 727-100 aircraft so they could get converted each
weekend. In addition to some cockpit equipment, such as an on-board
computer that alerts pilots to other aircraft in the area and
required on passsenger planes but not cargo flights, there was the
design and cost of the overhead bins complete with emergency oxygen
masks that pop down, rows of seats and kitchens. The interiors cost
about $2.5 million per aircraft. And then there was some crew
training, after all UPS pilots do not usually make in-flight
announcements to the cargo on board, and prior to this endeavor,
they never had to worry about evacuating anyone but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the matter of flight attendants. UPS
contracts with Denver-based Inclusive Solutions Inc. to hire
experienced flight attendants. But unlike the most visible of UPS
employees, the flight attednants don't wear brown uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about it fleetingly, but decided it would be too
dull,'' said Martins. Instead, the interior of the planes are blue
and flight attendants are dressed in blue and gold. ``It is a
vacation-mindset interior.''
</P>
<P>
   The exterior of the planes, however, do not change. The brown
stripe runs the length of the white fuselage along the window line
and the UPS logo is printed in gold on the brown empennage.
</P>
<P>
   The first flight took off in 1997 and one of the original
companies using the planes was Boston-based TNT Vacations. UPS
started flying passnger charter flights out of Logan International
Airport in 1998 and had one flight as recently as June 5. The TNT
contract has lapsed, however and both companies are in the process
of negotiating a new one.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tour operators, other regular clients include the
White House, which charters a UPS plane to transport overflow press
on some presidental trips.
</P>
<P>
   While a Boeing 727 can seat 137 people, the 33-inch pitch in
seating _ more generous than the standard 31-inch pitch, means the
UPS planes can seat only 113 passengers. In addition, the company
spends between $7 and $8 per passenger on food, while the industry
average is about $5.
</P>
<P>
   The planes have flown more than 180,000 passengers to Florida,
the Carribean, Cancun and Costa Rica. Perhaps most impressive is
the on-time arrival rate. UPS says it is 87 percent, well above the
industry average (which was 75 perent for April of this year).
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard some of the jokes from our customers: `Do we have to
wear brown uniforms?' and `Does the plane have windows?' but as far
as service goes, both in terms of of quality and on-time
performance, they have been outstanding,'' said John Dircks, chief
operating officer of TNT Vacations.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough demand for the charter flights that two of the
five planes stay configured as passenger aircraft during the week.
The planes now fly more hours ferrying passengers than they do
cargo. They are making money for the company, but Martins would not
say what the return is.
</P>
<P>
   The operation has yet to make back the original investment of
more than $12 million in interior equipment alone. ``I don't think
anyone went in to this with the expectation we would make that back
in two years,'' said Martins. ``But we are certainly making a dent
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that you have to be smarter with the assets
that you own and how you can get as much bang for your buck as
possible and no airline in the world makes money when planes are
sitting on the ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
