<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TIDES-BOS &LR;      06-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIDES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORMY RELATIONSHIP OF MAN AND THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AGAINST THE TIDE 
The Fate of the New England Fisherman 
By Richard Adams Carey 
Houghton Mifflin, 381 pp., $23 
 
AGAINST THE TIDE 
The Battle for America's Beaches 
By Cornelia Dean 
Columbia University Press, 279 pp., illustrated, $26.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning tide one recent February, Richard Adams Carey
joined the crew of the Honi-Do, an all-purpose dragger out of
Chatham, Mass., in an anything's-better-than-staying-ashore run to
haul enough shrimp to pay expenses with something left over for the
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   As they head out, Carey observes that in the 25-knot blow of the
day before, ``a piece of the beach had been stripped away'' and
that a summer house was ``sagging fatally'' into ``what Thoreau
described as . . . `the true Atlantic house, where the ocean is the
land-lord, as well as the sea-lord.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Except as the chance observation of a writer who misses nothing
and cannot resist a literary allusion, this scene has little to do
with Carey's account of four Cape Cod fishermen in the declining
years of a livelihood that is also a culture. But it neatly links
together two books which by the oddest of coincidences have been
published in the same month with the exact same title.
</P>
<P>
   In both Carey's ``Against the Tide'' and Cornelia Dean's, which
is about the threat to America's beaches, the underlying issues are
viewed as ``tragedies of the commons,'' that ecoscience formulation
in which a common good _ in one case the sea and the fish in it, in
the other the beaches _ are ruined for all by the greed of
overfishing or overdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Carey's account of the Honi-Do's shrimp run is a beautifully
reported set-piece, his prose bringing the reader aboard. ``Around
five o'clock the (sun had) mouldered to a purple bruise in the
west, and we finished our fourth tow in the dark, hauling the net
in the hard glare of the Honi-Do's cockpit light, the gulls
hovering in silence at the frayed edges of the darkness. `We need a
nine-box tow,' Dave said as the winches began to grind, the reel to
turn, and a drowned gull came up attached to a sweep cable, one
foot tangled between the cable and a chain link.''
</P>
<P>
   The attentive New Englander reading this does not need to be
told that this tow, like the day's others, brings up barely enough
shrimp to fill three boxes. But over the marine radio the Honi-Do's
skipper learns that back on the dock in Chatham there's a buyer for
whatever he has, and they head in, only to run hard aground on the
outer bar. ``I've got a bad feeling that we're going to eat our
catch,'' Dave mutters. For that same New England reader, hardened
by years of doom-and-gloom reports on the region's fisheries, this
shapes up as the ultimate metaphor _ the Honi-Do's crew watching
the lights of the shrimp-buyer's truck disappearing down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But the buyer stays on the dock, and the Honi-Do sells its catch
_ and that ending turns out to be the metaphor for Carey's
optimistic view of the future of the New England fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   It is a view based partly on recent legislative and regulatory
actions that promote sound ``ecosystem management'' practices, and
partly on omen _ the catch, three summers ago, of a rare golden
haddock in the nets of a New Bedford dragger. ``From such small
coincidences of beauty and fortuity,'' writes Carey, who spent a
year working with the fishermen he writes about, ``hope breathes
like a fair-weather breeze across the berths and moorings of
another generation of voyagers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean, the science editor of the New York Times, covers
considerable territory as she details the persistent efforts of
developers and developer-prodded government agencies to ``armor''
the coast against the action of wind and waves. But ``nature,'' she
notes, usually ``has the last word,'' undercutting seawalls and
toppling houses.
</P>
<P>
   Like Carey, Dean also sees in government action a hope for the
preservation of the beaches, citing, among other cases, the
successful fight to save South Beach in 1987 _ a place which ``for
many . . . summed up what it meant to live on Martha's Vineyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Carey nor Dean gloats over misfortune and tragedy, but
both his overloaded scalloper Patricia Marie (which sinks with loss
of crew and catch) and her ``beachless beach towns'' along the
coast, from New Jersey south, stand as grim reminders of the
results of overfishing or overdevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Carey and Dean have to say is _ or should be _ well
known to New England readers. Not all New Englanders, however, will
share their optimism that the fishing industry and the coastal
beaches can survive against the tides. So the vigilance of those
who care about such matters should not be lulled by that optimism
for these are still tragedies ``of the commons'' very much
occurring before our eyes and in our time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
