<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS, UST CHIEFS WERE DRIVEN TO GET DEAL DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What drove UST Corp. and Citizens Financial Group into each
other's arms? The answer was just a few blocks away from Citizens'
Boston headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In this region, at this time, everything that has to do with
banking takes place in the shadow cast by the pending merger of
Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp. The coming divestiture
of more than 200 branches and $12 billion on deposit at Fleet or
BankBoston looms as an event that will affect every banking
competitor in New England.
</P>
<P>
   UST chief Neal Finnegan argues that he might have made the same
deal with Citizens chairman Lawrence Fish absent the daunting
backdrop. Perhaps sometime, but probably not right now.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.4 billion price tag, good but not extravagant, is an
indication that Citizens and UST truly need each other at this
moment. Both banks could have been hurt in the Fleet/BankBoston
divestiture if they stood alone. Together, they are assured a much
stronger position no matter how the divestiture bidding unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens could have soon turned into a number three competitor
by some measures if a big national bank won all or nearly all of
the divested business. A giant Fleet-BankBoston would dominate New
England and some other company would be viewed as the primary
banking alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't let that happen,'' said Fish. ``Couldn't.
Wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   UST brought its investment bankers in to survey all of the
options as soon as the Fleet-BankBoston deal was announced.
Standing still was not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very clear that making a deal with another company
made the most sense and Citizens was the most attractive,'' said
Finnegan.
</P>
<P>
   UST and Citizens began to talk about six weeks ago, two months
after the Fleet-BankBoston announcement, and the deal was done by
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the last leg in an impressive comeback for UST,
which recovered from serious loan problems in the early 1990s.
Finnegan, a longtime Shawmut executive who later worked for Bankers
Trust in New York, was recruited to run the company after efforts
to sell it failed to attract an acceptable offer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Finnegan grew UST through several acquisitions and the purchase
of branches divested in another local merger, BankBoston's purchase
of BayBanks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the upcoming Fleet-BankBoston divestiture,
conducted by the companies with the Department of Justice looking
over their shoulders, will probably be announced in July or August.
Final bids are weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   Three possible decisions seem most likely: a big bidder winning
the entire package; big winners in each of the states where
branches will be sold (Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Rhode
Island); or one dominant winner with some piece of the business
carved out for small banks.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome that most worries Fish and Finnegan _ a national
bank winning the entire divestiture package _ is no longer such a
severe threat. A combined Citizens/UST will control more than twice
the deposits to be divested by Fleet and BankBoston, and more than
three times the loans.
</P>
<P>
   But UST will bring more than branches, deposits, and consumer
loans to Citizens. Its longstanding commercial lending operation to
small- and middle-market businesses is an important building block.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens grew through the 1990s mostly as a savings bank serving
retail consumers. It tried to generate its own commercial lending
business with tepid results, later acquiring more capacity when it
bought First NH in New Hampshire three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pace has picked up very recently. Just last month, Citizens
spent $350 million to acquire the commercial business of State
Street Corp. and its $2.2 billion portfolio of loans. Add UST's
operations and Citizens has dramatically improved its standing as a
commercial lender in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens, which is owned by the Royal Bank of Scotland, has no
publicly traded stock of its own and pays cash when it buys a bank.
That usually means Citizens is spending money out of its parent's
pocket _ and this time it dug deep for UST.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens has purchased 14 New England banks since 1992 for a
combined $1.5 billion. The UST deal, for $1.4 billion, will nearly
double that figure in a single transaction. It is about twice as
expensive as its largest previous purchase, the $710 million
acquisition of First NH.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Royal has spent money to make money.
Citizens, which started as a modest American subsidiary, accounts
for 25 to 30 percent of its parent's profits today.
</P>
<P>
   That's as good a reason as any to pony up for a deal that will
help protect its American franchise against the threat posed by the
Fleet-BankBoston divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is always the possibility that Citizens will
actually win a part of the divestiture package. Combined with the
other recent deals, it could turn out to be a transforming period
for the Citizens franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Fish is coy about his interest, if any, in the divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to wait and see,'' he said. ``We'll stick
around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
