<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK SALES AMONG GOOD ECONOMIC SIGNS FOR SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soccer economy appears to be still growing. Two weeks ago,
when Christian Vieri was transferred to Inter from Lazio for $48
million, even high-powered agents in Italy expressed shock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lazio is negotiating a deal worth nearly $90 million,
including salary and ``miscellaneous fees,'' for Arsenal's Nicholas
Anelka.
</P>
<P>
   As inflated as these prices appear to be, they will likely
continue to increase as revenue streams continue to open. Lazio
S.p.A. became the first club to be quoted on the Italian stock
exchange, and president Sergio Cragnotti made moves to establish
the team among the elite in Serie A. Many teams in England have
gone public.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Barcelona concluded a deal with Via Digital e
Telefonica for television rights worth nearly $500 million for
2003-08.
</P>
<P>
   And in England, a financial firm predicted that Manchester
United's value would increase to about $3 billion in five years.
Rupert Murdoch's BSkyB recently bid $1.06 billion for Manchester
United, so upsetting fans and minority stockholders that they
successfully blocked the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hands-off approach
</P>
<P>
   One team that will miss out on the financial advantages is
Obilic, the Belgrade club controlled by Zeljko Raznatovic, better
known by his nom de guerre, Arkan. Obilic has been prevented from
playing in the UEFA Cup, despite finishing second to Partizan in
the Yugoslavian League, because Arkan has been accused of crimes
against humanity. Also, the French club Bordeaux ended negotiations
for an Obilic player, Ivan Vukomanovic, signaling the start of an
informal commercial boycott of the club. Obilic's national team
players, Nenad Grozdic and Nenad Lukic, likely could also have
attracted interest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going gets rough
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiras coach Luiz Felipe Scolari attained the results he
promised upon being hired in 1997, leading the team to the Copa
Libertadores title and a date with Manchester United in the Toyota
Cup in Tokyo in December.
</P>
<P>
   But Scolari's ultra-pragmatic style has caused problems in
Brazil. Palmeiras had a player ejected in losing to Corinthians in
the Sao Paulo championship final Sunday. When Cleber was red-carded
in the 21st minute, he became the 11th Palmeiras expulsion in 14
matches. But instead of taking further action, referee Paulo Cesar
de Oliveira simply whistled the match to a halt after an
altercation in the 30th minute of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Corinthians won the first leg, 3-0, and had tied the second on a
goal by Edilson in the 29th minute of the second half. But Edilson
then provoked the Palmeiras team, leading to a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Edilson paid a high price for his involvement. He was dropped
from the national team by coach Wanderley Luxemburgo and will not
play in Copa America, which starts next week in Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's on the mark
</P>
<P>
   Milton resident Dick Johnson was among the most prescient of
those involved in women's soccer in the US when he promoted the New
England Sports Museum Challenge Cup in 1991. Johnson, director of
the museum, not only attracted crowds that shocked US Soccer
Federation officials, he also anticipated the finalists in the
first Women's World Cup: Norway and the US. The Norwegians won both
Challenge Cup matches, 1-0 before 5,563 in New Britain, Conn., Aug.
30, and 2-1 before 4,758 at Tufts University Sept. 1. The night
before the Tufts match, Norway's 16-year-old goalkeeper Bente
Nordby suffered an appendicitis attack and was rushed to Mt. Auburn
Hospital. Nordby then held the US to a Kristine Lilly goal and has
kept the starting position through Norway's 2-1 win over Russia at
Foxboro Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The color purple
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Renegades paid tribute to fired coach Rick Copland by
wearning purple ribbons in their game last Friday. Kara Brown
scored as the Renegades, under interim coach Peter Bradley, took a
1-0 victory over the Springfield Sirens in a W League match before
1,800 spectators at Bowditch Field in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Copland, who guided the Renegades to a 13-3 record, including a
loss in the league final last year, had been fired earlier in the
week after a dispute with chief operating officer Farrukh Quraishi.
The Renegades, in third place in the Northern Division with a 6-3-1
record, visit the Laval Dynamite Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Copland coached Charles River United to a 3-2 win
over the Boston Bolts in the Under-18 State championship game
Sunday to qualify for the Northeast regional tournament starting
July 3 in Kingston, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clock watching
</P>
<P>
   The MLS competition committee should take a lesson from the
Women's World Cup. In every game, the clock counts up and the
official time is kept by the referee. This is a very simple system,
universally applied, and appreciated and understood by 5-year-olds,
teenagers, and pensioners of both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   An incident that decided the D.C. United-Los Angeles Galaxy game
Saturday indicates the committee understands neither the game of
soccer nor how to promote a new league.
</P>
<P>
   With six seconds remaining in a 1-1 game, United's Geoff Aunger
pulled down Greg Vanney. Chinese referee Baojie Sun called a direct
free kick. The clock was stopped by a ``fifth official,'' allowing
Mauricio Cienfuegos to line up the kick, which he converted for a
2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The first lesson is that the referee, and only the referee,
should be allowed to terminate the match. The clock should run to
45 minutes in each half, then the referee decides the stoppage
time. If others are allowed to make crucial decisions, the
referee's authority becomes usurped, and the door becomes open to
even more outside interference in what is a very simple game.
</P>
<P>
   The second lesson is that if someone else is going to control
the clock, at least do so in favor of the home team.
</P>
<P>
   Said United coach Thomas Rongen, ``This is one of the reasons
that we're not taken seriously by the rest of the world
sometimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
