<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' BELLE TOSSES TANTRUMS, FINANCIAL ADVICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're surfing the Internet looking for advice on how to
allocate your 401(k) plan. And the online tips are abundant.
</P>
<P>
   You've got Charles Schwab. Merrill Lynch. Morningstar. Albert
Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The enigmatic Baltimore Orioles outfielder, who
signed a five-year, $65 million deal in December, has been doling
out financial advice at his Athlete Direct site (keyword: ADsports)
since its launch on America Online two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Belle, who as usual is throwing temper tantrums and refusing to
talk with reporters this season, has been directing anyone seeking
his comment _ writers or otherwise _ to his AOL site the past three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, Belle posts an explanation about why he was
upset for being replaced in the ninth inning of a recent game.
Orioles manager Ray Miller benched Belle for not running out a
ground ball, and Belle later responded by shouting expletives at
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Belle doesn't raise his voice at his site. The only
sound the site emits is a welcome clip by Belle.
</P>
<P>
   His financial advice is only a small part of his site, but
considering that he's not exactly people-friendly, it is worth
noting. Belle's recommendations are standard and come with a
disclaimer, but he also advises that investors try speculative
investments, such as Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Belle's site also includes an interactive crossword puzzle and a
youth-oriented cartoon series featuring an animated Belle dressed
as a superhero. Fans also can buy the fat-free corn flakes that
Belle markets for charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different perspective of Albert that he usually doesn't
get from the media because he doesn't talk to the press,'' said
Ross Schaufelberger, president of Los Angeles-based Athlete Direct.
</P>
<P>
   Belle works closely with his brother Terry, a financial analyst,
to develop the site's content, Schaufelberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Athlete Direct also produces commercial sites for Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman, Stars goalie Ed Belfour and Rangers
catcher Pudge Rodriguez. Belle's site is among the three
most-visited sites for baseball players, Schaufelberger said. A
recent visit to the site's message board shows nothing but
pro-Belle posts.
</P>
<P>
   Belle's site also has an Ask Albert section where fans can
e-mail questions, which begs the question: Does Belle actually
respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, definitely,'' Schaufelberger said. ``We've been happy with
his popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   You might want to get a second opinion on Belle's financial
tips, however.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY NIGHT FIGHTS: Paulie Ayala fans who don't want to shell
out for pay-per-view access can crowd around the computer at 8 p.m.
Saturday when the Fort Worth, Texas, boxer fights Johnny Tapia for
the World Boxing Association bantamweight title in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime Entertainment Television's SETBoxing.com
(www.setboxing.com) plans live online scoring as part of the
pay-per-view event. The site has scheduled chats with Tapia and
other fighters participating on the three-bout card. Ayala is not
scheduled up to chat, but the site does post a two-minute-plus
audio interview.
</P>
<P>
   SETBoxing.com also includes exclusive footage from Peter
McNeeley's fight against Mike Tyson and video of former ``Playboy''
model Mia St. John's workout for her nontitle featherweight bout
against Mary Ann Haik. McNeeley is scheduled to fight Eric
``Butterbean'' Esch for the International Boxing Association title.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION, GOLF HACKERS: CNN/SI.com bolstered its golf content
by signing a deal with GolfServ. The section is designed to help
recreation golfers improve their game. Users can track the progress
of their game, search a database for courses to play and access
profiles of other members as potential playing partners.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
