<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WWC-LILLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN MIDFIELDER PROVIDES THE FOCUS FOR US SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISLE, Ill. _ The photographs are almost always the same.
Captured at the center of a midfield goal celebration is Mia Hamm.
Members of the US team with broad smiles surround her. They have
their arms around each other in a jubilant, jumping hug. And almost
always Kristine Lilly is there, standing with her back to the
cameras, face obscured. In the moment of arrested joy, the
midfielder is identifiable only by her No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in mid-celebration or the middle of a difficult workout,
Lilly does not cut an inposing figure. A slight 5 feet 4 inches,
125 pounds with a straight-to-the-point demeanor and a reputation
for consistent rather than spectacular play, she does not attract
the attention her more famous teammates do. That's fine.
</P>
<P>
   The player with the most international soccer appearances in
world history always has known how to make her presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen of Caps has saved her biggest statements for the field
and the record books. On May 21, 1998, in Kobe, Japan, she played
in her 152d international match and passed Norway's Heidi Store.
Lilly now has 181 career caps and counting. But the figure becomes
more impressive when you learn just what representing your country
181 times means over a 12-year career. Through 1998, the veteran
had appeared in 87 percent of the games played by the US women's
national team in its history. Also by the end of 1998, Lilly had
started in all but four of her international appearances and played
a full 90 minutes in 134 of her then-record 163 games. She has
played more than 1,000 minutes on the US team for six consecutive
years and ranks as the Americans' all-time leader in minutes
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when people ask about it, I think about how many
(caps) there are,'' said Lilly. ``I can't even believe it. I never
counted how many or kept track of how many games I played. Every
once in a while I look back and I think, `Holy cow, I've been doing
this for a while.' And the body keeps reminding me every so
often.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the US opener against Denmark provides any indication,
the 27-year-old attacking midfielder may play her best soccer in
the 1999 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   When the US needed an offensive spark and with young striker
Cindy Parlow struggling against the Danes, Lilly moved from the
midfield to forward in the second half. She proved the switch a
smart decision after launching a leftfooted shot from the top of
the box and tucking the ball just inside the left post in the 89th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, Lilly provides a lot of mobility and can showcase her
strength, which is movement off the ball. Depending on the opponent
she can find more room to maneuver at forward or be more productive
starting the offense from midfield. In the second half Saturday,
she found the seams in the Danish defense, saw lots of touches on
the ball, and worked well with Hamm and Tiffeny Millbrett leading
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The versatility demonstrated by Lilly should be an important
asset as the US prepares for two teams it has never faced before _
Nigeria and North Korea. Although known as the world's best flank
midfielder before a recent move to attacking midfielder, she has
seen significant time at forward this year. Monday, coach Tony
DiCicco did not know if Lilly would remain at forward or return to
her midfielder position. But even as attacking midfielder she
utilizes her speed and fitness, covering a lot of ground and
frequently joining the attack. Regardless of her place on the
field, DiCicco and the US team know they can depend on Lilly not
just to show up, but contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that she had an excellent game in the first game
of the World Cup and I hope she has her best games from here on
in,'' said DiCicco. ``She deserves to have a World Cup that
distinguishes her in everyone's mind as one of the very best that's
ever played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Added cocaptain Julie Foudy: ``Lil's unbelievable, the most
capped player in the world and I would say in every single one of
those games she's had a presence. That's so hard to say for any
player at any level. She's so consistent. If I could point to one
player, it's Kristine who I would take day-in and day-out becaue
she's always going to be there. You know when you walk onto the
field that she's going to be battling right next to you. If she
scores, great. If not, you know she's going to be creating a lot of
things just with her mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Her teammates realize that Lilly has quietly built a career
filled with personal milestones and historic accomplishments. It's
often said that she is the most respected member of the national
team for her caps, commitment, and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   When Lilly first played for the national team as a 16-year-old
in China, she wasn't quite sure what she had gotten herself into.
The player raised in the suburban soccer preserve of Wilton, Conn.,
claims that at the time she was called to duty, she didn't even
know the national team existed. Now like so many of her veteran
teammates, who won the 1991 World Cup title in China in relative
obscurity and Olympic gold with fanfare but little respect from
NBC, Lilly stands as a prime example of how far women's soccer has
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this moment,'' she said. ``We've been
waiting for big crowds. We've been waiting for media to come out
and support us. Thank God it's happened because this is what we've
been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   After 181 international appearances, it appears the Queen of
Caps finally has her chance to hold court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
