<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOERNE'S 150TH ANNIVERSARY PROMPTS RENEWED INTEREST IN TOWN'S
HERITAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Ripley Arnold and his dragoons were swatting mosquitoes on
the banks of the Trinity and building Fort Worth, a group of German
settlers was chiseling away at the limestone rocks of the Texas
Hill Country, trying to establish Boerne almost 300 miles to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1849 and the Germans were spreading out over the Hill
Country. They had flooded in from an impoverished homeland where
only the wealthy could look forward to getting wealthier.
Intellectuals had no place in the German economic struggle, and
religion was a cause for persecution.
</P>
<P>
   They were deceived about Texas, told that there was abundant
land for everyone, plenty of crops, plenty of freedoms. They were
not told that the land was actually inhabited by very angry
Comanches who were stubbornly reluctant to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   As Boerne celebrates its 150th anniversary this year, it is
trying to tell the story of the early settlers, and it is
struggling to prove that it is not merely a bedroom community for
nearby San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   It should be said, however, that the later mission is made
harder with the ``Go Spurs Go'' signs that populate almost all
Boerne stores, and the red and black Spurs flags that fly from
nearly every passing car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals here don't like the term `bedroom community,'''
said Bettie Edmonds, a retired Air Force colonel and Boerne
historian. ``We've tried hard to keep our own identity, but it has
been tough the past 10 years or so. The Texas Hill Country is very
popular now and people are moving here from all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Boerne's growth is generally attributed to Interstate 10. When
the town was established, it took two days to get to San Antonio;
now it's 30 minutes, tops.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Edmonds pointed out, Wal-Mart inadvertently caused a boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wal-Mart came in the early 1980s, it decimated
downtown,'' she said. ``It ran some of the mom and pop businesses
out and left 25 or 30 buildings vacant.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened then transformed the sleepy town into one of the
hottest tourist stops in the chalky hills. In a word _ antiques.
</P>
<P>
   From the tiny town of Evant, down through Lampasas, Marble
Falls, Johnson City, and on from Llano, to Fredericksburg and
Kerrville, antiques are the life's blood of the hills. It seems at
times that workers must be laboring day and night to create all
these antiques.
</P>
<P>
   When the affected businesses packed up and fled the Wal-Mart
shadow in Boerne, antique stores instantly filled the vacuum. Now,
quaint stores, eateries, gift shops and inns populate Main Street
and welcome the hordes of vacationers who hop from town to town in
search of treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we've been able to keep the old architecture,''
Edmonds said. ``People are restoring the old buildings and adapting
them for modern use. We continue to get historical markers for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she insisted, the 150th anniversary is bringing the town
closer to its roots. The year-long celebration has made people
aware of their local heritage. It has made them aware that Boerne
is more than a bedroom community.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
