<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHING-ASSISTANTS-H     06-22 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-ASSISTANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TEACHING ASSISTANTS VOTE TO UNIONIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Teaching assistants on all eight University of
California campuses have voted to unionize under the United Auto
Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge victory,'' said Berkeley graduate assistant
Ricardo Ochoa, president of UAW Local 2165. ``We've been fighting
for union representation for 16 years. It's been a long battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The university system's 8,400 teaching assistants, plus 1,200
readers and tutors, voted for unionization by a 68 percent majority
Monday, with a voter turnout of 55 percent, according to a final
tabulation of election results at six campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Academic student employees at the Berkeley and Los Angeles
campuses voted to unionize last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The system's teaching assistants are undergraduate and graduate
students who work as teachers. They account for more than half of
the actual instruction at University of California campuses. They
work 20-hour weeks for the nine-month academic year and earn
$13,600 _ if hired for two semesters _ plus benefits, said
University of California spokesman Brad Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   The system resisted unionization strenuously but was forced to
accede to the representation elections by pressure from the
Legislature and a decision last December by the state Public
Employment Relations Board. The board determined that teaching
assistants, tutors and readers have bargaining rights as employees.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Dion Aroner, a Democrat from Oakland, said she
doubted the university system would have agreed to go forward with
the elections without legislative pressure, notably from Senate
President pro tem John Burton, a Democrat from San Francisco, and
Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, a Democrat from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them that if they had not come to an agreement to
allow for the elections that we were going to put pressure on their
budget,'' Aroner said. ``It's very disconcerting that public
dollars were being used to fight unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Collective bargaining for readers and tutors is under way at
Berkeley and for teaching assistants at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Employment Relations Board finished counting the
ballots for the other six teaching campuses Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bargaining will be conducted by teams elected by the bargaining
unit's membership on each campus.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW also represents graduate teaching assistants at two
University of Massachusetts campuses and has petitioned the
National Labor Relations Board for elections at the State
University of New York campuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
