<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISS PICKERELL' PROBLEM SOLVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for a series of books that came out in the '50s.
One was titled ``Miss Pickerell Goes to Mars.'' Where can I find
them?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.K., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Several ``Miss Pickerell'' books turn up on the Internet
auction site eBay at www.ebay.com. Auction items include the title
you're looking for, plus ``Miss Pickerell and the Supertanker,''
``Miss Pickerell Tackles the Energy Crisis'' and ``Miss Pickerell
Harvests the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   You also can buy many books in the series from Dave Edwards, a
dealer who specializes in such series as ``Nancy Drew,'' ``Hardy
Boys,'' ``Tom Swift'' and several hundred others.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, write to Dave Edwards, Box 8, Fort
Dix, NJ 08640-0008, or visit the Web site www.seriesbooks.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Miss Pickerell'' series was created by Ellen MacGregor and
continued by Dora Pantell after MacGregor's death in 1954. The
title character is an eccentric elderly woman who often solves
problems through her knowledge of science.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to teach French to home-schoolers but do not
know how to get in touch with parents who are home-schooling
children. Is there a newsletter?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.M.J., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: In Texas, a good place to start looking is at the Texas Home
School Coalition, a nonprofit organization established to support
home-schooling parents.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has two publications: ``Texas Home School
Review,'' a free quarterly magazine financed by advertising, and
``ALERT Newsletter,'' a $25 publication sent out 8-10 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   To order, write to Box 6982, Lubbock 79493, or visit the Web
site www.thsc.org. You also can call the coalition at (806)
797-4927.
</P>
<P>
   Crosswalk.com, a national resource for home-schoolers, is
available on the Web at homeschool.crosswalk.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for a movie that stars Patty Duke and someone
named Freeman. It's called ``My Sweet Charlie.'' Where can I find
it?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.J., Watauga, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1970 film is available on video for $39.99 from Movies
Unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   Duke won an Emmy for her work in the film, which was so
well-received on TV that it was released to movie theaters.
``Charlie'' also stars Al Freeman Jr. and Noble Willingham.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 668-4344 or visit the Web site
www.moviesunlimited.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
