<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5179 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANTS-GARDENER-GLOBA     06-22 1992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANTS-GARDENER-GLOBAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GLOBAL GARDENER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The architecture of Dan Hinkley's garden on the Kitsap Peninsula
in Washington State is native, shaped by old Douglas firs and a
seeping bog.
 &HT;    But in the cultivated understory, he has convened plants from
all around the globe, reuniting the tribes of the botanical
diaspora. More than 50 kinds of arisaemas _ called
jack-in-the-pulpit in North America _ rocket from the soil, and
one, Arisaema nepenthoides, stands fully erect, a single cobralike
spathe beside a rotting stump crowned with ferns.
 &HT;    Thirty-five varieties of Solomon's seals, or polygonatums, from
China, Japan, Taiwan, Nepal and Sikkim unspiral from their early
growth, and dozens of types of hellebore have just passed their
prime.
 &HT;    Throughout the garden, hydrangeas and viburnums are beginning to
dispense their leaves; Stachyurus and Edgeworthia, winter-flowering
shrubs from Asia, are leafing out. On some loops of the garden
trail, where a Cardiocrinum giganteum thrusts its antediluvian
seedpod six feet into the air, you almost expect to see a dinosaur
wander past. Bud-break has stirred among an orderly chaos of
growth-forms.
 &HT;    The man behind this collection of plants is Daniel Hinkley, a
45-year-old native of northern Michigan who has come to be regarded
as one of the pre-eminent plant explorers in the world. Hinkley is
the co-owner and chief plantsman of Heronswood Nursery, started in
1987, which lies within the visual domain of the Olympic Mountains
across Puget Sound from Seattle.
 &HT;    Heronswood is Hinkley's personal garden, his trial garden and a
two-and-a-half-acre commercial nursery rolled in one. It's also
Hinkley's home, which he shares with his partner, Robert Jones, an
architect who is to the mailing list, the account books and the
commercial operations at Heronswood what Hinkley is to the plants.
 &HT;    Here are more than 9,500 plants sprung from seed gathered all
over the world. Most are numbered and listed in a loose-leaf binder
that Hinkley calls the Big Bang, a compilation of plants already
for sale and those that someday will be. The binder listing current
inventory is called the Grand Mal. To most gardeners, the plants on
these lists would be unfamiliar.
 &HT;    Instead of the classic Hosta ``Frances Williams,'' for instance,
there is Hosta kiyosumiensis, which Hinkley collected from Mount
Kiyosume in Japan's Chiba Prefecture in 1995. Instead of hybridized
Asiatic and Oriental lilies, there is Lilium nanum, collected by
Hinkley during a joint expedition to the Himalayas in 1995.
 &HT;    Instead of a Norway maple or a David Austin rose, there is Acer
rufinerve, a striped-bark maple he gathered in central Japan in
1997, and a rose of as yet undetermined species collected from an
altitude of 10,800 feet in China's Yunnan province in 1996.
 &HT;    From this garden each year also comes the Heronswood catalogue,
a major literary artifact in the world of gardening ephemera.
Printed solidly in small type, it begins with Hinkley's wry musings
on the imperfect art of running a mail-order nursery and ends 300
pages and some 2,500 plants later.
 &HT;    The catalogue is a saga of botanical excitement and a chronicle
of adjectival fatigue, the fate of a man driven to travel the world
searching for remarkable plants and then doomed to write a terse,
descriptive paragraph about one $6 or $8 clone after another,
beginning with Abies balsamea ``Nana'' in the ``Conifers'' section
and ending with the New Zealand sedge Uncinia unciniata, the final
plant in the section on grasses.
 &HT;    Though it advertises nowhere and admits visitors only by
appointment, Heronswood Nursery mailed 35,000 copies of the 1999
catalogue, and subscription requests are currently arriving at the
rate of 100 a week. At $8 for a two-year subscription, the
catalogue just pays for itself, unless you count the cost of
Hinkley's writing time, in which case it is grossly underpriced.
 &HT;    Subscribers pleasantly lost among Hinkley's paragraphs can be
forgiven for wondering whether the nursery exists to justify the
catalogue, or vice versa. Still, appealing to a newly adventurous
generation of gardeners, Heronswood was an almost instant success.
In 1993, the year after it incorporated, it had a gross income of
$220,000. In 1998, it was five times larger, $1,100,000.
 &HT;    These days, as Robert Jones says, he and Hinkley are trying to
choose their limits, trying to let Hinkley's interests, rather than
mere economic growth, continue to shape their offerings.
 &HT;    At Heronswood, mid-April is the peak of the spring
plant-shipping season. Overworked staff members try to meet the
florid expectations of gardeners by selling them plants that are
not only garden-worthy but that also carry, for many customers, an
echo of the exotic places where Hinkley has collected _ Nepal,
Sikkim, China, Japan, Korea, Tasmania, Mexico and Chile.
 &HT;    The nursery office, an attractive prairie farmhouse of sorts, is
surrounded by open shade-canopies sheltering tables crowded with
flats, each marked with a customer's name and shipping date.
 &HT;    Hinkley's Michigan drawl crackles over a walkie-talkie clipped
to a plant-packer's belt. Concealed somewhere in the woodland
garden, he is the ghost in this botanic machine, enjoying a 10-day
respite from a busy spring speaking schedule and preparing for a
collecting trip to Japan.
 &HT;    A path leads into the benign enveloping shade characteristic of
the Northwest woods. The light falling on the mounded garden beds
seems detached from its source, and what it illuminates has a
freshness that is an attribute of the early season and of the
vegetation itself. A hundred yards down the path, Hinkley works in
mottled shade helping a new crew member shovel steer manure from a
garden cart onto a planting site.
 &HT;    Hinkley speaks quietly, slowly, but there is a sense of haste
about him, the result of living in what he calls ``a perfect
madness of plants,'' a garden that needs to be brought into peak
condition within the next few weeks. ``At this point it feels like
it's moving day,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``But as long as I keep bringing new plants into trial, it's
always going to be like this. I get tired of one plant, or it's
just not doing for me, so I get rid of it and start over again. But
every time you do that you want to rejuvenate the soil, and to do
that you've got to move another plant.''
 &HT;    Hinkley kneels on the ground, chopping at the soil with a border
spade and looking up from time to time as he talks. He is direct
and delicate at the same time, handling plants with none of the
hesitation of the amateur gardener. He overflows with affection for
the garden he has made, and yet his criticism of each individual
plant-form _ a kind of veiled self-criticism in fact _ is
unsparing.
 &HT;    Hinkley is bearded and balding, and he wears wide suspenders
over a T-shirt from the J.C. Raulston Arboretum at North Carolina
State University. Raulston, who died at 56 in a car accident three
years ago, was one of Hinkley's mentors and a widely respected
emblem of intellectual and horticultural generosity.
 &HT;    Hinkley has dedicated his next book, ``The Explorer's Garden,''
which Timber Press will publish in the fall, to Raulston and to
Gerald Straley of the University of British Columbia, another
gardening mentor who died in his 50s.
 &HT;    ``J.C.'s everywhere in this garden,'' Hinkley said. ``Every day,
I could take out a plant that he gave me, and I would never run out
of plants. He knew, he sensed what a good plant was.''
 &HT;    To sense what a good plant is _ to recognize it in the wild and
then confirm it in his own garden _ is the essence of Hinkley's
work.
 &HT;    ``We have all this Lutheran guilt,'' he says. ``We all moved
west from the Midwest where we couldn't have winter gardens, and so
our gardens in Seattle and Portland and Vancouver are amazingly
timid as far as what our climate can actually do.'' But there is no
timidity in this garden.
 &HT;    What takes it beyond timidity isn't massed plantings or vibrant
color or expansive scale or even mere exoticism. It is Hinkley's
subtle reliance on the globally diverse forms of individual plants.
Each plant, grown well, reveals itself and reveals something too
about its neighbor.
 &HT;    What creeps grows next to what climbs. The fastigiate and the
pendulous conspire. Bark peels, thorns protrude, vines finger their
way across an arbor, and what unites it all, what makes these
plants garden-worthy, is the interest they bestow upon each other.
 &HT;    There are few explicit canons for deciding what makes a plant
garden-worthy, but one of them _ a base line below the realm of the
esthetic _ is lack of ecological invasiveness. Most gardeners are
familiar with species that tend to be invasive in the garden, such
as Ajuga reptans, sometimes called carpet bugle.
 &HT;    But what haunts Hinkley is the thought of plants that can break
loose from cultivation and run rampant across the landscape _
purple loosestrife, kudzu, tamarisk, honeysuckle. ``My greatest
concern,'' he says, ``is the introduction of a bad plant.''
 &HT;    Invasiveness is a hot issue, and it inspires a botanical
xenophobia, a fear that just because a plant is exotic _ i.e.,
non-native _ it's inevitably invasive or otherwise harmful to the
suite of native plants, changing the balance of nitrogen in the
soil, for instance, or causing the water table to dip below the
roots of native plants.
 &HT;    But in horticulture, as in agriculture, the distinction between
exotic and native has been blurred by the ancient, extensive
exchange of plants for their economic or ornamental value. Because
plant material _ seeds, cuttings, fruits _ moves as readily as
humans do, human plant collecting, like the invention of
agriculture, predates history itself.
 &HT;    Hinkley points out some of the plants he admires _ such as
Podophyllum delavayi, a May apple from Sichuan, which, he says,
``deserves to be worshiped'' _ and some of the plants he thinks
will become important to American gardeners in the years ahead, not
only among ``plant nerds,'' as he puts it, but also among gardeners
generally. He points out a group called the woodland lilies _
Smilacinas, Polygonatums, Uvularias, Disporums and Disporopsis.
 &HT;    But above all he points out Hepatica _ Hepatica acutiloba, an
American native and Hepatica maxima, which grows only on one island
in the Japan Sea, Hepatica in a single clone, in many clones, in
enough clones one day to sell.
 &HT;    To a casual visitor, these are perplexing plants, modest,
growing in low mounds with rather formal, old-fashioned leaves and
small flowers, not half as striking as the arisaemas and trilliums
that are rioting in the woodland.
 &HT;    But besides being a ``simply good'' plant, Hepatica maxima, for
one, is also very rare in cultivation, which makes its goodness no
longer simple. It goes about its business in a quiet corner of the
garden, reaffirming a strange premise of life itself, for being
there at all is part of its beauty.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Verlyn Klinkenborg writes editorials for The New York Times.
He is the author of ``Making Hay'' and ``The Last Fine Time.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
