<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AUTHOR'S FIRST NOVEL IS A GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My wife of more than 45 years shot herself yesterday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that is what the police assume, and I am playing the
part of a grieving widower with enthusiasm and success. Life with
Sarah has schooled me in self-deception, which I find _ as she did
_ to be an excellent training in the deceiving of others. Of course
I know that she did nothing of the kind. My wife was far too sane,
far too rooted in the present to think of harming herself. In my
opinion she never gave a thought to what she had done. She was
incapable of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was I who killed her.''
</P>
<P>
   So begins ``The Drowning People'' (Warner Books, $24, 340
pages), 21-year-old Richard Mason's amazing debut novel that deals
with love, betrayal, murder and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Now James Farrell looks back on his life to figure out just what
led to the murder of his wife in their castle in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   It all began nearly 50 years ago, during a magical summer in
London. Having just graduated from Oxford and determined to pursue
a career as a violinist against his parents' wishes, James
encounters the beautiful aristocrat Ella Harcourt one day in the
park. Learning that she is engaged to an upper-class Brit she
doesn't love, 22-year-old James is determined to win her heart.
</P>
<P>
   They begin a passionate, clandestine and selfish affair and she
agrees to break off her engagement. Ella encourages James to accept
his friend Eric's offer of a place to stay in Prague, where he can
study with one of the great violinists of his day.
</P>
<P>
   When Ella and James are reunited, she forces James to prove his
love by committing an unspeakable act against Eric. Unable to face
himself, James breaks off the affair and retreats into his music.
Three years later, they will meet again, but the lies of the past
and a cunning act of murder will damn the future.
</P>
<P>
   Mason wrote ``The Drowning People'' when he was 18. How a
man-child could have so much wisdom and insight is baffling. His
elders will be jealous of his storytelling ability, not to mention
his beautiful command of the language. His descriptions of Prague
are lyrical and his take on British high society uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   Mason has produced a literary gem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Peters' latest mystery featuring archaeologists Amelia
Peabody and her husband, Radcliffe Emerson, (``The Falcon at the
Portal,'' Avon Books, $24, 366 pages) is a delight.
</P>
<P>
   As the Emerson clan is about to leave for the 1911 excavation
season in Egypt, they learn someone is selling fake antiquities and
trying to point the blame at archaeologist David Todros, who is the
best friend of the Emersons' son Ramses and the new husband of the
Emersons' niece, Lia.
</P>
<P>
   On arrival in Egypt, they learn that the director of
antiquities, who is terrified of Radcliffe, has once again given
him a very poor archaeological spot _ the pyramids of Zawaiet el
Aryan. Ramses is pursued by the pretty but dimwitted Maude, while
the Emersons' beautiful and bright ward, Nefret, is being courted
by almost every unattached American or British male in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   When Maude is found dead in a shaft at Zawaiet, her brother Jack
accuses Ramses of the murder. En route to the digs, someone takes
potshots at Amelia. More forgeries turn up, as does a small girl
who looks amazingly like Amelia. Meanwhile, there are accusations
of drug smuggling and Amelia must use all her wiles to clear
David's name and keep her family together.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the dialogue is witty, the pace is as fast as a
sandstorm, and the intrigue just escalates. But it is Peters' wily
cast of characters that keep this reader coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More light-hearted than the previous nine ``Prey'' thrillers,
``Certain Prey'' (by John Sandford, G.P. Putnam's Sons, $24.95, 339
pages) pits Lucas Davenport against one of his most unlikely foes.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis defense attorney Carmel Loan has almost everything
she wants _ a million-dollar practice, a Jaguar, a beautiful
apartment. But she doesn't have the gorgeous but not-so-bright Hale
Allen, a married attorney at her firm; so Loan uses one of her
former clients to hire a hit man to kill Allen's wife. To her
surprise, the assassin is a well-dressed young female named Clara
Rinker.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted by the FBI for 25 previous hits, Rinker has left few
clues behind. However, when one of Loan's former clients tries to
blackmail her, Loan again asks Rinker to help her clean up the
loose ends. Now the high-priced lawyer becomes a murdering
sociopath. Meanwhile, Davenport asks the FBI for help in tracking
down the Minneapolis killer. When he finds evidence linking Loan to
the murders, things really heat up.
</P>
<P>
   The previous ``Prey'' thrillers have all been riveting, with a
lot of edge. ``Certain Prey'' is more of a summer romp. Like
Davenport, you gain a certain respect for Rinker _ after all, she's
just doing her job. You root for Loan to get her comeuppance. And
you are glad Davenport will be around for the 11th ``Prey.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Martin Cruz Smith's latest thriller, ``Havana Boy,'' landed
on my desk, I was delighted, especially since its main character is
``Gorky Park's'' extremely likable protagonist, Arkady Renko. But
the book (Random House, $24.95, 329 pages) is as tired as the
middle-aged Renko, now suicidal because his beloved wife Irina is
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Renko has flown to Cuba after receiving an urgent message from
the Russian Embassy requesting his help in finding his old
acquaintance Pribluda. On arrival, he is told that a corpse just
fished out of Havana Bay is Pribluda's, but he soon learns that the
body had been in the water too long to make identification certain.
Renko wants to hang around to see if Pribluda is really dead and,
if so, how it happened and why.
</P>
<P>
   Once Havana held out the welcome wagon to Russians, but no
longer, not since the Soviet Union fell and all aid to the island
has stopped. The Cubans want Renko to leave immediately, and during
one of several attempts on his life, he ends up killing one of his
attackers. A female Havana police officer reluctantly decides to
help him solve the puzzle so he can go home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, Renko trudges around Havana wearing a cashmere
overcoat that still bears Irina's scent. Unable to speak the
language, Renko doggedly traces Pribluda's last days and meets an
unsavory cast of characters.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz's descriptions of the decaying Havana are beautifully
written. He is a master of weaving complex plot threads and drawing
out an incredible cast of offbeat characters. Yet the story seems
worn and faded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
