<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-DISABILITIES-1S     06-22 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABILITIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT NARROWS SCOPE OF DISABILITY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: UPDATES, added material, minor edits throughout.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday narrowed the scope of
a federal law banning discrimination against people with handicaps,
saying it does not apply to such disabilities as poor eyesight that
can be corrected medically.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on three related cases, the court dismissed lawsuits by
two nearsighted pilots, a truck driver almost blind in one eye and
a mechanic with high blood pressure _ all of whom were either fired
or denied employment.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the lawsuits was brought under the 1990 American with
Disabilities Act (ADA), which was designed to end discrimination on
the job, in housing and at medical facilities and other places that
serve the public. The court's dismissal of the suits means that the
ADA did not protect those plaintiffs and others like them.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decision, the ADA was thought to cover about 160
million people. As a result of the court's ruling Monday it covers
about 43 million.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines disability as ``a physical or mental impairment
that substantially limits one or more major life activities'' or a
condition where a person is ``being regarded as having such
impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing in the case of the two
nearsighted pilots, said, ``We hold that determination of whether
an individual is disabled should be made with reference to measures
that mitigate the individual's impairment, including, in this
instance, eyeglasses and contact lenses.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 7-2 opinion, she said, the poor eyesight of the two
pilots, Karen Sutton and Kimberly Hinton, failed to ``substantially
limit a major life activity'' for them, and therefore they were not
covered under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   The court reached the same conclusion in the other two cases,
ruling unanimously that truck driver Haille Kirkingburg and, by a
7-2 vote, that mechanic Vaughn Murphy should not be considered
disabled under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the cases, the court also ruled that the plaintiffs
failed to show that the companies they sued had banned them from an
entire class of jobs, such as pilot or driver. Instead, the court
said, the companies refused to consider each person for a specific
job because of strict, reasonable criteria that the plaintiffs
failed to meet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Sutton and Hinton, twin sisters who were regional
airline pilots from Spokane, Wash., applied for jobs as commercial
pilots at United Airlines in Colorado. Although they met basic age,
education, experience and Federal Aviation Administration
qualifications, United turned them down for employment because
their uncorrected vision was worse than the airline's requirement
of 20/100.
</P>
<P>
   In Kirkingburg's case, his employer, Albertsons Inc., a
supermarket chain, hired him as a truck driver in 1990 based in
Portland, Ore. Kirkingburg had had more than a decade's experience
and performed well when on a road test for the company. But after
two years with the firm, he took an exam and failed to meet
Department of Transportation standards for drivers. As a result,
the company fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to meet Transportation Department standards also led to
Murphy's dismissal. Murphy, who suffers from high blood pressure,
was hired by United Parcel Service in Manhattan, Kan., as a
mechanic, a job that required him to drive to different locations
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   A month after being hired, the company discovered Murphy's high
blood pressure, which disqualified him from driving under
government regulations, and fired him.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulings Tuesday, the court said that under the ADA, a
company can prefer certain physical characteristics over others,
such as favoring people with perfect vision over near-sighted
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``An employer is free to decide that physical characteristics or
medical conditions that are not impairments are preferable to
others, just as it is free to decide that some limiting impairments
make individuals less than ideally suited for a job,'' O'Connor
said in the pilots' case.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Bokat, general counsel of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
called the court's decision in rejecting the lawsuits ``extremely
important'' for American business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that those with true disabilities will continue to be
covered, but people with easily correctable conditions will not be
considered disabled,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Louis Bograd, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties
Union, a legal watchdog group, said the court's ruling were a
``serious blow'' to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has narrowed the ADA so that it covers only a small,
small group of people and not the people it was meant to cover,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years employers have won 92 percent of the 700 ADA
cases resolved in court from 1992 to 1997, according to the
American Bar Association. Lower courts had split over how far the
law's protections extend in the cases decided Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate ruling that also centered on the ADA, the high
court held 6-3 in a Georgia case that states may have to place
people with mental disabilities in homelike settings if they can
fare just as well there as in state hospitals. In a narrow
decision, the court said the ADA requires such community placement
of the mentally disabled whenever appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confront the question whether the proscription of
discrimination may require placement of persons with mental
disabilities in community settings, rather than in institutions,''
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote for the court. ``The answer, we
hold, is a qualified yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case, Lois Curtis and Elaine Wilson, two mentally
disabled women, challenged the state of Georgia's insistence that
they remain in a state hospital in Atlanta until places in a less
restrictive community care center opened.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the state should make places for them at the
care center because it would offer them a setting where they could
interact with more people who are not disabled and that forcing
them to wait amounted to isolating and segregating them from
mainstream American life.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
