<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-CO     06-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Swapping stories, swapping punches
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Larry L. King (the one who wrote ``Best Little
Whorehouse in Texas,'' not the little guy on TV) doesn't fight
anymore, except maybe with book publishers and that's mostly on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he's nearly 70 years old. For another, after
almost that many years of cigarettes, his lungs are, in his words,
``tattered as a 10-year-old sock.''
</P>
<P>
   A long-standing AA, he has now quit smoking as well after a
serious sinking spell put him in the hospital awhile back. Thank
goodness he still has the breath to tell a good story.
</P>
<P>
   We got together with friends for lunch one day. Somehow James
Dickey's name came up, famous dead author of the novel
``Deliverance,'' and King launched into this story.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't taking notes, so the quotes are approximate, and I have
cut the account about in half, having eliminated the cussing, which
is King's native tongue, being from Texas. As a result, the
following loses much in my retelling.
</P>
<P>
   This was in the 1970s. Playboy magazine was hosting a writer's
conference in Chicago. King and Dickey met for the first time while
occupying adjacent bar stools in the hotel lounge.
</P>
<P>
   King knew something of Dickey's disposition. Fellow author
Willie Morris had warned him that the man was nice enough sober,
but in the course of boozing could become mean and dangerous, more
so in the fact that he was big and strong.
</P>
<P>
   Morris's advice: ``Get in the first punch.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was after countless rounds of toasting one another's
genius as literary giants, Dickey's eyes turned suddenly cold and,
just as suddenly, he turned on King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever gave you the idea that you could write, you
blankety-blank,'' he snarled.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, you double-blankety-blank,'' King responded,
``that's exactly what you've been telling me for the last two
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Dickey could react, King punctuated his remark with a
roundhouse right, knocking Dickey off his stool and onto the floor,
then leaped upon him and proceeded to pummel him sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   As he fled the bar just before the cops arrived, his departing
words were, ``Thank you, Willie!''
</P>
<P>
   King laid low in his room until he figured he was safe from
arrest, then, noting on the agenda of hotel events that Dickey had
a poetry reading scheduled at that hour, headed to the gathering,
where he commenced to heckle Dickey relentlessly from the back of
the room. Finally a Playboy representative had to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime later, feeling he had put in a full day and deserved a
bit of relaxation, King made his way to the conference hospitality
suite where drinks were available. Better if hospitalization had
been available as well.
</P>
<P>
   Great turmoil greeted him at the door. A pie-eyed, cold-eyed
Dickey, in his usual challenge to a colleague's credentials as a
writer, had backed Michael Crichton into a corner and, with a rage
akin to a T-Rex from Crichton's ``Jurassic Park,'' was slapping and
cursing the terrified novelist.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of onlookers, well-read but ill-prepared for violence,
could do nothing but cry for someone to do something to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   King did something.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up from behind, King got Dickey by the neck in a strangle
hold, choked him to the floor and held him there until, at King's
prompting, Dickey squeaked surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The villain was vanquished. Ladies swooned. Maybe some of the
writers did, too. Such are the great moments of lesser-known
literatary history.
</P>
<P>
   You can read more of King's adventures, unexpurgated, in his
upcoming book, ``A Writer's Life in Letters, Or Reflections in a
Bloodshot Eye,'' TCU Press, set for publication this fall.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; web page, http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
