<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     06-22 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: A slippery slope too far
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent encounter in the House of Representatives between gun
control and religion was, depending on your politics, well intended
or set new standards for applied cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Littleton, the National Rifle Association and its
House allies faced gun control Armageddon in the form of a
developing consensus against too casually mixing criminals,
teenagers and guns. The nation seemed dangerously close to agreeing
that something, if only marginally, needed to be done. One can only
imagine what might have been said or done if Congress had debated
faith-based strangler's cloths instead of faith-based handguns.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans and the NRA did not disagree. Their
conclusion, however, was astonishing in its audacity. What was
needed was not more gun control but a more ubiquitous display of
the Ten Commandments. The thought became a scriptural poison pill.
An argument about hardware had transmogrified into a test of faith.
</P>
<P>
   In suggesting that public policy must submit to particularized
faith, the gun lobby has placed us on an amazingly smooth slope,
debating all the while how many angels can dance on the pointy end
of a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
