<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIAL-OF-CENTURY-HNS &LR;      06-22 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIAL-OF-CENTURY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK REVIVES HISTORY OF FAMOUS MURDER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHUYLERVILLE, N.Y. _ In the small canal hamlet once known as
Fort Miller's Bridge, a bullet crashed through the window in the
home of one of the wealthiest families in town 120 years ago this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Mary Eliza Billings was seated with her daughter and
maid, when without any sound except the discharge of the gun and
the shattering of the window pane, her head drooped to her left
shoulder,'' writes Hollis Palmer, assistant superintendent of the
Cohoes school district.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly end of Mrs. Billings' life marked the beginning of a
true tale of intrigue, mystery and wealth told in a self-published
book, ``To Spend Eternity Alone,'' released by Palmer on June 4 on
the anniversary of the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The story, according to Palmer, pits the eyewitness daughter,
Jennie Billings, against her father, Jesse Billings Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's death divided the hamlet, two miles north of
Schuylerville, into warring camps, and ultimately led to the trial
in nearby Ballston Spa of Jesse Billings Jr., a speculator, boat
builder, merchant and farmer who had amassed a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were newspapers from the whole country covering the
case,'' Palmer said. ``New York papers were here, Chicago papers,
San Francisco papers. It was the biggest trial of the 19th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, 52, a resident of Saratoga Springs, said he developed a
love for history hearing tales of the region's past at his
grandfather's knee. Reading about the history of this area in
upstate New York, he stumbled on the subject of his first book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading a book called `The Early Settlers of Eastern
Saratoga County,''' he said. There was one sentence that referred
to the Billings tragedy of 1878.
</P>
<P>
   His curiosity piqued, he looked for a book on the subject and
found none. He began his own research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I collected eight different newspaper accounts, I visited
local historians. I checked out wills. If you can think about the
range of research you have to do, I think I did it,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   There were 199 witnesses, so many that the defense commandeered
the Eagle Hotel, now the site of the post office in Ballston Spa.
The trial's five judges stayed at the Medbery Hotel, which still
stands, although no longer as a lodging. The jury stayed at the
American Hotel, now a newspaper bureau. The prosecution stayed at
the Sans Souci Hotel, which no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be the longest, most expensive criminal trial
in U.S. history until the 1930s,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   In today's dollars, defense costs alone were more than $3
million, Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He began the project a year ago, and with no particular
background in writing. He said he chose a chronological approach,
which made the organization simple. He hired four people to edit
his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only sleep four hours a night, so I literally have four
hours nobody else has,'' Palmer said. ``I would get up around 4
a.m. and write until I left for the gym every morning. I would try
and get at least four pages roughed a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer sought to maintain a cycle in which he would re-read his
last four pages, try to type two pages and outline two more. ``Once
I started it was like my doctoral dissertation. I really flew
through it,'' said Palmer, who has an advanced degree in
educational administration and political science.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to self-publish rather than look for a publishing
house, he said, because he anticipated trouble selling the work as
a first-time author without a recognizable name. In addition, he
wanted to maintain editorial control and to speed the timetable
between writing and publishing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a book on the process as his guide, he invested about
$20,000 and has printed 5,022 copies.
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping the book will attract a market for those interested
in the region and the broader market for aficionados of true crime.
</P>
<P>
   The title of the book, ``To Spend Eternity Alone,'' is based on
the circumstances surrounding Jesse Billings Jr.'s burial in the
family plot, one of the largest in Prospect Hill Cemetery adjacent
to the Saratoga Monument in Schuylerville. His is the plot's only
grave.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Palmer chuckles and says, ``Read the book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
