<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAELLA-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     06-22 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAELLA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY SPLENDORS OF PAELLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Paella! Spectacular Rice Dishes From Spain'' (Henry Holt,
$27.50), Penelope Casas gives nearly 50 recipes for this single
dish.
</P>
<P>
   Why not 100? The variations are infinite, once you grasp the
basic method. It's as easily mastered as risotto: saute seasonings,
add the seafood, meat or vegetables, then rice and liquid, cook
uncovered, then finish in the oven. After adding the rice, it takes
about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Casas, who has traveled all over Spain and written many
books on Spanish cooking, explains that paella is judged by the
rice, the way the Japanese judge sushi. The other ingredients are
garnishes. Like risotto, successful paella requires short-grain
rice, with its ability to swell and absorb a flavorful liquid.
Spanish short-grain rice, especially the bomba rice of Valencia,
the home of paella, is preferable, but Italian arborio rice works
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Paella is traditionally cooked in a shallow, uncovered pan on
top of the stove or over a wood-burning fire on an outdoor grill.
In her flawless recipes, Ms. Casas has developed a combination
stove-top and oven cooking method for home kitchens, including
variations for electric and gas ovens. A traditional paella pan is
not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the recipes are made with seafood, as you
would expect since paella is said to have originated in coastal
Valencia. The mixed version with pork sausage, chicken and seafood,
commonly called paella a la Valenciana in America, is reserved for
tourists in Spain, Ms. Casas says: it's not authentic. But there's
a fine recipe for this crowd-pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   In many classic paellas, one main ingredient is featured, like
an assortment of earthy mushrooms, or several kinds of shrimp, or
salt cod. Ms. Casas also branches out with combinations like a
delicious lamb and red pepper paella, salmon and asparagus paella,
and others seasoned with pesto.
</P>
<P>
   POTPOURRI-OF-MUSHROOMS PAELLA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Paella! Spectacular Rice Dishes From Spain''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon crumbled thread saffron
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   Kosher or sea salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken or vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 medium-size leeks, white part only, well rinsed and finely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { pound serrano ham or prosciutto in \-inch-thick slices, finely
diced
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, skinned, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   } cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds assorted fresh mushrooms (but not portobellos),
brushed clean and very coarsely chopped. If using shiitakes, remove
stems.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups imported Spanish or Italian arborio short-grain rice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a mortar or mini-processor, finely mash or process
saffron, shallots, \ teaspoon salt, parsley and garlic. Heat broth
in large pot over lowest heat. Preheat gas oven to 400 degrees,
electric to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oil in paella pan or other shallow casserole 17 to 18
inches in diameter, using two burners if necessary. Saute leeks and
onions over medium heat until softened. Add ham, cook 1 minute, add
tomatoes, cook 2 minutes. Add wine and let it boil away.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add mushrooms and cook 1 to 2 minutes to soften. Stir in rice
to coat with ingredients in pan. Pour in broth and bring to a boil.
Add saffron mixture and salt to taste and continue to boil about 5
minutes, occasionally stirring and rotating pan, until rice is no
longer soupy but still has some liquid.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer to oven _ 10 to 12 minutes for gas, 15 to 20 minutes
for electric _ until rice is almost tender. Remove from oven, put
in a warm place (on top of stove on unlighted burner, for example),
cover with foil and let rest 5 to 10 minutes, until rice is fully
cooked. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
