<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-2TAKES-NY     06-22 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENNEL ADDS A LILT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This is the fifth of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the chef
and owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. His
collaborator is Michael Ruhlman.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A single vegetable brought to its essence _ that's the meaning
of summer soup. Winter soups, with their soothing richness and
warmth, tend to be a composition of ingredients _ beef-vegetable,
chicken-noodle, chowder, minestrone.
</P>
<P>
   But summer soups refresh rather than soothe. And with so many
vegetables hitting their peak of freshness, my first urge for
summer soups is to isolate each one and make it more than what it
is on the vine, to refine it to its purest form. (An exception is a
bright gazpacho, whose many flavors blend into a single taste.)
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of summer soups _ one main ingredient served hot or
cold _ is that they're so easy. Zucchini, spinach, tomato, bell
pepper: the less you change them, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The technique for all vegetables is the same; learn it and you
can transform any vegetable into an extraordinary summer soup,
whether it's pea or fennel, watercress or artichoke, tomato,
carrot, haricots verts or even a soup of fine herbs, tarragon,
chive, parsley and chervil.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a matter of cooking your vegetable, pureeing it in a
blender, adjusting the consistency with stock or water, seasoning
it, and straining. Some vegetables, like tomatoes and cucumbers,
don't need to be cooked.
</P>
<P>
   The principle is simple: separate the flavor and color from what
contains it, the cellulose. The tool that separates it is the
chinois.
</P>
<P>
   The chinois, a fine-meshed conical sieve, is critical to these
soups. It creates the texture of luxury. The chinois combines
layers of fine mesh that catch even the smallest particles of
fiber, producing a finely textured liquid that feels like silk or
satin. Certainly, you could heat your puree and serve it without
straining, or you might pass it through a food mill and then
through a strainer. But again, when you're looking for an essence
of something, you must remove all the extraneous vegetable fiber
that has no flavor.
</P>
<P>
   My thinking about soups is so similar to my approach to sauces
that I always wonder, is sauce a soup or is soup a sauce? Which
came first? If it's a great summer soup, it can be a great sauce,
too. And vice versa. Sometimes we'll make a sauce that tastes so
good, we decide to put it in a cup and call it soup.
</P>
<P>
   Soups are the most chameleonlike dishes. They can be served at
any point during the meal _ as a canape, a first course, the
perfect intermezzo, a dessert canape, the dessert or a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite way is as opening canapes _ two or three spoonfuls
of intense flavor presented in small white bowls before the meal
begins. A canape soup excites the senses and prepares you for the
meal ahead. And these summer soups make the very best canapes,
because they focus on a single flavor. One sip of carrot soup
should be as powerful in flavor as a mouthful of carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of finesse make a big difference. And cooking the
vegetable well is one of them. All green vegetables should be
cooked in so much water that the water does not lose its boil,
water that has a cup of salt for every gallon, and the cooked
vegetable must immediately be shocked in ice water. This big-pot
blanching and chilling insures the brightest green possible.
</P>
<P>
   Root vegetables and red and yellow bell peppers are simmered in
a small amount of stock or cream, then blended.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of finesse is introducing some sort of fat _
cream or oil _ to enrich the flavor and add body, although some
vegetables, like cucumber and sorrel, require no fat. Perhaps
you'll also want an acid like sherry or balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Some vegetables benefit from a secondary component (add a little
blanched dill to the cucumber puree for cucumber soup, for
instance). But ultimately, the great summer soup is a single cooked
vegetable pureed and strained through a chinois.
</P>
<P>
   Gazpacho is the perfect warm-weather soup, and the
interpretation I offer here is intense, and easy. The main
technique is turning on your blender, and then straining the
liquid. The flavor is extraordinary because you're using fresh
ingredients _ cucumbers, onion, bell pepper, tomatoes _ and
overnight marination develops and blends flavors. Serve in a
chilled shot glass.
</P>
<P>
   Or serve it hot. Or think of it as gazpacho sauce: it goes
perfectly with grilled chicken or fish, and I serve it at the
restaurant as the sauce for an artichoke salad. (Put a little vodka
in your gazpacho sauce and it becomes the world's best Bloody
Mary.)
</P>
<P>
   The yellow pepper soup uses the simmering method; the peppers
and the cooking liquid are blended and strained. This soup can be
served hot or cold.
</P>
<P>
   The pea soup is extraordinary for its color. If you cook your
peas properly, you'll never see such a beautiful shade of green.
Put an ounce of it on a plate and it becomes an equally beautiful
sauce for sweetbreads. The menu will call it a coulis. But we all
know it's really summer soup.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PUREE OF ENGLISH PEA SOUP WITH WHITE TRUFFLE OIL
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups shelled English (green) peas, from about 3 pounds of pea
pods
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups salt
</P>
<P>
   \ to { cup vegetable stock or canned vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white truffle oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. To help peas retain bright color during cooking, place them
in a bowl, cover surface with ice, and toss peas and ice together
to chill.
</P>
<P>
   2. Fill a large stockpot with 6 to 7 quarts of water, and bring
to a boil. Add sugar and salt. Lift a small batch of peas with a
strainer, letting the ice fall back into the bowl. To keep the
peas' vivid green color, it is important that the water return to a
boil almost immediately, so add the peas in small quantities. Cook
peas until completely tender, 7 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. While the peas cook, fill a large bowl with ice water and
submerge a colander in it When peas are tender, transfer to
colander as quickly as possible. Lift the colander from the ice
bath, and drain the peas well. Using a food processor, puree the
peas, then scrape the puree through a tami (for best results) or
fine mesh strainer. There should be about 2 cups of puree.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer to a blender, and add \ cup vegetable stock and \
cup water. Blend the mixture until smooth; the color may lighten
from the air blended into it but will darken after it sits. Check
the consistency of the soup; if desired, add more stock or water.
Add a pinch of Kosher salt and white pepper to taste, and blend
again. Pour soup through a chinois or fine mesh strainer. To serve
cold, stir in the truffle oil and refrigerate in a covered
container until serving. To serve hot, reheat gently over low heat,
and stir in truffle oil just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 3 cups (6 to 12 servings)
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW PEPPER SOUP WITH PAPRIKA MOUSSE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 large yellow (or red) bell peppers, seeded and cut into
one-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1} cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   \ cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon paprika, or to taste.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare soup: In medium pot over medium-low heat, simmer
peppers gently in 1{ cups of heavy cream until they are tender and
cooked through, 15 minutes. Puree cream and peppers in a blender
for 2 to 3 minutes. Strain through a chinois; season with salt.
Press to release all liquid. Set aside, or refrigerate up to two
days.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare mousse: In small bowl, whip creme fraiche and paprika
until paprika is blended and mixture stiff. Add salt to taste.
Refrigerate till ready to use, up to two days.
</P>
<P>
   3. To serve: Whip remaining cream until it forms peaks. In a
medium sauce pan over medium-high heat, bring soup to a boil.
Remove from heat, and vigorously whisk in whipped cream to create a
frothy consistency. Pour the soup into hot soup cups, and garnish
with the paprika mousse.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 first-course servings.
</P>
<P>
   Gazpacho  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus chilling time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped peeled tomatoes (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped peeled red onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped English (seedless) cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chopped peeled garlic
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup plus 2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 cups tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   Sprig of thyme.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large nonreactive mixing bowl, combine all ingredients.
Cover, and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. The next day, remove sprig of thyme. Using a blender, puree
remaining ingredients until smooth. For a smoother texture, the
soup may be strained (this will reduce the quantity). Refrigerate
gazpacho until well chilled. Ladle soup into bowls, and serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 quarts (8 to 16 servings).
</P>
<P>
   Note: To peel fresh tomatoes, cut a shallow X on the bottom of
each tomato, and submerge in boiling water for 5 to 10 seconds to
loosen the skin. Remove and chill under cold water. The skins will
slip off easily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
