<HEADLINE>
WINE TRADE GATHERS TO SIP AND SELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ Every two years, representatives of the wine
business from all over the world gather here at a weeklong
convention called Vinexpo to meet, gossip, buy and sell, make deals
and, of course, party. In many ways, Vinexpo, which ended on June
18, is just another trade show. But it's different in one important
way.
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining is a part of all conventions, but if the subject is
selling airplanes or plumbing supplies, it's usually very separate
from the work. But wine is inseparable from entertainment, and over
two or three centuries, Bordeaux winemakers have made entertaining
a fine art. It's always been the way to sell wine here, where
chateaus are private homes and their cellars are open only by
invitation. Vinexpo, which began 20 years ago and this year drew
55,000 visitors from 125 countries, has only turned up the volume.
</P>
<P>
   Vinexpo draws together the whole range of wine professionals,
from winery sales and marketing representatives to buyers for
liquor stores to auctioneers and writers. Vinitaly, in Verona, is
similar, but it focuses on Italian wines. Vinexpo is international,
making it the place to see and be seen. (In off years, there's a
smaller version in Tokyo.)
</P>
<P>
   Consider the party given for the news media by the most famous
Bordeaux wine chateaus, organized as the Union of Great Classified
Growths. The dinner, for about 200, including nonmedia types like
sports figures, entertainers and restaurateurs who had wangled
invitations, was held in the courtyard of the wine cellars at
Chateau Latour. The chef was Pierre Gagnaire, whose eponymous
restaurant in Paris has three Michelin stars. The wines were
supplied by the hosts, and even for Bordeaux they were remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception, the aperitif was Krug Grande Annee champagne
in magnums. At my table the wines started with the 1982 vintages of
Chateaux Lascombes, Lafon-Rochet, Montrose, Gruaud-Larose and
Latour. Then came the 1961 Lascombes, the 1970 Lafon-Rochet, the
1979 Gruaud-Larose and the 1970 Montrose. They were followed by two
more from Chateau Latour, the 1966 and the star of the evening, the
1959. Two sweet Sauternes were served with the dessert: Chateau
Suduiraut 1975 and Chateau Rieussec 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Lavish as it was, this dinner was only one of many that evening
and merely one of the seemingly endless round all week long.
</P>
<P>
   Vinexpo is based in a convention center just north of here. The
main exhibition hall, about a mile long, houses most of the 2,400
exhibitors, grouped loosely by country. This year Eastern Europe
and Latin America were better represented than in the past.
Exhibitors from the United States included giants like E.&AMP; J.
Gallo, Canandaigua, Kendall Jackson and Robert Mondavi , along with
smaller producers like Duckhorn, Clos de Val and Bonny Doon.
</P>
<P>
   During Vinexpo, a social hierarchy quickly develops. At the top
are the fortunate few invited to stay at the most famous chateaus.
The best answer to the perennial question ``Did you have trouble
getting hotel rooms?'' is ``Well, actually, we're old friends of
Philippine'' _ de Rothschild, that is _ ``and we always stay at
Mouton.'' (``Old friends'' usually include some good customers.)
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, much of the time at dinners is spent discussing
other dinners and here, too, the hierarchy closely follows that of
the chateaus themselves. At the pinnacle are the five so-called
first growth chateaus, Haut-Brion, Latour, Lafite-Rothschild,
Margaux and Mouton-Rothschild. Then come the best-known of the
second growths, like Chateau Pichon-Lalande. An invitation from its
owner, May-Elaine de Lencquesaing, is as prized as one from a first
growth chateau. So, too, is one from Jean-Michel Cazes, the owner
of Chateau Lynch-Bages.
</P>
<P>
   The Gendarmerie is out patrolling in force for Vinexpo, trying
to rescue non-French-speaking visitors lost on the back roads. A
fortunate few use helicopters, the ultimate perk, to get from
Vinexpo to the chateau where they're staying and then to the
chateau where they're having dinner. The trick is to arrive a bit
late and say, ``My pilot got lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Vinexpo, deal-making in the guise of entertaining in
Bordeaux was a discreet, almost secretive phenomenon. Buyers and
potential buyers were met at the train station in Bordeaux and
whisked off to the chateaus before competitors could get to them.
There are stories of wine merchants' bribing bellhops and
concierges learn which buyers were in town and where they were
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux has changed greatly in the past three decades, but the
tradition of lavish and stylish entertainment has survived.
Television crews come to the big parties and the best-known chateau
owners appear on talk shows to promote their wines.
</P>
<P>
   The region is still a bit starchy compared with Burgundy and
California. But the big parties here make it very clear that the
wine trade will never be like the plumbing supply business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
