<SLUG> BC-TV-PAX-NETWORK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE PAX' BANKS ON THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Pax President Jeff Sagansky tells the story of
talking to a fellow airplane passenger, a guy who knew nothing
about the television business, and explaining that his nascent
network had a 1 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who that one person is who is watching, but you
better keep him happy,'' the passenger replied.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Pax has closer to 1 million viewers, and the story is
almost assuredly apocryphal, but you get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year old, the seventh network is desperate for
attention, any kind of attention, as it weaves in more original
``family friendly'' programming to its lineup. It is rarely
mentioned in discussions on the state of television, an
afterthought, the home of CBS reruns like ``Touched by an Angel''
and ``Diagnosis Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when many publications wrote last month about the
upcoming network fall lineups, Pax wasn't even included.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say that for one day, one stinkin', lousy, solitary
day, the network _ 30 or so channels removed from the rest of the
pack _ suddenly moved into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It would have to be something big, really big, and Pax has an
idea what it has to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pax TV, little Pax TV,'' spokesman Steve Sohmer said, ``is
going to own the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not all 1,000 years of it, but how about a day, 25
hours actually, with broadcast networks from around the world
linked to welcome in the year 2000 as it enters East to West?
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV, little Pax TV, would be the U.S. outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Now in addition to the networks, throw in some Internet
interaction, where people can soon start e-mailing in their hopes,
dreams, poems _ whatever _ for the next 1,000 years. What do you
have?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be the first-ever global, live, interactive
broadcast,'' David McGuigan said.
</P>
<P>
   McGuigan knows big; the producer for the project was also
involved in the landmark 1985 Live Aid concert. It's a smart
gambit. After coming into being, the biggest headlines Pax received
were for an initial advertising campaign that was viewed as
anti-gay. After that ... nothing. Meanwhile, the network is
building a schedule of original programming in a unique way, by
time slots rather than days. This coming season, for example,
features all new 8 p.m. shows.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Pax is touting its growth. Then again, starting out
with zero viewers there had better be some. The network needs a
jump-start. Just one day, one really good day, would be a nice for
openers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
