<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-CHEFS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCH FRESH INGREDIENTS: THE CHEF AS BEEFCAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advertisements are titled, ``famous chefs naked with their
blender.'' The first one appeared in the June issue of Food Arts, a
glossy trade magazine: Jean-Louis Palladin wearing nothing but some
jewelry, his glasses and a strategically placed Vita-Prep blender.
</P>
<P>
   The respected French-born chef at Palladin in Manhattan and Napa
in Las Vegas looks so sinewy and buff, a rumor spread that his
53-year-old head had been grafted onto a younger body. (Not true.)
The next models in the series may draw even closer scrutiny: Eric
Ripert of Le Bernardin and Aquavit's Marcus Samuelsson, two of the
food world's four-star heartthrobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ripert, for his part, is no stranger to the provocative pose. On
the cover of the Bernardin cookbook, published last year, he and
the restaurant's owner, Maguy Le Coze, smile mischievously behind a
table set with wineglasses and an ice bucket. Back to back, their
trim bodies are bent in a position known in the disco era as ``the
bump.''
</P>
<P>
   Cookbooks, television shows, magazines, personal appearances and
demonstrations, the whole business of ``branding'' _ success for
modern chefs can demand much more than just high-level cooking
skills. They need charm and glamor. And now, good looks: the chef
as hunk. It's a development that some chefs clearly revel in,
others tolerate and still others find silly and trivializing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, chefs  &UR; are &LR;  hot, in celebrity terms, and cooking
has never been more cool. That combination has led to a power shift
in the culinary pantheon. Dionysus is out; Apollo is in. The portly
middle-aged epicures who would never be seen out of the kitchen
during service have been replaced by pretty-boy wonders who work
out, ride motorcycles and accessorize their whites with the
occasional piercing or tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   The chef-hunk _ ``chunk,'' if you will _ is visible on almost
every other page of Bobby Flay's latest cookbook, ``Boy Meets
Grill'' (Hyperion, $32.50). For every five recipes, the reader gets
one picture of Flay, a generous ratio by cookbook standards.
</P>
<P>
   When Jean-Christophe Novelli flew to New York from London last
month to promote the American edition of his titillatingly titled
cookbook, ``Your Place or Mine'' (Clarkson N. Potter, $35), his
arrival was heralded by a barrage of smoldering head shots _
forelock dangling, dark eyes burning _ and news that the British
magazine Harper's &AMP; Queen had voted him the world's fifth sexiest
man: ``Tall, dark, and delicious,'' it gushed.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the June issue of Food &AMP; Wine on ``Sex and the
Single Chef'' goes even further, likening chefs to groupie-plagued
rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of women think chefs are hot,'' the article reports.
``And that's just where the trouble starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still dominated by men, the profession is being aggressively
marketed to its female following. Dana Cowin, Food &AMP; Wine's editor
in chief, said she published this breathless display of chef
idolatry because ``there's a buzz out there about how attractive
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Palladin has been a respected New York chef for 30 years, but
welcomes the attention from the Vita-Prep ad. In fact, over coffee
one morning last week at the Time Hotel, which houses his
restaurant, he seemed to be basking in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are a chef, you are a sex symbol,'' he said, good-humored
irony inflecting his thick French accent. ``It is a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there have always been sexy chefs. The difference nowadays
is that the ones blessed with looks as good as their soufflees are
being packaged and sold for both attributes.
</P>
<P>
   In August, both Vogue and P.O.V. magazine will feature chefs in
fashion spreads. Anthony Giglio, a senior editor at P.O.V., a
monthly manual for ambitious twentysomethings, said that the chefs'
publicity people were more than eager to place their clients in the
spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have called 20 reps for this story,'' he said. ``And
every single one of them had head shots ready to send overnight.
They ranged from straightforward, in whites with toque, to surreal
fashion poses, like the one of John Villa'' of Park View at the
Boathouse in Central Park. He was, Giglio recalled, ``in black
jeans and a black muscle T-shirt walking his Doberman _ the women
on the staff were swooning.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogue employed one of its top fashion photographers, Steven
Meisel, to shoot Matthew Kenney, 30, in the kitchen of his SoHo
restaurant, Monzu. The concept of the article, Kenney said, was
``urban chic'' _ models posing with an architect, a writer, him.
``The fact that a chef would appear in that group is pretty cool,''
Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney is also the subject of ``Life With a Side of Fries,'' a
film in production that has been likened to the fashion documentary
``Unzipped,'' with Kenney as its Isaac Mizrahi. The director and
producer of the documentary, Matthew Pestorius, said he chose
Kenney because he ``makes a great main character _ he's sort of
brooding.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when trying to get a documentary made, it helps to
have a leading man as handsome as any Hollywood actor. ``In the
course of going around getting financing for the film, we can throw
down a picture of Matthew and say, `Look, here's the star,' and
both women and men are, like, `Wow!' It's definitely a selling
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Many chefs reluctantly acknowledge that glamour has become a
necessity in their business. ``We don't have any choice,'' Kenney
said, ``if we want to compete in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
