<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PANEL VOTES TO EXPAND CARIBBEAN TRADE PREFERENCES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to last year's hurricanes and the threat
of increased competition from Asia, a Senate panel Tuesday agreed
to expand the Caribbean Basin trade initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous action in the Senate Finance Committee came as the
panel considered a package of bills to reauthorize trade laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean trade bill would expand the 1983 program to give
tariff preferences to formerly excluded items such as certain
textile and apparel products, footwear, canned tuna, petroleum and
watches and watch parts through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who sponsored the Caribbean trade bill,
said its purpose has evolved from giving the 25 CBI countries in
the Caribbean and Central America parity with Mexico to offering
humanitarian assistance following last fall's hurricanes Georges
and Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham said a new rationale for expanding Caribbean trade
looms in the near future when the international multi-fiber
agreement, which limits the quantity of apparel goods that each
country may sell, lapses in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up two nearly identical sport shirts _ one made in
Nicaragua, one in China _ Graham said there was one important
difference. The shirt made in Nicaragua was assembled from textiles
and thread from the United States, while the shirt made in China
was produced from fabric and thread from China.
</P>
<P>
   Once the multi-fiber agreement lapses, cheaper apparel made in
China and elsewhere in Asia could flood U.S. markets, driving out
apparel made from U.S. textiles, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, the committee rejected, 11-9, a proposal that
would have extended up to $10,000 a year in assistance to farmers
hurt by foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., who offered the amendment with Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said it would ``put farmers at a level
playing field'' with other workers who receive such benefits if
they lose their jobs because of foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman William Roth, R-Del., urged committee members to
address the issue next fall but not to adopt the amendment now.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Jonathan Hall of The Palm Beach Post contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
