address the issue next fall but not to adopt the amendment now.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Jonathan Hall of The Palm Beach Post contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUDE-CHEFS-ART-2NDTAK     06-22 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-CHEFS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the market.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no longer desirable for a chef aspiring to superstardom to
look like a Wagnerian baritone in a toque. Karine Bakhoum, a
publicist for many New York chefs, including Kenney, often advises
her clients to indulge less in their own art. ``Some of them,
they're fat and it's OK,'' she said. ``But others, they want to be
the next Bobby Flay and we're, like, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Murphy, 30, the chef at La Forchette, is also in the P.O.V.
fashion spread, looking fit in a form-fitting leather coat. He said
he ``doesn't have time'' to go to a gym, but stretches every
morning and hits a heavy bag at home, ``instead of beating up on
the sous-chef.''
</P>
<P>
   He also rides his Ducati motorcycle to and from work every day.
``Riding a bike is a workout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs can hardly be blamed for being more appearance conscious.
They're far more visible than ever before, in this era of the open
kitchen and, especially, the TV Food Network. One indicator of the
changing nature of chefs' fame is the volume of fan mail the
network receives. Recipes aren't the only things viewers request,
said Heidi Diamond, its senior vice president of marketing.
``Indecent proposals'' are not uncommon, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're passionate about these cute-boy chefs for a variety of
reasons,'' she said. ``Food is so sensual. There's something magic
about these people's hands and the way that they caress a knife or
handle a naked potato.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also accessible in a way that few stars are anymore. A
smitten fan can visit a chef's restaurant, eat his food, meet him,
perhaps even touch him.
</P>
<P>
   For publicity-shy chefs, this accessibility can be a
distraction. Floyd Cardoz, the soft-spoken chef at Tabla, is as
acclaimed as any of his high-profile contemporaries but an almost
invisible presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't, as a rule, just walk the dining room,'' he said.
``Unless I know the person or it's a good friend.'' Cardoz, who has
no personal publicist, added, ``I'm happy I don't get recognized
outside the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the chef-eat-chef world of New York restaurants, does the
camera-ready hunk stand a better chance of survival or success than
the quiet craftsman? ``I don't think it's easier to get a good
job,'' said Michael Batterberry, the editor of Food Arts magazine.
``I think it's easier to get media coverage. But if the talent is
equal, the better-looking guy has the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   And many aspiring chefs entering the business know it. Graduates
of the New York Restaurant School are ``hungry for attention,''
said Brendan Keenan, a program director at the school for eight
years. ``Previous generations of chefs let the food talk for
itself,'' he said. ``Now they want to be recognized by face and
name, as well as the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognized they are. Even hard-core foodies now inspect chefs'
8-by-10 glossies almost as closely as their menus. Jane Miller,
associate editor of publications at the James Beard Foundation,
said, ``We get pictures of chefs coming to cook at the Beard House
and we're always on the lookout for cute ones.''
</P>
<P>
   She said one member of the publications staff has a picture of
Samuelsson as her screen saver. This weekend, Samuelsson, the chef
at Aquavit, posed naked for the third ad in Vita-Prep's blender
series.
</P>
<P>
   When, a concerned diner might wonder, do chefs find time to
cook?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of how chefs are being spread thin, with
fashion shoots and everything,'' Ms. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The topic makes many chefs, and their editors, uncomfortable.
Neither Ripert nor Miss Le Coze would comment on their frisky
cookbook cover shot. And Judy Kern, editor of ``Le Bernardin Cook
Book: Four-Star Simplicity'' (Doubleday, $35), played it down. ``I
don't know if it's because they're good-looking or not
good-looking,'' she said. ``We could have put fish on the cover,
but we thought this would be a more interesting and inviting
image.''
</P>
<P>
   Flay, 34, hesitatingly agreed that his title, ``Boy Meets
Grill,'' was ``obviously a play on boy-meets-girl.'' And he
acknowledged the link between sex and fine food. ``I think that
cooking is a very sexy thing,'' he said. ``It's the old cliche that
the way to a girl's heart is through her stomach. And if you're a
professional chef, you have that ace in the hole.'' But when it
comes to the exploitation of his looks as a marketing tool, ``I'm
not that comfortable with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask my publisher why they put all those pictures of me in the
book,'' he suggested. His publisher declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many ``Baywatch'' stars yearning to be taken seriously,
today's chefs want to be appreciated as artists, not beefcake. As
they should be. But they might want to keep in mind that when James
Beard endorsed Cuisinart, he kept his apron on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
