A5287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      06-22 0219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE WINES OF MEDOC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Les Arums de Lagrange 1997, Chateau Lagrange, Bordeaux, France.
About $22. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the only important Bordeaux white wines were the
sweet wines of Sauternes and the dry whites made in the Graves
region, led by the white of the Chateau Haut-Brion. North of the
city, in the Medoc region, the only significant white wine was
Pavillon Blanc, from Chateau Margaux.
</P>
<P>
   According to the tough Bordeaux wine regulations, the Medoc is
red wine country and no white wine can carry any of the prestigious
appellations like Pauillac, St.-Julien or Margaux. Even Pavillon
Blanc can use only a Bordeaux appellation.
</P>
<P>
   Now a few other Medoc chateaus are putting out white wines,
gambling that their own reputations will outweigh the lack of a
prestigious appellation. The latest of these is Chateau Lagrange,
in St.-Julien. Les Arums de Lagrange is a blend of 60 percent
sauvignon blanc, 30 percent semillon and 10 percent muscadelle.
</P>
<P>
   The wine is elegant, harmonious and, unlike many sauvignon
blancs, it is not overly acidic. It will appeal to those who like
the Bordeaux style in white wines, and might even lure away some
committed chardonnay fans.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, les arums means the calla lilies in French.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EATING-WELL-NYT &LR;      06-22 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANCIENT GRAIN, NEWLY AU COURANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cachet of peasant food in this country and in Italy just
keeps growing. Farro is one of the more recent examples. As
Americans have been discovering this whole-grain variety of wheat,
Italians have been rediscovering it.
</P>
<P>
   It's now found in the best Italian restaurants, both here and in
the mother country. And when it's cooked like risotto and served as
farrotto, it may eventually displace arborio rice because it is not
just ``new,'' but also a good source of fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a whole grain it is perfect for all the current
diets that forbid white carbohydrates like white flour, white rice
and, of course, white sugar.
</P>
<P>
   After eating farrotto at Le Madri last week, I vowed to make it
part of my culinary repertory. Farro is a bit like barley but much
firmer, and slightly nutty like brown rice. It can be used like
barley in soups, but it is most appealing in risotto mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot of personality,'' said Marta Pulini, a consultant
to Le Madri and all the rest of Pino Luongo's restaurants. ``Serve
it with something strong, like morels or butternut squash or
dandelions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pulini remembers farro from her childhood because her mother
came from Umbria, where farro is commonly used. ``It was food for
country people,'' she said. ``Even in Italy it was not so well
known, but in recent years there has been much more interest in
country food because it is healthy and it is made by artisans.''
</P>
<P>
   By that Ms. Pulini means that the farro is grown organically on
small farms. (At least so far.) As for its healthfulness, farro has
about the same nutritional value as the whole wheat in breads: high
in B vitamins, vitamin E, magnesium, selenium and, of course,
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Farro was one of the first grains used in the Mediterranean
region. It has been found in ancient Egyptian tombs, but after
ancient times, it was gradually replaced in the Middle Ages when
new varieties of wheat were cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   In this country farro is sometimes confused with spelt, another
ancient type of wheat, and spelt is sometimes sold as farro, but
they cannot be used interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
   Farro has to be soaked before cooking in farrotto; the time
depends on its age and therefore hardness. Soaking overnight is
best; the farro will then cook in about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Farro prices vary radically, from $4.60 to $13 for 17 ounces. It
is available in Manhattan at Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Avenue
(79th Street), 212-452-0690; Buon Italia in the Chelsea Market, 75
Ninth Avenue (15th Street), 212-633-9090; Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560
Broadway (Prince Street), 212-431-1691; Fairway, 2127 Broadway
(74th Streets), 212-595-1888, and Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third
Avenue (71st Street), 212-737-0600. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FARROTTO WITH FAVA BEANS, TOMATO AND MARJORAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Le Madri &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes plus soaking overnight &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups farro
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, smashed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled and diced ripe tomato (1 large)
</P>
<P>
   { cup blanched and peeled fava beans
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh marjoram leaves, washed and torn
</P>
<P>
   { cup freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl filled with warm water, soak farro overnight at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large, shallow pan over medium heat, add 1{ tablespoons
of the olive oil, the butter, shallots and garlic. Simmer 2 to 3
minutes, stirring continuously with a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drain farro, and add to pan. When the grains are well coated
with oil and butter, start adding hot water little by little, just
enough to cover the farro. Stir often, and continue adding hot
water if needed.
</P>
<P>
   4. After about 10 minutes of cooking, add the tomato. Keep
stirring to prevent grains from sticking to pan. At this point the
farro should be just about cooked, its texture al dente. Add fava
beans; remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add marjoram, cheese and remaining oil. Season with salt and
pepper. Stir, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings as an appetizer or side dish. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
