<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Richmond, Va.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush takes
aim at Vice President Al Gore, saying there's a ``huge difference''
between the two early front-runners. ``He thinks Washington has all
the answers. I don't,'' Bush says of Gore. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ After a campaign stop in Virginia, Gov.
George W. Bush meets with U.S. Senate supporters and raises money
at a glitzy capital fund-raiser. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   HATCH-2000 (Washington) _ Saying the country is in need of a
``moral resurgence,'' Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah announces that he
plans to run for Republican presidential nomination. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-DISABILITIES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court narrows the
scope of the American Disabilities Act that bans discrimination
against people with handicaps. It says the law does not apply to
such conditions as poor eyesight that can be corrected medically.
By MARK HELM. (Will update.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-BIAS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court makes it easier for
victims of job discrimination to win extra damages from their
employers. In the case of a woman denied a promotion because of her
gender, the court rules 7-2 that such victims can collect punitive
damages without showing their employer's conduct was ``egregious.''
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-STADIUMS (Washington) _ A Senate panel hears arguments on
a proposal that would require owners of National Football League
and major-league-baseball teams to pay at least half the costs of
building a new stadium. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., the bill's
author, says it is aimed at stopping teams from threatening to
leave an area unless a new stadium is built with mostly public
funds. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Also will be filed in the ``s''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL-OATH (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
is scheduled to administer the oath of office on June 29 to James
Hormel, the American ambassador-designate to Luxembourg. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REFUGEES (Skopje, Macedonia) _ President Clinton urges
patience and vows allied support for ethnic Albanian refugees who
eagerly wait in tent camps to return to Kosovo. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Stenkovec, Macedonia) _ As he ends a European
visit heavy with talk of finances and politics, President Clinton
comes face to face with the more human element of geopolitics and
speaks to U.S. troops who will join peacekeeping forces inside
Kosovo. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore, behaving as though they already have their
party's presidential nomination, are competing for the political
center, campaign funds and the lead in the polls. So far, Bush is
outpacing Gore on all three fronts, but the race has just begun. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS (New York) _ The San Antonio Spurs and New York
Knicks prepare for Game 4 of the NBA Finals on Wednesday night. The
Spurs lead the best-of-seven series 2-1. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
