<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-KITCHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST KITCHEN: THE RIGHT TONGS: HANDS YOU CAN COUNT ON   (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just a few years ago, kitchen tongs were practically
unknown to home cooks. Now, no one can live without a pair. But as
useful as tongs can be, they are not the perfect tool for all
tasks. Tongs can tear delicate foods, and the shape can make
picking up thin slices of food maddeningly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   I tried five pairs to see which worked the best all around. For
such a simple tool, there were surprisingly great differences among
them. A good pair of tongs should not open too widely. If they
expand more than about six inches, you will have to keep them
partially contracted rather than let them lay comfortably in your
palm. The tongs must also move fluidly, and the tension of the
springs should not be too great, to avoid muscle strain.
</P>
<P>
   A pair by Hoffritz demonstrated all that tongs should not be:
They did not open and close easily, and the spoon-shaped ends were
so concave that the edges pierced every piece of food I tried to
lift _ slices of roasted eggplant, sauteed baby zucchini and
poached white peaches. They are $9.99 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway
(80th Street), (212) 787-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Edlund tongs open too widely, but worse, the ends are squared
off and rimmed with sharp, pointy teeth that tear up whatever they
touch. They are $12.99 at Broadway Panhandler, 477 Broome Street
(Wooster Street), (212) 966-3434.
</P>
<P>
   A pair with flat, plastic spatula ends from Gracious Home _ 1220
Third Avenue (70th Street), (212) 517-6300, for $8.99 _ were a
failure with small pieces of food and round shapes like potatoes
and peaches. But they were fantastic with broad, flat foods like
eggplant. The spatula ends were gentle and took hold from both
sides, giving me plenty of control.
</P>
<P>
   Amco stainless steel tongs, the brand many chefs use, were
sturdy, and gave you a sense of dexterity _ I felt I could flip a
pin if I needed to. My only complaint about these tongs _ $4.98 at
Zabar's _ is that the spring mechanism is a bit tight.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen tongs by Oxo were by far the best. They moved
fluidly, the spoon-shaped ends were nearly flat and softly edged so
they did not damage food, and I could make extremely precise
movements _ from picking up a sprig of thyme to moving a soft-shell
crab claw back into place. They are $9.95 at a Cook's Companion,
152 Atlantic Avenue (Clinton Street), Brooklyn, (718) 852-6641.
</P>
<P>
   A final but important consideration is length. Most models are
available in 8-, 10-, and 12-inch lengths. When sauteeing at a high
temperature, a 12-inch pair may seem best, but with every extra
inch you lose some control. Generally, 8-inch tongs are best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
