<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPERM-BANK-HNS &LR;      06-22 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPERM-BANK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPERM BANK OFFERS MIRACLES FOR THOSE FIGHTING ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Suspended in liquid nitrogen vapors, at an
unimaginably cold minus 156 Celsius, is the possibility of
parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   In vials, stored in cryogenic tanks, is the frozen sperm of
young men who have had to plan for future fatherhood even as
they've fought life-threatening illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Men, some as young as adolescents, rely on an underused,
somewhat unknown sperm bank. The Assisted Reproductive Technology
Laboratory at Albany Medical College stores the sperm of men
risking reproductive damage from chemotherapy or radiation during
cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Here, lab director Charlene A. Alouf and other embryologists
conduct the well-known stage of in vitro fertilization, when a
petri dish, awash in a couple's sperm and eggs, substitutes for a
woman's fallopian tube. If science sometimes provides the
possibility of biological parenthood, so too does the faith and
determination of the couples involved, particularly the prospective
fathers who have had to confront cancer, treatment and life,
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   One father, George, relied on the sperm bank to have a son, now
almost 4, with his second wife. Another married couple, Carl and
Sandra, are just starting to plan a family. Because they wanted to
preserve some privacy in this highly personal subject, they
requested that their last names not be used.
</P>
<P>
   George, who had testicular cancer, hopes to alert men to this
disease, and to the foresight of banking sperm in the event of
illness. Now chasing a preschooler around, George is awestruck by
his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so amazing that someone could come from something in a
frozen state, and become this little man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carl, treated for Hodgkin's disease, also wants to sound
optimistic by stressing the importance of family support and
looking forward when fighting illness. ``It was one year of my
life, and I've lived nearly 35. I don't let that one year of life
consume me.''
</P>
<P>
   George's story begins as many Americans': Married for the second
time, with two young children from his first marriage, George and
his wife of two years had just started planning to have children.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was diagnosed with testicular cancer in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One doctor missed the diagnosis, but, bothered by a heavy,
uncomfortable sensation, George consulted a second urologist, who
found a quarter-sized tumor and recommended the subsequent surgery
to remove the testicle.
</P>
<P>
   Before George elected to have precautionary radiation, a nurse
who is a family friend advised him and his wife that the treatments
could cause sterility. He says the urologist who treated him never
mentioned the option of banking sperm.
</P>
<P>
   George, then 35, was out of surgery five days when he started
collecting his sperm to store at the Albany Medical College lab.
The step did not necessarily ease the anxiety that he might have
missed the chance to be a father, a second time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel like I would never be able to have children
again. That was a big fear I had with the cancer, and the
radiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing, and time, became critical factors in prompting the
couple, in the early months of 1996, to use George's banked sperm
to help them conceive: The radiation had in fact lowered his sperm
count, and his wife was then 38, said George.
</P>
<P>
   George's stored sperm, analysis showed, contained two key
components of fertility: sufficient numbers and movement. This
allowed George and his wife to choose artificial insemination. His
wife took Pergonal, the powerful fertility medication that
stimulates egg production. They sweated out the possibility of
multiple births, realizing the often attendant medical problems
such children can have.
</P>
<P>
   Their first attempt at conception failed. ``Naturally, the first
time was a letdown, and the second time, we were very reluctant,
because we didn't think it was going to happen again. Then, when it
did, we were very excited and so happy about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's health insurance paid for the procedures. Coverage
for assisted reproductive technologies, which cost thousands of
dollars, differs from plan to plan, but remains rare, according to
doctors. One cycle of in vitro, for example, can cost $4,000 to
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   George views the conception as ``more of a miracle than
anything.'' The couple's son was born Nov. 2, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   George is approaching the five-year benchmark since diagnosis,
which medically defines a cancer survivor, and his interim tests
have shown no signs of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He has moved on to savor late fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would have a 3-year-old at 40 years old. I
think it's better to have children when you're older, because you
can appreciate them more, rather than when you're younger.''
</P>
<P>
   George's sperm count has regenerated, though he is keeping his
banked sperm in storage. ``We'd like to have another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids,'' he said, ``are great.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carl and Sandra had been engaged a mere 11 days when he was
diagnosed Oct. 25, 1995, with Hodgkin's disease, the form of
lymphoma that is more responsive to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Carl had just entered his freshman year at Albany Medical
College, beginning his plan to specialize in family practice.
Sandra was well into her career as a graphic designer.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to have children came up on their first date, most
likely because both come from big families: Carl's has 15 children
and Sandra has four siblings. As their relationship progressed, the
number six became a somewhat playful hint about the size of their
future family.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Sandra, who is not big on hospitals, said she'd be willing
to return to a hospital six times in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The couple married June 27, 1997, a year later than they
originally planned so that Carl could finish his treatment. Carl
also took a leave from medical school. Chemotherapy, administered
in eight cycles from November 1995 until July 1996, was causing
nausea that forced Carl to lose class time.
</P>
<P>
   Medical school ``deserves your full attention. ... My disease
deserved my full attention, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A surgeon friend referred Carl to the sperm bank at Albany
Medical College; after discussing with his oncologist the
possibility that chemotherapy could cause sterility, Carl opted to
bank six samples before beginning treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Carl was a medical student, Sandra said, ``I don't
know if we would have thought about going to the lab, had we not
been informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Both come from Roman Catholic families _ the church objects to
reproductive technology _ but the use of the sperm bank and
possible subsequent help to conceive did not pose for them an
impossible moral dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that if we're going to have a family, this was
our only option. We thought it was appropriate to go ahead and make
the donation,'' Carl said. ``From our standpoint, we practice our
faith every day, we're good honest people and we thought the good
Lord wouldn't object to this.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the harsh chemotherapy has lived up to its billing.
Tests showed that Carl was sterile immediately after treatment,
and, two years later, analysis showed only one viable sperm.
</P>
<P>
   The two feel the timing is right to begin planning a family,
particularly since Carl shows no recurrence of cancer and is
finishing the second of two study-intensive years of medical
school. Sandra is beginning fertility testing, which will help
determine the method they'll choose to conceive.
</P>
<P>
   They've ruled out no options, from having one child, to six, to
adopting a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be blessed if we just have one. If we have six,
great,'' said Carl. And, if they cannot conceive, ``that's just
fine, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, Carl pointed out, is at the threshold they had hoped
for just a few years ago, when they predicted they'd be paying a
visit to the sperm bank, saying, ``Here we are, we're ready to
start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
