<SLUG> BC-GOOD-CROPS-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GRAIN AND CORN GROWERS ANTICIPATE A HEALTHY HARVEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Just for pleasure, Rodney Mowery likes to stand in the
bed of his pickup truck and look out across an expanse of tall corn
in one of his fields just south of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It has been years since Mowery has seen corn this good. He won't
know if it will be a bumper crop until he starts harvesting in a
few weeks, but one of his fields, located on rich bottom land, is a
good candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many Texas growers, this member of a farming family from
Rosharon is enjoying one of those rare periods of high yields.
</P>
<P>
   A series of agricultural plagues _ droughts and floods during
the planting season, soaring temperatures, crop-devouring insects
and a toxic fungus known as aflatoxin _ have meant bad crops for
many Texas farmers since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest estimates of potential yields for the two biggest
feed grains range from ``near-record'' for corn in the Central
Texas Blacklands to ``awesome'' for grain sorghum in the Coastal
Bend.
</P>
<P>
   This year's rains have come in the nick of time all the way from
the Lower Rio Grande Valley, where some crops already are being
harvested, to the later-planted upper portion of the Texas
Panhandle, where corn plants are only about a foot tall.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton County agricultural agent Johnnie Cosper sees the
best-looking crop of grain sorghum in years and ``some excellent
looking corn.'' The rice crop is beginning to head, and there have
yet to be major problems with disease or insects.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be a little early in the growing season to be
bragging about the prospects for cotton, observers say, this most
important of Texas crops is off to a good start. The same is true
for rice and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   This year's promise of good yields won't dispel the storm clouds
on the horizon for the struggling farm economy.
</P>
<P>
   The selling price for milo in the Valley _ a low-lying area that
borders Mexico _ is approximately $3.50 per 100 pounds, ``way below
anything that could possibly be considered a profitable price,''
said John Norman, a Texas A&AMP;M Extension Service entomologist
stationed in Weslaco.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the milo from the Valley, where the harvest is well
under way, goes into Mexico to feed poultry there.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of corn, the current national market price is only
about $2.25 per bushel, compared with near &UR;  &LR; $3 per bushel during
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Crop prospects are equally good in Central Texas, which was hit
hard by last year's drought.
</P>
<P>
   With just one more rain, the farmers in Central Texas could see
near-record yields on corn and milo, said Williamson County
agricultural agent Ronald Leps of Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I fear is that even if we have above-average yields, with
commodity prices being as low as they are, it will be tough to make
the debt carried forward from 1996 and 1998. The agriculture
picture is not really good,'' Leps said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mowery family grows rice and soybeans in addition to corn,
in an effort to weather the ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Their tall corn at Rosharon is in stark contrast to 1998 and
1996, when the Mowery fields were withered by drought. Out of 250
acres last year, about 160 acres were so ``horrible'' they didn't
warrant running a combine through, Mowery said.
</P>
<P>
   Too much rain also is a threat. Between the 1996 and 1998
droughts, it rained so much in the Houston area during the early
months of 1997 that Mowery's corn crop never got planted.
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall since the start of this year hasn't been heavy.
Rosharon was running eight inches below normal through a week ago,
Mowery said, but showers have come just in time.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny dents in the kernels of corn are evidence that the crop is
past the stage where it could be damaged by lack of rain or searing
heat, always a threat during Texas summers. Growers were able to
plant early this year, a big help in getting ahead of hostile
weather.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in Central Texas. Even without another drop of
rain, the corn crop around Waxahachie will be above average, said
county agent Gary Stanford. ``What a difference a year makes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, last year's corn was so poor the dried-up stalks
were baled for cow feed.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean acres have pulled ahead of corn in Ellis County, and the
beans look as impressive as the corn, Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really proud of the crop, from the Blacklands to the
Coastal Bend,'' said Jerry Don Glover of Dimmitt, executive
director of the Texas Corn Producers Board. Panhandle fields were
hammered by terrible storms, but corn can take it, Glover said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
