Yugoslav bus. Under police escort, they were driven to the Croatian
border. From there, the soldiers were transferred to a Croatian
tourist bus rented by the U.S. Embassy and were driven to the Pleso
airstrip in Zagreb. Then they were flown to Ramstein Air Base in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the soldiers were whisked away to the Landstuhl
Regional Medical Center for a couple of days of testing before
their families arrived. So the Jackson group proceeded to
Washington, without the fruits of their labor.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Jackson had obtained the release of Goodman,
the pilot was not delayed by military authorities in Europe;
instead, the group was flown home aboard Air Force One and treated
to a ceremony in the Rose Garden. That was under Ronald Reagan, a
Republican president viewed as hostile to civil rights. Under
Clinton, who prides himself as a friend of African-Americans,
Jackson did not receive the red-carpet treatment, causing Jackson
to view the administration as ingrates.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he was ``very pleased'' that the soldiers were
coming home, Clinton said that nearly 1.5 million Kosovars could
not enjoy similar freedom. The president said conditions for ending
the bombing were simple: ``The Kosovars must be able to go home
with security and self-government, Serbian security forces must
leave Kosovo. An international security force must deploy with the
power not just to monitor but to protect all the people of Kosovo,
Albanians and Serbs alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was carrying a private letter to Clinton from
Milosevic, strongly urged the president to release two Serb
soldiers held by U.S. military as a reciprocal peace gesture.
Several weeks later, the administration did just that, denying the
release represented a quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by David Letterman how he could be civil to such an
international outlaw, Jackson's answer was simple: ``He had the
power to keep our guys or let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he returned from Yugoslavia, ``Jetstream Jesse,''
as he is sometimes called, was off to Africa, successfully
brokering a cease-fire in the Sierra Leone civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no budgetary commitment to rebuilding this
war-torn nation as we heard in Europe,'' Jackson said, after taking
credit for securing the release of 2,000 prisoners of war, most of
them children and soldiers from bordering countries. ``When the
Yugoslavia war is over, there will be billions spent on rebuilding
the cities. The same kind of security and stability and democracy
in Kosovo and Yugoslavia must apply to Sierra Leone and to Africa
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's exploits aren't likely to stop with Yugoslavia and
Sierra Leone. After all, this is the same person who crashed the
1985 Geneva Summit that was supposed to feature only Ronald Reagan
and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Jackson confronted
Gorbachev in a crowded lobby, asking about the treatment of Soviet
Jews. Where he shows up next is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (George E. Curry is editor-in-chief of Emerge magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
