<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOOD-CROPS-ART-2NDTAK     06-22 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-CROPS-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
HOUSTON: Glover said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's grain sorghum looks like an awesome crop in the
Coastal Bend area around Corpus Christi, said Jeff Nunley,
executive director of the South Texas Cotton and Grain Association
in Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   San Patricio, one of the major counties for grain sorghum,
probably will average 5,000 pounds per acre or better, estimates
County Agent Jeff Stapper of Sinton.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Lower Rio Grande Valley, combines are working to
harvest a grain sorghum crop covering perhaps 450,000 acres, said
Norman of Texas A&AMP;M. The acreage appears to be up sharply, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers who raise these crops have pinched pennies, trying to
eke out a profit in a year when they knew prices would be low.
</P>
<P>
   Mowery, for instance, chose to do without a fertilizer test,
applying just a little nitrogen and hoping there would be enough of
the other plant nutrients carried over in the soil from past years.
</P>
<P>
   To save on fuel, his cornfields weren't cultivated. Resulting
weeds and grasses were held back using the cheapest herbicide on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Up the coast in San Patricio County, there are cornfields
containing what appear to be 100 bushels per acre, said Robert Box,
general manager of the Planters Grain elevator in Odem.
</P>
<P>
   There will be as much corn produced in the county this year as
there was in 1998, he predicts, although the acres planted are off
by 45 percent. Aflatoxin, not expected to be much of a problem this
year, takes the blame for the cutback in acreage.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of grain sorghum from the sprawling, flat
fields there will be placed into storage unless prices improve,
according to the manager of the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, prices at the start of harvest were at least 60 to 70
cents per 100 pounds higher than now, Box said. Only one time since
he started with the co-op in 1983 have prices been lower than now,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon demand and price, there is a very strong
possibility that from 80 to 95 percent will be stored,'' Box said.
Farmers who need cash flow will put their harvest into the
government loan program.
</P>
<P>
   The sorghum will be stored in hopes of getting a better price in
the future. The only thing that could cause a price rally would be
problems with the corn crop in the Midwest, according to Box. At
latest report, the crops there were doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   Corn and grain sorghum are virtually interchangeable for feeding
livestock, although historically the sorghum sells for less.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that sorghum prices are way down is a poor
outlook for exports, Box explained. In past years, Japan was a big
buyer, but it apparently has looked elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. cotton crop being pegged at a possible 18 million
to 19 million bales, ``I don't see much hope for prices,'' said
Texas A&AMP;M economist Carl Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley farmer who picked this year's first bale of cotton in
Texas, Thomas Zdansky of Lyford, complains about the current
50-cent-per-pound price.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five cents a pound or more is needed to make growing
cotton worthwhile, according to Zdansky. ``When I was a kid, it was
50 cents,'' said the farmer, who started growing cotton in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of his bales, the first one, brought a good price,
which was picked in late May and was auctioned for a whopping
$3,000. A 477-pound bale, it would have been worth only $238 at
current prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Insects weren't bad this growing season, and agricultural agents
expect to harvest a very satisfactory bale per acre or slightly
more from this year's fields. The Valley was the site of the beet
army worm invasion in 1995, when the plant-eating pests spread up
the coast and north to San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   The acres planted to cotton are up, and just within the area
from South Texas to Uvalde to Fort Bend County, 1 million bales
could be produced.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. crop will be larger than can be sold at a price higher
than the federal loan, Anderson said, and farm-level prices could
drop into the mid-40-cent range.
</P>
<P>
   There have been severe storms in the Lubbock area, but on the
other side of the coin, he said, that is an area where rain always
is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Huge swaths of fields were hammered by hail, but cotton is grown
on millions of acres there. Most hail-damaged fields have been
replanted.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook there remains good. ``We are light-years ahead of
where we were at this time last year,'' said A&AMP;M agronomist Randy
Bowman of Lubbock. ``The moisture is outstanding, and the planting
was very successful. There was good, warm soil, and it seemed to
click.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
