<HEADER>
A5359 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-REMAKES-TEX     06-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-REMAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVER GIRLS (AND BOYS) ON THE REMAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget ``The X-Files'' _ nothing on the radio is what it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Ya know that new song by Pearl Jam, ``Last Kiss?'' That's really
an old song by J. Frank Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   How 'bout Jo Dee Messina's ``Lesson in Leavin'''? Not hers.
Dottie West had a No. 1 hit with that in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for ``Players Holiday,'' currently being sung by a rap
army made up of T.W.D.Y., Too Short and Mac Mall. That's really
Bill Withers' ``Lovely Day'' in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Remakes in pop music are, obviously, nothing new. Right now,
though, the radio waves and music charts are inundated with them.
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than 10 remakes are currently on Billboard's country,
R&AMP;B, modern rock or pop charts; several others are getting serious
airplay.
</P>
<P>
   So in case you thought Lenny Kravitz wrote ``American Woman,''
here's our remake guide, with the song, current artist, original
artist, chart action and our verdict on whether the new song does
the old one any justice.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Last Kiss''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Pearl Jam
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 2 on Modern Rock Tracks, 55 on Hot
100
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: J. Frank Wilson, born in Lufkin
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 10 in 1964
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Pearl Jam's upgrade of Wilson's sad tale of a couple's
last kiss amid a car accident is stunning. It's far more
melancholic and effective than Wilson's campy, very-'60s version.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``American Woman''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Retro rocker Lenny Kravitz
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 7 on Mainstream Rock Tracks
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: The Guess Who
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 4 in 1970
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Most of what Kravitz does sounds like remakes from the
'70s anyway, so what's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Lesson in Leavin'''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Country star Jo Dee Messina
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 12 on Hot Country Singles, 61 on Hot
100
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: Dottie West
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 1 in 1980
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Way cool. Messina's one of country music's few
hopefuls, and her take on West's
you're-gonna-get-what's-coming-to-you anthem ranks as one of this
year's best country songs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Can't Take My Eyes Off You''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: R&AMP;B goddess Lauryn Hill
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: Has yet to be released as a single, but
local pop radio station KISS/106.1 has already put it in heavy
rotation
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 6 in 1967
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Here, the usually despotic and opinionated Hill is
romantic and tender; it's nice to hear this other side of her.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Crazy Little Thing Called Love''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Country great Dwight Yoakam
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 25 on Hot Country Singles
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: Queen
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 1 in 1980
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Dwight Yoakam may be one of country music's greatest
singers, but his soft spot for sap like this _ and various Elvis
covers _ is embarrassing. Please make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Players Holiday''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Rap team T.W.D.Y., Too Short and Mac
Mall
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 40 on Hot R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: This is really Bill Withers' ``Lovely Day''
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: Reached No. 1 in the UK in 1978, but
never cracked the Top 20 over here
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: The perfect example of what's wrong with rap today: Too
many remakes and samples, not enough originality. We could do a
separate story on all the samples and remakes rappers have borrowed
to make their own songs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``God Must Have Spent a Little More Time on You''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Country vets Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 14 on Hot Country, 38 on Hot 100
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: 'N Sync
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 3 on Adult Contemporary
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Alabama pulled a Mark Chesnutt here, remaking this 'N
Sync ballad as fast as Chesnutt did up the recent Dionne
Warwick-penned Aerosmith hit, ``I Don't Wanna Miss a Thing.'' Whose
``God'' is better? Major toss-up _ it's both the perfect pop
``and'' country song: sweet and memorable. Let the fans fight it
out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Blue Monday''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Industrial-music headache-inducers Orgy
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 17 on Modern Rock Tracks
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: Groundbreaking English techno band New Order
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 4 in 1983 on the UK charts
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Easily one of the worst covers this side of Limp
Bizkit's recent thrashing of George Michael's ``Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Cars''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Metal dudes Fear Factory
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: No. 21 on Mainstream Rock Tracks
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: New Wave pioneer Gary Numan
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 5 in 1980
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Funny, this actually sounds very true to original. One
reason: Numan sings on it. Fear Factory's trademark layer of
brick-wall-falling-loud guitars makes it even cooler. Good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Song: ``Sweet Child O' Mine''
</P>
<P>
   Currently being done by: Pop singer Sheryl Crow
</P>
<P>
   Current chart position: Has yet to chart. Pray it won't.
</P>
<P>
   Original artist: Guns N' Roses
</P>
<P>
   Highest original charted: No. 8 in 1988
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Sorry, Sheryl. No one can do Axl better than Axl.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
