<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKET-PRICES-ARTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMING-ARTS TICKET PRICES INCH STEADILY UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: pls note that accents should be added to the ``e'' in Jose
(Jose Carreras) and the ``a'' in Placido Domingo.) 
 
(Dur United Entertainment is cq) 
 
By EVERETT EVANS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ There are a few things in life that you can count on.
Death and taxes. The rich get richer, the poor get poorer. And, as
time goes by, ticket prices for performing-arts events go up.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the increases usually have been gradual _ a few
dollars every couple of years _ may explain why so many arts
patrons seem to take them in stride.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, Broadway ticket prices have jumped from the
1989-90 season's range of $35-$55 for musicals and $25-$42 for
plays to the current range of $40-$85 (musicals) and $25-$60
(plays).
</P>
<P>
   In Broadway circles, a mild reaction usually follows the first
show whose top ticket price hits a new plateau _ ``The Act,'' the
first with a $25 ticket, in 1977; ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,''
hitting $60 in 1989; ``Show Boat,'' becoming the first production
with a $75 ticket in 1994. The 1998 Tony-winning ``The Lion King''
topped out at $85, while all tickets to the current revival of
``The Iceman Cometh'' are $100. Yet these milestone price hikes
usually are just a notch above their competitors, which soon follow
suit. Customers bite the bullet and buy the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are instances when an event carries such an exorbitant
price tag that it backfires.
</P>
<P>
   The textbook case was a concert by Three Tenors Jose Carreras,
Placido Domingo and Luciano Pavarotti, planned for March 1997 at
the Houston Astrodome by Dur United Entertainment, a promoter out
of West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   It was asking for $1,000-$2,500 for floor seating in the Dome,
$350-$1,500 for most other seats in the stadium. A small number of
$50-$250 seats in the ``nosebleed'' sector disappeared quickly,
leaving $350 the best price available. Needless to say, tickets did
not sell like hotcakes. After several price reductions, the concert
was canceled. Though the promoter blamed a ``faulty sound system,''
sluggish sales were to blame. Maybe the promoter should have been
named Duh! Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the long view of Broadway tickets through the years, one
sees just how much prices have risen. In 1949, the top price for
orchestra seats to a musical was $6.60. Today, the top price for
musicals is $85. Even the cheapest balcony seats for today's
Broadway musicals cost $35 or $40. The range for plays is $25-$60.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a Broadway show on its road tour in Houston is less
expensive. That's appropriate, since tours generally are scaled
down and play in halls twice the size of the Broadway theaters,
with more customers per performance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, most touring shows in the Houston Broadway Series
charged $22-$35, with $38 the most expensive ticket for ``Les
Miserables.'' In the current Broadway Series, prices are $25-$50 _
except for ``Ragtime,'' with a $58 top ticket, and ``Riverdance''
at $69.50.
</P>
<P>
   That seems the general trend of price increases, with the cost
of orchestra seats rising more sharply than those in the balcony.
For Broadway productions or tours, it's useful to remember that
most theaters have comparatively few balcony seats, so most patrons
wind up paying the top price, which applies for orchestra seats and
front mezzanine as well.
</P>
<P>
   At Theater Under The Stars, Houston's homegrown producer of
musicals, prices have risen from the 1989 range of $15-$35 to
today's $15-$56. The cheapest seats stayed the same, while the cost
of prime orchestra seats went up 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Single-ticket prices for a show in the Alley Theater's
subscription season have increased from $10-$29 during the 1989-90
season to $19-$49 for the upcoming 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the top ticket prices of Houston's largest resident
producers of plays and musicals, national tours and Broadway
prices, the increase during the past decade is fairly uniform. But
it's more than the overall cost-of-living increase, which the
consumer price index says rose 37.8 percent from 1988 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Scanning the rest of Houston's performing arts to see what
companies charge and how much the cost has increased in the past
decade is a case of mixing apples and oranges _ or perhaps, grapes
and watermelons.
</P>
<P>
   The opera, ballet and symphony are the big-ticket items of the
performing arts, because of the high cost of presentation and the
limited number of performances of most programs.
</P>
<P>
   Single tickets for a production at Houston Grand Opera cost
$10-$95 in 1989-90. They've nearly doubled for 1999-2000 _ to
$22-$182.
</P>
<P>
   Why is opera the most costly ticket of all performing arts? HGO
imports the world's top singers, directors and conductors _ the
same talents who perform in New York, London and Paris. The
productions are elaborate, expensive and play a limited number of
performances. Even at those prices, the box office does not begin
to pay the cost of production, which must be heavily underwritten
by philanthropic sources.
</P>
<P>
   Single tickets for a production by Houston Ballet cost $11-$84,
up from 1989's $8-$65. The company's annual run of ``The
Nutcracker'' has a top price of $65, however, because of its longer
run and larger attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Symphony's ticket range for single concerts in its
upcoming 1999-2000 season is $16-$69 (classical series), $20-$69
(pops series). This is a jump from the 1989-90 prices of $7-$50
(classical), $10-$44 (pops series).
</P>
<P>
   Society for the Performing Arts presents a divergent array of
artists, from orchestras and dance troupes to solo musicians. SPA
estimates its average ticket price for music or dance events today
at $15-$38, an increase from 1989's $12-$23.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, intermediate-sized theaters such as Stages Repertory
Theater and Main Street Theater charge less than HGO, the Alley or
Broadway tours. Small and/or newly established theaters charge the
least of all. But even some of the funky pioneer troupes are
beginning to raise their prices as production standards improve.
</P>
<P>
   Stages' top prices have more than doubled in a decade, from
1989's $16.50 to the current $37. Cheaper seats went up by only
$3.50, from $13.50 10 years ago to today's $17.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Main Street Theater's increase has been scarcely
noticeable, from $10-$15 in 1989 to $13-$18 today.
</P>
<P>
   Although Houston's small non-Equity companies usually stay in
the $15-$18 range, some are breaking the $20 ceiling. While the
Little Room Downstairs Theater charges $16 for all seats to its
current ``The Last Session,'' New Heights Theater's prices for its
current ``Pageant'' are $18-$20, and Theater LaB Houston's recent
``Blood Brothers'' charged $20-$22. (None of these companies were
around in 1989.)
</P>
<P>
   While ticket costs have gone up enough to be prohibitive for
some patrons, there are ways to attend less expensively. Virtually
anyone can still afford to attend the performing arts _ at least
some of the time.
</P>
<P>
   As far as overall ticket prices are concerned, however, history
has shown that what goes up will keep going up. Ticket pricing is a
realm where the law of gravity does not apply. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
