<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-DISABILITIES-2N     06-22 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABILITIES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT NARROWS SCOPE OF DISABILITY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: RECASTS lede and 4th graf, ADDS reaction from disabilities
association, minor edits.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday narrowed the scope of
a federal law banning discrimination against people with
disabilities, saying it does not apply to such conditions as poor
eyesight that can be corrected medically.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on three related cases, the court dismissed lawsuits by
two nearsighted pilots, a truck driver who is almost blind in one
eye and a mechanic with high blood pressure _ all of whom were
either fired or denied employment.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the lawsuits was brought under the 1990 American with
Disabilities Act (ADA), which was designed to end discrimination on
the job, in housing and at medical facilities and other places that
serve the public. The court's dismissal of the suits means that the
ADA did not protect those plaintiffs and others like them.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decisions, the number of people covered by the ADA
was estimated to be as high as 160 million people, more than half
the 272 million population of the United States. As a result of the
court's action Monday, the law covers about 43 million, according
to Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who wrote two of the court's three
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA defines disability as ``a physical or mental impairment
that substantially limits one or more major life activities'' or a
condition where a person is ``being regarded as having such
impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion in the case of the two nearsighted pilots,
O'Connor said, ``We hold that determination of whether an
individual is disabled should be made with reference to measures
that mitigate the individual's impairment, including, in this
instance, eyeglasses and contact lenses.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the poor eyesight of the two pilots, Karen Sutton and
Kimberly Hinton, failed to ``substantially limit a major life
activity'' for them, and therefore they were not covered under the
ADA. In the court's 7-2 decision, the dissenters were Justices John
Paul Stevens and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   The court reached the same conclusion in the other two cases,
ruling unanimously that truck driver Haille Kirkingburg and, by a
7-2 vote, that mechanic Vaughn Murphy should not be considered
disabled under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the cases, the court also ruled that the plaintiffs
failed to show that the companies they sued had banned them from an
entire class of jobs, such as pilot or driver. Instead, the court
said, the companies refused to consider each person for a specific
job because of strict, reasonable criteria that the plaintiffs
failed to meet. Stevens and Breyer also dissented in the Murphy
case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Sutton and Hinton, twin sisters who were regional
airline pilots from Spokane, Wash., applied for jobs as commercial
pilots at United Airlines in Colorado. Although they met basic age,
education, experience and Federal Aviation Administration
qualifications, United turned them down for employment because
their uncorrected vision was worse than the airline's requirement
of 20/100.
</P>
<P>
   In Kirkingburg's case, his employer, Albertsons Inc., a
supermarket chain, hired him as a truck driver in 1990 based in
Portland, Ore. Kirkingburg had more than a decade's experience and
performed well when on a road test for the company. But two years
later, he took another exam and failed to meet Department of
Transportation standards for drivers. As a result, the company
fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to meet Transportation Department standards also led to
Murphy's dismissal. Murphy, who suffers from high blood pressure,
was hired by United Parcel Service in Manhattan, Kan., as a
mechanic, a job that required him to drive to different locations
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   A month after being hired, the company discovered Murphy's high
blood pressure, which disqualified him from driving under
government regulations, and fired him.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulings Tuesday, the court said that under the ADA, a
company can prefer certain physical characteristics over others.
For instance, it can favor people with perfect vision over
near-sighted people.
</P>
<P>
   ``An employer is free to decide that physical characteristics or
medical conditions that are not impairments are preferable to
others, just as it is free to decide that some limiting impairments
make individuals less than ideally suited for a job,'' O'Connor
said in the pilots' case.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Fay, spokesman for the American Association of People with
Disabilities, a Washington-based group, called the court's
decisions a ``terrible setback.'' He added, ``The law now excludes
people it was meant to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Chai Feldblum, a Georgetown University law professor, said,
``These decisions create the absurd result of a person being
disabled enough to be fired from a job but not disabled enough to
challenge the firing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Bokat, general counsel of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, called the rulings ``extremely important'' for American
business. ``It means that those with true disabilities will
continue to be covered, but people with easily correctable
conditions will not be considered disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years employers have won 92 percent of the 700 ADA
cases resolved in court from 1992 to 1997, according to the
American Bar Association. Lower courts had split over how far the
law's protections extend in the cases decided Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate ruling that also centered on the ADA, the high
court held 6-3 in a Georgia case that states may have to place
people with mental disabilities in homelike settings if they can
fare just as well there as in state hospitals. In a narrow
decision, the court said the ADA requires such community placement
of the mentally disabled whenever appropriate. The dissenters were
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Clarence Thomas and
Antonin Scalia
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, writing for the court majority,
said, ``We confront the question whether the proscription of
discrimination may require placement of persons with mental
disabilities in community settings, rather than in institutions.
The answer, we hold, is a qualified yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case, Lois Curtis and Elaine Wilson, two mentally
disabled women, challenged the state of Georgia's insistence that
they remain in a state hospital in Atlanta until places in a less
restrictive community care center opened up.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the state should make places for them at the
care center because they could interact with more people there who
are not disabled and that forcing them to wait amounted to
isolating and segregating them from mainstream American life.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the 1990 law requires states to place the
mentally disabled in the ``most integrated setting'' appropriate,
but only after ``taking into account the resources available to the
state and the needs of others with mental disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many of the 70,000 mentally disabled people
living in state hospitals nationwide might be affected by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ADAPT, a national disability rights group based in Denver,
praised the ruling for reinforcing ``the fundamental intent of the
ADA, which is to prevent discrimination and promote the integration
of people with disabilities into our communities,'' according to
the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Downing, a Georgia assistant attorney general, said the
ruling ``doesn't appear to be too burdensome.'' She noted that the
court did not condemn the state's practice of keeping eligible
people on a community-placement waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
