<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TICKET-PRICES-POP-HNS     06-22 1989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKET-PRICES-POP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP ACTS TAKING TICKET PRICES TO THE LIMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Quick, which is more important? Two premium tickets to
Neil Young or your monthly car payment?
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, that's the kind of choice pop music fans must face
as concert ticket prices keep going up, up, up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the average cost of a ticket for the year's 50
top-grossing concert tours was $19.02. In 1998, the average cost
had gone up to $33.59, according to figures tallied by Pollstar,
the trade magazine of the pop-concert industry.
</P>
<P>
   That's an increase of 76.6 percent. By comparison, the overall
consumer price index as measured by the federal Bureau of Labor
Statistics has increased 37.8 percent in that same time frame.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the cost of concert tickets has gone up at more
than double the rate for all consumer items in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   By far the greatest increase has been the cost of premium seats.
When the Eagles broke the $100 ticket barrier in some markets on
their 1994 tour, fans willingly forked over the dough because it
was viewed as a once-in-a-lifetime reunion.
</P>
<P>
   But now, triple-digit ticket prices are becoming more the rule
than the exception for aging rock icons on the road. Rod Stewart
had a top price of $100 for his spring date at The Woodlands
Pavilion just outside of Houston. Young sold a limited number of
$125 V.I.P. tickets to his recent solo shows at the Aerial Theater
in Houston; all other seats were ``only'' $75.
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Dylan-Paul Simon arena double-bill is getting $125 in
some cities, as is Cher's comeback tour with Cyndi Lauper. Last
year, the Rolling Stones charged up to $350 a ticket _ the kind of
high-roller tariff previously reserved for Frank Sinatra or Barbra
Streisand on New Year's Eve in Las Vegas _ for the band's first
arena tour in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tour didn't sell out in many cities, the Stones
carried home enough loot to feel the unprecedented prices were
justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists have given up the illusion that they're not in it for
the money,'' says Pollstar editor Gary Bongiovanni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years ago, a lot of rock artists wanted to
maintain their countercultural credentials. That's not as important
now. The truth is, the artist sets the price. If Garth Brooks
charges $20 a ticket and Rod Stewart charges $70, it's because
that's how much money they wanted to make that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Even bands and artists that haven't had a hit record in decades
are getting in on the action. The double-bill of Journey and
Foreigner has a top asking price of $76 for a July date at The
Woodlands Pavilion. The Allman Brothers want $65 for the best seats
in the house, and the Motown revue of the Temptations and the Four
Tops commands $61.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to these shows, Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers'
Sept. 19 date at The Woodlands Pavilion seems almost underpriced at
$60.50 for all reserved seats, until you realize that general
admission lawn tickets for Petty are going for $30.50, while a seat
on the hill costs only $18.75 for the Allmans, $16.50 for the
Tempts/Tops and $13.50 for Journey/Foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday's Houston date at The Woodlands Pavilion, Cher
switched to a simplified pricing plan of $35 general admission and
$75 reserved, rather than the original plan starting at $25 and
topping out at $125. The sold-out take added up to the same amount
either way.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Roux, the talent buyer for Houston-based Pace Concerts, says
the trend in the concert tour business has been toward multitiered
pricing structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always felt that the seats up front are worth more than
the seats in the back,'' says Roux, who is responsible for booking
the pop-music season at The Woodlands Pavilion, as well as
overseeing Pace operations in several Southern and Southwestern
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1995, we decided we wanted to try to hold all the lawn
seats to $15. In order to compensate for that, we pushed the front
price up. I think that type of pricing structure has probably
become more prevalent as we went along, because it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 42 pop concerts that played the Pavilion last year, Roux
estimates that 38 were profitable; 13 of those were sell-outs. For
most shows, a relatively small number of seats are priced in the
highest tier, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about four or five ways we scale The Woodlands, but
in some cases, we only have 329 seats at the highest price (out of
13,000 capacity). In most cases, it's only 160 people buying two
tickets making that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bongiovanni points out, these are the same hard-core fans who
would be tempted to pay a scalper even more money for a front-row
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, the top artists have been watching the people
sitting down front paying much more money than the face value of a
ticket. It got to the point where the artist was starting to feel
stupid. If people were willing to dictate that a $30 ticket was
worth $130, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Pace Concerts was purchased by SFX
Entertainment. Since divesting itself of its radio broadcasting
empire, SFX has spent more than $1 billion in the past 18 months
purchasing regional concert promotion companies and sports
management firms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Pace, SFX has swallowed up such respected
operations as Delsener-Slater in New York, Bill Graham Presents in
San Francisco and Cellar Door International, which ruled the
Southeast. As a result of its spending spree, SFX has acquired full
or partial ownership of 82 concert venues, including at least one
amphitheater in each of the top 10 U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   Independent promoters have accused SFX of using its newly
acquired national dominance to outbid competitors for national
tours such as Dylan/Simon and Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Pollstar's Bongiovanni doesn't hold SFX solely responsible for
escalating ticket prices. But he observes that the company has
clearly embraced the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got at least 20 national tours out this year.
Competitors have accused them of bumping up the cost of the tours
they've acquired, like the Petty tour, because that's what they
needed to do. Ultimately, that will result in higher ticket prices,
because the artists don't say no to more money.''
</P>
<P>
   In a standard concert performance contract, Roux says, about 85
percent of the net profit after expenses goes to the artist, with
the promoter collecting the remaining 15 percent for assuming the
risk of putting the show on. In some cases, the artist might reap
as much as 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While greed remains a powerful motivational force for driving up
prices, Bongiovanni and Roux agree that, ultimately, the buying
public determines how high the prices will go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Eagles' tour had not been wildly successful, with fans
supporting the price structure, it might not have led to the
Fleetwood Mac tour. From there, it started to build upon itself,''
Roux says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got the Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young tour coming
out this summer. These superstar reunion tours are motivated mostly
by money. These are wealthy guys. At the end of the day, they want
to know how much they can expect to make by getting back out on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the Eagles' 1994 concert at Rice Stadium topped out
at $85. The first pop act to break the $100 barrier at The
Woodlands Pavilion was Bette Midler. Generally, it's veteran
artists appealing to middle-aged baby-boomers who charge the most
for tickets. But the Spice Girls got a top price of $75 from their
pre-teen fans _ and their boomer parents.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, the idea of spending $50-$100 for a concert
ticket seems extravagant. Jerry Smith, an Internet salesman in
Houston, took his 14-year-old daughter to see the Backstreet Boys
at The Woodlands Pavilion last year. He paid about $25 per ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like it was a reasonable price,'' he said. ``But I
would definitely freeze at $50 a ticket. I look at the ads on TV
now, you see these concerts, they're all $75.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the face value of the tickets, patrons also must
pay a service charge to the ticket outlet. Ticketmaster uses a
sliding scale for service charges, says Chris Doss, director of
promotions and marketing. Other variables include cash vs. credit
and whether you buy your ticket in person or via phone or the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more expensive the ticket the higher the service charge,''
Doss says. ``The least expensive way is to pay cash at a ticket
center.''
</P>
<P>
   But some avid music fans from the baby-boom generation indicate
they are still willing to pay top dollar for acts they really want
to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of people who really trip the switch for
us,'' says Doug Darrow, a Houston attorney. ``But I think we'd pay
$200 to see Springsteen again. I think we're emotionally prepared
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrow's wife, Susan Darrow, a marketing manager for a Texas
bank, said the couple used to go to more national concerts before
Rockefeller's closed two years ago. Now, she says, they prefer to
support regional artists who appear regularly in local clubs.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``If it's someone we really want to see _ Dylan,
Springsteen _ price is not the issue for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Elliott, a copywriter for a local advertising agency, says
he spends a ``disproportionate'' amount of his discretionary income
on concert tickets. He recently paid $75 to see Young at the Aerial
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was too much, especially when you consider that he
had the quintessential low overhead _ two microphones, a harmonica,
eight guitars,'' he says. ``At the same time, I'd do it again. It
was a high-quality show.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott says he resents scalpers and wonders how they manage to
obtain so many good seats. But he admits he that he will go to a
scalper for certain shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time, I was in a scalper's office, and there
were these young girls _ like, too young to drive _ and they were
just agonizing over whether to spend that much money to see Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to them and said, `Go ahead and spend the money. When
all is said and done, you'll be glad you did. Six months from now,
you won't miss the money. But you might regret not getting a better
seat to a great show.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pace's Roux believes it's in the best interest of the concert
industry to try to hold the line on prices whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My No. 1 goal is to try to make deals that will allow the
ticket prices to be set at a level where they are accessible to the
vast majority of fans who have an interest in seeing the
attraction. That's how we sustain and grow our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with the economy strong and many baby boomers enjoying
their peak earning years, Bongiovanni forecasts that ticket prices
will continue to rise. He adds that artists who play against the
trend could be doing themselves a big favor in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garth Brooks has made a big thing about his populist image by
setting his prices low,'' Bongiovanni says.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Brooks, Garth's brother and co-manager, says Brooks'
insistence on holding prices down stems from his own experience as
a teen-ager going to rock concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some shows that he wanted to go to, but he couldn't
afford it. The main thing was, he wanted to make price not an
issue. If you don't go see someone, it should be because you don't
want to, not because you can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he could easily be charging three or four times as
much, Brooks has held the line at $20-$25 a ticket. He also insists
that tickets to his shows have the base price listed separately
from service fees and other add-on costs.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' populist stand has resulted in a fanatical audience
loyalty that has carried over into his phenomenal album sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people appreciate it,'' says Kelly. ``I know I
would.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
