<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELYEM-WINERY-2TAKES-     06-22 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELYEM-WINERY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT AMERICAN WINE SWIRLS IN TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: In 6th graf: The New, etc., the I H New York advertising
campaign, the capitalized H should be a regular size letter.)  
 (af)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALDSBURG, Calif. _ The question sounds like a line from an old
radio script:
</P>
<P>
   Can a minuscule winery, started by a couple of ornery,
rough-hewn rural Californians, find continuing happiness as part of
an international combine owned by a big-time venture capitalist
from Wall Street?
</P>
<P>
   The winery is Williams Selyem, whose pinot noirs have moved to
the head of the table in the years since the first was made in a
garage in 1981. Fewer than 8,000 cases a year are produced. Almost
all go directly to people on the Williams Selyem mailing list,
which is as hard to crack as the guest list for a royal wedding.
(Two of the winery's seven full-time employees are officially
designated as ``keepers of the list.'')
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, happily, the stuff shows up from time to
time on top restaurant wine lists, like Montrachet in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Smoky, voluptuous, intensely flavored, Williams Selyem pinot
noir is among the most coveted American wines. Part of its cachet
is scarcity, but by no means all; it is surely one of the best of
its type, along with Calera and Domaine Drouhin and a few others.
Now the winery has been sold, and the wine world is watching
intently to see if standards will be maintained. Nobody knows the
answer, because no outsider has tasted the new Williams Selyem yet.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner is John Dyson, a scion of the Hudson River
squirearchy. A former New York state agriculture commissioner and a
former deputy mayor for finance and economic development under
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Dyson is often credited with creating the I
New York advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he paid Burt Williams and Ed Selyem $9.5 million for
the operation, which came onto the market because Selyem developed
a serious back problem after years of hefting wine cases. One of
the unsuccessful bidders was Joe Montana, the onetime San Francisco
'49ers quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson said he sees Williams Selyem as ``a job of stewardship, to
be enhanced, not exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dyson's big bucks bought him no vineyards; Williams Selyem
has always been made from grapes purchased under handshake
agreements. Many of those agreements continue, but not the most
important one, which covered the grapes produced on Joe Rochioli's
prize plot in the Russian River Valley, his so-called West Block.
</P>
<P>
   Those grapes went into Williams Selyem's Rochioli pinot noir,
one of the wines produced under the ancien regime from grapes of
single vineyards. It usually commanded the highest ratings and
prices, and it was the winery's benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Dyson get the long-term services of Williams, the
winery's gruff winemaker, who once told a visiting Canadian
journalist: ``We were friends with most of the growers, so I knew
we could get great fruit. Then it's just a matter of not messing it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams agreed to a continuing role after the winery sale, and
Bob Cabral, the new winemaker, says he made the 1998 vintage
``under Burt's direction.'' That wine _ only 4,200 cases, owing to
sparse fruit production _ rests in oak barrels, awaiting release
next year. So far, it seems promising.
</P>
<P>
   But the two men came from different generations and different
cultures. Williams, 57, is self-taught, for example, and Cabral
taught winemaking at Santa Rosa Junior College. People who worked
with them both say that they didn't mesh very well.
</P>
<P>
   So for this year's vintage, Cabral, a heavyset, unassuming
37-year-old, is more or less on his own. Williams ``has kind of
backed out,'' Cabral said, spending most of his time on his fishing
boat in Santa Barbara. Selyem spends summers in Alaska, winters in
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson installed Jean L. Arnold, a respected wine executive who
helped put Jordan Vineyards on the viticultural map, as president
of Williams Selyem, but she, too, found it a difficult place to
work and left. The conflicts between Ms. Arnold and Dyson
reportedly centered on questions of marketing strategy for Dyson's
wines.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the turmoil, a 20-year-old winery worker, Taylor J.
Atkins, was accidentally asphyxiated on Jan. 7 in a bottling tank
full of deadly nitrogen. It was as if some kind of curse hung over
Williams Selyem.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, rumors began flying that Dyson planned to double,
triple or quadruple Williams Selyem's output to recoup his
investment _ rumors that Cabral denies. The present winery, he
said, will never produce more than 15,000 cases a year, which is
the target for the 2005 vintage, and ``anyway, the place is very
profitable as is.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, pinot noir can be a captivating wine: rich, complex
and sensuous, with the scent of cherries and chocolate and
sometimes leather. But the grape that makes it is capricious and
demanding, so much so that Marq de Villiers called his book about
the Calera Wine Co., a California pinot noir specialist,
``Heartbreak Grape'' (HarperCollins West, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Even in France, its homeland, it reaches greatness only in a few
small plots in Burgundy, and there only in the hands of gifted
winemakers like Henri Jayer and Armand Rousseau. For decades, New
World winemakers tried with limited luck to duplicate the subtlety
and silkiness of fine Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   The key, as it turned out, was a cool climate, and it is in such
climates that pinot noir has finally succeeded in the United States
_ in Oregon, in certain areas near Santa Barbara, in the Carneros
district, between the Napa and Sonoma valleys, and in the Russian
River Valley, northwest of Santa Rosa in Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   In most of them, coastal breezes and fogs keep the temperatures
down; other successful pinot noir vineyards are cool because they
are planted at high altitudes, like Chalone, founded by Richard
Graff near Pinnacles National Park in central California in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Selyem was a leader in developing and perfecting
California pinot noirs with Burgundian characteristics. Its best
wines have always been made from cool-climate grapes. Some have
come from the Russian River Valley _ the Rochioli West Block,
identified as Rochioli on the label, and the Rochioli River Block,
identified as River Block on the label, and the Allen vineyard,
also farmed by the Rochioli family.
</P>
<P>
   Some have come from nearby lowland vineyards, like Olivet Lane.
And some have come from the coastal mountains near Fort Ross, west
of here, including the Hirsch, Precious Mountain and Summa
vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Other suppliers are Ferrington Vineyards in the Anderson Valley,
near Ukiah, and the Coastlands vineyards of Diane and David Cobb,
east-facing plots well above the fog line.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Neither Summa nor Olivet Lane will be available to Williams
Selyem in the future. But the loss of the West Block, which was
planted in 1969 and 1970, hurts most of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was faithful,'' said Joe Rochioli, sitting on a terrace
overlooking his vines and a tree line that blocked the meandering
Russian River from view. ``I gave Williams and Selyem grapes from
the West Block even after my son, Tom, joined me and started making
wine, even when Tom ran short. But when Burt sold out, it was our
chance to get back the fruit we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and genial as he may appear, Rochioli is a man possessed
in the vineyard, determined, as he said, ``to grow better grapes
than anyone.'' He and his workers painstakingly thin the vines and
discard less-than-perfect clusters, concentrating all the plant's
energy on a small amount of fruit. The results are yields of two to
three tons an acre, against eight for some rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``I'm up at 4 a.m., then out in the
vineyard. I don't owe anybody anything. I built my own house,
plumbing, electricity, everything. I don't own a suit. I hate
vacations. For me, farming is all about pride, not money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rochioli is stocky and vigorous at 65, with forearms the size of
fireplace logs. His father grew hops on this land; now he is
considered one of the world's best grape-growers by his peers. He
is careful to praise both Dyson and Cabral as ``good men,'' but he
has serious doubts about expanding Williams Selyem's output and
especially about bringing pinot noir grapes from other areas to the
Russian River Valley to make wine. ``Different nose, different
flavors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just down Westside Road from the glamorous Rochioli spread, the
Williams Selyem winery occupies a cluster of small,
utilitarian-looking buildings, including a modest new office. There
is no visitor center and no tasting room on the dusty site. Nor is
there any elaborate landscaping or any sign out front, only a
discreet street number, 6575.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10,000 customers on the Williams Selyem mailing list,
including the White House, but not many make their way here.
</P>
<P>
   Cabral, the son of grape-growing parents, worked for seven years
at De Loach Vineyards, another well-regarded Russian River Valley
operation. He greeted me warily, well aware, as he put it, that
``everything I do here is under a microscope.'' Before joining
Dyson he worried, he said, about whether he could maintain Williams
Selyem's reputation for quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my doubts,'' Cabral said. ``I still do, sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   So do others.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Parker Jr., the wine critic, said recently that he
feared the new owners might try to make money by living off the
winery's name.
</P>
<P>
   One of California's leading sommeliers, Larry Stone of Rubicon,
a San Francisco restaurant, has been a Williams Selyem fan for
years. The 1991's and 1992's were brilliant, he told me, ``complete
wines, fleshy and complex, way beyond anything seen in California
before.'' The 1996's are fine as well, he added, ``really masterful
products of intuitive artisans.''
</P>
<P>
   But the future, Stone argues, is an unmapped road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's in charge,'' he said. ``Dyson has paid a
long price, and it remains to be seen whether he can deliver. He
bought a lot of good will, but that will evaporate if he can't put
the goods in the bottle. What kind of enterprise is this going to
be? How big?''
</P>
<P>
   Absentee owners are not necessarily bad, especially if they have
deep pockets. When a wealthy Japanese group bought Ridge Vineyards
in 1986, a renowned specialist in powerful zinfandels and cabernet
sauvignons, it pumped money into the property and permitted its
winemaker, Paul Draper, to do exactly as he wished. Ridge has gone
from strength to strength.
</P>
<P>
   Cabral is no Paul Draper, but he has developed a formula that he
hopes will produce both quality and quantity in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   He envisages making as much of the single-vineyard wines, the
top of the line, as he can, ``and trying to keep them
extraordinary.'' The grapes for those will come from the longtime
suppliers that remain on the Williams Selyem roster, plus the first
vineyard the winery has ever owned, a 38-acre tract near
Guerneville it bought several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the growth will come in less expensive blends labeled
Russian River Valley, if all the grapes come from vineyards in this
area, or Sonoma Coast or Sonoma County, if the grapes come from
broader areas. Will those bottlings dilute the value of the
carefully nurtured Williams Selyem brand?
</P>
<P>
   And what if Dyson decides to put the Williams Selyem label on
wines made from grapes grown elsewhere? His Pebble Ridge Vineyards
&AMP; Wine Estates owns Milbrook Vineyards in upstate New York, which
produces some of the best wines east of the Mississippi; Villa
Pillo Estate in Tuscany, and Mistral and Vista Verde Vineyards on
the central California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he brought grapes from the Hollister area, south of
San Francisco, to the winery here and made wine from them. But
Cabral said that no decision had been made yet about releasing the
wine.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams Selyem stumbles, plenty of able competitors are
waiting to lure its customers. Some are newcomers, relatively
speaking, like the ambitious Walt and Joan Flowers and the tiny
Quail Hill Vineyard. A bottle of Quail Hill's emphatic Lynmar
reserve pinot noir impressed several of us at dinner in Santa Rosa
recently when tasted against a group of Russian River rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are well established figures like Tom Dehlinger and
Gary Farrell, as well as our old friend Tom Rochioli, to whom it
will now fall to make his father's prized West Block grapes into
pinor noir. Will he be the next pinor noir superstar?
</P>
</TEXT>
