<HEADER>
A5382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WRIGHT-BOOK-NYTR &LR;      06-22 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WRIGHT-BOOK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CBS GOLF ANALYST WHO FELL FROM GRACE WILL TELL HIS SIDE OF STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RON WAGNER   
 Times-News, Hendersonville, N.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAT ROCK, N.C. _ Ben Wright is writing back.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that fateful interview with Valerie Helmbreck of the
Wilmington (Del.) News Journal on May 11, 1995, the former CBS golf
analyst has had to sit back at his home here and helplessly take
shot after shot from the print media.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, he took hits that drove him to depression. Hits
that took away the job he loved dearly.
</P>
<P>
   But now Wright is firing back, in the form of an autobiography
he finished this month entitled ``Good Bounces and Bad Lies.''
</P>
<P>
   It's due out in August, and with it Wright hopes to tell his
story. In his own words. No reporters, no blaring headlines, no
surprise angles.
</P>
<P>
   And then, he doesn't want to talk about it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book will, I hope, lay it all to rest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' would be the firestorm that erupted after Helmbreck
quoted Wright as saying that lesbians were hurting the corporate
sponsorships of the Ladies Professional Golf Association and that
women generally have a more difficult time with golf because
certain gender-unique parts of their anatomy get in the way of a
good swing.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was roundly roasted and he issued a staunch denial _ with
CBS' backing _ before later retracting the denial and admitting to
Sports Illustrated in its ``Golf Plus'' section in May 1998 that he
had indeed made the comments.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, he's been suspended by CBS and blocked from
working in television unless someone buys out his CBS contract,
which expires Nov. 1. Wright says he has reconciled with Helmbreck,
and he's ready to move on with his life, with or without
television.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's all behind me. I'm trying to persuade people, let's go
on,'' he said. ``Why the hell do I have to keep looking back?''
</P>
<P>
   Wright takes particular exception to the beating he took from
journalists he knew personally. Even the generally positive Sports
Illustrated piece written by Jamie Diaz draws his ire, primarily
because of the headline: ``By declaring war on CBS, Ben Wright was
finally able to make peace with Valerie Helmbreck.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I never said that. That was their headline ... CBS took grave
exception to that, and I said `I'm not going to wage war with the
people who pay me my money. They're doing me a favor.' That's just
a pure invention of these people,'' he said of the headline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused me a lot of grief, with CBS saying, `Why the hell do
we need to pay you if you're at war with us?' I never said it. It
was just a pure Sports Illustrated ploy. I don't care for that too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did me no favors. Nobody has done me any favors, but in
my book I'm going to outline most of the truth as I see it, but
without bitterness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's relationship with CBS, despite the fact that he still
draws a salary, has been icy since the story. In it, Wright says
the network encouraged him to lie, which is something CBS denies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated screwed me twice, so they won't get another
chance,'' he said. ``I'm not exactly in love with the print media.
I'm a print media man myself. I was trained that way. I started in
the print business in 1954. So I was really surprised at how many
guys turned on me and savaged me. Guys that I knew, that I thought
were friends. But that's the way it is today. It's a dog-eat-dog
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wright was quick to point out that telling his side of this
particular tale is a small part of the book, which will be
published by Sleeping Bear Press. The motivation, he said, is to
``tell a lot of funny stories, which is what I like to do,'' as
well as some not-so-funny ones, like the six years he and his
sister spent sleeping underground while his native England took
bomb after bomb from Germany during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was hired by CBS in 1972, when he moved to the United
States. In 1982 he settled in western North Carolina, first in
Asheville and then moved in 1988 to Flat Rock, which he said
reminds him of Scotland, his mother's homeland. All the while, he
was making a name for himself as perhaps television's most popular
golf analyst, with a rich voice that eloquently carried an
extensive, poetic vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Wright says that people tell him every day how much they miss
him on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss it, but at the same time you have to move on. There's
no point sitting and feeling sorry for myself,'' he said. ``I did
that for a while and it didn't get anywhere, so I just decided to
get on with my life and go do what I'm going to do ... I find
myself damn busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright disputes the notion that he's seen as insensitive or, at
worst, a sexist homophobe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Absolute rubbish. It's not a perception of the general public.
It's a perception of the media, if it's a perception at all,'' he
said. ``I have more friends than I ever had before, because people
think that I was screwed or shafted or whatever you like to call
it. I don't give a damn about perceptions. I go on about my life
and I do what I have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people who really know me, know me for what I am. And
they're the people who matter. The people who want to put me down,
get on with it. But the people who really matter, don't. Because
they know I'm not a bad guy ... I don't have to listen to the
people who want to put me down four years later.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said the best part of life after CBS is the time he
spends playing golf. Golf-course design, documentaries,
commercials, writing, speaking engagements and, of course, golf
tournaments take up Wright's time these days.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know if he will even try to get back into television
once his contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be 67 by the end of the contract, and I think I'm going
to do what a lot of people do when they get to be my age _ go and
play golf,'' he said. ``I'm downsizing. I've lived a grand
lifestyle on the CBS expense account, and now I'm living a much
quieter life. And quite frankly, I enjoy it. Enormously.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Wagner writes for the Times-News, Hendersonville, N.C.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
