<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-VETO23-COX     06-22 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VETO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush cites 'government intrusion' in decision to veto
accountability bill
 &HT;    By Jerry Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush has vetoed a bill that
would have ensured public accountability by groups spending tax
dollars on programs designed to help the poor, the disabled and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was introduced by state Rep. Bob Glaze to require that
the 55 community action agencies in Texas open their records to the
public and hold public meetings when they decide how they will use
tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in a veto memorandum that the bill could subject
``faith-based organizations in Texas to unnecessary government
intrusion'' if they get state or federal grants of tax dollars to
provide the services.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze (D-Gilmer) introduced the bill because of years of
financial irregularities by the East Texas Human Development Co.,
known as HUDCO.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze was baffled and disappointed that Bush vetoed the bill
under the rationale that it would intrude upon faith-based
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make sense that something should be vetoed
that simply exposes the record of where taxpayers' dollars go,''
Glaze said. ``You can draw a lot of nonsense from that. Him running
for president, it is hard for me to believe he would veto a bill
that does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaze said his bill was narrowly drafted to apply to HUDCO and
the other 54 community action agencies that receive federal grants
funneled through the state.
</P>
<P>
   It would not apply to faith-based organizations unless they
received a federal contract to operate as a community action
agency. And even then it would open up to the public just those
funds the organization receives in tax dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   HUDCO has operated Head Start and programs providing housing,
weatherization, energy assistance and emergency services in Gregg
and four surrounding counties. HUDCO received some $3 million in
Head Start education funds annually.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, the Longview News-Journal reported HUDCO spent
$900,000 in Head Start education funds that included $17,000 to pay
for a parent-staff banquet. About $12,500 of that money was spent
on gifts for board and staff members, the newspaper reported. Other
funds went for snow cone and popcorn machines, cameras, sewing
machines, microcassette recorders and similar items. At that time,
less than one-fourth of Longview's eligible children were being
served by the local Head Start program and that continues to be the
case.
</P>
<P>
   HUDCO was forced to give up its Head Start contract earlier this
year and bids to take over the local program are being considered
now.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal auditors have criticized HUDCO for a
``pervasive misapplication of grant funds,'' financial and
management problems, failure to follow state and federal
regulations in spending grant funds, substandard or nonexistent
record keeping, violating federal contract terms, failure to seek
competitive bids and improperly shifting funds from one program to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever the tax dollars go, that is where we have the right
to see. That argument did not sell,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vetoed more than 30 bills and two concurrent resolutions
that were passed by lawmakers during the 1999 legislative session,
according to the Associated Press. He handed most of the vetoes
late Sunday, hours before a midnight deadline for him to take
action on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg County Clerk Laurie Woloszyn, upon learning of Bush's
veto, expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow! I am disappointed, I am really disappointed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Woloszyn, a Republican like Bush, served two months on the HUDCO
board of directors and then quit in disgust over the way the agency
handles public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it. In my mind, he obviously was not familiar
with our local problems. I am disappointed,'' Woloszyn said of the
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone, any entity that is entitled to governmental funds
needs to be open to the public. That is the only way you are going
to ensure the most proper spending of those funds,'' Woloszyn said.
</P>
<P>
   She disagreed with Bush's assertion the bill would unnecessarily
intrude upon faith-based organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations' main purpose is to help those people, and,
``When it comes to spending those funds, even a faith-based
organization needs to allow public access to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine. I just don't comprehend that kind of logic as
far as opposition from a faith-based organization,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a genuine, true, faith-based organization, it should
not matter to them if the public is allowed to attend those
meetings where they discuss the public funds, the distribution and
whatever guidelines they have to follow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze said he will introduce the bill again in the next
legislative session two years from now, and Woloszyn said she would
join him in trying to push it through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Glaze is to be commended for committing to do it again,
because it needs to be done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze said Bush's second objection to the bill was that any
future problems such as those with HUDCO would be dealt with
promptly by the Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs,
which supervises the grant programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't do that, as we have witnessed over the last five
years with HUDCO,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze said officials with TDHCA and the federal Department of
Health and Human Services told him that when they try to deal with
problem agencies such as HUDCO, they find they cannot shut down a
federal program without a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lawsuit requires a lot of time, and their history on winning
those is very bad,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If HUDCO wanted to sue now on one of the programs they lost,
TDHCA tells me it is almost impossible to beat the thing. You are
talking about a two- to five-year court battle before it is
complete with a verdict,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they stay in charge of the program until the court battle
is over. That is the sad part about it. And they can even continue
to get funds appropriated,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the governor's staff called him Saturday night to tell
him of Bush's objections. He said he warned that Bush should avoid
such a stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'You don't understand. This is not a good thing for
the governor. This puts him in the position of saying he doesn't
want to ensure that all tax dollars be exposed to public scrutiny,'
`` Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a right everyone should have. None of this should be
in the dark or kept quiet. We should have an opportunity to know
where these dollars go, particularly whenever the services are
delivered to people who are as vulnerable as this group of people
are, and in such important programs as Head Start,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand his rationale at all. And I think this
thing will not play well nationally whenever we look at it in terms
where the governor is not agreeable to federal dollars being
exposed to public scrutiny,'' Glaze said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's position is especially puzzling because the bill
passed out of committee and off the floor in both the House of
Representatives and the state Senate without a single dissenting
vote. And no one mounted a concentrated lobbying effort against it,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make sense that something that simply exposes
the record of where taxpayers dollars go should be vetoed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze said the only way officials started correcting the problem
with HUDCO was in ``the opening of what records we did get. The
press got involved and created the situation where we changed it
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Graham writes for The Longview News Journal, Longview,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
