<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-PROPOSALS-NYTR     06-22 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-PROPOSALS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO KEEP NASCAR IN CRUISE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rose (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ The sound and the fury, signifying
everything, is coming to town. NASCAR will be in town this weekend
at Sears Point, and when it comes to making all the right moves,
NASCAR is Magic Johnson in the open court.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, this sport knows how, all right: How to do it the right
way. How to keep its athletes clean. How to attract fans.
</P>
<P>
   But how does NASCAR keep it that way? How does it stay ahead of
the curve? How does it not fall victim to its own success? How does
it head into the next millennium flat-out down the backstretch?
</P>
<P>
   This is how.
</P>
<P>
   DO A BOSTON TEA PARTY AND DUMP TOBACCO _ If NASCAR truly wants
to walk down Main Street, U.S.A., and appeal to every corner of
America, it must sever its 29-year-old relationship with R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co. NASCAR is expert at projecting wholesome
family entertainment, but taking a drag on a cigarette is hardly a
popular American pastime anymore, especially with the tobacco
companies getting roundly tagged in lawsuit after lawsuit. NASCAR
is cool; smoking is not. Time after time, NASCAR has instinctively
made the right decision to back winners. Tobacco, however, is a
loser. Tobacco is a dead-end. Snuff it.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS HATE A MONOPOLY _ Of the top 25 drivers in the points
standings, only three come from single-car owners. The growing
trend in NASCAR is for multicar ownership, such as Jack Roush with
his five drivers. Conflict-of-interest questions immediately
surface. Can Roush pay as much attention to Johnny Benson, who is
23rd in points and has not won in 77 career starts, as opposed to
Jeff Burton, who is third in points and has a fair chance to win
every week? Specifically, can Roush give equal treatment to all
five of his drivers, no matter how they finish? Human nature would
say not. The little guy, the maverick with the Junior Johnson
attitude, is being squeezed out, but it was the maverick who
sustained NASCAR, kept it alive in its infancy and still
contributes to the image NASCAR likes to think of itself. That the
sport represents America at its best: tough, independent, free
thinking, swashbuckling, not afraid to buck a trend. Not anymore,
not if you have to join your competition in order to race with it.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATE JEFF GORDON, DON'T TRASH HIM _ There is much
resentment and jealousy in the NASCAR community toward this
27-year-old wonder who has been so successful. It's as if Gordon is
a detriment to the sport. No more than Gretzky was to hockey, Babe
Ruth was to baseball, Michael Jordan was to basketball. Like all of
those superstars, Gordon has raised the bar. NASCAR should feel
fortunate Gordon has come along. It can _ er, it should _ make
everyone try harder, which then elevates the quality of
competition. Find a way to beat Gordon, not a way to whine about
him. That's the way John Wayne, I mean Junior Johnson, would have
done it. Damn straight.
</P>
<P>
   BE GOOD TO THE PEOPLE WHO BRUNG YA _ Letters by the bushel
arrive constantly at ``Winston Cup Scene,'' the sport's trade
journal, complaining about traffic congestion, ticket prices and
tighter security around drivers. Most of this is a by-product of
the growing popularity of NASCAR. Once a small, sleepy Southern
town could handle a crowd of 20,000, but not 120,000. Once a NASCAR
ticket was a convenient and inexpensive purchase; but it's two
months before the Goody's 500 in Bristol, Tenn., and the event is
already sold out, at $80 a pop. Once Richard Petty would stand for
two hours after a race signing autographs when the garage area was
opened to anyone; but that doesn't happen anymore. Drivers rush
out, trying to beat the traffic along with everyone else, grabbing
a few precious minutes of down-time before the next sponsorship
event. Build roads, stabilize prices, keep the lines of
communication open. Don't step on the toes of people who adore you.
Consult baseball for details.
</P>
<P>
   AND, IN SUMMATION, I'D LIKE TO SAY _ NASCAR, don't grow so big,
don't be so consumed with making money that you forget how you got
to be so rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Padecky writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif., which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
