<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-SHELTER23-COX     06-22 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-SHELTER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park landlord gives residents shelter from storms
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH PHOTO.)
 &HT;    By Wes Ferguson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLSVILLE, Texas _ Duane West wanted a little bit more
protection than his mobile home had to offer the next time a
tornado came through East Texas. West, the landlord of Tall Pines
Mobile Home Park, kept his tenants in mind when he decided to buy a
tornado shelter.
</P>
<P>
   West settled for three underground shelters, spread out among
the 24 mobile homes and about 75 people in his park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a shelter, but we wanted one for all the people,''
West said. ``It wouldn't be fair for just the landlord to have
one.''
</P>
<P>
   West spent $17,000 for the three shelters. Each holds 25 to 30
people comfortably, but about 50 people could squeeze into one if
need be, he said. He owns 17 of the 24 homes in the park, but he's
not going to raise the rent for the shelter services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized we didn't have anywhere for people to go in the
park, or anywhere else in Hallsville,'' West said of the community
of 3,000 5 miles
</P>
<P>
   east of Longview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a service I feel most landlords should provide their
tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   West worked for the Red Cross in Tulsa, Okla., before he moved
to Hallsville five years ago. He saw the destruction tornadoes
could leave there, so he wanted to make sure he and his tenants
were safe here.
</P>
<P>
   Tall Pines tenant Roszetta Shores' parents live near Oklahoma
City, so she heard the horror stories of the tornadoes that tore
through Oklahoma and Kansas in early May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised. Nobody in Arkansas would ever do
anything like this,'' said Shores, who moved to Hallsville from
Mena, Ark., about a week
</P>
<P>
   ago. ``This is the first I've heard of a landlord doing
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel safer,'' Shores said. ``I've got three kids,
and I feel better and more at ease with the shelter there.''
</P>
<P>
   After tornadoes passed through East Texas in late April, West
searched the Web and found Texas Tornado Shelters, based in Tyler.
The company built, delivered and was almost finished installing the
solid steel shelters by Monday afternoon. R.C. Nelson, co-owner of
the Texas Tornado Shelters, said he expected them to be ready for
action by Monday night or this morning. The Tall Pines job was one
of a kind, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first park owner we've had to pay for this,'' said
Nelson, whose customers range from owners of mobile homes to brick
houses in town or in the country. ``With the number of tornadoes
getting worse, I expect more and more park owners to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he lives in a mobile home park and owns two tornado
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Ferguson writes for The Longview News Journal, Longview,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
