</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV29-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SIBLING CLASHES _ DON'T AUTOMATICALLY FOCUS ON THE
OLDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, June 29)  
(bl) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 8-year-old son and I were curled on the couch with popcorn
and soda, watching a rented video about a gooey green killer fungus
that had taken over a town.
</P>
<P>
   With my husband on a business trip and our 2-year-old daughter
visiting grandparents for a few days, my son and I were enjoying a
peaceful weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know you haven't been in trouble all day?'' I asked
him, suddenly realizing that there hadn't been any threats, yelling
or time outs in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling you it's always Sarah who gets me in trouble,''
he said, barely looking away from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   He was right, and I had known this months ago on one level.
Sarah, being the temperamental toddler, could scream louder, throw
longer tantrums and cry more tears.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to determine the instigator of every brother-sister
conflict was often too much trouble, so the older kid always got
the blame, or at least the responsibility of fixing the situation.
</P>
<P>
   It was always easier to tell Adam to ``let your little sister
have the toy,'' or ``leave her alone, she's in a bad mood,'' or
``if she cries one more time, you're going to your room.''
</P>
<P>
   But was it fair? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah really does stir things up, doesn't she?'' I said to
Adam.
</P>
<P>
   He turned his whole attention toward me then, and said the most
insightful thing I've ever heard him say about our family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``It's like she's a puzzle piece that doesn't
quite fit in yet.''
</P>
<P>
   My friends, through our parenting e-mails that tumble back and
forth across states and modems, are saying the same things: Their
children are mixing together about as well as water and Desenex.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children are so different they astound me,'' says Kristin.
``They torture me in completely different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``My oldest, with his fiery temperament, is the tough one on the
surface, but I have come to realize he is all bark and very little
bite. He complains loudly as he does whatever you are asking. He
never once tried to climb out of his crib, climb over a baby gate,
color on walls or in books. He always liked his high chair, and
never tried to push a chair up to the front door to unlock the
chain so he could get out. He threw temper tantrums, but he
followed the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``BEWARE THE QUIET ONES! My youngest is much more mild-mannered.
He does not throw fits when you tell him no. He simply waits for
you to leave the room, and then he does what he wants anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't like any of the hand-me-down toys that used to be
his big brother's favorites, showing nothing but disdain for the
hammering toys, dump trucks or Duplos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having my first son did NOTHING to prepare me for my second,''
Kristin says. ``I am starting from scratch again.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to sense a conspiracy among the second-borns. They
want to make absolutely sure no one mistakes them for their older
siblings. And, by golly, they'll fit in when and where they're
ready.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a features writer for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers. She has master's and specialist degrees in
marriage and family counseling.)
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
