<HEADER>
A5438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-TUNA-ART-NYT &LR;      06-22 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TUNA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 900-YEAR-OLD RITUAL STIRS WATERS OFF SICILY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to change slug to ITALY-TUNA, sted SICILY-TUNA, so slug
conforms to photos.) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By JAMES HILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAVIGNANA, Italy _ For more than 900 years, the fishermen of
this little island off Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the
same ritualistic way. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate
through these waters, the men await a signal from their leader to
begin the mattanza, a highly choreographed communal hunt with
prayers and songs and rigid rules that is seldom seen around Sicily
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the fishermen, called tonnoretti, were waiting for
the signal, as they had been every day since late May. The island
community's head fisherman and de facto leader, called the rais,
watched the sea, to decide if it was calm enough for them to set
out in their long wooden boats. On Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday
he just shook his head slowly and uttered hopefully, ``Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the weather relented and the mattanza began: six
wooden boats headed out to sea, the fishermen joining in
traditional song.
</P>
<P>
   Over three to four hours, the boats surrounded a huge web of
nets set up to trap the tuna as they swam past, corralling them
into successively smaller holding pens until they were tightly
surrounded in a final section _ the camera della morte, or chamber
of death. The thrashing fish were then confined closely enough to
let the tonnoretti gaff them and haul them aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual, which on this day netted 38 tuna, is the antithesis
of large-scale commercial fishing. But after a stop at the fish
processing plant in nearby Trapani, about 70 percent of the tuna
were destined for the same place so many bluefin land today: the
sushi bars and fish markets of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of years, the fishermen of Favignana could live off
the sea. But the cannery on the island, the largest building there,
closed 16 years ago for lack of product.
</P>
<P>
   With each year, the fish have become smaller and fewer. The
tonnoretti are not sure why, and the only finger they uncertainly
point is at the factory ships of the Japanese that prowl the ocean
beyond Gibraltar. In the last 25 years, fish as large as 1,154
pounds have been caught, but the average weight of this year's tuna
has been only 140 pounds. In the mid-1800s, it was possible to pull
14,000 tuna from the sea each season, but by 1987 the number
reached a low of 285. This year, the fishermen will feel lucky if
the mattanzas take a thousand.
</P>
<P>
   The plant pays only about $2.25 a pound for the fish, which is
barely enough for the tonnoretti to rent their nets. As a result,
almost none of the sons of the tonnoretti work at sea. Instead,
they find jobs catering for the island's tourists, or they head to
the mainland. The sea no longer holds the work of the future. And
each time they head out in those wooden boats, a way of life ebbs
further away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
