<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOGG-DONATION-NYT &LR;      06-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOGG-DONATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD GETS DUTCH-MASTER DRAWINGS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A trove of 17th-century Dutch drawings _ including works by
Rembrandt, Pieter Bruegel, Adriaen van Ostade and Jacques de Gheyn
II _ has been given to the Fogg Art Museum at Harvard University by
Maida and George Abrams of Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The 110 drawings, which experts said are worth as much as $20
million, are the core of a huge collection the Abramses began
building 40 years ago that is considered the finest of its kind in
private hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theirs is probably the most remarkable collection of Dutch Old
Master drawings put together ever in America,'' said Martin
Royalton-Kisch, the curator of Dutch and Flemish drawings at the
British Museum. ``It's remarkable for its breadth as well as its
out-and-out masterpieces and a selection of pieces that are just
charming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any museum would have wanted it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Fogg got it because it has long been a center of study for
Old Master drawings. ``The reason this is going to a teaching
museum rather than a repository is so students can hold these
drawings in their hands and get the magic feeling from that,'' said
Abrams, who graduated from Harvard College in 1954 and Harvard Law
School in 1957. ``The idea of perhaps turning them into Dutch art
scholars is exciting to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fogg's Old Master drawing collection has until now been
stronger in French and Italian works. ``By their gift, the Abramses
have profoundly strengthened our very mission,'' said James Cuno,
the director of Harvard's museums. ``We will be able to teach and
encourage further research in Dutch Old Master drawings by offering
students and scholars a collection of the greatest importance and
highest quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams is a member of two committees of the Harvard University
Art Museums, a trustee of the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and a
fellow of the Pierpont Morgan Library. Mrs. Abrams, a graduate of
Sarah Lawrence College, is president of Very Special Arts
Massachusetts, a nonprofit organization that develops arts programs
for people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the couple have lent many drawings to museums,
and in 1991-92 an exhibition called ``Seventeenth-Century Dutch
Drawings: A Selection from the Maida and George Abrams
Collection,'' which was organized by the Fogg, was shown there and
at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam, the Morgan Library in New York,
and the Albertina in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, writing in The New York Times, called the show a
``must see.'' It ``burns small, and it burns slowly,'' he wrote.
``But in the memory it blazes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 drawings in that exhibition, 65 are going to the
Fogg. ``We've added another 45 to give it additional strength and
completeness,'' Abrams said. Royalton-Kisch said: ``The gift is a
choice selection without necessarily having all the high points.
It's a good cross-section.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift contains works of many styles and subjects by artists
active in the Netherlands between 1580 and 1700, when Dutch artists
had their greatest impact on the development of European art. Among
them are Rembrandt's ``Landscape With a Farmstead,'' once part of
the renowned collection at Chatsworth; a singular landscape by
Bruegel in white gouache on blue paper; one of the few works by
Cornelius Vroom still in private hands; three drawings by Willem
Buytewech, an early practitioner of ``merry company'' genre
pictures, and a rare ``friendship album'' in its original binding
that consists of 41 drawings made between 1628 and 1641 by at least
28 artists, including the only known drawing by Emanuel de Witte, a
painter of church interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams' interest in Dutch art began when, as a law student, he
worked in the Netherlands for two summers, visiting Dutch museums
and spending time in Leiden, Rembrant's birthplace. The couple
began collecting drawings in 1960, soon after they married.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, French and Italian works were popular, so the
Abramses, in their early 20s, focused on more affordable Dutch
drawings. Over the years, they gave nearly 100 drawings to the Fogg
and also donated works to several other museums.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said he and his wife decided to make their big gift to
the Fogg now to encourage research.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Old Master drawings become rarer, the number of collectors
will be thinning,'' he said. ``And when that happens, there can be
a lessening of interest and involvement in the field by museum
people and scholars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after transferring these 110 works to the Fogg, the
Abramses will still own several hundred drawings and many paintings
by Dutch Old Masters. And they have not stopped collecting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
