   SELYEM-WINERY (Healdsburg, Calif.) _ The question sounds like a
line from an old radio script: Can a minuscule winery, started by a
couple of ornery, rough-hewn rural Californians, find continuing
happiness as part of an international combine owned by a big-time
venture capitalist from Wall Street? The winery is Williams Selyem,
whose pinot noirs have moved to the head of the table in the years
since the first was made in a garage in 1981. Fewer than 8,000
cases a year are produced. Almost all go directly to people on the
Williams Selyem mailing list, which is as hard to crack as the
guest list for a royal wedding. By R.W. Apple Jr.
