<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-STAD-PA     06-22 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STAD-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        LEAGUE AND PLAYER OFFICIALS OPPOSE SPECTER'S STADIUM
FINANCING BILL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, -- Football league and player officials played
defense yesterday against Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter's
proposal that would require the NFL and Major League Baseball to
pay for half the cost of new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue traveled to Specter's home
field, a Senate Judiciary hearing Tuesday, to speak out against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is not only unnecessary,'' Tagliabue said, ``but
would have serious and negative consequences for local communities,
for state and local governments, for sports fans, and for sports
teams, themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing featured opponents of the measure that would tie the
NFL's limited anti-trust exemption and Major League Baseball's
anti-trust exemption to the condition that the leagues put 10
percent of their television revenue in a fund to pay for stadium
costs and renovations.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the league's power to deny a franchise team's
decision to move.
</P>
<P>
   Without the measure, Specter said the leagues are involved in
``legalized extortion'' -- when cities and states are forced to
pony up millions to build new stadiums in order to keep their teams
from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Specter used as an example of the high costs of stadiums the
situation in Pennsylvania, where four projects are being eyed at a
price tag of more than $1 billion. Two-thirds of the cost for these
stadiums will come from the taxpayers, through state and local
funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies and Eagles want to build sites in Philadelphia, and
two other stadiums are under construction in Western Pennsylvania
for the Steelers and Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said smaller market teams would be hurt if they were
forced to use a set percentage of television revenues for stadium
costs. He said it would hurt their ability to compete for the best
players and worsen their situations.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee member Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis.,
agreed. Television revenue makes up 60 percent of the Green Bay
Packers' operating revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said the bill would hurt the existing television
revenue sharing arrangement that has allowed the Green Bay Packers
to survive and develop into a better team.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Klein, an economics professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles, said the bill would be harmful because
it would encourage state and local governments to build more and
more stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said it would go against the principles of a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Upshaw, executive director of the NFL Players Association,
said the group opposed the bill because it threatened the
collective bargaining agreement in place. He said if leagues had to
use 10 percent of television revenue for construction, it would
effect the determination of player salary caps.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Richardson, owner and founder of the Carolina Panthers
said the issue is a local one and shouldn't be decided by lawmakers
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand why the members of this Committee would
feel they need to impose a uniform federal approach to what is
clearly a local issue,'' Richardson said. ``This bill tells mayors,
city councils, and even voters that they do not known what they are
doing..''
</P>
</TEXT>
