<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-HALLOFFAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRIFIED AND DIGNIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ A CD or book with the imprint of the Rock-and-Roll
Hall of Fame has always seemed like nothing more than merchandise,
a souvenir. But a CD or book with the yellow circular logo of the
Country Music Hall of Fame, a museum here that predates the opening
of the Rock-and-Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland by more than 25
years, has always been an object of cultural value, a necessity in
the collection of anyone who appreciates American music. The
museum's output ranges from its impressively exhaustive
Encyclopedia of Country Music to its CD of early Johnny Paycheck
recordings, featuring some of country's greatest parentheses songs,
like ``(Pardon Me) While I Go Murder Somebody'' and ``It Won't Be
Long (and I'll Be Hating You).''
</P>
<P>
   So it was with the typical class of a museum and the down-home
casualness of country music that the Country Music Hall of Fame
celebrated the groundbreaking of its new $37 million museum
building in downtown Nashville on June 17. Lined up in the front
row at the outdoor ceremony were the voices, faces and fingers of
country legend: Chet Atkins, Brenda Lee, Eddy Arnold, Little Jimmy
Dickens, Kitty Wells and Earl Scruggs. Performing onstage were the
younger inheritors to Nashville: Bryan White, Randy Travis, Kathy
Mattea (a former tour guide at the museum) and Vince Gill, who _
inspired by a speech in the ceremony by Garrison Keillor _ deviated
from his planned performance of ``I Still Believe In You'' to strum
a moving tribute to his late father called ``Key of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was authentic,'' the hall's director, Kyle Young, said of
Gill's song change. ``As I sat up there and I saw that happen, I
thought, `That's it.' If we could operate like that all the time we
would be up there. He made such a real connection, and that's part
of our job, to connect the present with the past. And if we want to
be real pompous, we can say we want to affect the future too.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Stuart, the musician and president of the Country Music
Foundation, said of the hall: ``It's holy ground. As an artist it's
where we all want to end up. Every note of music I play is aimed at
this building.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Hall of Fame, designed by Ralph Applebaum and scheduled
to open in May 2001, was built at the behest of Nashville Mayor
Phil Bredesen. It is a complicated structure: From the air it looks
like a treble clef, from one side it looks like a piano keyboard,
and from another angle it is a Cadillac fin. Besides creating room
for newer and splashier exhibitions, the museum's main purpose is
to house the Hall of Fame's collection of one million artifacts
(from photographs to albums to mandolins), which are stuffed in
cabinets, on crude shelves and in lockers in the basement of the
current museum off Music Row in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered in the basement are also some of country's most
enthusiastic supporters, revivalists and resuscitators. In a room
off the library sits Alan Stoker (whose father led Elvis Presley's
backing band the Jordanaires). Most of the day Stoker hunches over
the desiccated grooves of old records and transcription disks; his
current project is to restore Hank Thompson's earliest recordings.
His video collection holds many rarities, including a Hank Williams
television appearance on ``The Kate Smith Evening Hour.'' As he
shows it to a visitor he enthusiastically points out every lanky
move and subtlety, down to the final smirk and nervous head nod
that ends Williams' performance of ``Cold, Cold Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In the archive room nearby is Mark Medley, an archivist who sees
the material world as one inhabited by ghosts and accordingly
spends his time looking for objects that have come in contact with
country legends, whether they be favorite instruments or napkins
with a soup stain. Locked away in his small office are Jimmie
Rodgers' guitar, a chair that Elvis may have sat on once, a classic
Lefty Frizell outfit and a boot made from painted macaroni given by
a fan to Little Jimmy Dickens. On display upstairs are many of the
Hall of Fame's greatest possessions, a highlight being Webb
Pierce's personalized Pontiac with horseshoe-shaped pedals, a
saddle-shaped gearshift, pistol door handles and rifle hood and
trunk ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that driving around town when I grew up here,'' said
Young, whose first job at the museum was as a ticket collector 20
years ago. ``I didn't know what to think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Hall of Fame announced which performers it planned
to induct in September. They are Dolly Parton, Conway Twitty and
the cowboy actor and songwriter Johnny Bond. ``What a great honor;
I really am surprised,'' Ms. Parton said in a statement, adding,
``I thought I'd have to be as old as Roy Acuff or as ugly as Willie
Nelson to get in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
