<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATISSE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MATISSE: FATHER &AMP; SON': THE FINE ART OF A FAMILY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By PHYLLIS TUCHMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are several exceptional books devoted to the art of Henri
Matisse, from Alfred Barr Jr.'s classic ``Matisse: His Art and His
Public,'' first published in 1951, to ``The Unknown Matisse,''
Hilary Spurling's detailed biography of the artist's early years,
published last fall. Now the picture of this remarkable colorist is
rounded out further by John Russell's splendid ``Matisse: Father &AMP;
Son,'' an account of the artist, his son Pierre and their dealings
with other painters and sculptors, based on letters between the
father and son and between the son and the modernist innovators he
represented in his eponymous gallery on East 57th Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, the former chief art critic for The New York Times, has
written a page turner, a quality setting it apart from most other
volumes on art. He has fashioned an absorbing tale about the
ordinary life of an extraordinary painter, sculptor, draftsman and
printmaker. And he has advanced his narrative with an ingenious yet
understated literary style.
</P>
<P>
   In alternating chapters, he traces Henri Matisse's development
as artist, husband, father and friend; the business career of his
son, and the studio life and exhibition history of the European
artists who showed with Pierre Matisse in New York before and after
World War II. By selectively excerpting correspondence _ over 825
letters between father and son, more than 150 from Jean Dubuffet
alone _ Russell achieves a special immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   After situating each artist Russell steps aside to allow
forthright and illuminating remarks by all the painters and
sculptors to make the reader feel as if they are sharing their
confidences and perspectives with you and no one else. For this,
Pierre Matisse's gifts as a correspondent must also be
acknowledged. Those who wrote to him seem to speak straight from
the heart, an attribute of their art as well.
</P>
<P>
   To an inquiry from his dealer in the United States, Joan Miro
revealingly says: ``You ask me about the objects, and how I come to
make them. ... I feel myself magnetized by a particular object.
There is nothing premeditated about it. After that, I feel myself
drawn toward another object. When the two are put together, their
contact produces a poetical shock, a mutual and immediate
infatuation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My work has nothing whatever to do with Freud, or with the
theoretical,'' he added. ``It has nothing to do with `literature'
or `intellectuality.' Work of that sort is born dead, already
rotting and destined to disappear in short order.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as Henri Matisse, at 76, started to arrange cut and colored
paper shapes into exhilarating pictures, Russell has taken the
innermost thoughts put down on paper by the Matisses and
personalities like Miro, Balthus and Alberto Giacometti and woven
them together into an emotion-packed volume. Over and over, the
elder Matisse tells his son that he finds it possible to express
thoughts and feelings in his letters that are impossible for him to
discuss in person.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924, as a concerned parent, Henri advised Pierre, who was
newly installed in New York: ``Keep in constant touch with me, and
above all don't do anything without telling me.'' To his son, the
father also once declared, ``Of course, one never knows what other
people are really like.'' The letters allow Russell to partly
circumvent this truth.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, Russell introduces a range of previously
unfamiliar material: from Matisse's feelings concerning Ballets
Russe's 1920 production of ``Chant du Rossignol'' with his decor
and costumes, to invitations he and Picasso received in 1931 to
paint murals for Radio City Music Hall, to the genesis of pictures
like ``Interior With a Dog'' and ``Still Life With Oysters.''
</P>
<P>
   Movingly, on several occasions the father reports on his mental
state to his son. ``I need complete calm,'' Henri notes. ``I have
lived for a long time now _haunted by a mortal disquiet that
pursues me day and night.'' And he added, ``Your mother is better,
in certain respects, but she is in a state of total nervous
exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell's approach makes it seem as if the artists themselves,
rather than art historians, are explaining what they do. Henri
Matisse refers to problems getting a series of still lifes started,
while Giacometti writes that ``heads are the most important thing
for the moment, in spite of my longing to go back to the figures.''
And some of the artists' comments also arouse one's sympathy as
they talk about their need to be paid and about aging and illness.
Just before an operation for an intestinal disorder Henri tells
Pierre: ``My eyes are better. But my inside isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters also present intriguing expressions of confidence,
and insecurity, as well as responses to compliments. While Miro
seems constantly to be asserting that whatever is currently at hand
surpasses his previous efforts, Giacometti does the opposite. ``A
lot of people think that it may be the best thing that I've ever
done,'' he writes about a particular work. ``But I see its defects
so clearly.'' And there are poignant notes of anxiety, as when
Giacometti broods: ``I wonder how I shall look beside Maillol and
Despiau. They are two big men, after all.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pierre Matisse seems less compelling than the other
personalities in the book, Russell says that is not the case at
all. These pages mirror the way Pierre conducted himself in life as
well as business. Russell writes: ``Pierre the dealer had an air of
reserve, and sometimes almost of severity. In private, he had
stores of wit, irony and deadpan high spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Matisse was willing to let others shine. As he himself
once put it: ``I did not `make' my artists. My artists made me.''
Nevertheless, he had the talent to get their paintings and
sculptures placed in the finest museums. And now the thoughts he
exchanged with them have finally been brought together by Russell,
who has produced an important record of the way European art of the
20th century entered the hearts and minds of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Matisse: Father &AMP; Son'
</P>
<P>
   By John Russell
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 415 pages. Harry N. Abrams. $39.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
