<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ATTACKS GORE AS A `WASHINGTON, D.C. PERSON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va._ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading Republican
presidential candidate, took aim at Vice President Al Gore Tuesday,
saying the leading Democratic contender ``thinks Washington has all
the answers. I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning here in this reliably Republican state, Bush also
sought to strike a contrast between himself and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal that nearly
cost Clinton his presidency, Bush told some 300 wealthy GOP
contributors at a lunch that if he becomes president, he will
``swear to uphold the dignity of the office to which I have been
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   He collected $300,000 at the luncheon and planned to be the
featured guest at a blue-chip Republican gathering in Washington
Tuesday night. Karen Hughes, Bush's press secretary, said the
Washington gathering would yield $1.5 million in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Republican field in fundraising and in the polls,
Bush started the day by attending a story-telling session at a
library in the predominantly black East End section of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia has supported Republican presidential candidates in
every election since 1964 when voters here sided with Democrat
Lyndon Johnson in his landslide victory over Sen. Barry Goldwater,
R-Ariz. Virginia also has moved up its primary date to Feb. 29,
2000, making it an important state in the Bush campaign strategy to
sew up the nomination early.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife Laura, who has worked as a librarian, read to a
day-care group of 23 children ages three to five, as did Roxanne
Gilmore, wife of Virginia's Republican governor, James Gilmore.
Bush did not read but he presented a children's book, ``Hank, the
Cowdog,'' to the library as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   After the library appearance Bush was asked about Gore. ``He's a
Washington, D.C., person,'' Bush told reporters. ``He thinks
Washington has got all the answers. I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential race unfolds, he added, voters will notice
``a huge difference between (Gore) and me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own campaign tour last week, Gore fired a potshot at Bush
by saying he would continue economic prosperity ``the right way,
not by letting people fend for themselves or hoping for crumbs of
compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the implied criticism, Bush, who calls himself a
``compassionate conservative,'' responded that ``there are no such
things as crumbs of compassion as far as I'm concerned. There are
people who show compassion for a neighbor. That act ought to be
lauded. That act ought to be praised.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that laws and government are not the key to
improving peoples' lives. ``Societies change when neighbor helps
neighbor, when a person in need gets a helping hand. I don't view
that as crumbs. I view that as the greatness of America, the soul
of America. ... My job as president, should I be fortunate enough
to win, is to elevate our spirit, so that America continues to
perform the common-day miracles of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the East End library employees as an example of ``the
armies of compassion staffed by people who care as to whether or
not children in this neighborhood learn how to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also argued that injecting a higher level of morality into
the American culture has been a theme of his since his first race
for governor in 1994. ``This isn't something I just discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the library, several young Democrats held aloft protest
signs saying ``Robertson + Falwell  &QC;  Bush'' (a reference to
christian conservatives Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell) and ``Bush
_ conservative, not compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Bieber, executive director of the Virginia Democratic
Party, who was standing nearby, said of Bush, ``I'm not sure really
what he is or what he stands for. All we have to go on are these
feel-good slogans and these photo opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rosa Whiting, an East End resident who attended the reading
with her 10-year-old daughter Tara, said Bush had impressed her.
``I enjoyed everything he had to say,'' she said, adding that she
planned to him if he wins the Republican nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
