<HEADLINE>
ACTORS TAKING TO THE STAGE  
 THE WEDDING BEAT  
 SNAGGING `AUSTIN'  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACTORS TAKING TO THE STAGE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Actors in television series usually have three months
off in the summer. Some use the time to earn money, making a movie;
some use it to spend money, taking a vacation. And then there are
those intrepid few who tread somewhere in the middle, on the stages
of Manhattan, taking their chances with the New York theater
critics and paying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did turn down a movie, and I thought of taking time off
because our `NYPD Blue' schedule is pretty brutal,'' Bill
Brochtrup, who plays the homosexual station-house administrative
aide in that ABC police drama, said on Tuesday. ``But I'd never
done theater in New York before and it was something I always
wanted to do. And it was the best script I'd seen in a long time,
far better than most movie things I'd read.''
</P>
<P>
   So Brochtrup is now acting in ``Snakebit,'' the Off Broadway
play by David Marshall Grant. He joined the cast on June 8 but will
have to leave the first week in August to resume his television
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Although making a movie would have earned him more money,
``probably by a factor of 10,'' he said, ``This play was, by a
factor of much more than 10, the best choice I could make as an
actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Brochtrup is rare but not alone; this summer, New York theater
has attracted a small flock of television actors. The most
celebrated among them is Calista Flockhart, star of the Fox
network's ``Ally McBeal,'' who is appearing Off Broadway in a
limited run of ``Bash, Latterday Plays'' three separate monologues
by Neil LaBute about murder and other evils.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, two NBC sitcom stars, George Segal (``Just Shoot
Me'') and Wayne Knight (``Third Rock From the Sun'') leapt into the
three-man play ``Art'' almost as soon as their shows stopped
shooting. Their run, starring with Buck Henry, began on May 11 and
is to end on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   And Scott Wolf of ``Party of Five,'' the Fox family drama, has
taken over as Clifford, the son, in ``Side Man'' until July 17.
</P>
<P>
   At least one writer has also made the theater switch this
summer. Julia Dahl, one of six main writers on ``Party of Five,''
wrote ``Wonderland'' four years ago, when she was 24. Last week,
she saw it open at the American Place Theater Off Broadway. (Wolf
was in the audience; she had watched him in ``Side Man'' the
previous night.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up loving theater, from the first play you did in
second grade,'' Ms. Dahl said. ``However you end up making a
living, you do it, but there's nothing like live theater, so that's
why you see people gravitating back to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is always the chance of a siren song calling. Thursday
was opening night Off Broadway for Lisa Gay Hamilton, a regular
cast member in the ABC legal drama ``The Practice.'' Playing the
lead in ``Angelique,'' a drama about an 18th-century Canadian
slave, Ms. Hamilton was called ``luminous'' and her performance
``gallant'' by The New York Times reviewer on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night will be her final performance. She has
resigned from the cast _ to make a movie.
</P>
<P>
   --LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   THE WEDDING BEAT
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been the wedding of the century, but the latest
royal marriage involving the British royal family still proved to
be a potent draw for several cable networks that carried it on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, thanks to the wedding of Prince Edward to Sophie
Rhys-Jones, NBC's all-news channel, MSNBC, was able to beat CNN in
the ratings for a full day for the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
   For the three-hour period the wedding was shown, both MSNBC and
Fox News, which also carried the wedding live, easily beat CNN,
which did not. MSNBC totaled just over 1 million homes for those
three hours, Fox had about 800,000 homes, and CNN trailed with
about 600,000.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question about why CNN chose not to cover the
wedding live. The answer, at least partly, is that it was too
expensive, though CNN executives also objected to a fee that was
being charged for coverage of a state event.
</P>
<P>
   The television rights to the wedding were held by the BBC, which
was able to sublease them to any other broadcaster for a fee
determined by the channel's reach. MSNBC and Fox, which reach about
two-thirds as many homes in America, thus had to pay less than CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The fee that would have been imposed on CNN would have included
its worldwide reach, which is what made it untenable, a CNN
executive said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC and Fox News each paid $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   All the fees are going to the Bagshot Trust, a collection of
charities organized by Prince Edward.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding was also carried live on BBC America, the BBC's
service on American cable systems, which reaches only about 10
million homes, and on one non-news channel, the Learning Channel.
That channel does have a special connection to the prince, however:
Several of the programs produced by his documentary company, Ardent
Productions, have appeared on that channel.
</P>
<P>
   --BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   SNAGGING `AUSTIN'
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its efforts to corral many of the biggest box office
movies for their first broadcast run, TBS announced on Tuesday that
it had acquired initial broadcast rights to this summer's huge hit,
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The film joins other hits recently acquired by the cable
channel, including ``The Mummy,'' ``The Matrix,'' ``Analyze This''
and ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   TBS usually markets a separate rights deal to a broadcast
network for the films, which means that the movies will be shown
six or eight times on TBS before going to say, CBS for a run or
two, before reverting to TBS.
</P>
<P>
   --BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
