<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIOR-DRUGS23-COX     06-22 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-DRUGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS PUSH BILL TO LOWER DRUG PRICES
 &HT;    340&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jim Turner, D-Texas, wants to bring relief to
Frances Staley and all Americans like her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a lovely senior citizen,'' Turner said of Staley, 85,
who he met last year in Orange, Texas. Staley spends her entire
Social Security check trying to pay for 12 prescriptions but still
doesn't have enough money. Like many of her friends, she found a
practical solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a prescription for 30 days and you don't have
the money ... well, you buy half of it,'' she said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Turner described Staley's predicament at a Tuesday press
conference on Capitol Hill where Democratic lawmakers touted a
measure designed to lower the price of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by Turner, would require drug
companies to sell their products to pharmacies at the lowest price
paid by the federal government, which by law can command a lower
price than hospitals or health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It would result in a 30 to 40 percent discount in prescription
drug prices at no significant cost to the federal government,
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No senior citizen in this country should have to take half of
their medication,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Large pharmaceutical companies have conducted a lobbying and
media blitz against the measure, saying that it would eventually
drive up prices for everyone and stifle drug research and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most profitable industry in the country is charging the
highest prices in the world to seniors who have no coverage,'' said
Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine. ``This is bad medicine, bad economics and
bad public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The relief can't come soon enough for Staley, who is blind and
needs a dozen prescriptions to treat ailments including a heart
condition and high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Staley said many politicians in Washington don't realize the
hardships of senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they know the half of what the common people are
having to contend with,'' she said. ``Our Social Security wouldn't
pay for one of their meals.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have embraced the issue in an effort to court senior
citizens, a group that could be vital to a Democratic hopes of
regaining control of the House in next year's elections. Recent
polls show senior citizens tending to prefer Republican policies to
those of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription drug issue is part of a larger Democratic
health care plan that includes adding a prescription drug benefit
to Medicare and creating a ``patients' bill of rights'' that would
impose new regulations on health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Democratic efforts to end the ``exorbitant'' cost of
prescription drugs will
</P>
<P>
   resonate with the public throughout next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it. This is a kitchen table issue,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The expense of prescription drugs and the stress and hardship it
causes senior citizens has been a focus for Turner, who sits on a
congressional task force on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Turner commissioned a study last year that found that some
senior citizens in his district are paying twice as much as drug
companies charge large customers such as health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
