<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REFUGEES-HNS &LR;      06-22 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REFUGEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES REFUGEES TO DELAY RETURN TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVEC REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ President Clinton implored
ethnic Albanian refugees Tuesday to delay their rush home to Kosovo
so that peacekeeping forces can clear land mines, stockpiles of
Serbian ammunition and unexploded allied bombs that could
jeopardize their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appeal had a secondary goal of trying to keep clogged
roads into Kosovo clear of returning refugees to speed the
deployment of the 50,000-strong allied security force. Barely half
of the force of British, French, German, Italian and U.S. soldiers
had moved into Kosovo by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have suffered enough. I don't want any child hurt,''
Clinton told several hundred cheering, chanting refugees squeezed
into a fenced enclosure in a sprawling tent city that shelters
10,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I ask you, please be patient with us, give us a couple of
more weeks to take land mines up,'' the president said. ``I want to
make sure it is a happy return.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 camp residents already have returned to
Kosovo, a province of Serbia. Serbia is the dominant state of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's caution came one day after two Nepalese Gurkhas in the
British Army and two civilians died as they prepared to dispose of
unexploded munitions found in a school in Negrovce, 20 miles from
Kosovo's capital of Pristina. Clinton spoke by phone with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials estimate that Yugoslav forces sowed one million
mines across the largely agrarian province, an area the size of
greater Los Angeles. A United Nations' survey found mines, booby
traps and unexploded bombs lurking in almost 800 separate areas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
their daughter Chelsea, addressed the refugees after an emotional
rendezvous with refugee children.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons met Idriz Magastena, 29, his wife Nerimane, and
their son Besart, 4. The father told the Clintons the family fled
their village and sheltered in Pristina for five weeks until
Serbian troops broke in. A soldier seized their son, put a knife to
one side of his throat and a lighted cigarette to the other side,
and demanded money from the boy's frightened family.
</P>
<P>
   The father told the Clintons the family joined a caravan of
civilian vehicles headed toward Macedonia. Armed Serbs intercepted
the convoy, seized one person from each vehicle, and shot or
stabbed the victim to death.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother told the Clintons that her son is ``still very
much afraid. He has seen people killed and wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The president replied, ``We have to make sure families get help
for their children. There are some things children should never
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after meeting with the Magastena family, told
reporters: ``Many of the children have a glazed-over look. It's the
children that don't cry that you worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   After his meeting, the three Clintons walked hand-in-hand with
refugee children toward a plain flat platform set before the
assembled refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton moved deliberately, without exuberance or an air of
triumph. It was only well into his remarks that Clinton struck a
note of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of what we did (in Kosovo) because we think it is
what America stands for,'' he said, as a crowd chanted ``U-S-A,''
``Billy'' or ``Clinton'' at different points.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president chose not to appeal
directly to the refugees to surrender their own hatreds of the
Serbs when they return to their homes. Clinton privately conceded
that he had detected ``some bitterness'' among refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Weary refugees interviewed at random in the camp said they were
so wounded by their upheaval, the loss of relatives, the
destruction of their homes and their fruitless search for loved
ones that it may take generations before their families can live in
harmony with the Serbs, who are the minority ethnic group in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees clutched a telephone-book style listing of 19,658
families, representing 130,000 refugees, who had registered with
the International Rescue Committee's ``Kosovar Family Finder
Project'' in an effort to track down missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aroh Hysehi, 30, a barber who escaped the Serb enclave of Kovo
Polg, said his trusted Serbian neighbors turned on his family the
night allied bombing began March 24. ``Living with Serbs is not
possible now,'' Hysehi said. ``I know this in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismeti Cerkiki, 54, clutching his 23 month-old son Granit, said
he is only willing to return to his home in Ferizaj because Serbs
have been driven out by fear of reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Serbs are gone and I'm glad they're gone,'' he said.
``I can live there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatmir Berisha, 27, of Pristina, who took his wife and two
children, ages 4 and 3, to the camp a month ago, said thoughts of
reconciliation have withered after returning to Pristina to see
what was left of his family home. Berisha returned to the camp
Monday from Pristina to tell his wife and children that their home
was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' he said. ``I would like to go back home but
I have nothing to go home to.''
</P>
<P>
   Berisha said he would remain in the camp to see if the allied
security force or international relief agencies might help him
rebuild. But if they cannot, Berisha said he would look into the
possibility of emigrating to another country with his family,
possibly to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start where it is safe,'' Berisha said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees welcomed Clinton's visit to the camp even though they
said they expected little immediate relief from their day-to-day
plight _ or the challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Florent Kqiku told the Clintons through an interpreter: ``The
Albanian people will never forget, you brought the most precious
gift of all _ freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Vjolca Demiri, a refugee from Gilan who was holding her
eight-month-old nephew Florent Basija on her chest as she spoke
with a reporter, called Clinton a hero. ``The president saved us _
2 million people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to a refugee camp and a subsequent stopover to
thank allied pilots based in Aviano, Italy, capped a seven-day trip
to Europe to launch a Balkan reconstruction effort. The president
hopes to substitute prosperity and tolerance for the ethnic hatreds
and rivalries that enabled Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
carry out a murderous rampage across Kosovo that killed an
estimated 10,000 civilians and uprooted 1.6 million others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must create real opportunities for ordinary citizens
throughout Southeastern Europe,'' Clinton told President Kiro
Gligorov of Macedonia, which absorbed an estimated 300,000 refugees
from Kosovo. Some 50,000 of them have already returned home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before joining her husband for the visit to the refugee camp,
Mrs. Clinton took part in a ceremony in Skopje where New York-based
Liz Claiborne Inc., announced the donation of fabric and components
for Macedonian suppliers to produce more than 200,000 shirts and
trousers for Kosovars in Macedonia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is expected to announce preparations for a Senate
campaign from New York in early July.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development donated $881,000
to Mercy Corps International, which in turn will purchase the
finished clothing form Macedonian suppliers who will employ up to
3,000 workers for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Claiborne Chairman Paul Charron told the first lady and
others attending the ceremony: ``We hope to make a small but real
difference in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached by E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
