<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 23, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A plume of moist air will stream north through the Mississippi
Valley to the central Great Lakes as breezes from the south quicken
ahead of a weak cool front. Clouds and clusters of showers and
thunderstorms will be common in these regions. Sultry air will
combine with a jet stream disturbance over the southern Mississippi
Valley to cause a concentrated cluster of thundershowers that will
produce locally heavy rain in parts of Arkansas southern Missouri
and western Tennessee. Farther north, a few strong thunderstorms
will develop as the cool front lifts the increasingly humid air
over the northern Mississippi Valley. In the wake of the front,
drier air will sweep from the northern Rockies to the northern
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast and Middle Atlantic States will become warmer and
slightly more humid. Sunshine will be plentiful in most areas,
however, some puffy cumulus clouds will develop during the
afternoon, especially over interior sections. Sea breezes will cool
the shoreline during the midday and afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Florida will have fewer showers than recent days as an offshore
front drifts farther east. Elsewhere in the Southeast, there will
be a mixture of sunshine and clouds with isolated afternoon
thundershowers, particularly near the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, clouds and a few showers will cling to the coast
from Washington to central Oregon. Meanwhile, the Southwest will
continue to be very warm with ample sunshine. Clouds and a few
thunderstorms will form over the Rockies in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Abnormal Warmth
</P>
<P>
   A period of persistent warmth at Madison, Wis., has reached a
record-setting 18 months. Every month since December 1997 has been
warmer than normal. For climatological record keeping, ``normal''
is defined as the average for the most recent complete three
decades. The period 1961-1990 is currently used. Regional climates
display complex rhythms of warmth and chill that span many time
scales from years to decades to centuries. The 30-year period is
used to help even out some of the peaks and valleys that represent
the constantly changing climate of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
