<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more than 900 years, the fishermen of Favignana, a small
island off Sicily, have gone after bluefin tuna in the same
ritualistic way. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate
through the surrounding waters, the men await a signal from their
leader to begin the mattanza, a highly choreographed communal hunt
with prayers and songs and rigid rules that is seldom seen around
Sicily anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times Photo Service has moved a photo package of six
photos on Tuesday, June 22, 1999, slugged: ITALY-TUNA.
</P>
<P>
   The photos, by New York Times Photographer James Hill, are as
follows:
</P>
<P>
   NYT1, Clemente, a tonnoretti, or fisherman, steers his boat out
to sea to fish for bluefin tuna.
</P>
<P>
   NYT2, Fishermen pull in a haul of bluefin tuna.
</P>
<P>
   NYT3, a heavy load of tuna is pulled onto a boat off Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   NYT4, A small fishing boat lies on the beach in front of the old
tuna factory which is now closed. For hundreds of years, the
fishermen of Favignana could live off the sea. But the cannery on
the island closed 16 years ago for lack of product.
</P>
<P>
   NYT5, A bluefin tuna is pulled into a boat off Sicily by
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   NYT6, Tuna is prepared by a fishmonger.
</P>
