<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPANISH-TALK-SHOW-2TA     06-22 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPANISH-TALK-SHOW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH-LANGUAGE TV'S CRISTINA SARALEGUI: LATIN FLAIR (AND FLARE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The subject was ``I have the worst husband in the
world,'' and the three couples dug into it with relish. The women
complained that their husbands never took them out and were too
jealous or boring; the men retorted that their wives denied them
sex and would rather go out than take care of the children.
</P>
<P>
   The standard talk show fare droned on for a while when a
confrontation erupted from an unexpected corner. A man in the
studio audience, speaking up to side with one of the husbands,
referred to the man's wife as ``vieja.'' In Colombia, where the man
was from, vieja means woman, but in Mexico, where the wife was
from, it means  &UR; old &LR;  woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``For starters, do not call me `vieja,' because you don't know
me and you have no reason to be disrespectful to me!'' the
aggrieved woman said angrily as the audience clapped and hollered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling you `vieja' in the most affectionate sense of the
word,'' the man stammered nervously, ``not because of age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, be specific,'' the woman snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Semantics is just one of the pitfalls with which Cristina
Saralegui contends in ``El Show de Cristina,'' the highest-rated
talk show on Spanish-language television. It is celebrating its
10th anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saralegui, a Cuban-American with sparkling green eyes and
dyed platinum blond hair, has often been described as the Hispanic
Oprah Winfrey. (They have the same birthday, Jan. 29.) But Ms.
Winfrey has not had to juggle the slang of dozens of countries or
faced a boycott for hurting national sensitivities or gone to
Mexico to face a scandalized audience accusing her of corrupting
the whole country.
</P>
<P>
   Many viewers were shocked in 1996 when Ms. Saralegui told two
gay couples, ``I'm marrying you here because I don't have any type
of prejudice and because I think that what you're doing is
correct,'' and had the ceremony broadcast. That show cost her bomb
threats and pickets.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there widespread understanding when she had a doctor
demonstrate proper condom use on a large cucumber. To this day the
show, a five-days-a-week program (with one night special edition)
that is taped in Miami and broadcast to the United States and as
many as 18 countries, is shown only at night in many Latin American
markets because of its risque content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience is a lot more traditional than your
general-market American audience,'' Ms. Saralegui (pronounced
sah-rah-LEG-ee) said over lunch recently at her Miami Beach mansion
in one of the exclusive islands that dot Biscayne Bay. ``Hispanics
in the United States were not used to talk about incest,
homosexuality, AIDS, domestic violence or child abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before Ms. Saralegui contributed to linguistic common
ground with words like heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saralegui, 51, was editor-in-chief of the Spanish-language
edition of Cosmopolitan when she was tapped to do her own talk show
in April 1989 by Univision, the country's largest Spanish-language
television network. The network promoted her as ``the Oprah Winfrey
with salsa.'' The term made Ms. Saralegui wince, but she joked that
she preferred it to being called ``Donahue in drag.''
</P>
<P>
   While Phil Donahue, Ms. Winfrey, Sally Jessy Raphael and Geraldo
Rivera dominated the talk-show format on English-language
television, Ms. Saralegui was among the first to try it in Spanish.
And while she borrowed from the other shows, she was all alone in
trying to tame that multi-headed beast, the Hispanic-American mass
market.
</P>
<P>
   This meant that before she tackled issues like cheating husbands
and lesbian mothers, there was the business of Ms. Saralegui's
accent. As a writer for magazines that sold all over Latin America,
Ms. Saralegui said she was mindful of using what she calls ``a
Pan-American vocabulary'' to avoid words that are common in one
country but are considered obscene in another, and to be sensitive
to colloquialisms and the many terms that Hispanic people can use
to refer to something like beans, depending on nationality.
</P>
<P>
   But she was insulted when the network suggested diction classes
to neutralize her Cuban accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said no because I was 41,'' Ms. Saralegui said, too old for
such a drastic change, and because ``I'm really proud of being a
Cuban.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the hate mail after the first few shows, criticizing
her as ``too white'' to represent Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were as prejudiced with me as others were with
them,'' Ms. Saralegui said.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has long won acceptance, the balancing act required
to appeal to dozens of subgroups was underscored again last year
when several Dominican organizations in the United States accused
her of distorting the image of Dominicans by having a
disproportionate number of them on shows with sordid themes. The
groups managed to get some advertisers to cancel ads and brought a
television news magazine expose in the Dominican Republic, where
some panelists admitted having invented their stories to get a free
trip to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part in which she has experts counseling people lasts two
minutes,'' complained Nuria Piera, the producer who did the expose.
``The rest of the show is people applauding anti-values _ vices,
our garbage. What is highlighted is the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In full-page newspaper ads in the Dominican Republic, Ms.
Saralegui called the charges absurd. Her own investigation, she
said, turned up only one panelist who admitted to lying to get on
the show, and she denied that nationality played any role in the
selection of her guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are chosen based on their eloquence, the emotion they
project and, of course, the journalistic importance of their
story,'' she wrote, ``never because of their nationality.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ratings and her audience of 1.1 million households daily and
1.9 million on Monday night in the United States and millions more
in Latin America have held up through the controversies. Even the
most horrified Hispanic viewers, it seems, appreciate watching
their particular idiosyncrasies and dysfunctions on television
through debates on subjects like bigamist immigrants and surgically
restored virgins.
</P>
<P>
   And they have embraced a host who is opinionated and so
unmercifully blunt that sometimes she is the one bleeped out, who
admits her age (and that of her husband, who is younger, at 40),
her plastic surgeries, her cellulite and her weakness for tequila,
who has become a forceful advocate of causes like AIDS prevention
and who has assumed the parts of cheerleader, teacher, role model
and mother hen to Hispanic viewers in the United States, whether
they like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has opened up avenues of communication, she has shed light
on a lot of issues that needed to have light shed on them,'' said
Lisa Navarrete, a spokeswoman for the National Council of La Raza,
a Hispanic civil rights group. ``She helps in the education and
assimilation process in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saralegui, who is called Mati by relatives, close friends
and staff, has also become a millionaire, parlaying her show into a
multimedia empire she owns with her husband and manager, Marcos
Avila. The couple have three children.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cristina Saralegui Enterprises Inc. produces her show and
``Cristina Opina,'' a syndicated radio program, and publishes
``Cristina,'' a monthly magazine. She has a Web site, commercial
endorsements and even her own line of fashion eyewear.
</P>
<P>
   This year the company plans to move all its operations into a
$3.1 million, two-story building here, with another $3 million for
renovations in the works, Avila said. The building will have three
studios to produce other shows.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Saralegui just signed a three-year contract for her
show, she said that even she, ``a work mule with menopause,'' was
tiring of the grind of doing 220 shows a year and was looking for
other endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to be compared to somebody, it is to Martha
Stewart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But before Martha or Oprah, her model was Helen Gurley Brown,
the longtime editor of Cosmopolitan. In a book published last year,
``Cristina! My Life as a Blonde'' (Warner Books), Ms. Saralegui
described her as mentor and ``the person I admire most in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 years Ms. Saralegui served as guru to ``la chica Cosmo''
as editor in chief of Cosmopolitan en Espanol was the culmination
of a long career in Spanish-language magazines before her move to
television. (Ms. Saralegui was born into a wealthy publishing
family that owned Cuba's leading magazines before Fidel Castro took
power, and it went into exile in 1960, when she was 12.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Ms. Saralegui tried a crossover into English with a
trial run of her show on 25 CBS stations. She and Avila said they
dropped the idea despite encouraging ratings because they could not
settle on financial terms for future shows.
</P>
<P>
   Back in her Spanish-language habitat, Ms. Saralegui is totally
at ease, whether urging a quarreling couple to get a divorce or
scolding an audience member for vulgarity. The show fills several
niches _ it can be as raunchy as Jerry Springer's and as
soul-baring as Oprah's, a mixture of sex and confrontations,
celebrity interviews and educational debate _ and Ms. Saralegui
herself can be all over the place. She is irreverent and
foul-mouthed, immodest and self-effacing, ruthless and nurturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you something,'' she told a woman in between takes
during the recent taping of a show about orphans of natural
disasters and the infertile couples who want to adopt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I married my second husband, I wanted to have a child,
and I had the same condition as yours and lost a baby just like
you. The doctor told me `Take out your uterus,' and I told him:
`You know what? This uterus is mine, not yours.' I changed doctors
and now I have a 13-year-old son.''
</P>
<P>
   Call her Oprah-Martha-Helen with a dash of Judge Judy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She speaks her mind,'' said Enrique Rivas, 48, a Colombian in
the audience who has lived in the United States for 12 years. ``She
makes us laugh and cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saralegui said she also strives to uplift; her trademark
signoff is a flickering thumbs-up. After a decade on the air, she
said, her goal remains ``raising my people's self-esteem and
knowledge quotient so they can succeed in this very competitive
country, and making them feel that they are supported in their
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   She also insists on ``translating'' Hispanics for one another
and pursuing their elusive unity, saying common denominators such
as the value that Hispanics place on family, spirituality and
tradition, and being hobbled by the same problems, far outweigh the
differences and prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common denominator all Latinos have is that we want some
respect,'' she said. ``That's what we're all fighting for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
