<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO _ LJUBLJANA, Slovenia - Final day of visit by
President Clinton to Slovenia. The president is expected to stop
off at Stenkovich I refugee camp in Skopje, Macedonia. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MAIN _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Belgium postponed a decision on
whether to remove its ban on some Coca-Cola Co. products.The
Belgian government, whose own scientists said there's nothing to
gain from extending the ban, late today said a decision wouldn't
come today. The French press gency is reporting that Marylise
Lebranchu, the French consumer affairs official, said Tuesday that
she had a ``personal conviction: that the end of the Coke crisis
very near. (Roughton, Cox News Service in Brussels; Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution in Atlanta). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ Coca-Cola's stock was up 4 percent in early trading
on Wall Street. Coca-Enterprises also traded higher. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-COKE _ MIAMI _ Coca-Cola Co. has had a run of bad fortune.
First the Asian crisis and the collapse of the Russian ruble. Now
there are the difficulties in Europe. But Coke's image and
prospects have yet to be hurt in one important area: Latin America,
the company's second-biggest market after the United States. Coke
officials say they look to the region, where Coke has been a
presence before the turn of the century, to drive growth in coming
years. (Emling, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BOX _ Coca-Cola's market share in various countries.
(Emling, Cox News Service). 6.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas holds a news
conference Tuesday at the Capitol with some of his numerous
congressional supporters. The event underlines Bush's strength and
also a potential weakness because Democrats are trying to tie him
to a Republican-led Congress it says is bowing to the gun and
tobacco industries. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Political categories.
</P>
<P>
   LAURA-BUSH _ AUSTIN _ Much has been made about whether Gov.
George W. Bush got what he wanted from the 1999 Legislature. But
few people even knew First Lady Laura Bush also had a legislative
agenda. But while the spotlight was on her husband, Laura Bush
quietly worked for passage of a bill creating special Head Start
programs for reading. Are these the beginnings of her own White
House career? (Brooks, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITIES _ States may have to place people with
mental disabilities in homelike settings if they can fare just as
well there as in state hospitals, the Supreme Court said today in a
narrow, middle-of-the-road ruling. By a 6-3 vote in a Georgia case,
the court said a federal anti-bias law, the Americans with
Disabilities Act, requires such community placement of the mentally
disabled whenever appropriate. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   CARTER _ WASHINGTON _ Former President Jimmy Carter delivers
remarks at the Global Health Council's conference on ``Global
Health, Poverty and Development.'' (Hill, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS _ WASHINGTON _ Linda Jones's history of lying and
psychological treatment were brought out Tuesday by government
prosecutors trying to get tapes she made of former HUD Secretary
Henry Cisneros admitted in Cisneros's fraud trial. The damaging
information was seen as an attempt to ``inoculate'' Cisneros's
former mistress against attacks by his defense lawyers, who start
cross-examining Jones later Tuesday. (Malone, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Finance Committee
marks up the U.S.-Caribbean Basin Trade Enhancement Act. (Lipman,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-TRAVEL _ WASHINGTON _ So you're bored with the beach and
you've toured Europe. When it comes to traveling, you've been
there, done that. Where on earth can you go for a real adventure?
How about a vacation in space? ``It's a lot closer than a lot of
people think,'' said Eric Anderson, general manager of Space
Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories. (Dart,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   LABS _ WASHINGTON _ As many as 5,000 nuclear scientists and
other officials with top-secret clearances at the Energy Department
will be given lie detector tests as part of a broader program to
beef up security and anti-espionage programs, department officials
say. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson was expected to provide
details of the polygraph testing program today at a Senate hearing
where he also was to resist broader restructuring of his department
_ a reorganization that critics say would give weapons programs
greater autonomy and safeguard nuclear secrets. (Carr, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ Drug companies should be ashamed of
themselves for gouging senior citizens, a group of Democratic
lawmakers said Tuesday. At a press conference, Rep. Jim Turner, of
Texas, and other House members urged their collegues to support a
measure designed to lower prescription drug prices. Democrats have
embraced this issue as they try to court senior citizens - a group
that some say could be vital to a Democratic take-back of the House
next year. (Moscoso, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AUSTINPOWERS-DOLL _ ATLANTA _ Toys R Us responds to a metro
Atlanta mother's battle to get the Austin Powers doll off the
shelves of suburban stores That's where Tamatha Barron's
11-year-old son first had his harrowing experience with the word
''horny.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Also moving in (e) Entertainment category.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO SHELTER _ Duane West wanted a little bit more protection
than his mobile home had to offer the next time a tornado came
through East Texas. West, the landlord of Tall Pines Mobile Home
Park, kept his tenants in mind when he decided to buy three
underground shelters, spread out among the 24 mobile homes and
about 75 people in his park. w/art of shelter being installed.
(Ferguson, Longview News-Journal).
</P>
