<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABUTE-PROFILE-2TAKES     06-22 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABUTE-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILMMAKER'S FAITH IN GOD, IF NOT IN MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Wash., Utah)  (mk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For many moviegoers there is almost nothing like
sitting through a Neil LaBute film. Nothing more depressing on
screen. Nothing more likely to induce despair, or more frightening,
perhaps, for what it shows us about human beings. Sexual cruelty.
Domination. Hatred. LaBute shoves them in your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meanest movies in Hollywood,'' Details magazine has said
of LaBute's work.
</P>
<P>
   And now with ``Bash, Latterday Plays,'' which opens Thursday at
the Douglas Fairbanks Theater in New York and is to continue
through July 24, LaBute has done it again, for the stage this time,
in three separate monologues starring Ron Eldard, Calista Flockhart
and Paul Rudd. The first two are about infanticide and the third is
a brutal account of a gay bashing.
</P>
<P>
   And yet here sits LaBute, a Mormon convert, father of two, who
lives in a pleasant suburb north of Chicago, a big teddy bear of a
man in an unironed shirt over a T-shirt, politely answering
questions in a midtown restaurant. ``You're the last person in
charge of what you write,'' LaBute, who is 36, said in his soft
voice. The dark stories seem to pour out despite himself. In
creating the monologues he said he consciously borrowed the
techniques of Greek tragedy, like characters telling of horrific
events that have occurred offstage.
</P>
<P>
   He is also drawn to the monologue form because it allows the
character to be ``as personal as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute is best known for his film ``In the Company of Men,''
about two men who deliberately set out to destroy a young deaf
woman by seducing and then brutally rejecting her. In his second
film, ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' about emotional violence and
sexual failure among a group of friends, a character announces that
the best sex he ever had was when he participated in the gang rape
of a boy in high school.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bash, Latterday Plays,'' which is directed by Joe Mantello,
the characters are all associated to varying degrees with
Mormonism, a first in LaBute's work.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Medea Redux,'' one of the play's monologues, Ms. Flockhart,
on hiatus from the television show ``Ally McBeal,'' plays a
teen-ager who has been seduced by her teacher and becomes pregnant.
When he abandons her, she exacts a terrible revenge. Ms. Flockart
does not portray the teen-ager as a victim, she said. ``She's
betrayed, but strong and capable and smart and hurt. She's Medea.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening's second segment, ``Iphegenia in Orem,'' Eldard
plays a young executive who recounts two stories, one about being
told he is going to lose his job and the other about his baby
daughter's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   The final segment of the play, ``A Gaggle of Saints,'' is a dual
monologue with Rudd and Ms. Flockhart. Rudd portrays a handsome,
initially charming college student who, during a night on the town
with his girlfriend, beats a gay man in a bathroom in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The trick of playing such a brutal figure, said Rudd, whose most
recent stage role was Orsino in the Lincoln Center Theater
production of ``Twelfth Night,'' ``is getting the audience on your
side'' so that it will stay with the character.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's monologue is interwoven with that of Ms. Flockhart. She
plays his girlfriend, describing a wonderful weekend in New York,
blissfully ignoring whatever knowledge of his behavior she might
carry in her heart. ``I view her as somebody in denial,'' Ms.
Flockhart said, ``able to shut out the dark, ugly truth, but she
knows the truth fully.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute said he chose Ms. Flockhart for the play because ``she
comes in with a great deal of good will,'' because of her role on
``Ally McBeal.'' ``A lot of people put a certain kind of trust in
her,'' LaBute said. ``I want to see how that works when you lead
them into a place they may not want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flockhart has performed on Broadway in ``Three Sisters'' and
``The Glass Menagerie,'' but she said she had never acted in
anything like ``Bash,'' reciting for 35 minutes straight before an
audience without cues or interaction with other actors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the play's Mormon subtext, LaBute said he does not
intend ``Bash'' to be a commentary on Mormonism. He uses Mormonism
because he is familiar with it, he said. In the play it is ``a
universal for characters brought up under a religious authority.
You would imagine they would know better. But just being part of a
religion doesn't make you good.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does the preoccupation with violence and evil come
from? LaBute, who was raised in Spokane, Wash., hints at a
difficult relationship with his father, who was a truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reaction to my father in terms of the severity of
my male characters,'' he said. ``I found my father to be a
difficult character to grow up with.'' When his mother saw ``In the
Company of Men,'' with its sadistic male characters, LaBute
recounts, she said, ```Oh, that was his father.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was gregarious, quite charming, very handsome,'' LaBute
said of his father. ``He had lots of great qualities from afar. But
on closer examination the painting did not hold its light.'' His
parents are now divorced, and he and his father are ``pretty much
estranged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute, who has an older brother, a businessman, attended a
nondenominational Protestant church with his family, though they
were not deeply religious. He accepted a scholarship to Brigham
Young University in Provo, Utah, a Mormon institution, because it
had a good theater program and a film studio.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham Young ``was a very refreshing change'' from his home
life, LaBute said. He was ``surrounded by very nice, helpful, kind
people, so driven by a passion for religion.'' He fell in love with
a Mormon student, Lisa Gore, and they married. His wife is now a
family therapist. Their children are Lily, 11, and Spencer, 8.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Brigham Young he was required to study the Book of Mormon. He
found himself drawn to the religion's ethical and spiritual stance,
and he converted. ``The great thing about it, you can say
definitely, `This is what it is,''' said LaBute, who accepts the
basic Mormon belief that the angel Moroni appeared to the
religion's founder, Joseph Smith, in Palmyra, N.Y. ``The idea of
modern prophecy makes people very nervous,'' LaBute said. ``I have
little difficulty acknowledging the possibility of modern prophecy
by an inherent faith.''
</P>
<P>
   After he graduated from college, he got a master of fine arts in
dramatic writing at New York University, and while he was there his
first play, ``Filthy Talk for Troubled Times,'' a series of
explicit and sometimes profane monologues set in a bar, was
produced in 1992 Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Brigham Young to study for a Ph.D. in theater.
There he was barred from staging one of his productions, but gained
access to the campus theater and the show went on. The play,
``Lepers,'' was about ``some disagreements between the men and
women,'' he said with a smile. Otherwise, there has been
``fortunately, precious little reaction'' to his work from church
elders. ``I always liked things that had parameters, demarcation
lines,'' LaBute said of Mormonism's strict teachings. ``And to see
how far I can travel within those lines.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a professor of theater at St. Francis College in Fort
Wayne, Ind., when he made ``In the Company of Men'' on $25,000
borrowed from a friend. Like most of his work, it provoked praise
and outrage. At one screening, an audience member even punched the
film's publicist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here all we are dealing with is sociopathic behavior that has
no real-world resonance,'' Richard Schickel wrote in Time magazine.
``The movie's sheer grimness militates against anyone other than a
masochist volunteering to pay money to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it won the Filmmaker's Trophy at the Sundance Film
Festival and the award for best first feature from the New York
Film Critics Circle. The New York Times critic Janet Maslin praised
it as a ``tremendously gutsy first feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Today LaBute's home near Chicago is ``equidistant from
everything,'' he said. ``Besides, there's a lot of good theater''
in Chicago, he added. LaBute said he had written several
full-length plays that are not monologues. But there are no
immediate plans to produce them.
</P>
<P>
   He is editing his first big-budget feature film, ``Nurse
Betty,'' with Chris Rock, Morgan Freeman, Renee Zellweger and Greg
Kinnear. In the movie, written by James Flamberg and John Richards,
Ms. Zellweger is a woman who witnesses her husband's murder and
becomes delusional, convinced that she has jilted her favorite soap
opera star, played by Kinnear. Rock and Freeman are hit men sent to
kill her.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may look at it at first as more upbeat'' than his other
work, LaBute said. ``It has both light and dark in it. In the past
my work was mostly black or dark gray. This one broaches into the
territory of beige or eggshell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
