<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFRICAN REFUGEES SHORTED ON AID, CARTER SAYS
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ Former President Jimmy Carter said Tuesday he
is increasingly disturbed by the disproportionate media coverage
and financial aid given to war victims of European nations compared
to those from Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said that while he was pleased with the assistance given
to Kosovo refugees, those from Third World nations are equally
deserving of help. You could travel a sizable portion of Africa and
``never set foot on peaceful ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the great progress that has been made in
globalization, we still have a long way to go in terms of
comprehending the lives of those who are much different from us,''
Carter said. ``We know about it, but we don't do much about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter spoke at the Global Health Council's annual conference,
``Global Health, Poverty and Development.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president's comments reflect his recent reply to a
question about the greatest challenge facing people in the coming
millennium. Carter replied that he believes it is the ``existing
and growing chasm between rich people and poor people,'' and
suggested that increasing poverty is the cause of more wars today
than ever before in history.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
