<P>
   COKE-MAIN _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Belgium postponed a decision on
whether to remove its ban on some Coca-Cola Co. products.The
Belgian government, whose own scientists said there's nothing to
gain from extending the ban, late today said a decision wouldn't
come today. The French press gency is reporting that Marylise
Lebranchu, the French consumer affairs official, said Tuesday that
she had a ``personal conviction: that the end of the Coke crisis
very near. (Roughton, Cox News Service in Brussels; Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution in Atlanta). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ Coca-Cola's stock was up 4 percent in early trading
on Wall Street. Coca-Enterprises also traded higher. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   PC-EXPO _ NEW YORK _ At PCExpo in New York, Michael Dell speaks
to reporters Tuesday morning about the problems and the future of
the computer industry. Netscape founder Marc Andreesen gives the
keynote. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Finance Committee
marks up the U.S.-Caribbean Basin Trade Enhancement Act. (Lipman,
Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PARTNERS _ BellSouth long said it needed no partners.
Then it finally invested in Qwest, buying 10 percent of the
company. Now, as the landscape keeps changing, it's wondering if
that is enough? BellSouth, Qwest, Global Crossing, US West and
Frontier.... How will this all shake out? What are the stakes for
BellSouth? What are the options? (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-AIRFRANCE _ Delta and Air France say their new exclusive
marketing partnership, announced as expected Tuesday, is the first
step in creating a global alliance to compete with those that
already include several rivals. We also talk to Delta CEO Leo
Mullin, who chalks up a strategic win with the Air France deal
after previously losing a bid to buy Continental and seeing a
domestic alliance with United fizzle. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-QA _ Q&AMP;A with Greg Stromberg, president of
MindSpring's new division, MindSpring Biz (cq). (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WEB MD _ WebMD Inc. and Healtheon Corp. may be poised for a
multi-billion merger, but the companies have a business built with
smoke and mirrors, hyped wildly beyond their abilities to deliver
goods and services _ let along make a profit during the foreseeable
future. But wait: WebMD and Healtheon are, in fact, readying for a
merger that will leave the combined company well-positioned to
become one of the dominant players in healthcare services delivered
online to physicians, institutions and consumers. Only in the
Internet business might both sentences be true. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 55.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ A new study reaffirms a painful situation: Most
Americans think they will have enough money to support a
comfortable retirement, but many haven't done much to make it
happen. Last Tuesday, a Washington think tank released an important
survey on how Americans are dealing with a much broader range of
tasks that go into building a prosperous retirement. The 1999
Retirement Confidence Survey shows we have a high degree of
confidence things will come out right. The study also indicates a
high degree of self-reliance. Nearly half the respondents said
their personal savings will be their most important source of
retirement income. Only one in eight said they look to Social
Security or other government programs. It sure does sound good. But
the study also points out specific actions that many people haven't
taken. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0622 _ The Isuzu Amigo defiantly isn't for
everyone who's given thought to owning a sport-utility, compact or
larger. The chief reason is that the Amigo won't let driver or
passengers forget that it's a truck. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color photo of car's
exterior and 2-column color photo of car's interior and 1-column
photo of car's interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 1999 Isuzu Amigo.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ This summer, instead of sending your teen off to
the beach, pool or a typical summer camp, you might want to
consider something different _ driving camp. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist.
</P>
