<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZA-ABBOTT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT LABS TO BUY DRUGMAKER ALZA FOR $7.3 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     and CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alza Corp., the Palo Alto drug company that
developed the NicoDerm anti-smoking patch, said Monday it has
agreed to be acquired by Abbott Laboratories for $7.3 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Alza is one of the Bay Area's oldest and biggest pharmaceutical
companies and one of the few profitable ones. Monday's deal is the
latest in a recent string of buyouts of local biomedical firms.
</P>
<P>
   Alza Chief Executive Ernest Mario announced the acquisition
Monday afternoon to several hundred employees at a hastily arranged
meeting on the lawn of the company's headquarters. Mario then
jumped on a plane to join Abbott Chief Executive Miles White in New
York, where they will explain the deal to Wall Street investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Alza Vice President Jim Young, Mario told employees
that he would leave the company once the deal is complete.
</P>
<P>
   White said Alza will keep its name and operate as a division of
Abbott. He said it would be premature to name a successor to Mario.
</P>
<P>
   Alza employs about 2,000 people, including 1,300 in the Bay
Area. White said any layoffs would be ``incidental,'' because
Abbott, a drug industry giant based in Illinois, is acquiring Alza
for its research and development expertise and its brand name in
drug delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Alza was founded in 1968 by Alejandro Zaffaroni, who named the
company using the first two letters of his first and last names.
Zaffaroni wanted to find ways to deliver drugs to the body other
than pills and shots. Alza's early products included a glaucoma
patch inserted under the eyelid and an intrauterine device.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost money for 14 years, but an anti-motion-sickness
skin patch introduced in 1984 helped turn around its fortunes. In
1991, it released the first anti-smoking patch, marketed by
SmithKline Beecham under the name NicoDerm.
</P>
<P>
   Ciba-Geigy, the Swiss drug company, bought about 80 percent of
Alza stock in 1978, and Alza bought back all but 10 percent of that
in 1982. It went public in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Zaffaroni, who founded several other Bay Area biomedical firms,
retired as Alza's chairman at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Alza concentrated on drug delivery and relied
mainly on royalties from the companies that sold the actual drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But now Alza has begun developing its own pharmaceuticals,
specializing in urology and oncology. In February, it started
selling Ditropan XL, a new one-a-day formula to control weak
bladders that competes with Detrol, an incontinence medicine from
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alza had grown into one of the Bay Area's few
profitable bio-pharmaceutical companies, with several promising new
products in the wings, the company's shares had fallen in recent
months as Wall Street soured on biotech.
</P>
<P>
   Alza stock hit a 52-week high of $53.31 in March before falling
to almost $33 in April. Its shares had started to rise in recent
weeks as news leaked out that Alza might be in merger talks with
Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Monday, Abbott will exchange 1.2 of its
shares for each Alza share. Based on Monday's closing prices for
the two firms, Alza shareholders would get a 15 percent premium
over Alza's closing price of $46.25 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout was announced after the market closed, so the actual
value of the deal could rise or fall depending on what happens to
the companies' shares as investors digest the news.
</P>
<P>
   June has been an extraordinary month for local biotech deals.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, South San Francisco-based Sugen was purchased by
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn for $650 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, Roche Holdings of Switzerland said it would buy the
third of Genentech stock that it did not already own and resell
some stock in a public offering. That deal was worth more than $3.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, said the Alza acquisition illustrates a recent trend in
which drug companies have been acquiring mid-size biotech firms to
get access to their research into new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech firms need to sell out, he said, to get access to
the global sales forces of the large drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Alza acquisition, which is subject to approval by Alza
shareholders and regulators, is expected to close by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott sells a variety of antibiotics and other drugs, including
an anti-HIV drug called Norvir. It developed the world's first AIDS
test in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
