<SLUG> BC-LOVESTORY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AN AMERICAN LOVE STORY': A SUCCESSFUL BUT UNORTHODOX MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio)   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is the secret of a happy marriage, especially one that
flies in the face of social convention and is fraught with personal
turmoil? The mysterious emotional chemistry that unites spouses
from disparate backgrounds is a major subject of Jennifer Fox's
absorbing 10-hour documentary, ``An American Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The courageous partners who opened their personal lives to Ms.
Fox's camera crew are Bill Sims and Karen Wilson, an interracial
couple who met in 1967 in Ohio, married in 1979, and have two
daughters. Because Sims is black and Ms. Wilson white, ``An
American Love Story'' is much more than an exploration of ties that
bind. It is a sustained meditation on race relations and
opportunity in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary opens Wednesday in New York at the Film Forum
with showings of blocks of three hourlong episodes, three times a
day over the next two weeks. The 10th hour, Episode 6, will be
added when the film is shown on PBS later this year.
</P>
<P>
   While portraying the union as fortified by a
you-and-me-against-the-world attitude, it reveals the price paid by
the children of an interracial marriage. As wonderful as it may be
to grow up in a color-blind household, an idyllic home life can
make encountering racism outside all the more distressing.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the documentary was filmed at the couple's apartment in
Flushing, Queens, where a crew moved in during the mid-'90s
(exactly when isn't clear) and chronicled a year and a half. Sims,
a blues musician, was then 43, Ms. Wilson, a corporate
businesswoman, 42, and their daughters, Cicily and Chaney, 20 and
12 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The completed documentary was whittled down from more than 1,000
hours of film. The daily rhythms of domestic life are much the same
as those of the Loud family, examined in the groundbreaking 1970s
PBS documentary ``An American Family,'' which ``An American Love
Story'' emulates without apology.
</P>
<P>
   A lot happens during that year and a half. Sims, a talented
singer and guitarist, experiences the jagged ups and downs of a
career that takes him on the road, where he admits he becomes a
different person from the family man we see throughout much of the
film. Near the end he admits he's an alcoholic and seeks treatment.
He also makes a trip to his hometown, Marion, Ohio, to visit his
parents and see his son and daughter from a previous marriage to a
black woman (shown only in a snapshot).
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, Ms. Wilson becomes seriously ill with
fibroid tumors that drain much of the blood from her body, and she
ends up having a hysterectomy. The camera goes to the hospital to
show her in an alarmingly weakened, almost catatonic post-operative
state. It's not until the final episode that the series returns to
Ohio with Ms. Wilson for her 25th high school reunion. Only then,
in the reminiscences of her friends, do we learn the vicious extent
of the community's disapproval of her relationship with Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Cicily, a junior at Colgate University, travels to Nigeria with
a group of fellow students to study for several months. While
there, she meets her first serious boyfriend. Upon returning, she
graduates from Colgate and begins looking for a job. Chaney, who
remains largely in the background of the series, is the center of
only one rather dull episode in which she has her first, carefully
monitored date with a boy her own age.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that ``An American Love Story'' shows of the lives
of the Wilson-Sims family, certain crucial elements are missing.
The film seems deliberately to avoid looking at Ms. Wilson's
professional life. Since she is the family's chief breadwinner, its
refusal to visit her workplace and explore what she does eight
hours a day is a significant gap. And in a documentary that relies
heavily on interviews dubbed over scenes of the family's domestic
life, Ms. Wilson is so guarded and clipped in her remarks that we
never get a complete picture of her.
</P>
<P>
   By far the richest characters are Sims and Cicily. Sims, with
minimal education, is certain that he would have ended up, like
other men in his family, in a life of petty crime, were it not for
his music. The scenes of him performing in clubs around the country
suggest that the series might not have been made if it hadn't
offered Sims, who still dreams of a major musical career, a potent
national showcase.
</P>
<P>
   He not only bares his soul in his music but in numerous
monologues that lend the series much of its emotional depth. Again
and again he reiterates what becomes the series' mantra: Family is
the only thing in life that really matters, and family members are
the only people in the world you can really trust. By the end he
has emerged as a noble but flawed individual whose thoughts and
feelings about family, music and black history cohere into a
compelling portrait of a man who has chosen values based on his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary's saddest moments belong to Cicily, who because
of her racially mixed background finds herself in a kind of social
limbo. She is rejected by the black students at Colgate, and while
accepted into a mostly white sorority, still feels alienated among
the polite middle-class students she calls ``Stepfords.'' Even in
Nigeria, she experiences a similar alienation. What holds her
together is the same thing that keeps her father from falling
apart: the unconditional love of her parents and shared family
values.
</P>
<P>
   That's finally what makes ``An American Love Story'' quite
moving in spite of its sometimes sluggish pace, occasional
vagueness and overall demureness in asking tough questions. In
every scene in which the family members are together, you can feel
the love bursting out of them. Their vibrant, nurturing home is a
refuge from an outside world that still tends to see things (and
people) in terms of black and white.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AN AMERICAN LOVE STORY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jennifer Fox; director of photography, Ms. Fox;
edited by Jay Freund; music by Marcus Miller; produced by Ms. Fox,
Jennifer Fleming and Vickie Kenny; released by American
Playhouse/ITS/Zohe Film Productions. At the Film Forum, 209 Houston
Street, New York. Total running time: nine hours, shown in three
three-hour programs. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Karen Wilson, Bill Sims, Cicily Wilson and Chaney Sims. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
