<HEADLINE>
HOT STUFF  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Editors note: Psst! Read the latest? If not, you haven't read
Hot  Stuff, the San Francisco Chronicle's weekly roundup of great
new 
 home-and-garden items and places to visit.   c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SHOPPING EXPERIENCE: Discover More Than a Store in Sony Center  
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ The new Discovery Channel Store in San Francisco
isn't really a store _ it's an experience.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you walk into the enormous space on the ground floor of the
Sony Metreon Entertainment Center, your senses are bombarded by
lights, colors and action.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended from the ceiling is a sporty Pitts S-1S biplane and a
400 million-year-old, 20-foot-long whale skeleton. A telescopic
ceiling gives you views of the night sky at the stargazing
pavilion, while images of cheetahs sprint across a 110-foot-long
video screen.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive stations invite you to see underwater through the
eyes of a fish, take a visit to outer space and create a souvenir
photo cube, and test your airplane-identification skills.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of home accessories for sale. The store
``has a host of one-of-a kind objects for the home that were
selected from around the globe,'' says publicist Kim Airhart. These
include Russian spirit carvings, meditation fountains and frames
inspired by Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the merchandise: assorted masks from West Africa used
during tribal ceremonies, from $130 to $345; children's furniture
and accessories, including a height-measuring giraffe, at $20 to
$345; and even a Wurlitzer jukebox for $7,995.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company, Discovery Communications Inc., plans to have
200 stores by the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Discovery Channel Store is open from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. &LR; 
 &LR; daily in the Sony Metreon Entertainment Center, 101 Fourth St. &LR; 
 &LR; (at Mission Street), San Francisco; (415) 442-0706. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Terry Nagel, San Francisco Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MULTIPLE PURPOSES: Designing Furniture to Fit Right In &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ The design world is always aiming to merge fun and
functionality, and a new furniture line from a San Francisco
company actually does it.
</P>
<P>
   Blank and Cables, which designs and fabricates furnishings for
other companies, including the Gap, now has its own collection, and
it's a winner. The pieces are both practical and whimsical: Tables
transform into chairs; boxes climb up ladders; leather pouches
serve as drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Usability was a big factor in designing the collection. ``It
solves a lot of problems that San Franciscans have with smaller
living spaces,'' says owner/designer Walter Craven. ``We're trying
to redefine our relationship to furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites the company's Hingetable as a space-saving example: It
serves as your desk if you work at home, and when guests come, you
lift up a leaf and have a full, beautiful dining table.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes the Box Chair (around $800), a simple
wooden box with stainless steel legs and an aluminum top. You lift
the lid up to form a chair back, and you get an upholstered seat
into the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Want a stylish filing or storage system? A series of wood veneer
and aluminum boxes slip into place in a steel ladder that can move
around the house (around $1,300). If you need a side table with
pizzazz, Blank &AMP; Cables makes a handsome piece (pictured, $1,700)
with a polished glass top, steel base, wood box, and fun sloping
leather pouch in place of a drawer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For more information, or to make an appointment to view the &LR; 
 &LR; collection, call Blank and Cables at (415) 648-3842. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A FIND: Wide Array of Gifts Makes This Store Tick &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LAFAYETTE, Calif. _ A wonderful sound fills your ears when you walk
into &UR; Clocks Etc. &LR;  in Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Every kind of instrument to measure time is here, from
wristwatches to alarm clocks to grandfather clocks. There are
clocks for kids, clocks that tell you it's time to go fishing,
clocks that tell you to wake up and clocks that chime, ring,
whistle, cuckoo and cluck.
</P>
<P>
   The store also features barometers, thermometers, fountains,
hourglasses, small pieces of furniture and home and garden
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hampton founded Clocks Etc. more than 22 years ago in
another Lafayette location. He and his wife, co-owner Wendy Tamis,
recently moved to the new Lafayette Square shopping center in a
custom-designed, 2,600-square-foot space complete with a huge clock
face suspended from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Top-quality manufacturers are represented, from Seth Thomas to
Howard Miler to Sligh to Linden, and grandfather clocks are a store
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from less than $10 to $8,800 for a ``Legend''
grandfather clock _ only 1,000 of these clocks were made.
</P>
<P>
   This is the perfect place to shop for the person who has
everything. As Tamis likes to point out, ``Nobody ever has enough
clocks.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Clocks Etc. is open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through &LR; 
 &LR; Saturday, and Sunday and evenings by appointment at 971 Moraga &LR; 
 &LR; Road (near Mount Diablo Boulevard), Lafayette; (925) 284-4720. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Karyn Houston, San Francisco Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
