<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERGOLAS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 2086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERGOLAS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Garden Hideaway: A pergola offers a room for dining and relaxing   By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO  &LR; _ Call it a pergola, call it an arbor, call it _ if
you must _ a shade structure. By any name, a vine-covered outdoor
dining area is an appealing feature of many gardens. With filtered
sunlight dappling the table and the scent of jasmine wafting down,
a summer lunch under a pergola can be a sensual feast.
<P>
   Especially in warmer areas, homeowners consider these shady
outdoor rooms an extension of their home: a place to have weekend
brunch, an aperitif before dinner or a summer dinner alfresco. From
rustic do-it-yourself designs to engineered creations with
cast-stone pillars, pergolas support the California habit of living
much of life outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use one per garden probably,'' says Jack Chandler, a Napa
Valley landscape architect. ``If you're going to use the garden,
you want an outside room _ a place to sit and entertain friends and
hang your hammock.''
</P>
<P>
   You can plant a lot of trees and wait for them to grow, Chandler
says, or you can build a pergola.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a structure that's an intermediary between
the natural world and the totally enclosed world of the house,''
says Jennifer Chandler, Jack's daughter and a landscape architect
with her own Napa Valley practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Chandler says she installs pergolas on about 70 percent
of her jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another way to extend the house into the landscape, to
make another room,'' she says. ``And that sense of enclosure makes
people feel comfortable in their garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Pergolas also provide height and the chance to plant in layers,
with plant material at the base, up the posts and on top, Oakland
landscape designer Bob Clark says. With or without plants, a
pergola can provide architectural interest in a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Because a pergola can be costly _ figure $12 to $25 a square
foot _ designers recommend careful consideration of all aspects of
its design, from site selection to the choice of vines.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; View From the House
</P>
<P>
   For a freestanding pergola, choose a site where you like to sit
and spend time, advises Martina Ladova, a garden designer for Magic
Gardens in Berkeley. The view from the house should be part of the
planning, she says. How will the pergola look from the kitchen
window or a second-story window? From the house, a pergola should
serve as an alluring focal point.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider access. The path to the pergola will need to be
integrated with the rest of your garden and should be part of the
overall design.
</P>
<P>
   A pergola attached to the house raises structural issues that
may require professional engineering. An engineer will make sure
your design is stable and doesn't create places where water can
enter the house walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's freestanding and you don't have tons of weight on top,
it's probably not that big of a deal to build your own,'' Jennifer
Chandler says. ``But if it will be attached to the house or has
heavy beams on top, or if you have expansive soil, you definitely
should get it engineered.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you design, have your soil tested to learn its potential
for expansion, Chandler recommends. Clay soil, for example, expands
and contracts a lot. In yards with heavy clay, pergola posts should
be set in large concrete footings to keep the structure from
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Less-expansive rocky soil requires smaller footings. After soil
analysis, a structural engineer can tell you how large your
footings should be.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing materials for your pergola, designers recommend
taking cues from the house or garden. For pergolas attached to the
house, Ladova says, ``it's definitely best if some of the materials
and structural themes found on the house are repeated.'' To match
the home exterior, a pergola's columns might be stuccoed, shingled
or made of painted wood.
</P>
<P>
   A freestanding pergola removed from the house is better treated
as part of the garden, Ladova says. If you have lots of large
redwood or oak trees, consider a rustic design, perhaps with
branches as cross beams. In an English garden, a more romantic
approach would work, such as painting the structure white and
adding lattice detail. If you have stone walls or wrought iron in
your garden, consider incorporating those materials into your
pergola.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Chandler's stunning pergola for Long Meadow Ranch in St.
Helena includes cast-stone columns that mimic the columns on the
house, and a roof of recycled railroad timber.
</P>
<P>
   For a contemporary look and unmatched durability, consider steel
for posts and beams. Jennifer Chandler created a simple arbor on
one house by attaching sturdy brackets to the wall and stringing
heavy wire between the brackets' five-foot arms.
</P>
<P>
   Wood for pergolas can be painted or stained, pressure-treated or
untreated. Never put untreated wood posts directly in the ground,
designers say; the wood will rot without a concrete footing. For
the budget-minded, wood that has been pressure-treated with
chemicals can go straight into the ground, but Danville designer
Jill Appenzeller has safety concerns. Who wants chemical-laced
splinters?
</P>
<P>
   Redwood is a popular choice for unpainted posts and beams. Fir
and pine are better choices if you intend to paint or stain.
Appenzeller prefers stain to paint because paint needs occasional
retouching. For a painted structure, it's easier to paint first,
then build, says Jennifer Chandler, although you may want to do one
final coat in place.
</P>
<P>
   Good designers also select a pergola's floor material carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``One rule we try to stick to is not to use too many different
materials,'' Ladova says. ``If there already is brick or flagstone
around the house, we try to repeat that wherever pavement is
needed.'' When a pergola is attached to the house, it's even more
important to aesthetically link the flooring to the main structure.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever material you choose, make the pergola tall enough and
large enough to be comfortable. Jack Chandler suggests making the
posts at least eight to nine feet high, so vines don't dangle in
your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to feel good in this space,'' he says. ``You don't
want the room falling on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Pergolas should be a minimum of eight feet square to accommodate
a table and chairs, Appenzeller says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything gets smaller outdoors,'' she says. That's because
outdoor furniture needs to be substantial, with at least three feet
behind each chair (and four feet is better). Decide how much
seating you want and how you'll arrange it before you decide on
pergola size.
</P>
<P>
   To create mass and architectural interest, Jack Chandler likes a
multilayer roof. One new Chandler-designed pergola in Yountville
has four tiers: two 8-by-12 cross beams topped with a layer of
6-by-8 beams, then 3-by-3 beams, then 2-by-2 beams. The layering
creates shade and a handsome appearance even without a vine cover.
</P>
<P>
   During the design phase, consider whether you want illumination.
Chandler hides electrical conduit in fascia boards that cover the
posts; these molding-like boards also give the posts more mass and
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to leave room for planting vines to climb the
pergola posts. If you intend to have container plants under your
pergola, determine your irrigation needs before you build. Ladova
recommends installing PVC pipe under the pergola floor if you
intend to drip-irrigate your pots.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, before you start any pergola project, check with your
local building department. Many may require a permit; others may
insist that your pergola be a minimum distance from the property
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just, on a whim, get a pile of wood and put some
vines on it and live happily ever after,'' says Jack Chandler. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIDEBAR: Plants Make It Perfect &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
When deciding what to plant on a pergola, consider exposure first.
Is the roof in sun or shade? Even on a pergola shaded by trees or a
house, you may want to plant a vine to soften the look. Choose a
shade-tolerant vine such as climbing hydrangea.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want an evergreen vine for year-round shade or a
deciduous vine that lets winter light through? To provide interest
all year, designer Jill Appenzeller recommends mixing vines _
evergreen star jasmine with deciduous wisteria or clematis, or the
evergreen  &LR; Clematis Armandii cq  &LR; with a climbing rose.
</P>
<P>
   How dense a vine cover do you want? In hot areas, you might
welcome an aggressive grower like  &LR; Jasminum polyanthum, &LR;  which can
form a thick mat on the pergola roof. In cooler areas, you might
want to let more sun through.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Several designers say they avoid ``thugs'' such as potato vine,
a vigorous plant that needs constant pruning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want tracery and some shade, but I don't want it like
night in there,'' says Oakland landscape designer Bob Clark.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  However, be sure to plant a vine vigorous enough to cover
the top eventually, if you want it to. Some clematis and climbing
roses may not make it across the roof of an eight-foot pergola,
says Napa Valley landscape architect Jennifer Chandler, but their
shorter size can be used to advantage: She uses them to make the
planting beautiful from the inside. ``What happens with many
pergolas is that it's pretty above but you have an unsightly tangle
underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Vines with hanging flower or fruit clusters &LR; , such as
wisteria, kiwi or grapes, &LR;  can make the pergola as attractive to
those people under it as it is to those outside.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; With plants such as climbing roses that want to go straight to
the top to perform, Clark covers their ``bare legs'' on the pergola
posts with clematis or pots of abutilon. Wisteria also has bare
legs, but its thick, twisting trunk is part of its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Choose vining plants suited to your climate. Some vines are
frost-sensitive and won't make it through a difficult winter.
Landscape architect Jack Chandler says he regularly battles Napa
Valley clients who want to plant bougainvillea, usually after a
visit to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they plant one,'' says Jack Chandler, ``and two years
later, they say, `Chandler's wrong. It's grown like a champ.' Then
God comes along and, poof, it's gone.'' &LR;  Be aware that  &LR; heavy
vines &LR; , &LR;  such as &LR;  wisteria, need considerable support. Also ask
yourself whether you mind sharing your pergola; wisteria and
honeysuckle are bee favorites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Janet Fletcher, San Francisco Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VINES FOR PERGOLAS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Landscape architect Jennifer Chandler assembled this list, which
has been supplemented slightly by others interviewed for this
story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Actinidia chinensis  &LR; (kiwi): deciduous; attractive foliage
and edible fruit; need both male and female plants to produce
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Bougainvillea &LR; :evergreen; long-blooming; protect from frost;
will succumb to heavy frost.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Campsis radicans  &LR; (trumpet vine): fast-growing; can damage
buildings and be invasive; yellow, orange and red varieties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Clematis armandii  &LR; (evergreen clematis): fast growing; prune
often to control growth and prevent woodiness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Clematis montana  &LR; `Rubens' (Jackman clematis): showy flowers
briefly in spring.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Clytostoma callistigoides  &LR; (purple trumpet vine): evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Hardenbergia violaceaa &LR; : evergreen; may not grow tall enough
to cover; purple flowers in winter; frost-sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Humulus lupulus  &LR; (common hop): fast growing and long lived;
chartreuse flower; cut back to the ground in winter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Ipomoea  &LR; `Heavenly Blue' (blue morning glory): fast growing;
flowers all summer but unattractive in winter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Jasminum polyanthum  &LR; (jasmine): evergreen; fragrant; long
flowering period; may not cover pergolas in cold-winter areas; gets
dense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rosa &LR; : Among the many climbing roses suitable for pergolas,
consider:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rosa banksiae  &LR; (Lady Banks rose): evergreen to deciduous;
flowers once; vigorous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rosa  &LR; `New Dawn': pale-pink climber; long flowering period;
nice with purple or blue clematis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rosa  &LR; `Dortmund': red; disease resistant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rosa  &LR; `Bloomfield Abundance': repeat-blooming variety of
`Cecile Brunner'.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Thunbergia alata  &LR; (black-eyed susan vine): fast-growing
perennial grown as annual; may survive mild winters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Vitis  &LR; var. (grape): edible; good fall color; choose variety
appropriate to area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Wisteria sinensis  &LR; (wisteria): purple or white; vigorous;
trainable; attract bees; heavy, twisting trunks enhance posts.
</P>
