<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Blair Answers His Critics
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair turned aside criticism that his
government had abandoned Labor's traditional left-wing
constituencies in its pursuit of support from the middle class.
Blair told an unemployment conference that he had abandoned forever
``a Labor Party that ignored the importance of business and
ambition.'' His speech was viewed as an effort to silence union
leaders who have been calling for a return to old Labor values.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Britain Sends in More Troops
</P>
<P>
   Britain announced it was sending 1,300 soldiers to the province
to help control any violence during the season of Protestant Orange
Order parades. They bring the number of troops in the province to
about 17,000. Security forces will deploy in the Drumcree area of
Portadown, west of Belfast, where Orange Order militants want to
march through a Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Fayed Challenge on Citizenship
</P>
<P>
   A High Court judge gave Mohamed Al-Fayed the go-ahead to
challenge the government's decision denying him British
citizenship. The Egyptian-born owner of Harrods has been seeking a
British passport since 1994, but the government has ruled twice
that he is not of the necessary ``good character'' because of what
it called questionable past business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Prosecutor Charges Reinstated
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court reversed a lower-court judge and reinstated
criminal corruption charges against Prosecutor-General Yuri
Skuratov, who has bedeviled the Kremlin with inquiries into
official corruption. Skuratov, who enjoys support from Communists
and other anti-Yeltsin forces, was ensnared in a sex-and-blackmail
scandal this spring, then charged with abuse of his office, when a
videotape surfaced showing a man resembling him in bed with two
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Rebels' Drive on Rightist Area
</P>
<P>
   In their second attempt in six months to eliminate the leader of
the main paramilitary group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia have attacked four villages in the northern province of
Cordoba and killed at least eight peasants, according to civilian
and military officials. The left-wing guerrillas are said to have
committed 500 of their best fighters to the drive to seize the
headquarters of Carlos Castano, leader of the outlawed United
Self-Defense Forces of Colombia, an alliance of right-wing death
squads.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Torture Still in Use
</P>
<P>
   Federal and military policemen continue to use torture in
prisoner interrogations despite a ``frontal'' government campaign
to stop it, the National Human Rights Commission, a government
agency, reported. In 1998, the commission examined 21 complaints of
``this barbarous practice,'' its president, Mireille Roccatti, said
in her annual report.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   East Timor: U.N. Delays Key Vote
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to growing concerns about security and logistics,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced he would postpone the vote
on the future of East Timor set for Aug. 8 until later in the
month, although a new date was not announced. Annan said the
900-member U.N. mission would enable the 400,000 East Timorese to
have a ``free choice.'' But a new Amnesty International report
accuses Indonesia of using militia groups in East Timor to
intimidate those favoring independence over autonomy under
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Ethiopian Jews Arrive
</P>
<P>
   The first of 40 flights of Ethiopian Jews from the remote
province of Quara arrived in Israel. The Quara Jews were not
included in the airlifts from Addis Ababa in 1984-85 and 1991 that
brought in tens of thousands of Ethiopian Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Likud rejoins talks
</P>
<P>
   The Likud Party re-entered negotiations to join the coalition
government of Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak. Barak has until July
9 to form a government, and he wants it to be a broad-based one to
back his peace and domestic initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
