<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-STADIUMS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-STADIUMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR WANTS PROFESSIONAL SPORTS TEAMS TO PAY FOR STADIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Also filed in the Washington, ``w,'' category.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Professional football and baseball teams would be
required to pay for at least 50 percent of the costs of
constructing and renovating stadiums as part of legislation pushed
Tuesday by Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the measure is aimed at stopping teams from using
the threat of relocating to prod cities to build new stadiums at
public expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legalized exhortation,'' Specter said during a Senate
Judiciary Committee hearing on the issue, citing the Cleveland
Browns football team's 1996 move to Baltimore, lured by the promise
of a $200 million stadium financed by the state of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Specter also cited his own state's decision to contribute $320
million toward four new stadiums in Philadelphia and Pittsburgh as
an example of ``legalized exhortation.'' And he referred to the
recent bidding war between Massachusetts and Connecticut over the
New England Patriots football team.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, state and local governments have spent
about $7 billion to pay for new arenas for 41 professional
football, hockey, basketball and baseball teams, according to Mark
S. Rosentraub, a professor at Indiana University who studies
stadium financing. In many of those cases, the stadiums were built
to keep teams from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's legislation _ which is unlikely to be enacted, at
least in its current form _ would compel professional football and
baseball teams to place 10 percent of their television revenues
into a construction trust fund in order to maintain their federal
antitrust status.
</P>
<P>
   The fund would be used to pay for half the costs of building and
renovating stadiums. The antitrust provisions allow the teams to
equally share television revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining half of stadium costs would be picked up by
private sources _ which could include a team owner _ and states and
cities. State and city financing would be capped at 25 percent of
the total stadium price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the National Football League, who testified
at Tuesday's hearing, opposed Specter's plan.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said the plan would ``establish
a rigid and misguided federal approach to a particularly local
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Richardson, owner and founder of the Carolina Panthers,
noted that last month voters in Arizona rejected a new football
stadium for the Cardinals and voters in Minnesota recently rejected
a new ballpark for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stadium proposals face a great deal of publicity and spirited
debate,'' Richardson said. ``I do not understand what national
problem requires a congressional act to override the carefully
considered judgments of state and local governments, many of which
have been the subject of direct action by the voters themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said state and local officials have no choice but to
kick in public money to build or renovate a new stadium when a team
threatens to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hold a gun to somebody's head it's not a voluntary
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers, including Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
sided with the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think each community has to settle for itself the degree to
which it wants to become a part of stadium funding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., said he favored the bill's
premise but is opposed to using football television revenue _ which
runs about $2 billion a year _ to pay for stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   He said such a mechanism hurts small-market teams, like the
Green Bay Packers, whose budgets rely on a greater portion of
television revenues than teams in cities like New York or Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If Specter's bill were to become law, it would require teams or
the leagues to pay significantly more for stadium costs then they
do now. The Pittsburgh Pirates are to pay $40 million toward a $211
baseball park, while the Pittsburgh Steelers are to pay $76.5
million of the $233 million for theirs. Under Specter's bill, the
baseball and football leagues would have to pick up more than $100
million for each Pittsburgh stadium.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and byt
e-mail at jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
