 For Release WEDNESDAY AMs, June 23, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Stenkovec Camp, Macedonia) _ Refugees in a tent
city embrace President Clinton as a beloved conquering hero.
Speaking within sight of Kosovo, Clinton urges ethnic Albanians not
to rush home to the bomb-ravaged province before land mines were
cleared. By Ann Scales. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COURT-DISABLED (Washington) _ In a rush of important rulings on
the Americans with Disabilities Act, the Supreme Court restricts
who can sue for employment discrimination under the 1990 law and
also tells states to expand housing and treatment options for the
mentally ill. By Mary Leonard. 1300 words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-MEN (Attleboro, Mass.) _ They were three buddies on
vacation in the sun, blue-collar bachelors who jumped into a shiny
truck near Disney World last fall and never came back. Until now.
Scott Renquin, Dan Nelson, and Roger DesVergnes died in 16 feet of
water, their 1999 GMC Jimmy lying upside down in a retention pond
near a bend in the road in an upscale Florida community called
Celebration. By Thomas Farragher. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST-DROUGHT (Boston) _ No rain for a month means brown
lawns, worried farmers and limits on outdoor water use, part of a
quiet drought that is afflicting the Northeast from Maine to
Virginia. By Scott Allen. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLKLIFE-FESTIVAL (Washington) _ New Hampshire, South Africa and
Romania _ strange combo as it seems _ will be featured in this
year's Folklife Festival put on by the Smithsonian on the Mall. By
Eun Lee Koh. 750 words
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COURT-BURMA (Boston) _ US appeals court unanimously upholds a
lower court decision that struck down as unconstitutional the
``Burma Law.'' The law penalizes Massachusetts companies doing
business with Burma. By Heather Kamins. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-MERGER (Boston) _ New England is the nation's most
``overbanked`` region, with scores of little community
institutions. What happens to these banks in a consolidating
industry? By Lynnley Browning. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   TIAC-PSINET (Undated) _ The Internet Access Company, one of the
largest independent Internet providers in New England, is snapped
up by giant PSINet. By Hiawatha Bray. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (London) _ A two-match losing streak
shouldn't be the end of the world _ unless your name is Martina
Hingis, the planetary No. 1. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES (Baltimore) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
