<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIRAMAX-WILDE-LADN     06-22 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRAMAX-WILDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIO GIVES `IDEAL HUSBAND' MAINSTREAM PUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First they gave us Shakespeare we loved. Now
Miramax _ the studio most associated with corsets, costumes and
cleverness _ wants to make us wild about Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like having a rocket behind you,'' says filmmaker
Oliver Parker, who wrote and directed an adaptation of Wilde's
play, ``An Ideal Husband,'' which began a limited engagement in New
York City and Los Angeles last Friday. The film will then expand to
the top 20 markets this Friday and to the top 60 markets July 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're able to take what some might perceive as an art-house
movie and take it into the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what Parker was after with ``An Ideal
Husband.'' Although the play ranks as one of Wilde's lesser-known
stage comedies, Parker thought it might be the most relevant to
modern audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels are certainly obvious enough. ``An Ideal Husband''
is set at the end of a century (in this case, the 19th) and
features a popular but flawed politician who harbors a dirty secret
that threatens to ruin his career. The politician's principled wife
is kept in the dark, mostly from fear of an ethical scolding.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``Primary Colors,'' the prequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we had to get this movie out this year,'' Parker
says. ``It's just so pertinent. And the wonderful thing about a
period piece is you can have a bit of a comment on these
contemporary events without it becoming tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Rupert Everett, who stars in the film with Cate Blanchett,
Julianne Moore, Minnie Driver and Jeremy Northam: ``Moral
repression ... political scandal. The play is like a mirror of
what's been happening the past two years in America. It's
fascinating _ people haven't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde wrote ``An Ideal Husband'' in 1893, when he was at the
height of his powers but also inching near the social precipice
from which he was soon to fall. The play premiered in 1895, the
same year Wilde brought a slander suit against the Marquess of
Queensberry, who had left a note at Wilde's club accusing him of
``posing as a sodomite.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde lost the case and was then tried and convicted of ``gross
indecency.'' The subsequent two-year prison term destroyed him both
mentally and physically. He died in 1900 while living in exile in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The plea for tolerance, which is at the heart of ``An Ideal
Husband,'' undoubtedly resonated with Wilde, who was living a
double life as a homosexual in late-Victorian England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was asking for fairness for himself, but not
exclusively for himself,'' Parker says. ``Tolerance was a quality
he demanded for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wilde's background and the present-day parallels in mind,
Parker began to fashion an adaptation of ``An Ideal Husband'' that
would break what he calls the ``British stranglehold'' on the
piece. It's the same approach he used four years ago when he
brought Shakespeare's ``Othello'' to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit fed up with how I've seen Oscar Wilde's work done,''
Parker says. ``In his time, his plays were very subversive and
unusual, and now people play the words for the effect and not
what's behind them. What happens is every character ends up
sounding like Oscar Wilde. It's all very witty, but, ultimately,
rather pointless.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't get any argument on that point from the film's stellar
cast, which Parker rounded up quickly once he completed the
screenplay. Producers Barnaby Thompson of Fragile Films (they gave
us ``Spice World,'' the movie) and Bruce Davey of Mel Gibson's Icon
Productions sold the distribution rights to Miramax within a couple
of days of announcing the ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I remember it, (Miramax co-chairman) Harvey (Weinstein) did
the deal in two hours,'' Davey says. ``I don't think he believed we
could get the five actors we ended up getting. When he heard we
did, he snapped it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is standard procedure, says former Miramax acquisitions
executive Treah Hoving, who brought ``An Ideal Husband'' to
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvey doesn't take much time to make up his mind,'' Hoving
says. ``And really, this film is such a natural for Miramax. It's
intelligent, witty and classy. It has a real elegance that they've
been able to sell successfully to audiences in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, coming as it does in a summer dominated by broadly
commercial heavyweights like ``The Phantom Menace,'' ``Austin
Powers'' and ``Tarzan,'' ``An Ideal Husband'' would seem to be a
case of right-movie, wrong-time scheduling _ were it not for
Miramax's genius at making audiences notice its films. Nobody
thought the literary sensibilities of ``The English Patient'' would
make for good box-office, nor did anyone see ``Shakespeare in
Love'' making $100 million and winning the best picture Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Miramax's marketers proved them wrong. And
unlike, say, Fox Searchlight, which was unable to take its recent
version of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' beyond the art house
ghetto, Miramax is determined to make ``An Ideal Husband'' into a
crossover hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hurdle is preconception, and Miramax seems brilliant at
getting audiences beyond that,'' Parker says. ``It would be easy to
look at `An Ideal Husband' and wonder, `Is it just a funny,
old-fashioned play about a bunch of fops where nothing much
happens?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have easily been,'' Parker continues. ``But that was
certainly the last thing I wanted to make. To me, what makes the
material so exciting is that it speaks to audiences today, people
of all ages and nationalities. And that's precisely how Miramax
wants to sell the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, however, wasn't the only one thinking about ``An Ideal
Husband.'' Two other film productions of the play were being
readied at the same time Parker was preparing his version; one, a
British movie that sets the work in modern times, made it and is
now awaiting a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me a little nervous, but at the same time I thought it
might help raise our profile a bit,'' Parker says. ``Now, I needn't
worry. Miramax is doing that just fine on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the experience _ writing, directing, post-production _
has been so pleasant that Parker is considering a return to Wildean
wit with a film version of the playwright's most famous work, ``The
Importance of Being Earnest.'' Parker has already begun to write
(or ``doodle'' as he puts it) and reveals that everyone in the
``Ideal Husband'' cast has expressed a desire to return for another
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he would have to do is ask,'' Everett says. ``I've done
Wilde on stage, but the cinema just lends itself to the material so
much better. In the theater, you have to project your performance
for up to 300 yards, so it automatically becomes more studied and
structured. With the cinema, you can say these wonderful barbs and
epigrams as they're meant to be said, as afterthoughts that are
thrown away and spoken naturally. So I would savor the opportunity
to do it all again.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Parker: ``You can't predict if you can do it or not. But
it's hard to resist. It's just so damn good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
