<HEADER>
A5550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-22 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGES UPSET BY A QUALIFIER AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Her face was as white as the chalk lines
traced into the grass court underfoot, drained of its normal color
by a combination of rage and disbelief and the premonition that she
had seen a ghost across the net on Court One. Jelena Dokic was the
ghost of the anxiety-free girl Martina Hingis used to be at 16.
</P>
<P>
   With a backhand return that popped out of bounds at match point
like a foul ball, Hingis, the world's No. 1 player, surrendered in
just 55 minutes, 6-2, 6-0, to Jelena Dokic, a 129th-ranked
Australian qualifier who pulled off the biggest slam upset of the
Open era. Hingis had counted herself a favorite to add this year's
Wimbledon title to her 1997 championship; instead she became just
the third top-seeded woman since 1968 to falter in the first round
of a Grand Slam tournament. And Dokic (pronounced DOE-chich) thus
joined Lori McNeil, who upset Steffi Graf at Wimbledon in 1994, and
Australia's Margaret Sawyer, who stunned Virginia Ruzici in the
1979 Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, the teen-age champion whose mask of invincibility
developed some unflattering cracks during her loss to Graf in the
French Open final three weeks ago, was almost unrecognizable as she
disintegrated against Dokic, the world's top junior last year. The
blonde and beaming Dokic, who arrived in Sydney seven years ago by
way of Serbia and Belgrade and is coached by her father, Damir, a
truck-driver turned tennis sage, totally dominated Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I still can't believe I've beaten her,'' said Dokic,
who earned her way into the main draw by winning three qualifying
matches. Dokic also managed to shake off the embarrassing publicity
her father engendered two weeks ago at Edgbaston, where he was
thrown off the tournament grounds for drunk and disorderly
behavior. After sobering up in the local jail, Damir Dokic was
released without being arrested, and the father and daughter came
through the Wimbledon qualifying event at Roehampton without
further incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe him a lot; he knows what I have to work on and what I
have to fix,'' said Dokic, who received no criticism from her
father Tuesday. ``He was out of words,'' said the player. ``But
just because I've beaten Martina doesn't mean I'll win the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's got a better chance of it than Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Hingis floundered like an amateur and let herself be
mowed down by a stream of piercing, well-placed groundstrokes from
her understudy. Hingis won only 44 percent of her first service
points, hit just one winning return, lost her serve five times and
failed to convert two break chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to everybody sometimes,'' said Hingis, who hadn't
had it happen to her at a slam tournament since she was 14. Hingis
attributed her loss to Dokic's ``great play.'' But she nearly burst
into tears when she disclosed that she suffered through it without
the helping hand of her mother-coach, Melanie Molitor. Hitherto
inseparable, Hingis said the mother-daughter duo came to a mutual
decision to ``distance'' themselves from each other as of this
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just decided to have a little bit of distance and probably
work a bit more on our private lives,'' said Hingis, adding that
she had no plans of finding another coach to replace her mother.
``I wanted to be more independent, not having somebody else telling
me what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis admitted that timing the split to coincide with the start
of Wimbledon was, in retrospect, too big a dose of cold turkey.
After all, it was just a few weeks ago that she cried in her
mother's arms after failing, once again, to win a French Open. It
was her mother who dragged her back onto the court for the trophy
ceremony in Paris after reminding her that ``great champions''
aren't supposed to be dwarfed by temporary disappointments. And it
was only a few months ago that, triumphant at the Australian Open
for the third straight year, she said she couldn't have captured
any of her slams, or risen to No.1 in the world, without her
mother's constant input.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt different walking on court by myself,'' Hingis said
Tuesday. And it felt much worse when she walked off it after
sharing a cursory handshake, and a sheepish smile, with Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis never found a comfort zone Tuesday. She seemed still
unsettled by the controversy provoked by her temper tantrum in the
French final, where she was booed from center court after crossing
the net to argue a line call and defiantly delivering underhand
serves on two of Graf's match points. In essence, she seemed more
concerned with putting on a non-confrontational front than putting
Dokic out of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably too nervous, not much believing what I can
do,'' said Hingis. Asked what went wrong with her game plan, the
formerly unflappable Hingis confessed that she wasn't sure what, if
anything, went right. Aside from winning 9 of her 10 treks to net,
she was passive as a punching bag, and Dokic betrayed no qualms
about pummeling her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She played a great match,'' said Hingis, who noticed the crowd
seemed partial to the underdog even after Dokic took control.
``They were clapping for her great shots, not against me. I just
didn't make many winners. They had nothing to clap about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had routed Dokic, 6-1, 6-2, en route to her 1999
Australian Open title, but Hingis was so impressed by the
newcomer's style, which unabashedly mirrors her own, that she
invited her to Trubbach, Switzerland this spring for some practice
sessions. Tuesday, Dokic, apparently as quick a study as her
hostess, showed Hingis what she'd learned there. Dokic did no less
than deal Hingis her rudest and earliest slam exit since Graf
drummed the Swiss out of Wimbledon's first round, 6-3, 6-1, in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got all the shots in the book,'' said Dokic, ``and she
can do anything. I mean, she's No.1 in the world, but once I got
going, I played very well. Everything worked today: I knew I had to
keep it deep, play to her forehand, hit winners. I don't think
there was any pressure at all, because she's the one who was
supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Hingis abruptly withdrew from the women's doubles
_ she and Anna Kournikova were seeded second _ citing ``a recurring
medical problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
