   SCOTUS-ADA (Washington) _ Isolating people with disabilities in
big state institutions when there is no medical reason for their
confinement is a form of discrimination that violates federal
disability law, the Supreme Court rules. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-Y2K (Moscow) _ Even as the government rachets up a
crusade to rid Russia's 7 million desktop computers, its software
and its microchips of the so-called Year 2000 Bug, many experts are
urging businesses and other organizations to gird for digital
breakdowns next January that could disrupt industries and services
like power, transportation and telecommunications. By Michael
Wines. 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-Y2K-NUKE.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GUILT (Obilic, Yugoslavia) _ Who is guilty or innocent in
Kosovo? While sorting out responsibility is difficult after any
conflict, the task is especially daunting in Kosovo because many
Serbian paramilitaries wore masks while they committed crimes,
according to refugees. By David Rohde. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-QUOTES (Washington) _ The Senate voted 57-42 against a
motion to restrict debate on the import quota bill _ 18 short of
the 60 votes needed. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SYMINGTON-APPEAL _ A federal appeals court overturns the bank
fraud convictions that drove Gov. Fife Symington from office in
1997. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON (Naval Weapons Base Concord, Calif.) _
During World War II, an explosion on a segregated naval base here
killed 320 men. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to
resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty of them refused, were
court-martialed by an all-white panel, found guilty of mutiny and
imprisoned. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for one
black veteran have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that the
black sailors failed to follow orders out of legitimate fear and
had no intent to mutiny. The petition pits the racial symbolism of
a celebrated case against the military's view that servicemen
cannot choose which orders to obey. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and a map.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-U.N.-DUES (Washington) _ The Senate overwhelmingly
approves a bill authorizing the payment of more than $800 million
in back dues to the United Nations but cutting future U.S.
contributions to the organization. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SALINGER-AUCTION (New York) _ J.D. Salinger's letters are
auctioned. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   HATCH-2000 (Washington) _ Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, the
conservative chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, says he
intends to make what he admits will be a long-shot bid for the 2000
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
