<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAM-COKE-0623-1STLD     06-22 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-COKE-0623-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: corrects second 'it's' in lede to read 'its'
 &HT;    FOR COKE, LATIN AMERICA PROVING A SAFE HARBOR IN A GLOBAL STORM
 &HT;    325&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With COKE-BOX-0622.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It's been a bumpy ride for Coca-Cola Co. in the global
markets the last two years. The Asian economic crisis. The collapse
of the Russian ruble. And now, a health scare crisis in Europe that
threatens Coke's most valuable asset: its image.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this turmoil, however, the primary foreign market
that remains a constant source stability for the Atlanta-based
company is Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, the fizzy drink's outlook south of the
border is anything but flat. Although the region has suffered
economic turmoil this year, it still accounts for a fourth of
Coke's global sales volume.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, known simply as ``Coca'' in many Latin cities,
analysts say Coke's image would be hard to tarnish in countries
such as Mexico, where -- in many households -- the ubiquitous soft
drink has become as much a staple as the tortilla.
</P>
<P>
   The company's unshakable grip is due to a variety of factors:
the region's hot climate, the product's popularity with a growing
middle class, and the company's vast, highly polished network of
bottlers and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is so entrenched in Latin America and the brand is so
well-known, it's hard to beat,'' said John Sicher, editor of
Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter based in New York. ``Latin
America is a terrific market for Coke, and should remain that way
for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the picture's been completely rosy for Coke in
Latin America, which has felt the ripple effect of the Asian
financial crisis on its own economies over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales in Latin America grew only 7 percent in 1998, after
shooting up 12 percent the year before. In the first quarter of
1999, sales actually fell 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coke has experienced big declines this year in Chile, Colombia,
and Venezuela -- all countries hard-hit by the global economic
crisis -- which have been offset somewhat by slight gains in
Argentina, the Caribbean, and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, where the soft-drink giant invested $1.4 billion
between 1995 and 1997, the recession has forced many thirsty people
to migrate to cheaper brands.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company has lost more than one-tenth of its
market share in recent months to low-cost local drinks produced by
family-owned bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the company's bottler in Brazil lowered prices on some
Coke products by as much as 20 percent in order to fight the
growing competition.
</P>
<P>
   But economists these days are almost buoyant when it comes to
Brazil, which bodes well for Coke.
</P>
<P>
   The country's stock market has bounced back, as has its
currency, after investors bailed out of emerging markets like
Brazil following the crisis that began in Southeast Asia in the
summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In general, Coke is a significant leader when it comes to market
share in most Latin American countries, and analysts say the
company has plenty of room to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Americans consume 890 servings carbonated
soft drinks per person a year, compared with only 259 servings in
Brazil and 332 in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Coke has had to contend with some
difficult economic troubles in certain Latin countries, but the
potential to build consumption in this region is high, despite
what's happening in Europe,'' said Marc Cohen, a beverage analyst
for Goldman Sachs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Coke's dominance south of the Rio Grande -- where it enjoys 60
percent of the carbonated soft drink business -- is
long-established.
</P>
<P>
   But Coke had an enormous jump on its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1886, Coca-Cola opened bottling operations in Cuba,
Panama and Puerto Rico just after the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, where Coke was introduced in 1926, Mexicans today
consume some 412 Coca-Cola products per person a year, outstripping
even U.S. per capita consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials point to Mexico as an example of the strength
and success of their long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   During that country's peso crisis in the early 1990s, Mexican
managers decided to invest in even more new production plants --
and it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Market share jumped from 53 percent to 68 percent. Even this
year, as sales have declined elsewhere in Latin America, they've
increased 6 percent in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is a symbol of purity in a lot of these places,''
Coca-Cola spokesman Bill Hensel said. ``Whenever you're in a
country and you can't safely drink the water, you drink
Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
