<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-OATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TO SWEAR IN HORMEL AS U.S. AMBASSADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is scheduled
to swear in gay rights advocate James C. Hormel next Tuesday as the
new U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   For Hormel, Albright's participation in the ceremony is a double
honor. Because of her busy schedule, she only occasionally presides
over such ceremonies. Also, she happens to be a former boss of
Hormel.
</P>
<P>
   When she was America's ambassador to the United Nations in 1997,
Hormel was the alternate U.S. representative and worked for her.
</P>
<P>
   Invitations to the ceremony are being sent to members of
Congress and the administration who supported Hormel's
long-embattled nomination as well as to Hormel's family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Last year four conservative senators put a so-called ``hold'' on
President Clinton's nomination of the San Francisco philanthropist
to take the Luxembourg post. They said they feared he would pursue
a gay-rights agenda there, but Hormel said he would not do so. The
hold blocked a vote on the nomination, which requires Senate
approval.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 4, while Congress was on a week-long break, Clinton
announced he was giving Hormel a recess appointment, which will
allow him to serve without Senate approval until the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony is set for 4 p.m. in the seventh floor Benjamin
Franklin room of the State Department, which is used for diplomatic
functions. It will last about an hour and include an oath of
office, remarks by Albright and Hormel and a reception.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel will leave for Luxembourg soon afterward to present his
credentials to his royal highness, Grand Duke Jean of Luxembourg,
according to a State Department official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
