<HEADLINE>
NEWSSTANDS BULK UP WITH MEN'S-HEALTH MAGAZINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You better hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The June edition of Men's Health magazine promises ``Max Muscle
by June 21.''
</P>
<P>
   It urges men to ``Get Naked, Save Your Life'' by letting her
play doctor; tells you how to ``Build Beach Arms''; tests baldness
cures, comparing Rogaine and Propecia with toupees; and offers 54
new ways to lose weight and get in shape in an article headlined
``Burn Fat Faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's health issues seem to be a subject whose time has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you're not the first to make an appointment with your
doctor when something hurts, the kind of guy who discusses the
intimate parts of your body or even the kind of guy ready to make
the drastic decision to lose a few pounds _ with us, you're at
home,'' editor Christian Maguerou promises in the first edition of
the new French version of ``Men's Health.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which was launched in the United States in spring
1988, has a circulation of 1,525,000 in this country, and is now
published in nine languages, in 12 editions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Men's Fitness, Muscle and Fitness and Men's Journal
were launched in recent years to focus on what men need to do to
stay healthy and take better care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty magazines like Skiing, Runner's World, Mountain Bike
and Fitness Swimmer also offer health and fitness advice.
</P>
<P>
   What could a man combing through his local newsstand learn about
his health this summer? Here's a sampling of what's out there:
</P>
<P>
   Men's Health, French edition: ``Have Sex Every Day Until You
Die,'' ``Beginner's Guide to Running,'' ``What to Eat When'' and
``The Ultimate Arm Workout'' _ with a free pullout poster.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise &AMP; Health: ``Fueling Your Physique,'' ``Growing
Younger,'' ``Feets Do Your Stuff: Building Up Ankles, Toes and
Calves,'' ``Bodysculpting Under the Sun,'' and ``Training Secrets
of Superstar Athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Health &AMP; Fitness: ``Young at Heart,'' ``Live Pain-Free,''
``The Ups and Downs of Viagra,'' ``Is Bald Better?'' and ``Your
Midlife Crisis is Real, Now Get Over It.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's Fitness: ``Brain Boosters: Viagra for Your Mind,'' ``Be a
Fit Vegetarian,'' ``Fight Heartburn,'' ``Be King of the Beach,''
``Build Bigger Shoulders'' and ``He's Gotta Have It: Can You Ever
Have Too Much Sex?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
