<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS CAUGHT IN A MOUSE TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A two-match losing streak shouldn't be the end of the
world _ unless your name is Martina Hingis, the planetary No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And unless the two matches are the French Open final and the
first round at Wimbledon, where a 16-year-old Serbian refugee
without credentials takes maiden steps onto the revered sod and
kicks you out of town.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, as it did stupefyingly Tuesday at the Big W,
you become the historic party of the worst part _ the 6-2, 6-0
victim of a girl so far below you that she might have come out of a
coal mine: Jelena Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic had the time of her life, a big-top baptism amounting to
54 minutes of an afternoon of sunshine and clouds. Hingis got the
clouds. They didn't drip, but Hingis's eyes did at the end, as they
had 16 days earlier in Paris when Steffi Graf jolted her.
</P>
<P>
   Then, her mother, Melanie Molitor, had come onto the court to
help an unraveled Martina pull herself together _ demanded it,
really. But Tuesday, when it was ``I want my mama!'' time, Molitor,
who had reared the child to be a champion (even presciently naming
her for a great one), was absent. Never had this mom/coach/closest
friend missed one of her offspring's jousts.
</P>
<P>
   So there was more to it than just tennis. The umbilical cord had
been severed at a late date, and a teenager decided she wanted
``more independence, some distance to make my own decisions, time
for our private lives. We, both of us, made the decision last week.
We would try it. I'm here alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis never looked more alone on a tennis court. ``I was
nervous, not believing,'' she said. ``It felt different without
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, what 19-year-old hasn't yearned to get out from under
mom's wing at one time or another, especially a world-traveling
self-assured professional? But was this the time for mom to go off
with her boyfriend? Was this a lesson in self-sufficiency from a
strong parent?
</P>
<P>
   In successive days on the job, Hingis had heard the crowds roar
lustily for her opponent, 16,000 in Paris, 11,000 here at Court 1.
It couldn't have felt very good for someone who'd been the youngest
Wimbledon champ of the century 24 months ago and had lost at the
start of a major only once before, here as a 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you lose unexpectedly to Graf, the aging lioness? Graf
has been around the jungle a few times. But Dokic, a qualifier with
an Australian passport ranked No. 129 with merely 13 mainstream
professional matches in her dossier and a 7-6 record? A juvenile in
her second major, whom Hingis had beaten, 6-1, 6-2, at her first,
the Australian Open five months ago? The very same Dokic who had
failed in the qualifiers of three minor tournaments earlier in the
year?
</P>
<P>
   This adds up to just about the most outrageous form-bending in
the annals of women's tennis. No. 1, owner of five major titles,
including the 1999 Australian Open, stoops to be conquered by No.
129, a Wimbledon stranger, and at the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   It stands with _ actually above _ two other prominent Wimbledon
first-round upsets of defending champs ranked No. 1: Graf losing to
No. 22 Lori McNeil in 1994 and Manolo Santana losing to Charlie
Pasarell in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   But as an open-and-shut, hello-goodbye case, Hingis must be
acclaimed the local queen. She took a 2-1 lead. No problem. Then
she was hit off the court through the next 11 games by her
opponent's more powerful drives. Dokic served sharply to the
corners as Hingis faded, entranced.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Hingis was in the clutches of post-Paris syndrome as
well as Dokic, a friend with whom she'd practiced at home in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure the people here cheered a lot for Jelena,'' Hingis said,
``but it wasn't like Paris where everybody was against me. I just
didn't give them much to cheer for today.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris was a firestorm of displeasure and abuse hurled at Hingis
in whistles and catcalls as she misbehaved during the battle with
Graf. It will take a while to exorcise that tumult and anger from
her head, time she intends to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a break to recover from everything,'' said Hingis.
``Five weeks until the hardcourts in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise move.
</P>
<P>
   So was the Dokic family move from Belgrade to Sydney in 1994,
beating NATO bombs by five years. And before that deserting Osijek,
Croatia, to elude the previous Balkan war. Sydney meant sunshine
and tennis, and a new language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous,'' Dokic said. ``I played quite well . . .
uh, all right, I played the best match of my life. It will take a
while to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether she does or not, Wimbledon has its all-time debutante.
The Dokics will be watched closely, particularly her father, Damir
Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no, not another member of the Bad Dads Club, letting the kid
support the family in the manner of Jim Pierce, Peter Graf, Stefano
Capriati, and too many others.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before Dokic's eviction of Hingis, her old man _
apparently overserved _ was bodily evicted from the Birmingham
(England) tournament for vocally disrupting her match and insulting
club members. Shortly thereafter he was arrested, but released, not
charged, for disturbing the peace: i.e. throwing himself in front
of autos as a self-styled protest against NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, though shaken, remained the consummate pro. She answered
all the questions and praised her adversary: ``Jelena was good,
don't forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   She wore her Cheshire cat grin. But Tuesday the longest shot,
the mouse, won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
