<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILEAN PRESIDENT ANNOUNCES ECONOMIC STIMULUS PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ President Eduardo Frei of Chile
overhauled his Cabinet and announced an economic stimulus package
Monday night in response to rising unemployment and increasingly
tense relations with the military.
</P>
<P>
   With less than nine months remaining in his term, Frei and his
center-left coalition government are facing a daunting mix of
economic problems stemming from a persistent drought and low
international copper prices. In the past year, the unemployment
rate rose from 5 percent to 8.2 percent as an estimated 140,000
workers lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, top military officers are growing restive over the
government's inability to bring home Chile's former dictator, Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, who has been under arrest in Britain for eight
months and faces possible extradition to Spain to stand trial for
human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the nation Monday, Frei announced new public
works projects, housing subsidies for the poor and loan programs
for farmers and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``How easy it would be for me to pass on our problems to a
future government, which will be elected in only six months time,''
Frei said. ``But that is not an option.'' While noting that the
Chilean economy slowed by 3.2 percent over the first four months of
the year, he predicted that it would grow by up to 5.5 percent in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new programs do not represent a fundamental shift in
economic policy, and Frei did not announce any changes among his
top economic advisers. But before his speech he overhauled his
political and national security team, most notably replacing his
chief of staff and returning to the post of defense minister an
official who has long had good relations with the military.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the sudden and unexpected economic and political moves
were designed to shore up the government's declining credibility
and to aid the presidential campaign of Ricardo Lagos, the
candidate of the governing Christian Democrat-Socialist coalition
to succeed Frei.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had not made the political changes, the economic changes
would have lacked credibility,'' said Ricardo Israel, a political
scientist at the University of Chile. ``People were beginning to
joke that Frei was no longer president.''
</P>
<P>
   Frei's credibility problems began to look serious in April when
Gen. Ricardo Izurieta, the Army commander-in-chief, traveled to
London to meet with Pinochet and with senior British military
officials and politicians without first consulting with the
president. Izurieta also publicly asserted that Pinochet is not
guilty of charges of torture and other crimes against humanity, a
position that did not coincide with the government's, that any
trial of the former dictator should take place in Chile, not Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders became increasingly restive earlier this
month when five retired senior army officers were indicted and
arrested for the executions of 72 leftists in northern Chile
following the American-backed military coup in 1973 against the
socialist president, Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments were issued by the same judge who is considering
18 lawsuits filed against Pinochet by relatives of dissidents who
disappeared. That added to the military's fears that the
83-year-old former commander will face legal troubles for the rest
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In a response to the judge's action, Adm. Jorge Arancibia, the
navy commander, proposed the formation of a commission to
investigate past human rights abuses ``on the basis of national
unity.'' Rights advocates expressed skepticism at the offer,
especially since it came without any consultation with Frei or
other civilian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The limits of democratic rule nine years after civilians
replaced Pinochet in the presidential palace were further
underscored last week when two executives of a Chilean publishing
house were arrested and indicted under Chile's State Security Law
for publishing a book examining abuses in the country's justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts and foreign diplomats generally agree that a
military coup is highly unlikely, even if Lagos, a member of the
same Socialist Party as Allende, is elected in December.
Nevertheless, Frei attempted to shore up his tattered relations
with the military by returning Edmundo Perez Yoma, currently
Ambassador to Argentina, to the defense minister post.
</P>
<P>
   Perez Yoma won friends in the military in 1998 when he called
for an increase in military salaries. But salaries and arms
spending were frozen when he was transferred to Buenos Aires, and
the economist who replaced him in the defense ministry never
developed a close rapport with the top brass.
</P>
</TEXT>
