<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-BIAS-HNS &LR;      06-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-BIAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT EASES REQUIREMENTS FOR JOB-BIAS VICTIMS TO WIN DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court made it easier Tuesday for
victims of job discrimination to win extra damages from their
employers, ruling that such workers do not need to show their
boss's conduct was ``egregious.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a woman denied a promotion because of her gender,
the court ruled 7-2 that job-bias victims need only prove that
their employer was ``recklessly indifferent'' to
anti-discrimination laws to receive punitive damages, which are
usually large amounts of money intended to punish or deter
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concluded that an employer's conduct need not be
independently `egregious' to satisfy requirements for a punitive
damages award, although evidence of egregious misconduct may be
used to meet the plaintiff's burden of proof,'' Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a separate 5-4 vote in the same case, the justices
said employers cannot be forced to pay the extra damages for
managers' discriminatory decisions when that conduct is contrary to
the employers' good-faith efforts to run a bias-free workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good decision for employers, in particular the part
... that says employers' anti-discrimination policies should be
taken into account,'' said Robert E. Williams of the Equal
Employment Advisory Council, an association of about 300 large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for
Women, said the ruling means that if employers ``know or should
know that they've violated the law in discriminating against you,
then they can be hit up for punitives.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Congress amended the Civil Rights Act of 1964 to allow
people who prove they were victims of job bias to collect punitive
damages if they can show their employer acted with ``malice or with
reckless indifference'' to their rights. The amended law also set
the limit for punitive damages at $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Rights Act bars job discrimination based on race,
gender, national origin and religion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Carole Kolstad was working as the American Dental
Association's director of federal agency relations in Washington
when the association's director of legislation announced his
retirement. Kolstad and another ADA Washington office employee, Tom
Spangler, expressed interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having a lower position and less experience, Spangler
eventually won the job, and Kolstad sued. She contended that the
ADA had chosen Spangler before a formal selection process began and
that the choice was motivated by sexual bias against her.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged that Leonard Wheat, who headed the
association's Washington office, told sexually offensive jokes at
staff meetings and sometimes used derogatory terms to refer to
professionally prominent women. Wheat strongly denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a federal jury found that the ADA had illegally
discriminated against Kolstad and awarded her $52,718 in back pay.
</P>
<P>
   However, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson disagreed with the
verdict but could not overrule it. However, he did not allow the
jury to award Kolstad punitive damages and held that she was not
entitled to be installed in the director's position.
</P>
<P>
   Kolstad appealed, and in March 1997 a three-judge panel for the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled in her
favor, writing that the jury should have been allowed to consider
punitive damages for her.
</P>
<P>
   But later that year, the entire D.C. Court of Appeals, in a 6-5
decision, sided with the ADA, ruling that Kolstad was not entitled
to punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   To recover such damages, the appeals court said, workers must do
more than show the employer intentionally discriminated against
them. They must also prove ``egregious conduct'' by their employer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court rejected that standard and sent
Kolstad's case back to the District Court for reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said the lower court must consider whether Kolstad can
show that Wheat discriminated against her knowing that he was
breaking federal law. In addition, for Kolstad to receive money
from the ADA, she must also prove that the organization did not try
hard enough to create a bias-free atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Clarence Thomas
dissented from the part of the court's ruling that said a showing
of egregious conduct was not required.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist and Thomas joined O'Connor and Justices Antonin Scalia
and Anthony M. Kennedy in ruling that employers do not always have
to pay for the discriminatory acts of their managers.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented from that part of the court's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
