<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLICE-SHOOTIN     06-22 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLICE-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SHOOT ISRAELI LAWMAKER, AN ARAB, DURING PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOD, Israel _ Azmi Bishara earned a dubious distinction when he
visited a slum neighborhood here to join a demonstration of its
Israeli Arab residents on Sunday night. He became the first member
of Parliament to be shot with a rubber-coated metal bullet by the
Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
   It resembled a scene from the West Bank, where Palestinian
youths routinely clash with Israeli troops, but the battle took
place between Israelis just miles from Ben-Gurion International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   And it took place against the backdrop of a festering social
problem here, which is the marginalization of Israeli Arabs who
live in slums in the mixed Arab-Jewish cities like Lod.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Arab population, which was courted by and voted for
Ehud Barak for prime minister last month, is certain to accelerate
its quest for civil rights during his administration. And this
incident, considered ugly by all, is a reminder at the outset that
the atmosphere is volatile.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was called to protest the city's demolition
early Sunday morning of an Arab family's home _ one illegal
structure in a neighborhood of illegal structures, a shantytown
that has existed for two decades in an area zoned for industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bishara, whose face is well known because he ran for prime
minister during the recent election, attended in a suit and tie. He
stood in a crowd of angry young men. The protest got out of hand;
the youths threw stones, injuring five officers, and the police
beat some with riot sticks, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Without warning, Bishara said, the police let loose a barrage of
rubber-coated bullets. He was struck in the shoulder, a light
wound. A physician friend, Dr. Ziad Muhareb, who arrived to help,
was wounded more seriously and bled profusely from the face. The
shooting did not let up, so the member of Parliament and the doctor
crawled behind a car.
</P>
<P>
   Bishara said he tried several times to call the police's
attention to the injury of Muhareb, while the youths yelled: ``He's
an MP! He's an MP!'' But the police continued to shoot in his
direction, Bishara and the other demonstrators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very depressing,'' Bishara said Tuesday. ``The police
used a disproportionately massive quantity of rubber bullets
against the demonstrators, including me. Certainly I was not
throwing stones. I don't like to believe that they shot at me
intentionally, although the fire did follow me even when I got
behind the car.''
</P>
<P>
   A justice ministry internal affairs department Tuesday opened an
investigation into the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The regional police chief, Zeev Even-Hen, defended the use of
force as commensurate with the violence of the demonstrators. He
said that five police officers were hurt in the rain of stones.
About 16 demonstrators were hurt, with 9 requiring hospital
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Even-Hen also said, ``A member of Parliament who participates in
a violent demonstration like the one in Lod cannot serve as a
shield for demonstrators who are rioting in such a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Shimon Peres, the acting speaker of Parliament, called ``any
such injury'' to a member of Parliament ``grave and irregular.'' He
also visited City Hall here Tuesday to negotiate a temporary freeze
in house demolitions and building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to denounce,'' he said at City Hall. ``I
came here to calm down these outbursts, which I'm sure neither side
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident was debated on Israel radio for much of the day.
One popular and influential radio personality, Sheli Yehimovich,
challenged Even-Hen on the air to defend what she said was a level
of force _ shooting rubber-coated bullets _ that is never used
against Jewish demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Jewish protesters violently attacked cars
driving on the Sabbath on a main street that transects a religious
neighborhood, the police, who were also attacked, responded by
shooting water at them.
</P>
<P>
   The police official repeated that the level of force used was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 10 Arab party members of the Parliament visited the
scene of the disturbance Tuesday, while several Jewish members of
Parliament _ including Yossi Sarid, the head of the leftist Meretz,
and Dalia Rabin-Pelossoff of the Center Party _ called Bishara to
express regrets.
</P>
<P>
   At the scene, protesters put up a makeshift tent beside a tangle
of concrete and wires, the remains of the demolished house. The
neighborhood is one of the worst in Israel, hard by a railroad,
laced with raw sewage and dangerously jerry-rigged connections
hooking up the illegal homes to electricity and water supplies.
Drug dealers have set up shop there amid the very poor residents
who have nowhere else to go.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Pinchas Idan, elected last November, plans to demolish
every makeshift house there, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions are thick in Lod, where the Arab community, about a
quarter of the population of 70,000, has watched with frustration
as new housing was built for thousands of new immigrants from the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Idan proposed last week that the city be severed from two of its
Arab neighborhoods. The residents do not want to cooperate with his
efforts to help them, he said, and the national government refuses
to help develop the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, the mayor wanted to come see us here,'' said
Mahmoud Muhareb, a political scientist and brother of the doctor
who was shot. ``He said he wanted a cease-fire. I said: `We are not
at war. We are your citizens.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
