<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0623-1     06-22 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0623-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 22nd graf, deletes clause, '. . . like the ones that
killed two British peacekeeping troops and two civilians outside of
Pristina on Monday . . .
 &HT;    CLINTON MEETS REFUGEES, ASKS FOR PATIENCE IN RETURNING TO KOSOVO
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVEC REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ Paying tribute to the
shattered lives and resilient dreams of the ethnic Albanians of
Kosovo, President Clinton told refugees here Tuesday that his
country took a stand for its bedrock principles in striking at the
repression that forced them to flee their native land.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, he thanked several hundred of the American pilots
and air crews who backed those ideals with might by carrying out
the 78-day NATO air war that broke the spine of the Yugoslav forces
in Kosovo and opened the door through which more than a million
refugees have begun to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of what we did, because we think it's what America
stands for,'' Clinton told several thousand ethnic Albanian
Kosovars here at the Stenkovec Refugee Camp on the outskirts of the
Macedonian capital of Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States never acts alone,'' Clinton
said, standing atop a small platform of olive green military supply
boxes and plywood. ``It is the American people who care about you,
who believe in you, who want you to be free, who want you to be
able to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message, pitched time and again since the start of the
NATO air strikes against Yugoslav forces and Serb police and
paramilitary gangs last March -- but never before to an audience
quite like this -- was that this was a conflict about a brutally
simple principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever, ever should be punished and discriminated
against, or killed or uprooted,'' he said, ``because of their
religion or their ethnic heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a hero's welcome at this sprawling camp of
white and khaki tents, the temporary home to the 10,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees still here anxiously awaiting the day they may
return in safety to their homes across the mountainous Kosovo
border less than 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and their
daughter, Chelsea, President Clinton visited with several small
groups of refugees in tents before addressing several thousand
others, many of whom chanted vigorously, ``USA! USA! USA!'' as
Clinton stood before them in light brown chinos and a green sports
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an angel for peace in Kosovo,'' said Astrit Ajvazi, 17,
``and it's real, I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Said a sturdy raven-haired woman named Vjolca, ``the president
saved us -- two million people.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kosovars like Astrit, a teen-aged boy from the town of
Kamenica and Vjolca, a young mother from Gjilan, were moved by
Clinton, so was the president taken in by what he saw and heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a beautiful boy,'' Clinton said to Nerimane
Macastena, nodding toward her blonde son, Besart, 4, as the family
gathered around the president in a billowing canvas tent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then listened as members of the family told of the day
in May when Serb army troops surrounded their house in Pristina,
collared young Besart and placed a knife at one side of his neck
and a lighted cigarette on the other and demanded all of the
family's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still very much afraid,'' his mother told Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure families get help for their children,''
Clinton responded. ``There are some things children should never
see. Some will need extra help.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, a triumphant but somber Clinton strode toward the
makeshift dais for his remarks, holding the hands of children who
gazed up at him and beamed, their youthful eyes and weathered faces
fixed on his every move.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on was Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger, who monitored every frightening twist and turn of
the Kosovo conflict, helped Clinton stay the course through the
darkest moments of the risky campaign and went on talk show after
talk show to defend the mission from its critics on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, though, Berger stood astride a small pile of
crushed rock and gazed out at the throngs of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the human face of what we've been fighting for for the
last three months,'' he told a reporter. ``And to see these people,
with all they've been through, and the fact that they are going to
be going home in just a few weeks, is a very moving experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Ajvazi, in fact, is already planning his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I go tomorrow,'' he said. ``Why not? Of course, with
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned the refugees, though, of the continuing dangers
of landmines and asked them to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appeal had a secondary goal of trying to keep clogged
roads into Kosovo clear of returning refugees to speed the
deployment of the 50,000-strong allied security force. Barely half
of the force of British, French, German, Italian and U.S. soldiers
had moved into Kosovo by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a couple more weeks,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any child hurt. I don't want anyone else to lose
a leg or an arm or a child because of a landmine,'' Clinton said.
``You have suffered enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's cautious tone came one day after two Nepalese
Gurkhas in the British Army and two civilians died as they prepared
to dispose of unexploded munitions found in a school in Negrovce,
20 miles from Kosovo's capital of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials estimate that Yugoslav forces sowed one million
mines across the largely agrarian province, an area the size of
greater Los Angeles. A United Nations' survey found mines, booby
traps and unexploded bombs lurking in almost 800 separate areas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left the camp to speak to about 300 members of the NATO
peacekeeping force for Kosovo, called KFOR. He challenged critics
of the mission to absorb the meaning behind the mounting evidence
of the Serb atrocities committed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the people of the world, when they see these horrible,
horrible stories coming out, the mass graves and all of that, just
imagine what it would have been like if we had stepped to the side
and not done what we did for the last three months,'' Clinton said,
speaking to troops from the United States and several other NATO
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton amplified on the theme hours later before pilots and air
crews at Aviano Air Base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for this noble endeavor,'' Clinton said, standing
before several hundred U.S. service personnel and their families
inside a large hangar at Aviano, the base for nearly 9,000 sorties
flown in Operation Allied Force -- more than one fourth of the
total.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did prove that a sustained air campaign, under the right
conditions, can stop an army on the ground, '' said Clinton, as
U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme NATO commander, looked on
in front of a huge American flag. ``You also stopped a vicious
campaign of ethnic cleansing and made it possible for us to reverse
it . . . the refugees are going back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks at Aviano wound up a week-long tour of Europe
focused on the aftermath of the allied air war and the need to
rebuild the war-torn Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   He left Aviano Tuesday night aboard Air Force One and was
expected to return to the White House early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I did not want to leave,'' Clinton told the U.S. forces at
Aviano, ``without having the chance to thank those of you who
protect our freedom every single day, who fought for human dignity,
and won its cause, in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
