<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      06-22 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TALKS TO ETHNIC ALBANIANS AT REFUGEE CAMP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVICH 1 REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ In a sea of tents and
eager faces, President Clinton on Tuesday offered words of both
encouragement and caution to ethnic Albanians readying to return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tour of this sprawling tent city near the Macedonian
capital of Skopje provided an emotional and human finale to the
president's European trip, which largely focused on the logistics
and the finances of policing and rebuilding the war-torn Balkan
region.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who was accompanied by the first lady and their
daughter, Chelsea, was enthusiastically received by the refugees,
many of whom spoke little English but still broke into cheers of
``U-S-A, U-S-A'' and ``Clinton, Clinton'' when the first family
came into sight.
</P>
<P>
   As Apache helicopters buzzed overhead, the first family,
surrounded by children, toured a portion of the camp and spoke
personally to a handful of the 10,000 refugees who remain there.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks to the refugees, Clinton stressed that the
United States was committed to the reconstruction effort in Kosovo,
``to helping people rebuild their lives, rebuild their communities
and then to helping Kosovo and all the countries of the region
build a brighter, more prosperous future based on the respect for
the human rights of all people.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned the refugees to be careful about rushing home
before the peacekeeping forces had cleared out dangers such as land
mines or other traps.
</P>
<P>
   The dangers remaining in Kosovo were underscored this week when
four people, including two Nepalese soldiers attached to the
British army, were killed in an explosion as they cleared
ammunition from a deserted schoolhouse in a village 20 miles west
of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I ask you, please be patient with us. Give us a couple of
more weeks to take the land mines up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO peacekeeping forces must also deal with the exodus of
Serb civilians from Kosovo. The Serbs fear retribution from the
Kosovo Liberation Army and from refugees who are returning to
burned-out homes and villages.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides had said earlier this week that the president
would use the refugee camp address to speak out on the need for
tolerance among those returning to their old enemies.
</P>
<P>
   But at the camp, facing those who had been forced from their
homes, the president was silent on the issue of revenge and the
need for acceptance of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   And later, speaking to reporters, he said he was uncertain if
the ethnic Albanians and Serbs could get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know,'' he said. ``It all depends on what kind of
message the soldiers are sending. It depends on a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the camp there were many who said they were not prepared
to let bygones be bygones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot live with those people anymore,'' said Nezar Hidori,
who was waiting on the muddy grounds for Clinton to speak. The
55-year old Hidori, sporting a cap of the professional basketball
team Miami Heat, was forced to leave his home in Pristina two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he and others interviewed gave Clinton credit for the
successful outcome of NATO's 79-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is a big man,'' said Agrom Husseii, a barber who
spent a month in the refugee camp with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Mineree Rexhepi, 24, said she had so much wanted to see Clinton
that she postponed leaving the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rexhepi said she was not angry at the average Serb for what
happened in Kosovo but instead blamed their leaders, particularly
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   During their afternoon visit to the camp,the Clintons listened
to personal accounts about the hardships suffered by the refugees.
Sitting in a tent with one family, the president held a 2-year-old
boy on his lap, as he heard the story of how the family fled from a
village where 60 people were massacred.
</P>
<P>
   The family escaped to Pristina where they were beaten and they
watched as Serb troops threatened a 4-year-old boy with a knife and
lighted cigarette until the soldiers were given money.
</P>
<P>
   The president told the mother that ``you have a beautiful boy.''
She responded that the 2-year-old on the president's lap was still
afraid because of the atrocities he has witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has suffered very much. He has seen people killed and
wounded,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The president told her, ``we have to make sure families get help
for their children. There are some things that children should
never see.''
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at the refugee camp the president met with the
leaders of Macedonia and Albania, the two nations bordering Kosovo
that housed most of the refugees. Clinton promised the leaders of
these Balkan nations that the United States would continue to
provide economic aid as well as encourage business development in
their relatively poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady attended a ceremony in Macedonia, where the
president of Liz Claiborne announced that the New York-based
clothing company would keep open its operation in Skopje, saving
3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with refugees, the president spoke to the
peacekeeping forces in Macedonia and then headed to Aviano Air
Force Base in Italy to thank the pilots who flew most of the
bombing missions over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At his last stop before returning to Washington, Clinton told
the cheering pilots and their families gathered in a hangar that
they deserved credit for stopping the Serb campaign of ethnic
cleansing. He also said that they proved wrong the critics who said
the conflict could not be won through an air war.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also said that the peacekeeping phase will require
as much effort as the military campaign and may be as dangerous, as
evidenced by the death of soldiers this week, who were searching
for land mines when an unexploded NATO bomb detonated.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks it (peace) will take hold without difficulty,''
he said. ``We have to win the peace with the same qualities with
which you won the conflict _ with determination and patience ,with
discipline and precision.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
