<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON-A     06-22 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED MUTINEER'S BID FOR PARDON POSES DILEMMA ON RACE AND
MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ala.)  (ART ADV: Photos of Meeks in 1940s and 1990s were sent to NYT photo
clients as NYT5 on June 21. Locator map is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAVAL WEAPONS STATION CONCORD, Calif. _ In the midst of World
War II, an explosion at the naval base here killed 320 men, two
thirds of them black sailors who had been loading 5,000 tons of
ammunition onto ships. The blast, on the Sacramento River northeast
of San Francisco, tore two ships to shreds and was felt as far away
as Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   It also began an extraordinary legal battle over the legacy of
segregation that is now, 55 years later, heading for the White
House. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to resume
loading ammunition onto ships bound for the Pacific theater. Fifty
refused, were court-martialed, found guilty of mutiny by an
all-white panel and imprisoned. All of the sailors who had been
doing the loading at the time of the blast, including the 50
ultimately convicted of mutiny, were black.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington on May 27, lawyers for one of the sailors, Freddie
Meeks, now 79, filed a petition for a presidential pardon, arguing
that Meeks and the others had had no intent to mutiny. The lawyers
argue that the sailors were simply afraid that they, too, would
become victims of a careless Navy that used black sailors on the
base only as laborers and gave them no training in loading
munitions.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon request is now before the Justice Department, which
will review it and make a recommendation to President Clinton. One
of Meeks' lawyers said it could be as long as 18 months before a
presidential decision is made but that he hoped it would be sooner
because of his client's poor health.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks' petition presents an awkward choice for Clinton between
the racial symbolism of a case that has been gaining attention in
recent years and the military's view that servicemen, particularly
in time of war, cannot choose which orders to obey.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the president's decision, Meeks' pardon application is
very likely to be the last legal move in a case that has threaded
through the nation's modern race history. It helped propel the
integration of the Navy and, some historians say, influenced
President Harry Truman's decision to issue an order formally
desegregating the military in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944 at the Naval Weapons Station Concord (which at that time
was known as Port Chicago), white officers directed black crews in
loading the ammunition, and black survivors of the blast said the
officers sometimes had their crews compete to see which could load
explosives faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, the world should know what happened at
Port Chicago,'' Meeks said the other day in his Los Angeles living
room. ``It should be cleared up that we did not commit mutiny, and
we were charged with that because of our race.'' Meeks, a seaman
2nd class at the time of the explosion on July 17, 1944, is
believed to be one of only a few survivors among the 50 convicted
mutineers.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution gives the president the power to pardon. No
hearing is permitted and there is no appeal, which, lawyers say,
means that applications are judged subjectively. The president may
grant the pardon, deny it, or close the case without presidential
action. But few cases, some lawyers say, are as difficult to
predict as Meeks'.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is very committed on race,'' said Michael Small,
a former senior Justice Department lawyer who is now chief counsel
of the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California. ``But
there could be an uproar in the military. I can imagine people
saying, `Clinton is saying it's OK to countermand orders.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the Pentagon will modify the position it
expressed as recently as 1994 that the Port Chicago mutiny
convictions should stand. Navy officials did not respond to recent
requests for comment. A spokeswoman for the Justice Department said
the department would not comment on a pending case. White House
spokesman Jake Siewert also said there would be no comment on a
pending case.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some veterans have said the Port Chicago men had
not been subjected to any greater dangers than sailors and soldiers
who fought in the war, and should have followed orders.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after Congress directed the Pentagon to review the Port
Chicago case, the Navy concluded that ``the convictions were not
tainted by racial prejudice'' and declined to expunge the
convictions. ``Sailors are required to obey the orders of their
superiors, even if those orders subject them to life-threatening
danger,'' said Defense Secretary William Perry in a 1994 letter to
Congress on the Port Chicago case.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 Navy review did acknowledge that racial prejudice had
influenced work assignments in World War II, when the Navy was just
beginning to change its tradition of using black sailors primarily
as laborers and mess attendants. But the Navy said the mutineers
had already been given leniency; they received sentences of up to
15 years but served only a maximum of 17 months, and they rejoined
regular Navy units afterward. All except those who committed later
offenses were eventually discharged ``under honorable conditions,''
which does not carry the recognition of an honorable discharge.
</P>
<P>
   As the war continued, the military was under growing pressure to
abandon its practice of using blacks in menial jobs. Half a century
later, some federal agencies accept that conditions at Port Chicago
were dangerous and discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1944 the Navy did not have a clear definition of how
munitions should best be loaded,'' says a National Park Service
brochure discussing the dangers the black sailors faced. The
brochure is given to visitors to a memorial at the site of the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people,'' the brochure adds, ``the explosion on July
17, 1944, became a symbol of what was wrong with American
society.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, the Port Chicago explosion was front-page news across
the country, and the mutiny trial that fall was followed closely.
After the black sailors had completed the gruesome task of removing
the unrecognizable victims of the explosion, they were assigned to
a nearby base, Mare Island, and ordered to resume loading
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   At first, 258 black sailors said the conditions remained
dangerous and they refused. Eventually, 208 of those returned to
work, leaving the 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am willing to be governed by the laws of the Navy and do
anything to help my country win this war,'' Meeks said in testimony
at the time. ``I will go to the front if necessary, but I am afraid
to load ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s and since, the Navy has said the refusal to obey
orders could have had a devastating effect on the war and that any
member of the armed services would have been dealt with harshly,
regardless of race. But instead of charging the black sailors with
disobeying an order, a lesser offense, the Navy brought the more
serious charge of mutiny, because it said it had evidence that they
had joined together to resist the orders of their officers.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsuccessful appeal of the convictions, Thurgood Marshall
represented the men two decades before he joined the Supreme Court.
If anything, Marshall said, the men were guilty of disobeying an
order. ``I can't understand, then, why, whenever more than one
Negro disobeys an order, it is mutiny,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   An inquiry by the Navy within days of the explosion did not fix
a specific cause but suggested that rough handling or the
combustion of a super-sensitive device could have contributed. Here
on Suisun Bay, where the Sacramento River widens on its way to the
Pacific, the Navy has for decades loaded ships with everything from
small-arms ammunition to large bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In the papers they filed May 27, Meeks' current lawyers, G.
Brian Busey and Bernice Harleston of the Washington office of
Morrison &AMP; Foerster, repeated many of Marshall's assertions of
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Handling the case without fee, the lawyers have added new
evidence, including a memorandum of the commandant in charge of
Port Chicago that said many of the black sailors ``are of a low
order of mentality, and as such are particularly susceptible to
group influence and to believe wild rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   The town of Port Chicago, near the base, was razed in 1968 when
the Navy bought the land, so there are few reminders anywhere of
what happened here.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Meeks said in the recent interview, the explosion and
its aftermath were forgotten, and he was grateful for the
anonymity. His own sentence of 15 years had been reduced to 17
months, but he needed to work to support his wife and three
children and he worried about the stigma of being a convicted
mutineer.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for a time as a butler for entertainer Danny Thomas
and actress Ann Sothern, and later as a stock clerk for Los Angeles
County and a security officer. Until a few years ago, he said, he
did not mention Port Chicago to anyone, including his children. In
the 1950s he burned papers he had that mentioned the case so no one
would learn the indignities he had suffered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the 1980s, the Port Chicago story was rediscovered.
A sociologist at the University of California, Dr. Robert L. Allen,
wrote a book, ``The Port Chicago Mutiny'' (Amistad, 1989). Rep.
George Miller, D-Calif., whose district includes the naval station,
began pressing for a review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, partly as a result of those efforts, the National Park
Service dedicated a memorial to the 320 men killed in the
explosion. Of those, 202 were black. In March, a television movie
told the Port Chicago story.
</P>
<P>
   After all the years, Meeks said, Port Chicago has become, once
again, a subject he cannot avoid. ``It hurt me so bad to talk about
it, I cried,'' he said, as his wife of 59 years, Eleanor, hovered
near him in the living room of their tidy stucco home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you think about,'' he said in a low voice, ``is how
you were treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, now blind in one eye and suffering from heart disease and
diabetes, said he is running out of time for a review. His lawyers
say they have been able to find only one other survivor among the
50 court-martialed sailors, Jack Crittenden of Montgomery, Ala.,
who said he wanted no part of a pardon application.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Crittenden, a retired Alabama
official, said it was too late for a pardon to do anyone any good.
``I know they did me wrong,'' he said. ``I don't need them to say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A pardon for Meeks would be a largely symbolic move to correct
the historical record.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who have handled pardon applications say the process
requires legal arguments and supporting documents like those used
in a typical court case. At the same time, they say, the fact that
it is also a political process means the president can make his
decision on little more than a feeling about the message a pardon
would send.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the lawyers' standpoint,'' said Dennis Curtis, a
professor at Yale Law School who has handled pardon applications,
``it's like any other case, and then it's not like any other case.
The rules are, you have to have a narrative that is persuasive.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 17, Allen, whose book helped revive interest in the Port
Chicago story, visited the site of the explosion on the naval base
with a reporter. When he is here, Allen said as a breeze blew off
the Suisun Bay, he remembers the stories told to him by the black
sailors of Port Chicago, many now dead.
</P>
<P>
   The water lapped the pylons of the pier that was destroyed that
day, 55 years ago in July. ``I think about how horrible it must
have been to be here that horrible day,'' he said. ``And then,
being put back in that same situation three weeks later; and these
men _ these teen-agers _ having to decide what they were going to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
