<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE BEEF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is it over already?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Not a soul has yet cast a ballot. New Hampshire
and Iowa have not spoken. So how come everybody thinks it's a done
deal?
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore have just
announced their presidential candidacies. But to hear the pundits
tell it, we might as well skip the campaign, go directly to the
conventions and then escort Bush into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The common wisdom holds that both Bush and Gore have their
respective nominations sewed up. They are behaving that way
themselves, competing against each other for the political center,
the campaign fund-raising prize and the lead in the polls. This
election is perceived as a two-man race before the primaries and
caucuses have even been held.
</P>
<P>
   The party conventions are more than a year away, and the common
wisdom has been wrong before. Not much has happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats tell the pollsters they overwhelmingly prefer Gore
to his single primary rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
_ by 59 percent to 21 percent. Since Bradley is about the only
politician in America with a reputation for being more wooden than
Gore, the ratio is unlikely to change much.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's two strongest primary challengers, Elizabeth Dole and
Arizona Sen. John McCain, are similarly far behind. Compared with
the roughly $20 million Bush is expected to raise by the end of
June, Dole and McCain expect around $4 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else is even on the national radarscope. If Steve Forbes
intends to catch up, he will have to spend more of his own millions
than he has been willing to so far.
</P>
<P>
   So we are left with Bush running against Gore and we are into
the general election campaign way ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Can we sustain our interest in this dull duo for another year
and a half?
</P>
<P>
   There's a considerable, if premature, basis for the conclusion
that Bush will win. Thus far, he is outpacing Gore in centrist
moves, fund-raising and poll numbers, the big three tests of the
campaign. Gore can't seem to do anything right lately.
</P>
<P>
   A new Reuters poll has Bush with 55 percent support and Gore
with only 37 percent, roughly the same split as a couple of months
ago before both began campaigning in key states.
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing about Bush's lead is that other polls indicate
a majority of voters still say they don't know very much about
either man despite their public careers. They like what they don't
know about Bush better than what they don't know about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's announcement came across on television better than
Gore's. Where Bush seemed genial and at ease, Gore shouted and
appeared uncomfortable. Gore had to distance himself from Clinton,
not an easy task, whereas Bush simply had to be Bush the younger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father, the former president, initially had Gore's
job-transition problem when he ran in 1992 after eight years in the
shadow of President Ronald Reagan. Bush was tense and uptight,
although he eventually relaxed and won the election. It cannot be
easy to shift from a low-key role in second place to the intense
scrutiny of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, both Gore and George W. Bush speak a bit in
Spanish, demonstrating that neither intends to concede the Hispanic
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Style, however, is only part of the story here. Both candidates
come from patrician backgrounds. They are pampered sons of the
political elite who earned their own way, Bush in business and Gore
in public service. The stylistic differences between them are
superficial.
</P>
<P>
   But the money matters a great deal, because it symbolizes the
extent to which the party establishments have signaled their
approval. It also buys a lot of television time. It puts them on
equal footing as frontrunners. In the end they are expected to
raise about $50 million each.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of what the two men are beginning to say will
matter even more.
</P>
<P>
   Bush needs to sound safe, a harbor of moderation preserving
conservative values while rejecting the extremist pressures
engulfing the Republican Party and threatening to wipe out GOP
control of Congress. Gore needs to sound dignified and truthful, a
believer in the progressive programs of President Clinton but one
who has none of his personal behavior flaws that so embarrassed the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath those general goals are basic philosophical differences
only now emerging. Bush and Gore may be middle-of-the-road captains
not eager to rock any boats, but one is clearly a conservative and
the other a progressive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is terribly evasive. He wants to be all things to all
voters, a devious approach that got Bill Clinton elected but will
be hard for Bush to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the governor says he won't ask for an
anti-abortion pledge from any new Supreme Court nominee but will
pick those who share his philosophy _ which is anti-abortion. He
has not taken a stand on campaign finance reform, financing of
Medicare or the humanitarian foreign policy behind the NATO air
strikes in Kosovo. He will be asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is stuck with Clinton's policies and programs. It is easier
to be fresh, if evasive, than having to make the stale sound novel.
The best Gore can do is expand, revise or upgrade Clinton's
message. He cannot stray too far without seeming disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The campaign begins. Surprises await.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
