<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-QA-COX     06-22 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-QA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A: Greg Stromberg, Mindspring Biz
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday, MindSpring Enterprises launched a separate
division for its small-business users called MindSpring Biz. Made
up largely of staffers from the company's recent Netcom
acquisition, MindSpring Biz hopes to become a leader in
small-business Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stromberg, executive vice president of MindSpring Biz,
talked recently about the new division.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's behind the launch of MindSpring Biz?
</P>
<P>
   A: We were thinking about MindSpring Biz before. We did have
some small-business customers, but our primary focus was always on
individual customers. Netcom was more focused on the business
customer than MindSpring had been. With their Web hosting,
dedicated access and other infrastructure, we saw an opportunity to
stake a claim in a market niche that was not being served _ the
small-business marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're also going to offer high-speed telephone Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Our agreement with Kovad Communications, will provide
sDSL, (synchronized digital subscriber lines), high-speed Internet
service starting in Atlanta, Dallas, Los Angeles and San Francisco.
Right now we haven't announced pricing, but we will have a product
offering that will be very affordable for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you see the small-business Internet market right now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I really believe this is going to change the way people do
business. People are gaining confidence in the Internet. What we're
evolving to is a really focused Internet market economy. The
Internet is changing the definition of a small business. You used
to need a physical storefront to be a small business. Now your
storefront is an electric one.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
