<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICM-COHN-NYT &LR;      06-22 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICM-COHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP AGENT LOSES ROLE AT ICM TALENT AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ For decades, Sam Cohn had been the premier film
agent in New York, a shrewd, cantankerous and somewhat eccentric
figure who represented some of the biggest movie stars and
filmmakers in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, International Creative Management, a top talent agency,
plans to announce that Cohn, 70, will be replaced as the head of
its New York office by Esther Newberg and Amanda ``Binky'' Urban,
who run the agency's literary division. He will continue to
represent such clients as the writers Arthur Miller, John Guare and
E.L. Doctorow and the actors Paul Newman and Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   During his heyday in the 1970s and '80s, Cohn's clients included
Robin Williams, Mike Nichols, Woody Allen, Meryl Streep and Whoopi
Goldberg, but except for Allen, who went to the William Morris
Agency, all have shifted to ICM's chief rival, the Creative Artists
Agency. The bulk of film agents are in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohn is cut from a different cloth than most agents. He
detests Los Angeles, often refuses to respond to phone calls and
views himself more an intellectual than the kind of slick, Armanied
dealmaker now commonplace in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Jeffrey Berg and James Wiatt, the two men who run ICM,
said the change marked, in some ways, a generational shift at ICM's
New York office. ``The appointment reflects our desire to bring in
a new group of senior executives who are also leaders in their
professional fields,'' Berg said. Privately, agents said that
relations between Berg and Cohn had turned rancorous in recent
years, partly over cost-cutting efforts in New York and Los
Angeles. By some accounts, Cohn resisted those efforts in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement with Berg and Wiatt, Cohn, a partner at the
agency and until recently a vice chairman, has sold his equity
stake, which is valued at $6 million to $7 million, people involved
in the negotiations said. He will remain a member of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn said over the phone: ``Nothing's really happened. I had
sold my shares. I'm remaining with the company. I'm changing my
management role. That will be conferred on other people, namely
Binky and Esther, who'll do a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if relations with Berg had anything to do with the move,
Cohn said he would have no comment. And asked how he felt about
relinquishing his management role, he replied: ``Sic transit
gloria.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to replace Cohn with two literary agents makes
clear that ICM is responding to the fact that Los Angeles, and not
New York, dominates the movie and television landscape, while New
York is the center of the publishing business.
</P>
<P>
   And the film business is undergoing some turmoil. Like other
talent agencies, ICM has begun to cut back overhead costs, partly
because many Hollywood studios have trimmed film production.
Several ICM agents in New York and Los Angeles have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   ICM is one of the most powerful film and television talent
agencies in Los Angeles. Its film-star clients include Mel Gibson,
Julia Roberts, Meg Ryan, Denzel Washington, Eddie Murphy and
Michelle Pfeiffer. It also represents such filmmakers as James
Brooks, Francis Ford Coppola and Nora Ephron, and television
producers like the creators of ``Friends,'' Kevin Bright, Marta
Kauffman and David Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Even New York-based actors now generally retain agents in Los
Angeles, which is a far cry from the '70s and '80s. One of the
handful of remaining New York-based film agents is ICM's Elaine
Goldsmith-Thomas, whose clients include Ms. Roberts and Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Newberg, 57, who represents such writers as Patricia
Cornwell, Carl Hiaasen and Pete Hamill, said that she and Ms. Urban
would oversee a team of 50 agents in New York, involved mostly in
literary, music and television commercial work. ``Our primary
responsibility is representing our individual writers,'' Ms.
Newberg said. ``We have terrific people running each division.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Urban, 53, whose clients include the writers Toni Morrison,
Richard Ford and Cormac McCarthy, was on vacation in Europe and
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, the co-chairman of ICM, said that the promotion of Ms.
Newberg and Ms. Urban to run the New York office was ``a
recognition of their stature.''
</P>
<P>
   To clients, associates and studio executives, Cohn has had a
reputation for sometimes offbeat behavior that amuses some and
irritates others. He is said to be very picky about whom he speaks
to over the phone, sometimes snubbing movie executives and even
fellow ICM agents. His tendency to eat paper when nervous has been
used as a joke in film comedies of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn is also known to have an antipathy to Los Angeles that
rivals Allen's. And associates have said that he far prefers
attending the theater in New York or music recitals than going to
movies, unlike most agents in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
