<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS23-COX     06-22 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CISNEROS DEFENSE CHALLENGES CREDIBILITY OF EX-MISTRESS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorneys for former Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Henry Cisneros tried Tuesday to chip away at the
credibility of his ex-mistress, Linda Jones, by suggesting she
intended to use 88 secretly recorded tapes to inflame the scandal
over their affair so she could cash in on book and movie deals.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, testifying for the second day in a pretrial hearing,
responded that she had no recollection of such plans beyond seeking
paid appearances on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really read the legal things,'' she said when defense
attorney Brendan V. Sullivan Jr. produced a contract in which Jones
agreed to give two lawyers 25 percent of any revenues from selling
her story about her seven-year affair with Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the contract, Jones said, ``I would sign it. I
don't know that I always read everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan then produced a book manuscript, saying, ``Do you
recognize this?'' Jones looked it over and told him that she
believed her former attorney Bruce Magness from her home town of
Lubbock, Texas, had written it from notes she jotted down. ``I've
never seen this in this form,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange came as part of the defense effort to persuade U.S.
District Judge Stanley Sporkin to suppress the recordings.
Prosecutors want to use 34 of the tapes to help prove that Cisneros
lied to the FBI and conspired to hide more than $250,000 in alleged
``hush money'' he paid to Jones _ then known as Linda Medlar _ when
he was undergoing a background check for his housing post.
</P>
<P>
   He served as housing secretary from 1993 until his indictment in
1997, which came out of an investigation by independent counsel
David Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who is currently serving a 42-month prison term in
Carswell, Texas, for bank fraud in a case involving Cisneros's
payments, testified earlier that she had secretly taped her
conversations about money with Cisneros because of her financial
worries and her desire to have a record of his promises.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had duplicated the recordings and edited out
portions of five or six of the copies while discarding the
originals. She said the conversations she deleted were chiefly
those in which she threatened to expose the truth about Cisneros's
payments to her. Her lawyers had advised her those remarks could be
construed as extortion, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys, who have charged that her tampering makes the
tapes inadmissable as evidence, are expected to continue to try to
pick away at Jones's credibility Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The judge indicated late Tuesday that the government had yet to
make its case that the tapes should be admitted as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a little imprecision here,'' Sporkin said in a
reference to the prosecution's tall stack of transcripts plus three
boxes of the tapes. ``I don't know what they want out of these
records.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
