<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GOALIE-COX     06-22 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GOALIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fundamentals the key to a good goalie
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An NHL goalie of some note once was drafted in the
10th round, traded for one Stephane Beauregard and thought that he
had suffered the ultimate humiliation by being left unprotected in
the expansion draft _ until he proceeded to go unselected in the
same draft.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Dominik Hasek turned out OK.
</P>
<P>
   Such a career evolution, while extreme, is not atypical for many
NHL goaltenders. For that reason, the Thrashers' attempt to zero in
on worthy netminders available in Friday's expansion draft is only
slightly more scientific than a dart game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest position to predict,'' Thrashers goaltending
consultant Andy Moog said. ``If you have a forward who is 6-2, 220
and is scoring 50 goals a year in the juniors, you can pretty much
project what he's going to do in the NHL. But sometimes the best
goalies are buried on team's rosters. Maybe he doesn't have great
statistics, but he's not in the best situation and he's not getting
a lot of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what you try to do,'' Moog said, ``is look for the guy with
the best fundamentals. So many things can affect a goalie's
performance, but if the fundamentals are there, then you know
eventually he'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the expansion draft ends, the Thrashers probably
will be in possession of six veteran goaltenders. They acquired
probable starter Damian Rhodes last week from Ottawa in exchange
for ``future considerations.'' In return, they agreed to draft a
Senator only from a list provided by the team.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is required to take at least three goaltenders in the
draft, but it probably will take five, the maximum allowed. Rhodes'
projected backup probably will come from Detroit, where 24-year-old
Norm Maracle is considered by some to be a future NHL star. Top
candidates for the remaining four spots are Carolina's Trevor Kidd,
San Jose's Mike Vernon, Boston's Robbie Tallas and St. Louis' Jamie
McLennan.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, who was a business major, views players as ``assets,''
and Vernon and Kidd, in particular, are two worthy assets. The
Thrashers probably would not keep either but instead would work out
trades with the players' former teams _ or elsewhere _ for extra
players or entry-draft picks. Vernon also has a clause in his
contract allowing him to become an unrestricted free agent in July,
further clouding his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that, if you're an average hockey team
with a good goaltender, you're going to steal games,'' Waddell
said. ``An average team with average goaltending is going to have a
hard time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltending is the strength of the expansion draft,'' he said.
``We're not going to get a lot of goal-scoring in the expansion
draft. That's going to have to come from the entry draft and
potentially some European players.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog, who has watched Rhodes a dozen times in the last few years
as an opponent or a scout, thinks he has the style that will enable
him to avoid prolonged slumps. He also thinks Rhodes (22-13-7, 2.44
goals-against average) was hurt last season by the Senators'
decision to rotate him with Ron Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time in everyone's career where (rotating goalies)
is a good fit if it complements both players involved.'' Moog said.
``But that's not a career-long situation. I was in the same
situation (in Edmonton), and I felt I needed to be challenged and
that's what motivated me to leave (there).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything in Damian's past history that would lead
me to believe he can't be a No. 1 goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Maracle is a bigger question mark for the Thrashers. He was only
a fifth-round draft pick of the Red Wings in 1993 but recorded a
2.76 goals-against average in his final year in the juniors
(Saskatoon) and made All-Star teams in his last two years in the
American Hockey League. This year, he was 6-5-2 with a 2.27
goals-against average in 16 games and a saves percentage of .918,
best among goalies available to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan, 27, was not expected to be available to the Thrashers.
But the Blues worked a last-minute deal for Dallas backup Roman
Turek and can protect only one goalie, forcing them to leave both
McLennan (2.38, .891) and Grant Fuhr (2.44, .892) unprotected.
Atlanta would not draft Fuhr, Philadelphia's Ron Hextall or the
like because of their advanced age and salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues thought enough of McLennan last year to trade center
Darren Turcotte and a second-round draft pick to Nashville in
exchange for the Predators' agreement not to take McLennan in the
expansion draft. But that doesn't guarantee success for McLennan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goaltenders are in a category all by themselves,'' Waddell
said. ``Look at the finals this year _ both guys (Hasek and
Dallas's Ed Belfour) are 30 and had been traded. Coaches are
impatient with goalies. Goalies tend to develop when they're
older.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when nobody expects it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
