   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-Y2K (Moscow) _ Armed with thick repair manuals and
rosters of technical experts, Russian officials have opened an
all-out campaign to expel the so-called Year 2000 bug from the
nation's eight million computers, their microchips and their
programs. Technology chiefs and computer experts say Russia has
awakened to the Year 2000 threat too late, spread the alarm too
thinly and has far too little money to perform much more than
digital triage on the government and economy. By Michael Wines.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-Y2K-NUKE.
</P>
