   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GUILT (Obilic, Yugoslavia) _ One of the most difficult
issues in this most complicated of conflicts is the question of who
is guilty or innocent of the killings, beatings and burnings in
Kosovo and how will the guilty ever be brought to justice? Long
after the peace accords were approved in Belgrade, those questions
are likely to remain unresolved. And they are almost certain to
spark repeated clashes as returning Albanians and Serbs attempt to
resume living together. What is festering here is an unfocused rage
that can well up in even the most innocent of circumstances. By
David Rohde. (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-QUOTES (Washington) _ The Senate blocks the passage of a
bill that would have sharply restricted the import of foreign steel
to the United States, a blow to unions and steelmakers and a
victory for President Clinton, who warned that the legislation
would have revived protectionism. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SYMINGTON-APPEAL (San Francisco) _ A federal appeals court
overturns the bank fraud convictions of former Gov. Fife Symington
of Arizona, saying that the trial judge wrongfully dismissed a
juror who disagreed with the others over the governor's guilt. By
Evelyn Nieves. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
