   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo reefer to: TEN-WIMBLEDON-HINGIS; story inside
Sports. (The story has moved in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON (Naval Weapons Base Concord, Calif.) _
During World War II, an explosion on a segregated naval base here
killed 320 men. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to
resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty of them refused, were
court-martialed by an all-white panel, found guilty of mutiny and
imprisoned. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for one
black veteran have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that the
black sailors had no intent to mutiny. The petition pits the racial
symbolism of a celebrated case against the military's view that
servicemen cannot choose which orders to obey. By William
Glaberson. (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   OZAWA-VIENNA (Undated) _ With top classical music orchestras
already shopping for scarce new leadership, the Boston Symphony
Orchestra joins the worldwide game of musical chairs with a
surprise announcement that its long-reigning conductor, Seiji
Ozawa, will leave after the 2002 season to take over the Vienna
State Opera. By Ralph Blumenthal. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET
in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-U.N.-DUES (Washington) _ The Senate overwhelmingly
approves a bill authorizing the payment of more than $800 million
in back dues to the United Nations but cutting future U.S.
contributions to the organization. By Philip Shenon. (Scheduled to
move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SALINGER-AUCTION (New York) _ The saga of the hermitic author,
the confessional writer, the love letters and the auction block
comes full circle and ends, at least in theory, happily for
everyone. Fourteen letters written 27 years ago by J.D. Salinger to
Joyce Maynard were sold at Sotheby's for $156,500 to a software
entrepreneur, Peter Norton. Norton then announced that he is going
to return them to Salinger. By Dinitia Smith. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HATCH-2000 (Washington) _ Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah conservative
who came to Washington to battle Democratic liberals but has moved
toward the center on health and children's issues, says he will
seek the Republican presidential nomination. By Adam Clymer.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
