<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH23-1STLEDE-COX     06-22 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH23-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH GREETED AS A HERO IN FIRST CAPITAL VISIT AS A CANDIDATE
 &HT;    Eds: Restores dropped word ``Hilton'' in graf 17.
 &HT;    710&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush moved through the capital
Tuesday in an atmosphere of triumph more befitting a campaign
victor than a fledgling candidate, receiving a hero's welcome from
Republican congressional leaders before appearing at a Texas-sized
presidential fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after deriding Vice President Al Gore as a
``Washington, D.C. man'' at another fund-raising appearance in
Richmond, Va., the Texas governor strode into private meetings with
32 senators and 100 House members with an insider's flair.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any worry in the Bush camp that the ``compassionate
conservative'' might be tainted by the hard-hearted image of the
GOP-run Congress, it was hardly apparent in the governor's
pilgrimage to the Capitol, his first since declaring his intention
to seek the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And if there was any concern among Bush advisers about the
anti-Washington candidate being embraced by the Washington
establishment, it was lost in the scramble to join Tuesday night's
$1,000-a-person reception, the biggest presidential fund-raiser
ever held here.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters after his meetings with the lawmakers, ``I
believe I'm going to be here to work with them for tomorrow. I know
I've got a long way to go, but I'm really pleased with the support
I've received inside this building. And the best way to convey my
thanks is to look each in the eye and say, 'Thank you very much.'
``
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., a longtime political ally of Bush's
father, former President George Bush, escorted the governor around
the Capitol. Coverdell told reporters that the senators with whom
the governor met share his views on cutting taxes, reforming Social
Security and education and rebuilding the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our visions of the future and the new millennium are very
homogeneous,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen Republican senators and 114 Republican House members
have endorsed Bush's candidacy, an unprecedented showing of
congressional support this early in the nominating process with 13
other candidates, including three senators and one congressman,
seeking the party nod.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas said Republicans up and down
the ballot will have to stick together next year if they want to
recapture the White House and avoid a Democratic takeover of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be productive for members of Congress
to run a campaign isolated from the presidency,'' Hutchison said.
``What we have to do is convince the American people that if we
elect a Republican president and a Republican Congress, we are
going to do the things that people believe are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party leaders used Bush's visit to the Capitol to
link him to unpopular legislative priorities of the Republican-led
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he hasn't said much about his ideas, when you press
him for specifics, Bush follows the far-right GOP Congress more
than he leads it,'' said Democratic National Committee General
Chair Roy Romer.
</P>
<P>
   But polling data suggests Americans like Bush more than the
Republican leadership of Congress. In the latest CNN poll, 54
percent said they preferred Bush over Gore, the Democratic
front-runner, but only 36 percent said they favored the GOP
continuing to control Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk to Bush is that he gets too close to the Republican
Congress,'' said William Schneider, CNN's senior political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps reflecting this assessment, Bush did not pose for
photographs with the party's congressional leaders, and he stood
alone at a microphone outside a Senate hearing room for his brief
comments to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Tuesday night's fund-raiser, however, Republicans
are not shying away from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The 425 sponsors of the Bush reception at the Washington Hilton
included many of the city's most powerful and influential
lobbyists, as well as many former officials from the presidencies
of Bush's father and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The event was expected to raise more than $2 million, which
would make it the largest fund-raiser ever by a presidential
candidate, and especially a candidate who, as Bush has done
recently, derides the ``zero-sum politics'' of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the millionaire publisher who is financing his own
campaign for the GOP nomination, criticized the Bush fund-raiser
and accused the governor of ``becoming inextricably intertwined''
with ``Washington fat cats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush gained a new challenger Tuesday as Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah
joined the GOP contest, telling reporters that he was entering the
race even though he considers himself ``the longest of long shots''
at this ``late stage'' of the White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said Bush ``seems to have it all,'' but said he intended
to position himself as a viable conservative alternative if the
Texas governor should falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens to George W. Bush, I don't know if we
would have an alternative who could beat Al Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his Richmond stop earlier Tuesday, Bush directed his
anti-Washington rhetoric Tuesday squarely at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Washington, D.C. person,'' Bush said in response to
reporters' questions. ``He thinks Washington has got all the
answers. I don't. I believe the answers are found in our
communities. I believe the answers are found in faith-based
institutions, in community organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
