u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GUILT-2TAKES-N     06-22 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GUILT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTION OF WHERE TO LAY BLAME INFLAMES TENSIONS AS REFUGEES RETURN
TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OBILIC, Yugoslavia _ Frightened by Albanians streaming back into
this central Kosovo town, Snezana Ivanovic and Sabrija Popic sought
out a newly arrived British soldier on Saturday and asked for
``guarantees of protection.'' The two women, one Serbian and one a
gypsy, feared retaliation as Albanians returned here to find their
dwellings and shops looted or burned.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Popic told the soldier that masked paramilitaries were
responsible for the damage, not her. ``There are people who were
robbing and beating people who have escaped,'' from the town, she
said. ``And now the innocent people will pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Abdullah Restelica, a 49-year-old Albanian passing by,
protested. ``I came today from Macedonia,'' he said angrily. ``My
family was beaten here before my own eyes! My house was robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Ivanovic, the Serb woman, shot back: ``Who robbed your
house?'' ``I didn't. Innocent people didn't do anything. We
shouldn't have to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The British soldier answered, ``We are trying to provide a safe
environment for every community.'' But his words did little to calm
the tension of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   In virtually every corner of this embattled province, such
exchanges illustrate one of the most difficult issues in this most
complicated of conflicts. Who is guilty or innocent of the
killings, beatings and burnings in Kosovo and how will the guilty
ever be brought to justice?
</P>
<P>
   Long after the peace accords were approved in Belgrade, those
questions are likely to remain unresolved for months even years
here. And worse, they are almost certain to spark repeated clashes
as returning Albanians and Serbs attempt to resume living together.
</P>
<P>
   An unfocused rage that can well up from either direction is
festering here under even the most innocent of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday in Slovi, another small village in the middle of the
province, Jasmina Stanisic ran into the road and blocked a passing
car. Pounding her fists on the hood, Ms. Stanisic, a Serb, demanded
that British NATO soldiers immediately search its trunk. Her
brother, she shrieked, had been kidnapped by Albanians 15 minutes
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took him!'' she thundered. ``They took him!''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was found in the car and for the next chaotic hour,
26-year-old Lt. Graham Shannon and 30 other British soldiers
struggled to keep this ethnically mixed village from exploding.
During the last two nights, Albanian refugees and Kosovo Liberation
Army soldiers have been returning home here to find houses looted
and burned. In retaliation, they had pillaged the homes of
departing Serbs. The kidnapping on Tuesday threatened to spark a
new, more deadly cycle of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   The task of sorting out responsibility for the atrocities is
especially daunting in Kosovo because reports show that the
violence was carried out by a combination of Yugoslav army
soldiers, paramilitary units and internal security forces. Some
Serbian paramilitaries wore masks while they committed many crimes,
some had local guides point them to the homes of wealthy Albanians,
and many followed orders from a central command led by one of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's top military aide.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to determine who is accountable complicates NATO's
efforts to keep the peace and prevent revenge attacks. The
poisonous legacy of few thousand masked paramilitaries _ and
Belgrade's decision to unleash them _ is that innocent or not, all
Serbs in Kosovo are now all suspects in the eyes of returning
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Some Albanians are convinced they recognized the voice of a
paramilitary who abused them as that of a local Serb or a gypsy.
Others insist a local Serb must have guided the paramilitaries. How
else would they have singled out houses that belonged to prosperous
local Albanian businessmen? But few Albanians can definitively say
which Serbs, if any, were involved.
</P>
<P>
   The International War Crimes Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia
and whatever local justice system is eventually established here
faces a daunting task in sorting through tens of thousands of
crimes. A tribunal official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said investigators are initially concentrating on who had command
responsibility for the most serious crimes. In some cases, masks
may prevent tribunal officials from eventually identifying specific
perpetrators unless a fellow paramilitary, soldier or policeman
becomes a cooperating witness, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo Liberation Army officials, for their part, said they are
discouraging revenge attacks. Hydajet Hyseni, the acting justice
minister of the self-appointed KLA provincial government, said his
organization would fully cooperate with the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned to stop any such reactions,'' he said,
referring to revenge attacks. ``The consequences will be very grave
if we find anyone carrying out reprisals.''
</P>
<P>
   But fear and rumors of reprisals are rampant in the handful of
communities where Serbs remain. NATO officials said they do not
have a complete tally of the number of Serbian civilians killed
since they arrived last Saturday. But there have been dozens of
sniping attacks and at least four Serb civilians have been shot
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge attacks are already occurring here in Obilic. A gypsy's
home was ablaze here Monday night, set on fire by angry Albanians,
according to a local Albanian farmer. The bodies of five men, two
teenagers and three middle-aged, were found shot dead execution
style in a field outside of town Saturday morning. British soldiers
said the men appeared to have been killed recently but they did not
yet know their identities. Local Serbs said they believed the
victims were Serbs. Albanians said they believed the victims were
Albanians.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Problems in Obilic are in some ways to be expected. Zeljko
``Arkan'' Raznatovic, the Belgrade-based Serb paramilitary leader
indicted by the International War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague,
made this his base in Kosovo. He owned a soccer club here and the
town was a major center of paramilitary activity. The town had its
own citizens defense brigade that fought with Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions here were evident in the shouting match between Ms.
Popic, Ms. Ivanovic and Restelica. Albanians bitterly complained
about their suffering at the hands of paramilitaries and accused
local gypsies of looting homes and stores. Ms. Popic admitted the
looting occurred but insisted she was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't rob anything,'' she said. ``You can come to my house
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanians emerging from hiding or returning home from Macedonia
or Albania were divided over the issue of assigning guilt. The vast
majority of those who were interviewed said they believed some
local Serbs and gypsies took part in the killing and pillaging. But
none of them could cite by name a local Serb who was involved.
</P>
<P>
   They split over whether Serbs and gypsies should be allowed to
stay here. ``They should go,'' said Ingi Nasuri, a 17-year-old who
spent the last three months in hiding in the town. ``They don't
belong here. They don't have any place here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barije Kostanica, a 34-year-old woman who also spent the
last three months in hiding, said the Serbs and gypsies with
``clean hands'' should be allowed to stay. When asked the question
at the heart of the dilemma _ who should determine guilt or
innocence _ Ms. Kostanica said simply, ``I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
