<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5604 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMINGTON-APPEAL-600&AMP;     06-22 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-APPEAL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OVERTURNS BANK FRAUD CONVICTION OF FORMER ARIZONA GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal appeals court on Tuesday overturned
the bank fraud convictions of former Gov. Fife Symington of
Arizona, saying that the trial judge wrongfully dismissed a juror
who disagreed with the others over the governor's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting
in San Francisco, said that there was a ``reasonable possibility''
that the juror was removed because the rest of the jury was
frustrated that she did not agree with them, and not, as the jurors
had complained to the judge, because she refused to deliberate with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Symington, who resigned during his second term in September
1997, one month after he was convicted of lying on financial
statements to lenders during his career as a real estate developer,
is now entitled to a new trial. He had been sentenced to two and a
half years in prison, but had remained free on bail pending his
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great sense of relief,'' Symington said Tuesday
afternoon from his home near Phoenix. ``I'm very grateful for the
decision and frankly, emotions are very high right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once on the short list of rising stars in the Republican Party,
Symington, a Harvard graduate and decorated Air Force veteran of
Vietnam, was convicted on seven felony counts of defrauding his
lenders by falsely inflating his net worth to obtain new loans to
salvage failing projects, then falsely deflating it to have loans
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they had no intention of dropping the case.
They said they were considering three options: appealing to the
United States Supreme Court, asking the full 11-member appeals
court to hear the case, or retrying the case. ``Obviously we're
disappointed,'' prosecutor David Schindler said, adding that they
``were certainly prepared to re-try the case'' or to try to
negotiate a plea agreement with Symington.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in his trial was in its sixth day of deliberations when
Judge Roger Strand of U.S. District Court in Phoenix dismissed the
juror, Mary Ann Cotey, 74, and replaced her with an alternate. The
rest of the jury had complained that Ms. Cotey was inattentive and
confused, seemed not to understand evidence, and refused to discuss
her positions. Strand, after interviewing Ms. Cotey, decided that
she was ``either unable or unwilling to deliberate with her
colleagues,'' which constitutes a ground for removing her.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit ruled that the judge should have ordered more
deliberations or declared a mistrial, given that some of the
jurors' objections to Ms. Cotey seemed to be based on disagreements
with her over the merits of the case. The appeals court noted that
when interviewed by Strand, Ms. Cotey suggested that the other
jurors' frustrations with her might be because she ``couldn't agree
with the majority all the time, at least temporarily,'' and that
she felt she was being pressured into a vote by the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there may have been some reason to doubt Cotey's
abilities as a juror, there was also considerable evidence to
suggest that the other jurors' frustrations with her derived
primarily from the fact that she held a position opposite to
theirs,'' Judge Betty Fletcher wrote in the court's 40-page
decision.
</P>
<P>
   When told of the decision, Ms. Cotey said, ``Hallelujah! Free at
last! Free at last!'' She said she felt the same as she did the day
she was removed from the jury _ that she had been wrongfully
dismissed, and that she never thought the case against Symington
was very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, I'm sorry you resigned,'' she said she would
tell the ex-governor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Symington, a great grandson of Henry Clay Frick, the
turn-of-the-century coal and steel magnate, and a cousin of Stuart
Symington, a Democratic senator from Missouri, was relatively
unknown when he announced his candidacy for governor in 1989,
promising to run the state the way he ran his real estate empire in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He was re-elected in 1995, despite the by-then four-year
investigation into his finances. He has contended that he filed
false statements unintentionally, and that those mistakes should
have been caught by his accountants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt,'' he said Tuesday, that ``I was wrongly
convicted, that what happened to me was inappropriate. It's a
wonderful day to see truth and justice win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
