<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE ALL SMILES IN ENGLAND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Off with his head,'' said  &UR; Prince Edward &LR; , and the deed was
done, never mind that the giver of orders, seventh in line to the
throne, is five places behind the beheadee,  &UR; Prince William &LR; . The
problem was that the victim had failed to smile in the official
royal family wedding picture; Edward ordered that his nephew's head
be removed by computer and replaced with another version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince Edward said he didn't think Prince William looked
absolutely his best, so digitally we were able to put in another
picture of Prince William from one of the other shots where he is
smiling and laughing,'' said photographer  &UR; Geoffrey Shakerley &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   William received what the royals described as a ``sensible''
vehicle, his first, for his 17th birthday on Monday. The palace
wouldn't be more specific, but British media said it was a
Volkswagen Golf.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. MSNBC says  &UR; Madonna &LR;  is speaking nowadays with a ``clipped
British accent.'' Her makeup artist explained to the Sunday Mirror
that the singer ``almost finds it hard to remember her own accent
sometimes because she has so many English friends and she spends so
much time in England.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYBERITEMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ First sentence of  &UR; John Boe &LR; 's Great Electronic Novel: ``Call
me Email.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sybase company followed its Adaptive Server model 12 with
model 14, presumably to avoid the unlucky number 13.
</P>
<P>
   The company's in-house question-and-answer site includes a
letter from a Hong Kong employee who notes that in Chinese
numerology 14 means ``certain death.''  &UR; May Lee  &LR; of the
Chinese-Western Cultural History Institute explained to Personals
that the number four is the one considered unlucky, because the
Chinese word for four sounds similar to the word for death. The
Sybase writer said that one stands for certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shipping `System Certain Death' might be considered
inauspicious, especially in Hong Kong, Singapore, China and
Japan,'' says the letter from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WIFE'S SECRET BLOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Columba Bush &LR; , wife of Florida Governor  &UR; Jeb Bush &LR; , has been
fined $4,100 in duties by the Customs Service for failing to report
the purchase of $19,000 worth of clothing and jewelry she bought in
Paris. Mrs. Bush, who returned to the country from a European trip
last week, had declared $500 in purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush said during a press conference Monday that his
wife ``feels horrible'' about her lapse. He said her real intention
had not been to defraud the government but to keep him from knowing
how much she'd spent. ``It is a lot of money,'' he said, ``but
look, that's between her and me.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Teen magazine suggests turning stressful situations into
laughing matters. ``Imagine the person who's giving you your
driving test has a watermelon for a head.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The license of psychologist  &UR; Irene Kassorla &LR; , who ministered
to  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , has been put on probation for three years for
``repeated negligent acts'' including failing to keep proper notes
on therapy. In testimony quoted in the Starr Report, Kassorla had
called Lewinsky depressed and said she had low self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Kassorla was called ``shrink to the stars'' by  &UR; Merv Griffin &LR; ,
and played herself on ``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Post says that talks are under way, and there's
an 80 to 85 percent _ what the heck, 83.4 percent _ chance that the
``Today'' show will hire the  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  as a
celebrity-interviewing correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mixed messages:  &UR; Benny Shaboy &LR;  is in favor of passing a law
that would require the Ten Commandments to be printed in large type
on every gun. And  &UR; Tom Ammiano &LR; , suffering from cultural overload,
says he spent the weekend watching ``The Ring That Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Rachel Klein &LR;  noticed that  &UR; Adam Sandler &LR; , on the cover this
week of the San Francisco Chronicle's Datebook section, is repaying
the nod from San Francisco. He's appeared twice on TV recently _ on
Jay Leno's show and on the MTV Movie Awards _ wearing that familiar
reversible San Francisco public school physical education T-shirt.
</P>
