<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-GAME4-ADVANCE-COX     06-22 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GAME4-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   A devine hero
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Denberg
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Modest, a little shy, Allan Houston is an unlikely
basketball hero for this brawling, irreverent town.
</P>
<P>
   He says God sent him.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who scored those 34 points in Game 3 of the NBA Finals
on Monday, who rescued the Knicks from a sweep before tonight's
Game 4, who has advanced to the forefront of the league's special
shooting guards, says he believes it. And Houston doesn't appear
the sort of person who would tell you a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he wondered about his calling in the winter of 1996-97,
when he first arrived in Manhattan and took a beating from the
boo-birds in the stands and the tabloids in the sidewalk kiosks.
His problem was he didn't come in swaggering and dominating and
showing he was a player worth $55 million over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never really one to read the papers and look at the
media too much,'' he said Tuesday. ``I knew that (approach) would
be a positive for me here. I relied on my ability just to try and
get the job done on the court. I didn't worry about my personality
in a contrast with this city. Just continue to be the type person I
was and continue to work hard. And I knew that things would work
out.'' He was coming off a big year with Detroit, where he averaged
19.7 in a formidable young tandem with Grant Hill. He was a star on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
   A free agent, he was told by Detroit owner Bill Davidson to
satisfy himself _ to go out and find the best deal in the league
because Davidson would top it. The Knicks were looking at Steve
Smith, and they had vague interest in Reggie Miller. But when the
Knicks waved their huge offer at Houston, the game was over. The
Pistons never had a counter-offer.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, they blamed Doug Collins, who was the coach and
general manager Collins reportedly insulted Houston and agent Bill
Strickland by asking Strickland when he would get his client to
play defense.
</P>
<P>
   Houston distances himself from that version. ``I was
disappointed in that people didn't give me credit for making my own
decision in coming here, and people were throwing out all kind of
reasons,'' he said. ``But I knew it was a great opportunity because
look where I am now. I'm in the Finals. That's where God sent me. I
figured that was the reason for me being here.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first year with the Knicks, his scoring average dropped
almost five points and his shooting percentage plummeted. In games
against Detroit, Houston disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But he bloomed last year after Patrick Ewing broke his wrist.
The Knicks' offense turned away from the post, and the tempo of the
game increased. Houston established himself by averating 18.7
points. This season, even with the difficult adjustment in learning
to share with Latrell Sprewell in a lockout-shortened season,
Houston was able to take the next big step to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy has seen a noticeable difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his hunger to continue to score even when he scores
well early is different now,'' he said. ``I thought for the first
year and a half he was here, he was very content if he got 20 to
stay at 20. And now, I think he has a continuing hunger to try and
score.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston says his position demands that. ``They call it shooting
guard. The first word is shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes he is better than good. ``In my mind, I've always
been (a superstar), and I will continue to be that type of player.
That's the belief I have in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he can't get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get to the point where people say, 'He doesn't have
any weaknesses. He's an all-around player.' That's where I want to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a Michael (Jordan), Spree, the great scorers and
players in this league. They aren't happy with 20 points. if they
have a great start, they want to keep it going. Earlier, I was
unselfish. If I got some points, I wanted to get some assists. You
can still do that, but I've learned to stay hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Monday's game. Houston had 18 at the half. The Knicks made
four baskets in the third quarter, and he had all four of them. He
had 34 of their 89 points. That's on top of the 32 he hung on the
Pacers in the decisive Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals.
That's on top of the 34 he dumped on the Hawks in Game 1 of the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   He can do this because he has size (6-foot-6) and quickness and
health, because his dad and former college coach, Wade Houston,
encouraged his intermediate game. He can get you going to the hoop
and from behind the arc and in between.
</P>
<P>
   They used to call him Mr. Softee. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
