u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHEAST-DROUGHT-BOS     06-22 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHEAST-DROUGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEAST DRYING OUT; OFFICIALS GUARD WATER SUPPLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Water levels in the Ipswich River have dropped so low
that state officials fear fish may begin to die. Farmers such as
Bob Connors have turned to costly, around-the-clock irrigation to
keep crops alive. Towns have begun ordering cuts on water use, as
filling pools and lawn-watering drain wells.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days into the summer of 1999, the Northeast is
already in the grips of a drought that is leaving ballfields,
parks, and untended lawns a parched brown across much of New
England. If the trend continues, state officials say a water
shortage could jeopardize everything from fire protection to the
fall cranberry harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off to a terribly rocky start,'' said William A. Wood,
water superintendent in Topsfield, where plummeting well levels
prompted officials to ban almost all outdoor water use except with
a watering can.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, communities such as Topsfield are particularly
vulnerable because their water supply is small and isolated, but,
after nearly a month without measurable rainfall in Boston and none
forecast until next week, weather watchers from government
officials to farmers are getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service is expected to announce Wednesday
that southern New England is experiencing its first ``moderate
drought'' since 1995, with precipitation 15 to 25 percent below
average for the year. Boston already set a record for lowest-ever
rainfall in April, while Cape Cod, Martha's Vineyard, and Nantucket
are among the driest places in New England now.
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Service's Climate Prediction Center expects
near-average rainfall for southern and eastern New England this
summer, and above-average rain for parts of the Northeast. But even
weather officials caution against putting too much faith in these
long-term forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are advising people to take precautions to
conserve water so, if we remain dry over the next few weeks, we
won't have any problems,'' said Joe Dellicarpini, meteorologist at
the National Weather Service office in Taunton.
</P>
<P>
   The New England drought is part of a broader dry spell that
stretches back to last August and covers much of the region from
Maine to Maryland. The Northeast Regional Climate Center at Cornell
University calculates that Maryland has been hardest hit, missing 8
to 14 inches of rain over the past 10 months that normally would
have helped its $500 million farm industry.
</P>
<P>
   The drought crept up on New England, which has had a few wet
months sandwiched around very dry months such as last December.
Since April 1, Massachusetts has had about 5 inches of rain, half
the normal amount, including no measurable rain since May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can use any rain that we can get,'' said Keith Eggleston,
senior climatologist at the Cornell climate center. ``One or two
heavy rainfall events could help things that rely on the short
term, like gardens, crops, and agricultural interests. But for more
groundwater, we'll need a few months of above-normal
precipitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought hasn't gone on long enough to affect major water
resources such as the Quabbin Reservoir that provides Greater
Boston's drinking water. The massive reservoir in western
Massachusetts remains 94 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dry spell is leaving its mark in places such as the
Ipswich River in northern Massachusetts, where the water level has
dropped to a trickle during the month of June, raising fears that
the fish will begin dying. On Monday, Department of Environmental
Protection officials wrote to 14 towns that draw drinking water
along the river calling on them to educate citizens on the need to
conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers also are taking precautions to keep their new crops from
dying of thirst in the field. Connors of Danvers is dousing his
corn with 5 million gallons of water a week, and still praying for
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of scary,'' Connors told the Associated Press.
``We're talking about losing hundreds of thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, communities such as Franklin, Norfolk, and Topsfield
are restricting the amount of water residents can use, both to ease
immediate pressure on the water system and to conserve water for
the dog days of summer ahead.
</P>
<P>
   For many officials, the scary thing is how quickly the water
problem developed. Norfolk water superintendent Jim Martin
initially warned people to conserve in May, then imposed an
every-other-day lawn-watering rule in early June, but quickly found
out that wasn't enough when hilltop residents reported bursts of
air along with water coming from their showerheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do fine until it gets down to everybody having to water a
quarter acre of lawn,'' said Martin, who banned outdoor lawn
watering last week, in part to ensure enough water pressure to
fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   Lealdon Langley, director of watershed permitting at the DEP,
said the drought isn't nearly as serious as in 1988, when months of
dry weather dangerously depleted even the Quabbin reservoir. But
each dry day makes water officials more anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely at this point a heightened level of
concern among all the water policy planners and water department
supervisors,'' said Langley.
</P>
</TEXT>
