</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR FINDING THAT POST-COLD WAR WORLD CAN BE CONFUSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Gov. George W. Bush often tells campaign
audiences that the world is a dangerous place in the post-Cold War
era. It can also be confusing.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor had a little trouble with the new world order
on Tuesday when a foreign journalist asked him about Slovakia, a
spin-off from the former Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I know about Slovakia is what I learned
first-hand from your foreign minister, who came to Texas,'' Bush
replied at a news conference during a campaign stop in Virginia.
``I had a great meeting with him. It's an exciting country. It's a
country that's flourishing. It's a country that's doing very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor added that he was ``very impressed'' with his guest
from the former Eastern bloc.
</P>
<P>
   There were only two problems with Bush's answer: His April 26
visitor in Austin wasn't a foreign minister and he wasn't from
Slovakia. He was Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek of Slovenia, a
breakaway from the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes acknowledged that her boss is
still getting up to speed on foreign policy issues. In recent
weeks, Bush has referred to Greeks as ``Grecians,'' Kosovars as
``Kosovarians'' and East Timorese as ``East Timorians.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the acknowledged front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination, has assembled a team of foreign policy
advisers that includes former Secretary of State George Shultz and
former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He readily concedes that, as governor, he does not have
extensive foreign policy experience,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bush isn't the only presidential candidate who has
had trouble keeping track of events of Eastern Europe. In the 1976
presidential debates, Gerald Ford suggested that Poland was not
under Soviet domination, which came as big news to Poland. And that
was before the Soviet Union's collapse created a host of new
republics and ethnic enclaves with nationalist goals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came to Virginia on the second day of a five-day campaign
swing that will include stops in Pennsylvania, Michigan and
Florida. He also stopped by the Capitol on Tuesday for closed
meetings with House and Senate Republicans. The Bush campaign
counts 20 out of 55 GOP senators and 126 out of 223 House
Republicans as supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The three dozen senators who huddled with Bush Tuesday included
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who told reporters earlier in the day
that he plans to run for president ``in case Bush stumbles.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Hatch's comments, Bush said, ``That's an
interesting vision. No, I don't intend to stumble. I'm running. I'm
running hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's meeting with congressional Republicans came as Democrats
sought to link the Texas governor to House Majority Leader Dick
Armey of Irving and Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land. A
Democratic National Committee news release asserted that Bush came
to Capitol Hill to ``plot strategy'' with conservative GOP leaders
even though Armey, DeLay and Speaker Dennis Hastert skipped the
session to hold their own separate leadership meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he hasn't' said much about his ideas, when you press
him for specifics, Bush follows the far-right GOP Congress more
than he leads it,'' said Democratic Party chairman Roy Romer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shrugged off the Democrats' line of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race, if I'm the nominee, is between me and Vice
President Al Gore,'' he said. At his earlier news conference in
Richmond, Bush predicted that voters would see ``a huge
difference'' between himself and Gore if they face off in November
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Washington, D.C. person. He thinks Washington has got
all the answers. I don't,'' Bush said. ``I believe the answers are
found in our communities. I believe answers are found in
faith-based organizations and community organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush ended his Washington visit with a sold-out fund-raiser that
was expected to raise about $1.5 million for the GOP front-runner.
The sold-out event in the Washington Hilton Hotel drew a host of
Republicans with ties to former President George Bush, the
candidate's father.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
