<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTINPOWERS-DOLL23-C     06-22 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTINPOWERS-DOLL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta mom takes issue with sexy toy spy
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Talk about a mojo meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of talking action figures based on the hit movie
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' may disappear from Toys
``R'' Us stores nationwide after an East Point (Ga.) woman
complained that her son was exposed to the swinging secret agent's
saucy catch phrase: ``Do I make you horny, baby? Do I?''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Whitty, a spokeswoman for the giant toy retailer, said
store managers will check their remaining stock of Austin Powers
dolls and remove those that repeat the phrase that offended Tamatha
Brannon and her 11-year-old son, Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   The Brannons were shopping in the chain's Morrow (Ga.) store
Saturday when Marvin picked up one of the dolls, read the phrase
written on the package and asked his mother what ``horny'' meant.
Brannon subsequently filed a criminal complaint against the store
and has demanded an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not acceptable,'' said Brannon, who stood next to her
son during an impromptu press conference in the store's parking lot
Tuesday. ``My son is not old enough to be talking about sex, and I
think Toys ``R'' Us should be responsible for putting something
that's inappropriate for kids on their shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brannon said that two years ago, Marvin saw the first Austin
Powers movie with his father, from whom she's divorced. Even though
the earlier film contained many sexual references, she criticized
the store for ``embarrassing'' her son.
</P>
<P>
   Whitty blamed the incident on a shipping mix-up, saying the
chain's 700 stores were only supposed to receive versions of the
dolls that uttered innocuous lines from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to get the action figures, but from now on we
will check, and those with the phrase will be sent back to the
vendor.'' It was unclear Tuesday how many of the dolls remained,
because they had been selling briskly since the movie's release
June 11. Whitty said she had gotten no other complaints.
</P>
<P>
   However, Whitty said the store planned to keep versions of the
doll that repeat the word ``shag,'' a British euphemism for sex
that is also part of Powers' retro hipster vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think that's right,'' said Brannon late Tuesday.
``I don't think any of those words should be in a child's toy
store. If they don't correct this, my son won't be back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Doug Jewett of the Clayton County (Ga.) police said the
department is no longer investigating Brannon's complaint. But
county solicitor Keith Martin said he's still reviewing the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here is whether this is obscene or offensive,''
said Martin. ``I don't know who we would even prosecute here.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd McFarlane, owner of the Arizona-based company that
manufactures the dolls, which sell for $14.99, said the ``horny''
versions were intended for stores that cater to older shoppers,
such as Spencer Gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody mixed a couple of boxes up and one of them landed in
Georgia. I won't make any excuses,'' said McFarlane, who is also
the creator of the ultra-violent comic book character ``Spawn.''
</P>
<P>
   But McFarlane, who is the parent of two young children, said
Brannon had blown the issue out of proportion. ``These are the
moments in life when you have to make a decision whether you're
going to save the world from evil or sit down with your kids and
tell them what you think is appropriate, and what isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
