<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOLKLIFE-FESTIVAL-BOS     06-22 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLKLIFE-FESTIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL TO SHOWCASE DIVERSE CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first glance, New Hampshire, with its quaint
covered bridges and critical presidential primary, doesn't seem to
have much in common with Romania or South Africa _ until today
(Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   The culture and customs of all three regions will be featured at
this year's Smithsonian Folklife Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the nation's capital will be able to witness a chip
off the Granite State during the festival, which annually features
a diverse triad of communities from the United States and around
the world. The festival, now in its 33d year, runs through July 4.
</P>
<P>
   On the National Mall Tuesday, participants hammered at covered
bridges and carved into granite tablets, bringing parts of New
Hampshire to life as they prepared for the festival. About 140 New
Hampshire residents will be showing off more than 30 exhibits that
were previewed last month at a folklife festival in Concord, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   As next year's presidential election looms, one exhibit
highlights the outsized role New Hampshire residents play in
national politics. With the exception of Bill Clinton in 1992, no
president has been elected without first winning the New Hampshire
primary, the first in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors also can peek inside a two-story timberwood barn with
live animals or walk through a smaller-scale model of a covered
bridge. They can attend demonstrations on herding sheep and learn
about the history of making Shaker furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry? Tourists can purchase their pick from a menu of lobster
rolls, New England clam chowder, baked beans, maple sausage
hoagies, and fresh-squeezed lemonade. And in the evening,
Franco-American fiddlers will serenade as visitors dance.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to feature the Granite State this year stemmed from
the suggestion of a New Hampshire resident, who, after visiting the
folklife festival four years ago, called the festival director,
Diana Parker, and rallied for his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went on and on about the great craftspeople and wonderful
history that New Hampshire had,'' Parker said. ``So we decided we
had to look into it.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of researchers from the Smithsonian and from the New
Hampshire Arts Council set out to uncover the state's many cultural
traditions _ from music to local culinary treats.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Kaufhold, 63, of Peterborough, N.H., who was helping set
up the exhibit Tuesday, said, ``There's so much great things that
people do in this state. I'm glad someone noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufhold and her husband, Hans, who runs a granite and marble
carving business in Peterborough, will hand-carve an outline of New
Hampshire with the state motto ``Live Free or Die'' onto a slab of
granite as part of their exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufhold's family has been in the business for as long as she
can remember. Her father has helped carved headstones for soldiers
in the Tomb of the Unknowns in Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in New Hampshire still do things the old-fashioned
way _ with hammers and mallets,'' Hans Kaufhold said. ``Not
everything is made with machines.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which usually features one state and two foreign
countries, chose Romania and South Africa this year out of
``curatorial interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one way we choose which countries or states to
feature,'' Vicki Moeser, a Smithsonian spokeswoman, said. ``We
really try to get a mixed variety every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibits from Romania feature music and dance groups, in
colorful costume, from the provinces of Moldova, Transylvania and
Wallachia.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenters from Maramures, a region in northern Romania, have
also carved and constructed a model of a wooden church, similar to
those that line their city streets. Visitors can sample traditional
Romanian dishes such as sarmale, a cabbage dish, or mamaliga, a
corn dish.
</P>
<P>
   The South African exhibit highlights the country's political
history, its success in breaking from apartheid and its continuing
struggle to unite its multiple races and cultures. Traditional
pottery and beadwork is being featured, along with urban artwork,
such as rugs woven from plastic shopping bags and baskets made with
telephone wires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
