<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 27,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAME-CONCEPT (Undated) _ Has the concept of fame shifted in the
past decade? Has Andy Warhol's ``everyone will be famous for 15
minutes'' become a cultural cliche? Today the Warholian trajectory
of fame has been reversed: instead of the ordinary becoming famous,
the famous seem to become more ordinary, more like us. In
entertainment, politics and social mores, the high and mighty are
tumbling all around us, or so true celebrities would have us think.
By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORFEU-FILM (Rio De Janeiro, Brazil) _ Even before he emerged as
a torchbearer of the Cinema Novo movement here in the 1960s, the
director Carlos ``Caca'' Diegues yearned to film the myth of
Orpheus and Eurydice. Over the years, he admits, as he was working
on the 13 movies on his resume, including ``Bye-Bye Brazil'' and
``Xica da Silva,'' images of what a Brazilian version of the myth
would look and sound like constantly filled his imagination. Now,
after more than 40 years of dreams, delays and dashed hopes, his
persistence has paid off: ``Orfeu'' is showing in Brazilian
theaters and may be released later by Warner Bros. in the United
States. By Larry Rohter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAUNTING-FILM (Nicasio, Calif.) _ ``The Haunting,'' directed by
Jan De Bont, is the second film adaptation of Shirley Jackson's
novel ``The Haunting of Hill House''(Robert Wise directed a 1963
version), and once again Hill House is meant to sound as
frightening as it looks. From its eerie opening scenes, ``The
Haunting,'' set to open on July 23, is layered with the sounds of
inhuman conversations _ between wood and air, between stone and
glass, and between an evil entity and its tormented victims. By
Justine Elias. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTURO-UI-THEATER (Undated) _ Next month, the renowned German
troupe Berliner Ensemble will bring the production of Bertolt
Brecht's ``The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui'' to Berkeley and Los
Angeles. Brecht's drama, a parable about the rise of the Nazis,
thinly disguised as Mafiosi and gang members (the characters Giri
and Givola are Goering and Goebbels), will be presented in a
successful 1995 production by the company's director Heiner Muller
who died that same year. By Anne Midgette. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JONES/ZANE-DANCE (Riverside, Calif.) _ History has neglected
Arnie Zane, co-founder of the Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance
Company. His partnership with Jones produced the paradigmatic
post-modern repertory of the 1980s, but after his death from AIDS
in 1988 and the notoriety of Jones's subsequent career, Zane faded
into a shadow legend, invoked less as artistic innovator than
tragic hero. Paradoxically, it is an exhibition of Zane's
photography _ a solo pursuit predating his entry into dance via
Jones _ that promises to revive Zane the choreographer. By Ann
Daly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BMG-DIGITAL-CDS (Undated) _ BMG's new High Performance series at
the bargain price of $12 per CD promises digital revelation for
classic recordings from deep within the vault of RCA Victor Red
Seal. The new project, headed by a veteran engineer, Nathaniel S.
Johnson, is something of a higher-tech sequel to BMG's compact disk
revival of the RCA ``Living Stereo'' series, which helped to launch
stereophonic sound in the late 1950s and early 60s. By Lawrence B.
Johnson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALCIDE-OPERA (Undated) _ In a new recording, a group of singers
and instrumentalists from Lviv in newly independent Ukraine has
lovingly resurrected ``Alcide,'' an opera by Dmitri Bortniansky, a
distinguished native of the Ukrainian village of Glukhov who never
thought of himself as a Ukrainian, and who spent most of his life
trying to forget he ever saw the place. Bortniansky wrote
``Alcide'' to an Italian text by the great librettist Pietro
Metastasio during his apprentice years in Bologna, where he was
studying at the expense of the German-born, French-speaking Russian
Empress Catherine the Great. Performed in Venice (once only) in
1778, when the composer was 27, the score now rests in the British
Library. By Richard Taruskin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ After 500 years of denying the country's
Hispanic hue, the Anglo-Saxon United States is recognizing its
darker cousin. And one way Americans are doing so is by consuming
Latin culture, especially its music. By Peter Watrous.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER-LOPEZ-ALBUM (New York) _ The title of the actress
Jennifer Lopez's recently released debut album, ``On the Six,''
reflects the cross-cultural experience of her formative years, the
record presents a polished urban mix of Latin, rhythm-and-blues and
soul-tinged ballads and dance numbers, with most of the songs in
English but a few in Spanish. By Guy Garcia. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-STARCK-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ New York is witnessing a
small invasion of major French talent. Earlier this year, Philippe
Starck, the most gifted designer of his generation, moved to New
York. If this town cared as much about design as it does about
baseball, there would have been a ticker tape parade in his honor.
Even if Starck does no more than remodel a few extra Ian Schrager
hotels, his relocation here is an important cultural event. By
Herbert Muschamp. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MAY-STEVENS-ART (Boston) _ May Stevens, artist, activist and
daughter of Alice Stevens and subject of the show ``May Stevens:
Images of Women Near and Far'' is at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts
through Aug. 8. A show of Ms. Stevens's drawings and prints is on
view concurrently at the Mary Ryan Gallery in New York through Aug.
27. By Ken Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-METRO-ANTIQUES (Bilbao, Spain) _ The giant caterpillerlike
entrances to the Metro, this city's subway system, are made of
glass ribbed with steel and alive with light. Symbols of a city
reborn, they beckon riders with their sparkle by day, their glow by
night, all part of the design signature of the British architect
Lord Norman Foster, the winner this year of the Pritzker
Architecture Prize. By Rita Reif.
</P>
