<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS LAWYERS RENEW ATTACK ON FORMER MISTRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros
produced documents in federal court Tuesday showing that his former
mistress planned to ``aggressively market'' taped telephone
conversations for television publicity and possibly a book and
movie deal.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Linda Jones, denied knowledge of any book or movie
offers, but admitted that her attorneys hired a Dallas public
relations specialist to place in the media her story about her
extramarital affair and financial arrangement with Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two attorneys thought the case should be generating more
money,'' said Jones, formerly known by her married name Linda
Medlar.
</P>
<P>
   Jones testified she received $15,000 for an interview with
television show ``Inside Edition'' and signed an agreement that
would give attorneys Floyd Holder and Bruce Magness, both of
Lubbock, Texas, a 25 percent share in any book or movie deals and
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were going to aggressively market the tapes and do a book
and do a movie?'' Brendan Sullivan, Cisneros' lawyer, asked during
a hearing in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were entertaining offers from television, but I
didn't know anything about a book or a movie,'' Jones replied.
</P>
<P>
   She testified for a second day in a hearing to determine whether
34 tapes of her telephone conversations with Cisneros can be
entered into evidence in the Sept. 7 conspiracy trial against
Cisneros, the second member of President Clinton's Cabinet to be
tried on ethics charges.
</P>
<P>
   Former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy was cleared in December
of 30 counts of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes form the crux of Independent Counsel David Barrett's
case against Cisneros, who is accused of orchestrating a conspiracy
with aides to conceal from the FBI $250,000 in payments to Jones.
The FBI conducted a background probe in 1993 into his nomination to
head the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros and the aides, John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia,
have pleaded not guilty to the charges that carry a maximum
sentence of five years upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros and the aides did not attend the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan attacked Jones's credibility after she told District
Judge Stanley Sporkin that she erased portions of the tapes where
she threatened to expose Cisneros' then-unknown financial agreement
to provide her $4,000 a month after their affair ended.
</P>
<P>
   She said her lawyers, Holder and Magness, told her the threats
could prove to be trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was threats that could be termed as extortion,'' Jones said
in explaining her editing. ``It had been indicated to me that I
could get into legal problems, if there was extortion or if it
looked like extortion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones originally signed an immunity agreement with Barrett, who
yanked the deal and indicted her on 28 counts of fraud after she
lied about the origins and authenticity of the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   She pleaded guilty to those charges and is currently serving a 3
1/2-year sentence in the Carswell Federal Medical Center, a prison
facility in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Jones agreed to testify for the government against Cisneros in
exchange for a reduction in her sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a nightmare for you personally?'' Sullivan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, now 50, admitted the case has been a hardship on her, a
daughter and other family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get back to your daughter, understandably, don't
you?'' Sullivan asked her.
</P>
<P>
   His questions were an attempt to raise doubts about her motives
for taping Cisneros and to paint her as selfish and greedy for
seeking money while Cisneros' newborn son, John Paul, was in need
of heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Paul's illness haunted Henry Cisneros, didn't it?''
Sullivan continued.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros made the affair public in 1988, when he was mayor of
San Antonio and a promising Democratic Party prospect for higher
office.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure of the affair forced Jones into a hospital where she
became dependent on an anti-depressant medicine. She underwent
detoxification while in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 52, was HUD secretary from 1993 to 1996. He is
currently president of the Los Angeles-based, Spanish-language
television network Univision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Cisneros became aware of her drug dependency during
counseling sessions that Cisneros paid for with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get through this with our relationship in tact,''
she told the court.
</P>
<P>
   Both had contemplated divorce when the affair was disclosed.
Jones was divorced by husband, Stan Medlar, a San Antonio jeweler,
and Cisneros separated from his wife, Mary Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she was irate when she read in the press that
Cisneros, following gallbladder surgery in Houston, announced he
and Mary Alice had reconciled. Jones said he was then living at her
San Antonio home.
</P>
<P>
   The taping began when Cisneros was entertaining an offer to join
Clinton's Cabinet in 1993. She said she feared Cisneros would skip
out on their souring relationship and his financial pledge to
support her.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she first concealed the authenticity of the tapes and
her editing of sensitive topics, on the advice of Holder and
Magness, who were her attorneys in a civil suit against Cisneros
for breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   After deleting passages she deemed hurtful to her case, Jones
made a second set of tapes that she palmed off as the originals to
FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   She also misled Internal Revenue Service agents and prosecutors
for the independent counsel's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Jones appeared collected when she recalled the web she created
with repeated lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like getting yourself into a box and not knowing how to
get of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is expected to continue his cross-examination when the
hearing continues Wednesday. Cisneros' lawyers also plan to call a
government tape expert to testify all the tapes have been tampered
with.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin rejected Tuesday a second request by Cisneros's lawyer
Barry Simon to close the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just be improper to close the hearing. I see no basis
for it,'' the judge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
