<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO COMMANDER WANTS KOSOVO DEPLOYMENT ACCELERATED, POSSIBLY
INCREASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ With acts of violence and retribution
continuing in Kosovo, NATO's senior commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
said Tuesday that the allies should speed up the deployment of
their troops to the Serbian province and suggested that more than
the 50,000 peacekeepers originally planned might be needed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's force in Kosovo now includes 19,500 soldiers, and it is
growing by 1,000 a day. But the NATO-led troops are still
confronted with sporadic killings and worsening confrontations
between ethnic Albanians and Serbs in cities and villages across
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who visited Macedonia on Tuesday with President Clinton,
called upon the NATO allies to move more quickly to flood Kosovo
with peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am calling on NATO governments to accelerate the arrival of
the troops to the greatest possible extent,'' he said in an
interview with Reuters. ``There are not enough troops in there
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said there was ``room for more,'' but he emphasized that
the priority now was to send in the troops already promised.
</P>
<P>
   The general could not be reached Tuesday night to expand upon
his comments.
</P>
<P>
   He had repeatedly pressed for more aggressive action in NATO's
air war against Yugoslavia, sometimes to the annoyance of the
United States and other NATO members. And his remarks Tuesday
underscored the volatility that remains in Kosovo and the
difficulty NATO is having controlling it.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO troops have become increasingly visible in Kosovo's
major cities, especially the capital, Pristina, many smaller, more
remote villages racked by tensions between returning Albanian
Kosovar refugees and the remaining Serbs have yet to see more than
occasional patrols.
</P>
<P>
   In Mitrovica, Serbs have declared a ``Serbian zone'' from the
city north to the border with the rest of Serbia and are blocking
Albanians from returning to their homes. French soldiers have
failed to defuse the situation. Their commanders acknowledged that
they are handicapped by the fact that their entire contingent has
not yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The war ended before NATO had assembled its entire peacekeeping
forces in Macedonia and Albania. In the last weeks of the war,
Clark advocated moving more quickly to build up the force so that
it would be ready to move in, but Only about 15,000 troops had
arrived by the time Serbia accepted NATO's terms.
</P>
<P>
   Even in towns where NATO troops have been deployed, like Grace,
there have been repeated scenes of Albanians looting and burning
the homes of Serbs who have fled.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, the NATO commander in Kosovo, Lt.
Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain, appealed for calm. ``The important
thing is to reduce tensions through maintaining a physical
presence,'' he said when asked about the situation in Grace in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days after the first NATO troops poured into Kosovo,
Britain has by far the most troops deployed, with 8,500. The United
States now has 3,500, roughly half the 7,000 the Clinton
administration pledged. The other major allies have been slower to
build up. Germany and Italy each have about 2,000 troops at this
point, but they control sectors in the western part of the
province, where the worst destruction occurred. France, which
controls the northwest, has 1,700 troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have said it could be the end of July before the
entire force of 50,000 arrives, joined by some 3,600 Russians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
