</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MACEDONIA, CLINTON HEARS REFUGEES' TALES OF HORROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVEC CAMP, Macedonia _ In the shadow of Kosovo, President
Clinton on Tuesday came to meet face-to-face with the people on
whose behalf he had fought the war. He heard their stories of
brutality and vowed that he would help make their homeland safe.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to this muddy refugee camp, now emptying at the rate
of more than 1,000 people a day, was planned while the NATO air
attacks were at their peak and an end to the war seemed far away.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, this camp, the first established in Macedonia and
once overflowing with 30,000 refugees, was in the throes of closing
down and in several weeks will most likely be an empty,
trash-strewn field.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could have made this visit a stirring conclusion to a
conflict that caught the imagination at home only fitfully but
represented survival to the Albanian Kosovars who escaped Serbian
brutality to find shelter here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, standing on a crude wooden box and without the
trappings of the White House podium, Clinton spoke in muted tones
to a crowd of several hundred refugees, their faces now brighter at
the prospect of going home, though often to homes burned and looted
by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed not only to making Kosovo safe but to helping
people rebuild their lives, rebuild their communities and then
helping Kosovo and all the countries of the region,'' he said
during his speech of a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who was here in
May, and their daughter Chelsea, the president visited a selected
group of refugees whose well-spruced tents were at the entrance to
the camp. He heard first-hand a version of a story that had been
told repeatedly on television and newspapers since nearly 1 million
Albanian Kosovars were forced over the borders in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Idriz Macastena, 29, his wife, Nerimane, 26, with their son,
Besart, 4, described their escape from their home near Podujevo, in
northern Kosovo, soon after the NATO bombing started.
</P>
<P>
   Macastena described how they fled to a nearby village in the
mountains, and then how, as they tried to leave in a convoy of cars
and tractors for Pristina, the capital, the Serbs attacked. ``Sixty
people were massacred,'' Macastena said.
</P>
<P>
   In his account to reporters, before Clinton arrived, Macastena,
a carpenter, said the Serbs took one man from each of the vehicles
in the second half of the convoy and killed them.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching Pristina, Macastena told Clinton, his family
stayed for five weeks. Yugoslav army soldiers surrounded the
building where they were staying, he said, beat many of the
Albanian Kosovars and threatened their son, Besart, with a knife
and a lighted cigarette held to his neck.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Clinton told Macastena's wife, Nerimane, that her son
_ decked out in clean white jeans and a vest for the occasion _ was
a ``beautiful boy,'' the mother replied: ``He's still very much
afraid. He has suffered very much. He has seen people killed and
wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the refugees at the camp, some of the Macastena
family had already returned to Kosovo, the couple told the
Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the refugees, Clinton had other business here: dealing
with the leaders of Macedonia whose country was economically
battered by the war. Clinton met with President Kiro Gligorov and
pledged, as Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had done 10 days
before, that the West would help restore the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced a gift of $12 million in food commodities,
assistance that some officials described as modest given the
dramatic economic decline here and the attention paid by Clinton's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said clothing manufacturer Liz Claiborne would reopen
Macedonian factories so that 2,000 to 3,000 Macedonians could work
again.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 2.2 million, Macedonia took care of some
300,000 Albanian Kosovar refugees during the war, a burden that
threatened the ethnic balance between the Slav majority and the
Albanian minority. Macedonia's trade, largely dependent on
transportation through Serbia, was decimated by the war and there
were concerns that the fledgling democracy would be seriously
destabilized.
</P>
<P>
   For this high price, Gligorov has been asking for a big reward
from the United States _ membership in NATO and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Gligorov has been publicly skeptical of Washington's promises of
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Gligorov, a former Communist who serves with a young reformer,
Prime Minister Ljubcho Georgievski, on Tuesday boasted of
Macedonia's resilience under the pressure of the last three months,
and reiterated, in front of Clinton, his request for NATO and
European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
