<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-MEN-BOS &LR;      06-22 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRISLY FIND IN FLORIDA POND RESOLVES MYSTERY OF MISSING MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER AND DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTLEBORO, Mass. _ They were three buddies on vacation in the
sun, blue-collar bachelors who jumped into a shiny sport-utility
vehicle near Disney World last fall and vanished without a trace.
Until now.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the $5,000 reward, Internet bulletins, the powers of
a pyschic, and aerial searches did not matter. Scott Renquin, 35,
Dan Nelson, 32, and Roger DesVergnes, 31, did not disappear into
some mysterious mist.
</P>
<P>
   The Attleboro men apparently died in 16 feet of water, their
1999 GMC Jimmy upside down in a man-made retention pond near a bend
in the road in an affluent Florida community called Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just find it hard to believe they couldn't get out of the
car,'' said Paul Renquin, Scott's brother. ``Were they all knocked
out or something? My brother was a SCUBA diver. These were all
strong guys. It boggles my mind that they couldn't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Their families, who tried unsuccessfully to drain themselves of
grief over nine months of uncertainty, are not waiting for
authorities to positively identify the three bodies found in the
same truck Renquin rented at the Orlando airport last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning we had a little bit of hope,'' said Roxanne
DesVergnes, whose brother was the father of three. ``We tried to
encourage each other with anything we thought was positive. But we
needed to have the closure for the kids' benefit. They now know
that their dad is in a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida authorities expect to be able to positively identify the
three men as early as Wednesday through dental records shipped from
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of the submerged truck late Monday capped a
nine-month ordeal for friends and relatives of the men, who shared
a love of the water and outdoor adventure. The men left behind $200
worth of burgers and beers, hot dogs and chips in the
pink-and-white Orlando time-share apartment of which Renquin was
part owner.
</P>
<P>
   As far as investigators can tell, the three men made plans on
Sept. 28 to get together two days later with a boyhood friend of
Renquin's, now living in an Orlando suburb. They were never heard
from again.
</P>
<P>
   Police do not know how the men found themselves on the long
country road to Celebration, a planned community opened by Disney
in 1994, but investigators said Tuesday they might have gotten lost
looking for an on-ramp to Interstate 4.
</P>
<P>
   The posted speed limit is 35 mph, but motorists usually drive
faster, and if they miss the turn could end up in the water. Police
have received a number of complaints, including one that led
Orlando police to ask for a search of the pond, which is in the
neighboring county of Osceola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from a dentist who said he was driving along
talking to his wife when he realized he'd missed the turn and
nearly skidded over the curb and into the pond,'' said Detective
Barbara Bergin, the lead investigator. ``He suggested we search the
pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Police had pulled at least eight automobiles out of the pond, an
isolated spot favored as a dumping place for car thieves, in the
last six months without ever sighting the GMC Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   The Attleboro victims' SUV jumped the curb with enough speed
that it settled to the bottom about 100 feet from the water's edge.
``The driver may have fallen asleep, and when someone falls asleep
at the wheel, the vehicle starts to accelerate,'' said Sgt. Darryl
Farrar of the Orlando Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the SUV's air bags did not deploy. ``We may
never know who was driving because none of the men was wearing a
seatbelt and the bodies were out of their seats,'' said Lt. Chuck
Williams of the Florida Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   DesVergnes, who ran a small construction company in Attleboro
and was engaged to be married this autumn, suddenly stopped his
daily phone calls that delivered details back home such as the
quality of his lamb-chop dinner or that afternoon's adventure on
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a free-spirited guy and a loving father,'' said
Paulette Rioux, his sister. ``He'd give you the shirt off his back.
Your priorities were his priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a machinist who worked in Rhode Island, put in overtime
to support his 5-year-old son who lived with him. He had been
expected at his sister's nuptials in Warwick, R.I., on Oct. 4, two
days after the Florida trip was to have concluded. When he missed
the Oct. 3 rehearsal dinner and then the wedding, where his son
served as ringbearer, his family became alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Renquin, who ran an auto body business and was certified pilot
and a Mr. Fix-it type, left behind a note in his Attleboro
apartment which read: ``If anything happens to me when I'm away,
then everything I own is to be left to my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past months, as his family worked to dissolve his
business and rental property, they've learned the note has legal
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Renquin said the news of his brother's death will help
silence some of the demons he's lived with since Scott Renquin
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up once in the middle of the night just bawling,'' he
said. ``I had this dream that Scott walked into my house. He came
into the kitchen and sat down. I walked over to one of the counters
and backed up to it. He's sitting there and I look down at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Scott, how's Florida?' And he looked up at me
with the scariest look and all of a sudden he was gone. He just
vanished.''
</P>
<P>
   Along a rural stretch of Lindsey Road, an enclave of sorts for
the DesVergnes family whose members live in separate homes there,
family members spoke of dreams, too, when Roger would once again
take his place at family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just glad that we finally know,'' said Roxanne
DesVergnes, who said she's troubled by lingering questions. ``Now,
they're building a stone wall which wasn't there at the time of the
accident. We'd like to get some questions answered. Obviously, this
was a bad curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Those questions were being posed in Florida Tuesday, too, where
a spokeswoman for the Celebration Company, the Disney subsidiary
that is developing the land there, said the company is no more free
to make changes to a county road than any other citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have plans for walls, fencing and landscaping,'' said
Marilyn Waters, Celebration's director of communications, but those
plans have to work there way through the standard approval and
permitting processes.
</P>
<P>
   Waters took exception to broadcast reports that Disney had
hampered police searches of the pond. It was about two months ago
that investigators first decided to search the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the Osceola County Fire-Rescue Department said the
two-month delay was due to staffing shortages caused by wildfires
that have burned about 1 million acres in Florida since last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless it's an emergency, we have to think about our overtime
budget,'' said one Osceola fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Jordana Hart contributed to this story from
Massachusetts. Globe correspondent Brad Liston contributed from
Florida.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
