<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOSING-IT-COX     06-22 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSING-IT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MELT DOWN: Mysteriously, the skills vanish _ an athlete's worst
nightmare
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When you live in the Australian city of Sanctuary
Cove, your world is supposed to be serene. The city's name conjures
up images of a safe haven, a real-life utopia unsullied by
real-world problems. By reputation, it is a place to retreat, soak
up some sun and solace and toss another shrimp on the barbee, a
place where neighbors prefer to discuss nothing more serious than
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Sanctuary Cove is all those things to Ian
Baker-Finch, whose golf game deteriorated so disastrously after his
1991 British Open championship that he walked away from the sport
almost five years later at age 37.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not able to walk away from the persistent questions:
How could Baker-Finch and other athletes like him, who spent years
developing finely tuned mechanics, unravel in a moment's notice?
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch can't speak for everyone; he still doesn't have the
answer for his own problem: He cannot hit a golf ball anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, you're the last one to see (the problems)
coming,'' he said. ``Maybe it's just a classic rationalization, but
you always believe the next swing is going to be the one that pulls
you out of it. Instead, it's more like quicksand. The harder you
try to break out of it, the faster it pulls you down. You feel like
you're alone, simply trying to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The quick demise of Baker-Finch might be the extreme. But
examples of professional athletes who hit the psychological wall _
one day the game is there; the next day it's gone _ appear to be on
the increase.
</P>
<P>
   It was graphically demonstrated recently by the decline of
former Atlanta Braves pitcher Mark Wohlers, whose rehabilitation
attempt has been painful to watch. But the disintegration of
Wohlers, who got the last out in the franchise's only World Series
championship in 1995, is just one of many sports meltdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Blass pitched a complete-game victory for the Pittsburgh
Pirates in the seventh game of the 1971 World Series and two years
later couldn't throw a strike.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Sax spent 14 major-league seasons playing second base
for four different teams, but he went through a stretch with the
Los Angeles Dodgers in which he couldn't make the simple throw to
first base.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Buffalo Bills kicker Scott Norwood missed the potential
game-winning field goal in the last seconds of Super Bowl XXV. A
year after he pushed a 47-yard attempt wide right, he was released.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Braves standout Dale Murphy was moved from catcher to
the outfield, in part because he couldn't throw the ball back to
the pitcher. Asked about the strange aversion, Murphy still
couldn't offer an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Atlanta Falcons used a third-round draft choice on
Appalachian State punter Harold Alexander in 1993. Alexander
averaged a nifty 43.3 yards as a rookie, fell off to 39.9 yards the
following season and by 1995 was back home in Pickens, S.C., his
confidence shattered beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who should have lasted 10 or 12 years in the
league and been a Pro Bowl (punter),'' former Falcons special teams
coach Bobby April said. ``After he got past that first training
camp and all the harassment he got from Jerry Glanville, he should
have been OK. But instead he went south. I mean, just like that, it
all disappeared. For me, it might always be one of the all-time
mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the drop from excellent to eccentric is so dramatic in
such cases, it often is blamed as much on the player's mind as on
his mechanics. As a result, the role of sports psychologist, once a
sideline, has expanded tremendously. More than half of the NFL's 31
teams list a team psychologist in their directory.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them deal primarily with such matters as career
counseling and IQ tests. But a few are forced to confront and treat
the kinds of career collapses suffered by Baker-Finch and Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you are, you're usually stepping into tough
territory, mostly because of who you're dealing with,'' said Robert
Crowley, a clinical psychologist who helped salvage Sax's career in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popular perception of the professional athlete is that of
a hardened person,'' Crowley said. ``The truth is, they take their
problems even harder than most 'civilians' would. It's hard for
them to accept something is wrong. A lot of times, the simplest
explanation is rendered complex because there's such ego involved.
It's a tricky deal, sometimes, trying to get to the nut of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists and players agree that the cases of players who
suddenly lose effectiveness are different from those who have
battled long phobias. Shaquille O'Neal, for instance, never has
been a strong free-throw shooter, so his annual shortcomings at the
foul line probably don't affect him as much. Had he been a 75
percent foul shooter who suddenly couldn't hit 50 percent, the
situation would be different.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Crowley said, the problem is not identified and just
goes away. When former Rookie of the Year Sax arrived in Crowley's
office in 1983 _ midway through a season in which he committed a
league-high 30 errors, more than half of them on throwing miscues _
he was more than just another patient in denial. Sax, 23, was a
high-profile performer in a town filled with celebrities, and his
career was collapsing around him.
</P>
<P>
   Sax, now a Fox Sports analyst, offered an emotional assessment
of Wohlers' problems during an on-air appearance last month. He
said his emotions for Wohlers' plight went way beyond sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been through something similar, it's more like
empathy,'' he said. ``To have the rug pulled out on you like that,
it's a tough thing. When you've experienced it, then it's even
harder to watch from afar. (Steve) Blass and I have discussed it.
We agree that it's hard for most people to understand how you can
have it all going for you one minute and, poof, it's gone the next
minute. It's an ego-deflating experience, let me tell you. If
there's no one to help you, going it alone is devastating. You
really do become a head case.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lufton, a Long Island psychologist who has treated several
athletes, said that people who earn a living with their bodies
characteristically overreact to any kind of physical dysfunction.
The slightest hint of faulty technique, he said, can trigger all
sorts of insecurities. As the mechanical problems persist, the
player loses confidence and treats every appearance as a must-win
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to succeed is intense enough to begin with,''
Lufton said. ``For a guy who is going bad, whose confidence is
sliding, it increases exponentially with every bad outing. Just as
with any profession, different guys react different ways to
pressure. But for an athlete, hitting the wall tends to be a more
humbling thing than it would be for, maybe, a construction worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people whose lives revolve around esteem,'' Lufton
said, ``losing the confidence of your teammates and then your own
self-esteem is a terrible thing to try and handle.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first six years of his NFL career, Norwood converted
74.2 percent of his field-goal attempts. After missing the kick
that would have given Buffalo a 22-20 victory over the New York
Giants in Super Bowl XXV, Norwood retreated to his home in Virginia
and declined all interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   The following year in training camp, he talked only in
generalities about the miss, then made 18 of 29 field goal tries,
62.1 percent, during the 1991 season. The Bills signed free-agent
Steve Christie the next spring, and Norwood never kicked in another
NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ancient history,'' Norwood said recently. ``(It's) not
worth dredging up.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Baker-Finch won at Royal Birkdale with weekend rounds
of 64 and 66, including birdies on five of the first seven holes on
Sunday and a front-side score of 29.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a stretch in which Baker-Finch failed to make a single
cut on the American tour for three consecutive years. In a two-year
period, he averaged $76 per tournament. His driver abandoned him
and he put more pressure on his short game. It became an agonizing
struggle. After the 1995 British Open, Baker-Finch lost his will to
keep trying.
</P>
<P>
   While he refuses to use the word retirement to define his
current status, Baker-Finch is content to deal with his several
businesses in Australia, do commentary for television and
occasionally try again to understand what happened to him.
Resignation has replaced remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody, no matter what they do for a living, has had a run
where things didn't go right for them,'' he said. ``But when you're
out there on center stage, with the whole world watching you fall
apart _ that's a shattering experience, a helpless feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
