A5655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-PARTNERS-CO     06-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PARTNERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth watches as Qwest battles for deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. again stands at the edge of the ring,
watching others tussle and holding back from a leap into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The $23 billion-a-year Atlanta-based regional phone company sat
in the stands during one huge telecom merger after another. Now, it
is Qwest Communications struggling to keep its $55 billion bid
alive for U S West and Frontier Communications, both of which are
on record as preferring a competing offer from Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest, which has seen its stock pummeled since launching the
dual-takeover attempt, on Tuesday urged U S West to talk.
Meanwhile, Qwest continued lining up loans that would let it add
enough cash to force a conversation and worked Wall Street to lobby
for the plan. Qwest Chief Executive Joseph Nacchio also argued in a
letter to his targets that the Qwest offer is superior, especially
given a drop in Global Crossing stock.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth could conceivably plop enough cash on the table to
send Global Crossing home but has held itself aloof. And But
BellSouth does have a dog in this fight: The company this year
bought 10 percent of Denver-based Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth was apparently ambivalent about Nacchio making a run
at the two companies. Now, BellSouth has a stake in the outcome _
win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has long passed up the chance to bid on U S West, a
less-profitable Bell with a sparser region and a reputation for
customer service trouble.Because BellSouth put money into Qwest
looking for long-distance and high-speed lines, why buy Frontier?
</P>
<P>
   A successful Qwest bid will not only dilute BellSouth's
ownership, it will create a company of nearly equal size _ perhaps
big enough to buy BellSouth. BellSouth has long argued that bigger
is not always better, that what matters is value. Has anything
changed?
</P>
<P>
   Only the landscape. A series of deals has raised the specter of
a global industry dominated by a handful of ``supercarriers.''
Linked with a bulked-up Qwest, BellSouth might be muscular enough
to challenge the likes of AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Bell Atlantic _ if
that's what BellSouth wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boils down to whether BellSouth sees itself as needing to
expand its scope, and that would be contrary to their philosophy up
to now,'' said Boyd Peterson, analyst with the Yankee Group.
``BellSouth has exhibited more restraint than its brethren. The
larger question is where they see themselves 10 years from now, and
that's the harder question.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has pegged much of its planning on delivery of
high-speed data. Qwest has added some juice to that strategy by
investing in RhythmsNet Connections Inc. and Covad Communications,
which also offer high-speed lines.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's $3.5 billion current investment in Qwest has shrunk
by about $1 million, thanks to the drop in Qwest stock. That could
be a positive, since the cost of buying all of Qwest has also
fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, if Qwest stock continues to dip, it's a bargain,''
Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Network World has reported that Qwest has been in merger talks
with BellSouth, a rumor that BellSouth will not confirm. A deal for
all of Qwest has been discounted because BellSouth and U S West _
like other regional Bells _ are still not permitted to offer
long-distance service in their regions. But Qwest has promised not
to offer long-distance in the U S West region should that deal go
through.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest could take the same pledge for the Southeast, said Mel
Marten, analyst at Edward Jones &AMP; Co. ``BellSouth could buy Qwest,
as long as they didn't offer long-distance service.''
</P>
<P>
   A purchase of Qwest could short-circuit discussion about U S
West and Frontier, companies in which BellSouth sees relatively
little strategic value. Qwest stock closed at $35.31 1/4 a share.
At that price, the 90 percent BellSouth does not own is worth about
$22.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
