<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER BANKS NEXT, MERGER WATCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Now that New England's largest banks have morphed into
a heavyweight contender and a robust regional player, scores of
smaller institutions from Massachusetts to Maine are rethinking
their futures.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers are not just for banks with hundreds of billions of
dollars in assets, and smaller banks are likely to see a flurry of
combinations in coming years, industry observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability that many of these smaller banks are going to
survive in their current form is slim,'' said Stanley Wells, a vice
chairman at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, an investment bank that
specializes in financial services.
</P>
<P>
   The logic that will send local community institutions into each
other's arms or force mergers of New England's two-dozen
billion-dollar banks is familiar.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the savings and loan crisis and the dismantling of
restrictive interstate banking laws helped spark a first round of
consolidation. More recently, mergers in the financial services
industry have been fueled by drives to cut costs and gain market
share amid fierce competition. Such an eat-or-be-eaten philosophy,
which has spawned ever bigger banks, led Citizens Financial Group
to snap up US Trust on Monday, three months after Fleet Financial
Group paired with BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   But the circumstances facing New England banks as they reassess
their positions have a particular cast.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty over who will own the assets that Fleet and
BankBoston are selling as part of their mega-combination into a
$160 billion institution is keeping many smaller banks on
tenterhooks. Local institutions want to know who is going to own
those deposits, branches, and loans _ nearly $14 billion worth _
before they ponder any deals.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are also concerned that the region's latest deal has
removed two prominent buyers from the acquisition ring, at least
for now. Citizens, now a $28-billion bank, is likely to be so busy
digesting US Trust and making a grab for the Fleet-BankBoston
assets that it may not be interested in buying more banks, bank
advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for People's Heritage Financial Group of Portland,
Maine, which recently bought Banknorth Group of Burlington, Vt. to
form a $17 billion bank and become the other mid-size bank in the
region, with the new Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors that will figure in future mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Many attractive banks, like the $9.9 billion People's Mutual
Holding Co. of Bridgeport, Conn., are mutuals, meaning that they
are owned by depositors and cannot easily be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Some mutuals, like the $1.9 billion Seacoast Financial Services
in New Bedford, have recently become publicly traded companies,
with listed shares that could make a transaction easier. But such a
conversion process usually leaves a bank off-limits to a merger for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks, including People's Heritage, are relatively big but
are focused on slow-growth markets like Vermont. And hundreds are
old-fashioned savings banks, with only a few branches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some companies are already in play. New England Community
Bancorp, an $803 million bank based in Windsor, Conn., said
recently that it was in talks with potential suitors.
</P>
<P>
   James Moynihan, a senior vice president at stock brokerage
Advest Inc., is so certain that consolidation will accelerate in
coming years that he is creating a mutual fund-like product to
invest in stocks of smaller regional banks that he considers likely
to participate in mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Topping his list are Cape Cod Bank &AMP; Trust Co., a $1.8 billion
bank based in South Yarmouth.; the $1.6 billion Independent Bank
Corp. of Rockland; and Westbank Corp., a $355 million bank in West
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England is totally overbanked, and I think we're going to
see a lot of deals before the year's end,'' Moynihan said. He said
new accounting rules that take effect next year will make mergers
more difficult and more costly, creating pressure to complete deals
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to other areas, the six-state New England region has
more than 400 banks _ including 240 in Massachusetts _ with less
than $1 billion in deposits, a size that some observers consider a
cutoff point for qualifying as a community bank.
</P>
<P>
   Banks with less than $5 billion in assets control nearly one
quarter of the $233 billion in deposits held by all New England
banks, according to the Massachusetts Bankers Association, a trade
group. In a world where the nation's biggest bank, BankAmerica, has
more than $570 billion in assets, those deposits would collectively
constitute a single regional bank.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of what designs the big players
outside New England have upon the region. Giant banks are
scrambling to win a toehold through the Fleet-BankBoston
divestiture _ the largest in banking history _ and could eventually
even push to acquire Fleet-BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any significant out-of-region presence here,''
said Warren Heller, president of Veribanc Inc., a bank analysis
firm. ``There's probably someone out there who wants to capture
some of New England's rich store of banks.''
</P>
<P>
   But big players could conceivably eye the region's smaller,
billion-dollar banks, too. Indeed, of the nation's 50 biggest banks
in 1985, only 15 are still standing, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep that in mind,'' he added, ``when you speculate on the
fate of those $1 billion to $1 billion commercial banks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
