<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES PRICES FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices for Treasuries fell Tuesday as corporate
borrowers prepared to sell about $10 billion in debt. Traders and
analysts also said that expectations continued to weigh on the
market that the Federal Reserve will increase short-term rates at
its two-day policy meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day, the yield on the benchmark
30-year bond stayed above 6 percent as market participants had more
reasons to sell securities than to buy them. The supply of debt
easily outstripped demand and the government and corporate issuers
came to market at the same time and found themselves competing for
cash.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of the New York cash market, the yield on the
30-year bond was 6.06 percent, up from 6.02 percent on Monday; its
price, which moves in the opposite direction, fell 15/32, to 88
31/32.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Credit Co., Avis Rent a Car and other companies are
getting ready this week to sell debt before the Fed raises
short-term rates. Typically, underwriters issuing corporate debt
sell Treasuries from their portfolios as a hedge until their
corporate deals are done _ and thus put the Treasuries market under
pressure. After the corporate deals are completed, the securities
firms then buy back Treasuries and return them to their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is expected to sell $3 billion to $6 billion worth of debt
in blocks to international investors. Neither the precise size nor
the timing of the sale have been set, but traders expect the deal
to occur this week.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Jones, an economist with Briefing.com, a market analysis
firm in Burlingame, Calif., said that the coming corporate and
government issues had the bond market focusing on the lack of
demand and higher rates. ``So with the Fed close to raising
short-term rates, it's not surprising why no one wants to step up
and buy new supply.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Treasury sold $10 billion of a new 52-week bill,
and it will auction $15 billion of a new two-year note Wednesday.
By late in the afternoon the note was being offered at a price to
yield 5.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill auction Tuesday was described as mediocre at best, with
the bills awarded at a rate of 4.89 percent, worse than expected.
The bid-to-cover ratio, or the number of bids compared with the
amount being sold, was 2.6 to 1, only marginally better than the
ratio last month but far less than the average ratio of 3.14 to 1
for the last 12 auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries were also being hurt by concern that the dollar may
decline in the coming months. This concern came after the release
earlier this month of figures that showed the Japanese economy grew
a greater-than-expected 1.9 percent in the first quarter. A weaker
dollar makes Treasury securities less appealing to international
investors who see their investments lose value when they convert
them into other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Mexico sold its first euro-denominated issue, raising
400 million euro, or about $412.6 million, through J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. and Paribas. The yield on the seven-year bond was 9.625
percent, or about 337.5 basis points more than a comparable German
government security. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage
point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
