<SLUG> BC-TIAC-PSINET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA INTERNET COMPANY BUYS INTO NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fast-growing Virginia Internet company PSINet Inc. is boosting
its presence in the Northeast, buying one of New England's oldest
and largest Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   PSINet has acquired The Internet Access Co. (TIAC) of
Woburn, &UR;  &LR; Mass., a privately-held firm that serves 33,000
individuals and businesses in Massachusetts, New Hampshire,
Connecticut, Rhode Island, New York, and New Jersey. Financial
details of the purchase were not disclosed, and calls and
electronic mail messages to TIAC officials were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement on the TIAC Web site, the company plans
to maintain offices in the New England area. TIAC will be operated
as a division of PSINet and will retain the TIAC name.
</P>
<P>
   Computer entrepreneur Tim Jackson founded TIAC in January 1994,
making it one of the first companies to sell Internet services to
homes and businesses. It rapidly became a major regional Internet
company.
</P>
<P>
   John Kraft, president of PSINet's northeast region, said TIAC is
ideally suited to his company's goal to become a leading Internet
provider in the world's top 20 markets for telecommunications
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a reputation for excellent customer service,'' said
Kraft, adding that TIAC has about 50 ``points of presence'' in the
region _ telephone numbers that allow customers to connect to the
Internet with a local phone call. The purchase of TIAC means that
PSINet customers will also be able to dial into these points of
presence, expanding PSINet's coverage area.
</P>
<P>
   PSINet plans to build an enhanced set of services around its
TIAC assets. For example, Kraft said the company plans a major
drive to sell Internet data center services in New England. A data
center operates computer systems for businesses that prefer not to
do the work themselves. Many large companies employ data centers to
run their Web sites, and Kraft expects demand for such services to
increase rapidly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
