<HEADER>
A5663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-AIRFRANCE-COX     06-22 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-AIRFRANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta calls French alliance 'terrific win'
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines' new management team, which had seen
two big strategic moves fizzle in the past 18 months, chalked up a
victory on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Leo Mullin and other executives flew home from
Paris with an exclusive 10-year marketing deal with Air France. The
two carriers said they'll add more partners by the end of the year,
creating a new global airline alliance to challenge those already
formed by rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific win,'' Mullin said in a brief phone interview
as he prepared to board an Air France flight to Atlanta after the
formal announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Air France chief Jean Cyril-Spinetta said the pact will add
about $160 million in annual revenue for each carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Air France chose Delta over rival Continental Airlines. Both
U.S. carriers had formed limited marketing pacts with the French
carrier in 1997 but were vying for a broader, exclusive deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Continental that spurned Delta's buyout bid
in early 1998, shortly after Mullin arrived at Delta. Delta later
attempted a domestic alliance with United but had to scale it back
because of pilot union snarls.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was important for Mullin and his new executive
team to close the Air France deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that they're players and are being aggressive in the
international arena,'' said Ray Neidl of ING Barings Furman Selz.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came after months of lobbying, with the Delta effort
led by Mullin and marketing chief Fred Reid, hired last year from
Lufthansa.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations got serious last fall, when Delta hosted an Air
France delegation for a secret summit at posh Amelia Island, Fla.
This spring a similar retreat was held in Cannes, France, with many
smaller meetings in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have been at this very aggressively,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has a long-standing trans-Atlantic partnership with
Swissair, Sabena and Austrian Airlines, but most analysts feel its
been outflanked by larger alliances in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Air France, with 205 planes and flights to 85 nations, is
substantially bigger than Delta's other European partners combined.
</P>
<P>
   By code-sharing, or selling seats on each other's flights,
carriers in such alliances expand their international route
offerings without actually adding flights. The alliances also
include joint frequent flier awards and other service perks, along
with shared passenger handling.
</P>
<P>
   All of it is aimed at keeping customers within the alliance
wherever they fly, in theory boosting revenue for all the partner
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Air France's big hub at Charles de Gaulle Airport offers
extensive code-share connecting possibilities in Europe and beyond.
Delta already tickets passengers on seven Air France flights to
Paris and 48 other European cities. Those offerings will be
expanded, though no details were immediately announced.
</P>
<P>
   Air France, in return, will get greater access to Delta's route
system in the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said Delta hopes to continue the Swissair alliance and
eventually incorporate it with the Air France deal. However,
Swissair on Tuesday announced it was starting code-share flights
with American, raising the possibility it will switch to the
Oneworld alliance.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, Delta's code-share operations with Swissair
and other existing European partners are unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Air France plan to bring other carriers into the deal
_ aiming especially for Latin and Asian partners _ to compete with
existing multicarrier alliances. They include the Star Alliance,
which includes United, Lufthansa and others; Wings, with Northwest,
Continental, KLM and Alitalia; and Oneworld, a tentative pact
headlined by American, British Airways and Japan Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our key goal is to create an alliance that will be competitive
with the largest and most successful,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these alliances bring is an ability to get customers more
easily from anywhere to everywhere and have them feel like they're
dealing with one airline,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Neidl said the Air France deal ``reinforces'' Delta's position
in Europe but added he believes it will remain ``the weakest among
the four major alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   However, brokerage Merrill Lynch said in a recent report that a
Delta-Air France linkup ``could be the turtle in the old fable'' if
it is well executed.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin wouldn't comment on specific carriers that might be
candidates to join the Delta-Air France alliance. One strong
possibility is Aeromexico, which already has tight ties with Delta.
Asia is a bigger question mark. Both Delta and Air France suspended
code-sharing with Korean Air Lines this year because of safety
concerns, but say they hope to revive it when KAL fixes its
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
