<HEADER>
A5665 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-METRO-ANTIQUES-     06-22 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-METRO-ANTIQUES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER METRO MEANT TO BE MEMORABLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain _ The giant caterpillerlike entrances to the
Metro, this city's subway system, are made of glass ribbed with
steel and alive with light. Symbols of a city reborn, they beckon
riders with their sparkle by day, their glow by night, all part of
the design signature of the British architect Lord Norman Foster,
the winner this year of the Pritzker Architecture Prize.
</P>
<P>
   He designed the entrances to be sheltered spaces. ``These things
have got to be protective,'' he said. ``Bilbao has an Atlantic
climate. The weather can be quite hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbaoans were so delighted with everything about the Metro and
its creator that they have dubbed the entrances ``fosteritos.''
``It has to be the ultimate compliment,'' Lord Foster said. The
entrances soon became synonymous with the Metro itself; as he put
it, ``sort of an icon.'' ``Like the entrances to the Paris Metro
that say `Paris,' these say `Bilbao,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The entrances to the subways in the two cities are radically
different, though their designs are both organic in form. In Paris,
Hector Guimard's sinuous iron flowers framing the Metro entrances,
while standing as glorious expressions of the Art Nouveau style,
are purely ornamental.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bilbao's ``fosteritos,'' with their undulating
walls washed in light, look alive and are an integral link between
the street and the subway far below. These are places where riders
enter and move swiftly to glass-walled escalators and elevators to
reach the Metro, tunneling like a worm through the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The form invites you to descend,'' Lord Foster said. ``It also
tells you about the dynamic of rising to the light.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass has been a distinguishing feature of so much of Lord
Foster's work _ most recently the new dome of the Reichstag in
Berlin. An extensive use of glass was part of the design for the
Bilbao Metro, which took first place in a 1988 competition
sponsored by the local government, the award going to Lord Foster's
firm, Foster &AMP; Partners of London. ``My first shorthand throws at
them were rectangular,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of the entrances was changed a year later; they were
rounded for greater naturalness after the Foster design team, led
by David Nelson, reviewed plans for the entire transit system.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the subway system, 18 miles, has been
completed at a cost of $400 million. The deadline for the rest is
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Metro grew out of a 1970s program of the Basque
government of Vizcaya calling for improvements in the
infrastructure and economy of Bilbao. An ancient shipbuilding and
port city, Bilbao has been an industrial center for most of this
century, falling into decline in the '60s. Today, serving a million
people, the Metro links the region's coastal villages, industrial
zone, city center and suburbs, with connections to local rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the project had presented a daunting design
challenge. Architects usually envision a building from the outside
before detailing the spaces within. But because the subway system
was largely underground, there were virtually no exterior spaces
except for the fosteritos. ``We made models using toilet paper
rolls taped together to get the feel of those underground spaces,''
Nelson said. ``We had to get used to the totally interior series of
spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these constraints, Lord Foster's modernist sensibility
is ever present in the Metro's bold structures, extravagant use of
glass and vast open spaces in the mezzanines and column-free tunnel
platforms. What excited Nelson most, he said, was when ``the space
itself would tell you how you should move in it.'' If a building
can explain itself to the people who use it, he said, it becomes
comprehensible to all, and ``you don't need a sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus getting around the Bilbao Metro is self-explanatory. ``You
enter the underground through a slot in the street,'' Nelson said.
``Next, you move to the glass-sided escalators that take riders to
the mezzanine's ticket booths and turnstiles. From there, you use
the stairs to the terrazzo-tiled subway platforms below. For the
elderly and disabled, there are ticket machines at the street
level, and elevators from there to the trains.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are signs to guide riders. Matching the color of
a Basque police officer's hat, the signs are bright orange-red with
spare white lettering, a scheme created by Otl Aicher, the German
graphics designer, shortly before his death in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem that Lord Nelson and his colleagues had
anticipated has not materialized. ``When we started 11 years ago,
the reputation of the Basques was synonymous with anarchy,'' he
said, referring to the unrest associated with the Basque separatist
struggle. ``Everybody expected the worst in Bilbao. We thought
signs of protest would erupt all over the subway system. So we made
a tremendous investment in time, energy and research to making
concrete graffiti-proof. The subway system, which opened four years
ago, is so appreciated and loved that it always seems to look
pristine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
