<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES-R     06-22 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES-RDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES RULE ON DISABILITIES IN STRING OF EMPLOYMENT DECISIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, delving into the civil rights
arena Tuesday, made it more difficult for disabled workers to claim
employment discrimination but easier for people hospitalized with
mental disabilities to return to their communities.
</P>
<P>
   In a string of employment decisions, the high court ruled that
employees and job applicants making discrimination claims must
first prove their disabilities cannot be easily alleviated.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices also ruled that the Americans with Disabilities
Act requires states to place mentally disabled people in community
settings, rather than institutions, when doctors deem it
appropriate and state resources permit it.
</P>
<P>
   With its decisions in these cases, the high court continued to
define the scope of the ADA, a 1990 federal law designed to end
discrimination against the disabled and to help historically
outcast individuals into mainstream society.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights law, however, has divided the business
community, which fears increased litigation, and disability rights
advocates ever since the measure was first debated in Congress 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also has split civil libertarians and state
governments, which fear the financial cost and public-safety risk
of releasing mentally disabled people into the community.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decisions Tuesday did little to bridge these
divides.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce hailed the Supreme
Court's employment decisions while a disability rights group
assailed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is applying a common-sense standard to the
workplace,'' said Steve Bokat, the chamber's general counsel.
``Employers make reasonable accommodations for employees who are
truly disabled, but they should not have to relax necessary
standards for employees who have common and easily correctable
ailments.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Lawyers for the Public Interest, by contrast, called
the employment rulings a blow to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court undercut Congress' desire to help people with
disabilities in their efforts to work and lead full and responsible
lives,'' said John Gresham, the group's senior litigation counsel.
``It would be far better to support people who have found ways to
overcome their impairments, rather than stripping them of legal
protection against discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's other ADA decision, clearing the way for mentally
disabled people to return to the community when appropriate, marked
a defeat for Texas Attorney General John Cornyn, who had urged the
court to give states breadth in deciding how and where mentally ill
residents will be treated.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Attorney David Kahne, a board member of the Texas
chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union, hailed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has recognized that there can be
discrimination when people are unnecessarily segregated in
institutions,'' Kahne said. ``In Texas, and particularly in
Houston, there are people in nursing homes and similar facilities
who desperately want to live in the community. This decision can
open the door.''
</P>
<P>
   In its employment decisions, the court agreed with the
employers' position that the term disability should be interpreted
narrowly to include only those physical and mental handicaps that
``substantially limit'' a major life function and cannot be
corrected. The high court also ruled that companies cannot be held
liable under the law if their decision to fire or refuse to hire a
disabled worker was in compliance with a federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also said employers may generally consider a
worker's physical and mental abilities when making employment
decisions without violating the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   In one employment ruling, the court said two airline-pilot
applicants with poor vision could be considered disabled under the
law because their affliction could be corrected with eyeglasses or
contact lenses. In another decision, the justices discounted a
fired truck driver's high blood pressure because the medical
problem could be reduced with medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person whose physical or mental impairment is corrected by
medication or other measures does not have an impairment that
presently `substantially limits' a major life activity,'' Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the majority in the pilots' case,
Sutton vs. United Air Lines Inc. ``To be sure, a person whose
physical or mental impairment is corrected by mitigating measures
still has an impairment, but if the impairment is corrected it does
not `substantially limit' a major life activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also resolved, in the employers' favor, a provision of
the ADA that prohibits companies from discriminating against a
worker or job applicant they ``regard as'' disabled. Employers are
free to consider in their employment decisions a worker's physical
and mental impairments that do not substantially limit major life
activities, the high court said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accordingly, an employer is free to decide that physical
characteristics or mental conditions that do not rise to the level
of an impairment _ such as one's height, build or singing voice _
are preferable to others, just as it is free decide that some
limiting, but not substantially limiting, impairments make
individuals less than ideally suited for a job,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor's opinion in Sutton were Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David
H. Souter, Clarence Thomas and Ruth Bader Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   But dissenting Justices John Paul Stevens and Stephen G. Breyer
said the ADA should be interpreted broadly to allow even a person
whose poor eyesight can be easily corrected to sue employers that
have allegedly refused to hire them on the basis of an ``irrational
fear and stereotype'' regarding the impairment. An employee with
glasses might not win the lawsuit, but he or she nevertheless has a
disability that is protected under the law, Stevens wrote in a
dissenting opinion Breyer joined.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, in a case brought by two hospitalized mentally
ill Georgia women seeking community treatment, said the ADA's
prohibition on discrimination favors having the mentally disabled
treated in a home rather than in an institution. Under the law,
states must provide home-based care whenever feasible and
appropriate, Ginsburg wrote in the court's majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutional placement of persons who can handle and benefit
from community settings perpetuates unwarranted assumptions that
persons so isolated are incapable or unworthy of participating in
community life,'' Ginsburg wrote. ``Confinement in an institution
severely diminishes the everyday life activities of individuals,
including family relations, social contacts, work options, economic
independence, educational advancement and cultural enrichment.''
</P>
<P>
   But hospitalization of a mentally ill person seeking community
treatment may pass ADA muster if the state concludes confinement
should continue based on the ``reasonable assessments'' of doctors,
the court said. Mentally ill patients who favor hospitalization
also retain the right to refuse to be treated in a community
setting, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Thomas said the ADA's prohibition on
``discrimination'' against the disabled does not apply to the
institutionalization of the mentally ill. The discrimination
Congress sought to redress in the ADA is disparate treatment
between mentally disabled and able-minded individuals,, not among
mentally ill people, Thomas said in a dissent Rehnquist and Scalia
joined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
