<HEADER>
A5671 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STARCK-ARCHITECTUR     06-22 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STARCK-ARCHITECTURE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPIRIT OF DECO RISES FROM THE DEAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York is witnessing a small invasion of major
French talent. Earlier this year, Philippe Starck, the most gifted
designer of his generation, moved to New York. If this town cared
as much about design as it does about baseball, there would have
been a ticker tape parade in his honor. Even if Starck does no more
than remodel a few extra Ian Schrager hotels, his relocation here
is an important cultural event.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Jean Nouvel, another radiant Parisian talent,
presented his design for a hotel-spa-movie theater complex on the
Brooklyn waterfront. Pressure from community groups may well
prevent this project from being realized. Fortunately, they have no
power to wish away the world-class quality of Nouvel's design.
</P>
<P>
   And now, due for completion on July 15, comes the LVMH Tower on
East 57th Street, between Fifth and Madison Avenues, the American
headquarters of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the maker of
luxury products whose businesses include Christian Dior, the
perfumer Guerlain, Moet Champagne and Hennessy cognac, and Louis
Vuitton leather goods.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Christian de Portzamparc, the youngest architect to
be awarded a Pritzker Architecture Prize, in association with the
Hillier Group, the 23-story office tower does the skyline a great
service. Portzamparc has reimagined the idea of Art Deco. In doing
so, he has released the city from the grip of the Dead Deco
imitations that in the 1980s began to turn New York into a theme
park version of itself.
</P>
<P>
   The building is on New York's most privileged stretch of luxury
shopping. With Chanel, Burberry and Hermes lined up in a row, the
north side of the block has long been a window shopper's dream.
Portzamparc has lifted that fantasy peep-show to new heights. The
entire facade of his building is a gigantic shop window. Here,
windows themselves are on display.
</P>
<P>
   Portzamparc has described the facade as a flower. It is safe to
assume that a shrinking violet is not what he had in mind. Though
the facade remains strictly within the boundaries set by the city
zoning code, it appears to burst forward from the perpendicular
plane of the typical curtain wall in a flourish of tapering,
origami-like folds.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of this exotic bloom is a pillbox of blue glass,
lodged on the eastern edge of the facade at the 10th-floor level.
The petals, of irregular size and contour, radiate upward in
crystalline shapes that recall a bird of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The folded segments are fashioned from extra-transparent,
so-called white glass, which has been sandblasted to produce a
pattern of clear wedges _ windows within windows (or petals within
petals). The wedges, in turn, are incised with a pattern of
delicate horizontal bands that increase in thickness toward the
top. From within, the sandblasted lines create the effect of skinny
Venetian blinds. At night, they will pick up the glow from strips
of neon tubing, set beneath one of the folds, which will radiate a
rainbow spectrum of changing colors.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the tower is a three-story glass cube, a party
space that Portzamparc calls the magic room. It's a place for
swooping grand entrances down a spiral staircase, a slice of
cinematic glamour that makes the Rainbow Room look like a caterer's
hall.
</P>
<P>
   The penthouse further elaborates an already complex facade. But
the composition is held together by an implied Z-shape that extends
the full height of the building. The shape starts at the roof,
slashes diagonally down and finishes off with the rectangular glass
frame around the entrance. Louis Vuitton wasn't the first to put
his initials all over the place. This building bears the mark of a
very tall Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you count Baroque moldings, the folded plane has few
precedents in Western architecture. It was a staple of Czech
Cubism, which flourished in Prague in the late teens and early 20s.
More recently, folding was taken up by Peter Eisenman, Wolfgang
Prix and others as an avant-garde riposte to post-modernism's
period style ornament.
</P>
<P>
   Portzamparc, however, is not a favorite of the avant-garde.
Though his 57th Street building may strike New Yorkers as cutting
edge, other architects of his generation regard him as
conservative. (Some saw the decision to award him the 1994 Pritzker
Prize as a slap at the children of '68.) Portzamparc's work is not
derived from literary theory. He never practiced Deconstruction,
whatever that was. On the contrary, one of his specialties is
mending rips in the urban fabric shredded by Parisian planners in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It may be fair to call Portzamparc an urbanist first, an
architect second. This is meant as a compliment. His designs rely
heavily on context, often by playing counterpoint to it.
Portzamparc designed LVMH's light, free-form facade to contrast
with the dark, uniform walls of the hulking IBM Building across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the Chanel Building next door, designed by Charles Platt
after Portzamparc had completed his plan, also makes an excellent
foil. With its impeccably tailored facade of granite, glass and
steel, the Chanel Building is perhaps the best of the Dead Deco
breed, a place where the ghosts of departed Rockettes go browsing
after dark.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when one of the worst things you could say
about a serious work of architecture was to call it Art Deco. In
1925, when the style emerged at the Exposition des Arts Decoratifs
in Paris, modern architects rallied around the Pavillon de l'Esprit
Nouveau, a machine for living designed by Le Corbusier that was
segregated from the main exposition by a tall fence. That fence
drew the line between the Modern Movement and a style denigrated by
modernists as merely decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Portzamparc, 55, represents a fusion of these once opposed
esthetics. Trained at the Ecole des Beaux Arts, he came of age at a
time when Le Corbusier had come to stand for the classical
tradition. His work springs from Le Corbusier's later, sculpturally
expressive designs, like the chapel at Ronchamp. And Portzamparc is
practicing at a time when few architects still consider ornament a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why New York became preoccupied with Art Deco in
the 1970s and '80s. With confidence in the city's future waning, it
was heartening to look back at a style that flourished when New
York was beginning to displace Paris as the center of the cultural
universe.
</P>
<P>
   But Dead Deco buildings like World Wide Plaza and Trump Palace
were counterproductive. French architects conceived Art Deco, in
part, as an homage to the idea of New York: its speed, jazz and
power of invention. Buildings like the Chrysler, 70 Pine Street and
the Majestic apartments on Central Park West became shrines of that
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH looks nothing like an Art Deco building. Rather, it deforms
the style in order to reinvigorate its fresh, jazzy spirit. Instead
of symmetry, Portzamparc creates balance. He holds asymmetrical
elements together with the poise of a Balanchine dancer. He
emphasizes the building's height not with vertical lines, but by
tapering the curtain wall as it rises.
</P>
<P>
   The result is to today's jazz what Art Deco was to the first
Jazz Age. Looser in form, lyrically more seductive, this is a
building for the singer Sade to tuck behind one ear.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH is one of two new Manhattan buildings that rise from the
level of real estate to the plane of architecture. Both buildings
have been cliffhangers. The second of the two, Raimund Abraham's
design for the Austrian Cultural Institute, finally went into
construction three months ago on East 52d Street between Madison
and Fifth, after six years of diddling on the part of the Austrian
government. The LVMH went into the ground in 1996. The steel frame
rose a few stories, then work stopped, and the thing just sat
there, paralyzed by corporate squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the actual causes, it was hard not to see these
delays as signs of New York's ambivalence about architecture
itself. Would the city actually allow this art form to show its
face in New York again, after so many years of keeping it at bay?
Or would these holes in the ground just sit there until developers
bought them, hired the usual commercial architects, and let
business-class architecture go on as usual?
</P>
<P>
   The LVMH Tower was worth the wait. Watching the building rise,
seeing people on the street look up as its faceted, crystalline
contours took shape, even overhearing people say how much they hate
it: this has been like watching a flatliner's pulse revive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
