<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-22 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE ROUND OF SELLING HELPS DEPRESS THE MAIN INDICATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad retreat Tuesday as a
further rise in long-term interest rates and a late round of
selling depressed the main market gauges.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, optimism about coming earnings reports helped to lift
stocks in sectors like technology and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, analysts said they were troubled by the way
the market reacted to quarterly results from Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The securities firm reported second-quarter earnings that were
substantially above Wall Street's expectations. But the stock,
which rose more than 7 percent on Monday, fell 3 11/16 Tuesday, to
56 5/8, and dragged shares of other big brokerage firms down with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes numbers can be too good,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, who
heads his own stock research firm in Greenwich, Conn. ``But the
market's reaction to Lehman's huge profits was a little
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   For a second day, a rise in long-term interest rates helped to
push down cyclical stocks, which depend on a growing economy to
generate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in cyclical stocks was largely responsible for a
decline in the Dow Jones industrial average, which fell 94.35
points, or nine-tenths of a percent, to 10,721.63. Companies like
DuPont, Alcoa and International Paper led the blue-chip index
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which had rallied for five consecutive
sessions, pulled back Tuesday, and dragged down the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index and the NASDAQ composite index.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 lost 13.12 points, or just less than 1 percent, to
1,335.88. Stocks like Microsoft, Lucent Technologies, Cisco Systems
and America Online, which all gained ground on Monday, fell back
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those same stocks helped to pull down NASDAQ. After a
strong opening, sellers emerged and by the end of the session the
index had fallen 50.02 points, or 1.9 percent, to 2,580.26.
</P>
<P>
   Although stock traders appear to have accepted that the Federal
Reserve will raise short-term interest rates by a quarter of a
percentage point next week, Christopher Durbin, chief investment
strategist at J.P. Morgan Investment Inc., which manages more than
$300 billion, said the central bank would most likely have to
increase rates much more than that to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon with reporters in New York Tuesday, Durbin said
short-term interest rates would probably rise a full percentage
point over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his forecast for interest rates, and what he called the
market's sky-high valuations, Durbin said Morgan was advising
investors to shed U.S. stocks and bonds and buy stocks in Japan,
Europe and the emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the rise in long-term interest rates Tuesday was
caused by positioning in front of a heavy calendar of upcoming
corporate debt issues. And the rising rates probably did not help
brokerage stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the slide in Lehman's stock, Goldman Sachs, which is
expected to report earnings Wednesday, fell 1 1/2, to 68. Merrill
Lynch dropped 2 1/2, to 75 3/4. And Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
fell 2 3/8, to 55 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, DuPont fell 2 9/16, to 67 5/8. International
Paper lost 1 7/8, to 52 5/8. And Alcoa fell for a second day,
dropping 1 5/8, to 62 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, shares in Alza, the maker of sustained-release drugs,
gained 1 1/2, to 47 3/4, after Abbott Laboratories said it would
buy it for $7.3 billion in stock. In what was generally a good day
for drug stocks, Abbott fell 11/16, to 43 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks were weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, a Dow component, fell 9/16, to 90 1/8, after it said a
fire at its refinery near San Francisco would cut second-quarter
profits by about 15 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil dropped 1 7/16, to 98. Exxon fell 1 1/4, to 77. And BP
Amoco dropped 1 1/16, to 110 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
