   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REFUGEES (, Macedonia) _ President Clinton implores
ethnic Albanian refugees to delay their rush home to Kosovo so that
peacekeeping forces can clear land mines, stockpiles of Serbian
ammunition and unexploded allied bombs that could jeopardize their
lives. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Stenkovec, Macedonia) _ As he ends a European
visit heavy with talk of finances and politics, President Clinton
comes face to face with the more human element of geopolitics and
speaks to U.S. troops who will join peacekeeping forces inside
Kosovo. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Houston) _ Federal authorities intensified a
nationwide search for suspected serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez, who Houston's top FBI official described as
``Public Enemy Number One.'' The police waited for test results to
tell them whether Resendez-Ramirez killed an elderly Texas woman
and a young couple whose bodies were found a few hundred miles from
a double murder to which he has been linked in Illinois. By S.K.
BARDWELL.
</P>
<P>
   FEN-PHEN (Houston) _ The second fen-phen lawsuit in the nation
to go to trial is settled for $6 million-$7 million, according to
sources. Relatives of Mary Marisa Smith, who claimed the
once-popular diet drug killed the 35-year-old, had sued
pharmaceutical giant American Home Products Corp. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore, behaving as though they already have their
party's presidential nomination, are competing for the political
center, campaign funds and the lead in the polls. So far, Bush is
outpacing Gore on all three fronts, but the race has just begun. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
