<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OURGES REFUGEES TO AVOID MINE DANGER, DELAY RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVICH, Macedonia _ President Clinton visited a refugee camp
here Tuesday and asked ethnic Albanian refugees to give NATO
peacekeepers ``a couple of more weeks'' to remove land mines before
returning home to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have suffered enough,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional tour of Macedonia's largest refugee camp, which
at its peak held 30,000 people who had fled Kosovo and the security
forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Clinton sought to
comfort the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   He told them he understood they were anxious to get home and
knew that many had already left since Serb forces began withdrawing
its troops from Kosovo and NATO ended its 11-week bombing campaign.
The last of the Serb forces withdrew Sunday. Shortly after the
withdrawal, Kosovo Liberation Army leaders signed an agreement to
warehouse their weapons and end their fight.
</P>
<P>
   But only a day later, a top KLA leader said the rebels never
agreed to give up their guns and still hope to form an army.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said many land mines still lay on routes into Kosovo and
other communities, and that the United States was bringing in some
of the world's best experts to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I ask you, please be patient with us. Give us a couple of
more weeks to take the land mines up if the people here ask you to
do that, because you are going to be able to go back in safety and
security. I want to make sure it is a happy return,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of civilians already have died in explosions of land
mines since the peacekeepers entered Kosovo on June 12.
Peacekeepers' spokesman Lt. Col. Robin Clifford said mine blasts
killed one civilian Monday and a child on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the refuges continue to return. The UN refugee agency
said more than 170,000 of the 860,000 or so refugees who fled from
Kosovo have returned in little more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton, accompanied by his wife and daughter, arrived at
this vast camp, near Skopje, children rushed up to embrace him and
refugees greeted him with chants of ``Clinton, Clinton, Clinton.''
One small boy, standing with other children on top of portable
toilets, wore green sweatpants partially rolled and a grey Boston
College sweatshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the refugees, ``We are commited not only to making
Kosovo safe, but to helping people rebuild their lives, rebuild
their communities, and then to helping Kosovo and all the countries
of the region build a brighter, more prosperous future.''
</P>
<P>
   As Apache helicopters hovered overhead for security, and a
roadblock backed up traffic all the way into Kosovo, President
Clinton was received almost worshipfully by the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children think of him as a God that has descended upon
us,'' Said Mevlyde Dulaku, whose six-year-old son, Nexhat shook
hands with the president. ``We couldn't believe he came. He showed
he really feels for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sends his planes and saved out lives,'' said Nexhant, who
said he and his family would wait three weeks to return to their
Kosovo hometown, Vucitrn. ``Because Mr. Clinton told us we
should,.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaysreti Nuhiu, 32, said Serb paramilitary soldiers wearing ski
masks killed her five-year-old son Ferid, in front of her. Since
then, she said, she and her husband have been on medication to calm
their nerves. ``Mr. Clinton's visit to us took half my pain away,''
Nuhiu said. ``Seeing him conme and speak I feel we will be safe
now. I feel there is a force to protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   As two-year old Getuar Kqiku sat in his lap, Clinton heard the
story of one family that fled their Kosovo home 3 1/2 months ago
and had witnessed the massacre of 60 people in a small village
where they lived for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the army entered the buildings, they started beating
us,'' Idriz and his wife, Nerimane Macastena, told Clinton through
an interpreter. ``They took a four-year-old boy and put a knife on
one side of his neck and a lighted cigarette on the other and
threatened us to give them all our money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the refugees here also made it known that they also will
not forget the pain the Serbs caused them. When asked if she could
live with Serbs again, Shpresa Zairi, 17, she shook her head. ``The
police crushed my home, they took all my things. They massacred us,
they killed us. No.''
</P>
<P>
   After touring the camp, Clinton said he was aware of the
bitterness on the part of some refugees, but said it hadn't
resulted in a lot of retaliation. ``We thought there would be some
problems and I thought it would be worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he urged Kosovar Albanians not to retaliate against the
Serbs on Monday after attending a US-European Union summit, he did
not make such a request once he arrived in the Balkans. There was
evidence of retaliation by rebels or their supporters in Kosovo.
Serb houses burned in the western city of Pec and a Serb power
company worker was shot in the capital. The violence followed the
first deaths in Kosovo's peace force. Two soldiers from the British
contingent were killed Monday when unexploded NATO ordnance they
were trying to destroy accidentally blew up. Two villagers helping
the peacekeepers also were killed and a third was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Rrustem Mustafa, a KLA commander known for his hard-line views,
said an agreement in which the rebels pledged to turn in their
weapons, disband and put away their uniforms doesn't mean the end
of the insurgents or their struggle for an independent Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement does not demand that we give up our arms,''
Mustafa, known as ``Commander Remi,'' told the rebels' Kosova Press
news service. ``The arms will be gathered at certain places and the
KLA will take care of them while NATO has a right to observe
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Clinton also met with the leaders of Macedonia and
Albanians, the two countries that bore the brunt of the refugee
crisis. ``NATO could not have achieved its mission without you; the
people of Kosovo would not be going home to security and autonomy
without you. I came here, as much as anything else, to say thank
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders told Clinton they were prepared to work
together, and were committed to build a ``spirit of tolerance,'' in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the leaders that some analysts believe it wll take
several generations to instill trust between Serbs and Albanians in
the strife torn region, according to an administration official.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's response, the official said, was he believe it
could happen much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to Washington, the president stopped at the Air
Force Base in Aviano, Italy to thank American and NATO pliots for
their ``noble endeavor'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The president then began the flight home, where he was due to
arrive early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _Yugoslavia's parliament scheduled a session Thursday to end the
state of war.
</P>
<P>
   The state of war, in effect since March 24, banned men of
military age from leaving the country, let the army take over key
institutions and subjected the news media to censorship.
</P>
<P>
   _With the 78-day air war over, US warplanes sent to Europe as
part of the allied bombing campaign are coming home. The first of
367 military planes is to return Wednesday, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   _The foreign ministers of Italy, Britain, Germany and France
will visit Kosovo on Wednesday to meet with U.N. special
representative Sergio Vieira de Mello and NATO's Kosovo commander,
Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Kurt Pitzer contributed to this report from
Skopje. Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
