<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 50 FBI AGENTS HEAD FOR KOSOVO TO JOIN PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A team of more than 50 FBI agents left the United
States for Kosovo on Tuesday to join an international investigation
of possible war crimes, the first time that federal agents have
been sent abroad to investigate accusations of wartime atrocities
against civilians who are not Americans, law enforcement officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents flew to Kosovo carrying thousands of tons of gear,
including Humvees, tents, food, portable showers and specialized
equipment for field laboratory analysis of evidence, the officials
said. The agents, all volunteers, are likely to remain in the
region for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The agents are planning to set up a base camp in the U.S. sector
in the southeastern corner of Kosovo, but will be available to
investigate possible war crimes sites throughout the province of
Serbia. Among their tasks will be an effort to determine how
possible victims of war crimes died and who killed them.
</P>
<P>
   Agents trained in evidence collection, laboratory analysis and
forensic science are on the team along with other agents like some
from the FBI's Hostage Rescue Team, a highly trained paramilitary
unit and crisis response team, whose agents will secure areas in
which the agents will be working.
</P>
<P>
   Hostage Rescue Team, a highly trained paramilitary unit and
crisis response team, whose agents will secure areas in which the
agents will be working.
</P>
</TEXT>
