<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-GRANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GENIUS' GRANTS BUY TIME FOR 32 US SCHOLARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis A. Moore had spent much of last Wednesday night collapsed
on the floor of his home near the mouth of the Amazon River,
wracked by fever, violent shakes, and intense stomach pains.
</P>
<P>
   It had already been a horrible spring for Moore, a scholar of
tribal languages, who had recently learned that the Brazilian
government was cutting funding for his research.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Thursday, the phone rang. It was the man from the
MacArthur Foundation calling to say that he had just won a huge
cash award _ a ``genius grant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I'd just had the worst night of my life,''
Moore said. ``He said, `Yeah, well this is going to be your best
morning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a Michigan native, is among the 32 MacArthur Fellows
announced Tuesday by the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur
Foundation, which awards stipends to intellectual innovators to
free them from the constraints of their daily financial
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year grants, which range from $200,000 to $375,000, are
dropped like manna from heaven on winners who are rarely aware
thatthey are under consideration. The money comes with no strings
attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gift of time,'' said Daniel J. Socolow, director of the
MacArthur Fellows Program. ``It drops out of the sky, and it gives
extraordinary people the space and time to do their thing in the
way they want to. It's magical.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Massachusetts residents are among this year's winners.
They are John Bonifaz of the National Voting Rights Institute,
social historian Jacqueline Jones of Brandeis University, and
physicist Juan M. Maldacena of Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur Foundation is recognizing Maldacena, 30, for his
work in the abstract field of string theory, which postulates the
existence of constituents of matter that are too tiny to detect
with the latest experimental apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to understand string theory and how nature behaves
in very short distances and at very early periods of time, close to
the beginning of the Big Bang, the beginning of the universe,''
said Maldacena, who lives in Cambridge, Mass. He said he hadn't
decided what to do yet with the prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Bonifaz, 33, also of Cambridge, an energetic public interest
lawyer, uses litigation to press for campaign finance reform. The
National Voting Rights Institute, which he heads, has been retained
to defend several state-based campaign-finance reforms passed by
ballot initiatives or legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to say that we are a democracy,'' Bonifaz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is we have a plutocracy, where less than one
percent of the population is giving 80 percent of the money to
campaigns. That angers me deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, of Wellesley, Mass., the Harry S. Truman professor of
American history at Brandeis, is being recognized for her
scholarship on labor history. She has focused on how economic
transformations have affected the status of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a validation of the effort to bring the voices
of ordinary working people to a larger, modern audience,'' she said
of the award. Jones learned of the award as she returned Thursday
from a lunch in Cambridge to celebrate her 51st birthday. On her
answering machine was a message from the MacArthur Foundation,
urging her to return the call. The message said, ``This is a call
you'll want to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I just looked at each other and laughed,''
Jones said. ``It was a complete surprise _ pretty shocking
actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who was reached at his home in Belem, Brazil, said he was
still dumbfounded by the $365,000 prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take until the year 2016 for me to earn that kind of
money,'' said Moore, who was recognized for his work preserving the
language and culture of endangered indigenous groups in the Amazon
region. ``It kind of puts a floor under you when you've been
hanging from a cliff from your fingers for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
OTHER GRANT RECIPIENTS:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jillian F. Banfield, 39, associate professor of geology and
geophysics, University of Wisconsin, Madison; Carolyn R. Bertozzi,
32, of Albany, Calif., assistant professor of chemistry, University
of California, Berkeley; Bruce G. Blair, 51, of Washington, D.C.,
foreign policy analyst with the Brookings Institution; Shawn
Carlson, 39, of San Diego, founder and executive director of the
Society for Amateur Scientists; Mark Danner, 40, of New York City
and Berkeley, Calif., journalist and visiting professor, University
of California, Berkeley; Alison L. Des Forges, 57, of Buffalo,
writer and consultant, Human Rights Watch/Africa; Elizabeth Diller,
45, and Ricardo Scofidio, 64, of New York City, architects; Saul
Friedlaender, 66, of Los Angeles, professor of history, University
of California, Los Angeles and University of Tel Aviv; and Jennifer
L. Gordon, 33, of Brooklyn, N.Y., lawyer and community organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, David M. Hillis, 40, of Austin, Texas, professor of
zoology, University of Texas, Austin; Sara Horowitz, 36, of New
York City, executive director, Working Today; Laura L. Kiessling,
38, associate professor of chemistry and biochemistry, University
of Wisconsin, Madison; Leslie V. Kurke, 39, associate professor of
classics and comparative literature, University of California,
Berkeley; David Levering Lewis, 63, of New York City, professor of
history, Rutgers University; Gay J. McDougall, 51, of Washington,
D.C., executive director, International Human Rights Law Group;
Campbell McGrath, 37, of Miami Beach, associate professor of
creative writing, Florida International University; Dennis Albert
Moore, 54, of Belem-Para, Brazil, anthropologist and coordinator of
linguistics, Division Museu Paraense Emilio Goeldi; Elizabeth
Murray, 58, of New York City, artist and professor of studio arts,
Bard College; Pepon Osorio, 44, of New York City, artist; Peter
Shor, 39, of Florham Park, N.J., senior member, research staff at
AT&AMP;T Labs; Eva Silverstein, 28, of Stanford, Calif., assistant
professor of physics, Stanford Linear Accelerator Center; Wilma
Alpha Subra, 55, of New Iberia, La., public interest scientist; Ken
Vandermark, 34, of Chicago, musician; Naomi Wallace, 38, of
Otterburn, North Yorkshire, England, and Prospect, Ky., playwright;
Jeffrey R. Weeks, 42, of Canton, N.Y., mathematician; Fred Wilson,
44, of New York City, artist and curator; Xu Bing, 44, of New York
City, artist; and Ofelia Zepeda, 45, of Tucson, professor of
linguistics, University of Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
