<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ivester to give apologies on Belgian TV
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (i) International and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester plans to go on
Belgian television this evening with commercials to apologize for a
health scare involving his company's top brands and to reassure
consumers its soft drinks are safe.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as the Belgian government postponed a decision
Tuesday on whether to lift a partial ban on Coke products. A
decision, however, could come today.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a key French official hinted that similar
restrictions in her country could be removed today. Consumer
Affairs Minister Marylise Lebranchu said her country may be ``at
the state of coming out of the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester is expected to talk to Belgians in 90-second commercials
that will carry the same general message as his personal apology
that ran Tuesday in full-page ads in 15 newspapers. He will speak
in English, but there will be subtitles in the country's major
languages, which include French and Flemish.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Brussels, there is the sense that intense
negotiations are under way behind closed doors to resolve the
matter soon.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Health Minister Luc Van den Bossche had indicated
Tuesday morning that he was likely to make a decision on
Coca-Cola's request to end restrictions imposed for eight days. The
product ban was imposed after scores of people reported becoming
ill after drinking Coca-Cola products from bottling plants in
Antwerp and in Dunkirk, France.
</P>
<P>
   Bossche, who could not be reached for comment, has expressed
skepticism about explanations from Coca-Cola and its largest
bottler, Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises, about the cause of
the illnesses. The company has attributed the illnesses to
reactions to ``rotten egg'' smells caused by faulty carbon dioxide
gas in some beverage containers and a fungicide from wooden pallets
for others.
</P>
<P>
   Bossche also has publicly criticized the company for not
reacting promptly when the reports that people were falling ill
were initially made. Government officials here say it was Bossche's
frustration that led to a brief ban on all Coke products last week.
That ban has been relaxed to include Coca-Cola's main brands _
Coke, Sprite and Fanta.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's executives in Brussels also appear frustrated that
the process of getting their company's top brands back on store
shelves is taking so long. They met with the government during the
day Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to have detailed talks with the government,'' said
Paul Pendergrass, a spokesman for the company in Europe. ``We
expect to continue having detailed talks tomorrow (Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   At one point Tuesday, Ivester briefed Coca-Cola's board of
trustees on developments during a 45-minute conference call.
Ivester and board members also talked about the political situation
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman and chief executive of the world's largest soft
drink company has already met with Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc
Dehaene to apologize for quality control lapses at plants bottling
his company's products.
</P>
<P>
   And Coca-Cola spokesman Randal Donaldson said the soft drink
company has had positive responses from Ivester's apologetic
newspaper ads. But not all consumers have been impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds a little as if he's making excuses,'' said Martin
Bueiens, a university student who was reading the ad Tuesday during
his lunch at a Quick fast-food restaurant in central Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, really, it looks to me as if he's making too much of the
whole thing,'' Bueiens said between bites of a chicken sandwich and
fries. ``It was just a few cans of Coke, and for this they do all
this? American companies have enough money to waste, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The student washed down his lunch with an iced Coke. Belgium's
ban on fountain drinks was lifted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Upbeat about France
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged by the statements of the French
authorities,'' Donaldson said after the country said it had found
the company's products safe for consumption and a top official said
the crisis there may be near an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a personal conviction, but I may be mistaken, that we
will see a way out of the crisis this evening or tomorrow
morning,'' Lebranchu, the consumer affairs minister, told the
Agence French-Presse on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   French scientists say they have found nothing wrong with
Coca-Cola products tested over the weekend, confirming the
company's assertion that there is no health risk in consuming its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Hirsch, the head of the government's food safety and
agency, echoed this assessment and predicted that experts making
the final review of the data should wrap up their work today.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebranchu said while France will likely allow cans of
Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light (the European version of Diet Coke),
Fanta and Sprite from Dunkirk back on sale, the ban will remain in
place on beverages imported from Belgium to France.
</P>
<P>
   ``All (Coca-Cola) products transported on Belgian pallets will
remain under embargo,'' she said in a Reuters report. ``I do not
see who would allow them back.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Investigators from the European Union began inspecting
Coca-Cola Enterprises plants in Antwerp and Dunkirk Tuesday
morning. The EU was moved to enter the fray in part because it says
no one has turned up a conclusive explanation to explain the
illnesses. The EU's executive body, the European Commission,
expects to wrap up its inspection Friday and announce its findings
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health officials in Portugal plan to inspect a Coca-Cola
factory in Lisbon after a dark residue was found in the bottom of
several cans of the soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of carbon used in the Lisbon factory's water filtering
system became mixed with the drink in up to 3,000 cans, which the
company has withdrawn, company spokesman Tiago Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   A Capital newspaper reported no drink had an odd taste or odor
and no illnesses were reported. A Coca-Cola Portugal spokesman told
the paper that the residue was harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has published full-page newspaper ads in recent days
assuring the public that drinks produced at its Portuguese factory
are safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coca-Cola Co. handed out free Coca-Cola Light in Switzerland
to reassure customers its drinks are safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company informed the Mexican government that its beverages
posed no health risks after the country's health department asked
for a report on the situation in Europe, Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, the largest per-capita consumer of Coca-Cola products,
wanted to know whether a similar problem could arise there.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr. writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
