this? American companies have enough money to waste, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The student washed down his lunch with an iced Coke. Belgium's
ban on fountain drinks was lifted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Upbeat about France
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged by the statements of the French
authorities,'' Donaldson said after the country said it had found
the company's products safe for consumption and a top official said
the crisis there may be near an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a personal conviction, but I may be mistaken, that we
will see a way out of the crisis this evening or tomorrow
morning,'' Lebranchu, the consumer affairs minister, told the
Agence French-Presse on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   French scientists say they have found nothing wrong with
Coca-Cola products tested over the weekend, confirming the
company's assertion that there is no health risk in consuming its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Hirsch, the head of the government's food safety and
agency, echoed this assessment and predicted that experts making
the final review of the data should wrap up their work today.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebranchu said while France will likely allow cans of
Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light (the European version of Diet Coke),
Fanta and Sprite from Dunkirk back on sale, the ban will remain in
place on beverages imported from Belgium to France.
</P>
<P>
   ``All (Coca-Cola) products transported on Belgian pallets will
remain under embargo,'' she said in a Reuters report. ``I do not
see who would allow them back.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Investigators from the European Union began inspecting
Coca-Cola Enterprises plants in Antwerp and Dunkirk Tuesday
morning. The EU was moved to enter the fray in part because it says
no one has turned up a conclusive explanation to explain the
illnesses. The EU's executive body, the European Commission,
expects to wrap up its inspection Friday and announce its findings
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health officials in Portugal plan to inspect a Coca-Cola
factory in Lisbon after a dark residue was found in the bottom of
several cans of the soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of carbon used in the Lisbon factory's water filtering
system became mixed with the drink in up to 3,000 cans, which the
company has withdrawn, company spokesman Tiago Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   A Capital newspaper reported no drink had an odd taste or odor
and no illnesses were reported. A Coca-Cola Portugal spokesman told
the paper that the residue was harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has published full-page newspaper ads in recent days
assuring the public that drinks produced at its Portuguese factory
are safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coca-Cola Co. handed out free Coca-Cola Light in Switzerland
to reassure customers its drinks are safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company informed the Mexican government that its beverages
posed no health risks after the country's health department asked
for a report on the situation in Europe, Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, the largest per-capita consumer of Coca-Cola products,
wanted to know whether a similar problem could arise there.
</P>
