<HEADER>
A5714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-STOCK-COX     06-22 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke shares rise after Belgian ads
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (f) Financial and (i) International categories.)
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tuesday's public apology to Belgians by Coca-Cola
Chairman M. Douglas Ivester apparently was accepted on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock climbed as much as 5.2 percent at one point
during trading before retreating to a smaller gain after news broke
that Belgium had postponed its decision on whether to lift its ban
on the company's top soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed up 1.7 percent, or $1.06 1/4, at $62.62 1/2 on
heavy volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are concluding that eventually this, too, shall
pass,'' Manny Goldman, global beverage analyst for Merrill Lynch,
said of the European health scare. Ivester issued an personal
apology in full-page ads that ran in 15 Belgian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, analysts said bargain hunters may be on the prowl since
Coca-Cola shares had fallen 9 percent between June 8, when children
in Belgium first reported becoming ill after drinking Coca-Cola
products, and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Coca-Cola's shares fell nearly 3 percent after
Goldman Sachs analyst Marc Cohen cut his earnings and volume
estimates because of the company's overseas problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen expects Coca-Cola to have a second-quarter profit of 40
cents a share instead of 41 cents. He also indicated that the
company's case volume could be slightly weaker, partly because of
the product scare.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has lost $24 million in revenue from the recalls and
product bans, according to an estimate by analyst Martin Romm at
Credit Suisse First Boston. That amounts to 0.000595 per share in
lost profit.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises, the bottler that
owns the two plants at the center of the crisis, fell 50 cents
Tuesday to close at $32.62 1/2 on heavy volume. CCE's shares have
lost 10 percent since June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
