<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-MOVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCESS CRUISE LINE TO MOVE TO VALENCIA   IN SANTA CLARITA,
CALIF.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ANGELA M. LEMIRE AND PATRICIA FARRELL AIDEM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Princess Cruises will move its headquarters to
Valencia in the Santa Clarita Valley north of Los Angeles,
consolidating operations in a deal that marks the largest-ever
corporate relocation to Santa Clarita, company officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The move from Century City in Los Angeles will bring another 750
employees to Princess offices at the Valencia Town Center. Princess
moved its 750-employee customer service operation to Valencia in
November, lured by Santa Clarita's 15-year moratorium on business
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The new move is to consolidate as the company expands its
10-ship fleet with seven more ocean liners, said Rick James, senior
vice president of customer service and sales for the cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company will be doubling in size between now and 2004,''
James said. ``With that expanding work force, we wanted the company
to be in one location.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita's economic development manager, Michael Haviland,
heralded the announcement as solidifying Santa Clarita's
``prestige'' as a growing industrial center in Los Angeles County,
as well as a direct result of the city's competitive,
business-friendly policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously very pleased, especially since we worked
closely with them initially to bring them here,'' Haviland said of
the privately owned, 34-year-old cruise line. ``It's a pleasure
having a company of that prestige here in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the cruise line's move to Valencia will not yield
business tax revenues, the city regards its presence ``in terms of
the work force'' brought to the city, said Haviland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that work in a community spend money in a
community,'' he said, projecting that the company's workers would
frequent area retailers and restaurants. That, in turn, would lure
other prospective retailers to the Valencia Town Center.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line expects to complete the new headquarters in
spring of 2001. The new offices will be in two buildings _ of four
and five stories _ with the ground levels reserved for retail
shops. The buildings will house fleet operations, marketing,
finance, legal, land programs, yield management and human resources
departments.
</P>
<P>
   The customer service center is housed in a six-story building,
also with retail space on pedestrian-oriented Town Center Drive.
The trio of buildings will cover a total of 270,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Princess complex will be part of a shopping and
entertainment district under construction by The Newhall Land and
Farming Company. Restaurants, a Borders book store and an Edwards
Cinema with 12 screens opened recently on Town Center Drive, where
an Imax 3-D theater is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff loves it there,'' James said. ``It's a great
location.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees lived in Santa Clarita before the first
relocation, and several others have since moved to the area, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cushman Realty Corp. engineered the 15-year, $65 million lease
transaction on behalf of Princess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Princess Cruises move represents the largest corporate
headquarters relocation to the Valencia area,'' said John C.
Cushman III, the realty company's president and chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The planned relocation is a milestone transaction that
reinforces the favorable economic environment that is drawing
businesses to the Santa Clarita Valley, Cushman said.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction represents a 163,000-square-foot expansion of
Princess Cruises' 108,000-square-foot existing space, which will
allow the cruise line to expand the customer service center and
relocate its corporate headquarters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
