<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDU PRIEST CONVICTED OF SEXUALLY ASSAULTING ARKANSAS WOMAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ark.) 
 
(See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Hindu priest sobbed Tuesday when a jury convicted
him of sexually assaulting a 21-year-old Little Rock, Ark., college
student who sought his spiritual guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated about an hour and 45 minutes before
convicting Bhogeshwernand Sharma. He now could be given probation
or a prison term of up to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma, 37, wept and continually dabbed his eyes. He became even
more upset when his wife, Aneeta Sharma, testified in the
punishment phase and said her husband could obey any probation
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the monster these people have made him out to be,''
said the angry wife. ``This has been a masquerade here from day
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman also called the 21-year-old and her mother ``fools''
who envied her family.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma sexually assaulted the 21-year-old on or about April 3,
1998, at his Harris County home, according to testimony. The woman
and her mother said they first met Sharma in September 1997 at a
prayer meeting in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and daughter and her aunt said they had sought
Sharma's help with medical problems and he later converted them to
Hinduism, becoming their Hindu ``godfather'' or ``guru.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother and her sister say Sharma bullied them into sex
during the September 1997 visit, using the pretext of blessings or
rituals to get them alone on separate days.
</P>
<P>
   They say he told them he needed to cleanse them with his ``holy
sperm.'' They also say he told them they or their kin would suffer
or die if they didn't submit or if they told anyone about it.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and daughter saw Sharma again October 1997 in
Arkansas. They visited him in Houston in April 1998 and that's when
the daughter says he used the same tactics on her.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma is not charged in Arkansas with the alleged encounters
with the mother and aunt, but their testimony was allowed in this
case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fourth Hindu woman called prosecutor Kelly Siegler during the
trial and alleged that she had been sexually assaulted by Sharma in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler told state District Judge Ted Poe about the woman Monday
and, outside the presence of jurors, she said the woman told her
that Sharma's brothers and his mother talked her out of coming
forward in February.
</P>
<P>
   Bashist Sharma, the defendant's brother and co-counsel in the
case, said, with jurors out of the room, that he didn't recall the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler intended to call the defendant's brother, Jai Sharma,
and his mother to the stand Tuesday. But they, along with Bashist,
hired an attorney who told Poe they would invoke their Fifth
Amendment right.
</P>
<P>
   Jai Sharma, also an attorney, represented his brother at one
time.
</P>
<P>
   Poe ruled that any testimony on the alleged February meeting was
inadmissible. Bashist Sharma removed himself as co-counsel at the
urging of lead defense lawyer Katherine Scardino, who said she knew
nothing about the fourth woman until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler said in court Tuesday that a family friend of the
Sharmas apparently called the woman's father Monday to talk about
her accusations. That woman did not testify.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, lead defense lawyer Katherine Scardino hit
on the big themes of her defense, which has been a mix of alibi
witnesses and attacks on the credibility of the three women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case stinks,'' said Scardino, who argued that no
reasonable woman would believe such diagnoses and predictions, or
submit to such crude come-ons from a man they hardly knew.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said the three women had lied and that her defense
witnesses clearly showed that Sharma was never alone with them in
Houston or Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   But Siegler countered that the women had no motive to lie. She
said their story did sound strange, but that was because Sharma
picked his vulnerable victims well.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler also attacked the credibility of Sharma's alibi
witnesses, most of whom were either related to or friends of
Sharma. She said they had lied for Sharma out of loyalty to a
smooth manipulator who ``cloaks himself in the mystery and secrecy
of Hinduism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just a big incestuous mess,'' Siegler said of the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Over the Scardino's objections, Siegler hinted there might be
other victims in the Hindu community and a guilty verdict could
protect them from Sharma.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma's relatives were dismayed at the verdict. Scardino told
reporters later that her task had been made harder because she had
to defend Sharma against three accusations, though he was only
charged with one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the jury believed those three women from Arkansas
over all the witnesses I produced in front of this jury,'' Scardino
said. ``I don't mean to sound like sour grapes, but it's hard for
me to believe that they would believe those stories instead of the
credible people I put in front of the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said she hoped jurors would consider probation.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in the punishment phase will be Wednesday. If
Sharma gets prison time, he will have to serve a quarter of it
before he is eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
