<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL-QUOTES-NYT &LR;      06-22 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-QUOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BLOCKS BILL RESTRICTING STEEL IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., N.Y., Pa., Minn., Texas)  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Tuesday blocked the passage of a bill
that would have sharply restricted imports of foreign steel to the
United States, a blow to unions and steelmakers and a victory for
President Clinton, who had warned that the legislation would revive
protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   After some furious last-minute vote-switching, supporters of
placing tight quotas on imported steel _ both Democrats and
Republicans from steelmaking states that have been hit by Asian
imports _ attracted 42 votes of the 60 votes required to end debate
and move toward a vote on the actual legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is now dead, would have rolled back imports of
steel to the levels before the Asian economic crisis, ending a
surge that began as countries sought to export their way out of
their economic trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After the House of Representatives overwhelmingly approved the
import quotas in March, the debate over steel quotas took on far
greater dimensions. It became a divisive argument over the merits
of free trade, and the economic wisdom of protecting steelworkers
at the expense of raising prices on a range of every day goods _
from American-made cars, to housing, airplanes and farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Clinton won the day by allying with key Republicans
_ including the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., who
reversed earlier indications that he might support the legislation
and took to the floor of the Senate just before the vote to warn
his colleagues that if the measure passed, ``the consequences would
be dire indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lott, who a few days ago seemed to be enjoying the
administration's discomfort on the issue, sounded surprisingly like
a member of the White House economic team. He argued from the well
of the Senate that the bill would ``adversely affect our businesses
and farmers who depend upon access to the international market.
There's no question that this bill will undercut the economic
growth that we enjoy today.''
</P>
<P>
   The action also removed Vice President Al Gore from a political
quandary. He had been caught between the administration's
free-trade instincts and the United Steelworkers of America, whose
support he seeks in his presidential bid. On Monday night Gore,
siding with the White House, called the legislation ``unnecessary''
but was reluctant to join in working actively for its defeat.
</P>
<P>
   That was left largely to members of the Cabinet, especially the
outgoing Treasury secretary, Robert Rubin, and Commerce Secretary
William Daley. Daley successfully argued that a series of actions
he has taken to prevent the ``dumping'' of steel in the American
market _ including placing retaliatory tariffs on Japan, South
Korea and Brazil _ was already succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's brief but heated debate Tuesday on the steel quotas
revealed the degree to which the economic prosperity of the 1990s
has changed the nature of political discourse. While senators from
many steel-producing states argued passionately about the need to
protect the jobs of their constituents, they were outnumbered by
those who concluded that an industry that employs 170,000 workers
should not be protected by raising the price of steel for virtually
every consumer in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   One estimate, put together by the Institute for International
Economics, suggested that each job saved by the import quota would
cost consumers $800,000, an argument the steel lobby never
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators from both parties warned that the bill, while
it might protect steelworkers, risked repeating what is now
considered one of Congress' greatest economic blunders of this
century: the Smoot-Hawley Act of 1930, which many economists now
believe deepened the Great Depression. While economic conditions
today are the exact opposite of what they were then, Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., warned that passage of the bill would
result in ``an immediate reaction'' around the world, as countries
imposed retaliatory restrictions on American products.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, last-minute lobbying by agricultural interests,
which likely would have been the first victims of that retaliation,
turned the vote around. ``They came on big time,'' said Sen. Rick
Santorum, R-Pa., who served as the floor manager for the defeated
bill. ``And the White House lobbied hard. They saw this as a big
political loser for Al Gore, and they wanted to protect him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that appears to be exactly what happened in the last 90
seconds or so of voting, when senators are free to approach the
clerks and quietly switch sides. Several Democrats, realizing the
import quotas were going down to defeat, changed their vote to
support the White House, which on Monday night thought that the
vote would be extremely close. ``Two weeks ago,'' one senior
administration official said, ``we thought this bill might pass
with a veto-proof majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote clearly left a residue of anger, though, within
Democratic ranks. Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said, ``The White
House is saying that the steel crisis is over, and so they pulled
all the stops to defeat this bill. Well, last weekend I was on the
Iron Range in northeastern Minnesota. I talked to some of the
workers who just got laid off at EVTAC Mining in Eveleth, Minn.,
and to some of the workers who are going to be laid off at the end
of this month. For them, the steel crisis is not over. For their
husbands and wives and children, the steel crisis is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   In an economy with rising unemployment, such arguments would
probably have carried far more weight. But the remarkable expansion
of the last few years apparently led a number of senators to buy
the argument that the retaliation by other nations would be far
more costly to other American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will kill jobs,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
`Since we are the greatest beneficiary of international trade, we
will lose more than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a statement released by the White House,
acknowledged that ``the surge in steel imports has created a
significant hardship for many steelworkers and communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But quota legislation was the wrong approach and would have
weakened our economy and undermined our ability to tear down unfair
trade barriers in foreign countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate seems likely to take up in the next few weeks an
alterative to the quota bill that would strengthen American
anti-dumping laws, giving the Commerce Department more weaponry to
fight imports that are priced below manufacturing costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
