<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-DISABLED-BOS &LR;      06-22 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABLED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT NARROWS RIGHT TO SUE UNDER DISABILITIES ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a string of important rulings on the Americans
with Disabilities Act, the Supreme Court Tuesday restricted who can
sue for employment discrimination under the 1990 law and also told
states to expand housing and treatment options for the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups such as the US Chamber of Commerce hailed three
related workplace decisions as a ``victory for employers'' because
the court said people with correctable disabilities, like poor
eyesight or high blood pressure, cannot bring lawsuits under the
ADA against companies that fire them, or won't hire them, because
of their condition.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched cases involved two nearsighted sisters who
wanted to be pilots for United Air Lines, a truck mechanic fired by
United Parcel Service because of his high blood pressure, and a
trucker for Albertsons food stores who was dismissed after the
company learned he was functionally blind in one eye.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the 7-2 majority in the United Air Lines case,
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said Congress did not intend for the
disabilites act to cover the estimated 160 million Americans with
correctable impairments. The legislation was aimed at protecting
some 43 million people whose physical and mental disabilities limit
their ``major life activities,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Though acknowledging Congress's source for the 43 million was
unclear, ``the figure reflects an understanding that those whose
impairments are largely corrected by medication or other devices
are not `disabled' within the meaning'' of the disabilities act,
O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups for the disabled called the workplace rulings a
major setback. At the same time they applaudd the court for a
separate 6-3 decision that said states discriminate against
mentally ill people when they institutionalize them in psychiatric
hospitals rather than provide community housing and home-based
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unnecessary segregation of persons with mental disabilities
perpetuates unwarranted assumptions that such persons are unfit
for, or unworthy of, participating in community life,'' Justice
Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote for the majority. Dissenting were Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Clarence Thomas, who
wrote the minority opinion, and Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Temporary exclusion from community placement does not amount
to `discrimination' in the traditional sense of the word,'' Thomas
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case centered on two mentally disabled women who charged the
state of Georgia with discrimination for confining them to a
psychiatric hospital when they wanted to live and receive services
in their community and near their families.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, claiming a state's right to make its own mental-health
treatment and housing decisions, initially had 26 other states,
including Massachusetts, weigh in on its side. But an intense
national lobbying campaign last winter by disabilities-rights
groups persuaded Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly to change his
mind, and Massachusetts had its name removed from an amicus brief.
</P>
<P>
   John Widdison, spokesman for the state's Department of Mental
Health, said Tuesday's ruling would have little practical
application in Massachusetts because most of the state's
mental-health clients are already being treated in communities, a
trend that began in 1992 when the state closed four psychiatric
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In a White House statement, President Clinton said he was
pleased by the Georgia decision and pledged that the departments of
Justice and Health and Human Services would assist states in
carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing so will advance the goals of the ADA and bring us closer
to our ultimate goal _ a nation that integrates people with
disabilities into the social mainstream, promotes equality of
opportunity, and maximizes individual choice,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had argued in favor of extending the scope of
the ADA to protect people who claim a disability, even if there are
``mitigating measures'' _ medications, devices, treatments _ that
allow them to function fully in jobs and other activities. Lower
courts had been divided over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The court majority, in its first major interpretations of the
disabilities law, said a disability exists only when an impairment
``substantially limits'' a person's ability to have a normal work
and social life _ ``not where it `might,' `could,' or `would' be
substantially limiting if mitigating measures were not taken,''
O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the court said, employers under the ADA have the
right to establish physical criteria that suit the job. United Air
Lines, for example, did not discriminate against Karen Sutton and
her twin sister, Kimberly Hinton, by requiring its global airline
pilots to have uncorrected 20/20 vision while it does not impose
the same criteria on regional pilots or flight instructors, the
court said. The sisters, who had been regional pilots, had been
turned down as global pilots because they wear glasses.
</P>
<P>
   UPS did not discriminate when it fired Vaughn Murphy, the
mechanic with high blood pressure, because he was unqualified for a
particular job that required him to operate motor vehicles and meet
a high federal health standard, the court said. He was qualified
for other mechanic positions, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   And Hallie Kirkingburg, the truck driver for Albertsons who
compensated with his right eye for the amblyopia in his left eye,
had excellent vision for many jobs but it was not good enough for
driving a commercial truck, the court found.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision turns the ADA law on its head,'' said Chai
Feldblum, a professor at the Georgetown University Law Center who
worked with advocacy groups and Congress to write the disabilites
law. ``What the court said is that if you have an impairment that
makes you dysfunctional, you can be fired, and it's not
discrimination. And if you are qualified for the job, then you are
not disabled enough to be discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldblum said she expects disabilities-rights groups to urge
Congress to amend the law and clarify the definition of who is
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Writing dissenting opinions on the workplace cases, Stevens said
a corrective device does not, in itself, relieve a disability. The
court majority had a ``crabbed vision'' of the disabilities law, he
said, and Congress, ``by reason of legislative myopia, may not have
foreseen its definition of `disability' might theoretically
encompass not just some `43 million Americans' but perhaps two or
three times that number.'' Justice Stephen Breyer also dissented in
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Conrad, senior vice president of the Chamber of Commerce's
National Litigation Center, said she believed ``the 43 million
figure'' did make an impact on the court, just as the complexity
and reach of the law has had a chilling effect on the business
community. Tuesday's rulings, she predicted, represented the first
round of interpretations of a law that is in for much litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' Conrad said, ``but we are off to
a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases are Sutton et al. v. United Air Lines, Inc. No.
97-1943. Albertsons, Inc., v. Kirkingburg. No. 98-591. Murphy v.
United Parcel Service, Inc. No. 97-1992. Olmstead v. L.C. No.
98-536.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
