<HEADER>
A5730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-EMPLOY-DISCRIM     06-22 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-EMPLOY-DISCRIMINATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES 5-4 THAT EMPLOYER MAY NOT LIABLE FOR EMPLOYEE'S
DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Supreme Court ruling Tuesday in an important
civil rights case made it unlikely that many employees who bring
successful discrimination suits against their employers will be
able to collect punitive damages, a remedy that Congress made
available for the first time when it amended the Civil Rights Act
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision held that when a company has made ``good-faith
efforts'' to comply with the civil rights law, it cannot be
required to pay punitive damages for the discriminatory actions of
managers who violate company policy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority, said that
this standard would serve the purpose of encouraging companies to
adopt anti-discrimination policies and thus would help ``promote
prevention as well as remediation.''
</P>
<P>
   She said this was an important goal of Title VII of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964, the basic federal law that prohibits
discrimination in employment on the basis of race and sex. The
decision was important beyond Title VII cases, because that law's
remedial standards also apply to the Americans With Disabilities
Act and to the Federal Fair Housing Act.
</P>
<P>
   Although punitive damages have not been common under any of
these laws, the potential that a jury might award them has been a
factor in large settlements.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said the
standard the majority adopted was ``gratuitous'' and ``ill
advised,'' because it was based on a legal theory that neither side
had argued.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which left many important questions unanswered,
was a surprising outcome to a closely watched case that had already
produced a bitter 6-5 split on the federal appeals court here.
</P>
<P>
   The case began as a lawsuit against the American Dental
Association by a woman who was passed over for a high-level
position in the organization's Washington office in favor of a man
with less experience.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in U.S. District Court here found in 1996 that the
plaintiff, Carole Kolstad, had been the victim of intentional sex
discrimination and awarded her back pay of $52,718. But the judge
would not permit the jury to consider an award of punitive damages,
and the case turned into a battle over what circumstances Congress
had in mind when it amended Title VII in 1991 and made punitive
damages of up to $300,000 available in cases of intentional
discrimination in which the employer acted ``with malice or with
reckless indifference to the federally protected rights of an
aggrieved individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-5 decision last year, the District of Columbia U.S.
Court of Appeals held that punitive damages were available only
when the employer's behavior was particularly ``egregious'' _ a
word that did not appear in the statute and which, the dissenting
judges objected, reflected an effort by the majority to limit the
law by effectively rewriting it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kolstad's Supreme Court appeal, Kolstad vs. American Dental
Association, No. 98-208, focused entirely on the ``egregious
conduct'' standard _ an argument that she in fact won Tuesday.
Seven justices, all except Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justice Clarence Thomas, agreed that the law did not make egregious
conduct a prerequisite to punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor's majority opinion then turned to an issue that had
not been argued by the parties, and that was suggested only in a
friend of the court brief filed on the dental association's behalf
by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. That question was whether a
company could be held liable for punitive damages at all for the
discriminatory actions of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   This was a question the court dealt with in a somewhat different
context last year in a pair of sexual harassment rulings. In those
cases, the court ruled that employers generally had to take
``reasonable care'' to prevent supervisory employees from harassing
lower level workers. The court then went further: if the supervisor
had taken ``tangible employment action'' against an employee _
conditioning a promotion on yielding to a sexual demand, for
example _ the company had no defense and was liable.
</P>
<P>
   The court Tuesday made no such distinction among the range of
discriminatory situations that can arise in a workplace. O'Connor
said only that ``in the punitive damages context, an employer may
not be vicariously liable for the discriminatory employment
decisions of managerial agents where these decisions are contrary
to the employer's good-faith efforts to comply with Title VII.''
Nor did the opinion define a good-faith effort.
</P>
<P>
   The decision sent the case back to the appeals court for
reconsideration under the new standard, and it was not completely
clear how the standard would apply to Ms. Kolstad's complaint. The
men who made the promotion decision that the jury found to be
discriminatory were at the highest level of the organization, its
executive director and the acting head of the Washington office, a
factor that Stevens, in his dissenting opinion Tuesday, said made
much of the majority's discussion irrelevant because their actions
were those of the organization's.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy, along with
Rehnquist and Thomas, joined the majority opinion. Justices David
H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer joined the
dissent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
