<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES-C     06-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruling extends rights of mentally disabled
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ruling Tuesday in a Georgia case, the U.S. Supreme
Court extended the rights of people with mental disabilities,
giving them a greater voice in deciding when they can transfer from
state institutions into homelike settings.
</P>
<P>
   By a 6-3 vote, the high court gave a qualified victory to two
Georgia women who sued the state, seeking to transfer from Georgia
Regional Hospital in DeKalb County and to receive continued
treatment at state expense in a group home.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans With Disabilities Act requires states to move the
mentally disabled into more homelike settings when they are deemed
ready for release from mental institutions and when the state has
the resources to accommodate it, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the court's ruling _ that the unjustified isolation
of the mentally disabled in institutions is a form of illegal
discrimination _ was hailed as a landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous victory for people with disabilities,''
said Atlanta Legal Aid lawyer Sue Jamieson, who represented the two
Georgia women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has now made it clear _ the very act of
unnecessarily segregating a person with mental disabilities
violates his or her civil rights,'' she said. ``We've done that in
this country for generation after generation and decade after
decade without batting an eye. It's a very significant day.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, President Clinton said he was pleased with the
court's ruling, predicting it ``will increase access to home- and
community-based long-term care services and support for these
persons. . . . Our ultimate goal is a nation that integrates people
with disabilities into the social mainstream, promotes equality of
opportunity and maximizes individual choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the high court's ruling sympathized with state concerns
about being able to accommodate the transfers, state Attorney
General Thurbert Baker also claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling has something in it that is encouraging to both
sides,'' Baker said. ``It will afford states around the country to
address this in a more even-handed approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Since filing suit in 1995, Elaine Wilson, 47, and Lois Curtis,
31, have been released from Georgia Regional and live in metro
group homes. State doctors had said both women were ready to leave
Georgia Regional at the time they filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' Wilson said of the court's decision. ``It
will help other people who want to get out of institutions. I know
it will. I know it will help them get placed in homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg set
conditions for transfers out of state institutions: when the
state's treatment professionals have determined that community
placement is appropriate; when the transfer from institutional care
to a less restrictive setting is not opposed by the affected
individual; and when the placement can be reasonably accommodated,
taking into account ``the resources available to the state and the
needs of others with mental disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg also directed Georgia to put together a
``comprehensive, effectively working plan'' for placing qualified
people with mental disabilities in less restrictive settings than
an institution.
</P>
<P>
   And the state must have a waiting list that moves ``at a
reasonable pace not controlled by the state's endeavors to keep its
institutions fully populated,'' Ginsburg wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case now returns to federal court in Atlanta, where the
state will be allowed to further defend its position. Ginsburg
instructed lower courts to consider ``the appropriate relief, given
the range of facilities the state maintains for the care and
treatment of persons with diverse mental disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has eight psychiatric hospitals housing about 3,000
people, 1,500 of whom are mentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Human Resources Commissioner Tommy Olmstead
conceded Tuesday that it costs less to treat a person with mental
disabilities in a group home than in a psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But the state does not realize any savings if it has to pay for
both group home treatments and institutions with abundant
vacancies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olmstead said the state is committed to moving the mentally
disabled into community settings and will continue its efforts to
accommodate the transfers when appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this decision allows us to continue to expand our
community services, reduce our waiting list and safely move people
from our hospitals,'' he said. ``But it's a matter of financing. We
either need to get more money allocated by the state, or we've got
to close hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson, the Legal Aid lawyer, who took the case in 1995, said
the court's ruling means that the DHR can no longer continue
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision means the state has to begin identifying those
individuals who don't need to be in the psychiatric hospitals and
it means moving these people out at a pace that is appropriate,''
she said. ``The state now knows it can no longer keep people in an
institution when they don't need to be there. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
