<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON ASTROS MANAGER TO GO HOME WITH CLEAN BILL OF HEALTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Sports eds.: Press conference will be held at 10 a.m. CDT
Wednesday.) 
 
By DALE ROBERTSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Manager Larry Dierker of the Houston Astros will check
out of the hospital Wednesday morning sporting a burr haircut and a
conspicuous scar from ear to ear across the top of his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just keep my cap on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, however, is that Dierker will leave with a clean
bill of health eight days after undergoing brain surgery that, by
all accounts, removed the cause of the grand mal seizure he
suffered during an Astros game against the San Diego Padres on June
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt better,'' Dierker said. ``Of course, I haven't
had any toxins in my body in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he will remain on anticonvulsive medication for an
undetermined period _ until ``they wean me from them,'' Dierker
said _ doctors have told him he has no reason to fear a recurrence
of the seizures that struck without warning as he sat in the
Astros' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The game, which Houston led 4-1, was stopped and will be
finished July 23 _ presumably with Dierker back at the Astros'
helm. He expects to return to the Astrodome in street clothes next
week when the Astros host the St. Louis Cardinals and resume
managing the team after the All-Star break, which is July 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling me that will be OK,'' he said, ``so I'm
counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has seen or listened to most of the Astros' games since
the operation and has maintained regular contact with general
manager Gerry Hunsicker and interim manager Matt Galante.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with several players by phone Sunday, when he called
the clubhouse to congratulate pitcher Chris Holt for earning his
first victory since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's wife, Judy, will be charged with preventing him from
trying to do too much too soon when he returns home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   First order of business: Hide the golf clubs and the wine.
Dierker confessed he had ``a small sip, just enough to remind me I
like it,'' Monday night when his family ``smuggled'' a celebratory
bottle into his suite at Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``No alcohol for now,'' he said. ``Doctor's orders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I already know I'm going to have a hard time making sure he
doesn't overdo anything,'' Judy Dierker said. ``He's anxious to get
things back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker will go home Wednesday after a news conference at which
his surgeon, Dr. Rob Parrish, will discuss his progress since the
five-hour operation in which an abnormal tangle of blood vessels
that ruptured in the manager's brain was removed. The sutures were
removed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Once he returns home, he will spend much of his time over the
next few weeks answering the volumes of mail he has received since
the attack. A photo taken at the hospital and posted on the Astros'
Web site (astros.com) shows him viewing some of the thousands of
e-mail messages he has received. He is writing a response, which
the Astros plan to post on the Web site in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming, and very humbling,'' he said of the
public's response. ``The piles and piles of cards, all the flowers
... people have been just great. It's a hard way to find how many
friends you have, but if there's a good side to going through
something like this, I guess that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker offered special thanks to the Astros players and
personnel and the paramedics who rushed to his aid when the seizure
was in full force. He singled out outfielder Derek Bell, who jumped
atop Dierker's convulsing body in an effort to prevent him from
injuring himself against chairs or benches in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Don Wilson (the former Astros pitcher) have a seizure in
the clubhouse when we were teammates,'' Dierker said. ``It's really
violent, a scary thing to watch. I've gained a lot of respect for
Derek for his willingness to try to hold me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he cared to reflect on his ordeal, Dierker laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to,'' he said. ``But I can't remember much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A news conference by Dierker is scheduled at 10 a.m. CDT
Wednesday. It will be carried live by the Fox Sports Network
Southwest cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
