<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5737 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZAWA-VIENNA-ART-NYT &LR;      06-22 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZAWA-VIENNA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER KEY PODIUM TO BE VACATED AS BOSTON'S OZAWA HEADS FOR
VIENNA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo from Boston Globe is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867. See story, MUSIC-OZAWA-BOS.) 
(bl) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unexpected turn that opens a prime podium in the world of
classical music, the Boston Symphony Orchestra announced Tuesday
that its longtime music director and leading conductor, Seiji
Ozawa, would leave after the 2002 season to take over the baton at
the Vienna State Opera.
</P>
<P>
   The formalization of the decision, the orchestra said, is set
for Wednesday morning in Vienna, where Ozawa, 63, was to meet with
government officials and the opera's manager, Ioan Holender.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, who has led the Boston Symphony since 1973 and is often
referred to as the longest-tenured music director of any of the
world's major orchestras, notified the Boston Symphony's management
Monday. The orchestra's musicians were to be informed by letter
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The shift adds Boston to a list of venerable orchestras that
will have podiums to fill over the coming years _ Berlin,
Philadelphia, New York, Atlanta, Houston, Indianapolis and
Cincinnati and others. Berlin, where Claudio Abbado has announced
his retirement in 2002, is said to be close to a choice between two
likely candidates, Daniel Barenboim, music director of the Chicago
Symphony Orchestra, and Sir Simon Rattle, who recently left
Britain's City of Birmingham Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   This month, another vacancy was filled with the appointment of
the Austrian conductor Franz Welser-Moest by the Cleveland
Orchestra. The New York Philharmonic has said it is looking for a
replacement for Kurt Masur, whose contract expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Some music commentators said they could not remember a time when
so many prime conductorships were up for grabs. Although it has
become common for music directors to divide their time between
ensembles on both sides of the Atlantic, word that Ozawa's career
was to take this turn caught many music world observers by
surprise. He will be setting down in a music capital famous for
being hard on its musical icons from Mahler to von Karajan.
</P>
<P>
   Like that of many fellow conductors, Ozawa's tenure in Boston
has hardly been free of controversy. In 1997 and 1998, the
Tanglewood summer festival under his direction was roiled by
administrative battles and some recent reviews have been harsh,
although others have been favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ozawa's leadership, the Boston Symphony cemented a
reputation as one of the world's leading ensembles, touring widely,
helping to develop Tanglewood as a premier summer music festival,
and building on an endowment that is the envy of many an orchestra.
The 1998-99 season-long celebration of Ozawa's 25th anniversary
with the Symphony drew varying critical assessments. Writing in The
New York Times in November, James R. Oestreich praised his
conducting of the biting, driving ``Miraculous Mandarin'' by Bartok
as ``being just the sort of thing in which Ozawa excels.'' Mahler's
``Lied von der Erde'' was also ``music after Ozawa's heart, big and
bold.''
</P>
<P>
   But in February at Carnegie Hall, another Times critic, Bernard
Holland, detected `'a certain weariness'' and said Ozawa made the
Beethoven Violin Concerto ``sound almost vulgar''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, in his letter to the Boston players, called his years as
music director ``the most rewarding artistic experience that any
musician could ever hope to have.'' He said he would never leave
the Boston Symphony ``for another orchestra,'' but that that ``in
my own growth as a musician, I increasingly have come to love the
operatic repertoire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Symphony said that Ozawa will assume his position in
Vienna after the end of the 2002 Tanglewood summer season, for an
initial term of three years, and that he would be in residence in
Vienna five months a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna State Opera traces its history to the court opera of
the Hapsburgs in the mid-1800s and its intrigues with music
directors over the years have been the stuff of music lore and
history. It has been without a music director for several years
since the departure of Claudio Abbado. In an unusual arrangement,
the opera's musicians also constitute the famously independent and
self-governing Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, which operates
without a music director and engages its own visiting conductors.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Zervas, president of the Boston Symphony's board of
trustees, said ``Vienna's gain is certainly Boston's loss,'' and
voiced hope that Ozawa would continue to lead the orchestra as his
schedule allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The board of trustees will organize a search committee to find a
successor, the orchestra said.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be not easy. With so many leading orchestras on the
hunt for new leadership, it has become a seller's market, even at
salaries of $1 million and up a year. Famous names are floated one
day, only to be shot down the next.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, who was traveling Tuesday with the Vienna Philharmonic in
Baden-Baden, Germany, before breaking off to go to Vienna for the
announcement, began his music career as a youngster in Shenyang,
China. In 1959, at age 24, he won first prize at a competition of
conductors in France, drawing him to the attention of Charles
Munch, then music director of the Boston Symphony, who invited him
to Tanglewood, where he won another prestigious conducting prize.
</P>
<P>
   While working with von Karajan in West Berlin he drew the
attention of New York Philharmonic music director Leonard
Bernstein, who named him assistant conductor in New York for the
1961-2 season. He conducted the Boston Symphony for the first time
at Tanglewood in 1964, became artistic director of Tanglewood in
1970 and music director of the Boston Symphony three years later.
Over the years he has guest-conducted orchestras around the world,
in symphonic programs and opera. On July 4, he is scheduled to lead
the Boston Pops Esplanade Orchestra in its traditional ``1812
Overture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD23-COX     06-22 1914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD: The hype and the hope
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD Inc. and Healtheon Corp. may be poised for a
multibillion-dollar merger, but they are in a business that some
analysts view as smoke and mirrors, touting wildly hyped ability to
deliver goods and services _ let alone make a profit during the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   But wait: These same analysts predict WebMD and Healtheon will
be well-positioned to become a dominant player in their niche
business _ health care services delivered online to physicians,
institutions and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Only when discussing Internet businesses might both perceptions
be true.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Atlanta-based WebMD has come a long way fast. In one
year, WebMD has morphed from a tiny start-up, born from the ashes
of a young entrepreneur's previous company, into a big name on the
Net replete with prestigious board members, an experienced
management team, a merger deal with a California company whose
stock is worth billions and an arrangement for Microsoft to invest
$250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cinderella storyline has everything _ except profits.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in short, a typical Internet success story, told in
Internet time. A company soars to stratospheric value, its flight
fueled by investors blind to traditional measures. Cynics compare
it to the 17th century tulip craze, in which prices rocketed beyond
all reason only to suffer collapse beyond all precedent.
Traditionalists look at the Net and say: Gravity will have its way.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not sheer madness. Look at the potential of the Net as
a conduit for the economy and communications. A new report from the
Commerce Department says the Internet and technology industries
account for at least a third of the U.S. economic growth in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Health care represents 14 percent of the $6 trillion U.S.
economy, more than $840 billion. If any significant portion of that
is shifted to the Net and if WebMD can win any sizable piece of the
market, then current valuations could be far too modest.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too early in the game to take this seriously? No, said
Charlene Li, analyst with Forrester Research. ``They are leaders in
a field that doesn't exist. But they have as good a chance as
anybody to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   What gives them that chance? Does WebMD have the best Web site,
the most visionary business plan, the smartest technology?
</P>
<P>
   No way, Li said. But they might have the fastest, slickest and
most-image savvy sales pitch. And they are surely first in their
class at collecting cash _ by the hundreds of millions of dollars _
needed to market themselves into a winner.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a series of missteps leaves her wondering, she
said. ``There are a lot of things about this company that make me
uneasy. I can't figure out what these guys are doing, what the
value is, because they keep casting about for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet virtues and vulnerabilities can be reversed in the shadow
reality of the Internet. Consider the idea of a business model so
fluid that it's hard to tell from quarter to quarter how the
company expects to make a buck. It could be desperation. It could
be flexibility. The rise from obscurity started with founder
Jeffrey Arnold selling off much of his previous business, Endeavor
Technologies. In August, the company received a $10 million
investment from HBO &AMP; Co. Endeavor Technologies became WebMD with a
board of high-tech stalwarts. Olympic organizer Billy Payne joined
the company as vice chairman. During the next few months, an
experienced management team was named. In November, Jay Gilbertson
left HBO &AMP; Co. as it prepared to merge with McKesson and leapt to
WebMD as it prepared for a public offering of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Then WebMD announced a five-year deal with DuPont, in which the
pharmaceutical giant would pay $220 million, mostly to boost the
company's network of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But the hype reached a crescendo as the company delayed and
finally called off the IPO, choosing instead to merge with
Healtheon. It seemed an ideal fit on paper. WebMD had a
consumer-oriented Web site and an information service for doctors.
Healtheon handled transactions for clinics, insurance companies and
large medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet marriage made in heaven
</P>
<P>
   The stock market loved the match.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD is still privately held, but the current value of
Healtheon stock implies a combined company worth upwards of $6
billion. That would make the company _ which will be based in
Atlanta _ one of the most valuable companies in Georgia,
approaching the value of Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Delta last year had revenues of $14 billion and net income of $1
billion while moving millions of customers around the globe. By
comparison, Healtheon last year had revenues of $49 million along
with a $54 million loss. WebMD last year had revenues of $408,000
and a $23 million loss. Although Healtheon says it will handle 475
million transactions this year, that apparently comes from a
relative handful of customers. WebMD is no longer talking about how
many doctors signed up for its $30-a-month service. As to how many
consumers have clicked onto the Web site _ that, too, is only a
guess.
</P>
<P>
   And along the way, there have been a few WebMD slips.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a case of building a business on Internet time.
WebMD has developed so quickly because it had to, changed direction
because it must be Net nimble. It has slipped once or twice in its
haste. It could also be a simple case of overselling a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company proclaimed its plan to sell services to
doctors as the key to profits. A few months later, WebMD was
emphasizing consumers and advertising as a revenue source. Earlier
this year, founder Arnold listed himself on the company Web site as
a graduate of the University of Georgia. He attended, but has no
diploma. WebMD bought CertifiedMail.com in December, only to file
suit against the company in March, charging that it had been given
false information before the purchase. Arnold also drew criticism
from The Wall Street Journal for near-cocky predictions made during
the ``quiet period'' that follows the announcement of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of Jay Gilbertson
</P>
<P>
   And then came the clumsily handled _ and still pending _
departure of Jay Gilbertson.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson's arrival in November was touted by Arnold and other
officials as proof that the company was for real, compelling
evidence that Wall Street could take seriously its impending offer
of stock. But within a few days, the IPO was called off in favor of
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Healtheon and WebMD announced the combined management
team, Gilbertson's absence from the list of jobs was striking.
Arnold assured reporters that Gilbertson would stay and be given
``an operational role.'' But on June 14, a company spokeswoman said
Gilbertson had resigned _ an announcement that Gilbertson denied
that same day. The following day, the company stopped talking about
Gilbertson altogether _ a sign that only the terms of his departure
were in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, WebMD's claim to a unique set of services was being
undercut by a slew of newcomers also aiming to make a mark in the
health care sector. High-flying IPOs included CareinSite.com and
AmericasDoctor.com. Some like Claims.net, IDX, Atlanta-based
Medcast, Third Millennium Healthcare and AccentHealth are fighting
Healtheon for the online route to doctors or ``back office''
transactions. Others like Dr. Koop, Adam.com, HealthGate, WebDoctor
and CareData.com are striving to become the consumer's portal to
health care information on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   William Michalak, analyst at Wachovia Securities, chalked up the
strategic changes to an astute reading of the market. ``I think
both Healtheon and WebMD were going to approach doctors and they
found them much different than expected. That's why WebMD went to
the consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   What looks like a scramble is a clever effort to gain a foothold
before an inevitable consolidation, he said. ``I think there is
room in the market for five to seven significant players. But it's
like Rubik's Cube or like a multidimensional chess game and we are
not sure who all the players are right now. ''
</P>
<P>
   Wide-open cyberspaces
</P>
<P>
   Terry Lee, executive vice president of Claimsnet.com, said he
thinks there is space for plenty of competition. His company gives
physicians a Net-based method for handling claims, and the
potential is enormous for moving health care from paper to
electronics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 95 percent of all health care records are still
paper-based,'' he said. ``Technology abounds in health care, but
what is hanging on the end of every hospital bed? A clipboard
chart.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks, president and COO of AccentHealth, said his company
serves about 10,000 doctors' offices, most via video feeds to
patients in the waiting room. How that connection develops is hard
to predict, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He foresees selling doctors insurance adjudication, credit card
verification, medical education, videos and software of various
kinds. ``We say that doctors have deep pockets and short arms.
Doctors are not going to adapt technology just for the sake of
technology. They have to have a reason _ either economics or
productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks have for many months been purchased according to
rules that seem not to apply anywhere else. Profitability is simply
irrelevant _ at least for now. What matters is marketing,
deal-making, and _ perhaps most critically _ burning a brand name
into the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has been very good at all that. Among its deals, the
company has agreements with several well-known brands including
Lycos, Excite, CNN, MSNBC and Reader's Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Learning from the king of high tech: Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Quality of technology and service is not the end of the story,
said analyst Li. ``Look at Microsoft. They don't even come close to
having the best products, but they have a marketing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also knows how to scare off rivals with ``vaporware,''
announcement of products that sound frighteningly powerful but are
in fact nowhere near ready. WebMD has _ in some respects _ a
similar approach, Li said. ``It's basically a PR play. It's
vaporware. It may pan out, but not for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The WebMD-Healtheon merger is to be completed by the end of
September. And Microsoft will emerge with 17 percent ownership of
the combined company. And _ vaporware or no _ with the Microsoft
seal of approval, how far away can success be?
</P>
<P>
   Still, Microsoft has leapt aboard many a bandwagon, covering its
bets as with investments ranging from Dialogic Corp.'s computer
phone technology to ThingWorld's streaming media technology to
WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, too, doesn't want to get left behind when the
Internet truly takes off. And while everyone agrees that billions
of dollars are hanging at the horizon, no one yet has the reach to
pick them off. There is as much insecurity as there is
anticipation. Hence, the hysteria and hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebMD has a lot of competition,'' said David Restrepo, analyst
with Jupiter Communications. ``The WebMD-Healtheon merger was
really the kick-off of the hype about the sector. It's going to be
a while until we can assess that hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
