u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAD-STUDIES-NYT &LR;      06-22 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-STUDIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS LEAD POISONING IS TIED TO CHILDREN'S TOOTH DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Calif., Md., N.Y., Ohio) (rk) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children exposed to higher levels of lead have more problems
with tooth decay, according to a new study that suggests that lead
could account for as many as 11 percent of pediatric cavities.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying study that appears in Wednesday's issue of The
Journal of the American Medical Association found that children and
adults who had more vitamin C in their blood had lower levels of
lead, though the researchers stressed that they were not ready to
say that vitamin C could prevent lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to lead has fallen sharply in recent decades since it
was removed from household paint and gasoline. But nearly a million
American children are still believed to have elevated lead levels
in their blood , with consequences that can include a lowering of
I.Q.
</P>
<P>
   Both the studies drew on data from the Third National Health and
Nutrition Examination Survey, which collected detailed information
on thousands of Americans from 1988 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The study on cavities, conducted by Dr. Mark E. Moss and Dr.
Peggy Auinger of the University of Rochester and Dr. Bruce Lamphear
of the Children's Hospital Medical Center of Cincinnati, compared
dental records and blood lead levels from 25,000 children and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on children ages 5 to 17, they found that every
increase of five micrograms per deciliter in lead levels was linked
to an 80 percent increase in risk of tooth decay (the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention has set 10 micrograms as the maximum
acceptable level).
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are not sure how lead exposure may lead to
cavities, and Moss said that the next step in research would be to
figure out the mechanism involved. He speculated that lead either
reduced production of saliva, which contains elements that protect
teeth, or crowded out calcium during tooth formation or prevented
fluoride from bonding with tooth enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Tooth decay is concentrated among poorer, inner city children;
20 percent of the nation's children account for about 80 percent of
cavities. ``Tooth decay is a major health problem by itself,''
Lamphear said. ``This study provides additional evidence that lead
is a system toxin and that further efforts to reduce residential
hazards are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Goldstein, director of the Kennedy-Krieger Institute, a
center for the study of developmental disabilities in Baltimore,
said the research appeared to show a striking correlation but
should be replicated in a more focused study. ``When you have these
huge mountains of data, you have to remember that there were 10,000
other items asked about and try to try to look for the association
again in a prospective study,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The study examining vitamin C and lead levels also found a
striking link, but its authors were even more cautious about
suggesting the vitamin as a possible lead countermeasure. Anecdotal
evidence and studies dating from the World War II era, along with a
recent animal study, have suggested that the vitamin could be an
effective treatment for lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, two epidemiologists from the University of
California at San Francisco, Dr. Joel A. Simon and Dr. Esther S.
Hudes, looked at 19,000 children and adults and found that youths
with the highest levels of vitamin C in their blood were almost
twice as likely to also have low levels of lead in their blood as
youths with low levels of the vitamin.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers found no correlation between lead levels and
the amount of vitamin C the survey subjects reported eating, which
they speculated could either be due to a flaw in the survey or
because lead caused vitamin C to be flushed out of the body more
quickly. They also cautioned that the correlation they found could
be related to factors like a healthier way of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-BUSH-CUSTOMS-NYT &LR;      06-22 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUSH-CUSTOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. BUSH OF FLORIDA EXPLAINS WIFE'S CUSTOMS INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The first lady of Florida was worried about how her
husband would react to the fact that she had spent $19,000 on
clothes and jewelry during a shopping spree in Paris, and that is
why she told U.S. Customs Service agents that she had spent only
$500, Gov. Jeb Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you, it was a difficult weekend at our house,''
Bush said this week, adding that his wife, Columba Bush, is
suffering ``a deep feeling of remorse'' over her decision to
undervalue her purchases when she entered the country through
Customs at Hartsfield International Airport in Atlanta last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew what she did was wrong and made a mistake,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy, which Mrs. Bush called ``bad judgment,''
resulted in a civil fine of $4,100, and wound up as fodder for
front-page newspaper stories, radio call-in shows and spirited,
street-corner discussion around Florida. It spiced the radio and
television airwaves in Spanish and English in Miami, and became the
butt of jokes on the Howard Stern radio show.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a time when Florida's Bush is working after hours to
raise money and line up support for his older brother, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, who is running for the Republican presidential
nomination. And the $19,000 shopping spree _ which cost Mrs. Bush
$23,100 with the fines _ comes at a time when Republicans are
trying to persuade potential voters that the Republican Party is no
longer just a party for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, speaking to reporters at a news conference in
Tallahassee, the state capital, apologized on behalf of his wife
but added that the shopping spree itself was ``our money and our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any embarrassment it could cause in his brother's
campaign, Bush told reporters: ``Anything is possible in politics
in 1999. There is no dividing line anymore, as there should be,''
between public and private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts in Florida and elsewhere in the country, while
conceding the embarrassing nature of the incident, said they
doubted it would have even the slightest impact on either of the
Bush brothers' careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the stuff of which political commercials are
made,'' said Q. Whitfield Ayres, a Republican pollster based in
Atlanta. ``I mean, a Democrat is going to attack the Hispanic wife
of George Bush's brother? I'd like to see somebody try it,'' Ayres
said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Democrats have been mostly silent on the incident and
political experts who track voting trends and politics in Florida
say the attention it has brought the Bush family will soon blow
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is embarrassing publicly and privately but will
ultimately have no effect at all on Jeb Bush, his popularity in
this state or his chances in Florida,'' said Jim Kane, editor of
The Florida Voter, a news and polling service in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, Kane said, will it have an impact on Gov. George W. Bush's
political destiny in Florida, beyond being a ``footnote in Florida
presidential politics.''
</P>
<P>
   If it had been Jeb Bush himself who had misled the Customs
agents, it could have called into question his honesty, making ``a
significant difference,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Customs incident was no longer an issue in his
home. His wife, he said, is a private person, not ``a political
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   It all began on Thursday when Mrs. Bush, returning from a trip
to Paris that Bush had promised her during his campaign for
governor in 1998, was asked by a Customs agent if she had anything
to declare. Mrs. Bush, who had not been accompanied on the trip by
her husband, said she had bought just $500 worth of clothes and
jewelry. Travelers who purchase $400 or less pay no duty, or tax,
on the goods.
</P>
<P>
   But Customs agents found receipts for thousands of dollars of
clothes and jewelry stuffed in her passport.
</P>
<P>
   She was fined, and immediately wrote a check for the penalty _
about four times what she would have paid if she had admitted the
value of the goods and just paid the duty.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was a distraction for Bush on Monday, a day in
which he signed legislation that had been the cornerstone of his
campaign. Bush had promised to install a controversial school
vouchers program _ in which students in the state's worst schools
could receive state money to go to private or religious schools _
as part of his education reform package.
</P>
<P>
   Many public school teachers and administrators have fought the
program, which is certain to be challenged in state courts by
opponents who say it violates constitutional bans on financing
religious schools with taxpayer dollars. And on Tuesday, civil
rights groups filed a complaint in a state circuit court in
Tallahassee to block the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the school voucher program drew the attention of
educators and politicians, it was the airport incident that had
people talking in the streets in Miami, St. Petersburg and other
places around the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the jokes will soon die down, and few will even remember the
incident, said political experts and supporters of Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very upfront about this from the start, and then we
moved on,'' said Cory Tilley, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As for any political backlash down the road, Republicans seem
unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a stretch,'' Ayres said, ``worthy of an Olympic
gymnast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
