<HEADLINE>
OLD TRIESTE OUT OF GOLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old Trieste developed a fever Tuesday and was withdrawn from
Sunday's Hollywood Gold Cup, costing the brilliant front-runner a
shot at national prominence and leaving Hollywood Park with a short
field for its $1 million race.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Mike Puype said that when he went to his barn at the
afternoon feeding time, he found Old Trieste ``looked miserable,
very uncomfortable.'' The 4-year-old colt had a 103-degree
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Gary Biszantz indicated the illness stems from the body's
efforts to fight a recurrence of a foot abscess, one of the
maladies that sidelined Old Trieste for months before his
seven-length victory in the May 29 Californian.
</P>
<P>
   And Biszantz said that although Old Trieste could be well in
three or four days, ``you can't consider running him in a Grade I
race very soon after a glitch like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Trieste and jockey Chris McCarron would have been favored to
win the Fox-televised race against four other Southern
California-based horses _ 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet
(Jerry Bailey), the Richard Mandella-trained duo of Puerto Madero
(Kent Desormeaux) and Malek (Alex Solis), and longshot Budroyale
(Garrett Gomez).
</P>
<P>
   The son of 1992 Horse of the Year A.P. Indy would have been
shooting for his fifth consecutive victory following a 10th-place
finish in the '98 Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating, you just don't know how devastating,'' Puype
said of missing the Gold Cup, for which entries will be taken
Thursday. ``We'll just have to get him ready for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   A likely target is the Aug. 29 Pacific Classic, final leg of the
NTRA Champions on Fox series for older horses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
