<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN FINANCIAL ECLIPSE IS OPPORTUNITY FOR FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Looking beyond Russia's severe economic problems, Ford
Motor Co. announced a preliminary agreement with the government
Tuesday to begin construction in July of an automobile factory near
St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford's financial contribution is only $150 million, the
plant would be among the largest foreign investment projects in
Russia since the financial crisis that began nearly a year ago. A
final agreement on the plant is expected in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting in Moscow on Monday between Ford's president, Jacques
Nasser, and Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin reflected the
seriousness of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said in a statement that the plant represented ``an
important step in achieving our long-term growth objectives.'' And
Alain Batty, president of Ford Russia, said ``this will be a sound
agreement both in terms of the present rate of economic development
and Russia's huge potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans to establish a manufacturing joint venture with
Bankers House-St. Petersburg, a consortium comprising three
influential local banks. The exact terms of the venture were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The factory site is an existing facility once operated by
state-owned heavy machinery maker Russky Diesel and is situated in
the region surrounding St. Petersburg. Although the plant will be
designed to produce up to 100,000 cars annually, the company said
initial output of its new compact Ford Focus line would be about
25,000 vehicles. Ford expects the factory to be fully operational
by the first half of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker already has a small plant in a neighboring former
Soviet republic, Belarus, where it applies the finishing touches to
nearly assembled cars that are shipped in from factories abroad.
</P>
<P>
   While the new plant in the town of Vsevolozhsk is likely to
start with such assembly projects, Ford plans to gradually shift
more of the entire production process there.
</P>
<P>
   The company has chosen to expand its work in Russia at a time
when sales of imported cars have fallen drastically. The ruble has
lost about 80 percent of its value against the dollar since the
crisis began, which has priced foreign-made cars out of the range
of most Russians. Ford's plant in Belarus stood idle for months as
the company gradually sold off inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis has made foreign car companies either forget Russia
or become de facto domestic producers to cut costs,'' said Kim
Iskyan, an equity analyst with Renaissance Capital, a Russian
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Renault recently delayed until August the signing of a formal
agreement to begin manufacturing in Moscow, and Fiat has deferred
the start of a project in Nizhny Novgorod to some time next year.
</P>
<P>
   But BMW recently announced a car-assembly project in the far
western Russian enclave of Kaliningrad, and General Motors is in
discussions with Russia's largest car manufacturer, Avto Vaz, about
developing a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has sought to attract foreign car makers by offering tax
and customs breaks on their imported parts and machinery, which
would help make the non-Russian vehicles closer in price to
domestic ones. But such concessions are often insufficient to
compensate for the political and economic uncertainty that Russia
has presented in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such barriers to investment, it appears that few car
companies are willing to entirely abandon Russia. Faced with stiff
competition in more stable markets, the automakers hope to increase
sales by entering new markets such as Russia where the level of car
ownership is low. But analysts warn that the payoff is further in
the future than manufacturers may think.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ford really does have a long-term vision for Russia,''
Iskyan said, ``then maybe 10 years from now, when Russians are
buying one million cars a year, it will have a nice little car on
the market and 30 percent of the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5752 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAY-STEVENS-ART-2TAKE     06-22 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAY-STEVENS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRUSADER WHO LETS HER HEROES BE HUMAN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Ken Shulman recently wrote in Arts and Leisure about the
restoration of the Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi.  
 By KEN SHULMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The painting is called ``Forming the Fifth
International.'' On one side of the oversize canvas sits Rosa
Luxemburg, the Polish-born socialist leader assassinated in Berlin
in 1919 when she was 48.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, a figure from a different era, is Alice
Stevens, an aged, infirm, nursing-home patient who died in 1985 at
age 89. Rosa is weightless, a black and white projection. Alice is
heavy, pink and fleshy. Rosa stares out at the viewer; she seems to
intuit her imminent martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   Alice seems to stare at Rosa, rubbing her own swollen knee and
ankle and squinting behind her eyeglasses at the unfamiliar woman
beside her. Aside from the painting's rich green background, these
women share nothing. It is the type of meeting that could take
place only in art.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was voiceless,'' said May Stevens, artist, activist,
daughter of Alice Stevens and subject of the show ``May Stevens:
Images of Women Near and Far'' at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts
through Aug. 8. A show of Ms. Stevens' drawings and prints is on
view concurrently at the Mary Ryan Gallery in New York through Aug.
27.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not able to participate in the world at all,'' Ms.
Stevens continued. ``She essentially withdrew from life. And Rosa
was able to participate to the utmost, even though she was killed
for it. I want both of them to continue as symbols. I want Rosa and
her work to be remembered. But I also want Alice to be remembered,
to validate the lives of women like her, women who are discounted
when they are old and heavy and no longer glamorous or charming.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a message in Ms. Stevens' medium. For more
than five decades, her art has been animated by a host of political
and social causes. Born in 1924 into a working-class family in
Quincy, Mass., Ms. Stevens went on to attend the Massachusetts
College of Art in Boston. In 1947 she moved to New York, where she
met the painter Rudolf Baranik at the Art Students League. Baranik
had fled his native Lithuania in 1938. His parents, Lithuanian
Jews, were killed there during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The couple soon married and left for Paris in 1948. Ms. Stevens
had her first solo show there and also created her first political
painting, ``The Martinsville Seven,'' a work about seven black men
who had been accused of rape in Virginia. The couple returned to
New York in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Ms. Stevens and Baranik championed civil rights
and protested against the war in Vietnam. Their art was
transparently political. But it was also intensely personal.
Baranik, who died last year, is best known for ``Napalm Elegies,''
a series of paintings about the Vietnam War that also served as
unstated elegy for his murdered parents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevens first came into prominence in the late 1960s with
her ``Big Daddy'' series, a group of large paintings done over nine
years in which she expressed her resistance to racism, militarism
and sexism, along with her ambivalent feelings toward her father,
whom she remembers as a racist.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Ms. Stevens channeled much of her energy into
feminism. In 1976, she was a founding member of the feminist
journal Heresies, a publication whose founders included Lucy
Lippard, Joan Snyder and Miriam Schapiro. From 1976 through 1992,
Ms. Stevens painted her ``Ordinary/Extraordinary'' series,
contrasting the figure of Luxemburg with that of her own mother, a
woman she describes as ``housewife, mother, washer and ironer,
inmate of hospitals and nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevens readily admits that Luxemburg represents her
spiritual and intellectual mother. Yet the artist does not
repudiate her biological mother. Different as they were, Alice and
Rosa are presented as pawned icons that the artist has redeemed
from an archetypal store of memory. Both women are given equal
dignity. Both are equally tragic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not despise who I was, nor where I came from,'' said Ms.
Stevens, who left New York for Santa Fe in 1997, shortly before her
husband died. ``Because it's all part of this process. I think I
was trying to make Rosa real for me, and not just a figure I read
about in books. And I was trying to get some distance from my
mother. Because she was so powerful for me. And because she was so
unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Images of Women Near and Far'' features more than a dozen
large acrylic paintings done from 1983 through 1997. Most are from
the ``Ordinary/Extraordinary'' series. Several of the canvases are
unstretched, hanging down from wooden dowels like tapestries or
movie screens. The human figures, most of which are based on
photographs, look almost like slides one might use to illustrate a
sociology lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Ms. Stevens' canvases include text, with citations
from Christopher Marlowe, Virginia Woolf and, of course, Rosa
Luxemburg. The works are not quite as pedantic as primitive church
art, or as propagandistic as the posters Soviet leaders directed at
the Russian people after the Bolshevik Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevens' figures are working-class heroes, vehicles of
destiny intended to edify. But they are also fragile human vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can isolate an image that truly sticks in your mind,''
said Patricia Hills, a professor of art history at Boston
University, who has written extensively on Ms. Stevens. ``This is
what makes her work so haunting and elegaic. She is, of course, a
wonderful manipulator of paint. But she's not just interested in
surface. And this is where she distinguishes herself from so many
of her contemporaries. Her work is of her time. But she is not
narrowly topical. And in time, I think she will emerge as a major
painter of the late 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sea of Words,'' her most recent series, Ms. Stevens covers
her canvases with a dense, handwritten text taken from Virginia
Woolf and Julia Kristeva. Done in refulgent gold, the text becomes
the shimmering surface of a body of water. A group of boats floats
across the water. Some of them are empty; others carry ghostly
female forms, rowing through the verbiage. The Museum of Fine Arts
show includes four paintings from this latest series. The allegory
is almost embarrassingly legible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the work is once again redeemed by an implicit reference to
Ms. Stevens' childhood, the ``golden river'' formed by the sun
shining across the Quincy bay on a late summer afternoon. It is a
highly personal image that Ms. Stevens transforms into an
archetype, the same sort of alchemy that gilds all her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed that I could make a difference,'' Ms.
Stevens said, standing in front of ``Go Gentle'' (1983). The
painting is a composite of images showing her mother as child,
young woman and nursing-home patient. The final image shows Alice
seated on her stool, mute and frightened. She raises her hands in
an attempt to articulate words she cannot form. But the hands
dissolve before her eyes. It is the most powerful work in the show,
one that has caused more than one visitor to pause and weep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware of injustice, of the horrible things that have
happened during my lifetime,'' Ms. Stevens said. ``But I also
believe that the only way to live is to work against those things.
And I believe that I have something to give. I have always believed
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
