<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 06/22/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1999 -- EDUCATION-CONGRESS, 6-22
-- The House majority leader, Dick Armey, is among lawmakers
greeting youths in a school bus Tuesday at a news conference to
promote a Republican education bill. The bill builds significantly
on previous Republican efforts to give state and local governments
ever broader discretion over the spending of federal money. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MOSCOW -- June 22, 1999 -- RUSSIA-Y2K, 6-22 -- Boris V.
Mikhailovich, a top computer specialist at the Russian Federal
Aviation Service, is one of the numerous Russian experts who bridle
at the notion that their end-of-millenium efforts may not meet
Western standards. When asked whether air-traffic-control centers
were ready, he has a ready response. ``What do you think I am?'' he
asks, ``An enemy of my own people?'' (Jacqueline Mia Foster/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WUHAN, China -- June 22, 1999 -- ARGENTINA-BUDWEISER,
6-22 -- China has become Anheuser's fifth-largest overseas market
since Budweiser was introduced there in 1993. Through aggressive
marketing to a young, upscale and better educated slice of the
world's population - the same people who drink imports, as it
happens, back in St. Louis, where Anheuser is based - the company
is hoping to turn Budweiser into a truly global brand, something no
other has ever pulled off. (New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) LOS ANGELES -- June 21, 1999 -- BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON-2,
6-21 -- Fred Meeks at home with his wife Elinore. During World War
II, an explosion on a segregated naval base killed 320 men. After
the accident, black sailors were ordered to resume loading
ammunition onto ships. Fifty of the sailors, Meeks among them,
refused and were court-martialed by an all-white panel after being
found guilty of mutiny. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle,
lawyers for Meeks have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that
the black sailors failed to follow orders out of legitimate fear
and had no intent to mutiny. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1999 -- OZAWA-VIENNA, 6-22 -- Seiji
Ozawa conducts the Boston Symphny Orchestra at Carnegie Hall in
October, 1997. With top classical music orchestras already shopping
for scarce new leadership, the Boston Symphony Orchestra joined the
worldwide game of musical chairs with a surprise announcement that
Ozawa, its long-reigning conductor, will leave after the 2002
season to take over the Vienna State Opera. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-3, 6-22 -- Bone fragments seen on Tuesday in an area
where authorities suspect a mass grave existed. Serb forces dug up
some 100 massacred ethnic Albanians from a mass grave here late
last month and carried the bodies off, apparently to hide evidence
from the Hague war crimes tribunal, the municipal official in
charge of burials said on Tuesday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- June 22, 1999 -- SPACE-TRAVEL-COX, 6-22 --
Artist's rendering of an idea by the Space Island Group for
building orbiting hotels from the discarded external fuel tanks of
the space shuttle. It would be easy for shuttle crews to release
the tanks in space, says Gene Myers, president of the Space Island
Group, which is seeking funding through corporate sponsorships
similar to those for the Olympics. ``The tanks are as big as a
747,'' he says, and could be fitted together into a wheel shape.
(Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1999 -- BUSH-REPUBS, 6-22 -- Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, running for the Republican presidential
nomination, addresses Republican Senators, Tuesday on Capitol Hill.
Bush denounced Vice President Al Gore as a Washington insider
Tuesday but promised fellow party members in Congress he would
stand with them. At right is Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1999 -- HATCH-2000, 6-22 -- Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, with Warren Rudman, a former U.S. Senator and
current chairman of the President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board, on Tuesday. Hatch, the conservative chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said Tuesday he intends to make what he admits
will be a long-shot bid for the 2000 Republican presidential
nomination. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1999 -- LABUTE-PROFILE-2, 6-22 --
Calista Flockhart is a teen-ager seduced by her teacher in
``Medea,'' part of Neil LaBute's ``Bash, Latterday Plays,'' at the
Douglas Fairbanks. For many moviegoers there is nothing more
depressing on screen than a LaBute film. And now with ``Bash,
Latterday Plays,'' he has done it again, for the stage this time.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1999 -- LABUTE-PROFILE-1, 6-22 --
Neil LaBute's new play, ``Bash, Latterday Plays,'' opens Thursday
at the Douglas Fairbanks. For many moviegoers there is nothing more
depressing on screen than a LaBute film. Nothing more likely to
induce despair, or more frightening, perhaps, for what it shows us
about ourselves. Sexual cruelty. Domination. Hatred. LaBute shoves
them in your face. And now, he has done it again, for the stage
this time. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOD, Israel -- June 22, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLICE-SHOOTING,
6-22 -- A woman walks near the rubble of what is left of an
Israeli-Arab family's home which was demolished on Sunday. The
Israeli-Arab population, which was courted by and voted for Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak, is certain to accelerate its quest for
civil rights during his administration. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEWTON, Mass. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-BULLY-BOS, 6-22 --
Ted Harrington, left, with his father, Wesley Edward Harrington IV.
Ted was not a classic bully who used hostility to vent his anger
and insecurity. Rather, as a player in the often confusing,
socially uneasy, sometimes cruel culture of American boyhood, he
was one of those kids who initiate taunts rather than stand to the
side or take the heat themselves. ``It took being the victim to
realize it wasn't as fun as I thought it had been,'' he says. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ORLANDO, Fla. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-EXPECTATIONS-BOS,
6-22 -- Richard E. Lapchick, left, with his son Joe. By all
accounts, Joe Lapchick (Richard's father) was as gifted a father as
he was a coach and athlete. In turn, Richard, as a teacher, author,
human rights activist, and director of Northeastern University's
Center for the Study of Sport in Society, has spent much of his
life promoting better parenting by sharing the lessons he learned
from his father. ``Joe Lapchick was my hero,'' he says. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FAIRFAX, Va. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-MOTHERS-BOS, 6-22
-- Alex, Luke and Karen Taylor. Jeff Taylor's brain cancer and
death three years ago, when he was 41, clearly left a huge hole in
the Taylor family's heart. It also launched his wife, Karen, on a
difficult journey to find the stamina, means, faith, and humor to
fill Jeff's big fathering shoes and to raise their two boys. ``From
the beginning, I told myself there was no way I was gonna let these
boys fall through the cracks,'' she says. (John Blanding/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-NOTIME-BOS,
6-22 -- The Rev. Edward Palmer, left, with his son, Jadwin. It has
not been an easy path for father or son, though Palmer is hardly
the only father to struggle to balance great expectations and
tenderness, his own high ambitions and the time a child needs.
``You've go to remember, I came from a broken family before so I
always promised never to let my family be the same way,'' he says.
(John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) RAPID CITY, S.D. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-GUNS-BOS, 6-22
-- Glenn Jones, left, with his father, Ronn Jones. Glenn, 15, owns
three guns. Out here , in the West - less wild these days but still
wide open - that's the way it's always been and is supposed to be.
Children learn to shoot, and their fathers are proud to help. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DALLAS -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-OUTCAST-BOS, 6-22 --
18-year-old Willi Wagner, left, with his father Bill Wagner, before
being chaperoned to a ``gay prom'' in Dallas last month. In order
to protect his son from the rampant anti-homosexual racism of
Booneville, Ark., Wagner moved his family to Fayetteville, a
relatively liberal college community two hours away that bills
itself as ``The first home of Bill and Hillary Clinton.'' (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1999 -- NUCLEAR-SPYING-FLOATER,
6-22 -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson listens to former U.S.
Sen. Warren Rudman, currently chairman of the Presidents' Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board, during testimony before a Senate
committee on Tuesday. Richardson predicted that he would reach
agreement with Congress on a plan to tighten security at his
agency's nuclear labs, which have been hit with allegations of
Chinese spying. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-2, 6-22 -- Faton Polloshka, director of the local
sanitation agency, during an interview on Tuesday. Polloshka claims
that he, along with his employees, were forced by Serb forces to
dig up the remains of some 100 ethnic Albanians last month who had
been massacred. According to Polloshka, the Serbs removed the
remains to hide evidence from the Hague war crimes tribunal.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 1999 --
SUB-KOSOVO-GRAVES, 6-22 -- Bone fragments seen in a home on
Tuesday. Investigators from the International War Crimes Tribunal,
journalists and human rights researchers are fanning further out
through Kosovo finding more and more evidence of mass killings and
widespread destruction. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
-- EDS: DELETES REFERENCE THAT THERE REMAINS WERE FOUND IN A MASS
GRAVE IN A FIELD IN DJAKOVICA
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1999 -- NUDE-CHEFS, 6-22 -- Marcus
Samuelson, the chef at Aquavit, is made up for an advertising
campaign for Vita-Prep's blender series. The chef as a hunk in
advertising campaigns is a development that some chefs revel in
while others tolerate. And still others find silly and
trivializing. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-6, 6-22
-- A bluefin tuna is prepared by a fishmonger in the island off
Sicily. For hundreds of years, the fishermen of Favignana could
live off the sea. But the cannery on the island closed 16 years ago
for lack of product. Because of falling prices, almost none of the
sons of the tonnoretti, as the local fishermen are known, work at
sea. Instead they find jobs catering to the island's tourists, or
they head to the mainland. The sea no longer holds the work of the
future. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-5, 6-22
-- A bluefin tuna is pulled into a boat off Sicily by fishermen
known locally as tonnoretti. The fishermen of this little island
off Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way
for the last 900 years. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-4, 6-22
-- A small fishing boat on the beach in front of the old tuna
factory which is now closed. For hundreds of years, the fishermen
of Favignana could live off the sea. But the cannery on the island
closed 16 years ago for lack of product. Because of falling prices,
almost none of the sons of the tonnoretti, as the local fishermen
are known, work at sea. Instead they find jobs catering to the
island's tourists, or they head to the mainland. The sea no longer
holds the work of the future. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-3, 6-22
-- Bluefin tuna are pulled onto a boat off Sicily by fishermen
known locally as tonnoretti. The fishermen of this little island
off Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way
for the last 900 years. For the four weeks when the huge fish
migrate through these waters, the men await a signal each day from
their leader to begin the hunt, which they call the mattanza.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-2, 6-22
-- Fishermen, known locally as tonnoretti, pull in a haul of
bluefin tuna. The fishermen of this little island off Sicily have
gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way for the last 900
years. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate through these
waters, the men await a signal each day from their leader to begin
the hunt, which they call the mattanza. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-1, 6-22
-- Clemente, a tonnoretti, or fisherman, steers his boat out to sea
to fish for bluefin tuna. The fishermen of this little island off
Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way for
the last 900 years. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate
through these waters, the men await a signal each day from their
leader to begin the hunt, which they call the mattanza. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
