   (NYT14) FAIRFAX, Va. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-MOTHERS-BOS, 6-22
-- Alex, Luke and Karen Taylor. Jeff Taylor's brain cancer and
death three years ago, when he was 41, clearly left a huge hole in
the Taylor family's heart. It also launched his wife, Karen, on a
difficult journey to find the stamina, means, faith, and humor to
fill Jeff's big fathering shoes and to raise their two boys. ``From
the beginning, I told myself there was no way I was gonna let these
boys fall through the cracks,'' she says. (John Blanding/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-NOTIME-BOS,
6-22 -- The Rev. Edward Palmer, left, with his son, Jadwin. It has
not been an easy path for father or son, though Palmer is hardly
the only father to struggle to balance great expectations and
tenderness, his own high ambitions and the time a child needs.
``You've go to remember, I came from a broken family before so I
always promised never to let my family be the same way,'' he says.
(John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) RAPID CITY, S.D. -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-GUNS-BOS, 6-22
-- Glenn Jones, left, with his father, Ronn Jones. Glenn, 15, owns
three guns. Out here , in the West - less wild these days but still
wide open - that's the way it's always been and is supposed to be.
Children learn to shoot, and their fathers are proud to help. (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DALLAS -- June 22, 1999 -- MEN-OUTCAST-BOS, 6-22 --
18-year-old Willi Wagner, left, with his father Bill Wagner, before
being chaperoned to a ``gay prom'' in Dallas last month. In order
to protect his son from the rampant anti-homosexual racism of
Booneville, Ark., Wagner moved his family to Fayetteville, a
relatively liberal college community two hours away that bills
itself as ``The first home of Bill and Hillary Clinton.'' (John
Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- June 22, 1999 -- NUCLEAR-SPYING-FLOATER,
6-22 -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson listens to former U.S.
Sen. Warren Rudman, currently chairman of the Presidents' Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board, during testimony before a Senate
committee on Tuesday. Richardson predicted that he would reach
agreement with Congress on a plan to tighten security at his
agency's nuclear labs, which have been hit with allegations of
Chinese spying. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 1999 --
KOSOVO-GRAVES-2, 6-22 -- Faton Polloshka, director of the local
sanitation agency, during an interview on Tuesday. Polloshka claims
that he, along with his employees, were forced by Serb forces to
dig up the remains of some 100 ethnic Albanians last month who had
been massacred. According to Polloshka, the Serbs removed the
remains to hide evidence from the Hague war crimes tribunal.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 22, 1999 --
SUB-KOSOVO-GRAVES, 6-22 -- Bone fragments seen in a home on
Tuesday. Investigators from the International War Crimes Tribunal,
journalists and human rights researchers are fanning further out
through Kosovo finding more and more evidence of mass killings and
widespread destruction. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
-- EDS: DELETES REFERENCE THAT THERE REMAINS WERE FOUND IN A MASS
GRAVE IN A FIELD IN DJAKOVICA
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 22, 1999 -- NUDE-CHEFS, 6-22 -- Marcus
Samuelson, the chef at Aquavit, is made up for an advertising
campaign for Vita-Prep's blender series. The chef as a hunk in
advertising campaigns is a development that some chefs revel in
while others tolerate. And still others find silly and
trivializing. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-6, 6-22
-- A bluefin tuna is prepared by a fishmonger in the island off
Sicily. For hundreds of years, the fishermen of Favignana could
live off the sea. But the cannery on the island closed 16 years ago
for lack of product. Because of falling prices, almost none of the
sons of the tonnoretti, as the local fishermen are known, work at
sea. Instead they find jobs catering to the island's tourists, or
they head to the mainland. The sea no longer holds the work of the
future. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-5, 6-22
-- A bluefin tuna is pulled into a boat off Sicily by fishermen
known locally as tonnoretti. The fishermen of this little island
off Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way
for the last 900 years. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-4, 6-22
-- A small fishing boat on the beach in front of the old tuna
factory which is now closed. For hundreds of years, the fishermen
of Favignana could live off the sea. But the cannery on the island
closed 16 years ago for lack of product. Because of falling prices,
almost none of the sons of the tonnoretti, as the local fishermen
are known, work at sea. Instead they find jobs catering to the
island's tourists, or they head to the mainland. The sea no longer
holds the work of the future. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-3, 6-22
-- Bluefin tuna are pulled onto a boat off Sicily by fishermen
known locally as tonnoretti. The fishermen of this little island
off Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way
for the last 900 years. For the four weeks when the huge fish
migrate through these waters, the men await a signal each day from
their leader to begin the hunt, which they call the mattanza.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-2, 6-22
-- Fishermen, known locally as tonnoretti, pull in a haul of
bluefin tuna. The fishermen of this little island off Sicily have
gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way for the last 900
years. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate through these
waters, the men await a signal each day from their leader to begin
the hunt, which they call the mattanza. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FAVIGNANA, Italy -- June 22, 1999 -- ITALY-TUNA-1, 6-22
-- Clemente, a tonnoretti, or fisherman, steers his boat out to sea
to fish for bluefin tuna. The fishermen of this little island off
Sicily have gone after bluefin tuna in the same ceremonial way for
the last 900 years. For the four weeks when the huge fish migrate
through these waters, the men await a signal each day from their
leader to begin the hunt, which they call the mattanza. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
