u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS &LR;      06-22 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHUNT CONTINUES FOR SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nationwide manhunt for suspected serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez focused Tuesday on Illinois, where authorities
think the rail-riding vagabond may be a suspect in a third killing
in that state.
</P>
<P>
   In Pontiac, 80 miles southeast of Chicago, officials said
Resendez-Ramirez is a possible suspect in last week's slaying of
40-year-old Juanita Sapp, whose body was found near her apartment
complex.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday _ the same day the FBI included him on its Ten Most
Wanted Fugitives list _ Resendez-Ramirez was charged in the deaths
of two people in the tiny downstate-Illinois town of Gorham.
</P>
<P>
   Like the six homicides already credited to Resendez-Ramirez in
Texas and Kentucky, all three Illinois victims were killed a short
distance from railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he got out of Texas,'' said Texas Department of
Public Safety spokesman Tom Vinger. ``It got too hot for him here.
Unfortunately, that doesn't mean that he won't come back. I'm not
saying that to scare people. It's just that we shouldn't let our
guard down. ... There's no reason to believe he's stopped
killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez's movement north prompted some investigators to
speculate he may be heading for the Canadian border. Federal
authorities acknowledged Tuesday that that was a possibility, but
said it would change nothing in their search.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, 38, has ridden the rails for at least 20
years, authorities say. A Mexican national, he's been convicted of
federal offenses in Texas and Missouri and served time for state
crimes in New Mexico and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He's been charged in five Texas slayings _ two in Houston, two
in Weimer and one in Schulenburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously getting satisfaction from these crimes,''
Vinger said. ``He's brutal. He's sadistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac Police Chief Don Schlosser said Sapp's body was found
under a pile of brush outside her apartment complex early last
Wednesday. Her death, he said, was caused by ``physical trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no firearm used,'' he said. ``I don't want to say
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlosser said results of tests to determine if Sapp _ like many
of the other victims _ had been sexually assaulted should be
available by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are considering him a suspect because the crime occurred
near a railroad track and because there is evidence that
Resendez-Ramirez had been active elsewhere in the state,''
Schlosser said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gorham authorities charged him with first-degree
murder in the deaths of George Morber, 79, and his daughter,
Carolyn Frederick, 51. Morber, investigators said, was shot in the
head with a shotgun; his daughter was beaten to death with the
firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprints were found in the victims' car.
</P>
<P>
   Until late Tuesday, he had been a suspect in a second Illinois
double slaying, in Apple River, near the Wisconsin border. But
Sheriff Steven Allendorf said a local man had been arrested and
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Texas, Hughes Spring Police Chief Randy Kennedy
awaited word on whether the killing of an 87-year-old woman could
also be attributed to Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Lefie Mason, who lived alone in the town of 2,000
north of Tyler, was found Oct. 2. She had been beaten to death by
an intruder who entered her home through an unlocked window.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's home was near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Rewards for information leading to the suspect's arrest and
conviction now total $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
