<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO HEARS LONESOME WHISTLE BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not wanting to belie their clean and wholesome image
by complaining about the officiating in Game 3 of the NBA finals,
the San Antonio Spurs heaped praise upon the Knicks Tuesday while
refraining from the most overt forms of referee bashing.
</P>
<P>
   But during Tuesday's session with the news media, the Spurs'
feelings came out, even if the words did not.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell managed to get
to the foul line 22 times in Game 3, after totaling only 16
free-throw attempts over the first two games, Spurs Coach Gregg
Popovich smiled and kept silent. But his smirk, along with the way
he ran his fingers across his mouth as if zipping his lips, spoke
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, Sean Elliott, the Spurs' small forward, said the
Knicks were probably not the only ones who were pleased that this
initially lopsided series now stands at a competitive two games to
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as New York and NBC and the league are concerned, yeah,
I'm sure they're happy that the series is prolonged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Spurs were sending a subtle message to Wednesday
night's officiating crew, trying to create an us-against-the-world
mirage, or reacting in a spoiled-brat fashion after losing for the
first time in 13 games, the San Antonio players clearly had
questions about the work of the referees Monday night at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the Spurs' eyes, physical contact that was viewed as
aggressive, hard-nosed defense in the Alamodome suddenly became a
foul. And the Spurs' guards, Mario Elie and Jaren Jackson, suffered
because of it. Elie, San Antonio's best perimeter defender, was
whistled for two fouls in the game's first 1 minute 57 seconds.
Under five minutes later, his backup, Jackson, was forced to the
bench with two fouls himself, leaving Houston virtually free to
overpower the defense of the undersized reserves, Antonio Davis and
Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mario's an aggressive defender, and at home he was allowed to
defend them hard and last night he was taken out of the game right
away,'' said Kerr, a finals expert after playing on the Chicago
Bulls' last three title-winning teams. ``But that's the way it
goes. You're going to have some things like that happen on the
road. I think guys know that. Guys have been in the league a few
years, and it's always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The next two games are at the Garden, which could bode ill for
the Spurs. But Elie said he would not change his style and would go
after Houston with the same ferocity that has made him one of the
National Basketball Association's most respected defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let the ticky-tack fouls change my game,'' Elie said.
``I'm going to come out with the same aggressiveness that I've been
coming with the whole series.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Just let me play out there. There were a lot of
questionable calls. There were a lot of fast whistles. Two of our
guards had four fouls with eight minutes to go in the first
quarter. I mean, this is the finals, let the players decide the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Elie admitted that it would be interesting to
see how the Spurs reacted to a loss. They had not dropped a playoff
game on the road all year, and had an NBA record 12 straight
post-season victories. Their last defeat on the road was at
Sacramento on April 27, giving them a gap of 54 days between road
losses. Not since Feb. 28, when they had a 6-8 record, have the
Spurs lost consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen a great character and response in this team,''
Spurs center David Robinson said. ``We've come in the locker room,
and we are very upset about losses and really kind of mad at each
other. And it's just a bad atmosphere after we lose. That always
gets us wanting to be on the right track real soon. We come back
and play extremely well generally.''
</P>
<P>
   While the officiating was a concern, the Spurs were most
disappointed by their shoddy ball handling and distribution. They
gave out only 15 assists and committed 20 turnovers, 6 more than
their average during the playoffs. They had not committed 20
turnovers in a game since defeating Phoenix on April 12, and they
had only 15 assists or fewer twice during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time we had 20 turnovers in two
games,'' said Avery Johnson, overstating the issue but getting his
point across. ``The way we played was an abomination, but I don't
expect it to happen the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, the native New Yorker with the playground mentality, has
already embraced the mind-set that it is the Spurs against the
world. ``When you win a title, it's always hard,'' he said.
``Nobody's going to just let you take it. It's a test for our team.
It's a good test. I'm sure we'll respond. We've been in this
situation before. There's no need to panic. It's a seven-game
series. It takes four games to win the series, and all we can
control right now is what we do tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Try as they might, they certainly cannot control the officials'
whistles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
