<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-NUKE-LABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF ESPIONAGE, DEBATE ON NEW NUCLEAR ARMS AGENCY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate and the Clinton administration moved
closer to a drastic legislative restructuring of the Energy
Department, but in Senate testimony Tuesday Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson continued to resist a key element, a proposal to create
a new agency to oversee nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to establish an Agency for Nuclear Stewardship
within the Energy Department is scheduled to be considered by the
Senate this week. Support for a separate office to oversee
government nuclear weapons programs has built since the release
earlier this month of a scathing report about lax security at the
weapons labs after charges of Chinese spying.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which recommended the creation of a semi-autonomous
agency to oversee nuclear operations was issued last week by
President Clinton's foreign intelligence advisory board, headed by
former Republican Sen. Warren B. Rudman. Rudman testified at an
unusual joint hearing Tuesday attended by almost one third of the
Senate and drawn from four committees.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman told the senators that blame for the security problems
was widespread and bipartisan and therefore required a more
independent solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody,'' he said, including President Clinton, for
``acting too slowly,'' and Congress, where oversight ``probably
could be improved.''
</P>
<P>
   In talks on Monday night, Rudman and Richardson said they were
able to narrow their disagreements about how to reorganize the
nuclear weapons programs. Richardson signaled the hopes of the
Clinton administration for a ``consensus amendment'' and noted he
has already adopted 38 of the report's 43 recommendations. This led
Democrats and Republicans to express optimism about passage of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But by the hearing's end, Richardson had dug in his heels,
resisting a semi-autonomous agency for nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the `agency' word'' he told the senators, because ``it
connotes something that is a separate entity within my own''
department.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Richardson backs the creation of an undersecretary of
energy to take control of the array of department nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman countered, saying he and others do not ``understand the
secretary's abhorrence to this word.'' Rudman also addressed
concerns by some Democrats that civilian research would be harmed
by the reorganization. He noted that his report called for the
secretary of energy to keep responsibility for the nonweapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and Rudman testified later before the House Commerce
Committee hearing. There some members raised questions about
whether a separate agency would adequately oversee other issues in
the weapons programs, including those of safety and health.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative momentum seems focused now in the Senate, where
the three Republican sponsors of the proposed legislation said
Tuesday that they have largely adopted Rudman's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ultimate legislative outcome, it is increasingly
clear that the spy cases at the weapons labs will lead to a
reorganization of the Department of Energy, which was created in
1977. And significant changes seem likely in the way the government
investigates spy cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Select Committee on Intelligence has also been
working on legislation to address problems encountered during the
investigation of China's acquisition of design secrets of American
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the Justice Department rejected requests by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation to conduct surveillance of the chief
suspect in a case involving the theft of design information for the
W-88 warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman Tuesday said the rejection may have been based on an
``overly strict'' interpretation of the Foreign Intelligence
Surveillance Act. He asked whether the act, which balances privacy
and national security, was ``being administered properly,'' a
question at the heart of the intelligence committee's work.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman also criticized the FBI for miscommunications, saying the
Justice Department's decision ``might have had a different result''
if more of the FBI's evidence had been presented to the Justice
Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
