<HEADER>
A5776 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-22 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDER GAMBLING'S REAL EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For better or worse, the head of the American Gaming Association
is dead right when he says casino gambling has been accepted as
part of America's ``mainstream culture.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the response of Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr., the
association's chief exec, when a panel formed to analyze gambling
recognized last week a fact of life already acknowledged by just
about everyone except gambling's most ardent foes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the National Gambling Impact Study Commission report's
most significant finding for gambling's friends and foes alike was
that gambling had been a boon to local economies. Given America's
preoccupation with judging business activity by how it affects
local prosperity, this will give the gambling industry a strong
card to play.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the industry couldn't help but gloat a bit in
the aftermath. Its news release reacting to the report was
headlined, ``I hate to say I told you so...''
</P>
<P>
   What was somewhat surprising, however, was the commission's
findings on those who can't handle gambling. It estimates there are
2.5 million pathological gamblers and 3 million problem gamblers.
In a population of more than 260 million having widespread access
to legal and illegal gambling, those numbers seem relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on the social overhead costs of gambling were also
surprisingly small. The study found that compulsive gamblers cost
taxpayers, employers and creditors $6 billion to $9 billion
annually in lost jobs, crime, bankruptcies, divorce and health-care
costs. Assuming those numbers are valid, they're practically
inconsequential in the context of an $8 trillion economy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the number of problem gamblers and their cost to U.S.
society also seem insignificant when compared with, say, the number
of those with alcohol and drug-related problems and the social
overhead costs they create.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that it's unfortunate whenever someone's
life becomes a tragedy because of gambling problems. Nevertheless,
it would be irrational to deny the overwhelming majority of any
society a social and economic good they want simply because a few
can't handle its downside. Is there any human activity, after all,
that can be considered 100 percent free of potential threat or risk
to a society?
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say that gambling is an unalloyed good. It
isn't. Its allure is the prospect of getting something for nothing,
which appeals to the worst in us. On the other hand, gambling has
been a constant throughout human history. Its popularity ebbs and
flows, and for the past generation it has been in the ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The prosperity of the postwar era explains a lot of the
phenomenon. A gambling boom is nature's way of telling us we have a
lot more discretionary income than we can use constructively.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, doesn't mean it's wrong, bad or immoral. All it
means is that many of us are, well, human.
</P>
<P>
   This report isn't going to stop the debate over the merits of
legalized gambling. Both sides will probably find much in the
report to support their points of view. Nevertheless, the
commission has done a valuable public service by providing a common
referent for those on both sides of the debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
