<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-NEWS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KC police say fatal chase didn't violate policy  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Police commissioners on Tuesday said they
believed the police chase Monday that ended with three deaths was
conducted within department policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I have heard has caused me any concern that this was
not within our policy,'' said Board President Jeff Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said the department planned an internal review of the
chase, which is standard procedure. He said, however, the chase and
the subsequent wreck would not prompt a review of department
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are comfortable with the policy,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the department's policy, a pursuit is justified when the
officer knows or has reasonable grounds to believe the suspect
presents a clear and immediate threat to the safety of other
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Randy Sims, who supervises the accident investigation unit,
briefed commissioners for about 45 minutes at a closed meeting
Tuesday. Afterward, Sims said the car was traveling at 83.6 mph
just before the wreck that killed three men.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men who died in the fiery wreck at 38th Street and
Woodland Avenue had been identified, but police did not release
their names Tuesday. The third man had been tentatively identified,
but police were trying to verify his name.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said a police officer started the 90-second chase after the
three men who were in a Mustang convertible sideswiped a parked
police van containing two prisoners; the Mustang kept going. Sims
said officers then saw the occupants of the Mustang tossing beer
cans from the car.
</P>
<P>
   The officer reported that the Mustang ran two stop signs and two
stoplights, including the light at 39th Street and Woodland.
</P>
<P>
   At that intersection, a van pulled out in front of the Mustang.
The van's driver swerved right to avoid being hit and the Mustang
swerved left to avoid hitting the van.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustang's driver apparently lost control, and the car veered
off the road. The Mustang sheared off a fire hydrant, spun out and
flipped over, landing with its roof against a vacant building. The
car then burst into flames, which spread to the building.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the driver and one passenger were trapped under
the dashboard of the Mustang and had to be cut out by firefighters.
The backseat passenger was ejected into the building and his body
was found under a pile of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Results from toxicology tests to determine whether alcohol was a
factor were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   One unanswered question is how the three men acquired the
Mustang. The owner of the car told police he lent the car to a
friend on Thursday. The friend was not one of the dead men.
</P>
</TEXT>
