was priced Monday night at the low end of the projected price
range, and barely budged in its first day of trading. The offering
was a big test for SF investment banker Bill Hambrecht, and for his
whole notion of ``open IPOs,'' a way for small investors to get in
on new issues. What went wrong? Has the Net bubble burst? Is open
IPO a flawed concept? Or did investors just figure that a
content-only Web site like Salon was not a good investment? By
Arthur M. Louis
