r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-KAN &LR;      06-22 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE STUDENTS FINDING ROOM FOR SUMMER SCHOOL IN THEIR SCHEDULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARA ROSE WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Dinh Pahn had a choice this summer: hang out
with friends in California or stay in Kansas and take a six-week
American government class.
</P>
<P>
   Like a growing number of students, Pahn opted for summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really needed to take this class now, so that next year I
could take a business tech class,'' the 16-year-old high school
junior said during a class break last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Missouri officials don't have hard numbers, but in
the last five years, they've noticed many more students attending
summer classes, not because they failed during the regular school
year but because they want to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt about it. School officials all over Missouri
will testify that summer school is no longer just for kids who
flunk,'' said Carl Sitze, director of the Missouri School
Improvement Program in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more of our better students are going to summer
school all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pahn's honors government class, for example, includes 28 other
students who have ceded some of their summer to academics. Each has
a different story, but most want to get the required class out of
the way so they can take others during the regular school year.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Dix, an honor student in high school, is hoping for a
better-than-usual grade in government by focusing on one subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, summer school is a desperate attempt to raise my class
rank,'' Dix said.
</P>
<P>
   Students such as Dix are still in the minority, but the gap is
closing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shawnee Mission (Kan.) School District, said summer
school principal Jim Wink, about 40 percent of summer students are
taking classes for advancement rather than remediation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, officials said, accelerated students are a major
contributor to higher summer enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   In Shawnee Mission, enrollment jumped by 300 students from 1997
to 1998 and was up 75 more this year to 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas officials expect statewide numbers to be up, but figures
are not yet available. Last year, 50,000 students enrolled in
summer classes, about 3,000 more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, slightly more than 200,000 students are in summer
school, an increase of more than 20,000 from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Educators list several reasons for the rising popularity of
summer classes:
</P>
<P>
   - More air-conditioned schools. Climate control makes summer
classes bearable. And in the Independence School District, more
schools are being air-conditioned this year, partly to accommodate
the demand for summer classes.
</P>
<P>
   - Higher graduation requirements. When more math, science and
English are required, it becomes more difficult for students to
squeeze in the electives they want.
</P>
<P>
   - A tight labor market. The demand for young people in the
service industry makes employers more flexible, enabling students
to take classes and work, said Cliff Mohn, assistant superintendent
in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students go to summer school in the morning and work full
shifts later in the day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   - Economics. Some students take summer classes to gain time
during the school year to take college credit or advanced placement
classes. In the long run, that will save them money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get 12 to 15 hours out of the way in high school,
you can save $1,200 to $1,500,'' said Dick Howard, assistant
superintendent in the Blue Springs School District.
</P>
<P>
   Shawnee Mission students pay $240 for a six-week course, but
they can save much more by earning the college credits in high
school. It's an even better deal in Missouri, where summer classes
are free.
</P>
<P>
   - More attractive course offerings. In Missouri, state aid for
summer school is so generous that some schools can offer breakfast
_ and a smorgasbord of courses _ to summer students.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Independence School District, for example, can
study computer applications, advanced fitness, career planning, art
and health. The nearby Fort Osage district offers classes in
theater, broadcasting and film.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Pearson, a 14-year-old ``A'' student, spends four hours
each morning in film class at Fort Osage High School, where he'll
be a freshman next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun, and we hardly have any homework,'' Kyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Summer, he said, is the only time he'll have to take such
electives. He intends to take a load of weighted college prep
courses during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a B in a weighted course, it is like an A in a high
school course,'' Kyle said. ``But if you get an A, then you can get
above a 4.0 grade point. And that is what valedictorians and
salutatorians do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
