<HEADLINE>
BECKER STRETCHING OUT HIS FINAL WIMBLEDON
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-WIMBLEDON-HINGIS) 
 (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Boris Becker, the war horse who put himself
out to pasture two years ago but decided to tackle Wimbledon one
last time, Tuesday pawed and pounded his way out of a
two-sets-to-none deficit against Scotland's Miles Maclagan and into
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   On Court Two, this facility's renowned and reviled Graveyard
Court, Becker recovered his poise, erased three match points, and
secured his 69th victory at Wimbledon. Becker's 31st ace clinched
the 5-7, 6-7 (7-9), 6-4, 7-5, 6-2 comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still around, somehow; today was as close as it could get,
three match points down, two sets to love down, but there's a
reason why I've won so many matches here,'' the 31-year-old Becker
said after improving his record in Wimbledon five-setters to 9-2 at
the expense of the 298th-ranked wild card.
</P>
<P>
   The first-round match in Becker's 15th Wimbledon was almost too
much for his wife, Barbara, who is expecting the couple's second
child in August. ``I told her to calm down a little _ otherwise
we'd have had a baby on the court,'' Becker said. ``She's only a
few weeks away.''
</P>
<P>
   By wearing down Maclagan, Becker earned himself a second-round
Center Court grudge match against his Davis Cup
protege-turned-nemesis, Nicolas Kiefer. Of Becker, the 15th-seeded
Kiefer said: ``He doesn't want to talk to me. I don't know why, but
I don't care. I'm here to play tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker, a three-time Wimbledon champion, became this event's
youngest and first unseeded champion at 17 in 1985, defended the
title a year later, was ousted by Australia's Peter Doohan in the
second round in 1987, but then won the last of his three titles
here a decade ago in 1989. Becker said he reneged on his tearful
1997 Wimbledon retirement announcement because he realized his
total departure from the pro tour was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   With a second child on the way, Becker, who has played
sporadically since 1997 but won the last of his six Grand Slam
tournaments at the 1996 Australian Open, decided he would soon have
to quit all competition to concentrate on his family. That done, he
decided six months ago that he had one last Wimbledon in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of reasons why I can't leave Wimbledon
alone, that's for sure; it's taken this one last highlight to spur
me on,'' the 77th-ranked Becker said. ``But I haven't played a
five-setter in years. What I'm going to feel tomorrow morning, I
don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Becker, there were plenty of other notables who eluded
the upset bug that claimed Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-seeded Andre Agassi posted an impressive 6-1, 6-2, 6-3
victory against Romania's Andrei Pavel, the runner-up to Patrick
Rafter last week in a grass-court tuneup in the Netherlands. The
29-year-old Agassi, whose French Open victory three weeks ago made
him only the fifth man to win all four Grand Slam events and the
first to accomplish the feat on three surfaces, pronounced himself
ready for his next challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's like to be a two-time champion anywhere
now, so I'd like to win more, finish the year No. 1,'' the Las
Vegas resident said of his escalated ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Other top-seeded players to advance included the second-seeded
Rafter, who disposed of Italian qualifier Cristiano Caratto, 6-3,
6-2, &QC; 6-2. Fifth-seeded Richard Krajicek, the 1996 champion and the
only man to defeat five-time champion Pete Sampras here in the last
six years, crushed Norway's Christian Ruud, 6-2, 6-3, 6-1. And
eighth-seeded Todd Martin recovered from two sets down to defeat
Hendrik Dreekmann of Germany, 6-7 (8-6), 6-7 (7-5), 6-3, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
