<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY DOESN'T BACK DOWN, AND NEITHER DO THE KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It did not matter if Marcus Camby had the upper body
of a coat hanger, he was not about to hand over his milk money to a
star center with cargo room in his biceps.
</P>
<P>
   So Camby, once labeled a pushover, pushed back when fighting for
position against David Robinson during the Knicks' Game 3 victory
over San Antonio on Monday night. An incredulous reaction crossed
Robinson's face as Larry Johnson stepped between the two in
midflail, a look that seemed to say, ``The audacity of this kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I just had to stand my ground,'' said Camby, who will
start again Wednesday night in Game 4. ``I wasn't going to let this
guy come in and push me on national TV and try to embarrass me. I
wasn't going for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team saw I wasn't going to back down. And that's the way we
have to approach every game.''
</P>
<P>
   This defiant attitude, which has sustained the Knicks in their
desperate moments of the playoffs, helped put the team on the board
in the National Basketball Association finals. But what is
physically left in a team with spirit but few bodies to counter the
Spurs?
</P>
<P>
   If Allan Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Johnson have anything in
reserve, they have a chance to change the feel to this
four-of-seven-game series with a victory Wednesday night at Madison
Square Garden. If the Knicks slip on fatigue, as they did in Games
1 and 2, they'll find themselves one loss from elimination.
Wednesday night, they can put the league's 2-3-2 format to good use
or waste it.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the possibility of a Spurs sweep, Coach Jeff Van
Gundy came back with strategic adjustments in the Knicks' 89-81
victory. They worked hard to take away the high-low combination of
Robinson to Tim Duncan, used each other to create mid-range jumpers
instead of predictably driving into the shot-blocking path of the
Spurs' two 7-footers and bullied their way to the free-throw line.
All of this was made possible by an incredible hit of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday provided the only day of rest for the threesome that
carried the burden of Game 3 by pushing the envelope on playing
time. On a sprained knee, Johnson played a season-high 43 minutes,
while Sprewell and Houston played 46 and 45 minutes. Before the
finals, Sprewell was averaging 33.6 minutes per game in the
playoffs and Houston 36.8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But with Patrick Ewing's absence, and the team's litany of
injuries, what choice do they have?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the finals, you try to forget about the minutes
you're playing,'' said Houston, who was a little rubbery-legged
Tuesday. ``All I can say is there is a time where you do need a
little rest, with the schedule we're playing. But hopefully you can
kind of have a good strategy as to when you get that rest. But it's
the finals. This is what dreams are made of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have the same dream. A day after their first loss in
12 playoff games they were upset at several issues: their 20
turnovers, the officiating that put the Knicks on the free-throw
line 30 times and their uncommon loss of poise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, when we get a technical early in the game and start
fussing too much about calls, we're not focused,'' Avery Johnson
said. ``We think people are going to give it to us. When we're
really good, no matter what the calls are and what the opposing
team is doing, you'll see us locked in. We weren't locked in early
in the game, and that was the disappointing thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They will seek to gain some control in Game 4, while the Knicks
will stick with the strategy that worked for them in Game 3. Even
though Camby found himself in foul trouble early trying to guard
Robinson and played just 16 minutes, he'll start again. If anyone
has energy to burn for Game 4, it's Camby. If he can stay on the
floor, he can ease the burden on Johnson and company.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was one of the few Knicks unsettled by the whistles
Monday. As the aggressors, the Knicks got the calls, which piqued
the suspicions of a Spur or two. Half joking, some wondered if the
league and NBC were hoping to extend the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to be called on any given night,''
said Mario Elie, who picked up two fouls in the first two minutes
of the game. ``I've been playing Allan the same way all series, and
all of the sudden, Boom, I got three questionable calls.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fouls aside, the Knicks earned Game 3 with their execution,
aggressiveness and attention to Duncan. Johnson, moving as freely
as he has all series, planted his undersized but square body on
Duncan and kept him from catching the ball deep in the post. Forced
to settle for awkward shots, Duncan was 0 for 4 in the fourth
quarter. Growing uncharacteristically flustered, Duncan was called
for traveling and a three-second violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they wore Tim down,'' Elie said. `'They did a good
job. The Knicks were beating him up all game. They did a good job
of wearing him down.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
