<HEADER>
A5786 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALON-SALON_SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-SALON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 SALON.COM IPO GETS CHILLY RECEPTION  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the most tepid Internet stock debuts yet, investors
turned noses up and thumbs down yesterday on the closely watched
initial public offering of Salon.com, an online magazine based in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The stock went public at $10.50 _ but instead of doubling,
tripling or quadrupling like most Internet stocks, it actually
fell, finishing the day at $10.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com's offering was closely watched because it was the
highest-profile example of a radically new stock-distribution
method designed to give ordinary investors access to IPOs over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In most IPOs, investment bankers offer the bulk of the shares at
bargain prices to their biggest customers _ usually institutions
and rich individuals _ to thank them and encourage future business.
</P>
<P>
   Salon went public via an ``Open IPO'' with the help of San
Francisco investment banker Bill Hambrecht, who left his first
company, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, to form W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Salon stock was offered on Hambrecht's Web site
( &LR; www.openipo.com &LR; ) in a ``Dutch auction.''
</P>
<P>
   In such an auction, investors specify how many shares they're
willing to buy and at what price. At the end of the auction period,
the company figures out the highest price at which it can sell all
shares. It then sells all of its stock at that price to everyone
who bid that price or higher.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, following the conclusion of Salon's Dutch
auction, its IPO was priced at $10.50. The offering price was the
first sign that there might be trouble because it was at the bottom
of the $10.50-to-$13.50 price range set by Hambrecht in April.
</P>
<P>
   Financial experts scrambled yesterday to understand why the
offering flopped _ or even whether it really did flop.
</P>
<P>
   Some blamed the disappointing performance on the fact that
Internet stocks in general are well below their highs, and that the
entire stock market was weak yesterday, with the Nasdaq composite
index falling nearly 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Salon.com was down nearly 5 percent from its offering
price.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ramp Networks, another Internet company that went
public yesterday, jumped $5.75 from its offering price to finish at
$16.75 _ up 52 percent. The Santa Clara company produces software
for Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Robertson, another San Francisco investment banker and
longtime rival of Hambrecht, graciously pointed out that an IPO
based on a Dutch auction ``by definition'' balances supply and
demand, leaving little room for price gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory of the Dutch auction is that the issuing company is
going to get the very best price available,'' said Robertson. ``The
issuer doesn't leave a lot of money on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In a traditional IPO, investment bankers deliberately underprice
stocks to guarantee their customers a quick profit and generate
excitement in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   David Menlow, president of IPO Financial Network in New Jersey,
said he considers Dutch auctions foolish from the standpoint of
stock-market psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The offering should have been priced lower than demand
indicated, he said, so the stock would have room to soar the first
day. Now, when investors see how Salon.com performed, they won't
want to buy it, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPO investors should not go into a deal and buy a stock and
the very first day show a loss. The market is not used to that sort
of thing and has no tolerance for it,'' Menlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggested that Salon.com's stock was held back by
the company's unconvincing business model.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which publishes news and commentary online and
relies almost entirely on advertising for revenues, lost $6.2
million in the fiscal year ended March 31, or more than twice its
revenues of $2.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all Web sites are losing money, but unlike Salon, most
are relying in part on e-commerce _ selling goods via the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Content alone has not proven to be a ``viable business model,''
noted Lisa Allen, an analyst with Forrester Research in
Massachusetts. ``Content sites that are losing money are a dime a
dozen.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hagen, chief financial officer of Salon.com, insisted in a
brief telephone interview: ``We're very excited and happy. The
stock is performing as we expected, and now we are focusing on
running the company.''
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Hambrecht officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's top management includes President and Editor in Chief
David Talbot, who formerly served as the San Francisco Examiner's
arts and features editor. Andrew Ross, vice president for business
and strategic development, was the Examiner's foreign and national
news editor.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News reported that in the wake of the
2.5-million-share IPO _ which amounted to nearly a fourth of
Salon.com's stock _ Talbot's stake is worth $4 million and Ross' is
worth $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
