<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-ALLIANCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA AND AMERICAN JOIN NEW PARTNERSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new airline alliances were announced Tuesday, between Delta
Air Lines and Air France, and among American Airlines Swissair and
Sabena World Airlines of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   While both accords are expected to integrate flight schedules
and frequent-flier programs between partner airlines, the Delta-Air
France long range plan is to bring other partners into their fold,
so they can better compete with the eight-member Star Alliance, led
by United Airlines, and the eight-member One World alliance, led by
American Airlines. Both the Star Alliance and One World consist of
at least one airline from Europe, Asia, South America and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Airline partnerships, an outgrowth of the ``open sky''
agreements that have pried open aviation markets around the globe,
have accelerated tremendously since Northwest Airlines and KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines linked up in 1993. Eleven European airlines
from seven nations banded together last year under the name of the
Qualiflyer Group, and now serve more than 300 destinations.
Austrian Airlines, Sabena and Swissair are members of the Atlantic
Excellence partnership, as is Delta _ which said Tuesday that it
would continue as a member.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines belong to one or more alliances, because each one
is thought to confer different strengths. Later this year
Continental Airlines is expected to join the Wings alliance, which
currently consists of Alitalia, KLM and Northwest. Yet Continental
is already allied with Northwest and Alitalia, and Alitalia is a
partner with KLM.
</P>
<P>
   And several Asian airlines that are not yet committed to
existing alliances _ as Singapore Airlines appears committed to the
Star Alliance _ have talked about forming a regional alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller airlines benefit from alliances by being able to expand
their reach with the help of their partners, a reach that otherwise
would be financially prohibitive. And bigger airlines benefit by
being able to offer their passengers seamless travel and flights on
partner airlines to destinations to which they could never afford
to fly on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Early results suggest that alliances can be profitable. In May,
both United and Lufthansa said that their membership in the Star
Alliance _ which also includes Air Canada, Air New Zealand, Ansett
of Australia, Scandinavian Airlines System, Thai Airways and Varig
of Brazil) _ contributed significantly to their respective bottom
lines. United said the alliance contributed about $200 million, or
about 10 percent, of its $2.3 billion profit in 1998. For
Lufthansa, the alliance contributed about 18 percent, or $265
million, of its 1998 operating profit of $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
