<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: BALKAN TOURISM HURTING; NEW ORDERS FOR CRUISE
SHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dim Prospects for Travel in the Balkans, at least for now
</P>
<P>
   The end of the NATO bombing campaign in the Balkans will not
revive the region's travel or tourist industry anytime soon. But
Austrian Airlines has already restored its daily flight between
Vienna and Skopje, Macedonia, and is evaluating whether to restore
service to Tirana, the capital of Albania. Both flights were
suspended after the bombing began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago PricewaterhouseCoopers estimated that the
fighting in the Balkans could cost hotels, travel agencies,
airlines and cruise ships as much as $100 million. The conflict
certainly seems to have taken a heavy toll on travel to Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether you think of it as 'Clinton's War,'
`NATO's War,' `Our War' or `Their War,' there is no question that
the U.S.-led nightly bombings of Yugoslavia have brought the annual
summer invasion of American tourists into Europe to a near halt,''
Joel M. Abels, the editor and publisher of Travel Trade, wrote in
that trade publication's June 14 issue. With few exceptions, he
added, ``travel agents, tour operators, cruise lines and airlines
watched as the booking season was stopped practically dead in its
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Most travel industry analysts think that situation will improve,
now that the bombing has ended _ especially since airlines, cruise
ships and European hotels are dangling attractive discounts.
British Airways and American Airlines are currently offering two
round-trip economy tickets to London for the price of one, with
certain restrictions. And cruise lines are dangling upgrades and
substantial discounts on their Mediterranean cruises. Windstar
Cruises is offering as much as 50 percent on its European
itineraries, plus a ship-board credit of $100 for guests who book
by July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Order for New Ships
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises, which is owned by the Peninsular &AMP; Oriental
Steam Navigation Co., has ordered four new ships for delivery
between October 2001 and May 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the ships, which will carry 1,950 passengers each, will
be built by Chantiers de l'Atlantique of France. The other two,
which will each accommodate 2,600 passengers, will be built by
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of Japan. P&AMP;O Cruises, a sister
company, has also ordered a 2,600-passenger ship from Fincantieri
of Italy. The five ships will cost approximately $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Including three ships already under construction and scheduled
for delivery through 2002, the Princess fleet will grow from 9
ships currently to 16 and the number of berths will more than
double to 30,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
