A5789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS23-COX     06-22 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs not fazed byrare playoff defeat
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sean Elliott is sure San Antonio Spurs fans are
reacting rationally to the team's defeat against the New York
Knicks on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are burning their houses,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the Spurs consider expectations so unreasonable that they
either dismiss them offhand or make jokes to illuminate the
absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   To those who believed San Antonio was supposed to win its first
NBA championship by defeating New York in four straight games,
Elliott said, ``Everyone was talking sweep _ except us.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the Spurs have to admit that a different feeling has
set in now that their 12-game playoff winning streak ended with an
89-81 loss that cut San Antonio's lead in the NBA Finals to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strange day for us, the day after a loss,'' said
Avery Johnson, after the Spurs held a practice session to prepare
for tonight's game. ``It's a funny feeling, I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time they felt this way was May 11, after a defeat that
seemed more damaging than the one on Monday. On May 11 the Spurs
were beaten by Minnesota at the Alamodome, evening their
first-round series 1-1. The Spurs responded with an 85-71 victory
two nights later in Minneapolis, starting the winning streak that
ended on Monday after 40 days without a defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Spurs will do what they have done before, what every
team does after losing a playoff game: make adjustments. They will
tweak the offense. They will tinker with the defense. But they will
not burn their houses. They will not panic, although Coach Gregg
Popovich did not place mints on their pillows after the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop is brutal when we win,'' Johnson said. ``So you can only
imagine . . . he's a maniac when we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs do not agree with suggestions that New York has
changed the tone of the series by winning a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the same,'' Tim Duncan said. ``It's not out of control
and it's not in control. It's right there where it can swing either
way, but we're very confident with what we are doing. We've lost a
game, but we're not in a hole. We don't feel badly about the loss.
We're not crying about the loss.''
</P>
<P>
   At times Monday, the Spurs appeared to cry about the
officiating. For the first time in the series, the Spurs were
called for more fouls and the Knicks shot more free throws. Mario
Elie committed two fouls within four seconds of the first quarter
trying to guard Allan Houston, who finished with 34 points. Elie
received a technical foul for protesting the second personal foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of questionable calls,'' Elie said. ``I've played my
same defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs faced a similar situation in game three at Portland,
when David Robinson, Duncan, Elliott and Will Perdue were assessed
two fouls each in the first quarter. But they responded
significantly better than on Monday, winning 85-63.
</P>
<P>
   Elie's foul trouble seemed to set the tone for Monday's game. He
was forced to sit down after less than two minutes had elapsed. His
replacement, Jaren Jackson, also picked up two quick fouls, and the
Spurs never established a perimeter game.
</P>
<P>
   Elie, Elliott, Jackson and Johnson combined for only 23 points,
their lowest production during the playoffs and 14 fewer than they
had averaged before Monday. They hit only 10 of 27 shots and stood
around too much, watching Robinson (25 points) and Duncan (20) work
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't normal,'' Johnson said. ``We looked like
another team in Texas (Houston). We can't play like our I-10
counterparts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are not sure the perimeter players need to get more
shots. But they at least must refrain from standing still.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a little more movement and not be so
predictable,'' backup guard Steve Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   By doing that, Duncan, in particular, should have more
opportunities to score inside, and he might shoot more free throws.
His 20 points were nine fewer than he averaged in the first two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan did not score in the fourth quarter. He missed four shots
and committed three of the Spurs' turnovers during the game. Duncan
also shot only four free throws after averaging 9.5 in the first
two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs must play better defense on Houston and Latrell
Sprewell, who scored 24 points. The Spurs allowed Houston and
Sprewell to receive the ball closer to the basket than during the
first two games. When they did not score, Houston and Sprewell
combined for nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerr, a veteran of three championship teams with Chicago,
said the 30-22 edge New York had in free-throw attempts was the
biggest reason the Spurs lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at the line all night,'' Kerr said. ``We defended
them well in the first two games, and last night we didn't defend
them as well. Still, they shot only 39 percent (on field goals), so
the key was obviously getting to the foul line to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
