<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-POWER_SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-POWER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Regulator Wants to Rewrite State Electricity-Industry Rule  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The operator of California's high-voltage transmission system is
pressing federal regulators for permission to rewrite some of the
rules governing the state's $23 billion deregulated electricity
market.
<P>
   The request is prompted by apparent market gouging by Duke
Energy Corp., the new owner of some PG&AMP;E power plants, which last
week charged 10 times the normal price for an energy service it
provided to the grid operator, the California Independent System
Operator.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of who profits from new market rules, created when
California deregulated its electricity market 15 months ago, is
extremely important to consumers because, ultimately, they bear the
cost of market-design flaws or market abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Although not illegal, Duke's action was harmful because it
exploited defects in market design to garner a windfall profit of
roughly $1 million a day last week, said Terry Winter, chief
executive of the grid-operating ISO in Folsom (Sacramento County).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there will be a hue and cry from some of the
generators about our intervening, but I'm not going to allow
someone to make millions of dollars like this,'' Winter said. ``The
rules aren't right, so I'm changing the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke executives objected yesterday to the inference that they
were gouging but said they understood why the ISO took action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see the ISO doing a lot of tinkering with the
market, but if something's broken, they need to fix it,'' said
Randy Hickok, Duke's vice president of California regulatory
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As California's grid operator tweaks the rules to nip perceived
market abuse, other states are watching. In addition to buying
three plants from PG&AMP;E here in California, Duke, a Charlotte, N.C.,
operator which is one of the nation's biggest energy conglomerates,
has bought power plants from mainline utilities in other states
that are undergoing deregulation, including Connecticut,
Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In its June 18 filing with the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, the grid operator is asking for permission to change
market rules to correct market defects.
</P>
<P>
   The incident behind the unusual request _ one of only two such
cases identified since the ISO began running the electric grid 15
months ago _ concerns Duke's operation of the Morro Bay generating
station it acquired last year from PG&AMP;E along with Moss Landing and
Oakland power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is accused of exploiting transmission bottlenecks to
extract a higher price for the services that it and other
generators offer the ISO to help relieve occasional electrical
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   At certain times of the year, major transmission lines become
overloaded, usually because of high demand due to extreme heat or
cold in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   In those instances, the ISO must intervene and order power
plants in congested areas to reduce their electricity production to
ease the overload situation that jeopardizes power-line stability.
Additional power then must be obtained from other areas. Both those
reducing output and those providing extra electricity get paid by
the ISO.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the ISO taps the plants that offer the cheapest
prices for lowering electric output in an affected zone. The
problem is that, in some cases, there may be just one or two plants
permitted to ease the overload situation under existing ISO rules.
It's more a regulatory problem than a technical problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, important transmission lines connecting the Midway
and Vincent substations _ so-called Path 26 _ that straddle PG&AMP;E
and Southern California Edison service territories were overloaded.
But only the Diablo Canyon Nuclear Plant, still operated by PG&AMP;E,
and Duke's Morro Bay plant were considered qualified under ISO
rules to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Because nuclear plants can't be ramped up and down very easily,
the ISO called on Morro Bay to reduce its electrical output. Duke,
anticipating the need, raised its price for providing the
``adjustment'' service tenfold, to $250 per megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   It might have demanded an even higher price _ and the ISO would
have been forced to pay it under its tariffs _ but the ISO imposed
a $250 price cap last summer in response to previous instances of
gouging by other power plant owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankee ingenuity is alive and well,'' said ISO chief Winter.
``We had someone who saw an opportunity to make some extra money
and took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ISO wants the federal agency's permission to solicit the
services of power plant operators from a wider geographic area to
break the market power of any single generator.
</P>
<P>
   Duke executives said they simply charged what the market would
bear. Isn't that what markets are all about?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope was that $250 was the value of the service we were
providing,'' said Hickok. ``We provided the grid with the stability
that was needed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
