<HEADER>
A5793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-COX     06-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uneasy coexistence in Macedonia
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Most people didn't expect to come close to
President Clinton on his visit to Macedonia's capital Tuesday. But
almost everyone was willing to send him a message when given the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   What they said illustrated the deep differences within this
nation of 2 million people over NATO's policy on Kosovo, and showed
why the Balkan region remains a tinderbox.
</P>
<P>
   Sasko Velickovski, 28, a taxi driver, admitted that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic had made ``some mistakes,'' but he
said NATO's air strikes on Yugoslavia were also a mistake because
they harmed many innocent citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Serbs, we are the same religion,'' he said, referring to
Macedonia's Slavic, Orthodox Christian majority. ``Every family
from here has some family, some cousin, there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the American media, Mr. Clinton was not
well-informed about Serbia and Kosovo,'' insisted Emil Ribarski,
15, turning his attention briefly from flirting with two teenage
girls in a park in central Skopje. ``Many situations where
civilians died were on Serbian television but not on American
television and CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribarski loves American music, video games and movies. But his
feelings about the United States have changed. ``Before the war,
most Macedonians thought America was the promised land,'' he said,
``but now they are not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   But across the old stone bridge over the Vardar River from the
park, the mood _ and the message for the U.S. president _ were far
different.
</P>
<P>
   The old Turkish market area is the heart of Skopje's ethnic
Albanian minority _ a group that makes up, according to various
estimates, between 20 percent and 35 percent of the national
population.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters had begun a sometimes deafening roar, a signal to
everyone that the president had arrived in the city. And at cafes
along the narrow cobblestone alleyways, people drinking Turkish
coffee were unanimous in praising Clinton, America and NATO for
helping the Kosovo Albanians against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bugar Isene, a 16-year-old in a Mortal Kombat T-shirt, said his
message to the president was to continue ``to protect the people in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Isene was so impressed with the recent pounding of the Serbs and
the current occupation of Kosovo by peacekeepers that he has a new
career ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a NATO pilot,'' he said. ``I want to defend
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few steps away, Qenan Sabani, 32, the manager of a small
shoe store, said Clinton ``is a great man for me. Kosovo is only
one example of his greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabani's brother-in-law, Lundrim Memishi, 24, said he also had a
very important message for the president: He wants to live in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Memishi had arrived in Macedonia three weeks ago after escaping
from his home in Serbia, 5 kilometers from the Kosovo border.
Serbian troops were still occupying his house, he said, ``using it
like a bus station.'' He wished NATO had invaded and gone all the
way to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Skopje, people had heard about the sexual scandal
that threatened to bring down the Clinton presidency, but no one _
despite their views of Clinton's policies _ took the issue too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton won praise from everyone. Her appearance with a
group of Macedonian businessmen, broadcast live on local television
in early afternoon, local time, attracted crowds of viewers around
TV sets in cafes.
</P>
<P>
   The president's speech to the Macedonian parliament was taped
for airing in prime time, and viewers with satellite service could
watch his meetings with refugees and U.S. soldiers live on BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Isabela Hristovski, 54, a retired administrator for a
construction firm, was out for a stroll with one of her
grandchildren and wasn't following the day's events too closely.
But she said the president's ``personal life is his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Hristovski is part of the majority Slavic community that
identifies itself as Macedonian. Most self-described Macedonians
distinguish themselves from the minorities _ the ethnic Albanians
and the smaller Gypsy and Bosnian communities.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the Macedonian Slavs, Hristovski opposed the NATO
bombings, but she said she would not object to the peacekeeping
force in Kosovo if it is fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to the president is that it must be the same for
the Serbs as for the others,'' she said. ``If NATO is helping both
sides, the Serbs and the Albanians, that is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Slavic Macedonians raised the specter of a greater Albanian
movement, in which the country of Albania and ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo and western Macedonia would try to unite. Some feared that
many of the refugees from Kosovo will remain in their country,
while others expressed relief that many are already leaving. They
worried, too, about the high birthrate of Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Albanian community, meanwhile, complained that
they are discriminated against in both education and employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Both Slavs and Albanians who live in Macedonia said civil war
could erupt in the future, though not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite those fears, there were hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Symanovski, 63, chief of maintenance at a large shopping
center, said the point people should remember about the recent
conflict is that ``we did what the world asked of us. We helped the
Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the country that helped so many refugees despite
its own conflicts needs help from the world to build a stronger
economy of its own. With aid, he said, ``We may help make the
Balkans stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhamed Mashovitc, a Bosnian Muslim who manages a transport
business, agreed. ``If people are making money and have decent
jobs, then there will not be war,'' he said. ``But if the world
does not help these people, there could be war.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Velickovski, the cabdriver with a strong distrust of
Albanians, acknowledged that financial aid could help.
</P>
<P>
   The silver lining to the NATO strikes and the influx of not only
refugees but journalists, diplomats and humanitarian workers is
that ``for the first time in my life, all the hotels in Skopje are
filled. All the restaurants are filled, too'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be better, though,'' he added, ``if our factories
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Graham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
