<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chevron to Slash 1,500 More Jobs  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Chevron Chairman Kenneth Derr said the San Francisco oil giant will
cut an additional 1,500 jobs this year. That's on top of the 1,000
job cuts announced in December as part of a $500 million
cost-reduction program.
<P>
   One-quarter of the jobs eliminated are expected to be in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increase in job cuts, not many Chevron employees
actually will be laid off. That's because more than 2,500 employees
have elected to take an early retirement in exchange for an
enhanced pension. Due to the high number of voluntary quits, pink
slips will be minimal, said company spokesman Mike Libbey.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's isn't an exact match between the voluntary
quits and the jobs slated for elimination, Libbey said a
reshuffling of employees will enable most who want to stay with the
oil giant to remain.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron steadily has been reducing its workforce since 1985,
when it acquired Gulf Oil Corp. Just after the merger, Chevron's
workforce swelled to 80,000 employees, but subsequent divestitures
and reorganizations have slimmed it down to 33,700 employees
worldwide. Roughly 8,100 of those employees work in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Derr also said the most recent job cuts would result in a $150
million special charge against second-quarter earnings. Chevron was
expected to post second-quarter earnings of 78 cents a share,
according to a First Call survey of analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 2,500 people who have volunteered to take an
enhanced retirement package will be gone by the end of the year,
Libbey said. The job cuts will reduce Chevron's workforce by
slightly more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron's news came only weeks after discussions with Texaco
Inc. about a possible merger abruptly fell apart. Texaco said then
that the offer from its slightly larger rival was ``unacceptable in
all respects.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Derr refused to comment yesterday on the failed deal,
he said the company remained ``on the prowl'' for quality assets.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company's size will allow it act more quickly and
remain more flexible than in an environment of ``supermajor'' oil
companies typified by the Exxon-Mobil merger .
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to it the old-fashioned way _ by growing our
volumes,'' he said yesterday in New York, where he met with stock
analysts and news reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Derr also said a March fire at Chevron's refinery in Richmond,
and several separate refinery problems, would reduce second-quarter
operating earnings by an additional $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CHEVRON2 (3170 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Richmond refinery, with a 240,000-barrel-per-day refining
capacity, isn't expected to be fully operational until the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Chevron shares fell 56 cents, to $90.13, yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag  &LR; Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of CHEVRON2 (3170 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
