<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEASURE TO LIMIT IMPORTS OF STEEL IS KILLED BY SENATE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate killed a bill that would have sharply restricted
imports of foreign steel to the United States, a blow to unions and
steelmakers and a victory for President Clinton, who had warned
that the legislation would revive protectionism. The bill, which
became a divisive argument over the merits of free trade and the
economic wisdom of protecting steelworkers at the expense of
raising prices on a range of everyday goods, would have rolled back
imports of steel to the levels before the Asian economic crisis,
ending a surge that began as countries sought to export their way
out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN BROTHERS POSTS SOLID PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers, which has been broadening from its traditional
base as a bond house into equities and investment banking, reported
second-quarter earnings that were far above analysts' expectations.
But despite the unexpectedly high profits, shares of the company
fell $3.6875, or 6.11 percent, to $56.625, on volume of more than
four million shares _ more than four times the daily average.
</P>
<P>
   3COM RESULTS BEAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   3Com reported fourth-quarter earnings a penny above analysts'
expectations based on strong growth in products used to manage data
flow over networks.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK PRICES IN BROAD RETREAT
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices staged a broad retreat as a further rise in
long-term interest rates and a late round of selling depressed the
market. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 94.35 points, or
nine-tenths of a percent, to 10,721.63. Technology stocks dragged
down the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and the Nasdaq composite
index. The S.&AMP;P. 500 lost 13.12 points, or just less than 1
percent, to 1,335.88. Nasdaq fell 50.02 points, or 1.9 percent, to
2,580.26.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell as corporate borrowers prepared to sell about
$10 billion in debt. The yield on the benchmark 30-year issue rose
to 6.06 percent from 6.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE PANEL APPROVES SUMMERS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee unanimously approved the nomination
of Lawrence Summers, left, to be the next Secretary of the
Treasury, clearing the way for a confirmation vote by the full
Senate as early as next week. But the majority leader, Trent Lott,
Republican of Mississippi, said a final vote could be pushed back
because Democrats were threatening to add health care reform and
other initiatives to spending bills over Republican objections.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEANS TO INSPECT COKE PLANTS
</P>
<P>
   The 15-nation European Union announced plans for health
inspections of its own in Coca-Cola's plants in Belgium and France
that had produced soft drinks blamed for outbreaks of illness early
this month.
</P>
<P>
   FORD PLANS FACTORY IN RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor announced a preliminary agreement with the Russian
Government to begin construction in July of an automobile factory
near St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PROPOSALS ON FUND DIRECTORS
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund industry's leading trade group, Investment
Company Institute, is expected to recommend sweeping new rules to
strengthen the role of independent directors, going beyond earlier
proposals by Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SAID TO ENRICH ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   The financial benefits of the Internet and high technology go
beyond quick riches for high-profile entrepreneurs and investors to
the nation's entire economy, according to a Commerce Department
study.
</P>
<P>
   LAST WITNESS APPEARS FOR MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's final witness at its antitrust trial, Richard
Schmalensee, dean of MIT's Sloan School of Management, contended
there was no substance to any of the Government's charges and that
Microsoft, far from holding a monopoly in personal computer
operating system software, faced vicious and serious competitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
