<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S3-S3 </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S3 Will Purchase Internet Music Firm for $180 Million  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
S3 Inc., the Santa Clara maker of microchips that control computer
graphics, yesterday took aim at the world of Internet music and
home networking when it announced plans to buy Diamond Multimedia
Systems Inc. in a deal valued at about $180 million in stock.
<P>
   Diamond Multimedia, well known within the computer industry for
its 3-D graphic accelerator boards for PCs, made a splash in
consumer electronics and the worldwide recording industry in
November with its portable Rio MP3 music player.
</P>
<P>
   S3 hopes that the deal will allow it to branch out beyond PC
graphics into a new and promising market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Diamond Multimedia of San Jose expects the deal will
give it the resources to continue developing its new products such
as home networking equipment. In particular, it hopes that the deal
will help fund the spin-off of its Rio line of portable devices
that play music encoded in MP3 and other digital audio formats,
into a new company called RioPort.com.
</P>
<P>
   S3 President and CEO Ken Potashner said in an interview that the
acquisition marks a ``significant strategic shift'' as the company,
the second-largest maker of graphics chips, tries to rebound from a
money-losing year.
</P>
<P>
   Potashner said many details still need to be worked out, such as
what Diamond's corporate relationship will be to S3 and whether
there will be staff cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But Potashner clearly was upbeat about the move. ``Diamond
possesses some products that will be our entree into what we see
are high-growth and high-value markets, the Internet-appliance and
home-networking arenas.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, S3 will swap 0.52 shares of S3 common
stock for each share of Diamond Multimedia. Shares of S3 closed
down 69 cents at $8.75 on the Nasdaq stock market yesterday, while
Diamond's stock closed down 94 cents at $4.75, also on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The deal brings together S3, maker of a line of graphic chips
called Savage, with Diamond Multimedia, known for its Stealth and
Viper lines of graphics accelerator boards and Supra modems.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the merger, which is expected to be completed by
October, continues an industry trend of mergers between makers of
chips and boards.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Dan Scovel of Fahnestock &AMP; Co. gave the deal ``a
qualified thumbs up.'' ``Diamond has the MP3 player, and they're
moving into wireless networking,'' he said. ``And in the long term,
that's what makes sense for S3.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Scovel said the new company might alienate current
customers of both companies who will have no choice but to buy S3
chips and Diamond boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see that as a problem that will be limited to the second
half of this year,'' Scovel said. ``Next year at this time, nobody
will be concerned about customer alienation.''
</P>
<P>
   Potashner became CEO of S3 last November to turn around a
company that had posted a $113.2 million loss in 1998 on revenue of
$224.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said S3, which supplies chips to computer-makers like
Compaq, IBM and NEC/Packard Bell, apparently is back on track. Last
week, for example, S3 announced a deal that will give it about $660
million worth of stock in a Taiwan chip manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   With Diamond, S3 will take over a company about three times
bigger. Diamond reported $608.6 million in revenues in 1998, though
for the year posted a net loss of $39.5 million and sliced 20
percent of its workforce.
</P>
<P>
   S3 has about 450 employees, while Diamond employs 950. Potashner
will become CEO of the merged company, and Diamond's CEO William
Schroeder will become chief operating officer and president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
