r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      06-22 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Good Sites For Tiny Firms 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: What are some of the best Web sites to learn about e-commerce &LR; 
 &UR; and conducting business online and avoid self-serving promotions &LR; 
 &UR; for products and services? &LR;
<P>
   A: As you have no doubt discovered using Yahoo, MetaCrawler or
other search engines, it's easy to get overloaded online. Many Web
sites operated by companies such as IBM, Intel and Microsoft have
lots of good information, but they also have an ax to grind or
accessories to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there are a host of independent sites with less-biased
information.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few, including some newcomers:
</P>
<P>
   _Webentrepreneurs.com _ This online community for Internet
entrepreneurs will be launched next Tuesday ( &LR; www. &LR; 
 &LR; entrepreneurs.com &LR; ). The brainchild of San Diego small-business
attorney Steven Morgan, it aims to provide a one-stop destination
for small businesses to find information about operating online,
share stories and network with other Internet entrepreneurs and
potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure credibility and encourage the same sort of interaction
one might find in a trade association, Webentrepreneurs will not
depend on sales of products or banner ads to make money. Rather, it
will charge users a $99 annual membership fee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Workz.com _ Last month, this Seattle company launched its
e-commerce portal ( &LR; www.workz. &LR;   &LR; com &LR; ) to help small businesses
compete online. For a membership fee of $49 a year, it provides
access to information on how to build, manage and promote a Web
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We founded Workz.com because we saw that small businesses
needed the same online capabilities as their larger counterparts
but lacked a way to get them,'' said company President David
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides nuts-and-bolts information about setting up
credit card transactions online, creating cost-effective banner ads
and graphic design, securing and registering domain names for Web
sites, getting better position on search engines and expanding
globally.
</P>
<P>
   Workz.com also provides a place in cyberspace where small
businesses can exchange ideas, form partnerships and solve
problems. Eventually, it would like to provide Consumer
Reports-type product reviews and services with members joining in
the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has about 2,500 members, most of them with
one to nine employees and less than $500,000 in annual revenues.
Free trial 30-day memberships are available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Onvia.com _ This is another new Seattle site (www.onvia.  &LR; com &LR; )
that aims to be a one-stop, Internet-only resource for
entrepreneurs. The company says it can help small businesses
research, compare and purchase most any product or service at one
site, without linking to another site and without registering and
submitting credit information many times. Next month, it will kick
off a $10 million advertsing campaign to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_WorkingSolo _ If you are self-employed, a home-based business, a
consultant, telecommuter or ``e-lancer,'' you might want to check
out  &LR; www.workingsolo.com &LR; . It provides links to other sites, gives
answers to business startup questions and publishes Working Solo
eNews, a free monthly newsletter that offers technology tips and
other information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Inc.Online _ Associated with Inc. magazine, www.inc.com offers an
Internet index and Web links, an E-Commerce Advisor Newsletter, a
guide to Internet terms and concepts, bulletin boards and news
groups, charts and statistics to benchmark your business, and a
free and simple create-your-own-Web-site feature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Entrepreneur Magazine _ This publisher has a useful Web site
( &LR; www.entrepreneurmag.com &LR; ) that offers information and articles on
e-commerce essentials, cyberstars and Web site building.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
