<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENT-LIFE-KAN &LR;      06-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENT-LIFE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVER OF LIFE, NOT FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH, BECKONS CENTENARIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH and ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Roberta Green applied for Social
Security, she was carded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man at the counter very patiently explained to me that you
have to be 61,'' she recalled. ``I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 40 years ago. Today, with her porcelain skin and a
crown of white, curly hair, Green, 101, looks younger than 70.
She's also a member of one of the fastest-growing age groups in the
United States _ people who live a century or more.
</P>
<P>
   A recent U.S. Census Bureau report estimates that nearly 70,000
centenarians live in the United States, about double the number
from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving 100 years was easy, Green said, padding around her
apartment at the Overland Park Place Retirement Home in Kansas,
laughing about her younger days _ when she was only 70-something.
</P>
<P>
   She called that time her ``second middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in my third middle-age now,'' she said. ``I've been
married two times.'' Then she added with a wink, ``but I've been in
love four or five times. Oh, I need a computer just so I can count
all my blessings these years.''
</P>
<P>
   While California, New York and Florida had the largest numbers
of residents 100 years old or older, centenarians make up a larger
percentage of the population in Midwestern states. Among them Iowa
is first, Kansas sixth and Missouri 13th.
</P>
<P>
   That's not because Midwesterners are necessarily hardier, said
Victoria Velkoff, co-author of the census report. It's because
young people looking for jobs have been migrating from the rural
Midwest to cities. Left behind are parents and grandparents, too
attached to their land and communities to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortality is going down, life expectancy is increasing,'' said
Velkoff. ``People are living to older ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaner drinking water, better sanitation, antibiotics to fight
infections and better treatments for chronic illness have all
contributed to longer life expectancy, said Linda Redford, a senior
research associate at the Center on Aging of the University of
Kansas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   And of those living past 100, four out of five are women,
according to the new Census Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
   Green's secret? .MDNM/A little exercise. (She performs her own
version of ``aerobics,'' lifting her arms and legs and doing
sit-ups on the mattress of her bed.) And a belief in moderation.
But she's no faddist. No bottled water or tofu cakes. No handfuls
of vitamins or skin-firming elixirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dab of baby oil every night, and it works fine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she doesn't drink or smoke.
</P>
<P>
   For her, aging means gaining more time to experience life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to worry about except enjoying the
beautiful day God gives me,'' she said. ``I try to have fun, and I
think I can make my friends laugh. That's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   A positive attitude is one of the secrets of living longer,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know everything there is to know about the nuts and bolts
of aging,'' said Walter Bortz, former president of the American
Geriatric Society and an associate professor at Stanford University
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you get through with that, you ask, what's it all
about? What's the job description to living long? I think it's
believing that you're supposed to, especially if you have meaning
to your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bortz wrote a book about growing old, ``Dare to Be 100,'' a
compilation of his studies with the elderly. Although there was no
one-size-fits all lifestyle, there were common traits among this
age group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying life, having a reason for living, giving thanks for yet
another day of filling your lungs with air _ all are traits
centenarians share.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, life expectancy has soared in the 20th century, from
an average of 45 years for both men and women to about 63 for men
and almost 68 for women, according to the U.N. World Population
Revision for 1998. By 2050 the average life expectancy worldwide is
expected to hit 83.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States the population has been aging steadily for
decades. Last year, the median age was 35.2 years, the highest ever
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   In the next century, when the baby boomers reach old age,
perhaps 3 million of them may reach centenarian status, the Census
Bureau predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Better health care has helped people live longer, Redford said.
But medicine can do only so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genetics have to play a major role,'' Redford said. ``Modern
medicine allows that genetic potential (for long life) to be
realized.''
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy and lifespan are two different things, said
Bortz. Although life expectancy has increased, lifespan, the number
of years the human body can survive if not done in by disease or
injury, has not. Despite medical advances, the maximum lifespan of
the human body remains about 120 years.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest known human being, Jeanne Calment, of France, lived
to be 122 and died in 1997, five years after she quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can determine how long you will live except you,'' said
Bortz. ``Not your ancestors, your church, your doctor, your school.
How long you live is determined by how much living you have to do.
It's never too late to decide to live longer. It's a gift you can
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Remaining active, developing new interests and maintaining
social contacts are common attributes of those who are aging
successfully, Redford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not sitting home depressed,'' she said. ``When people
say they've lived too long, it's because they have outlived those
(social) connections. They don't feel they have the energy to make
new connections.''
</P>
<P>
   While their medical and nursing care can be costly, the very old
remain a great asset to society, Redford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a link to the past, someone who has lived so long and
seen so much,'' she said. ``They can share that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best gift centenarians and elders give to the world
is their attitude. Despite suffering the losses that inevitably
come with age, they overcome the emotional blues and forge onward.
They love life but do not fear death.
</P>
<P>
   For Roberta Green, living to 101 has meant she's learned one
precious skill: to laugh as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   And what does she look forward to now that's she's passed 100
years?
</P>
<P>
   Without missing a beat, she answers:
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven, honey. Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a good time there, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
