</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUINT-JOBS-KAN &LR;      06-22 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUINT-JOBS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Quintiles could double KC area work force  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Quintiles Transnational Corp. is expected to
announce today a major expansion in Kansas City that could double
the size of its local work force.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina health-care company could add at least 500
jobs to the 500 it already has in Kansas City, according to several
sources familiar with the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes and
several top Quintiles executives are expected to attend a 4 p.m.
news conference at Kauffman Legacy Park, 4801 Rockhill Road.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's top economic-development officials and the mayor's
office declined to discuss the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Grebe, a Quintiles spokeswoman, confirmed that the company
would participate in the news conference. She declined to comment
further, referring questions to the Kansas City Area Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marcusse, president and chief executive officer of the
council, declined to comment, citing a confidentiality agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Quintiles paid $93 million for a chunk of Hoechst
Marion Roussel's operations here. About 500 Hoechst Marion workers
in its Kansas City drug development and approval operations became
employees of Quintiles at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Quintiles provides research, sales and marketing services to the
pharmaceutical, biotechnology and medical device industries. The
company also provides health-care information management services
and conducts clinical drug research in Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement today is expected to put flesh and blood on the
skeletal development plan Quintiles disclosed in February, when
state officials approved a $4 million bond issue for the company.
The bond money can be used to acquire property and equipment,
expand facilities and upgrade public infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Quintiles said it would use the bond money as part of a $19
million plan to expand facilities it agreed to buy from Hoechst
Marion.
</P>
<P>
   In its application for bond financing, Quintiles warned that it
would consider transferring its expansion plans to North Carolina
or California if Missouri didn't provide significant incentives.
Both of those states had ``informally promised'' Quintiles
significant benefits for expanding within their borders, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the Missouri benefits, Quintiles said it would
add 532 new jobs to its Kansas City office. According to the
application, Quintiles would pay those workers an average annual
salary of $62,800. The total annual payroll for the new workers
would be about $33.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the information submitted to the state, Quintiles
said it would add the 532 workers between 1999 and 2002. Quintiles
said it would add 143 workers in 1999, 120 in 2000, 132 in 2001 and
137 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The group of new workers with the highest payroll would be 173
scientists earning an average starting salary of $75,800 a year.
The lowest average starting wage would be 166 technicians earning
$34,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Quintiles' expansion of its Kansas City office would not
surprise securities analysts who follow the publicly traded
company.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Miller, an analyst for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco,
said: ``They've always stated that their goal was to grow this
facility (in Kansas City). It's certainly a feather in your cap to
have Quintiles with such an important presence there.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintiles is benefiting from an explosion in drug development
and drug companies hiring other firms to handle the clinical trials
of new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Miller characterized Quintiles as a trendsetter in its field.
``They've been very aggressive in acquisitions. They've been the
leader in gathering under their umbrella all kinds of
pharmaceutical services companies'' and setting up ``one-stop
shopping'' for its customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has a big presence internationally, Miller
noted. Quintiles, for example, announced June 1 that it had
acquired Minerva Medical PLC, a clinical research organization
based in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The Quintiles expansion is occurring amid uncertainty over
Hoechst Marion's presence in the area. Hoechst Marion's parent
company, Germany-based Hoechst AG, is completing its planned merger
with Rhone-Poulenc SA of France.
</P>
<P>
   The new company would be called Aventis, and its pharmaceutical
unit would be known as Aventis Pharma. The merger could result in
Hoechst Marion's North American headquarters being moved to
Bridgewater, N.J., where Hoechst has a big facility, or to
Collegeville, Pa., the North American headquarters for the
Rhone-Poulenc Rorer pharmaceutical unit.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst and Rhone-Poulenc have said they will complete their
merger by November. Hoechst Marion has said its manufacturing
operations will remain in Kansas City, regardless of whether the
headquarters stays here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
