A5810 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEX-ASHCROFT-KAN &LR;      06-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEX-ASHCROFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEXTIME ISSUE RESURFACES ON CAPITOL HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a White House reception two years ago, President
Clinton pulled Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri aside and told him
that he wanted to sign some version of his bill that would allow
hourly workers to take time off to be with their families without
losing a day's pay.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's legislation, which he called ``flextime,''
disappeared in the political chasm that traditionally divides
business and labor issues on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was before the school shootings in Littleton,
Colo., and elsewhere sparked a national introspection about
children.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Congress suddenly sensitive to family concerns, and
with a pivotal election year looming, the issue has new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue whose time has come,'' said Ashcroft, a
Republican running for re-election next year. ``There are
exclamation points added over and over again about the need for
parents and children to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   His bill, the Family Friendly Workplace Act, would enable
employees and employers to work out flexible schedules to allow
parents more time for out-of-work activities, such as doctor
appointments for their children and school activities. If the
employer agreed, the employee could choose to be paid with
time-and-a-half compensatory time for overtime in lieu of
time-and-a-half pay.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes provisions that would permit workers,
with their employers' approval, to work biweekly schedules, as
federal employers are allowed. They could put in as much as 80
hours over a two-week period, with a 50-hour limit for any given
week. Unused time off would be converted to cash at the end of each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft reintroduced his bill last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Brundage of Jefferson City, who used to work in the Missouri
attorney general's office, said she would have liked that option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up quitting my job to spend more time with my family,
because there wasn't flextime where I worked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was a visit to the pediatrician, or a Mother's Day
program at her child's day-care center, Brundage said she kept
having to use vacation time or to take time off without pay just to
be with her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for me to be with my family, so we took
a financial hit, and I quit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But organized labor strongly opposes the issue. They argue that
it is a threat to the 40-hour workweek.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers, like John M. Franiuk, a machinist from Tonganoxie,
Kan., who works at the Trans World Airlines overhaul base, said
they just do not trust employers to honor commitments they would
make under the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen,'' Franiuk said, ``is there are
employers who will say, `Oh, yeah, I owe you 12 hours time off, but
you can only take that in two-hour increments, and only in Tuesdays
and Thursdays, unless it's the third week of month.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's bill died two years ago, despite White House
interest, because pro-labor Democrats, such as Sen. Edward Kennedy
of Massachusetts, filibustered the issue. It never reached a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The political divisions remain unchanged: Business still likes
the idea, and labor still hates it.
</P>
<P>
   If it is to have any chance at passage, it could be because
Republicans may attempt to link its fate to an issue that their
business supporters largely despise and that labor covets _ raising
the minimum wage, which now stands at $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats maneuvered a two-step, 90-cent increase in the
politically charged congressional debates of the 1996 presidential
campaign. Supporters this year hope to raise it by another dollar.
House Republican leaders, acknowledging the political punch that
opposing a wage increase could carry, have already conceded that
the increase may pass.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Manley, a spokesman for Kennedy, the expected sponsor of a
minimum-wage increase, dismissed the idea of linking it to
flextime. Calling Ashcroft's proposal a ``labor-bashing poison
pill,'' Manley said: ``That's a nonstarter. I can predict it would
meet with opposition on the Senate floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Taylor, a congressional lobbyist for the AFL-CIO, said she
had not even heard the idea being talked about.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, even the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, a strong
backer of flextime, is not keen on using the minimum wage to defang
Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are opposed, too,'' said Michael Bartlett, manager of
labor-law policy for the chamber. ``We are not in the business of
negotiating it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ``That is not a universally held position
among all employers. Where that will lead everyone remains to be
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft also kept the door open. He did not rule out linking
the two issues but said the possibility was ``too hypothetical.''
He noted, though, that he supported a minimum-wage increase when he
was Missouri governor.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over both issues, however, is certain to reflect the
political mood and be a harbinger of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Alston, executive director of the centrist Democratic
Leadership Council, said: ``I think the balance of family and work
is going to increasingly become a cutting-edge issue in American
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
