<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DENOUNCES GORE AS WASHINGTON INSIDER AT GOP FUND-RAISER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush huddled with
congressional Republicans on Tuesday, then milked a ballroom packed
with lobbyists out of an estimated $2 million for his presidential
campaign treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Before his back-slapping foray through Washington, the GOP
front-runner visited Richmond, Va., where he held another
fund-raiser and denounced Vice President Al Gore as a Washington
insider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Washington, D.C., person,'' Bush said of the vice
president, the current front-runner for the Democratic presidential
nomination. ``He thinks Washington has got all the answers. I
don't. I believe the answers are found in our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   When he reached Washington, Bush met behind closed doors at the
Capitol with 32 Republican senators, then later with more than 100
House members. When he emerged, he promised to stand with the GOP
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to bash Republican members of Congress,'' Bush
told reporters, dismissing suggestions that the GOP opposition to
stronger gun control might hurt his effort to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the support I've received inside this
building,'' Bush said. ``I believe I'm going to be here to work
with them for a better tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's fund-raisers, Bush outlined his broad campaign
themes, pledging to show compassion for the disadvantaged,
strengthen the military, cut taxes, raise educational standards,
remove trade barriers and lead with integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The two events, both low-budget affairs, were Bush's ninth and
10th in two weeks. By the end of the month, he will have held 26
fund-raisers across the country as he tries to cement his GOP
front-runner position, not only with endorsements and opinion
polls, but in money.
</P>
<P>
   Aides predicted that by June 30, Bush's campaign treasury could
top $20 million, well ahead of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he is sucking all the oxygen out of the
room,'' said Bill Paxon, a former Republican congressman from New
York and now a lobbyist with the Akin, Gump law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign ``seems to be pretty good at raising money,''
said Howard Opinsky, campaign spokesman for Sen. John McCain,
another Republican presidential hopeful. ``Raising money does not
guarantee you the nomination,'' Opinsky said. ``If money alone
makes you the nominee, then (publisher and GOP candidate) Steve
Forbes would be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Any concern that Bush's compassionate conservative message and
his repeated knocks on Washington politics would hurt him in the
nation's capital were dispelled Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people crowded into the ballroom of the
Washington Hilton, where they dined on standard Bush campaign fare
_ hot dogs, popcorn and cookies served from a buffet. There were no
waiters, no tables, no chairs. The liquor was free for those who
paid $1,000 to get in. The room swam with mostly white faces,
well-coiffed hair and summer-weight navy and gray suits.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Morrison, a Washington tax lawyer and former Treasury
Department official under President Bush, said it was the largest
crowd he had seen at the hotel. ``The night Ronald Reagan was
elected, there weren't this many people in this room,'' Morrison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the candidate was dazzled. ``I am honored with this huge
turnout, and I'm grateful you are on my team,'' Bush said,
</P>
<P>
   Not even Bush's father, who spent almost 25 years as a
Washington insider, raised as much money in a single evening in the
capital when he ran for president in 1988 or for re-election in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   While in Richmond, Bush and wife, Laura, visited a city library
to tout reading programs and present the library with a copy of
``Hank the Cowdog,'' a children's book. Later, he spoke to a crowd
of supporters who donated about $350,000 to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush heads to Pennsylvania for fund-raisers and
campaign stops in Bethlehem, Philadelphia, Harrisburg and
Pittsburgh. then to Michigan and Florida. Next week, he's scheduled
for seven fund-raisers amid campaigning in California before flying
back to Austin, the capital of Texas, for another fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
