<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REPUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S GOP ESTABLISHMENT EMBRACES BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Wash., Texas, Mo., Utah, R.I., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush was warmly embraced by
Washington's Republican establishment Tuesday as he swept from a
Capitol sit-down with senators to a meeting with about 100 members
of the House majority and finally to a glittering fund-raiser
attended by a veritable who's who of Republican power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Eager for presidential coattails in 2000, congressional
Republicans were virtually swooning over the Texan who has quickly
become his party's presumed front-runner and unquestioned
fund-raising leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just look in his eyes,'' said Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn.,
``and you can feel that he's prepared to serve.'' Rep. Jennifer
Dunn, R-Wash., said, ``He's really got the magic.'' And Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who escorted the governor into the
midday meeting with senators, said, ``He has an openness.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was a tricky balancing act for Bush, adding to an air of
his inevitability as the party's presidential nominee but also
complicating his effort to portray himself as a Washington
outsider. Even as he collected $2 million at a reception of
Washington political strategists and lobbyists Tuesday night, he
took several swipes at the capital's bitter divisiveness, hours
after he had assured Republican lawmakers that he would not run
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many across this land see Washington, and they don't like what
they see,'' Bush said. ``They see people more worried about who
takes the credit and who gets the blame than who gets results. The
purpose of politics is not to embarrass your opponents. It is to
advance your ideals, to make a difference, to make America a better
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He drew one of his biggest ovations when he assured the crowd
that he did not make decisions on the basis of the latest public
opinion polls. ``It's time that the most important job in
Washington be the president,'' he said, ``not the president's
pollster.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Bush's first presidential-campaign fund-raiser in
Washington, and, as is customary at his fund-raising events, the
overhead was minimal. Tickets cost $1,000 each, but there were no
seats or tables for the guests, who munched on hot dogs, brownies
and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, on his visit to the Capitol, Bush was spared
the one photo opportunity that Democrats so dearly wanted to see.
There was no tableau of the governor with a fellow Texas
Republican, Rep. Tom DeLay, the fiery House majority whip, who in
recent days has blamed everything from day care to contraception
for youth violence and complained that the government ``has decided
that schools cannot give kids the choice of learning about
creationism and evolution and then choosing what they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., who is both DeLay's chief deputy whip and
Bush's point man in the House, said DeLay and the other senior
Republican leaders had been too busy with their weekly Tuesday
meeting to stop by the Library of Congress with 100 other House
Republicans to hear Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor assured those Republicans that he would not run
against them and their record. ``I said I'd work with them _ `I
intend to hold you up as good citizens,''' he told reporters. ``I'm
not going to bash the Republican members of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not concerned that his embrace by congressional
Republicans, many of whom have already endorsed him, would prove a
liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure Washington itself is popular right now,'' he
said, ``but I intend to win, and I want to be able to work with
Congressmen because there's an agenda to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor called DeLay ``a friend'' and said, ``I look
forward to working with him.'' He dismissed Democrats' references
to the ``Bush-DeLay team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think attempts to tie me to DeLay and all that stuff, I
don't think it's going to hunt,'' he said. ``I think what people
want to know is: `Can he lead? Who's the best leader for
America?'''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate session on his first appearance at the Capitol,
Bush drew 36 curious senators _ including, briefly, Orrin Hatch of
Utah, who had just told reporters that he had decided to jump into
the Republican presidential race himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the senators that he expected to be working with them
in 2001. By the end of their 20-minute meeting, in the Senate
Foreign Relations committee room, he had another convert: John
Chafee of Rhode Island had become the 23rd Republican senator to
move to his side.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance in Richmond, Va., before arriving here, Bush
endorsed the House's vote last week for a measure that would allow
the Ten Commandments to be posted in public schools. ``I have no
problem with the Ten Commandments posted on the wall of every
public place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also portrayed Vice President Al Gore as the real insider.
``He's a Washington, D.C., person,'' the governor said. ``He thinks
Washington has got all the answers. I don't. I believe the answers
are found in our communities. I believe that the answers are found
in faith-based institutions, in community organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats fought back by linking Bush to the Republican
Congress that he came courting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he hasn't said much about his ideas, when you press
him for specifics Bush follows the far-right GOP Congress more than
he leads it,'' said Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
