<SLUG> BC-FILM-OLIVER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FILMS, DIRECTOR OLIVER PARKER LIKES TO SHAKE UP CONVENTIONAL
THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Despite, or maybe because of, his long career in the
theater, director Oliver Parker doesn't take a reverential approach
when putting stage classics on film.
</P>
<P>
   For Oscar Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband,'' a witty Victorian
melodrama, his goal was to make ``a period screwball comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's first film was a naturalistic version of William
Shakespeare's ``Othello,'' released in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed while on a tour promoting ``An Ideal Husband,''
which opens Friday, Parker says he braced himself for criticism for
cutting away at classic texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the inspiration behind both `Othello' and `An Ideal
Husband' has been the desire to shake up the conventional attitude
toward the works. It's almost as if they've been seen solely in
academic worlds until now. I feel more loyal to the spirit of the
original than the original words.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I feel if you don't take some angle, if you don't find a
way to win your audience over, then you have even less of a chance
at delivering the essence of the piece. Striving to make the work
accessible drives one along almost as much as making complex ideas
accessible. The trick is to retain the complexity but make the text
less fearsome for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his relatively scant movie-making track record, Parker
has been able to corral great talent for both of his films.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Othello,'' it was Laurence Fishburne, Kenneth Branagh and
Irene Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   For ``An Ideal Husband,'' it's Cate Blanchett, Minnie Driver,
Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore and Jeremy Northam.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde's witty comedy of manners, moral values and dark secrets
that threaten a rigidly loving marriage at the turn of the century
seems timely today. The movie was the closing feature at the Cannes
Film Festival and played earlier this month at the Seattle
International Film Festival, winning Everett the festival's best
actor award.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchett plays Gertrude Chiltern, a devoted and do-right wife
to brilliant politician Robert Chiltern (Northam). They have
everything they could hope for _ love, ambition and a future. But
when the mysterious adventuress, Mrs. Chevely (Moore), reminds Sir
Robert of a letter that could prove to be his undoing, the couple's
carefully structured, perfectly manicured world falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to hedonistic, happy bachelor and arch best friend
Arthur Goring (Everett) to come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Parker says he felt extremely lucky to get the cast. He waxes
especially enthusiastic about rising star Blanchett, who earned a
best actress Oscar nomination this year for ``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fantastic. I was so pleased to have her because her role
is essentially the toughest part. I was amazed she was even
interested in doing it, though I always felt there was something
interesting to get hold of in Gertrude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knows the play will, I think, be prejudiced
against her because she's normally the antagonist of the piece _
she stops everyone from having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were quite keen to try and craft a slightly different route
for her in our film. Wilde had, perhaps, a different agenda in his
day. He satirized the bureaucracy and the upper middle class
through her and, in a way, we tried to get behind the scenes a
little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main things we needed to dramatize was the battle
going on in her head. She has been brought up to believe in strict
moral codes, and she actually has feelings that are in opposition
to them when she learns the truth about her husband. In that very
moment, we get into her head and heart. Then there is interesting
drama.''
</P>
<P>
   The director says he purposefully cast an American to play the
antagonist, Mrs. Chevely. ``She's an outsider in the play so we
wanted a non-British person to play her, and Julianne has a
wonderful way of being hard, yet vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   So, is there one character in the play that embodies Wilde's,
well, wild personal philosophy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' says Parker. ``The obvious character who stands as a
mouthpiece for Wilde is Goring. He's the reluctant hero who has no
morality at all, but by the end has saved everybody from their
terrible troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Goring is ``a walking paradox'' and that is the ``heart'' of
Wilde, Parker explains. ``Even the main theme of the play was about
embracing the ambiguities in oneself, in a lover and in the world
we live in _ and not to be afraid of them because that's what makes
us human; that's what makes us unique.''
</P>
<P>
   And who does he personally relate to in ``An Ideal Husband?''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``The butler, of course. He's a little bit like a
director, watching people come and go and opening and closing all
those doors.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, he says, a relief to direct a comedy of manners after a
tragedy like ``Othello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a saving on the laundry bills,'' he says,
laughing. ``There was much less blood around because everyone was
still standing at the end of this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parallels between the two plays, of course, but in
terms of tone, it's a lot of fun to be working with Wilde's wit
infecting the filmmaking community. I think it was a terrific
atmosphere to work in, and I always believed it was crucial to the
quality of the relationships onscreen. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if you can encourage actors to relax and enjoy their
environment, you'll get their best. I have some lovely memories of
this cast and how they started to work together as a team, despite
their different backgrounds and cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker draws on a huge theater background in bringing his
directorial techniques to the screen. ``I worked in a company of
Clive Barker's,'' he says. ``I'd been an actor and also involved in
stage management, and I wrote a play about William Blake with
another actor in the company. I ended up in the director's chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in aspects of it. I enjoyed acting
immensely but I realized my weakness as an actor might be my
strength as a director.''
</P>
<P>
   He's scheduled to begin working soon on a third film _ a
fictional movie about Orson Welles from a script by John Sayles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2209EDT &QL; 
