<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SALON.COM AUCTION FAILS TO ENTHUSE INTERNET
INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Salon.com, an online magazine with meager
revenue, went public with a whimper Tuesday, as investors continued
to weigh not only the value of Internet issues themselves but also
that of the institutions leading them to market.
</P>
<P>
   Clouding the new stock's performance was the unusual method used
to set the opening price, a process called a modified Dutch
auction, which allows individuals to bid on the stock before it
begins trading publicly. The tepid response suggests the market's
lack of interest in Salon. But first-day enthusiasm may have been
undermined by the auction format, which eliminates the role of
traditional underwriters of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was priced Monday night by W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co. of San
Francisco at $10.50 a share, at the bottom of the anticipated price
range of $10.50 to $13.50 a share, and closed Tuesday at $10.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Tuesday's initial offering by Ramp Networks got off
to a roaring start. The company's product allows multiple users in
a small office to share an Internet connection, making it an
Internet infrastructure company rather than a provider of content
for the Internet. Its stock was priced at $11 and rose 61 percent
in the first day of trading to close at $16.75.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of Salon described the mood Monday as ``jubilant''
but business-as-usual as the staff celebrated the public offering
with a pizza lunch. The company, started by former staff members of
The San Francisco Examiner, wound up the day with a market value of
$107 million, having sold 2.5 million of 10.7 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   As remarkable as the valuation may seem given Salon's losses of
$6.5 million last year on $2.9 million in revenue, the offering is
a yawner by Internet standards. In March, for example, shares of
iVillage, a women's network, rose 300 percent the first day, while
stock in the financial news company TheStreet.com exploded 216
percent on its first day of trading in May. Both stocks,
underwritten by the venerable Wall Street firm of Goldman, Sachs,
have since given back much of their gains but remain well above
their offering prices, providing tidy paper profits for insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Salon chief executive Michael O'Donnell said the first-day price
had to be put into context, and he pointed out that the Internet
media ``sector is down 27 percent since we filed'' April 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of an IPO is to get company proceeds to grow,''
he said. ``If you're looking for a quick pop today, you may be
disappointed. We have nowhere to go but up.'' O'Donnell also said
that the auction attracted long-term investors, not day traders who
would put pressure on the company for immediate returns.
</P>
<P>
   For its stock to gain ground, Salon will need more advertising
and a bigger audience. Media Metrix reported that Salon attracted a
million individual visitors in May, substantially fewer than the
3.2 million who visited iVillage.com. TheStreet.com had 783,000
visitors in April, but it also derives revenue from more than
51,000 subscribers who pay $9.95 monthly or $99.95 yearly.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said Salon would use $5 million of the $25 million
raised Tuesday to embark on a national television, radio and print
advertising campaign. Since it began in 1995, Salon.com has spent a
mere $200,000 on marketing, though it has generated Internet buzz,
partly because of well-known writers, including Isabel Allende and
Paul Theroux, and its literary journalism and political reporting,
particularly during the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pleased shareholders is David Talbot, the former
editor of arts and feature articles at The Examiner who founded
Salon. Based on holdings reported April 15, Talbot, now the editor
in chief, has stock worth $3 million, and had options to buy
102,000 additional shares.
</P>
<P>
   The largest investor, with 26 percent of the magazine, is Adobe
Ventures, a venture capital firm, whose stake is now worth $28
million. Another prominent Salon investor is television mogul
Norman Lear, whose stake is now worth $2.57 million, excluding
25,000 warrants. O'Donnell's shares, in the form of options, are
worth $1.58 million. Hambrecht requires that Salon insiders hold
shares at least 90 days after the public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The Salon offering was the second auction from Hambrecht. The
first, in April, for Ravenswood Winery was also lackluster. Those
shares, which were also priced at $10.50, closed Tuesday at
$10.625.
</P>
<P>
   In Hambrecht's auctions, investors submit bids for how many
shares they are willing to buy and at what price. At the end of the
bidding period, Hambrecht starts awarding shares to the highest
bidders. It continues down the price list until all shares are
sold. The catch is that all bidders, regardless of what they bid,
pay only the price submitted by the lowest bidder in the winning
group.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht president Ian Zwicker said the Dutch auction was less
expensive for the issuing company. Traditional underwriters usually
charge 7 percent of the gross on a small stock offering like
Salon's, and Hambrecht charged 5 percent, or about $1.5 million,
Zwicker said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with Salon, the company going public may forfeit the
first day liftoff. That is' because individual investors eager to
snap up Internet issues have already bid on the stock to help set
its market value.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Pasternak, the chief executive of Knight Securities
Inc., one of the nation's largest market makers, said an auction
made sense in the era of highflying Internet stocks. Institutions
appear to be setting prices too low given the demand of individual
investors, a problem the auction can mitigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most IPO's don't properly reflect the pricing mechanics of
individual investors correctly,'' he said. In fact, TheStreet and
iVillage could be criticized for leaving money on the table, since
investors were willing to pay well above the offering price set by
their underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Pasternak cautioned, though, that the auction method is still
untested, given the two small issues from Hambrecht, and its
success will be determined in coming months. The next issue from
Hambrecht will be for GreatFood.com.
</P>
<P>
   At least one investor and stock analyst was optimistic about
Salon. Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology
Stockletter and manager of a technology portfolio that bought 6,000
Salon.com shares in the auction, said, ``If this trades in the
teens as I expect, it could validate this as a way to go public.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
