<P>
   STADIUM-OVERRUNS (Seattle) _ The Seattle Mariners seek mediation
with the stadium district over dispute on $100 million cost
overrun. The Mariners want a piece of the excess tax revenue that
is being raised to pay off the venue, and have asked the Public
Facilities District to seek all available bond funding from King
County. The district has said that it would not ask the county for
additional funds. Mariners now charge the PFD's refusal is ``a
breach of the PFD's statutory and contractual obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Snel. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGSTORE (Seattle) _ Bellevue, Wash-based drugstore.com has
signed a 10-year-agreement with Rite Aid Corp. and General
Nutrition Centers Inc. to be the exclusive Internet pharmacy for
the bricks-and-mortar retailers. The deal comes only a month after
Seattle-based Soma.com was sold to CVS Corp., another traditional
pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   By John Cook. (Story will move in the ``f'' category).
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE (WILLIAMSBURG, Va.) _ As Colonial Williamsburg, the
reconstructed capital of colonial Virginia, tries to broaden its
appeal and lure tourists, the 3,000 staffers operate by a new
credo: enter the 21st Century without leaving the 18th. That means
the actors who portray residents of the village now tackle
contemporary topics, like slavery and church-state relations. It
means the organization's lucrative catalog business is moving
beyond its collection of authentic furniture replicas to offer a
new line of casual, family-oriented home furnishings inspired by
colonial tastes. And increasingly it means turning to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PARK-B.C. (VICTORIA, B.C.) _ Under fire from environmentalists,
the British Columbia government sought to made amends Tuesday by
announcing designation of more than 3 million acres of new
provincial parkland. Several of the park areas will protect
north-of-the-border habitats of wildlife populations shared by the
U.S. and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   RICH-SUBURBS (Seattle) _ All that Microsoft and Amazon wealth
has propelled several Seattle suburbs to Worth Magazine's list of
the most expensive places to live in the United States. They
include Yarrow Point, Woodway and Clyde Hill and Medina, where Bill
Gates lives. Because of stock options and bonuses, a remarkable
number of home purchases at the very highest end are increasingly
transacted in cash.
</P>
<P>
   By Tracy Johnson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category).
