<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-HN     06-22 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The names came easily, quickly. Speaking of the lost art
of the midrange jump shot, Knicks guard Allan Houston rattled off
New York icons Walt Frazier and Earl Monroe. He spoke of Oscar
Robertson and Michael Jordan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now, in an era when the NBA's game has grown so ugly that
special committees are assembled to consider how to slap on some
polish, Houston is making a name for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Spurs forward Tim Duncan has risen in the West, becoming
the NBA's best player even as far as Houston's coach, Jeff Van
Gundy, is concerned. But Houston has grabbed a huge chunk of the
postseason as well and taken it for his own. He has walked onto the
league's largest stage and shone in his own quiet way.
</P>
<P>
   He hit the running, last-chance jumper that eliminated the Miami
Heat. He dominated the Indiana Pacers in the Game 6 clincher of
that series. And with the NBA Finals quickly fading from the
Knicks' reach, Houston would not allow his team to lose. In New
York's 89-81 Game 3 win over the Spurs on Monday, he matched the
best postseason scoring game of his career with 34 points and
carried the Knicks through their rough patches, much like another
shooting guard who carried his team to six championships this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind I've always been that, and I will continue to be
that type of player,'' Houston said. ``That's the belief I have in
myself. The farther this team goes on a consistent basis hopefully
we'll be back here again, and hopefully people will consider
that.''
</P>
<P>
   While a side-by-side comparison to Jordan would be laughable, it
is not too much to say that Houston has arrived in this postseason.
The celebrated revivals of Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby
notwithstanding, Houston has been the Knicks' most consistent
scorer, their most steadily improving force. Even in the
offense-challenged Finals, he scored 19 points in each of the two
games in San Antonio before his Game 3 eruption.
</P>
<P>
   In a single minute of Monday's second half at Madison Square
Garden, Houston scored seven points by nailing three consecutive
jumpers and a free throw. But immediately after that, the Knicks
missed nine consecutive shots over a span topping six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the dry spell, the Spurs forged a tie before seeming
to have a stop on defense. But New York's Kurt Thomas dived to pick
up a loose ball and sent it to Houston, who nailed his first
3-pointer of the series at the shot-clock buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of ironic,'' he said. ``When I first got to the
league, that's all I did _ shoot 3s. Now it's like I'm feeling more
comfortable taking the ball to the basket. It felt good to finally
make one.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, Houston drove the lane, drew a foul and
pushed the Knicks' lead to five, single-handedly regaining New
York's control of a game it had to win.
</P>
<P>
   By extending his game well past the soft jump shot taught to him
by his father, former Tennessee coach Wade Houston, Houston has
become almost impossible to defend. And while the NBA, despite its
declining scoring, still has players who can make an open shot,
Houston has become one of the few who can get good shots for
himself and teammates at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc (Rivers, the new Orlando coach who played with the Spurs)
always told us he (Houston) was the hardest guy on the team to
guard when he was isolated,'' said R.C. Buford, a Spurs scout and
assistant coach. ``He wasn't such a prevalent option, because
Patrick (Ewing) was always there on the low blocks. There was no
place to go get a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good on a crossover. He can step back or spin back
into his fadeaway. Now they put him on the post more than he ever
was. He's big enough to shoot over you. If he gets a little space,
it's very tough to get back to him in time. He goes away from the
double team or he can back out of a trap, then go at you when you
leave him. We'd like to play him straight and then come at him once
he gets to the paint. But he never really gets to the paint. He
takes that shot in between the start (of his drive) and the
paint.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to improving his skills, Houston has changed his
mentality. Once happy to defer to others and their talents, he now
understands and exploits his own abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's finally finding out how good he is,'' said Brendan
Malone, a Knicks assistant coach who also was with Houston for two
of the player's three seasons in Detroit. ``In Game 6 of the
Indiana series, he said, `This is my night, and it's going to
happen.' He continued to say that throughout the game. That was the
game that I think was his breakthrough game in a big situation.
(Monday) night, he was having a good time. He was taking the ball
to the hole, posting up, hitting the open shots. You could see his
confidence build.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a subordinate role when he first came here with
Patrick Ewing, in Detroit with Grant Hill. Right now, he's starting
to emerge. You're going to see him blossom as a super offensive
player.''
</P>
<P>
   It is telling, however, that Houston wants to be more than that.
He was always confident in his abilities, as evidenced by his
decision to sign with the Knicks as a free agent and assume the
pressure that comes with that. But now he wants to dominate and
might not even settle for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a guy like Michael, even a guy like Spree, the
great players and the great scorers in this league. They're not
happy with 20 points,'' Houston said. ``If they have a great start,
they want to keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in my career I was little unselfish. I think you can do
both. That's what I've learned stay aggressive and stay hungry for
48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this position, it's saturated. This position, you've got
the Steve Smiths, the J.R. Riders, the Reggie Millers. You can go
down the line. Even teams that are not great playoff teams have a
shooting guard. That's our job, to put the ball in the basket. The
first part of the position is shooting. That's what we do best. I
try to get to the point where people say, `He doesn't have any
weaknesses.' That's my goal. I try to be an all-around player.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent results would suggest he is succeeding and has taken his
game well beyond good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between good and great in this league is two
things: consistency _ who can do it often _ and who can do it
late,'' Van Gundy said. ``That's what it comes down to. I think
Allan is doing it more consistently, and he's doing it late in
games.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's doing it on the greatest stage, giving him a sudden
chance to join the legendary names he dropped as easily as open
18-footers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
