<HEADER>
A5825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-CO     06-22 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston scores 34 as Knicks climb back in NBA Finals
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Put the brooms away, San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are back in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   With their season seemingly fading, New York battled back with a
89-81 victory Monday in Game3, breaking the Spurs' 12-game playoff
winning streak and keeping alive their bid for another stunning
post-season upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks rode a hot Allan Houston, who scored a
career-playoff-high 34 points and held off a late Spurs rally, to
crush the hopes of the Spurs' fans who were chanting, ``Sweep!
Sweep! Sweep!'' at the end of Game2.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell had 24 points. Houston and Sprewell combined to
shoot 19-of-46.
</P>
<P>
   The undermanned Knicks _ who never trailed _ can tie the series
in Game4 Wednesday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio cut a 10-point deficit to four with 3:11 to play but
consecutive baskets by Houston and Marcus Camby, who suffered
through one of his worst playoff games after making his first start
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who scored 32 points total in the fourth quarter of
the first two games, had 24 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who lost on the road for the first time in the
playoffs, were led by David Robinson's 25 points. Tim Duncan had 20
points, but was scoreless in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was the Knicks' energizer off the bench, but the move to
start him backfired. Camby, who has been in foul trouble throughout
the season coming off the bench, picked up his second midway
through the first quarter, both against Robinson. He was replaced
by Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated Camby then picked up two fouls in the first 1 1/2
minutes of the third quarter, the first when he and Robinson pushed
and shoved with each being slapped with a foul and technical.
Seconds later, Camby fouled Robinson in the lane and went to bench
with no points and four fouls in 10 minutes. He fouled out with
five points.
</P>
<P>
   Camby had one highlight-reel play, a dunk in which he rose high
and shoved home a Houston miss. The play came early in the fourth
quarter and gave the Knicks a 69-62 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later he committed his fifth foul.
</P>
<P>
   Camby started at center, replacing Chris Dudley. Knicks coach
Jeff Van Gundy gave no thought to removing point guard Charlie Ward
instead, which would have made the Knicks bigger all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a radical change, but with any change you have to
do it because you believe in it, not because there's been a clamor
for it,'' Van Gundy said. ``We got here playing one way. Our style
is not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   That style had not been nearly good enough to beat the Spurs,
whose two victories in San Antonio were easier than the scores
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   But New York finally resembled the team that upset Miami,
Atlanta and Indiana in the conference playoffs, playing its best
quarter of the Finals in the first Monday. Behind Houston, the
Knicks built a 14-point lead before Antonio Daniels' three-pointer
in the final second cut New York's lead to 32-21. Daniels, who
played four minutes in the first two games, had eight points in the
first 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   New York moved the ball, exploited mismatches in the backcourt
after Mario Elie left with two fouls, and made its shots. The
Knicks' six assists in the quarter were two less than they had in
all of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Tom D'Angelo writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
