<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTRAL-FLORIDA-ART-H     06-22 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-FLORIDA-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL TAKES ON DISNEY WITH ITS HIGH-TECH ISLANDS OF ADVENTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Also see Central-Florida-Islands, Central-Florida-Disney,
Central-Florida-Citywalk and Central-Florida-Parks) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Here's a news flash for Disney: You may never be
outdone by Universal, but you've definitely been ``out-funned.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal Islands of Adventure, which celebrated its grand
opening Memorial Day weekend, delivers more thrills, chills and
excitement than the combined efforts of Walt Disney World's four
themed parks.
</P>
<P>
   And Islands is just what the doctor, or should we say the teens,
ordered for central Florida. While the Magic Kingdom and the
Muppets kept the tots happy, and Mom and Pop lapped up the
educational hooey of Epcot, teens vacationing here previously were
relegated to eye rolling and making do with archaic rides such as
Space Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
<P>
   With outstanding roller coasters, a revolutionary
three-dimensional thrill ride and a menacingly named Doctor Doom's
Fearfall, Islands of Adventure is targeting a young, sophisticated
audience.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't ignoring the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   For the wee ones, there is Seuss Landing, a 10-acre tribute to
the memorable creations of Theodore Geisel.
</P>
<P>
   And for parents ... well, there's the entire park.
</P>
<P>
   Islands of Adventure is just one giant tip o' the hat to baby
boomers. Every corner of the 110-acre park is filled with feel-good
icons such as Popeye, the Cat in the Hat, Sinbad, Dudley Do-Right
and Spider-Man.
</P>
<P>
   The park is designed around five themed ``islands'' with the
adventure beginning at the exotic Port of Entry, a little chunk of
Marrakech dusted off for Orlando. Moving clockwise around the port,
the ``islands'' are Marvel Super Hero Island, Toon Lagoon, Jurassic
Park, the Lost Continent and Seuss Landing.
</P>
<P>
   From the park's entry, the most stunning sight is Jurassic Park.
Film fans will have a sense of deja vu as they look across the lake
at Universal's faithful re-creation of the building from the Steven
Spielberg blockbuster movie.
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park includes several interesting attractions such as
the Discovery Center, where you can watch a raptor hatch, and the
Triceratops Encounter, where you can pet a dinosaur. The area's
thrill ride, Jurassic Park River Adventure, also offers some close
encounters as riders must outrace a tyrannosaurus rex and survive
an 85-foot plunge into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced animatronic technology makes these exhibits work. In
the intimately scaled Triceratops Encounter, a very real-looking,
24-foot dinosaur breathes, blinks, twitches and sneezes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think of trying the Pteranodon Flyers. This
slow-loading ride, which features a pair of chairs gliding over the
island, frequently requires two-hour waits for 80 seconds of air
time.
</P>
<P>
   But Universal anticipated long waits for star attractions such
as the Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man and Dueling Dragons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Queues are an opportunity for storytelling,'' explains Phil
Hettema, Universal's senior vice president for attraction
development. ``We didn't just build rides, we crafted legends.''
</P>
<P>
   Legends? That's a stretch. But Dueling Dragons certainly may
have one of the more satisfying queues in any theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Guests must wend their way through an enchanted forest, then
snake through Merlinwood Castle before boarding the roller
coasters. Along the way, would-be riders learn the tale of the Fire
Dragon and the Ice Dragon, two evil serpents each bent on the
other's destruction. The eerily lighted castle is filled with
ghoulish decor, including the sculls and wrecked bodies of fallen
knights.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is as satisfying as the wait. The coasters both begin
with a 125-foot drop and then separate into a tangle of tracks that
features five inversions and several near-collisions. Reaching
speeds of up to 60 mph, Fire Dragon dangles riders' legs a mere 12
inches from riders on the Ice Dragon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lost Continent also is home to arguably the most amazing
special-effects show produced by a theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Poseidon's Fury: Escape From the Lost City begins rather
innocuously. The Keeper, portrayed by an actor, tells guests the
story of evil water god Poseidon and his enemy, Zeus. Later the
audience is ``captured'' by Poseidon and, here's the awesome part,
forced to walk through a 42-foot water vortex. This glasses-fogging
effect is created with more than 17,000 gallons of water. The show
climaxes with a battle that features 25-foot fireballs and
drenching explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Drenching also is popular on Toon Lagoon, a colorful tribute to
the funny papers. This ``island'' is home to Dudley Do-Right's
Ripsaw Falls, a wild flume ride, and Popeye &AMP; Bluto's Bilge-Rat
Barges, a white-water raft ride.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of Toon Lagoon, however, isn't the rides. That
distinction belongs to the smile-inducing cartoon characters.
Nearly 80 characters from five decades of Sunday funnies are
depicted life-size here. A deli is dedicated to Dagwood; an
ice-cream parlor pays tribute to weight-conscious Cathy; and a
hamburger cafe is named for Popeye pal Wimpy.
</P>
<P>
   (Warning: We tried the line ``I will gladly pay you on Tuesday
for a hamburger today.'' It doesn't work.)
</P>
<P>
   Among other characters that pop up along Comic Strip Lane are
Beetle Bailey, Pogo, the kids from Family Circus and Hagar the
Horrible. Don't miss WossaMotta U., a shop with everything
Bullwinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Where Toon Lagoon is a garish splash of primary colors, Seuss
Landing is an inviting oasis of pastels.
</P>
<P>
   The characters and attractions here are taken from Geisel's
popular children's books. The elaborate Caro-Seuss-el features
seven whimsical characters including elephant-birds from ``Horton
Hatches an Egg'' and ``AquaMop Tops'' from ``One Fish Two Fish Red
Fish Blue Fish.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter book also is the inspiration for a ride of the same
name. Guests ride in red and blue fish that go around and up and
down. The trick is to listen closely to the ride's musical rhyme,
which tells riders when to fly high and when to go low. Riders that
don't listen to the lyrics get drenched by squirting fish.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat in the Hat ride is based on Geisel's most famous book.
Participants ride on couches for this fun attraction that retells
the visitors-run-amok story with more than 130 special effects and
animatronic characters.
</P>
<P>
   While Seuss Landing is all sweetness, Marvel Super Hero Island
has an edge. It is a macho attraction with three thrilling rides
and a teen-magnet arcade.
</P>
<P>
   While Doctor Doom's Fearfall, with its twin 200-foot towers,
will be familiar to theme park fans, even roller-coaster
aficionados are in for a surprise on the Incredible Hulk Coaster.
</P>
<P>
   The train ascends, as most coasters do, with a slow
clackity-clack up a steep track, but midway up, the train
accelerates as if it had been blasted from a cannon. There's no
slow anticipation of the first drop; riders go from zero to 40 mph
in two seconds. With seven rollovers, two underground dips and many
moments of weightlessness, the Hulk experience seems much longer
than its two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We've saved the best for last.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man is a ride for the next
millennium. It combines a motion-simulator car that moves along a
track with special effects and the latest 3-D film technology.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are along for the ride as Spider-Man battles bad guys
determined to steal the Statue of Liberty. Marvelous-looking scenes
unfold with the story, and encounters with villains usually include
a sensory effect such as heat or water. The ride climaxes in a
400-foot ``drop'' into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Spider-Man is no Mickey Mouse attraction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
