<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAURA-BUSH-COX     06-22 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURA-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education bill's passage is Laura Bush's first big move
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On a humid day in April, the spotlight, as
usual, was on Gov. George W. Bush. Bush was playing host to the
mayor of New York, the latest in a procession of Republicans who
had come to the Governor's Mansion to express support for a Bush
presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the throng of reporters, Texas first lady Laura Bush
was quietly savoring a political victory of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's education adviser had just informed her that key
lawmakers were lined up in support of her bill to create reading
readiness programs for preschoolers and to enhance the federal Head
Start education programs. Best of all, the legislators were ready
to ante up $17 million for the programs, $15 million more than she
had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Initiating her own legislation was a bold step that put
substance to her style in pushing reading.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of Senate Bill 955 _ signed into law last week by
the governor _ marks the first time Laura Bush pursued her own
legislative agenda. That she endorsed her husband's legislative
initiatives in 1995 and 1997 but claimed none as her own until now,
signals Laura Bush's movement onto the national political stage and
the agenda she intends to tackle if she becomes first lady in a
Bush White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the making of a political spouse who wishes to
use that position to make a contribution,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a
University of Texas government professor. ``We are seeing her move
in staking out an area of independent activity.'' Laura Bush, 52,
said that if her husband is elected president, she will use her
position to advance other early-childhood education initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George is elected _ this is what I've always been
interested in, really,'' she said in an interview with the Austin
American-Statesman. ``That was my career as a teacher and
librarian.''
</P>
<P>
   The niche she is carving out focuses on equipping preschoolers
with the skills they need to prepare for reading, writing and other
areas of learning by the time they enter kindergarten. It
complements her husband's focus on reading in elementary grades and
is a safe bet politically, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is an ambitious step as those of Texas first ladies go.
Bush, like other first ladies before her, has promoted her cause of
choice _ reading. The former school librarian has raised about
$600,000 for Texas public libraries and is a sponsor of the Texas
Book Festival. But in venturing into the legislative process, she
has gone where no Texas governors' wives have gone.
</P>
<P>
   Former first lady Rita Clements restored the Governor's Mansion
and Main Streets across rural Texas. She promoted volunteerism,
education, historic preservation and tourism. She hit the campaign
trail with husband Bill Clements and was an active member of the
Republican Party before she married him. But as first lady, she
avoided direct involvement in the legislative process _ viewed
largely as men's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not lobby on my own or sponsor any legislation,'' said
Rita Clements, who had two stints in the Governor's Mansion, the
last ending in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Nell Connally, wife of former Gov. John Connally, who served
from 1963 to 1969, said she ``tended to the things that were my
duty,'' such as homemaking and gardening. Connally used her
interest in gardening to refurbish the mansion grounds. In her day,
she said, a governor's wife would be seen as ``getting in where she
shouldn't get in'' if she directly engaged in getting bills passed
.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to Read Under Senate Bill 955, the education commissioner
will award $2 million in grants, starting this fall, for the Ready
to Read Initiative. Public and private early-education programs
would be eligible for the grants, which could be used for a variety
of purposes, such as training or hiring reading instructors or
buying books.
</P>
<P>
   The reading readiness program is modeled on the Dallas-based
Margaret Cone Head Start Center, a collaboration of the Texas
Instruments Foundation and Head Start of Greater Dallas. Bush said
her intense interest in working with children from impoverished or
low-income families stems from her earlier years as a teacher in
predominantly minority Kennedy Elementary School in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Cone center children were scoring in the 75th to
80th percentile on national achievement exams by the time they
graduated from the two-year program. Those same children had scored
in the bottom 1 percent when they entered.
</P>
<P>
   On their visit to the Cone center in February, Laura Bush and
Rep. Sherri Greenberg, D-Austin, who carried Bush's bill, liked
what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very language-rich curriculum,'' Bush said. ``I said
my name was Laura, and one little boy said 'Oh, I have your same
letter _ L.' His name was Larry and he could immediately see he had
the same letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the bill aims to strengthen the educational
component of federally financed Head Start program, which targets
poor children. Head Start has largely focused on children's
nutritional needs and social development. The new money would go to
preparing preschoolers for the academic learning rigors of
elementary school and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation gives Texas children the best possible start
for a lifetime of learning,'' Laura Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   She also worked to revamp a parenting magazine published by the
state Department of Health, a proposal that was included in the
agency's budget.
</P>
<P>
   A low profile
</P>
<P>
   Bush kept a low profile during the session. She never testified
on the bill. Instead, she won support of key lawmakers, including
influential Democrat Paul Sadler, chairman of the House Public
Education Committee, with a pre-legislative conference on
early-childhood development.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference last December, Bush brought together some of
the nation's top experts on early-childhood development,
highlighting research that showed the importance of providing
language and reading skills to children before they start school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were experts who confirmed the importance of early
education in brain development of very young children,'' said
Greenberg, who attended the conference. ``From there, myself, Mrs.
Bush and the governor's office continued to work together on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance with House Democrats proved key to passage of
Bush's legislation. It was Sadler who championed the Head Start
program, and his own pre-kindergarten programs, when Republican
senators moved to eliminate their funding to expand tax cuts that
were a key part of Gov. Bush's legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's brinkmanship yielded $15 million for Head Start _and
about $200 million for pre-kindergarten and kindergarten programs _
included in a bill he co-authored.
</P>
<P>
   Now, early education programs are finding their way into the
presidential campaign. Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
front-runner, announced early-childhood initiatives last week. And
Gov. Bush _ who skirted the issue during the legislative session
that ended May 31 _ is now talking in campaign speeches about
revamping Head Start to include phonics.
</P>
<P>
   If Gov. Bush wins the presidency, will Laura Bush promote
early-childhood education the way her famous mother-in-law, former
first lady Barbara Bush, promoted literacy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think definitely that I would, and George also is very
interested in paying attention to Head Start,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Would she take a more political role, such as trying to persuade
Congress to pass such education? ``We'll see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
