<HEADER>
A5828 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     06-22 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK IS ALLAN'S TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden, always crawling with big names, rolled
out a celebrity lineup that could skunk the Betty Ford Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   It was Monday night, the gritty Knicks were in a Love-2 ditch,
and chatter about Must-Sweep TV was gaining momentum. The lingering
forecast was a shower of respectful applause and street clothes for
Patrick Ewing, who when he's healthy seems old enough to start
walking sideways any day now. Latrell Sprewell had returned from
Texas with an exhausted right elbow and a bill from the Alamodome
for a fortune in orange paint.
</P>
<P>
   Bar-stool strategists were even irritated with tragically heroic
Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who on a good day looks like actor Bronson
Pinchot after two years in an Istanbul slammer. Willis Reed was
still retired. Chris Dudley still wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Van Gundy couldn't be any more undermanned than the review
list for Oprah's Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   So how did he and New York reach San Antonio and get back in
this NBA Finals series?
</P>
<P>
   They went through Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Of course we're referring to Knicks shooting guard Allan
Houston, whose 34-point performance in Game 3 cut the Spurs' lead
in half, inspired a group exhale at NBC and bridged a potential
soccer-as-a-second-sport gap between the Finals and next
Wednesday's NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been paying attention, you already may be aware that
Houston is the Knick who doesn't quite fit the profile. He's the
Saint Knick. The Knick whose mug shot has not been shot in profile.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the nasty Knicks are entertaining in the same way it used
to be entertaining to loiter on a train trestle. Bad actors? Think
of the original casting call for ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston is an exception.
</P>
<P>
   Houston hasn't leaned on obscenity while sassing the sporting
press, as has Larry Johnson, the ex-UNLV sluggo whose nickname can
be upgraded to ``MGM Grandmama.'' He didn't pocket money from
agents to rewrite his school's record book, as Marcus Camby was
accused of doing while performing for UMass. He wasn't the subject
of a voodoo curse, as was ex-Spur David Wingate after an allegation
of rape.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be slightly more under control than teammate Kurt
Thomas, whose tango with Dennis Rodman at the Forum earned The Worm
a media endorsement for a merit badge.
</P>
<P>
   And, as much as he might want to, he'd never wrap his hands
around P.J. Carlesimo's neck.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while flirting with Lone Star blasphemy, it should be
noted that Houston seems to belong in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs may have more ``good guys'' than they can use. It
took the acquisition of tough guy Mario Elie, a native New Yorker,
to convince them to make beard stubble part of their uniform.
Thanks to Mario, they now realize ``swagger'' is not the name of a
discredited evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   Their ranking go-to good guy is David Robinson, who slam-dunked
the SAT on his way to Annapolis. Teammate Tim Duncan, the people's
choice for MVP, deserved big-brain props after writing a lively
column for USA Today following the 1997 NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Even their low-post caddy, Will Perdue, attended Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Knicks aren't exactly knuckleheads. Dudley, for example,
attended Yale. And Camby, of course, is the pride of UMass, which,
um, can be found in the same state as Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the series, let's hope Houston finds his way
back to the state of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   As a reluctant star in New York, his only crime has been failing
to realize how good he can be.
</P>
<P>
   Is he Hall of Fame timbre, as NBA history requires in its
championship heroes? Nah. But we're not talking about the Knicks
actually winning this series. This is America; it simply wants to
be entertained.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the Knicks to keep it interesting, even push the
series back to Texas, Houston must continue punishing Elie. Yeah,
Elie's a willing defender, but he's not enough of an offensive
threat to make Houston work on defense. And Spurs coach Gregg
Popovich could continue promoting any theatrical value the series
may possess by allowing Steve Kerr to match up with Houston in a
reprisal of doomed strategy from Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich helped save NBA fans the indignity of following the
lockout with a Finals sweep. Of course, most of us knew New York
couldn't be swept.
</P>
<P>
   It's much too sticky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
