<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-FLORIDA-DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE GROWTH KEEPS DISNEY IN COMPETITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Never let them see you sweat.
</P>
<P>
   That's hard to do on a summer day in central Florida, but give
the folks at Walt Disney World Resort credit for effort.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what effect the opening of Universal's highly awaited
Islands of Adventure might have on the Magic Kingdom, Disney
officials are nonplussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a new park around here?'' responds Judson Green,
chairman of Walt Disney Attractions, with tongue in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Green says Universal is merely following the leader, but he adds
that any new attraction ``just makes central Florida a stronger
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Universal may be building new parks, Green says 1999
is the biggest year of growth in the Disney resort's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something new in every corner of the World,'' Green
gushes, declaring this the Disney Decade. ``We are always looking
at changes and adjustments, things we can do to increase customer
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney World Resort encompasses four theme parks: the Magic
Kingdom, Disney's Animal Kingdom, Epcot and MGM-Disney Studios;
three water parks; the Disney Institute; Downtown Disney, a retail
and entertainment district; 17 hotels, five golf courses, a racquet
club; and two mini-golf complexes.
</P>
<P>
   So what's new for 1999?
</P>
<P>
   _ Well, Test Track _ Disney's fastest ride _ finally is on track
after two years of stops and starts. Created in partnership with
General Motors, the $60 million Test Track takes riders over hills
and bumpy roads, through hairpin turns, arctic cold and desert heat
and finally into an exciting 65-mph blast down a 50-degree banked
curb.
</P>
<P>
   Now if they can only overcome the attraction's frequent
breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disney's Animal Kingdom grew by an entire continent this
spring. Guests cross a bridge to enter Asia, where they will find
several new attractions. Kali River Rapids is the ubiquitous raft
ride and Flights of Wonder is an aviary show starring macaws,
ibises and pelicans.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the new lures is the Maharajah Jungle Trek, a
splendid self-guided tour through a rain forest with crumbling
temples and palaces and fantastic species such as the tiger, tapir
and Komodo dragon. Don't miss the giant fruit bats, a marvel to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Along the lushly landscaped trek, guests meet Disney cast
members who hail from Nepal, India, Thailand and Indonesia. These
enthusiastic young people are eager to share information about the
exhibits and their homelands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opening mid-July at MGM-Disney Studios will be the Rock 'n'
Roller Coaster, which will further enhance the movie-themed park's
teen appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The roller coaster will feature three inversions, speeds up to
60 mph and a rocking soundtrack created especially for Disney by
those metalmen Aerosmith. The coaster's 24-passenger trains will be
outfitted with 120 speakers for a pulsing rock beat.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to MGM-Disney Studios also should give the Twilight
Zone Tower of Terror another try. After a couple of years of
tweaking, Disney imagineers have gotten it right. Enhanced visuals
and multiple drops will have you screaming for more. Or screaming
to get off.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Magic Kingdom embraces the chubby little cubby with a new
ride. Geared for tots, the Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh takes
guests on a storybook journey through the Hundred Acre Woods.
Another new kiddie ride is Buzz Lightyear's Space Ranger Spin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evening entertainment around the World gets a boost, too. Most
exciting is a new show created by Cirque du Soleil and presented in
a special permanent theater at Downtown Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Nouba'' is a high-energy show that blends circus,
theatrical arts and zany street entertainment with a high-tech
stage, dazzling lighting and an urban musical score. Like most
Cirque productions, ``La Nouba'' is presented by an international
cast of 60. While the aerial ballet and high-wire acts are
stunning, it is the young performers with their ``diabolos,'' or
Chinese yo-yos, that bring the crowds to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the World, the Magic Kingdom is paid a visit by
Disneyland's original Main Street Electrical Parade and Scorcerer
Mickey battles laser enemies in ``Fantasmic,'' a production at
Disney-MGM Studios that features animated fountains, balls of fire
and a timeless musical score.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
