<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT &LR;      06-22 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIXED DAY FOR COKE IN EUROPE'S ILLNESS SCARE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The European crisis for Coca-Cola began to ease in
France Tuesday, but the 15-nation European Union announced plans to
carry out health inspections of its own in plants in Belgium and
France that had produced soft drinks blamed for outbreaks of
illness early this month.
</P>
<P>
   While the French ban on Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light, Fanta and
Sprite canned by a Coca-Cola factory in Dunkirk, France, could be
lifted as early as Wednesday, Pietro Petrucci, a European Union
spokesman, said European inspectors would visit that plant and one
in Antwerp, Belgium, and might not finish their report until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, where the government was brought down June 13 in a
scandal over contamination of animal-feed grains by cancer-causing
dioxin, authorities maintained a nine-day-old ban on Coca-Cola,
Fanta and Sprite. The ban continued even after the company's
chairman, M. Douglas Ivester, met with the caretaker health
minister Monday night and apologized to Belgian consumers in
newspaper advertisements Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began in Belgium after 30 schoolchildren apparently
became sick after drinking Coke from cans on June 7, and fears
quickly spread to France, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Italy and
Spain. Today the anxiety spread to Portugal, where several thousand
cans of Coca-Cola were recalled after consumers there complained of
finding a black residue that the company later said was harmless
carbon particles.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 200 cases of stomach pains, nausea and
hyperventilation have been reported. France and the Netherlands
have loosened an earlier ban, limiting it to sales of cans of
Coca-Cola, Fanta and Sprite shipped through Belgium, but Luxembourg
is barring all Coca-Cola products.
</P>
<P>
   French tests of the beverages canned in Dunkirk produced no
evidence of contamination, the French government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kouchner, the health minister of France, said that
examiners had looked into 10 causes of people who became sick after
drinking Coca-Cola, but concluded that there were no links between
the illnesses and the beverage. Kouchner suggested that
psychosomatic causes were a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that health inspectors had found ``no relation in
particular'' between the death of a seven-month-old baby in the
mother's womb and any Coca-Cola that she might have drunk. But, he
said, a few empty cans in her possession had been put under seal as
part of the usual judicial inquiry into the death.
</P>
<P>
   Marylise Lebranchu, the consumer minister of France, said that
the government food safety agency could give the all-clear to
Coca-Cola in France on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola officials in Brussels with Ivester and Henry
Schimberg, chairman of Coca-Cola Enterprises, the bottling
subsidiary, did not return telephone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister of Belgium, Jean-Luc Dehaene, resigned a week
ago after his coalition government lost the national elections,
acknowledging that he had not handled the crisis over contaminated
animal feed properly. European Union authorities have accused the
Belgians of delaying action for weeks before withdrawing chicken,
eggs and later meat from the market until they could certify which
producers had not used the tainted feed.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian authorities arrested the head of an animal fat
processing company in southern Belgium Monday night, and Nicole de
Rouck, a spokeswoman for the public prosecutor's office in Ghent,
said Tuesday that it was possible that the company had mixed motor
oil with frying fat that had been used to enrich animal feed
grains. The company, Fogra, is the second to be investigated in the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has blamed a bad batch of carbon dioxide, used to
carbonate its soft drinks, for the problems in Antwerp. Aga Gas,
the Swedish company that said it had supplied the gas, has denied
that there was anything wrong with the gas.
</P>
<P>
   Cans from Dunkirk that were shipped to Belgium and Luxembourg
may have picked up phenol and other chemicals used to protect
shipping pallets, Coca-Cola said, but French authorities who tested
both cans and pallets from Dunkirk said they had found no trace of
such impurities.
</P>
<P>
   What effect the scare and the full-page advertisements Coca-Cola
has taken out in European newspapers this week to try to counter it
have had on the company's sales in Europe or elsewhere were among
the many questions that the company's officials could not answer
Tuesday. Analysts in New York said it was difficult to estimate how
much money Coca-Cola was losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $64 million question is, how effective their effort to
restore confidence in their brand is,'' said Marc Cohen, an analyst
for Goldman Sachs. An analyst for CS First Boston has said the ban
is costing Coca-Cola Enterprises some $3.4 million in revenues per
day.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian authorities lifted a ban on Nestea, Aquarius, Bon Aqua,
Lift and Minute-Maid drinks last week.
</P>
<P>
   And all Coca-Cola products, except those made in Dunkirk, are
back on the shelves and in vending machines in France.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Coca-Cola controls only 7 percent to 8 percent of
the French soft drink market, the government earlier this year
barred Coca-Cola from buying Orangina, a carbonated orange drink
owned by Pernod Ricard SA, because it feared a more intrusive
American presence in the nonalcoholic beverage business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
