<SLUG> BC-FBC-PLAYOFF-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE BOWL OPPOSES PLAYOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- A Swiss corporation's multi-billion dollar proposal
for a 16-team, NCAA Division I-A college football playoff is either
a threat to the integrity of college sports or a potential boon for
universities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   One thing appears certain. The Rose Bowl's future as the premier
venue for college football would be in peril if a playoff is
instituted -- the main reason Rose Bowl officials are speaking out
against the latest playoff proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go to a playoff, what this city has learned to love will
be gone,'' Harriman Cronk, head of the football committee for the
Tournament of Roses, said Tuesday. ``We could wind up as just a
quarterfinal game.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of recent developments, college football playoffs are a
real possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, International Sports and Leisure -- a
Swiss-based marketing and licensing firm -- has been approaching
athletic directors and university presidents around the country
with an eight-year, $3.06 billion plan for a 16-team playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for a playoff system beginning in 2003, said
Jim Wheeler, ISL's vice president for college athletics. Under the
plan, the Rose Bowl could host the finals every fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   The championship would rotate among the bowls in the Bowl
Championship Series: Rose, Sugar, Fiesta and Orange. The final game
would take place the weekend before the NFL's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a passionate subject, and you try to get people to
look at the facts,'' Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   ISL is already financially involved with the World Cup, the
Association of Tennis Professionals, the Olympics, the
international basketball championship, CART auto racing and the Big
Ten Conference, Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We handle all the marketing rights, licensing and media for
those events,'' Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sold on Wheeler's plan, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conference is very supportive of the bowl system. It's
been good to us and to college football,'' said Jim Muldoon, an
assistant commissioner with the Pac-10. ``It would take a lot to
change our minds. I haven't seen any groundswell among our
(university) presidents ... there's no support at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their ongoing relationship with ISL, the Big Ten isn't
going for the proposal, either, right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the same page with most of the major conferences,''
said Sue Ryan, a Big Ten assistant commissioner. ``The ISL group
has pitched their proposal, but we believe in the tradition and
history of the bowl system. We are committed to the BCS and our
involvement with it. A playoff system -- now or in the near future
-- is something we are not interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the NCAA, ``The Division I board has indicated there's
not an interest in a playoff at this time,'' said Dennis Poppe, the
NCAA's director of championships. ``But there's still an open
door.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the closest college football fans get to an actual
championship is through the BCS. The series promises that the top
two teams in the country will play for the national championship
during New Year's week.
</P>
<P>
   BCS standings, an inexact science at best, are determined by a
combination of national polls, win-loss records, strength of
competition and computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a playoff in place by 2003 could be tough. The BCS runs
three more years, but the Big Ten and Pac-10 conferences have a
contract with the Rose Bowl for three years after that.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler isn't fazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the presidents of the Pac-10 and Big Ten decide they want a
playoff, that can be worked out,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
