<SLUG> BC-PC-EXPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computers can follow path of TV sets, Andreessen says
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Powered by the lure of the Internet, personal
computers have the potential to become as ubiquitous as television
sets in time, but first the industry must make them vastly more
user-friendly, Marc Andreessen said Tuesday at the PC Expo trade
show.
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen, a co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp. who is
now chief technology officer at America Online Inc., said it took
only five years for the Internet to reach 5 million users, which
was eight years faster than television achieved that level of
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But convenience is critical to its continued growth. Just as
consumers don't care what microchip controls their microwave,
they're indifferent to the chip that runs their computers,
Andreessen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers don't care about the technology,'' he said. ``It all
has to be just completely push-button. It all has to be
point-and-click.''
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote address at the annual PC trade show, Andreessen
described e-mail as a ``tornado application.'' That is an
industry-changing software program whose value increases as more
people use it.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail and the World Wide Web are classic examples, he said.
They started slowly, but their attraction and potential grew as
more PC owners began using them.
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen criticized the PC industry's focus on hardware and
technology instead of the end user. That has created such
non-user-friendly requirements as holding down two or more keys on
a keyboard to perform certain functions.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the television as a model of convenience and ease of
use that the PC industry might follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to overestimate how important this is,'' Andreessen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-22-99 2214E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
