<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX DEBATE, THIS TIME ON ONLINE COMMERCE, IS REBORN IN
WILLIAMSBURG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG, Va. _ As Colonial Williamsburg, the reconstructed
capital of colonial Virginia, tries to broaden its appeal, its
3,500 employees operate by a new credo: enter the 21st century
without leaving the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   It means actors who portray colonial residents of the village
now tackle contemporary topics, like church-state relations. It
means the organization's lucrative catalog business is moving
beyond its collection of historical replicas to offer a new line of
casual, family-oriented home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly it means turning to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A federal commission on electronic commerce met here Monday and
Tuesday to debate whether to permit taxation of Internet shopping.
The dilemma is of great importance to Washington state, home to an
unusual concentration of electronic commerce businesses, but also
highly dependent on sales tax revenues to finance services such as
schools and police.
</P>
<P>
   The new commission, established and appointed by Congress, has
10 months to come up with a recommendation to Congress on whether,
and how, to tax sales made over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how widespread electronic commerce has become,
look at the role the Internet plays in promoting and funding this
tourist attraction, where 800 actors spend their days re-enacting a
time before electricity. The recording a caller to Colonial
Williamsburg hears when put on hold says it all: ``Need to send a
message to Colonial Williamsburg? Don't worry, the Internet has now
transcended time, reaching back into Colonial Williamsburg.''
</P>
<P>
   Log on to www.history.org, and you can buy a variety of
colonial-era collectibles: for $19.95, a hand-thrown bird bottle,
for $32 a salt-cured, hickory-smoked Virginia ham, for $3,675 an
oversized carpet like the ones Persian shahs sent to impress
European royalty. You have to dial a phone number to provide your
credit card number, but soon Williamsburg expects to move fully
online.
</P>
<P>
   Buy an item at one of the many gift shops here, and you must pay
Virginia's 4.5 percent sales tax. Buy the item via the Internet and
the tax isn't imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Tax policy always has been a hot debate in Williamsburg _ the
American Revolution arguably was triggered by colonial hostility to
British tax policy _ and the debate was reborn this week at the
307-year-old campus of the College of William and Mary, just down
the road from the colonial capitol where early Virginians debated
the controversial stamp tax.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions facing the new commission: Should electronic
commerce sales be taxed? What about sales of digital goods, rather
than physical goods? How to simplify the taxation system?
</P>
<P>
   At this first meeting, Washington Gov. Gary Locke and Dallas
Mayor Ron Kirk led the charge against granting the electronic
commerce industry a blanket exemption from the sales tax on which
so many state and local governments depend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that we're protecting and promoting the
growth of electronic commerce, but at the same time be cognizant of
the fact that so many local, county and state governments depend on
sales tax collections to pay for police, fire and schools,'' Locke
said.
</P>
<P>
   Locke warned that allowing a broad exemption from taxes for
Internet companies would not only disadvantage traditional
retailers, but also undermine government's ability to fund schools
as the percentage of commerce conducted over the Internet rises.
The Internet generated about $300 billion in revenue last year,
according to the University of Texas. Electronic commerce now
accounts for less than 1 percent of the nation's retail economy,
but is expected to grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is a world leader in technology ... because of the
education of the visionaries,'' Locke said. ``It would be ironic if
the growth of electronic commerce erodes our ability to educate the
innovators and leaders of tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk warned that if sales tax revenues to state and local
governments fall, there will inevitably be a push to increase other
taxes, such as property and income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Several commissioners expressed skepticism about allowing any
taxation of Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here as tax collectors for the current tax
regimes,'' said commissioner Stanley Sokul, a consultant to the
Association for Interactive Media. ``The 13 colonies' first attempt
at government collapsed because of the states' parochial tax
motives.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a clear majority of the commission seemed ready to
support allowing the taxation of goods sold over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that physical-distribution stores should be
disadvantaged by tax advantages for e-commerce,'' said commissioner
David Pottruck, president of the Charles Schwab stock brokerage.
And John Sidgmore, vice chairman of MCI Worldcom, said the Internet
industry doesn't need special tax breaks and that ``it is not
feasible to tax Main Street differently from the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington state's e-commerce companies, which are not directly
represented on the coalition, although one member has worked as a
registered lobbyist for Microsoft, are divided over whether they
should be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which sells software and services over the Internet,
has joined an industry group called the Internet Tax Fairness
Coalition in expressing a willingness to pay sales taxes if they
are not higher than those imposed on traditional retailers and if
the nation's patchwork of sales tax systems is simplified, which is
likely to be a major focus of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry view is that we support a fair tax policy, an
administrable tax system, with certainty as a result,'' said Bruce
Reid, director of state and local tax policy for Microsoft, who
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Amazon.com, the giant Seattle-based online retailer, is more
reluctant to participate in sales taxes. The company collects sales
taxes from customers in Washington state, as required by law, but
not elsewhere in the country. Amazon is one of the largest
e-commerce companies in the world, with 10 million customers and
$610 million in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not want to see anything happen that makes it more
expensive for people to access the Internet or participate in
e-commerce,'' Bill Currie, an Amazon spokesman, said in a phone
interview. ``The benefits of online shopping are convenience, a
selection far greater than anything in the physical world, and
lower prices, and it would be a shame to see taxes on Internet
access or any other kind of Internet tax deprive people of
e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, one of just a handful of states without an income
tax, derives 48 percent of its revenues from sales taxes. The
state's revenue director, Fred Kiga, said the state estimates it is
losing $150 million a year in tax revenue, of which as much as $25
million is uncollected taxes on Internet sales. The rest is is
uncollected taxes on catalog sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
