<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT WORKS HARD TO SHED A `SOFT' LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are detailed manuscripts devoted to players'
abilities _ and liabilities _ in this league. You can't find them
at Walden's or Barnes &AMP; Noble, and few assistant coaches would risk
their jobs by handing over a copy. But like labels and perceptions,
they're out there, imperfect career blueprints. The pages contain
more information about a player's tendencies and weaknesses than
any cable breakdown segment can show.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott knows. No matter how much he would like to rewrite
it, the book on him has been in its third printing. Quick first
step. Good finisher. Injury prone. And, yes, susceptible to
disappearing the more rugged his opponent plays defense against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said when asked if players had tried to
capitalize on the label. ``I had plenty of guys that tried to get
into me physically and lost that battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you still fighting the battle?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs forward was sitting up straight on a chair along the
Eighth Avenue baseline of Madison Square Garden Tuesday after San
Antonio finished practice. Wednesday night, Elliott, the team's
third-leading scorer, Tim Duncan and David Robinson will match
their skills and heart against that of Allan Houston, Latrell
Sprewell and Larry Johnson in Game 4 of the National Basketball
Association finals at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott does not consider himself a full-fledged member of San
Antonio's Big 3 for a variety of reasons; the most obvious is
Duncan and Robinson are 7-foot superstars. And on any given night,
Mario Elie or Jaren Jackson can become that third option that
catapults the Spurs to victory.
</P>
<P>
   While he may not admit it, playing well in the crucible of the
finals _ in the middle of a Garden madhouse _ would finally give
Elliott credence for changing an outdated perception about him.
</P>
<P>
   He went a long way in the Western Conference finals, burying
that outrageous 3-pointer in the final seconds of Game 2 against
Portland, a shot that demoralized the Trail Blazers. And hardly
anyone knows how hard he has worked to rehabilitate his body from
injury after injury the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But labels are labels. And when you go 3 for 9 in Game 3 at the
Garden, and wonder the next day why you didn't get more favorable
calls from the officials, the people not enamored with your game
come out in droves again.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Elliott is like Houston _ a carefree, easygoing soul
forever called soft. Houston has overcome the perception by putting
the ball on the floor and parlaying one clutch playoff shot into a
bevy of 30-point nights. They were teammates in Detroit during
Houston's rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the same personality types,'' Elliott said when asked if
there were any similarities. ``I think with Allan in Detroit, he
would hardly say anything and I would hardly say anything. In that
sense, we're probably pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   He added of Houston, ``I think his personality is quiet. He's
not a Generation X type player. If you're not a Generation Xer,
then you're considered soft, low key and mellow. I think he plays
hard. Soft guys don't go out and score 30 points in the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott ended up in Detroit at a time when the Bad Boys had lost
their swagger and were turning into a nasty bunch of curmudgeons.
If had to battle a bad back and aching knees, he also had to battle
a culture of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not fit in,'' said Don Chaney, the Knicks assistant and
former Piston coach. ``He and Isiah really didn't blend in as
teammates. Detroit was known at the time for banging and knocking
people around. And Sean came in basically as a West Coast player, a
finesse type guy. So a lot of the players wanted him to become that
guy. And that's not who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a knock on him, but it wasn't a great mesh there in
Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Elliott, ``I was maybe a different type of player, but I
fit in well there early on. It was just after that, it wasn't very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   He went back to San Antonio, persevered through injuries and
eventually became one of the key reasons why this team is playing
for its first NBA title. San Antonio just lost its first game in
more than a month, and nearly 20,000 people will pack the Garden
tomorrow to see if they can shake, rattle and tweak the Spurs once
more.
</P>
<P>
   If Elliott cracks, the criticism begins anew, the book on him
due for another printing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, you look at what a player is good at and then you
always look at what he's not good at,'' Elliott said. ``You always
see a breakdown of a player. You always see pros and cons. When I
was coming up, you never saw that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always talked about how good a guy was.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
