<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKIDE IS NIGERIA'S CELEBRITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DON'T mistake honesty for arrogance. If you do, you'll have a
hard time understanding ``Marvelous'' Mercy Akide of Nigeria's
women's national soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   She says things like, ``They're the whites and we have the
blacks, so we're not afraid,'' in reference to the U.S. team,
Nigeria's opponent in its World Cup game Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Akide is outspoken, nor is there any doubt
she's a celebrity in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm of the U.S. team films TV commercials with Michael
Jordan, but Akide is perhaps treated more like Jordan in her
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being a celebrity,'' says Akide proudly. ``They call me
Miss Marvelous at home and people give me gifts walking along the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see why Akide's becoming the rising personality of this
summer's Women's World Cup tournament. She has a loose tongue, an
easy-to-spot presence and has already performed her rhythmic goal
dance after a 2-1 victory over North Korea Sunday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Akide is an international personality,'' U.S. assistant coach
Lauren Gregg said. ``She's someone who can take over a game.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``by the grace of God,'' says Akide, the Super Falcons will
upset Team USA in Thursday's crucial Group A match in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Akide will stop for a manicure, then add more
hair color to the cool green-and-blonde streaks she received before
the North Korean match.
</P>
<P>
   She's not arrogant. Nor is she looking for attention. She's just
having the time of her life. She's as much a tourist as a World Cup
standout.
</P>
<P>
   When she saw herself on the cover of Sunday's World Cup program,
she tucked it away like a kid appearing in a newspaper for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her about her stay in Los Angeles and she'll tell you how
much she loved the french fries.
</P>
<P>
   We got our first look at Akide in February. She was on the FIFA
Women's World Cup all-star team that beat the U.S. in a friendly
hyping the World Cup draw in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Akide had doughnuts and coffee with a group of
reporters, asking as many questions as they asked her.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nigeria was placed in the U.S. group, the obvious
questions turned to her team's chances against the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke softly, smiling all the time, but the words coming out
of her mouth gave writer's cramps to those around her.
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``We're going to surprise the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And later, ``We have God on our side, and with Him, we can beat
anybody, including the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   She was also a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to play them so I can meet players like your No.9
(Mia Hamm) and No.13 (Kristine Lilly) and the goalkeeper (Briana
Scurry).''
</P>
<P>
   We can't wait to see Nigeria again and see what they will do
next.
</P>
<P>
   Also interesting are the Nigerian fans, who make up one of the
largest traveling contingents of the tournament. They purchase
seats, but rarely sit, preferring instead to sing and dance for 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And this game could turn out to be the most exciting of the
tournament. A score of 3-2 or 4-3 is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the all-stars can beat the U.S., Nigeria can do it, too,''
said Akide one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. They're (Nigeria) a force to be reckoned
with,'' said Gregg, who scouted the Nigerians in Los Angeles. ``I
think they're playing with confidence off their result with China
(a 4-3 friendly victory). They're clearly here to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, it should be fun to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
