<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON INSISTS KNICKS ARE NOT MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after he ignored a request by league
officials to speak at an interview session, Larry Johnson provided
a loquacious response to those who have cast the Knicks as an
unlovable band of misfits.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of railing against the image, Johnson embraced it in a
rather interesting way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of rebellious slaves on this team,'' Johnson
said Tuesday. ``We don't have a lot of mainstream; we don't go with
the mainstream. We're in a different stream on this team. We've got
a lot of rebellious slaves. We don't go along with the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was referring to himself, as well as a few teammates. On
Sunday, Johnson went on an obscene tirade after two league
officials asked him to stop shooting for a few minutes to grant an
interview during a mandatory session. The rant cost him $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Johnson doesn't care what anyone thinks of the Knicks,
outside of his own teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like you; and that's been my motto my whole life,
growing up,'' Johnson said. ``I don't like that person, and that
person don't like me. Fine. Have mutual respect and stay away from
each other. Don't come to me and smile and then stab me behind my
back.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point, Johnson referred to his days at UNLV.
That team was also criticized for its behavior and ties to
controversy. And the Runnin' Rebels were also loathed by many. But
in the end, Johnson's team wound up with a NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-GENIUS-COX     06-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GENIUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A 'genius' and his love affair
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Rose
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ David Hillis' love affair with the animal
kingdom sounds like an evolutionary tale:
</P>
<P>
   At age 6, he caught lizards and snakes in the African jungle. At
16, he published his first scientific journal article,
``Cannibalism among cornsnakes.'' At 24, he scaled a cliff in the
Andes to discover a new species of frog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just about to give up when I saw its head poke out from
a tree,'' said Hillis, now 40.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up is not his forte. This is a man who discovered a new
species of snake in Ecuador after a landslide blocked the road,
tossed rocks on his car and left him with nothing better to do.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the MacArthur Foundation announced that Hillis is
among 32 new winners of MacArthur Fellowships in recognition of his
brilliance in evolutionary biology. Hillis, a University of Texas
professor who helped to identify the Barton Springs salamander as a
species seven years ago, is the only Texan this year to win the
so-called ``genius grant.'' His prize: $295,000 over five years to
spend any way he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled,'' said Hillis, who has been at UT since 1987.
``It's not something I ever expected.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got a message last Thursday to call the foundation, a
private organization that has been making the awards since 1981,
his first thought was, ``a colleague was pulling my leg,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is extremely unassuming,'' said David Cannatella, a
friend of Hillis' for 20 years, a colleague and a curator at the
Texas Memorial Museum. ``If you just met him on the street, there's
no sense of pretense or affectation, but his mind is incredibly
clear. He just thinks about things in very different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillis is known nationally among biologists for his work in
phylogenetic analysis, the study of the genetic makeup of living
things by which a scientist is able to reconstruct the organism's
evolution. That kind of analysis not only gives insight into how
animals evolved, it can also help doctors trace the origins of
diseases and help police identify murder suspects.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Hillis assisted prosecutors in a Louisiana trial in
which a physician was accused of injecting his lover with the AIDS
virus. Hillis was able to determine that the virus came from one of
the doctor's patients. The physician was convicted of attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an exceptional man doing exceptional work,'' said Daniel
Socolow, director of the fellows program.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, given annually to scientists, artists, musicians and
others whom the program considers creative, come with no strings.
That frees people, either by easing financial worries or by
providing them the wherewithal to pursue their passions, program
spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillis, a graduate of Baylor University and the University of
Kansas, caught the attention of an undercover talent scout who
suggested him for the award. Hillis said he has no idea who
nominated him.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the program is supposed to work, said Socolow. At
any one time, 100 nominators spread around the country spend a year
secretly identifying potential winners.
</P>
<P>
   Hillis is the sixth UT faculty member to get the award, UT
spokeswoman Nancy Neff said. Ten UT students also have gone on to
win, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone in my whole knowledge of people deserves an award
like this, he does,'' said Mary Ann Rankin, dean of the College of
Natural Sciences. ``We're so lucky to keep him on the faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillis was being courted simultaneously this school year by
Harvard and the University of California at Berkeley, Rankin said.
He chose to stay at UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have such good colleagues who have helped me,'' Hillis said.
``A lot my success has been because of my colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillis also said he stays because he loves Austin and its music
scene; enjoys traveling to small Texas towns with his wife, Ann,
and two sons; and likes to garden at his 300-acre ranch in Mason
County. He also hunts deer with a bow-and-arrow.
</P>
<P>
   The son of scientists and the director of UT's new School of
Biological Sciences, he grew up abroad, living in such diverse
places as Denmark and Africa. He plans to throw a party for his lab
this summer and expects to spend much of the rest of the money on
research trips. He wants to study animals in South America,
Australia and Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillis said he that neither the award nor his new
administrative duties will take away from his other passion:
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' said Laurie Dries, one of Hillis' graduate
students and teaching assistants. ``Every little accomplishment you
make is a big deal. . .He has no ego.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillis also is fun and has no inhibitions about climbing a tree
to catch a lizard, no matter who's watching, she said. At
Christmas, he gets his students to serenade the office staff with a
favorite Robert Earl Keen song, ``Merry Christmas From the
Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great reward for him,'' Dries said. ``He's really
good at what he does and he loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Rose writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
