<HEADLINE>
COASTERS ACROSS THE COUNTRY TAKE VISITORS TO NEW HEIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ While Disney and Universal _ the big cheeses of
central Florida _ battle it out, other theme parks across the
country are luring guests with new attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaddy of themed attractions, Gatorland in Orlando,
Fla., celebrates its 50th birthday this summer. To mark this
achievement, Gatorland premieres its new Jungle Crocs of the World
Theater, where visitors will be able to observe the hunting skills
of Cuban crocodiles. Also new is a 500-square-foot hatchery, where
guests can view a mother gator and her young, and a Gator Jumparoo
show that features alligators springing from the water to snatch
raw chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Leaping lizards? Gatorland calls it ``old Florida
entertainment.'' Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Florida, Gwazi, the new double wooden roller
coaster at Busch Gardens in Tampa, pits two big cats in a battle of
coaster supremacy. The tracks for the Gwazi Lion and the Gwazi
Tiger intertwine, setting up six close encounters while riders
reach speeds of 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AROUND TEXAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ In Houston, Six Flags AstroWorld ratchets up the excitement
with its 11th roller coaster. Boasting more than 2,170 feet of
steel track, Serial Thriller reaches heights of 102 feet and
approaches speeds of 55 mph. It is the only suspended looping
coaster of its kind in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, WaterWorld is serving up some new activities,
including Hook's Lagoon, an interactive treehouse, and the Big
Kahuna, an exciting raft ride that features multiple high-banked
turns.
</P>
<P>
   _ In San Antonio, the Steel Eel is electrifying visitors to Sea
World of Texas. A 15-story dive is a highlight of this stunning
coaster that reaches speeds of nearly 65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Also new for this season is ``Fools With Tools,'' a
``home-repair nightmare'' starring the comical sea lions Clyde and
Seamore, and a Beluga Interaction Program that puts guests in the
water for encounters with the fascinating white whales.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also in San Antonio, two new coasters _ Poltergeist and
Boomerang _ are earning fans at Fiesta Texas, which debuted 15
rides and attractions this season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other new attractions is the 1 million-gallon Lone
Star Lagoon, the state's largest wave pool, and the Texas
Treehouse, a five-story playland that features more than 75
drenching gadgets as well as a 1,000-gallon cowboy hat that
periodically dumps H20 on unsuspecting guests.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Dallas, Six Flags Over Texas' newest coaster is Batman the
Ride, an inverted coaster with a 77-foot-tall vertical loop. The
new coaster and its 32-passenger trains are located within the
Wayne Foundation Industrial Park, also the site of Mr. Freeze, the
tallest, fastest roller coaster in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a need for speed, check out the park's new
live shows, which include a Batman-themed stunt show called
``Gotham City Carnival of Chaos and Illusionaria,'' featuring a
master magician and four tricky assistants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CALIFORNIA DREAMING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Take a hike, Swiss Family Robinson. The jungle now belongs to
Tarzan.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland in Anaheim has retooled the old Swiss Family Robinson
Treehouse, which debuted in the park's Adventureland in 1962. Last
week, the 70-foot-tall faux tree was rechristened Tarzan's
Treehouse. (It is probably no coincidence that Disney's new
animated film, ``Tarzan,'' also opened last week.)
</P>
<P>
   The new and improved treehouse offers visitors a
``climb-through'' experience with a creaky suspension bridge,
handmade musical instruments and wooden staircases salvaged from a
shipwreck.
</P>
<P>
   Also new for the summer season is the Mulan Parade, a tribute to
the Chinese heroine (also a Disney-animated star). The pageant
features jugglers, acrobats and a 150-foot-long people-powered
dragon.
</P>
<P>
   _ The nation's newest theme park also may be its most
delightfully low-tech. A celebration of creativity and the little
primary-colored plastic blocks of our childhood, Legoland in
Carlsbad, Calif., opened in March. While it is a hit with the
under-10 crowd, the park has taken some hits from parents irked by
slow lines and high prices.
</P>
<P>
   The 238-acre park cost $130 million and is constructed from more
than 30 million Lego blocks. Park highlights include Miniland,
which features replicas of famous structures from New York,
Washington and New Orleans; a Fun Town, constructed from the larger
Duplos building blocks; and a few kiddie rides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Universal Studios Hollywood unveils the world's largest 3-D
screen this summer as it debuts ``Terminator 2: 3D,'' a 12-minute
film created by Oscar-winning director James Cameron. The film,
enhanced with explosive live action, stars Arnold Schwarzenegger
and Edward Furlong, who reprise their roles from the ``Terminator''
film series.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six Flags Magic Mountain in Valencia, Calif., debuts its new
Bugs Bunny World, a six-acre interactive complex dedicated to tots.
Among attractions: the Looney Tunes Lodge, a colorful playground
with multiple slides; Taz's Trucking Company, where the pint-sized
pilot big rigs; and Pepe Le Pew's Tea Party with its cups of
swirling fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kids also rule at Paramount's Great America in Santa Clara,
Calif. The 100-acre park recently opened KidZville, an interactive
play area with a children's coaster, construction site and a
``Scooby-Doo'' live show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AROUND THE COUNTRY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cedar Point in Sandusky, Ohio, which boasts more roller
coasters than any other U.S. theme park, adds another to its
bone-rattling roster. Woodstock Express makes No. 13. The Peanuts
cartoon-themed coaster is designed for little thrillseekers and is
the centerpiece of a family playland called Camp Snoopy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elsewhere in Ohio, Paramount's Kings Island in Cincinnati adds
to its more than 100 thrill rides and attractions. New this summer
is Face/Off, an inverted roller coaster, and Drop Zone, the world's
tallest gyro drop that spins guests on a 30-foot ring as they
freefall 26 stories.
</P>
<P>
   _ A sister park, Paramount's Kings Dominion in Richmond, Va.,
also adds a new coaster this summer. Volcano: the Blast Coaster is
the world's fastest suspended roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Charlotte, N.C., Paramount's Carowinds offers high-flying
thrills with Top Gun: the Jet Coaster, an inverted roller coaster
that includes six inversions and two underground tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   _ The speed craze continues in Virginia, where Busch Gardens
Williamsburg introduces Apollo's Chariot. The new attraction claims
to be the world's largest hypercoaster with nine vertical drops.
The coaster's passenger seats are elevated above the car to create
a ``free-flight'' sensation.
</P>
<P>
   _ While Silver Dollar City in Branson, Mo., has long been known
for its live music and dance shows, the pioneer-themed park quickly
is earning a reputation for its thrill rides. New for 1999 is the
country's first liquid coaster. BuzzSaw Falls is a water rapids
ride that promises the speed of a conventional dry coaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Exterminator provides the newest chills at Kennywood in
West Mifflin, Pa. There is no peeking on this subterranean roller
coaster that delivers riders into a tunnel of terror with giant
rats. (Actually it's underground with the park's water and sewer
lines; now that's scary.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Six Flags Great Adventure in Jackson, N.J., spent more than
$40 million on expansions and improvements this season, including
25 new rides and attractions. Most awaited among these is the
Medusa, a floorless roller coaster. With their toes dangling just
inches from the track, riders are flipped upside down seven times
while traveling at speeds of more than 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   For the less adventurous, the park offers its new Looney Tunes
Seaport, a children's section with 10 rides, water play areas and
attractions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
