<HEADLINE>
32 RECEIVE GRANTS FROM MACARTHUR FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The annual grants popularly known as the genius awards announced
Tuesday by The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation were
heavily weighted toward the New York area, home to about a third of
the 32 recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a clump there this year because we just couldn't pass
them up,'' said Daniel J. Socolow, director of the MacArthur
Fellows program.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City area recipients included a community
organizer, a couple who are both architects, a reporter, a history
professor, a computer scientist and several artists.
</P>
<P>
   The grants, awarded this year to 17 men and 15 women, ranged
from $235,000 to $375,000, depending on the age of the recipient.
The youngest recipient was 28 and the oldest was 66. Since 1981,
when the program started, 563 Fellows have been named.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than genius awards, the foundation prefers to think of
them as grants to experts who are particularly gifted in their
fields. The recipients are selected anonymously _ there is no
application _ and given the money over five years to pursue
whatever interests they desire. Recipients do not have to produce
anything for the foundation, and they get free health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The winners were these: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jillian F. Banfield, 39, Madison, Wis., an associate professor
of Geology and Geophysics at the University of Wisconsin, has
contributed fundamental insights into the physical and chemical
forces that shape the earth's surface, $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn R. Bertozzi, 32, Albany, Calif., an assistant professor
of chemistry at the University of California at Berkeley, has made
important contributions to understanding how cells interact,
$255,000
</P>
<P>
   Bruce G. Blair, 51, Washington, a foreign policy analyst at the
Brookings Institution, is a leader seeking to reduce the risks of
nuclear engagement in a rapidly changing geopolitical environment,
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   John Bonifaz, 33, Boston, a public interest lawyer and executive
director of the National Voting Rights Institute, uses innovative
litigation to re-examine campaign finance reform arguments
typically debated on First Amendment grounds, $260,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Carlson, 39, San Diego, a physicist, educator and the
founder and director of the Society for Amateur Scientists, has
worked to make the scientific process less mystifying and more
comprehensible to nonscientists, $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Danner, 40, New York and Berkeley, Calif., a staff writer
at The New Yorker and former story editor at The New York Times
Magazine, specializing in foreign affairs, offers a new perspective
on the state of human rights and the role of the United States in
the international community, $295,000.
</P>
<P>
   Alison L. Des Forges, 57, Buffalo, a writer, researcher, and
human rights advocate, has documented and brought to light the
causes of genocide, $375,000
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Diller, 45, and Ricardo Scofidio, 64, New York, have
created an alternative form of architectural practice that unites
design, performance, and electronic media with cultural and
architectural theory and criticism, 375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Friedlander, 66, Los Angeles, a professor of history at the
University of California at Los Angeles and a scholar of the Third
Reich and the Holocaust, has transformed our understanding of this
period by weaving into a coherent whole the perspectives of the
participants: ordinary Germans, party activists, military and
political figures, victims and survivors, $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer L. Gordon, 33, Brooklyn, a lawyer and community
organizer founded the Workplace Project in 1992 as a worker's
center to fight employment abuse and discrimination against
immigrant workers, $260,000.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Hillis, 40, Austin, Texas, a molecular biologist and
professor of Zoology at the University of Texas, has developed new
molecular genetic analyses that contribute to our understanding of
the history of life on earth, $295,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Horowitz, 36, New York, a lawyer and executive director of
Working Today, has helped promote the interests of people engaged
in flexible employment arrangements, $275,000.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
