<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-GRANTS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: $275,000. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Jones, 51, Wellesley, Mass., a professor of American
civilization at Brandeis University and a social historian whose
scholarship examines the experience of workers through the lens of
economic transformations throughout United States history,
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Laura L. Kiessling, 38, Madison, Wis., an associate professor of
biochemistry at the University of Wisconsin, has developed
innovative organic syntheses that expand our capacity to understand
and control the biology of inflammation, $285,000.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie V. Kurke, 39, Berkeley, Calif., an associate professor of
classics and comparative literature at the University of
California, has been at the forefront of cultural poetics, the
study of the classics that combines the study of literary sources
with other fields, $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   David Levering Lewis, 63, New York, a professor of history at
Rutgers University, biographer, cultural historian, and scholar of
race relations, $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Martin Maldacena, 30, Cambridge, Mass., an associate
professor of physics at Harvard University, he works in the highly
abstract field of string theory, which focuses on the possibility
of matter that cannot yet be detected, $245,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gay J. McDougall, 51, Washington, executive director of the
International Human Rights Law Group, has crafted human rights
legislation for emerging democracies and has helped lead the
struggle for human rights in southern Africa, $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell McGrath, 37, Miami Beach, an associate professor of
creative writing at Florida International University and a poet
whose work is characterized by lyrical skill, intellectual breadth,
blending of high and low subject matter, and humor, $280,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Albert Moore, 54, Belem-Para, Brazil, a Michigan native,
has helped preserve the language and culture of endangered
indigenous groups in Brazil, $365,000.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Murray, 58, New York, a professor at Bard College and
a painter known for large, three-dimensional canvases, $375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pepon Osorio, 44, New York, an installation artist whose work
combines Hispanic popular culture and traditional aesthetic
sensibilities to explore community dynamics, $315,000.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shor, 39, Florham Park, N.J., a computer scientist at AT&AMP;T
Research Labs, his discoveries are increasing the speed of some
calculations, $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Silverstein, 28, Stanford, Calif., a theoretical physicist,
questions fundamental assumptions of physics theory, $235,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wilma Alpha Subra, 55, New Iberia, La., a chemist and an
environmentalist, helps ordinary citizens in Louisiana understand,
cope with, and combat toxic chemicals, $370,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Vandermark, 34, Chicago, a composer, improviser, and tenor
saxophone and clarinet player, is gaining recognition, as one of
America's most promising young musicians, $265,000.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Wallace, 38, Prospect, Ky., a playwright, employs poetic
and highly original language and a strong socio-political
sensibility in her works, $285,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey R. Weeks, 42, Canton, N.Y., a mathematician and educator
who has analyzed knots and interprets the shape of the universe,
$305,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilson, 44, New York, an installation artist, explores the
relationship between museums and works of art, $315,000.
</P>
<P>
   Xu Bing, 44, New York, an artist, uses ancient Chinese methods
of printmaking and calligraphy to explore new dimensions for
contemporary Chinese art, $315,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ofelia Zepeda, 44, Tucson, Ariz., a professor of linguistics at
the University of Arizona who is devoted to preserving Native
American languages and revitalizing tribal communities, $320,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
