<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM's, players meet to fix NBA...yeah, right
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A collection of NBA coaches, general managers and
players given a mandate to fix pro basketball convened Tuesday, met
for six hours, discussed everything from abolishing the illegal
defense to converting the lane into a trapezoid or the shape of
Gheorghe Muresan. After serious and candid dialogue, the 16 members
entrusted with making the game more aesthetically pleasing, less
rough and potentially higher scoring came away with the following
consensus:
</P>
<P>
   Please, come back, Michael. Please. We beg you.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the committee was more productive than that. It did
come up with a few minor tweaks, such as loosening the rigid
defensive rules, petitioning the referees to whistle more of the
physical play in the lane regarding cutters and screeners, and
instituting a 5-second rule to eliminate or limit the boring,
back-in isolation play, which will be known as the Charles Barkley
rule. No word yet on whether Barkley or Mark Jackson have retired.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, these measures likely will do little to boost scoring,
which has been in precipitous decline for the last 10 years. Just
because Avery Johnson might be able to tiptoe through the lane now
without getting clotheslined, don't expect the scores to return to
the vicinity of the 100s after a season in which Sacramento's Kings
were the only team to average that many points. Scoring is out,
snoring is in. Nothing that the committee suggested will help bad
shooters shoot better.
</P>
<P>
   The measures the committee unveiled Tuesday will be fine-tuned
and implemented during summer league play and are expected to go
before the NBA's Bored of Gover, uh, Board of Governors for
immediate approval before next season.
</P>
<P>
   Marine boot camps have been more free-flowing than NBA games
this season. The Nielsen ratings are not yet in for game three of
the NBA Finals, but they have been so low that even Nielsen isn't
watching. NBC could stick O.J. on a moped in Beverly Hills and more
viewers would turn in.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, NBA stands for No Basketball Allowed. It's become a
rugby scrum, hand-to-hand combat that represents a deterioration of
the game to alarming levels. Average points for a team have fallen
from 106.3 per game for 1990-91 to an all-time low of 91.6 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the game is in trouble,'' NBC broadcaster Doug
Collins told me. ``It's just become stagnant. The illegal defense
and the three-point shot lead to too much standing around. But if
scoring goes up 10 points a game and the game is played the same
way, it's still not good. We've seen a greater emphasis on strength
than skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, the league has too few Allan Houstons and too
many John Starks. Too much slashing and not enough swishing. Does
anybody teach the mid-range jumper any more?
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a lot of the great players, Walt Frazier and
(Earl) Monroe and Oscar Robertson,'' Houston said. ``Those guys
lived off that mid-range jump shot because nobody could do anything
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is trying to bring back the fast break and cut
back on the amount of contact in the lane. These experimental rule
changes are a start, but they're only going to continue to cover up
drastic deficiencies in this new brand of athletically gifted
players who are bigger and stronger but lack the skills of
yesterday's players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it football or basketball? Or is it a mishmash?'' Spurs
Coach Gregg Popovich asked rhetorically. ``In my mind, it's a
finesse game. But you can't move from A to B without getting
chucked.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not all about scoring. As analyst Jack Ramsay said,
``There's nothing magical about 100 points. I'd like to see better
movement of the ball and players, and that might result in more
scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Were David Stern really serious about fixing the game, here are
some no-brainers _ which, if the physical nature of the game is
allowed to continue, is what many NBA players like Luc Longley will
become:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make Karl Malone pay for all plastic surgery for his victims.
</P>
<P>
   _ Move in the three-point line two more feet to encourage
mid-range jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make shooters stay out of the crease. Oops, sorry, wrong
broken sport.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forget widening the lane. Raise the basket a foot. You saw
Marcus Camby get a foot above the rim on his rebound dunk in game
three.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlaw the back-in play. As Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy said,
``I hate the back-in. To me, you don't go to basketball camp and
learn the back-in move. Usually you learn jump hooks and
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Have NBA players actually practice free throw shooting in the
off-season between making movies, taping CDs and suntanning in
Belize.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get rid of the illegal defense. No one understands it anyway.
Allow zone defenses. Although Collins said he detests ``gimmicky
defenses'' like the box-and-one or triangle-and-two, I disagree. Go
with the parallelogram-and-one. Innovative defenses are one of the
things that separate the prettier college game from the ugly pros.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hire Tim Duncan to conduct the Bank Shot Camp. Attendance
would be mandatory for Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy Larry Johnson a dictionary to expand his vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
