<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN BROTHERS' EARNINGS RISE ABOVE EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. Tuesday reported second-quarter
earnings that were far above analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, which has been broadening from its traditional base as a
bond house into equities and investment banking, said it earned
$330 million in the three months ended May 31, up slightly from the
$324 million profits in the second quarter of 1998. Earnings per
diluted share were $2.09, down from $2.12 a share in the second
quarter of 1998, but well above the $1.68 consensus of 11
securities analysts surveyed by the First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman had second-quarter revenue of $1.455 billion, down
slightly from $1.473 billion in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Four analysts told First Call on Tuesday that they were raising
their 1999 earnings estimates for Lehman to an average of $6.73 a
share, up from the previous estimate of $5.85.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unexpectedly high profits, shares of Lehman Brothers
fell $3.6875, or 6.11 percent Tuesday, to $56.625, on volume of
more than 4 million shares _ more than four times the daily average
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The closing price was off exactly one-third from its $85 high on
July 13, but also well above its 52-week low of $22.625 on Oct. 8,
as investors fled the stock following worldwide financial turmoil
that put a crimp in Lehman's bond and equities underwriting
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was the first major Wall Street firm to report earnings
for its second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, who follows investment house stocks for Salomon
Smith Barney, said investors can expect strong results later this
week when Goldman Sachs Group and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
are scheduled to issue their second-quarter returns, next month
when Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., PaineWebber and other brokerage firms
whose second quarter ends June 30 report their results.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman has been retaining earnings to build its capital,
Moszkowski said. This policy was shown in a rise in book value to
$40.58 a share, up from $35.93 a year earlier, and a drop in return
on equity to 26.3 percent in the second quarter from 29.9 percent
in the period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds accounted for slightly more than one-third of total
revenue, down from more than half five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman has been expanding operations in Europe, which accounted
for 27 percent of total revenue in the quarter, said Chief
Financial Officer John L. Cecil. He noted that Lehman expected to
collect $70 million for advising in Olivetti SpA's purchase of
Telecom Italia SpA, but counted only $14 million of that revenue in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years we were thought of as a fixed income-oriented
firm,'' Cecil said. ``We have been following a path of growing our
equities and investment banking businesses and growing our European
franchise and what you see in this quarter's numbers is very clear
evidence of all of that coming to fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Profits in the latest quarter were also enhanced by a sharp drop
in the company's effective tax rate, to 27 percent from 32 percent
in the second quarter of 1998, part of which Cecil attributed to
the fact that profits earned in Europe, which are subject to
national corporate income taxes, but not to the equivalent of
American state and local corporate income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation and benefits consumed 50.7 percent of revenue, a
ratio the company said it has maintained for 17 consecutive
quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
