<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BUDGET FINALE IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without the pressure of deadlines, Gov. George Pataki and the
legislature would be arguing about this year's New York State
budget until Halloween. But since a raft of previously enacted
Medicaid cost reductions are due to expire next Wednesday, wiping
out savings that state and local governments were counting on, a
strong incentive exists for all sides to reach an agreement soon.
In a welcome step, Sheldon Silver, speaker of the
democratic-controlled assembly, has scaled back his spending
demands. It remains for Pataki to compromise by dropping proposed
cuts in school aid and health care payments and promising not to
veto at least some of the items desired by the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate results from an unusual set of financial
circumstances. Prosperity, particularly on Wall Street, has created
a state budget surplus of at least $2 billion. But because the
governor and the legislature have enacted budgets in past years
with tax cuts and expenses that balloon in size, the state is
projecting multibillion-dollar deficits in the future. Pataki was
thus in the odd position of demanding austerity for the lean years
ahead at a time when the state is flush. However prudent his
position might seem fiscally, it has not succeeded politically.
Even the Republican-controlled Senate has made it clear it would
reject the governor's proposed cuts in health and education.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's $73-billion budget, announced in January, was
punitive in many respects. It reneged on commitments to help New
York City, and its cuts in school aid, college tuition assistance
and payments to hospitals, nursing homes and health clinics hit New
Yorkers of modest means the hardest. Silver has been right to
oppose the worst of these cuts, but his opening bid of adding $2.6
billion in spending was too much for the governor and the state
Senate. His request is now said to be in the range of $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That seems like a reasonable number for Pataki to accept without
resorting to gimmicks or raiding independent state funds. The first
priority should be schools, especially in the city. The governor
and the legislature should then make sure that Medicaid
reimbursement rates are sufficient to maintain health care for the
poor and uninsured. There should be some funding also for vital
mental health programs, especially for potentially unstable people
released from mental hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers wondering why any cuts at all are necessary in
prosperous times need look no further than the enact-now, pay-later
strategy of their elected leaders. The governor's zeal for cutting
taxes is appreciated by voters, and he has indeed forced a
fundamental change in New York's fiscal policy. But New Yorkers
have also never been given an honest accounting when it comes to
tax cuts. At some point they will have to realize that the price
for tax cuts may be unacceptably large spending cuts in areas of
vital interest. First, the governor and the legislature have to get
through this year. A spirit of compromise would help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
