<HEADLINE>
FREDERICK SACHS, 61, DOCTOR AND PROFESSOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frederick L. Sachs, a physician, hospital
administrator and educator long associated with Yale University and
Yale-New Haven Hospital, died on Sunday at his home in Woodbridge,
Conn. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, said his wife, Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, a pulmonologist, or expert in lung diseases, was
associate chief of staff and associate chief of medicine at
Yale-New Haven Hospital in New Haven. He had been affiliated with
the hospital since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a clinical professor at the Yale University School
of Medicine from 1970 until earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs was born in Brooklyn on Feb. 28, 1938. He received his
bachelor's degree from Princeton University in 1959 and his medical
degree from Columbia University in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   He was a past president of the New England chapter of the
American College of Chest Physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, he is survived by three daughters, Lori
Sachs-Ceriello of Norwalk, Conn., Jennifer Sachs of Chicago and
Alison Cohen, of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
