<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attempted steal sends Lopez to disabled list
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A team already walking with a decided limp, the Braves
were staggering Tuesday after Javy Lopez, the club's hottest
hitter, was diagnosed with a sprained right knee. He will be placed
on the 15-day disabled list today and the club was undecided on who
would take his roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve catcher Eddie Perez, who started only his 19th game
Tuesday, is about to become a very busy man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have had another cheeseburger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Perez also needed medical attention Tuesday. A collision at the
plate left him with a bleeding eyebrow. He returned to the game.)
</P>
<P>
   Lopez just finished a .400 (10-for-25) road trip with five home
runs and nine RBIs in seven games, a stark contrast to Perez, a
career .265 hitter who was batting .222 entering Monday's game with
two RBIs and no homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed. I'm frustrated,'' Lopez said. ``It's a
time I can say I'm hitting the ball the way I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez went down attempting to steal second base on his own
Sunday night with the Braves leading Arizona 7-3 in the seventh. He
was easily thrown out and jammed his knee into the dirt short of
the base while trying to dodge Jay Bell's tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in here with no limp, no pain or anything,'' Lopez
said. ``I thought it was just a bruise or something. But they tell
me there's a sprain in there and that I should be careful. It could
get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will call up either Pascual Matos (.215, 0 HR, 12
RBIs) from Class AAA Richmond or Fernando Lunar (.235, 1 HR, 14
RBIs) from Class AA Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss waits
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss remained on the disabled list Tuesday,
though he was eligible to be activated. His left quadriceps has
been slow to respond to treatment and the team will not push him,
for fear the injury could worsen. Weiss has missed 21 of the last
24 games.All-Star update
</P>
<P>
   Updated tabulations on the NL All-Star voting did nothing to
improve the Braves' chances for a starting position. Third baseman
Chipper Jones has received more votes (281,265) than any Atlanta
player but is still running more than 75,000 behind Arizona's Matt
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is running third at catcher behind New York's Mike Piazza
and Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall; Bret Boone is third at second base
behind Houston's Craig Biggio and Arizona's Jay Bell; and Weiss is
third at shortstop behind Cincinnati's Barry Larkin and New York's
Rey Ordonez. Andruw Jones is seventh and Brian Jordan ninth in
outfield balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart made his sixth start of the year at second base.
Starter Boone, who was 4-for-28 (.143) during the last road trip,
has lost 33 points off his average to .251. ... Former Brave Mike
Mordecai, in his second season with the Expos, has already
established career-highs this year with four homers and 14 RBIs in
his first 93 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
