</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SEEKING CHANGES IN RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the former Bad Boy point guard, Isiah Thomas, to
the take-no-prisoners coach, Pat Riley, a 16-member committee of
coaches, players and owners convened Tuesday with essentially one
job: to transform the roughhouse NBA back into an esthetically
appealing game.
</P>
<P>
   The overly physical and predictable nature of NBA play was
displayed for the committee in a video showed by Rod Thorn, the
league's senior vice president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   With forearm shivers and hip checks increasing, and scoring and
shooting percentages declining, the videotape of the NBA's
evolution over the last three decades and the discussion that
followed may have helped pave the way for some of the most
significant rule changes of the league's modern era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis is a little strong, but there was a strong mandate from
our Board of Governors to try and make some improvements,'' Russ
Granik, the NBA's deputy commissioner, said. ``And that was
expressed up front by me to the committee today. There certainly
was a perceived need to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think we all realize there are some problems we
need to address as far as how the game is played.''
</P>
<P>
   The videotape was not a watershed, Granik said. But he added
that showing the committee the evolution of officiating through the
last three decades was particularly effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentiment was we have to have less contact,'' he said.
``As the game has evolved, there is too much contact away from the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the rule changes will not be made final until later
this summer, the committee came up with four significant proposals
during the all-day session at a midtown Manhattan hotel:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reduce contact below the foul line and away from the ball. The
usual grabbing, holding and impeding of progress that has become
ritual could cease by the 1999-2000 season. Players won't be
allowed to use their forearms when they are defending on the
perimeter, and officials will be instructed to call games more
closely. Players like Reggie Miller and Allan Houston would not
have to spend most of their time on offense fighting off their
defenders to get through and around screens, while teams that
clutch and grab in the lane, like Utah, would have to change some
of their approach. ``All the chucking in the lane, the having to
push off your guy to get a shot, we're going to try and do
something about that,'' Thorn said. ``Those kind of things could
eventually be considered fouls again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The illegal defense guidelines will be made more
understandable so that coaches do not exploit them. ``The coaches
have caught up with the guidelines,'' Granik said. ``The feeling of
the coaches is that it's to their advantage to isolate a player on
the post the majority of the time in order to take advantage of the
illegal-defense guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A five-second rule will be added to stop the litany of players
who isolate themselves on one side of the court and then take
between 10 and 15 seconds off the shot clock to back their defender
into the post. With only five seconds to make a move, players such
as Charles Barkley and Mark Jackson may have to diversify their
games a bit.
</P>
<P>
   _ And, finally, a 14-second rule will most likely be added to
the game. Instead of the shot clock being reset to 24 seconds in
the front court after a foul or a violation, the committee proposed
that the clock be reset to 14 seconds if the amount of time left on
the shot clock is less than 14 seconds. If 20 seconds remained on
the shot clock, then the clock would be reset to 20 seconds. Thorn
justified the proposed change this way: ``The theory being that
once you get the ball into the front court, you don't need the
extra time in order to get up a shot and this would get you four or
five more possessions in the course of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee was unanimous in deciding against altering the
dimensions of the court, changing the configuration of the lane,
the location of the 3-point line or the 24-second clock, Thorn
said. Granik said the rule changes could be voted on by the Board
of Governors and put into effect as early as July, when the NBA's
Atlanta summer league begins.
</P>
<P>
   Among others serving on the committee are the broadcasters Hubie
Brown and Doug Collins; the players Antonio Davis, Greg Anthony and
Steve Smith and the general managers Dan Issel, Billy King, Kevin
McHale and Donnie Walsh. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
