<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMINGTON-AZR &LR;      06-22 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON FRAUD CONVICTION OVERTURNED ON JUROR MATTER
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY 
 and JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank and wire fraud convictions that pushed Gov. Fife Symington
from office two years ago were tossed out Tuesday by federal judges
who said a troublesome juror shouldn't have been dismissed while
the jury was deciding the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled juror Mary Jane
Cotey, then 74, should not have been replaced, although her fellow
jurors said she was too befuddled and obstinate to do her job.
</P>
<P>
   Symington, 53, who was sentenced to 2{ years in prison, may be
tried again on the original charges. He was free during the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The only sitting Arizona governor in history to be criminally
prose cuted, Symington reacted to the decision with quiet
jubilance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great day,'' Symington told reporters at a
noon-hour press conference under a shade tree on the steps of a
political consulting firm near Third Avenue and Roosevelt Street.
``It may sound funny, but I always thought that we were right, but
I wasn't sure that was going to be enough for a reversal.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington cannot resume his term as governor, but he could run
for office again.
</P>
<P>
   During the press conference, Sy mington showed the
self-possessed style that has often led others to describe him as a
classic old-money Eastern blueblood.
</P>
<P>
   Casual in khaki pants and a button-down blue shirt, Symington
calmly said he believed he would ``do a lot better'' if he were to
be retried on the charges, and he hinted that he wouldn't
plea-bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm innocent, and I don't think you ever compromise
your principles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit's decision was the latest chapter _ and probably
not the last _ in the saga of Symington, scion of a wealthy
Maryland family whose career illustrates the boom-and-bust cycles
of business and politics in modern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Symington ap peared to be a high-flying developer.
In 1991, he was elected governor. In ensuing years, his
developments foundered. In 1995, he declared bankruptcy. In 1996,
he was in dicted on 23 counts of bank fraud, wire fraud, attempted
extortion and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   During a four-month trial two years ago, prosecutors alleged
Symington had lied desperately to try to rescue his collapsing
projects in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, they said, he misled banks about his net worth
in order to get new loans and avoid paying old ones, running his
debts up over $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Symington said the flaws in his financial statements were
mistakes that should have been noted and brought to his attention
by his accountants.
</P>
<P>
   After eight days of deliberations, members of the jury
complained about Cotey to U.S. District Court Judge Roger Strand.
They said she was inattentive, confused about the evidence, and
unbending when she took a position.
</P>
<P>
   Strand ruled that she was unwill ing or unable to continue with
deliberations and replaced her with an alternate. The jury began
its deliberations again.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 3, 1997, Symington was convicted of seven counts of
bank and wire fraud, but one of those convictions was later tossed
out by the judge. Prior to the verdict, the judge had dismissed two
counts. The jury deadlocked on 11 counts and found Symington not
guilty of three counts.
</P>
<P>
   Symington appealed his convic tions, saying his right to an
impar tial jury had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-1 vote, the 9th Circuit agreed.
</P>
<P>
   A judge cannot drop a juror for being unwilling to deliberate if
there is a reasonable possibility that the reason is the juror's
views, the court said. Instead, the judge must declare a mistrial
or order more delibera tions, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there may have been some reason to doubt Cotey's abili
ties as a juror, there was also considerable evidence to suggest
that the other jurors' frustrations with her derived primarily from
the fact that she held a position oppo site to theirs on the merits
of the case,'' said Judge Betty Fletcher, who wrote the majority
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Judge James Fitzgerald, who dis sented, said there was
overwhelming evidence to back up Strand's conclu sion that Cotey
was failing to take part in deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor in the case said his office will consider
whether to ask for further review of the case or, possibly, to
refile charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously disappointed with the majority's opinion,''
said David Schindler, assistant U.S. at torney in Los Angeles,
whose office handled the Symington case. ``We also feel bad for the
12 jurors who worked so diligently.''
</P>
<P>
   Schindler's office must now de cide from among several options:
ask for review by the entire 9th Circuit panel, appeal directly to
the U.S. Supreme Court, retry the case in Arizona, or drop the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to analyze the Ninth Circuit's opinion and decide
whether to seek further review,'' he said. He also turned aside
specula tion that the office might decide to trim the case down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we retry the case, it is my expectation that we would keep
all the counts'' on which the jury returned guilty verdicts as well
as the counts on which the jury hung, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Dowd, Symington's chief defense attorney, said he was de
lighted with the 9th Circuit rul ing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just very happy the system worked,'' said Dowd from his
office in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will ask the prosecutors to drop the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' he said. ``There is a very serious issue
of fairness and justice here. This man has lost public office, and
he and his family have expended a king's ransom. The government has
expended enormous resources too.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond to Dowd's statement that the case should be
ended, Schindler said he saw only one way to end it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always said that if Mr. Symington is willing to plead
guilty to felonies, we are willing to listen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, juror Harold Thomp son said he also thought Strand
was right and reacted with shock to the 9th Circuit decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' said Thomp son. ``If they were going to
over throw it, at least they could have had a good reason. I don't
know how in the world they thought Mary Jane Cotey was a good
reason. I know what she said and I know what she did, and I know it
was the right thing to dismiss her from that trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Hackett, an alternate juror in the trial, also said she
disagreed with the appellate court's decision because she viewed
Cotey as eccen tric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that unfortunately she may have some problems,''
Hackett said. ``From the outset, she was disruptive. She was
bringing news papers in. She was doing everything we were told not
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett added that the ruling ``sets a different set of
standards for people with money, position and influence and it just
leaves the general public (with a) justice system that just serves
the well-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey, however, said she felt the Appeals Court decision
vindicated her and was a just one for Syming ton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not proven in court that he was guilty of those
charges,'' Cotey said, ``and he did not cheat anyone out of
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotey has said that before to reporters, but at times has contra
dicted herself, saying she might have voted to convict Symington on
some charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Lynch, a professor at Columbia Law School, said cases
involving questionable jurors always create a quandary: Is the
juror incompetent or just hardheaded?
</P>
<P>
   ``The holdout juror is the hero of the system. Twelve Angry Men,
right?'' Lynch said. ``Right or wrong . . . the holdout takes his
posi tion. The problem is, it's very difficult to separate out
who's crazy or not.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the phenomenon usually occurs during
deliberations, where ``one sees just about every kind of weirdness
you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the trial judge is closer to the situation, Lynch said,
``It's unusual for an appellate court to second-guess what a trial
judge decides.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Fletcher's vote to overturn was not entirely unexpected,
based on her approach to the case when the three-judge panel heard
oral arguments on the Symington appeal last November in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Fletcher raised strong doubts about Cotey's dis
missal.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher cited ``a disturbing kind of dialogue'' between Cotey
and the other jurors, who had complained to the trial judge that
she was unable to maintain focus on their discus sions.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher asked federal prosecutors how willing the trial judge
should have been to believe the 11 other Symington jurors, who
complained in a closed hearing about Cotey's inability to fulfill
her duties as a juror.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much do we need to credit jurors who say that she isn't
basing it (her opinion) on the evidence?'' asked Fletcher, who at
76 is the same age as Cotey. ``She could come out of the last day
of evidence in the courtroom, and she knows that it's a thin case,
and she's just not going to convict on it. Now, there is nothing
wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher then noted that other jurors had pressed Cotey to
explain her positions onthe case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must she give her reasons?'' she asked. And if Cotey had
agreed with the other jurors, she asked, would the other jurors
have sought explanations?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they might have,'' federal prosecutor George Cardona
replied, prompting Fletcher to retort quickly, ``Would they be
entitled to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Fletcher said, ``This is a very disturbing kind of dialogue
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington defense attorney Ter ence Lynam argued that the real
reason the jurors were frustrated was that Cotey wanted to acquit
Symington of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Cardona said the panel should defer to the judgment
of Strand because the judge had ``very carefully listened'' to all
12 jurors in separate discussions before dismiss ing Cotey.
</P>
<P>
   Symington said Tuesday that his view of Cotey was that ``the
person who was standing against the tide got run off the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington lauded Cotey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember reading stories at the time when she was run off
the jury that she was being pictured as sort of out of it, and off
base, and all kinds of derogatory comments. She was right, and
she's just a very courageous person, and I admire her.'' &QL; 
tagRepublic writers Mary Jo Pitzl and Dennis Wagner contributed to
this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
