A5867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-STEEL-QUOTAS-NYT     06-22 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STEEL-QUOTAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROTECTIONISM AND THE AMERICAN STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the Senate may not go along with the House of
Representatives in voting to impose import quotas to protect the
steel industry. That is a welcome rebuff to protectionist impulses
that remain strong even while the American economy is booming.
</P>
<P>
   A procedural vote in the Senate Tuesday indicated that
supporters of the quota bill, which was passed by the House
overwhelmingly earlier this year, do not have enough support to
push the bill through. Only 42 senators voted to cut off debate and
force a vote, far fewer than the 60 needed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would impose quotas on steel imports, in direct
violation of the country's obligations as a member of the World
Trade Organization. It would be likely to damage the nation's
economy both by provoking retaliation and by hurting the exports of
American products that include steel.
</P>
<P>
   The steel industry nonetheless has scored some major successes
in its efforts to keep out inexpensive foreign steel that flooded
into this country after the Asian economic crisis slashed demand
for steel in other countries. Responding to the pressure, the
Clinton administration has aggressively sought to enforce
anti-dumping laws, which allow high tariffs on products sold either
below the cost of production or for less than the exporting country
charges at home. This week, Commerce Secretary William Daley
announced more dumping investigations. The result of such efforts,
combined with incipient Asian recovery, has been a sharp fall in
steel imports.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of world recession has eased since last summer. But
such countries as Argentina, Brazil and Indonesia, which are
targeted in the latest round of dumping investigations, are in
recession, and efforts to dampen their exports could weaken their
economies even further. While the Commerce Department should
enforce the law, it should take care not to act unfairly just to
pacify a politically powerful domestic steel industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
