<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; tth-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARK-B.C.-SPI &LR;      06-22 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-B.C.-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. GOVERNMENT SETS ASIDE 3.35 MILLION ACRES FOR PARK LANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under fire from environmentalists, the British Columbia
government on Tuesday responded by preserving 3.35 million acres of
land, creating 35 new provincial parks and expanding several
existing parks.
</P>
<P>
   But while protecting key wild valleys and wildlife habitat
across northern B.C., the government did not designate much new
parkland along the U.S.-Canada border _ where extensive logging is
taking place near or adjacent to parks and wilderness areas in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty grim (along the border),'' said Joe Scott,
conservation director of the Northwest Ecosystem Alliance, a
Bellingham, Wash.-based conservation group. Scott recently found
logging and road building in the Pasayten River, just over the
border from Washington's largest wilderness area.
</P>
<P>
   Only one small area near the boundary was protected in Tuesday's
announcement. A portion of the historic Dewdney and Whatcom trails
_ which led from Bellingham to the Cariboo gold fields of British
Columbia _ will be added to Manning Provincial Park.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, British Columbia environmentalists had much to
cheer about Tuesday. The government's announcement brings to 11.3
percent the area of British Columbia that is now preserved in
parks, wilderness conservancies or ecological reserves. Only 6.6
percent of the province was protected at the start of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Premier Glen Clark hinted that the government
may go beyond its goal of protecting 12 percent of the province's
land. ``Twelve percent is a goal, but not a ceiling,'' Clark told a
briefing in Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means is what the government's doing perfect, but they
are following through in what they have chosen to protect,'' said
Bill Wareham, executive director of the Sierra Club of British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has been under fire from the province's more radical
environmental groups for easing regulations on loggers under the
new Forest Practices Code. The British Columbia timber industry
endured severe cutbacks last year after losing markets in Asia's
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bits and pieces are put into parks and, in return, industry
gets speeded-up access to other places,'' Joy Foy of the Western
Canada Wilderness Committee, a frequent critic of the government,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The places preserved may not be household words, but the parks
announced in British Columbia Tuesday are particularly important
for wildlife. These include:
</P>
<P>
   _Northern Rockies: A 1.6 million-acre park in the northern Rocky
Mountains, near Fort Nelson, will protect a portion of the largest
unroaded area in North America south of the Yukon. Taking in the
Muskwa and Prophet rivers, it is an area where the relationships of
predators to prey have not been altered by human intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby 230,000-acre preserve, Denetiah Park, also protects a
predator-prey environment of moose, caribou, stone's sheep,
mountain goats, wolves and grizzly bears.
</P>
<P>
   _Nahatlatch River: A low-elevation valley, just west of the
Fraser River canyon north of Hope, is part of the most healthy
remaining grizzly valley in southwest British Columbia. The park
protects a major wetland.
</P>
<P>
   _Babine River: A new park in northern B.C. will protect a
52-mile stretch of the Babine River, major sockeye salmon and
steelhead habitat in the Skeena River system, the province's second
largest fishery.
</P>
<P>
   _Brackendale Eagles: A park near Squamish, south of the Whistler
ski resort, will preserve a section of the Squamish River that is a
major winter bald eagle habitat.
</P>
<P>
   _Kakwa: Located about 50 miles northwest of Jasper, an expanded
410,000-acre Kakwa Provincial Park protects a wilderness section of
the Rocky Mountains considered equally beautiful to crowded, nearby
national parks.
</P>
<P>
   _Spipyus: A small new park on the Sechelt Peninsula, north of
Vancouver, protects about 8,500 acres of old-growth forst and prime
habitat for the marbled murrelet, an endangered sea bird.
</P>
<P>
   _Entiako River: The province has protected 115,000 acres of
caribou winter range in the Entiako River valley, on the east
slopes of the Coast Mountains. The new area is adjacent to
Tweedsmuir Park, the province's largest protected area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not finished yet,'' Clark declared Tuesday. The premier
described the new parks, which will be formally established by the
B.C. Legislature, as ``the strongest possible measure government
can take to ensure preservation of these areas for future
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   But conservationists noted that areas along the border have
largely been cut out of British Columbia's rapid park creation.
</P>
<P>
   The provincial government is planning to allow logging of
Eighteen Mile and Twentymile creeks, two wilderness tributaries of
the Skagit River just north of the border. An additional 240 acres
of clearcutting is planned in already heavily logged Depot Creek,
the upper reaches of which are parts of America's North Cascades
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Pasayten River is of major concern. It runs into the
Similkameen River, which recrosses the U.S.-Canada border and feeds
into the Okanogan River. Salmon runs of the Okanogan River were
recently classified as endangered by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river runs crystal clear when it crosses into Canada,''
Scott said. ``Within three miles, due to erosion from logging and
roads, the water is brown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WASSERMAN-NYT &LR;      06-22 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WASSERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. LOUIS R. WASSERMAN, 88, AUTHORITY ON BLOOD  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Louis Robert Wasserman, an authority on the
diagnosis and treatment of blood diseases and the founder of one of
the nation's foremost hematology training programs, died on Monday
at Danbury Hospital in Connecticut. He was 88 and lived in Sandy
Hook, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman's association with New York's Mount Sinai Medical
Center and School of Medicine as a physician, teacher and
researcher spanned nearly 60 years, and the hematology program he
established there has attracted specialists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote or collaborated on some 200 papers on the red blood
cell, iron metabolism and the remediation of blood disorders
through radiation, antibiotics and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   One of Wasserman's most important contributions was his research
into polycythemias, a class of disorders that occur when the bone
marrow oversupplies the blood with red cells, resulting in a wide
array of abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman led an international study group that established the
standards for the treatment of polycythemia vera, to the benefit of
thousands of patients. The American Society of Hematology gave his
name to a lectureship.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Wasserman graduated from Harvard College in
1931 and received his medical degree at Rush Medical College of the
University of Chicago in 1935. Two years later he joined the staff
of Mount Sinai Hospital as a research fellow in hematology.
</P>
<P>
   He directed its division of hematology from 1953 to 1972 and was
named to the faculty of the medical school when it was organized in
the 1960s. He was chairman of its department of clinical science
from 1967 to 1972, when he became the school's second Distinguished
Service Professor. He was appointed to the Albert A. and Vera G.
List Professorship of Medicine in 1977, and was named its emeritus
professor when he retired in 1979. He continued his investigations,
writings and editing well into the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman was a member of many professional organizations, and
held such leadership positions as president of the American Society
of Hematology and vice president of its international affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 42 years, Julia Wheeler Wasserman,
and a sister, Natalie W. Wolf, of Newbury, N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-22-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
