<DOCNO> NYT19990622.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-MUSIC-$ADV27-2T     06-22 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-MUSIC-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COUNTRY NOW READY TO LISTEN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late one night a few years ago, Robert Ferris Thompson, who as a
professor of African and African-American Arts at Yale University
is considered the dean of African studies in the New World, was at
S.O.B.'s, the Manhattan club whose name stands for Sounds of
Brazil. He was standing next to an English rock critic. ``What am I
doing in this white skin?'' the critic asked in a moment of
self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson laughs about the story, but he uses it to help explain
the endless interracial and transcultural movements that have
occurred since Columbus arguably began the mulatto civilization of
the Americas, one based on the triumvirate of the Native-American,
African and European cultures. It's a triumvirate that undergoes
seismic readjustment once in a while, and at the end of the
millennium it's undergoing a big one, with the main producer of
cultural product, the United States, suddenly seeing itself
differently.
</P>
<P>
   After 500 years of denying the family's Hispanic hue, the
Anglo-Saxon United States is recognizing its darker cousin. And one
way Americans are doing so is by consuming Latin culture,
especially its music.
</P>
<P>
   ``What took so long? is the question I always ask,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the change in both the way Latin culture
is perceived and the way Latin culture represents itself was
inevitable. Centuries of immigration, from Mexico and Central
America, have altered American life, from what we eat to how we
talk. The influx of Puerto Ricans, Cubans and Dominicans over the
last century has profoundly changed the face of New York City and
the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos, it's often noted, will become the dominant minority in
the United States in the next several years. It seems logical,
therefore, that second- and third-generation Latino immigrants,
tugged between the country's various cultural poles, should have
come to some conclusion about how to exist in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more and more requests from Latinos who are young
and don't speak Spanish that well,'' said Bruce Polin, the owner of
Descarga.com, the leading online retailer for tropical Latin music.
``These are people who may have grown up listening to Led Zeppelin
and the Who and suddenly realize that the music of their parents,
and by extension their own culture, is pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   For Emilio Estefan, one of the most successful Latin pop
producers in the United States and an architect of the current
sound of high-gloss Latin pop (his wife is the singer Gloria
Estefan), the change has been radical.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started out, 20 years ago, people in the music industry
told me to get rid of the congas and horns on my records, if they
bothered to talk to me at all,'' he said. ``Now, if I had a dollar
for every time a record label head has called me in the last few
years, I'd be rich. In two years the entire way the music industry
relates to Latinos has completely changed. I'm really proud to be a
Latino. It's our time.''
</P>
<P>
   From Puerto Rico to the Texas border, Latinos are flowering in
circumstances markedly different from those their parents knew.
Fifty years ago a Mexican-American child was caned for speaking
Spanish in school; today, try not speaking Spanish in the Rio Grand
Valley and see how far you get.
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rico today there's a debate brewing about recouping
what's left of its culture, and there are more groups playing
bombas and plenas, the local rhythms of Puerto Rico, than there
have been in years. As these Latin populations grow in the United
States, and the effects of prejudice slowly slip away, it isn't
surprising that a talented, bilingual group of performers _ from
Selena to the extraordinary salsa singer Victor Manuelle, and
including Ricky Martin, Jennifer Lopez, India and Marc Anthony _
should appear, along with an audience that wants to hear the music.
The law of averages is in such performers' favor.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a tendency to see the huge success of Ricky
Martin as indicative of the crosscultural appeal of Latin
performers, it has to be remembered that his current hit, ``Livin'
La Vida Loca,'' apart from the title, is in English. But the
success of the Grammy-winning album ``Buena Vista Social Club''
points to an audience different from the one Martin is reaching.
</P>
<P>
   The album, a collection of pre-revolutionary Cuban songs
performed by a group of elderly musicians, was marketed in the
United States with the so-called National Public Radio audience in
mind _ a well-educated and mostly well-off group. Sales have been
strong (nearly a half-million in this country), suggesting that
there is a large, disenfranchised audience in America looking for
something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from East St. Louis, which is arguably the blackest
city in America,'' said Warrington Hudlin, a filmmaker who heads
out to salsa shows regularly. ``What I know is that modern black
pop, especially hip-hop, has very little in it that reflects my
culture. I go to salsa shows because salsa hasn't abandoned the
dancers. That interaction between live musicians and the dancer is
essential to black music, and it doesn't exist in hip-hop. It's
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bither, a senior vice president of Nonesuch Records, which
has been the marketing force behind the ``Buena Vista Social Club''
in the United States, agrees. ``Nothing's happening in
English-speaking pop,'' he said. ``I'm 44, and I grew up on pop
music, and I haven't cared about anything I've heard in 10 or 15
years. I've remained interested in music, but I'm not interested in
music made and marketed for 18-year-olds. If you still love music,
and freshness and honesty, you don't have that many places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bither has a point. Perhaps the reason that Latin music in its
various forms is appealing to English-speaking intellectuals and
trend setters is that much of American rock is simply less
interesting than it once was. A resolutely suburban music, rock is
as ahistorical as the suburbs themselves, and it has lost any sense
of time or place.
</P>
<P>
   The punk esthetic, which elevated the amateur, has contributed
to the incompetence of musicians; much of the songwriting has been
reduced to the self-absorbed whining of suburban children. How much
complaining can a person stand? Hip-hop, for all its rhythmic
pleasures and sense of humor, has replaced sensuality with
sexuality, and as a consequence has remained the music of
adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   All of pop, black and white, whether it be country music or
hip-hop, is parochial. America has so dominated global
entertainment over the last 100 years that a byproduct of the
so-called American century is that American producers of mainstream
pop culture have become utterly uninterested in other cultures,
ages, places or experiences, if not completely unaware of them.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the wells that gave rise to so much American music
have seemingly dried up. Blues culture is dead. Country has been
deracinated, and gospel has seemingly little more to offer than the
already heard.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite is happening in music across Latin America. There,
the information explosion in the form of MTV and the Internet has
made awareness of new ideas more possible than ever before, often
in places that only a few years ago saw the world through virtually
pre-Columbian eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian pop, in particular, is enjoying an extraordinary
period of creativity. Carlinhos Brown's new album is an amalgam of
everything from Bahaian drumming to Beatles melodies. Caetano
Veloso's last studio album integrates the sound of Europe in its
orchestrations with the drum-based sound of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Bloque, a group from Colombia, combines rock with native Indian
and African rhythms; indeed, there's an entire movement of
Colombian musicians merging African styles like soukous and juju
with indigenous Colombian music. Hip-hop shows up in Mexican pop,
but performed in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, which has been cut off from much of the world by a
repressive government and an American blockade, musicians are
blending their own music with the limited information they get from
outside.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense throughout Latin music that new technology and
improved communications are contributing to an unprecedented
cross-fertilization of styles. As a consequence, Latin musicians
are engaging in a kind of creative balancing act. They want to make
music that is both international yet true to their own cultural
identity. The results have amounted to some of the most powerful
pop music around.
</P>
<P>
   David Byrne, who was a master of American pop as the leader of
the Talking Heads in the 1980s, has changed his career and become,
among other things, the owner of Luaka Bop, a record company that
specializes in world music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Anglo-Saxon `Don't touch yourself, don't have a good
time or God will smack you upside the head' idea is such a big part
of America that drives Americans crazy,'' he said in an interview.
``People who have grown up here sense that something's missing, not
only in music but in our culture, and are looking to replace what's
missing to make their lives fuller.''
</P>
<P>
   This new interest in Latin music may have something to do with a
kind of millennial insecurity, with Americans longing for music
more rooted in a certain place and produced more honestly. If
American music has become narrow in scope and repetitive, then
Latin music at its best sounds ample, literate and international _
part of a polyglot future.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a transcendental, religious quality to the music
that at the dawn of the next millennium is clearly attracting
people. ``Do you sense religiosity in rock?'' asked Thompson of
Yale. ``Mambo, salsa and merengue constantly make reference to the
saints of Yoruba religion. When Machito sang a tune that made
reference to religion, he was suddenly using sacred medicine; he
wasn't just an anonymous black man lost in an angry sea of America.
Maybe people are looking for guidance. There's power in that sort
of conviction, and it comes across.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
