<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banged-up Braves fall to Expos
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is true the Braves lost to Montreal 2-1 Tuesday
night. It is not true the club has established a new statistical
category: body count.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux (6-5) gave up two runs (one earned) in seven
innings, allowing eight hits with two walks and three strikeouts.
But it was first baseman Randall Simon's throwing error that
allowed Manny Martinez to score the deciding run from second base
on an infield single in the fifth that decided the night.
</P>
<P>
   The more pressing issue was whether the Braves would have enough
players to finish the game. Javy Lopez is headed for the disabled
list, Brian Jordan was taken out by a fastball to the right wrist
and Eddie Perez was bloodied but unbowed in the first of 17 games
against NL East clubs. At this rate, they'll call their own blood
drive by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   With catcher Javy Lopez slated for the disabled list with a knee
sprain, the Braves watched Brian Jordan leave the game after five
innings. He was struck in the right wrist by Montreal starter Mike
Thurman in the fourth. X-rays were negative, and Jordan is listed
as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Perez went down in the sixth after a collision
with Montreal rookie Michael Barrett opened a gash next to his
right eye. Barrett attempted to score from third on a chopper by
Orlando Cabrera and crashed into Perez's shoulder, catching him in
the head with his batting helmet and leaving Perez dripping blood
down the side of his face. With Lopez unavailable and no other
catcher on the roster, the game was held up more than five minutes
while the wound was bandaged.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was cleaning up after himself most of the night. He
allowed five hits and nine baserunners in the first five innings,
five reaching scoring position. The Expos didn't catch up to him
until two out in the fifth, when Vladimir Guerrero sent a
check-swing bouncer down the first base line.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Randall Simon failed to backhand the ball deep behind the
base, allowing Thurman to score from third, and Simon compounded
the misplay by throwing wildy at Maddux covering first with little
chance of catching Guerrero. The ball skipped across the infield,
letting Manny Martinez come home with an unearned run for a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves appeared on the verge of reaching Thurman in the
fourth, when Chipper Jones opened the inning with a double, just
his third extra-base hit in 33 at-bats. Thurman followed with a
fastball that rode in on Jordan, striking him flush on the back of
the right hand, a team-high fifth time Jordan has been struck by a
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan Klesko bounced into a double play and Andruw Jones, who
is just 6-for-30 with a runner at third and two out, popped out
weakly to Cabrera in shallow left field.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
