<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5874 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAME-CONCEPT-2TAKES-$     06-22 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAME-CONCEPT-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUMBLING OF THE MEGASTARS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julia RoBerts, in a television interview promoting her hit movie
``Notting Hill'' recently, said she could slip out of the house and
go unrecognized at the market and the laundromat. The laundromat?
When was the last time anyone making $20 million a film went to a
laundromat?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not quibble about the details (even in cramped New York
City, plenty of middle-class people have washers and dryers in
their buildings). What matters is that Julia Roberts wants the
public to think she goes to the laundromat, just like them.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy echoes the plot of ``Notting Hill,'' in which the
Roberts character, a movie star, walks into the life of a bookish,
ordinary man played by Hugh Grant and decides to stay, prodding the
audience to think: aren't we lucky to be average?
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Roberts does more than that. On the screen and while
promoting the film, she offers a prime example of how the concept
of fame has shifted in the past decade. Her strategy suggests the
answer to an essential question: what happens now that Andy
Warhol's ``everyone will be famous for 15 minutes'' has become a
cultural cliche? Today the Warholian trajectory of fame has been
reversed: instead of the ordinary becoming famous, the famous seem
to become more ordinary, more like us.
</P>
<P>
   In entertainment, politics and social mores, the high and mighty
are tumbling all around us, or so true celebrities would have us
think. Martha Stewart may have her own television show and
magazine, but she also has a line of products at K-Mart, suggesting
she goes bargain-hunting, too. Prince Edward chooses to be known as
Edward Windsor, television producer, as if he were a commoner.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent reversal of fame is, of course, an illusion. The
popularity of Tom Brokaw's best-selling book ``The Greatest
Generation'' comes partly from its flattering concept that the
average American soldier in World War II, who returned to a most
ordinary life, is the truest hero. But would the book be selling
nearly as well without its famous anchorman author?
</P>
<P>
   Fame's post-Warhol era owes a great deal to cable television,
which in its rush to fill time with personalities (from CNN
profiles to A&AMP;E's ``Biography'') makes the famous familiar. An
exploding media culture also fosters the myth that everybody is an
insider, whether they're inside show business (with television
shows like ``Entertainment Tonight'' and magazines like
Entertainment Weekly) or big business (financial news channels like
CNBC).
</P>
<P>
   And the downward spiraling of fame would seem likely to expand
with the Internet, that great equalizer, which allows any
computer-literate nobody to become somebody with a Web site. This
leveling is yet another fantasy; let's face it, Bill Gates' Web
site will always be bigger than yours.
</P>
<P>
   However much it is based on illusion, though, the new attitude
is a real cultural force, profoundly altering the way we think
about celebrity. If everyone is inside, no one is outside; if
everyone is famous, no one is famous.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate how radical a shift this is, look at Salman
Rushdie's current novel, ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet.'' The
narrator describes a rock star at the moment her celebrity begins,
back in the late 1960s. ``Her dark skin had a burnished quality to
it: a heightening,'' he says. ``It was a gleam created by the
brilliant gaze of the public eye, the first rough licks of the
tigerish tongue of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   What a quaint notion! The novel is one of the most serious and
artful dissections of fame in recent years, dazzling on its own
terms. But its view of celebrity seems a beat behind the times. It
may be true to the period of the heroine's success, the '60s
through the '80s, but now megastars go out of their way to pretend
they're not glowing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Diana was the transforming figure in this fake
democratization of fame. Despite the fairy tale imagery and glamour
that surrounded her, one of the pivotal Diana images is the
videotape, replayed endlessly on cable television, of the princess
in exercise clothes driving herself to and from the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the royals could have installed an exercise room in some
palace or other if she had wanted one. But Diana was sending a
message that she preferred to be ``normal.'' Bulimia and a bad
marriage, even more than glamour, were the true secrets of her
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   When Prime Minister Tony Blair called her ``the people's
princess'' soon after her death, it was brilliant: the phrase is
pure oxymoron, an illogical combination that perfectly reflects
Diana's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Following Diana, fame itself has become a newly charged subject.
The heroine of the Rushdie novel, the rock star Vina Apsara,
inspires Diana-like, media-crazed mourning when she dies. And the
idea that the paparazzi had hounded Diana to death gave Peter
Galassi, the Museum of Modern Art's chief curator of photography,
the impetus for a new exhibit that considers the cultural import of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame After Photography,'' opening at the museum on July 8,
charts how photographic images have altered the way the public
regards and interacts with fame.
</P>
<P>
   As the show's curators, Marvin Heiferman and Carole Kismaric,
explained in a recent interview, the distance between the famous
and the ordinary has shifted back and forth as it has evolved from
19th-century still portraits through television and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, for instance, magazines like Life and the old
Vanity Fair created glamorized images of movie stars, who had
already seemed larger than life on screen. Television brought an
immense change, as even movie stars literally became smaller and
more accessible. They were visitors to our homes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the television clips in the MOMA show (displayed on
monitors throughout the exhibit) is the 1950s Edward R. Murrow
interview series ``Person to Person,'' in which viewers got to
return the visit and enter the homes of the famous (and an eminent
war reporter chatted up celebs long before the shaky line between
news and entertainment became a concern).
</P>
<P>
   Other clips feature the game show ``Queen for a Day,'' in which
contestants told sob stories and the most pathetic person won a
major prize like a new kitchen. The losers got a prize, too: a
bottle of a perfume called Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Even as fame was being passed around in a bottle, though, the
distance between the celebrated and the ordinary still seemed a
vast expanse the average person could scarcely hope to cross. Among
the exhibit's more recent artifacts is the jacket to Jane Fonda's
early 1980s workout videotape, which suggests that ordinary people
can look like a star. As Ms. Kismaric said, ``The barrier between
`us' and `them' gets thinner and thinner,'' over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While ``Fame After Photography'' charts the history of celebrity
within the museum's walls, its evolution goes on all around us.
Fame has become a series of vanishing lines. Though the difference
between the celebrated and the average only seems to be
diminishing, for the famous some lines are genuinely blurring:
between public and private lives, politics and show business,
notoriety and fame.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of ever faster and more relentless media, the famous
morph from one kind of celebrity to another in a flash. Jesse
Ventura translates minor fame as a wrestler into a job as a radio
talk-show host, parlays that into his election as governor of
Minnesota, then is played by an actor in a bad NBC television movie
based on his life, all in a few quick years.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson's resume is a catalogue of how fluid celebrity is:
football hero and star of television commercials, accused murderer
and star of his own endlessly televised trial. However dimmed his
star, his fame will not go away. Recently, the fifth anniversary of
the murders of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman brought a
flood of retrospective television reports, along with one
especially bizarre scene.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of Simpson's new girlfriend appeared on an MSNBC talk
show pleading with her daughter, ``You deserve better.'' She may be
proof that some people get only 5 minutes of fame, not 15, but
there is no more convincing evidence that Warhol's idea has taken
hold in the most banal way.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder fame's more dynamic movement is in the other,
anti-Warholian direction. The humbling of the famous is most
evident in the way politics, show business and celebrity culture
have merged. Where the private lives of the famous used to be
glossily contrived by Hollywood studios and softball television
interviewers, today's gossip culture charts every visit to drug
rehab and every rumored eating disorder.
</P>
<P>
   We know more about Bill Clinton's sex life than any stranger
should, as the line separating the government-financed Starr report
from Vanity Fair and other celebrity-gossip-mongering media has
blurred.
</P>
<P>
   When Monica Lewinsky appeared on ``Saturday Night Live'' playing
herself last month, a common response was, ``Aren't her 15 minutes
up yet?'' but that misses the point. The elevation of Ms. Lewinsky
to celebrity status is nothing. A more powerful cultural jolt came
from a year's worth of television chatter that cast the president
as the average, cheating husband next door (is he sorry enough?
will Hillary forgive him?). The change flows directly from and
feeds back into the idea that celebrities are just like us.
</P>
<P>
   But those who die by the sword of celebrity can pick up that
sword and live again; that is one result of the fluidity of fame.
Among the photographs in the MOMA show is Hugh Grant's mug shot, a
reminder of his arrest after a Hollywood escapade with a
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Even more memorable than Grant's fall was the savvy way he
redeemed himself in public opinion, appearing on ``The Tonight
Show'' and abashedly telling Jay Leno he had made a foolish
mistake. He displayed no hint of movie star prerogative or bad boy
glamour, just the sense that he was a regular guy who was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Hugh Grant who pioneered the culture of public
apology that Bill Clinton latched onto in the wake of the Lewinsky
affair. Maybe not. But throughout the impeachment furor the only
question I wanted someone to ask President Clinton was the one Jay
Leno asked Hugh Grant: ``What the hell were you thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Politics and show business have so completely bled together, the
question seemed more commonsensical and to the point than anything
Congress cooked up. With every star and politician trying so hard
to be ordinary, why not ask the question you would ask your best
friend?
</P>
<P>
   Of course that would work only if the ratcheting down of fame
were a fact rather than an illusion. ``The fame thing isn't really
real, you know,'' Ms. Roberts' character says nonsensically in
``Notting Hill,'' trying to talk the Grant character into giving
her a second chance (and proving her desperate need for better
lines).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a girl standing in front of a boy asking you to love
her.'' Well, of course she's more than that and of course the fame
thing is real. What isn't real is the idea that fame is actually
spiraling downward, that the next time we're at K-Mart we might run
into Bill Clinton and Martha Stewart buying detergent so they can
join Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts at the laundromat. But they might
not mind if we believed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
