<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE IN THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CHARLES STRUM with AMY WALDMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball Greats Shine in New Fields
</P>
<P>
   New York at its finest: YOGI BERRA went to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art Tuesday to look at baseball cards. TOM SEAVER went to
Alice Tully Hall to be the emcee at an orchestral concert.
</P>
<P>
   First, Berra and the Met, which many years ago became the
repository for a collection of more than 300,000 baseball cards
dating from 1887. The museum has displayed dozens of the cards in
its American Wing since 1993, rotating the exhibit every six
months.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it changed to honor one of Berra's former Yankee
teammates, Joe DiMaggio, who died in March. Among the images of
Honus Wagner, Dizzy Dean and Ty Cobb were seven of DiMaggio,
including an unusual composite card in which a photo of his face is
mounted on a cartoon body.
</P>
<P>
   There was also one of Berra, the Hall of Fame catcher, arrayed
with three other 1953 teammates, Billy Martin, Phil Rizzuto and
Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Berra viewed the DiMaggio cards reverently, then reminisced
about his own collection, long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to flip 'em,'' he said, adding that he no longer had a
full set of Yogi Berra cards, if he ever did.
</P>
<P>
   On the way out, past the banner advertising ``From Cezanne to
Van Gogh: The Collection of Dr. Gachet,'' someone asked Berra who
his favorite painter is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the painters,'' he said. ``I look at the picture.
If I like it, I like it. Then I ask who the painter is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seaver had a busy day, rushing down to New York from the Mets'
farm team in Binghamton to be the host of a concert by the American
Russian Young Artist Orchestra, which brings together conservatory
musicians from both countries for two weeks of rehearsals and
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Seaver, the Hall of Fame pitcher for the Mets who now broadcasts
their games, said that until Tuesday night the only word of Russian
he knew was ``nyet.'' A word he could not muster when his daughter,
SARAH SEAVER, the orchestra's deputy director, asked him to be the
host of the event, which benefits the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Dad, you're going to do this.' I said, `I don't
know about my schedule.' She said, `Dad, you're going to do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Seaver agreed to broaden his vocabulary and speak a
full Russian sentence as he introduced Stravinksy's ``Firebird''
suite. The sentence was written out phonetically for him. It meant:
``I want to marry your tractor.'' At which point a young Russian
violinist tugged on his sleeve and explained that the joke was on
him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vallone's Air of Authenticity &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of New York's City Council, PETER F. VALLONE, took a
busman's holiday Tuesday. From 12:30 to well after dinner time, he
portrayed a fictional New York City councilman in a Miramax film
called ``The Yards,'' which was being shot at Bronx Borough Hall.
Never mind that the yards refer to Queens, Vallone's home borough.
The director, JAMES GRAY, liked the Depression-era grandeur of the
Bronx building.
</P>
<P>
   Gray also liked his casting director's idea to approach a
certified politician. ``That's great _ he's the real deal,'' Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the plot: An act of industrial sabotage in the rail yards
ignites a political corruption scandal implicating the borough
president, a character named Arthur C. Mydanick.
</P>
<P>
   The actor MARK WAHLBERG, who, as a tough guy named Leo Handler
served time for a murder he did not commit, has the goods on
Mydanick and is called to testify before a council committee whose
chairman is Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone spoke lines like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you please state your name for the record?'' And, ``We
would like to thank you, Handler, for your courageousness in coming
forward this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m., with more shooting still to come, Vallone said, ``I
was supposed to be out of here a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it make politics seem easy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that,'' Vallone replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
