<SLUG> BC-NY-CORRUPTION-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 INDICTED IN BID-RIGGING ON 74 RESIDENTIAL BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a heavy blow to the embattled management industry
for co-ops and condominiums in New York City, the Manhattan
district attorney announced the indictments of 30 owners, agents
and contractors Tuesday on charges arising from what prosecutors
say is a widespread bid-rigging scheme that has driven up
maintenance costs for thousands of homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, said the scheme has
generated nearly $4 million in kickbacks from contractors for work
at 74 buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the pervasiveness of corruption in the industry,
prosecutors said, Jeffrey Gold, the vice president of Marvin Gold
Management and a man who helped draft ethics guidelines for the
industry after a scandal five years ago, was among those charged
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments Tuesday came almost five years to the day after
Morgenthau rocked the residential real estate industry with the
indictment of more than 72 companies and agents who managed some of
the city's most elite buildings on Park and Fifth Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the subsequent convictions and fines totaling $4
million, the corruption and collusion between apartment managers
and contractors continued unabated, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the people in the industry get the message that this is
an ongoing investigation,'' Morgenthau said. ``They apparently did
not get the message after the 1994 indictments.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest indictments, two of the largest
management companies in the city _ Marvin Gold and Elm Management
Associates _ functioned as criminal enterprises, taking millions of
dollars in payoffs from contractors for work at luxury Park Avenue
cooperatives and low-income buildings in Queens alike, although
most were middle-income buildings throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   By making the payoffs, the indictments charge, contractors and
suppliers could eliminate their competition and charge higher
prices. The kickbacks usually amounted to 10 percent of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Marvin Gold Management and Elm Management did not
return several phone calls seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An architect, a superintendent, two directors of cooperatives in
Queens, eight contractors and 18 managing agents were indicted on
charges relating to bid-rigging and kickback schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bid-rigging and kickbacks have obviously been a way of life
for many years in the residential real estate industry,'' said
Edward Kuriansky, commissioner of the Department of Investigation,
who was involved in the investigation along with the district
attorney's office. ``But by violating their positions as managing
agents, building superintendents, and co-op board members to divert
tenant funds into their own pockets, the defendants siphoned off
the scarce resources that co-ops and residents need to make
critical repairs to their buildings and to pay off their
mortgages.''
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move Tuesday, one of the 30 people indicted,
Bernard Ehrlich, a former managing agent at Marvin Gold, pleaded
guilty to a charge of grand larceny for taking more than $3,000 in
kickbacks at a Queens cooperative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
