<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS SUGGEST SYMINGTON COULD RESUME POLITICAL CAREER
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The room was strangely silent when the news was
announced Tuesday morning to a group of House Republicans that Fife
Sy mington's bank fraud conviction had been overturned.
</P>
<P>
   No applause, no shouts of joy from the GOP lawmakers, many of
whom were loyal followers of Sy mington during his years as Arizona
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were in shock,'' said House Majority Whip Jim
Weiers, R-northwest Phoenix, who made the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later that the news began to sink in, prompting
emo tions ranging from relief that their former leader had finally
scored a legal victory to anger that the federal government pursued
the case in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans suggested that Symington now has a future in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through this decision, he has the ability to rehabilitate
himself,'' said Sen. Scott Bundgaard, R-Glen dale. ``He's done an
excellent job for this state. I think time will heal those wounds
created by the mob that went after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Rusty Bowers, R-Mesa, agreed, saying he
hoped Symington would consider another run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a great governor and I hope he runs again. Chef
for governor,'' Bowers said, referring to Symington's enrollment in
cooking classes at the Culinary Institute in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican lawmakers expressed anger at federal prosecu
tors for spending six years getting Symington convicted and at the
federal judge who dismissed a juror for failing to take part in
delibera tions.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of the juror led the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals to overturn Symington's 1997 bank fraud conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just outrageous that they didn't test her for
. . . mental illness before throwing her off the jury,'' said Sen.
John Hup penthal, R-Chandler. ``It was perse cution of a
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers were equally shocked at the news and could
be heard speculating about the political future of their former
nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised to see him do something (politically)
down the road,'' said Senate Minority Leader Jack Brown, D-St.
Johns. ``I wouldn't count him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Senate Minority Leader Chris Cummiskey, D-central Phoe
nix, described Symington as the ``Bill Clinton of Arizona
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when you think the guy is down for the count, he gets his
conviction overturned by the federal courts, who he has railed
against for years,'' Cummiskey said.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Symington once referred to the federal courts as a
member of the ``three amigos of the anti-culture.'' The other two
were universities and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Cummiskey said that it was premature for Symington's support ers
to completely vindicate the ex-governor but acknowledged that talk
of his running for office again already had begun Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People already are asking each other in the hallways, `Do you
think he'll run for governor?' '' he said. ``We've got a ways to go
before 2002. But this breathes new life into the guy, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa, one of Symington's
staunchest legislative supporters, said it will be difficult for
Syming ton to polish his tarnished political image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's never good when justice and politics
collide,'' Groscost said. ``Usually the first thing to go overboard
is justice. The real travesty here is, where does the man go to get
back his good name?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
