<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON BANKRUPTCY TRIAL TO CONTINUE DESPITE APPEALS DECISION
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ySHAUN MCKINNON 
 and PAT FLANNERY 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   While federal prosecutors decide whether to retry Fife Symington
on charges of criminal fraud, lawyers in the former governor's
bankruptcy case are preparing for the first phase of a trial, now
set to begin in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the two sides keep their July 8 date in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court may depend on how they
</P>
<P>
   interpret Tuesday's 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruling, which
overturned Symington's conviction in the crimi nal case.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Manning, who represents a group of union pension funds
trying to force Symington to make good on a $10 million loan, said
Tuesday that he may seek to delay the trial in light of the Appeals
Court ruling, scrapping plans to try the case in several parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling has a pretty direct impact on the case because both
the mini-trials that were scheduled were based on existence of a
criminal conviction,'' Manning said. ``We may now be looking at a
full trial, where all the issues get done at once.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Shull, Symington's bankruptcy attorney, said he sees no
reason to change plans because ``it's our opinion the bankruptcy
case is not dependent on the criminal case either way, whether
there's a conviction or a reversal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent at this moment is to go forward and we hope to be
successful,'' he said. ``There's another portion set for the middle
of August, and we hope to be successful with that. We'll kind of
knock them off as they come.''
</P>
<P>
   The criminal and bankruptcy cases were winding through federal
courts independently until U.S. Dis trict Judge Roger Strand, in
sentenc ing Symington on the criminal counts, based financial
restitution on the outcome of the bankruptcy trial.
</P>
<P>
   But because Tuesday's ruling doesn't address the bankruptcy
case, Manning said he doesn't foresee any effects on the pension
funds' ability to collect a future judgment should they prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just means the whole process will take more time,'' he
said. ``It doesn't make our case more diffi cult. In fact, even
though the case has been overturned, there is a record with people
testifying under oath. There are admissions Mr. Symington was
forced to make under oath that are tremendously valuable to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shull said ``the facts and the lay of the land haven't really
changed'' as a result of the court ruling, a position he believes
has been backed up by the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pension funds literally within weeks of the conviction in
1997 argued that the case should be over on the basis of the
criminal conviction,'' Shull said. ``The judge denied that motion.
He said certain issues to be tried in bankruptcy court are
different. We're ready to go try this.''
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides agree to move ahead as scheduled July 8, bank
ruptcy Judge George Nielsen will hold a five-day trial, the first
in a series of steps that will finally decide whether Symington
must repay the money the pension funds lent him to build the
downtown Mercado project.
</P>
<P>
   The case is important because it will determine whether or not
Sy mington is still on the hook for what the pension funds say has
ballooned to more than $18 million with interest. If Nielsen
decides he is, the judge also will determine how much Symington
still owes the funds.
</P>
<P>
   The debt dates to June 1990, when a Symington partnership bor
rowed $10 million to refinance a development loan that built the
Mercado, a mixed-use office and retail project at Seventh and Van
Buren streets.
</P>
<P>
   The project was unsuccessful from the day it opened. By 1995,
the loan had gone into default, and Symington was unable to back
his guarantee. The pension funds sued and won an $11.5 million
Superior Court judgment against Symington.
</P>
<P>
   When Symington filed for bank ruptcy on Sept. 20, 1995, the
pension funds immediately sought to block discharge of the Mercado
debt by arguing that Symington had fraudulently obtained the loan
by misrepresenting his net worth in financial statements completed
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   One of the criminal convictions overturned Tuesday was based on
charges that Symington used those financial statements to hide his
worsening financial condition from the pension funds, then managed
by Calfornia-based McMorgan &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the funds argue Symington inflated his assets and
hid some of his liabilities to obtain the financing for the
Mercado. The funds would not have approved the deal had they known
Symington was saddled with so much debt, the attorneys claim.
</P>
<P>
   Symington's attorneys say that the pension funds agreed to back
the Mercado financing long before the 1990 statement was filed and
that the fund managers did not check the statement's accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Syming ton long has insisted that he is
unable to pay the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Although the former governor still enjoys an affluent lifestyle,
it is based largely on the independent wealth of his wife, Ann, an
heiress to the Olin Chemical fortune. Her fortune is out of reach
of Syming ton's creditors. Symington has not had any substantial
income since resigning as governor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If the pension funds win their bankruptcy case, any future
salary and income from family trusts and inheritances could be
garnished un til the debt is satisfied. Manning believes Symington
stands to inherit as much as $4 million when certain East Coast
relatives die.
</P>
<P>
   When Symington filed Chapter 7 personal bankruptcy in September
1995, he claimed $25 million in debts and only $61,795 in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The court since has discharged Symington's debts, but the
challenge by the pension funds would reinstate that portion of debt
owed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
