<HEADLINE>
MERCADO AND ESPLANADE: SYMINGTON'S REAL ESTATE LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER 
 and CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Gov. Fife Symington's real estate legacy is reflected in
a tale of two projects _ the Mercado in downtown Phoenix and the Es
planade at 24th Street and Camel back Road.
</P>
<P>
   While Symington developed, and ultimately lost, more than a
dozen projects, the Mercado and Espla nade are the most enduring
symbols of his former empire _ one as a crashing failure and the
other as a stunning success.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercado, at Fifth and Van Buren streets, is a ghost town.
The only sounds are the wind and the Mercado's decorative fountain,
which burbles at the occasional passer-by.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Monge, who owns a hair salon in the Mercado, says things
are pretty lonely, though his busi ness is doing well. His only
neigh bor is an arts and crafts store.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last six or seven years, it's been like this,'' said
Monge, eating a fast-food lunch in the Mercado's deserted
courtyard. ``We'd love to stay, but maybe they're going to sell the
property.''
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling complex also houses the ASU Downtown Center, the
Downtown Phoenix Partnership and the Sunray Charter School. It is
managed by McMorgan &AMP; Co., which took over after Symington and his
partners defaulted on a $10 million loan to a consortium of union
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   McMorgan has been unable to replace the restaurant tenants who
fled over the years. It gave the Southwest-style buildings a paint
job and improved the parking. Nothing seems to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is kind of what it is,'' said Paul Morton, a
senior vice president at McMorgan.
</P>
<P>
   Morton said there are no big announcements coming, though he
continues to pursue ``every reason able option that presents
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Esplanade _ once described by Symington as the
``crown jewel'' of his development career _ has thrived since
Syming ton sold out in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The project is home to the Ritz-Carlton Phoenix, two original
office towers and a third tower recently completed by developer
Opus West.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Symington spent so much money on the project, that
it would not have been a moneymaker for him had he kept it.
</P>
<P>
   The two Esplanade towers, the Ritz-Carlton and land for the addi
tional towers sold recently in sepa rate deals. The total price was
less than what Symington financed them for in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Esplanade was destined to be a winner just because of its
location, but the market still hasn't caught up to what it cost to
develop,'' said Stanley Paul Cook, a real estate analyst with
Phoenix-based Landiscor Aerial Information.
</P>
<P>
   The original financing on the towers, retail space and hotel
totaled about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the first two office towers at the Esplanade, built in
1987 by Symington, sold for $87 million. Last year, Host Mar riott
paid almost $75 million for the Ritz-Carlton, at the height of the
Valley's investment market.
</P>
<P>
   Parcels for a third and fourth office tower were recently pur
chased for about $10 million by Opus West. Together, those sales
add up to $172 million, well below what it cost Symington to
develop them.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fijan, an office broker with CB Richard Ellis, said all of
Symington's high-profile projects were viable, except for the
Mercado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he would have made money on them if he could have
weathered the downturn in the markets, is doubtful,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Many developers like Symington were building high-end projects
for big bucks in the mid-1980s, when the market came crashing down
due to a change in real estate laws that devalued many projects
almost over night.
</P>
<P>
   Symington developed numerous projects in the late '80s and kept
most of them in his portfolio until he was elected governor in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   After that, property after property fell into financial trouble.
In Janu ary 1993, Symington said his real estate empire was
virtually wiped out and that his net worth was ``zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Symington development projects include:
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale Seville, a mixed-used shopping and office
project, at Scottsdale and Indian Bend roads, which cost almost $26
million to build in the early 1990s. The project is thriving, full
of restaurants, shops and big-name office tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale Centre, an of fice project south of Seville on
Scottsdale Road. It has changed hands a few times since being
developed for $26 million in the late 1980s. With its central
Scottsdale location, the building is almost full and charging high
rents.
</P>
<P>
   A five-building, 20,000-square-foot office complex at 1002 and
1010 E. Missouri Ave. Phoenix publisher Preston McMurry says he
``loves'' the development, which he purchased from the state
retirement system in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McMurry paid $1.29 million for the complex, which he estimates
is worth between $3 million and $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Alta Mesa shopping center in Mesa, which Symington sold for
a $1.5 million loss in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Symington developed the center at 5761 E. Brown Road in 1987
with a $2.5 million loan from First Interstate Bank, now Wells
Fargo. In 1991, he sold the center to a family trust headed by
Californian Warner Scharff for $965,000. Scharff sold the center in
late 1996 to Cole Cos. for more than $2 million. Cole believes the
property has since appreciated significantly.
</P>
<P>
   A 70,000-square-foot office building at 5050 N. 40th St. in
Phoenix. Symington financed the building, which eventually went
into foreclosure, with a $10.6 million loan from Citibank. Citibank
sold the building in 1993 to a partnership led by Phoenix
businessman Steven Sherman for $1.6 million. Sherman estimates the
property is worth about $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a first-class building, he did a great job,'' Sherman
said of the property and its developer. ``His timing was just a
little off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or at
bill.muller &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Republic writer Max Jarman contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
