<HEADLINE>
JUDGES? SYMINGTON LOVES JUDGES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it was the noontime heat or maybe it was the heat of the
mo ment, but former Gov. Fife Sy mington was having trouble with
his memory.
</P>
<P>
   It had only been a couple of hours since Symington found out the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals had overturned fraud convictions
that would have sent him to prison for 30 months.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Symington was dizzy with happiness. Confused.
Distracted. Inatten tive.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like his new best friend, former juror Mary Jane Cotey.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit ruled, 2-1, there was a ``reasonable
possibility'' that Cotey, who'd been removed from the Symington
jury for failing to take part in delibera tions, actually may have
been yanked be cause she disagreed with other jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Now Symington, in an open-collar blue shirt and backed by the
young men in suits who once formed his inner circle, was saying how
``absolutely stunned'' he was by the judges' ruling.
</P>
<P>
   And how this was ``a very emotional event for me and my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   And how he just wanted to enjoy the moment and not dwell on the
future or, for that matter, the past. Particularly, those days not
long ago when Symington said federal judges ``rule over the nation
like so many philosopher kings,'' protect ing ``all manner of
anti-social behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraud, for instance. &QL; 
ERASED COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   Symington furrowed his brow when asked Tuesday about how he'd
trashed judges very much like the ones who'd temporarily removed
him from the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember all these com plaints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time he said, ``Through the considerable intellectual
gifts of well-edu cated lawyers, liberals have won in the courts a
long list of policy changes they could never achieve in the
democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if that would include over turning convictions on
technicalities?
</P>
<P>
   The former governor faced a tight semicircle of reporters from
all the local news organizations Tuesday. He was al most as
deferential to them as he now is to judges, an attitude far removed
from a speech he gave only a few years back in which he called
judges, teachers and jour nalists ``the three amigos of the
anti-cul ture.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the evil three have ``galloped off to a Brave New World,
dragging a confused and divided society behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the relief he felt at not having to gallop off to
the federal deten tion center at Nellis Air Force Base in Nevada
that prevented him from recalling such a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, his complaints about ``a warmed-over
version of 30-year-old, liberal-left sociology that has never been
of much value in the fight against crime.''
</P>
<P>
   These statements have appeared in the papers before. They've
been reprinted by guys like me before. This time, perhaps Symington
will cut out the article and save it, to refresh his memory. &QL; 
MATTER OF CONVICTION
</P>
<P>
   The judge who wrote the opinion in Symington's favor was a Jimmy
Carter appointee, the kind of judge Symington once blasted for
being soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminals destroy the peace and hap piness that mankind was
meant to enjoy on Earth,'' the tough old Symington said. ``That is
why they forfeit their right to be among us. That is why they are
locked away in prison cells. That is why the worst of them are
taken to remote places and hanged from sturdy oaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was before his trial and conviction. Before he
was forced to re sign from office. Before Symington him self needed
``the considerable intellectual gifts of well-educated lawyers'' to
beat a rap for which 12 other jurors believed he was guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Do you recall when the former gover nor said, ``After 30 years
of consistent policy failure, the public is no longer moved by
arguments for leniency and soft rehabilitative responses to
criminals''?
</P>
<P>
   No. Of course you don't remember. And neither does Symington.
</P>
<P>
   Now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
