<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM POSTS EARNINGS ABOVE PREDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ 3Com Corp. on Tuesday reported fourth-quarter
earnings that came in 1 cent above analysts' expectations based on
strong growth in products used to manage data flow over networks.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended May 26, 3Com had net income of $87.5
million, or 24 cents a diluted share, up 38 percent from $63.6
million, or 17 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Sales
rose 3 percent, to $1.42 billion from $1.375 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected 3Com to earn 23 cents a share, according to
First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, 3Com had earnings of $403.9 million, or $1.09 a
share, compared with $30.2 million, or 8 cents a share, in the 1998
fiscal year. Sales for the year were $5.8 billion, up from $5.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for the 1999 fiscal year included a charge of $12.7
million associated with the acquisitions of Smartcode Technologie,
certain assets of ICS Networking Inc. and NBX Corp. and a credit of
$21.8 million related to changes in previously recorded merger and
reorganization expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Before 3Com reported its results, its shares closed at $31.50,
up 56.25 cents, 38 percent off their 52-week high. In after-hours
trading, the company's shares slipped to $31.125.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, 3Com on Tuesday announced an alliance with America
Online Inc. intended to give America Online users access to their
e-mail through Palm Pilots. The two companies also said they would
explore distribution of America Online-branded wireless hand-held
organizers based on the Palm Pilot and ways to develop software for
the Palm that would allow subscribers access to AOL e-mail and
other features.
</P>
<P>
   3Com said fourth-quarter sales of systems products increased 17
percent, to $784.7 million, but sales of client access products,
which include modems and network adapter cards for personal
computers, decreased 10 percent, to $630.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has struggled in recent quarters because the parts of the
networking market where it is strongest have matured and slowed,
and it remains a distant second to Cisco Systems Inc. in the
fast-growing sector of data communications equipment. Although
3Com's Palm Pilot hand-held device had enjoyed rapid growth, it
still accounted for less than 10 percent of the company's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Client access products account for 45 percent of 3Com's revenue,
and the company expected sales to continue to fall, said 3Com chief
financial officer Chris Paisley in a conference call with analysts.
Those declines mean that the company's growth rate will fall below
the network industry average and that sales for the first half of
the 2000 fiscal year may trail the period a year earlier, he said.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has been the subject of rumors about a potential buyout,
and several analysts have suggested that the company sell its
underperforming units. But 3Com management ducked questions about
potential divestitures on the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is worth more in pieces than it is together,'' said
Al Tobia, an analyst with Banc of America Securities. ``Everyone
knows a list of companies that have dealt with these slow and
maturing businesses, and the stock never advances during that
period,'' he said. ``It becomes very hard to manage earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   3Com president and chief operating officer Bruce Claflin said in
a telephone interview that 3Com had no plans to exit any
businesses. ``The businesses that we think are long term more
attractive are becoming more of our mix,'' he said. ``The aggregate
for next year will probably look a lot like this year, but the
first half will be less favorable and the second half will be more
favorable, because the mix increasingly works in our favor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
