<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-FORECAST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS FORECAST EMPLOYMENT GROWTH FOR CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Propelled by a robust real estate sector and flush
with a staggering infusion of stock market muscle, California's
economy will continue expanding through 2001, albeit at a slightly
more moderate pace than the recent past, according to a widely
watched UCLA forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate boom, being driven by strong sales and, to a
lesser extent, new home construction, has boosted employment in
related manufacturing operations such as building materials,
furniture and fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   These factors should add up to a job growth rate this year of
3.2 percent, just 0.4 percentage points less than the 1998 level,
said the quarterly economic forecast from UCLA's Anderson School.
</P>
<P>
   Job creation should taper off to 2.5 percent and 2.2 percent in
2000 and 2001, respectively, the forecast said.
</P>
<P>
   Thank the real estate sector for some of the employment growth,
said economist Tom K. Lieser, author of the California report.
</P>
<P>
   He said an estimated 15 percent of home buyers in California are
using profits from the stock market for down payments. And at least
100,000 jobs created in the past year are related to real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Personal income has been growing at an annual rate of 5 percent
or more since 1995, in part because of the equity amassed by state
residents with stock portfolios. It is expected to grow 7.4 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, the big New York-based investment bank, recently
estimated the value of the U.S. stock market at $13 trillion.
``It's a good bet that California's share of that pie is
proportionately larger than, say, the state's 13 percent share of
national income or output,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatively estimating the state's share at 15 percent would
mean California's total stock portfolio is about $2 trillion, about
twice California's gross product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not saying the stock market is the only thing
driving California. The (economic) fundamentals are good and the
underlying trends are positive,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the expansion of individual and corporate wealth can't
be sustained forever, and in fact a slowdown could be just over the
horizon. UCLA's national outlook calls for flat or slightly
decreasing corporate profits through the end of next year. Over
that same period of time, the Federal Reserve Board is expected to
raise interest rates by about three-quarters of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will take some of the exuberance out of this stock
market. No one is predicting a crash but the kinds of returns some
investors have come to expect _ 25 percent to 30 percent a year _
don't look like they can continue,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Other economists concur with UCLA's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Williams, chief economist in the state Legislative
Analyst's Office, noted that UCLA's personal income forecast is
based on the most recent data available. ``The wealth effect is
having a positive impact on the California economy and it's a theme
we had earlier this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One puzzling aspect of the forecast is the modest gains expected
in home construction. During 1998, permits for 125,000 new units
were issued, less than 8 percent of the nationwide starts. The
number should grow to 208,000 by 2001. But that falls far short of
the annual pace of a quarter of a million annual units in the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales are at all-time highs so you would think that the demand
would be out there for a stronger level of home construction than
we are seeing. Maybe there are some supply-side constraints at
work; the builders can't get the land or workers,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some study highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry employment is at about 190,000 workers,
the level it ended 1997 with. The sector should grow by 2 percent
this year and 3 percent next year. It's gained about 10,000 jobs
since last August.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County will have a more moderate growth rate than
the state. And the county remains several hundred thousand jobs
behind the level it reached in the early 1990s before the defense
sector contracted.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing consolidation of banking likely will continue the
job-shedding process for several years. Job losses have been offset
by gains at brokerages, mortgage companies, real estate sales
offices and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
