r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-T     06-22 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' SPREWELL, FOR ONE, HAS PUT THE PAST BEHIND HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Allan Houston might have owned Game 3. But make no
mistake, Latrell Sprewell owns New York.
</P>
<P>
   Because The City That Never Sleeps also is The City That Loves
to Forgive and Forget, the controversial Sprewell's past is
invisible and his persona everywhere as the NBA Finals head into
tonight's Game 4 against the San Antonio Spurs at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Like Darryl Strawberry, Lawrence Taylor and George Steinbrenner,
the hellion New York Knicks forward has at least temporarily put
aside his black hat to become the most popular person in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree's the man around here if you haven't noticed,'' said
Houston, whose 34 points Monday night helped the Knicks narrow
their Finals deficit to 2-1. ``Some of it is cult-hero stuff, but
there's also a genuine appreciation of him as a person, and a
player. He spills his heart and plays his butt off on the floor,
and these fans fall in love with those types of players.''
</P>
<P>
   With dangling corn rows, funky glasses and gum-chomping
cockiness, Sprewell is hotter than Ricky Martin and Capri pants on
Madison Avenue. He has Knicks fanatic Spike Lee wearing his No. 8
jersey and companies like Hugo Boss and Calvin Klein begging him to
endorse their products. In a surprisingly popular television
commercial, he even boasts to being ``the American dream'' to the
backdrop of Jimi Hendrix's Woodstock version of ``The Star-Spangled
Banner''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I'm as shocked as anyone to be standing here in
this situation,'' Sprewell said. ``I've been through a lot in the
past couple of years, and I think people appreciate that. It would
have been different if none of it had happened. For one thing, I
probably wouldn't be as popular as I am now.'' In the past Before
his relentless energy and fearless creativity led the Knicks to an
unlikely Eastern Conference championship and a belief they can
rally to upset the Spurs in the Finals, Sprewell seemed to be the
poster boy for all that's wrong in the NBA. On his laundry list of
transgressions:
</P>
<P>
   He once threatened Spurs forward Jerome Kersey with a 2-by-4
when they were teammates in Golden State;
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off his pet Doberman's mauling of his daughter's ear
and face, saying ``accidents happen'' and deciding to keep the dog;
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to house arrest in his hometown of Milwaukee
last summer and forced to wear an ankle monitor after recklessly
driving an elderly couple off the freeway;
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, he choked his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's old news,'' said Sprewell, who has never personally
apologized to Golden State Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo for the
infamous attack that led to Sprewell's unprecedented one-year
suspension from the league on Dec. 1, 1997. ``We've all made
mistakes. I'm no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the glare of the Big Apple and in a series against the
Spurs' squeaky-clean God Squad, Sprewell apparently has persuaded
New Yorkers to laugh with the sinners rather than cry with the
saints.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was fined $25,000 by the Knicks earlier in the season
after his agent went public with a demand to start or be traded,
Sprewell has been a model teammate and one of the reasons Hope
Floats at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been great to coach, great to be around,'' said Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``The only difference we've had was that he
wanted to start earlier in the season, but everybody wants to play
more. I didn't know exactly what to expect with him coming in, but
I couldn't have asked for anything more from him.''
</P>
<P>
   After his highly publicized trade to the Knicks, Sprewell
provided only a glimpse of his talent before suffering a stress
fracture in his heel that caused him to miss 13 games. Now healthy
and starting, he is providing his team offensive octane and his
fans with an anti-Duncan. While Spurs center Tim Duncan quietly
scores on bank shots, baby hooks and all the flair of a statue,
Sprewell seemingly exorcises demons with every wide-eyed drive to
the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an emotional guy and that's the only way I know how to
play,'' Sprewell said. ``I guess I'm a good fit for this city.''
What might have been After an ugly third quarter in Game 3 in which
he missed all five of his field goals and 4-of-6 from the foul
line, Sprewell didn't stop running, didn't stop shooting. Like a
teen-ager on a sugar rush, he scored 10 of his 24 points in the
fourth quarter, including an acrobatic, arching, left-handed layup
over Duncan that gave the Knicks a five-point lead and reason to
believe they could finally beat the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a greyhound that just never gets tired,'' said Spurs
guard Mario Elie. ``Sometimes you can see him just pulling those
guys along, whether they want to run or not.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think, Sprewell was almost a Spurs player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very close,'' said Sprewell, who pushed for a
trade to San Antonio just days before his choking of Carlesimo. ``I
remember we played the Spurs and I kept running by and telling Pop
\RSpurs coach Gregg Popovich\S to pull the trigger. It's funny how
things work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich, who coached Sprewell as an assistant to Don Nelson
with the Warriors, wanted Sprewell, but Spurs owner Peter Holt was
leery of the move in the wake of Dennis Rodman's unstable stay in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Spree fan, and everybody knows that,'' Popovich said.
``I love his competitiveness. He's going to do anything he has to
do to win and that's pretty obvious to everybody. But I especially
love his honesty. Whether you agree with this kid or not, he is
going to tell you straight-up _ between your eyes, to your face _
what he's thinking every second of the day. I like that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sprewell bandwagon is fully en vogue because the only thing
New Yorkers love more than their heroes is their heroes with scars.
Scoring Spree While the Spurs' Twin Towers of Tim Duncan and David
Robinson have owned the paint in the NBA Finals, New York's Allan
Houston and Latrell Sprewell have been just as dominating on the
perimeter. A look at the point production and percentage of offense
provided by the Knicks' 1-2 punch and the Spurs' Twin Towers
entering tonight's Game 4: Players Game 1 Game 2 Game 3
</P>
<P>
   Points Pct. Points Pct. Points Pct. Duncan-Robinson 46 51 41 51
45 55 Houston-Sprewell 38 46 45 67 58 65
nn
</P>
