<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHINING STARS SERVE AS BEACON FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ They stayed up late and watched the deciding
game. They saw the parade highlights. They listened to the cheers
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Rangers admit, it's their turn to win ``the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   They share the same owner. The same club president. The same
character-first philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it's the trophy cases that are different.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars stand at the top of the hockey world. The Rangers are
at the summit of Planet AL West.
</P>
<P>
   One has the Cup. The Rangers still have only the salad bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a hot summer, anyway, at The Ballpark in
Arlington. And after what happened the other night in Buffalo, it
just got a tad hotter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to say there's more pressure on us,
because it's two totally different games, two totally different
teams,'' left fielder Rusty Greer said last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think, after seeing what's been done with the Stars over
the past few years, there is a good chance that the same things
could happen here. There's a feeling that if it comes down to
making moves at the right time, Mr. Hicks will do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think there's any more pressure that could be
added by any outside person than what the 25 guys in this clubhouse
have already put on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer is right. The Rangers realize, having heard general
manager Doug Melvin say it repeatedly, that a third division title
in four years will not be enough. The club needs to move, as Melvin
puts it, to ``the next level'' _ or the Rangers might as well be
the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   No one can accurately gauge how demanding team owner Tom Hicks
will be, now that he has ridden in a parade and owns a pair of
Stanley Cup boots. But the names John Mackovic and Tom Penders can
probably give us a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, baseball is rooted in some key differences. One
prominent hockey player _ one Ed Belfour _ can make an immediate
and conspicuous impact. In baseball, even a free-agent starting
pitcher gets to work only once every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   In hockey, one random slap shot from the point can change an
entire game. In baseball, offense tends to more often be a
cumulative exercise.
</P>
<P>
   And another key difference _ in hockey, a little money can go a
long way. In baseball, there are lot of contracts like Brett
Hull's.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars just finished beating a hockey club whose payroll is
$20 million less than theirs. And that team made it to the Stanley
Cup Finals. In baseball, a Buffalo Sabres spend-alike doesn't make
it to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   As we learned in the Todd Stottlemyre and Randy Johnson
courtings, the impact of a Tom Hicks in baseball is meaningful but
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be provided with all the physical means in the world,
but it still comes down to evaluation,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has said that he understands that.
</P>
<P>
   But now he has some new boots. He has a Cup. He just rode in a
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched what happened to the Stars, and my first thought was
that I was happy for the guys,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said
before last night's game with the Athletics. ``Second, I found
myself thinking that I want to have that experience here. I want to
know how that feels. That's what motivates me more than anything
else _ to be able to celebrate the way the Stars did.''
</P>
<P>
   From their hotel rooms in Boston last Saturday night, they
watched. On their TVs at home yesterday, the Rangers saw the
highlights and watched the entire community rise to cheer its
newest champions.
</P>
<P>
   As Oates correctly mused aloud, ``If they go that crazy for
hockey, just think what they would do here for a baseball
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be huge. The celebration would probably sprawl across
the two counties.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks could get yet another new set of boots.
</P>
<P>
   No pressure. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``The selfish part of me wants to experience that and know how
it feels,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the owner's done his part. Now it's up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Ballpark in Arlington tonight, the Rangers will get an
even-closer look at what the ``next level'' can be. A handful of
Stars players will be on hand to throw out the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   They will be accompanied by the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It's no salad bowl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
