<SLUG> BC-FLY-WITHOUT-FEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT GROUP OFFERS THERAPY TO EASE FEAR OF FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Maureen Werner's flight takes off, she counts
the number of children, priests, nuns and rabbis who are among her
fellow passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are lots of little kids, I feel more confident that
we won't crash,'' said Mrs. Werner, 48, a homemaker from Rye. ``And
when it comes to religious leaders, I'll take anyone. I'm
nondenominational.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Laabs can't really say what she does when she flies; she is
too drugged to remember. ``I'm usually so sedated, I pre-board in a
wheelchair,'' said Ms. Laabs, a brokerage company employee who
lives in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his 68 years, Ron Strickland's fear of flying was so
intense that he looked down whenever an aircraft flew overhead. ``I
couldn't imagine stepping onto a plane,'' said Strickland, a
grocery store owner from Queens. ``I just assumed I'd never see
Europe in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Weary of the crippling fear and the missed travel opportunities,
these self-described aviophobes turned up at La Guardia Airport
earlier this month, joining two dozen others for a meeting of Fly
Without Fear, a support group that has been easing air travel
phobias for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when jet travel is about as exotic as a ride on an
escalator, those who fly with anxiety _ or are too petrified to fly
at all _ say they get little solace from friends, family and
especially employers. Many turn to such support groups, especially
this time of year, when out-of-town weddings, class reunions and
family vacations beckon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the office, everyone's talking about their summer travel
plans to Prague or Turkey, which creates tremendous stress,'' said
Carol Cott Gross, who runs the La Guardia group wth her husband,
Herb. ``You can only take the train to Disney World so many
times.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that class size also spikes after aviation accidents
like this month's American Airlines crash in Little Rock, Ark.,
which killed 11 people. ``And whenever a disaster movie comes out
that features a plane crash, people really go nuts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fly Without Fear treatment regimen has changed little since
1969, when Mrs. Gross' father, Nate Cott, started the meetings with
her cousin, a psychiatrist. She and her husband took over the group
after Cott, an inventor and engineer, died in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The program remains a homespun mixture of behavior modification,
relaxation techniques, Aeronautics 101 and Alcoholics
Anonymous-style confessionals in which members take turns venting
their anxieties, recalling in-flight panic attacks or vacations
aborted by fear. She said that almost all attendees fly within a
year of joining, many of them on special graduation flights to
Boston or Washington that the Grosses organize every few months.
Still, she says there is no such thing as a cure, and many clients
have ``touch up'' sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Psychology of Air Travel in Boston estimates
that 35 million Americans have an acute fear of flying. Dr. Albert
Forgione, the director, said that at least a third of all air
travelers are apprehensive about getting on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   Those who treat flight phobia agree that it is less a fear of
crashing and more related to disorders like agoraphobia and
claustrophobia. Others have a history of panic attacks and are
simply anxious that they will be afflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Aviophobes are also cursed with an overactive imagination.
Forgione said it was not uncommon for his patients to fear being
sucked out of the airplane's toilet, or that a wing will snap off.
Others think that being so high puts them within easy reach of God,
who will take advantage of the close proximity to snatch them up to
Heaven. ``People imagine the most absurd, ridiculous things,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who attended a recent meeting agreed that their fears were
highly fantastic. Strickland worried that the pilot would get lost
in the fog. One woman said she was afraid the plane might run out
of gas. Another woman fretted about tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Russo, an American Airlines pilot, coolly explained
aircraft mechanics and the principles of flight. Then in detail he
described every imaginable sound a passenger might hear and what it
means.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they were especially unnerved by turbulence, convinced
that even minor jolts could shatter their aircraft. Russo told them
planes can handle more volatility than the human body. ``If you
didn't see a kid fly from row 10 to row 20, you didn't experience
severe turbulence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A bubbly extrovert, Mrs. Gross enthusiastically talks about her
own neuroses. Phobias, she said, run in her family, ``like blue
eyes and cellulite.'' Planes, tunnels, bridges and tall buildings
all give her the jitters. ``My worst nightmare is a party at
Windows on the World,'' she said, referring to a restaurant near
the top of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Members pay $30 a meeting; attendees tour La Guardia's air
traffic control tower and hear from flight attendants, mechanics,
radar specialists and psychologists. Each session ends with an
anxiety-busting climb aboard a parked plane.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gross repeatedly assures the group that the Boeing 727 will
not be going anywhere. ``The key word here is `stationary,''' she
said. Still, many find the visit jarring. As she walked beneath the
wing, Mrs. Werner visibly swooned. ``It's big,'' she said,
explaining the gobsmacked look on her face, ``and it shouldn't be
in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The brave ones gingerly eased down the aisle. Several sat
towards the rear, their seat belts tightly fastened. Feeling
emboldened, Mrs. Werner poked her head in the cockpit and sprayed
Russo with questions: ``You know what all those lights are for? Is
it a struggle to fly? Why did that plane in Arkansas crash?''
</P>
<P>
   After three successful plane tours, Joanne Mongiello of Franklin
Square on Long Island said she was ready for the real thing _ a
graduation flight to Boston that returns the same day. Mrs.
Mongiello had not flown in three decades, and besides a trip this
August to visit her daughter in Los Angeles, she had another
incentive: ``My husband bought me a 25th anniversary diamond ring
and he won't give it to me until I fly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, she got her chance. Nearly two dozen
members bought tickets for the 9:30 a.m. Delta Shuttle to Boston;
only one woman failed to arrive. ``I never coerce anyone to board,
because there's always another flight,'' Mrs. Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   The group gathered an hour before the flight, put rubber bands
on their wrists (to snap away negative thoughts) and congratulated
one another for showing up. They boarded 15 minutes before other
passengers. Ms. Laabs sat in the front, headphones over her ears,
her bag stuffed with distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Then the doors closed and the jet engines whooshed.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of taking off, the plane crept along the runway for
half an hour. Anxieties edged up. Three times, Ms. Laabs grabbed
her things and started heading for the exit. Mrs. Gross didn't try
to stop her, but instead unleashed her distraction-by-chattering
tactic.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the pilot announced imminent takeoff. As the Boeing 727
accelerated, Wendi Waldman tried to comfort her friend, Tammy
Siffert, whose cheeks had begun to lose their color. ``It's only 30
minutes, it's only 30 minutes,'' Ms. Waldman chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the plane was airborne. The front of the cabin
erupted in cheers, Ms. Laabs and Mrs. Mongiello hugged and
Strickland beamed like a 4-year-old (though he wondered aloud if
the thick cloud cover might hinder navigation).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
