<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTCLUB-PYRAMID-SCHE     06-22 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTCLUB-PYRAMID-SCHEME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO AUTHORITIES, `GIFTING' CLUB STACKS UP AS PYRAMID SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. _ The club has a basic sales pitch to new members:
donate $2,000 as a ``gift'' and, if all goes well, collect $16,000
in return.
</P>
<P>
   No, says the group's founder, Linda Shepard, it is not an
illegal pyramid scheme, only a private social club with members
eager to help loyal and trusted friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not `get rich quick,' it's not `get rich overnight,'
it's `get rich,''' Ms. Shepard told a big crowd of new and
potential members June 17 at a cavernous exhibition hall at the New
Jersey Convention Center. ``It doesn't happen today or tomorrow. It
takes some time to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, she said 1,048 people were recruited, each
doling out their payments in $100 bills, for a total of $2,096,000,
to obtain the entry-level position of ``star'' on a ``ship,'' the
club's organizational structure.
</P>
<P>
   Each ship has 15 members on four levels _ eight stars at the
bottom, four all-stars above them, two superstars above them, and a
captain at the top. Only the captains receive money. This
particular night's collection allowed 131 captains to walk away
with $16,000 each, Ms. Shepard said. Each captain returns $500 to
the club for its expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The club, Amigos Associates Social Club of New Jersey Inc., is
20 weeks old and already seems well-entrenched in the state. In
May, Ms. Shepard filed papers with the state Treasury Department
incorporating it as a nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shepard said it meets two or three times a week, usually in
a large restaurant or in the Garden State Exhibition Center in
Somerset, for newcomers to pay their $2,000. Security is tight.
Guards, some with metal detectors, search everybody for weapons.
Cameras and tape recorders are banned.
</P>
<P>
   The club has drawn the attention of law enforcement authorities.
State Attorney General John Farmer is investigating complaints that
six police officers in Plainfield who belong to the club illegally
recruited four merchants to join and pay $2,000, said Plainfield
Police Chief Edward Santiago. The merchants contend that the
officers solicited them while in uniform and on duty, Santiago
said. Police officers, he said, are barred from doing anything for
personal financial gain while on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   To Union County Prosecutor Thomas Manahan, Amigos Associates is
a well-organized pyramid scheme that has shielded itself from
criminal charges with carefully worded disclaimers. Its promotional
brochure defines the club as a ``private optional gifting program''
whose members donate their $2,000 voluntarily and expect no money
back. In boldface type, the brochure states, ``There is never a
promise or guarantee of a monetary return.''
</P>
<P>
   When new members turn over their $2,000, the brochure says, they
must read aloud this statement: ``This is strictly a gift, and I
expect nothing in return.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey courts have ruled that pyramid schemes are theft by
deception, banned by the state's Consumer Fraud Act. But Manahan
said he would have a difficult time proving theft by deception in
cases where people hand over a $2,000 gift and say they expect to
get nothing for it. He said the Legislature must tighten the law.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shepard, 36, the owner of a music store in Somerset and a
former drama and speech teacher, said lawyers helped her organize
Amigos Associates. She said she has invited detectives to attend
club meetings. ``I said come and look,'' she said. ``We're real
people. We have a face and a name. We've showed them everything. We
believe it's legal and ethical, and we're helping people.'' But she
declined to say what law enforcement agency the investigators
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials and mathematics experts predict Amigos
Associate will collapse, as all pyramid schemes do, because it will
eventually run out of recruits. Club rules require each new member
to recruit at least two more because as each ship captain collects
money and ``retires'' from the system, two new ships are created,
and other members move up a level. Membership must constantly
double to produce the $16,000 for each new captain. It takes eight
new recruits to pay a captain. For those eight people to get their
$16,000, the club must recruit 64 more people to pay $2,000 each,
or a total of $128,000. Club rules require that those 64 people
recruit 128 more, and that the 128 recruit 256 more. Fifteen rounds
later, the club will need more than 8 million recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just becomes completely impractical because it needs more
people than there are in the state,'' said Robert Berk, a professor
of statistics at Rutgers University. ``It's got to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Ms. Shepard said: ``I don't believe we'll run out
of people. We recycle ourselves.'' She said most members who
collect $16,000 start again with a new payment of $2,000. But
experts said that would simply delay the inevitable collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said his
investigators have been in touch with detectives working for
Manahan to determine whether Amigos Associates is linked to a
similar club that has been operating in Stamford, Conn. He said
that if he learns the identities of the organizers in Stamford, he
will file a civil suit seeking a $5,000 fine for every $2,000
payment collected in Connecticut, where civil law bars such
payments as an unfair investment practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic, blatant pyramid scheme,'' Blumenthal said of
the Stamford club. ``The essential principle is there is a limited
pool of people so foolish and gullible to pay $2,000, so eventually
there have to be losers among those who sign up last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
