<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-22 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS' BATTLE OF SEXES IS NO CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women of Wimbledon offered what they termed ``a mild
protest'' Tuesday, a soft backhand slice in the name of equality.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody boycotted _ or girlcotted, as Bud Collins, no doubt,
would have called it. Nobody burned a sports bra. The show went on.
</P>
<P>
   With T-shirts and lapel pins bearing an ``equal'' sign and the
kicker ``Get the point?'' members of the Women's Tennis Association
quietly drew attention to the fact that at Wimbledon, as at the
French and Australian opens, the men have bigger purses.
</P>
<P>
   At Wimbledon, the women's prize money totals more than $4
million, which sounds generous until you realize the men's prize
money is more than $5 million. The women think they should get the
same as the men.
</P>
<P>
   They're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They should be paid (begin ital)more(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``who deserves what?'' is a classic
depends-how-you-look-at-it question, whether you're talking about
an athlete, an actor or a barber.
</P>
<P>
   The Wimbledon hosts, grasping for a rational explanation for
this time-honored inequity, like to point out that men play
best-of-five-set matches while the women play best-of-three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women get paid more per game,'' an officer of the All England
Club said on HBO, demonstrating that he does not get the point.
</P>
<P>
   As if athletes are, or ought to be, paid by the hour. Should
golfers be paid by the shot? John Daly would love that.
</P>
<P>
   If we were all on the clock, the average history teacher would
make more than the best relief pitcher and the argument could end
right there.
</P>
<P>
   Other explanations are less convincing than that one, if it's
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we paid women (equally), we wouldn't have so much to spend
on petunias,'' another Wimbledon officer said. Or on brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, one of the leading men found the controversy
irresistible and stuck a grass-stained Adidas in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're probably a bit greedy,'' said Tim Henman, the
leading English player. He added that the women ``should worry
about getting their own tournaments at a bigger and better level''
before asking the Grand Slam events for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Henman should watch more women's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Their tournaments (begin ital)are(end ital) bigger and better.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that if you look at tennis players as entertainers,
then this is one arena in which women deserve the bigger paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't women's basketball, whose pro league, the WNBA, sits
at the head table of American sports prematurely, paid for by a
rich father, the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't women's soccer, whose World Cup seems to be
succeeding despite falling short against the usual standards of
sports appeal _ uniquely entertaining play, a historical context,
familiar personalities.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't women's golf, which has never, for whatever reason,
been as popular as the men's.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis' women are as big as the men _ and they've earned that
stature.
</P>
<P>
   Their personalities certainly are bigger. From Wimbledon's first
seed, Martina Hingis, to its last, Anna Kournikova, to Venus
Williams and Mary Pierce in between, the women's side has more good
guys and bad guys than the guys'.
</P>
<P>
   Now that bad-guy Hingis is out of the tournament, it's hard to
find anybody to root against at the top of the women's draw, where
Steffi Graf is No. 2, Lindsay Davenport No. 3 and Monica Seles No.
4.
</P>
<P>
   But this is about more than personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The women's game is more fun to watch, particularly on grass
courts like Wimbledon's, where the men's rallies rarely last longer
than serve, off-balance return, put-away volley.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the women play patty-cake, Chris Evert tennis anymore.
It's a muscular, athletic game now, a Navratilova bearing down on
every net at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   As for the old knock about shallow talent _ ask Hingis, knocked
out Tuesday in the first round, in straight sets, by 16-year-old
qualifier Jelena Dokic of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   These days women's tennis is quite competitive. It's the men who
can't keep up. This is what passes for intrigue on the men's side
at Wimbledon: wide speculation that Pete Sampras is on his way
down, and general shock that Andre Agassi found his unreliable game
at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   But if Sampras and Agassi, the biggest names in men's tennis,
meet in the July 4 final, it will be the first time they've faced
each other in any round of a Grand Slam tournament since Sampras'
victory in the 1995 U.S. Open final.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest names in women's tennis _ there are so many of them
_ face each other every day.
</P>
<P>
   Check the TV ratings. The women's matches usually dwarf the
men's. They probably will do it again at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Equal pay? It's the men who are probably a bit greedy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
